<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NY     04-27 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TRADING HITS, KNICKS FLOOR THE RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Vince Carter stared into the eyes of Latrell
Sprewell at the top of the 3-point arc, the noise blew up inside of
Madison Square Garden. Here was Carter looking at the one Knick who
had been able to counter him on Wednesday night, and he had a
chance to beat him one on one.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew it. But the play wasn't for Carter. It was for Dee
Brown. Just before the buzzer, Carter swung the ball to Brown, who
missed a 3-pointer that would have won the game for the Raptors and
devastated the Knicks. With Patrick Ewing charging toward him,
Brown's shot fell short as the time on the clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, the Knicks were using the court as their private
dance floor after winning, 84-83. They also took a 2-0 lead in
their first-round, three-of-five playoff series, which shifts to
Toronto for Game3 on Sunday afternoon, and absorbed the punch from
a sharper, more intense Raptor team.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearly 3-hour Game 2 that was filled with 60 personal
fouls, the Knicks endured whatever it took to come back from a
16-point, third-quarter deficit. They made their comeback with
Larry Johnson's 8 points early in the fourth and Sprewell's 13 to
end the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sprewell, who scored 25 points to shadow the 27 by
Carter, who gave the Knicks their first lead since the opening
minutes of the game. The Knicks had the ball with 25.6 seconds left
and trailed by 1 point. It was Sprewell and Carter, alone in
isolation. After he waited for the clock to spin down, Sprewell
darted from the left sideline into the paint, rose up over Carter
and hit a fallaway 6-footer with 7.9 seconds left to give the
Knicks an 84-83 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks finished the game shooting 40.3 percent; the Raptors
shot 41.4 percent. Allan Houston, nonexistent all night, scored 12
points on a 2-for-8 night while Ewing added 19 points despite
having foul trouble. The Knicks made 28 of 38 free throws and the
Raptors hit 33 of 41.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy worried about his
team's history of mishandling prosperity. Several players said he
was visibly angry about the team's bleary focus during Tuesday's
practice, and he wondered out loud if his team could unearth the
kind of hunger they had to start Game1.
</P>
<P>
   Even as game time approached, even after a successful
shoot-around on Wednesday morning, he was still concerned with the
Knicks' energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in Game 2's, and you look at what teams did yesterday,
and it's interesting for a team that wins Game 1,'' said Van Gundy,
referring to San Antonio and Charlotte's ability to come back and
even their respective series. ``I think there is a big difference
when you win Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we go for the win tonight. A lot
of times at 1-0, you're waiting for the other shoe to drop. What if
Vince Carter has a better night. All these things. We just have to
go for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's pregame anxieties were justified. A sharper, more
prepared Raptors team took the floor with Muggsy Bogues inserted as
the starting point guard to guide them. With him, there was calm.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was over his opening-night jitters, and his teammates
were ready for whatever the Knicks had.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Raptors opened up a 15-point lead midway
through the second, an edge aided after six straight turnovers by
the clumsy Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   With Houston unable to get his shot off with Tracy McGrady
around and Marcus Camby missing a flurry of putbacks, the Knicks
were in a dire state until Ewing came back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing had two quick fouls in the first quarter. After sitting
for nearly 10 minutes, Ewing returned with his team down, 32-20.
Maneuvering around Kevin Willis, he made an immediate impact during
a 12-2 run. Ewing scored 7 points as the Knicks tightened their
defense and pulled back to 34-29 with 2 minutes remaining in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley kept the game from being closer. He was already
beating the Knicks to loose balls and making the shots when Carter
fed him the ball out of double-teams. With 50 seconds left in the
half, Oakley was left open to hit a 3-pointer. His 9 first-half
points, combined with the 10 by a much more restrained Carter, gave
the Raptors a 41-34 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Knicks closed the gap, they expended a lot of
energy just to make up for their abysmal first quarter. They were
out of it as they exited the locker room while Carter was beginning
to feel it on his deadly fadeaway over Sprewell. Carter scored on 5
quick points, including a gravity-defying, hanging jumper on the
baseline, to give the Raptors a 52-37 lead with 7:35 left in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Ewing had to rescue the Knicks. By getting to the line,
he helped cut the Raptors lead to 55-46. But Carter continued to
counter Ewing's star treatment by the refs by also getting some
beneficial calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks couldn't afford to trade trips to the free-throw
line. With 3 minutes left in the third quarter, Camby came up one
of the easier blocks of his career when he slapped down a jumper by
the 5-foot-3-inch Bogues.
</P>
<P>
   With some active defense, plus a fadeaway jumper by Ewing over
Willis, the Knicks were just 8 points down with 1:50 left in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ewing or nothing. Houston was even struggling at the
free-throw line, and Sprewell was coated every time he touched the
ball by Carter, plus double teams. As the third quarter ended with
both teams marching to the line _ each team had 28 attempts through
three quarters _ the Raptors converted more to take a 67-55 lead
entering the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Knicks got close, the Raptors put on a spurt of
energy to pull away again. Their leader was Bogues. From the
beginning, Bogues gave the Knicks all kind of problems. This was a
lineup change Butch Carter made in an effort to get Toronto off to
a crisper start than the one that ended up with the Knicks taking a
19-point, first-quarter lead in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Bogues put pressure on the Knicks' point guards,
squeezed minutes off the shot-clock and left Houston, Sprewell and
Ewing rushing jumpers and forcing up attempts as the aggressive
Raptors closed in with double teams.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Carter, who passed with more precision out of
double teams, and hit his first 2 shots after missing his first 12
in Game 1, was doing damage. If he wasn't scoring, he was
attracting enough attention so that Oakley was left alone to fire.
The toll of it all left the Knicks shooting just 15 percent and
down 26-15 at the end of the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were in suffer mode. Even though they pulled to 41-34
at the half, they were not getting the same production as they were
in Game 1 from the Knick starters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
