<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBPHONE-NEXTEL-SFCHR     04-27 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBPHONE-NEXTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REVIEW: NEXTEL ONLINE  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Surfing the Web, getting e-mail and reading the
news on your cell phone?
</P>
<P>
   My first reaction was, ``Enough, already!''
</P>
<P>
   Do we really need (or want) to be connected to the Web every
second?
</P>
<P>
   While ``need'' is perhaps too strong a word, after using
Nextel's new Online service for a month, let's just say I've grown
accustomed to its face. Breaking up would be hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at Nextel Online, and what you can expect from the
new generation of digital PCS phones and wireless information
services.
</P>
<P>
   What does Nextel Online do, exactly? First, it gives you access
to the Web, albeit on a very small, text-only screen. It also
provides a number of information services through MSN Mobile, such
as stock quotes, weather reports, flight status, driving
directions, sports scores, news headlines, lottery numbers and so
on. E-commerce partners like Amazon.com even offer one-click
ordering by phone. Finally, paging and e-mail services let you send
and receive urgent messages while away from your computer.
</P>
<P>
   In order to take advantage of the Web-browsing and information
services, you first need a Web-enabled digital cell phone. Nextel
offers three Motorola models, the i500plus ($99), i700plus ($149)
and i1000plus ($199), to Bay Area users. We reviewed the basic
model, the i500plus. The i700plus adds vibrating ring capability,
as well as a missed-call indicator and lighted keypad; the compact
i1000plus model further adds a speakerphone.
</P>
<P>
   All include the Phone.com microbrowser for the Web, as well as
the ability to be used as wireless modems for your PC, Windows CE
or Palm device. Modem speeds are typically 19.2 Kbps, and
connection kits with software and cables cost $99 (no Macintosh
kits are available from Nextel, but third-party solutions may
work). You use the phone and cable to dial up to your regular ISP
or company network.
</P>
<P>
   At 19.2 Kbps, you won't want to rely on the wireless modem as
your main Net connection for a portable computer, but it's great
for occasional use, especially while traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've got the phone, setting it up for information
services is a snap. You simply go to the MSN Mobile Web site (while
on your computer, not the phone) and give it basic information like
your Hotmail and Expedia account names, ZIP code, favorite sports
teams, stock symbols you want to track, and zodiac sign.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you log on from the phone, your personalized data is
available. You can also get many types of information, including
stock prices, sent automatically as pager alerts.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotmail retrieval capability is by far the most valuable.
With Hotmail, you can access the same e-mail account on both
computer and phone, rather than requiring people to remember a
special account name to reach you by phone.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few snags, however. First, you won't be able to view
nontext messages, which seemed to comprise about half my mail.
Second, you'll need to wade through oceans of spam. I recommend
using Hotmail's new feature to direct spamlike mail to a special
folder, so it doesn't clog up your inbox. Finally, there's no way
to delete messages using the phone, a major oversight.
</P>
<P>
   You can also send mail from your Hotmail account on the phone,
but composing messages using the phone keypad is tedious, to say
the least. It's most useful for quick messages, like ``I'll be home
late'' or ``Meeting confirmed for 2 p.m.'' The phone does include
software called T9 that eases typing chores.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, T9 has a built-in dictionary that translates words
typed with the nine keys into the most likely candidate. Otherwise,
you would need to press the 2 key twice to represent the letter B,
the 9 key four times for the letter Z, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Some key combinations have more than one translation, but
hitting the ``next'' key cycles you through the options. This
system works amazingly well, saving a lot of keying time and
effort, although it will never be fast. We just wish there were a
special mode for entering e-mail addresses and URLs, which gave us
the most problems.
</P>
<P>
   The MSN Mobile information services are also handy, although not
essential for most people. Over the Easter weekend, I used the
flight status feature (through Expedia.com) to check on actual
flight times for various relatives coming in from around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   I could get the status repeatedly for delayed flights just by
pressing the back button. Watching the stock market indexes fall
last week was also entertaining, although since prices are delayed
15 to 20 minutes, day traders will need to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   More useful was the local business directory. You can find
businesses by ZIP code in many categories, such as restaurants and
movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The address of my favorite local Chinese restaurant pops right
up when I click on ``Dining'' and ``Chinese.'' Then you can also
get driving directions if you need them.
</P>
<P>
   Other options range from bagel shops to ATM locations and car
repair services. MSN Mobile is also available for Palm and Windows
CE devices, so if you have a PDA as well, your account can do
double duty.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Online is actually the second such service in the Bay
Area. Sprint's PCS Wireless Web, which uses information services
from Yahoo, CNN, MapQuest and several others, was the first. With
more time on the market, Sprint has signed up more information
partners than Nextel.
</P>
<P>
   Two examples: eCompare.com, which allows you to compare online
prices for items that you see as you shop in retail stores; and
Dictionary.com, a dictionary lookup and translation service.
</P>
<P>
   How do prices compare? Nextel Online adds $14.95 to your basic
calling plan, or $19.95 including the Web-browsing capability.
Since only a few Web pages are phone-friendly thus far, we
recommend going with the $14.95 service for now.
</P>
<P>
   This includes unlimited use of the MSN service, which does not
count toward calling-plan minutes; 300 text messages (such as the
automated alert services) are also included, more than enough for
most users.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Sprint's Wireless Web option costs $9.99 a month,
but you'll pay extra for text messages, starting at $1.99 for 30
messages, or $9.99 for 200. More importantly, you'll also pay 10
cents per minute for Web access to information services with
Sprint, a big advantage for Nextel.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of making the leap to digital anyway, by all
means get a Web-enabled phone, even if you don't sign up for the
PCS services right away.
</P>
<P>
   And if you frequently check stock prices, need directions or
just want to check movie times, you're already a prime candidate
for a PCS service. I didn't think I was, but I got used to the
convenience very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Becky Waring at &LR;  becky(AT)waring.org. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
