<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MEDIA BYTES: NEW-ECONOMY MAGS STILL GROWING  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Upside update: The San Francisco monthly's
former editor, Adrian Mello, whose departure last month sparked
widespread defections at the magazine, has landed on his feet and
brought a few former colleagues with him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Upside Media, the mag's parent company, is showing
some signs of maturity: It's gone on a hiring binge, it's opening
new offices, it reorganized and it hired _ at last _ a chief
financial officer and a director of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to help recruit and retain employees, Upside has
even started matching 401(k) contributions, and even though the
company is privately held and events of recent weeks have sent the
market for new stocks into the dumper, it's giving all employees
stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come too late for Mello and company, but perhaps
that's for the best. Mello will be editor of a new magazine and Web
operation in the (sorry, I'm about to use two terms I hate,
back-to-back) B2B space. That is, it'll be devoted to covering
businesses that cater to other businesses, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a niche that makes sense to Mello, who cites forecasts that
predict the B2B market will rise to nearly $2 trillion by 2003, or
10 times the consumer Internet market. Companies are jumping into
B2B to save money and become more efficient _ and will be hungry
for information on how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The publication is titled Line56, which must refer to something,
but I can't tell what from its Web site ( &LR; www.line56.com &LR; ). The
name may not stick, anyway. It's planning to launch July 1. The
site up now is merely a prototype, which is a good thing. It's a
jargon-packed listing of news stories that could use a hefty
revamping.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Line56 is trying to carve out a niche in a crowded
marketplace. At least with Mello, it's off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Mello, a seasoned journalist who once edited Macworld, has
already signed up former Upside Features Editor Howard Baldwin as
executive editor for the magazine and former PC World and Cnet
Computers.com Editor Eric Knorr as executive producer of the Web
site. The parent company, B2B E-Commerce International Inc., is
based in Los Angeles, but execs were willing to let Mello establish
the editorial operations in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognized this is where the pool of editorial talent is,
both for the magazine and the Web,'' Mello said.
</P>
<P>
   Mello's old boss, Upside CEO David Bunnell, couldn't resist a
poke, suggesting the publication change its name to ``2B or not
2B.'' Bunnell said with the latest challenges in the stock market,
investment in Internet firms will tighten _ and those companies
won't spend as much money on advertising. ``It's going to be
somewhat more difficult for newcomers to join the party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said the same thing when the Industry Standard came
out,'' Mello said. ``Who would think even a year ago you could have
the number of publications in this space, and they'd be doing as
well as they're doing. ... I would much rather be on a publication
that focuses on a specific need than be at one like Upside that's
one among many. What really distinguishes them from the market
leaders like the Industry Standard and Business 2.0?''
</P>
<P>
   It's funny that Bunnell describes a tightening ad market, since
that climate could hurt Upside, too. But Bunnell was typically
upbeat about his own prospects. Upside was the first new-economy
magazine, before even Wired, before there even was a new economy.
But as it approaches its 11th birthday, it has lost some luster to
newer, hotter magazines like the Industry Standard and Red Herring.
</P>
<P>
   Indefatigably, Bunnell plows ahead. He's hired 25 people in the
last three weeks, bringing the company to about 80 employees. He's
carved it into three divisions, devoted to the magazine, online and
events.
</P>
<P>
   He'll move the events business out of the Market Street offices
to 333 Sacramento St. in the Financial District, and the growing
online business _ run by his son, Aaron Bunnell, and posting 20
original stories a day _ will move to a new floor in the Market
Street headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He hired Rambabu ``Bobby'' Yarlagawda to be his chief financial
officer, the first one at the firm; Yarlagawda had been CFO at
Living Books, once a high-flying joint venture between Random House
and Broderbund Software.
</P>
<P>
   On the news side, he's brought in Tom Coyle from Dow Jones as
senior editor, reporter Rex Crum from Investors Business Daily and
reporter Adam Feuerstein from the San Francisco Business Times. To
replace the ousted impresario David Coursey as host of the Digital
Living Room, one of Upside's most popular events, Bunnell has
tabbed veteran ``Computer Chronicles'' television host Stewart
Cheifet.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell is luring these folks with the currency of the day:
stock options. Upside Media has only 3.5 million shares
outstanding, and Bunnell is giving employees the chance to buy in
at $10 a share _ even though he thinks the company is worth at
least triple the $35 million valuation that would bring.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is, at this point, they could only sell those shares
to another investor. But since most of Upside's investors are
venture capitalists and entrepreneurs, Bunnell said, ``There's
pressure on management to develop the company in a way that there's
going to be liquidity. ... Either to go public or be acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: The Upside story is not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   NOTEWORTHY BYLINE: The San Jose Mercury News placed an ad in a
recent issue of the Industry Standard showing a Merc front page
with certain words highlighted. But the funny thing was, the lead
story on that front page was by Jonathan Rabinovitz, who's no
longer at the Merc.
</P>
<P>
   You can now find Rabinovitz's byline in ... the Industry
Standard.
</P>
<P>
   HOT, AND NOT: Red Herring made it official: It will double in
frequency, going biweekly starting in November. (Not that I need to
get more Red Herrings, but at least they should be smaller: June's
issue is due to weigh in at 628 pages. Spare me!)
</P>
<P>
   And Imagine Media, which is pouring energy into launching new
mags _ five due out by next year _ has actually closed one. A
moment of silence, please, for PC Accelerator, a mag for die-hard
gamers, which is shutting down with its June issue. Its staff will
live on in the virtual world, contributing content to Imagine's
online game site, at  &LR; www.dailyradar.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   JUMPING JODI: Last week, I dinged Jodi Mardesich for writing a
column in Fortune about Drspock.com and then leaving the magazine
to go work for the Web startup. She e-mailed me: ``What's wrong
with that? It would be wrong if I wrote about the company with the
intent to get a job there. ... Problem is, that's not what
happened. I wrote about the company because I had a deadline and I
had the information and I thought it was an interesting subject _ a
well-known, instant brand that a dot-com was going to leverage. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until after I wrote the article that I considered
what it might be like to work there. What it might be like to get
to do something meaningful and stop writing about the technology
business and rich people.''
</P>
<P>
   At Drspock.com, she said, ``We're taking a book and making it
into a kind of living encyclopedia. We have an opportunity to
influence the way people approach parenting, and one of my goals is
to make sure that all kinds of families are included in the
dialogue. I think it's an interesting project. There are a lot of
personal reasons that this particular startup appealed to me. The
money was one small reason.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at fostd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
