<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VIDEO-EDITING-SFCHRON     04-27 1966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-EDITING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VIDEO EDITING ISN'T A QUICK JOB  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Desktop movies _ now premiering at an iMac
near you,'' proclaim the Apple ads.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the idea of using a desktop computer for video editing
_ capturing raw footage from a camcorder, VCR or TV, then
reorganizing it, adding special effects and putting out a finished
movie _ is neither new nor limited to the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Apple itself has marketed video-ready Macs off and on since
1993, and a slew of PC add-ons have offered similar capabilities
for Windows users for at least as long.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Apple's video-capable iMacs, you don't need a
fancy new digital camcorder to turn your PC into an editing
station. Most of the PC products (as well as similar products for
older Macs) are designed to work with ordinary analog-format video
cameras, which still dominate the U.S. market, and with
conventional VCRs and televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the digital technology Apple is pushing has very real
advantages, including higher quality and faster transfers between
the video device and the computer. But you can get those benefits,
too, on a Windows PC, if you're so inclined.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of video capture-and-edit packages for the PC,
I selected three that seemed particularly promising for review. All
are powerful enough to create high-quality finished videos, yet
they cost less than $300 and they're all designed for ordinary,
nonexpert users.
</P>
<P>
   Matrox Marvel G400-TV
</P>
<P>
   The first of the products I tried, Matrox Graphics' Marvel
G400-TV, is an example of what might be called a multifunction
graphics card: It serves as a standard display card for your
monitor, while also providing additional features such as video-in
and -out ports _ without taking up extra slots inside your PC.
</P>
<P>
   Like its competitors in this category _ ATI Technology's
All-in-Wonder 128 ($199 and up) and 3dfx's Voodoo3 3500 TV ($249
list) _ the G400-TV includes everything but the kitchen sink when
it comes to graphics: fast 2-D and 3-D acceleration, DVD player
software, and a TV tuner through which you can record your favorite
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The G400, which requires an AGP slot, also offers an unusual
feature Matrox calls Dual-Head Display, which lets you use a TV or
analog flat-panel LCD as a second display alongside your regular
monitor. You can use the extra screen space in any application to
keep more data, palettes and controls in sight simultaneously. It's
especially handy for video work.
</P>
<P>
   The card comes with an external ``break-out box,'' which
provides a convenient way to connect audio, video (composite or
S-video) and cable TV without having to crawl around behind your
PC.
</P>
<P>
   No PC today, at least without expensive special equipment, can
handle the huge volume of data video generates, so all mainstream
video-capture products use one or another form of compression.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the G400, it's Motion JPEG. The results aren't
quite up to broadcast or DVD standards, but to me, the quality
seemed perfectly adequate, both on the computer screen and when
written back to tape, at the default compression level.
</P>
<P>
   Matrox bundles several video applications and utilities with the
card, but the main capturing and editing tool is a program called
Avid Cinema. While Avid is best known for its professional editing
systems, this program (originally developed in collaboration with
Apple) was designed with novices in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It starts by offering you a choice among a dozen templates, or
preplanned sequences, for subjects from ``My Summer Vacation'' to
``Sales Training.'' Then you go to Storyboard mode, where you're
encouraged to flesh out the template or develop your own
shot-by-shot plan before you begin editing.
</P>
<P>
   The program then leads you step-by-step through the process of
capturing and editing your video. It makes it easy to arrange and
trim your clips, superimpose titles and captions (stationary or
scrolling), add music or narration, and choose among scores of
special effects for transitions between scenes, from ``barnyard''
to zig-zag.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I found quite a few problems mixed with the
program's virtues. First, there's no printed or even electronic
manual. An animated guided tour serves as a partial substitute, but
just when it got to editing it produced a dialog box reporting
``Script error: Cannot divide by zero'' and couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   While digitizing footage from my video camera, the program
repeatedly encountered errors that forced it to stop recording. It
uses QuickTime, Apple's cross-platform multimedia technology, but
requires Version 3 and isn't compatible with the current release,
Version 4.0.1. If you want to use the newer version with other
programs, you're forced into a constant shuffle of tedious
reinstallations.
</P>
<P>
   These are the sorts of glitches you might expect in a 1.0
release, which is exactly what the Matrox version of Avid Cinema
is. In this case, however, the program isn't about to get fixed:
Avid abandoned it last year. (There is actually a 1.5 version,
which fixes the QuickTime problem among others, but it's not
available for owners of the Matrox version.)
</P>
<P>
   The G400-TV is indisputably a graphics powerhouse, but features
alone don't compensate for problems like these. For nearly $300,
customers deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   Pinnacle Studio DC10 plus
</P>
<P>
   I had better luck with Pinnacle Systems' Studio DC10 plus, a PCI
card whose price has recently dropped to a suggested $149.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Matrox Marvel, the DC10 plus is a one-trick
pony: It doesn't replace a standard display card, nor does it
include TV and DVD features; its sole function is digitizing video
and helping you edit it.
</P>
<P>
   Because Pinnacle develops its own software, it's fully supported
and much more cohesive than the Matrox mishmash. It lacks the
novice-oriented features of Avid Cinema, but it does come with a
comprehensive printed manual.
</P>
<P>
   And it incorporates a terrific feature Avid lacks: Using an
algorithm that studies composition, color and other variables, the
program automatically detects scene changes and on that basis
divides captured footage into a series of smaller clips, each
represented on-screen by a thumbnail image of its opening frame.
For novices, starting with a series of small clips that can be
easily manipulated is a whole lot less intimidating than facing one
long, undifferentiated sequence.
</P>
<P>
   In other respects, the Studio DC10 plus application works
similarly to Avid Cinema. Incoming video is compressed in Motion
JPEG format as it's digitized. To edit your footage, you drag
around the thumbnails, then add titles, sound and special effects.
Built into the program is a library of more than 130 wipes and
dissolves for scene transitions, a collection of canned sounds, and
a title generator that makes it easy to add TV-style flying credits
and other fancy touches.
</P>
<P>
   When you're satisfied with your work _ or just tired of it _ you
switch to Make Movie mode. If you choose to produce a videotape,
rendering takes a long time (as with Avid Cinema or any other
product). Alternatively, you can leave the film in Pinnacle's own
compact digital format and play it on a TV or video monitor
connected to the DC10 plus card, or output an AVI file that can be
played on any PC.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, I was delighted with how well the Studio DC10 plus
worked, especially considering its very reasonable price. The only
real catch: You need a free PCI slot for it, and you have to open
your PC to install it or find someone else to do that for you.
</P>
<P>
   Pinnacle Studio DV
</P>
<P>
   The basis for Apple's ``desktop movies'' marketing campaign is
FireWire, a high-speed digital data transfer technology originally
developed at Apple and then adopted by virtually all manufacturers
of digital camcorders as their standard for connecting to
computers.
</P>
<P>
   FireWire ports are built into the iMac DV series as well as
Apple's business-oriented products, the Power Mac G4 and the latest
PowerBook. Having this technology designed into hardware and the
operating system from the ground up gives Apple a big advantage in
digital video.
</P>
<P>
   But by no means does it have a monopoly on the technology.
Compaq, Gateway and Sony offer Windows desktops and notebooks that
also have it built in, although they call it by different names _
i.Link in Sony's case, and IEEE 1394 (the technical name for the
industry standard built around the Apple technology) in others.
Most of these come with bundled video-editing software.
</P>
<P>
   You can also add 1394 ports to a standard PC that didn't have
the technology built in at the factory. Provided that you're
running Windows 98 (Second Edition strongly recommended), all you
have to do is find a free PCI slot, install a card and some
software, and you're ready to connect to a digital camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies now offer such cards at street prices under
$100, with video-editing software included. Being so pleased with
Pinnacle's consumer-level analog-video product, I opted to test its
digital cousin, Studio DV ($149 list, as little as $80.95 online).
</P>
<P>
   The card provides three FireWire ports through which you can
bring in footage from MiniDV- and Digital8-format camcorders. (For
my testing, I used a Sony DCR-PC1 Handycam.)
</P>
<P>
   The downside of digital video's high quality is that it takes an
enormous amount of disk space when you move it to your hard drive.
Even though all DV footage is automatically compressed at a 5-1
ratio, it still fills 3.6 megabytes per  &LR; second &LR; , or almost a
quarter of a gigabyte per  &LR; minute &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Since even today's humongous hard drives fill up pretty quickly
at that rate, Studio DV lets you import and edit your footage in a
preview mode that requires only 150 to 300 megabytes of space per
 &LR; hour &LR; , depending on your quality settings. When you're done
editing, the program does have to import all the footage you've
decided to include in your finished film at full DV size, but the
preview mode at least saves you from wasting disk space on material
you don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Studio DV's editing features are similar to those of the analog
DC10 plus. Unlike that product and the Matrox Marvel, however, the
DV card doesn't have a video-out port for a TV or VCR. Instead, it
writes your edited film back to your camcorder. That's not a real
problem, though, because most digital camcorders have a video-out
port built in, so you just connect that to your display or VCR.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to save your movie as a computer file, Studio DV
lets you choose between AVI, MPEG and RealVideo formats.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't test all these options, but everything I tested worked
well. In fact, though I like the iMovie application Apple bundles
with its FireWire-equipped iMacs, I liked Studio DV even better:
Its scene-detection feature worked better, and its preview mode
eases the pressure on your disk capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Closing Thoughts
</P>
<P>
   Whatever product you choose, whether analog or digital, video
editing places heavy demands on your hardware. You'll want a system
with the fastest processor and the largest, fastest hard drives you
can swing.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need time and patience. You can flip through a roll
of still snapshots in a minute, but simply reviewing a half hour of
video takes a half hour _ even before you start your digitizing,
reorganizing, adding special effects and all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that cost, you may not want to bother for every home
video _ I certainly don't. But for special occasions, and for
anyone who simply enjoys moviemaking for its own sake, it's nice to
know that you can now turn an ordinary PC into an amazingly
powerful editing station _ without even spending a fortune on it.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
