<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-27 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EWING'S PLAY WON`T PASS UNNOTICED 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hello to you, too, Jeff Van Gundy. We, the people,
the true Knicks fans, know all too well that your team was 8-3 with
Patrick Ewing in the playoffs last season, and 4-5 without him. We
know we can't win the championship without him. Know what, Coach?
We like what we saw on Wednesday night better. We loved the sight
of Latrell Sprewell on the left side of the basket, sizing up Vince
Carter, readying his game-winning drive and jumper in the lane,
while not a groan could be heard in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal. Good for you for defending your big fella. We,
too, respect his work ethic, his unshakable faith in himself. We
sure appreciated his 19 points and 9 rebounds in Wednesday night's
84-83 Game 2 victory, and the way he charged out of the lane with
7-feet worth of wingspan as Dee Brown clanged Toronto's last hope
off the back rim.
</P>
<P>
   We're still going to whine when he gets the ball in the post
during future tension-filled moments, and starts doing his
backing-in thing.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old habit, difficult to explain, harder to break. We are
New Yorkers and Knicks fans, cynical by nature and conditioned by
26 years of not winning the really big one. We have been fired up
so many times only to have our pilot lights blown out by events
unforeseen. When the ball goes inside and there is just too much
time to contemplate the failures of yore, the only viable
alternative to groaning is to not breathe at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other guys can miss and it's not the same reaction,'' Van
Gundy said before the Knicks took command of the first-round
series. ``There's something there, but I don't what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Coach. We're smart enough to know Ewing isn't the
reason we are title-less, at least not directly. He is just the
window through which we see Charles Smith under the basket
surrounded by the Chicago skyline, and John Starks misfiring in the
fourth quarter in Houston, and Reggie Miller loading up in front of
Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing gets the ball in the scary moments, we momentarily
have to forget we are looking at a certified Hall of Famer, one of
the greats. We can't help but see the silhouette of his
contemporaries who just happened to be greater. From Magic to Larry
to Hakeem to Michael to Tim Duncan, we have conceded too often that
it is some other star's turn.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, it is obviously not yet Vince Carter's. It is
supposed to be Shaquille O'Neal's. So yes, until Ewing wins, we
will groan. And then we will stand up and cheer like crazy people
if he happens to win his ring.
</P>
<P>
   Fickle? That's one way of looking at this love-hate
relationship, this complex affair. But that would be the wrong way.
Consider our groaning to be more of a greeting. Hello, Patrick. We,
the people, are still out here, still snatching up every ticket at
grossly inflated prices, still waiting, still with ya. Even if we
have to remind you now and then that we have much more confidence
in Sprewell and Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   No offense. We just prefer the new script after witnessing the
horribly timed torn Achilles' tendon, the coming and going of the
Bulls and every other act of finger-rolling fate that's conspired
against you, and us.
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of the playoffs are anything like these first two
games, hang in there, bear with us, it's going to be as tense, as
dicey, as that timeout Wednesday night with 54.8 seconds left and
the Raptors clinging to an 83-80 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing held Vince Carter flashing across the middle, without the
ball, putting him on the line. One of the faithful behind the bench
yelled in your face: ``Come on, Patrick. Use your brain. He wasn't
even in the play.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not what Ewing wanted to hear from the people who don't
appreciate him enough. Much more colorfully, he suggested the
paying customer sit down and mind his own business.
</P>
<P>
   Well, everything turned out fine, as Van Gundy made the wise
calls down the stretch, letting Sprewell and Houston take the game
from Carter and Tracy McGrady, who are long on talent and woefully
short on shot selection.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans could enjoy the 2-0 lead, and three days off to
dream about eventually turning the tables on Shaq and the Lakers,
who put the Knicks away like a folding chair, much like Toronto,
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   After 26 years, after 15 with Ewing, we are used to fantasy
ultimately being rejected by fate. We are entitled to worry that
this is not going to turn out like Wednesday night, especially when
Ewing gets the late call. Hello, Coach. Stop worrying that our
groaning ``takes away'' from your home-court advantage. Hello,
Coach. Just keep giving the ball to Sprewell and Houston at the
end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
