<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASHING IN AN OVERDUE RAIN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Writer's note: Most of what follows was written on
March 6, a Monday, when the high tem perature was 52 degrees and we
got 1.53 inches of rain. The column was stored in the computer ice
chest and not published because there was other news to write about
that day. Besides, I figured it would be best to serve it up, like
a frosty beverage, on our first 100-degree day. Before you
continue, remember, in order to prevent brain freeze, take small
sips:
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman called this morn ing to say she was worried about the
homeless out in the rain and cold. A lobbyist called to say she was
worried about a bill at the Legislature. A reader called to say he
was worried about his sanity. ``I agreed with you last week for the
first time ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was unopened mail on the desk, unread e-mail on the
computer screen, and it was the day before Super Tuesday. After
sifting through all the potential stories, weighing each against
the next, I did the only logical thing a longtime Arizona re porter
could do:
</P>
<P>
   I went to the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   I had no choice. It was raining. It wasn't one of those
late-summer thunderstorms that come boiling up from the south, then
barrel into town, muscles flexed.
</P>
<P>
   It was just rain.
</P>
<P>
   Gray skies. Cold damp air. The kind of weather that tasted
horrible to you as a kid, like wine, but tastes glo rious to you
now, like wine.
</P>
<P>
   It was our second day of rain, and even better than the first.
Colder, more gray and constant.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, fallen leaves stuck like postage stamps to the tops of
automobiles and the bottoms of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Children walking to school reached out from under their
umbrellas to catch raindrops in the palms of their hands, then lick
them off.
</P>
<P>
   On a normal day in March, the Phoenix Zoo would be filled with
tourists _ 3,000 or so, I was told _ but not this day. The man
taking tickets at the main entrance said he'd counted 14 patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the animals are staying inside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian elephant stood in the doorway of her barnlike
residence, shifting her weight back and forth and gently shaking
her head, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the alligators rose from the depths of their muddy pond,
choosing to watch the dance of raindrops on the water's surface
from below.
</P>
<P>
   An Aldabra tortoise was outside, but tucked into its shell and
blending into the landscape like a slick boulder.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a day to see the animals. It was a day to see the zoo,
the grounds painted in dark colors by the rain.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a day to see downtown Phoenix, chilled and looking _
as it does only in the rain _ like a real downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And a day to study the city from the overlooks on South Mountain
Park, where the parking lot was empty except for my pickup.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, the full weight of the moist air fell like gauze over
town, obscuring the view, making it magical.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the way tourists find the desert magical, but in a way
that only people who have been here for a long time can appreciate.
Vaca tioners come to Phoenix ex pecting the typical day to be sunny
and warm. We live with the knowledge that just about every day is
sunny and warm. But the rest are even better.
</P>
<P>
   Like Monday, March 6, a typically beautiful day in the desert,
only more so. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
