<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     04-27 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT, SLICK LABAUVE A STAR ON CYCLING HORIZON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas _ We have seen the future of American sprint
cycling _ and it just shaved its hair off.
</P>
<P>
   Serious times call for serious haircuts. And Jeff Labauve, the
slick new hope on the U.S. track cycling scene, knows that the
Sydney Olympics are no longer just a dream on a distant calendar.
</P>
<P>
   His specialty, for now, is called the Olympic Sprint, a new
event on the Sydney card. Three cyclists from the same team circle
the track, racing against time. Each must lead for one lap and then
pull off the track.
</P>
<P>
   The premium is on teamwork and speed, and Labauve is all about
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he rode a personal best this morning,'' Des Dickie,
coach of the American sprint team, said after yesterday's session
of the U.S. Olympic Trials for Track Cycling. ``But Jeff has been
doing that all week.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's two reigning Olympic track medalists, Marty
Nothstein and Erin Hartwell, can't sprint forever. Hartwell, a
medal winner both in Barcelona and Atlanta in the kilometer time
trial, has already bowed to injuries and seeks to remake himself in
the 4,000-meter individual pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Labauve, on the other hand, is only 21 and, Dickie said, ``He
has just continued to improve all year, from the first camp we had
in December.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his threesome did not make the Olympic Sprint finals last
night, Labauve and his new haircut took them around the track in
18.34 seconds, the fastest opening lap of the session. Dickie was
more than pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a bright spot,'' said the coach, who could well team
Labauve, Nothstein and a third sprinter for the event in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, however, Labauve wasn't even a blip. He was
12-years-old when he started riding on the roads and levees around
his hometown of Metairie, La. And he was 15 when he first climbed
aboard a bike on a velodrome track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared out of my mind,'' Labauve said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got over the fear of the 33-degree banking _ which is
nothing now _ I loved it. It was like a big roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   His cycling friends who watched him on that first track in Baton
Rouge, La., knew that young Labauve was on to something.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all pretty much in agreement that I was a talent,''
he recalled. ``They just didn't know what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So he trained himself. Made up his own schedule. Clocked his own
times.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up _ this kid from cycling Neverland _ at the 1997
Junior National Track Cycling Championships and qualified first in
the 200-meter sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just stronger than everybody else,'' Labauve reasoned.
``But when I got in there with the elite riders and we raced, I got
killed because I didn't know how to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Labauve's fourth-place finish, however, plus a third in the
kilometer time trial, had caught the eye of U.S. coaches. They
invited him in 1998 to a monthlong camp in the track cycling mecca
of Trexlertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Frisco one month later for his first senior national
championships and finished fourth in the sprint and fifth in the
Olympic Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably my breakthrough,'' Labauve said.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded a cycling scholarship to Collin County Community
College, home of the Superdrome, and moved to Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   The star was born. In 1999, the kid from Louisiana raced in
World Cup events in Spain and Italy. At the Open des Nations in
France, he raced in front of 10,000 Parisians chanting, ``U-S-A!
U-S-A!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that,'' Labauve said, ``make me want to do this
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet, 2 inches, and 210 pounds, Labauve is built like a
younger Nothstein. In the weight room, he squat-lifts 420 pounds
and clean-and-jerks 260 _ no one on the track does more, the
coaches say.
</P>
<P>
   As the resident hero at the Superdrome, Labauve's face adorns
the Olympic trials' souvenir poster. With Dickie, the national
sprint coach, now guiding his training program, Labauve has a firm
idea what the U.S. program's plans are for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we're planning on the Olympics this year,'' Labauve said.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his commitment, he arrived at the starting line
yesterday sporting a menacing goatee and a no-nonsense shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I saw today,'' said Dickie, who meant the lap
time, presumably.
</P>
<P>
   It was the look of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Bright and slick.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
