<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOSIDE1-ADDONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MACS BENEFIT FROM ADD-ONS  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although Apple Computer has made ``desktop
movies'' the center of its marketing efforts this year, even Mac
owners are likely to have to add extra hardware or software before
their machines are ready for video-editing duty.
</P>
<P>
   IMac DV models (the ones now priced at $1,299 and $1,499) have
FireWire ports for connecting to digital camcorders, and they come
with an easy-to-use video capture and editing program called
iMovie. But they have no built-in capability to handle video from
analog sources such as TVs, VCRs and the vast majority of
camcorders in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Power Mac G4 models (like the blue-and-white G3 models) and the
latest PowerBook also have FireWire ports, but Apple chose not to
include editing software with those models and they too are
unprepared for analog video. If you have an older Mac, unless it's
one of Apple's old AV models or you've already added a card, you're
at square one.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, reasonably priced third-party products can fill
these gaps, even though the selection isn't as wide as Windows
users enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   If you already have FireWire ports and a digital camcorder,
Apple won't, at least for now, give or even sell you a copy of
iMovie, but a company called Digital Origin (a descendant of the
old Radius) offers a software-only package called EditDV Unplugged
for $149. The company also offers a free online DV primer
( &LR; www.digitalorigin.com/learn/default.html &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in professional-level applications, and you
can afford their hefty prices, Adobe's Premiere ($599) can handle
digital video, as can Apple's own Final Cut Pro ($999). At the
other extreme, there are several shareware capture and editing
programs and even a free, unsupported Apple program called HackTV
(see links at  &LR; www.macintouch.com/firewire.htmledit &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   If your Mac doesn't have FireWire ports but does have a free PCI
slot, several companies, including Adaptec, Orange Micro and
PowerLogix, sell cards that add FireWire ports. Macally, Newer
Technology and VST Technology also offer FireWire PC cards for
recent PowerBooks.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Mac (old or new) with PCI slots and you're
interested in capturing video from analog sources, the best bet I
know of is ATI Technologies' Xclaim VR 128 card ($229 and up),
which offers QuickTime-based video editing along with fast 2-D and
3-D graphics and a TV tuner.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative for users who have FireWire ports: Sony's Media
Converter DVMC-DA1, a $399 external box, and a new model called the
DVMC-DA2 convert analog video to DV form and transfer it via 1394
( &LR; www.macintouch.com/dvmc.html &LR; ). Sony Digital8 camcorders have
similar conversion capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Mac with USB ports but no PCI slots _ a non-DV
iMac, for example _ you can use a USB capture device for analog
video. Options include Ariston's iView ($119.95), Eskape Labs'
MyCapture II ($129.99) and XLR8's Interview ($79).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0026EDT &QL; 
