A8439 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VIDEOSIDE2-SNAPPY-SFC     04-27 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOSIDE2-SNAPPY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EDITING OUTSIDE THE BOX  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Those who don't have room for a new card in
their PC, or don't want to face installing one, can look to a
variety of external video-capture devices that connect to your PC's
printer port or, in the case of newer products, to a Universal
Serial Bus port.
</P>
<P>
   Such solutions range from Play Inc.'s Snappy Deluxe ($139.95
list), an upgraded version of a classic PC product designed
originally for grabbing single frames from a video source, to
Dazzle Multimedia's $249.99 Digital Video Creator, which is
available with either a parallel-port or USB interface.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, TV-tuner add-ons for PCs, such as Hauppauge's WinTV
series and Pinnacle Systems' PCTV products, can digitize video from
other sources as well as TV.
</P>
<P>
   While all these products have their merits, their video
capabilities are no match for those of dedicated products like
Pinnacle Systems' Studio DC10 plus. Mini-movies made with Snappy
Deluxe 3.0, for example, display only two frames per second. The
Dazzle product is much more capable than that _ it can generate
MPEG-1 clips with 30 frames per second _ but its resolution is
limited to a maximum of 352 by 240 pixels.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for clips to e-mail to friends or post on your Web
site _ the product even supports the RealVideo streaming format _
but not for output to tape.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
