<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: FILE TRANSFER A SAFE BET WITH CD-R  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: &LR;  I am considering a desktop PC with a built-in Zip drive. &LR; 
 &LR; However, my office computer doesn't have a Zip drive. A &LR; 
 &LR; salesperson suggested as an alternative a recordable CD drive, &LR; 
 &LR; which would let me create, back up and store files on CDs. That &LR; 
 &LR; way, I could take the CDs to work and access the files. What do &LR; 
 &LR; you think? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: I think you ran into a salesman who knows what he's talking
about. A recordable CD drive (CD-R for short) is a good idea
because almost every PC can use CDs, while Zip drives are far less
common.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can cram up to 650 megabytes of information on a CD,
whereas Iomega's Zip drives top out at 250 MB (Iomega also makes a
2-gigabyte Jaz drive, but it's priced at more than $300. For less
than that, you can get a CD-R drive _ and you'll pay even less if
the thing is built into the computer you buy (the Compaq 7588 PC,
with a CD-R drive, can be had for about $1,300).
</P>
<P>
   Blank CDs for recording also are coming down in price _ you can
get them for less than $1 apiece. Expect to pay maybe twice as much
for CD-RW discs (rewriteable disks that you can erase and reuse).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Don't Mix Vendors
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm thinking about getting a new iMac, but I also need a
laptop. Should I stay with Apple products for both, or can a
Windows laptop work just as well with the iMac? Apple Powerbooks
cost more, it seems, than comparable Windows laptops, and
unfortunately, I can't stand the looks of the iBook (Apple's entry
level laptop).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I'd stick with one or the other. Mixing Apples and
Windows is, well, like apples and oranges. The operating systems
are different, and the file formats are different, so you'll need
to buy both Mac and Windows versions of application programs if you
want them on both computers. (You could use software on the Mac
that emulates Windows, but then what's the point?)
</P>
<P>
   The only situation in which I'd endorse a mix of Mac and Windows
is if the computers don't have to share files. For instance, if you
intend to use the desktop computer mostly for the Internet and the
laptop mostly for work, then you can probably get away with an iMac
and a Windows laptop. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMATIC RESPONSE UPDATE: Last week, I suggested a way in which
DSL and cable users can rig their PCs to send automatic e-mail
responses when they're on vacation. A reader points out that some
ISPs will do this for you. So check with your ISP first. The reader
also noted that in some cases an automatic response may not be wise
for a couple of reasons: 1. it confirms to spammers that they've
found a valid e-mail address; and 2. it lets strangers know that
your house is empty.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Save your work. Often. I can't tell you how many times my
computer has frozen for some weird reason, forcing me to restart
the thing, only to find that I've lost something I'd written but
hadn't bothered to save. If it's too much trouble to click on the
disk icon in the toolbar or go to Save in the File menu, just press
the ``S'' key while holding down the Control key (usually labeled
``Ctrl''). This combination works with almost every Windows
program. An ounce of prevention, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Einstein at computers(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
