<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-EARNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHEVRON'S EARNINGS HIT RECORD  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sky-high oil prices resulted in record quarterly
earnings for San Francisco's Chevron Corp., with the company's
profits rising almost fourfold to more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a good year for Chevron,'' said Matthew
Warburton, an analyst with brokerage Warburg Dillon Read in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But do not expect Chevron's windfall to result in lower prices
at the pump. The bulk of the company's earnings stemmed from
overseas sales of oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $1.1 billion pocketed in the first three months of the
year, only $55 million came from refining and selling fuel in the
United States, down 43 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lower U.S. gas returns reflect costly repairs to Chevron's
Richmond refinery, as well as extensive maintenance at a facility
in Pascagoula, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   For the average consumer, however, it may be hard to accept that
Chevron's bulging pockets are not a direct result of staggeringly
high gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, apparently sensing a public relations
disaster in the making, were prepared yesterday to explain the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We empathize with the consumer,'' said Dawn Soper Lyon, a
Chevron spokeswoman. ``But the reality is that our record earnings
were dependent almost exclusively on a part of our business that
nobody here in the United States has anything to do with.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that it would not be feasible to apply profits from
overseas sales to reducing prices at U.S. pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't look at underwriting one segment of our business with
profits from another,'' Lyon said. ``Prices at the pump are
dictated by the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The market has not been especially friendly in recent months to
U.S. motorists, particularly those in the Bay Area. With oil prices
averaging almost $29 a barrel during the quarter _ more than double
a year ago _ gas prices have soared to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent survey of gasoline costs, the state chapter
of the American Automobile Association found that San Francisco
motorists are paying an average $1.92 for a gallon of self-service
unleaded gas.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers in San Jose are paying $1.85, while those in Oakland are
paying $1.86 and in Santa Rosa $1.78.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Fortier, an energy-industry analyst with Olde Discount
Corp. in Detroit, said Chevron and other oil companies cannot
really be held accountable for high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to blame anyone, blame OPEC,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By limiting production in the first quarter, oil-producing
nations managed to drive crude oil prices as high as $34 a barrel.
Most analysts expect that figure to stay around $25 as production
increases over coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This will result in lower profits for Chevron, but analysts
expect the company will continue having a banner year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their profits will remain very strong,'' said Eugene Nowak, an
analyst with brokerage ABN AMRO in New York. ``They've done a great
job with production around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of steady production and high crude oil costs
meant that Chevron was able to report first-quarter profit of $1.68
a share _ way up from 43 cents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Such returns helped the company's stock resist an otherwise
gloomy day for financial markets. Chevron's share price rose $1.50
yesterday to close at $86.31.
</P>
<P>
   The company earned $653 million from finding and selling crude
oil overseas in the first quarter. It earned $365 million within
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron plans to apply a portion of its quarterly winnings to
repurchasing its own stock _ a move intended to boost the share
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a public company, we have a responsibility to maximize
returns for shareholders,'' Lyon said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
