<SLUG> BC-BAYVIEW-RESIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAY VIEW BANK'S NO. 2 EXECUTIVE RESIGNS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The No. 2 executive of Bay View Bank has
resigned, a move analysts said signals strategic trouble at the San
Mateo institution.
</P>
<P>
   David Heaberlin, president of the bank and executive vice
president of its parent company, Bay View Capital, announced his
departure late Tuesday, a week after the company reported
disappointing first-quarter earnings. The resignation takes effect
June 30 and no replacement has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Bay View, with 58 branches and $6.4 billion in assets, is one of
the largest banks headquartered in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The bank gave no reason for the move and Heaberlin did not
return a call seeking comment. But analysts said they suspected the
50-year-old executive is leaving because the aggressive expansion
program he sponsored has lately gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went on an acquisition binge and it wasn't working,''
said Sutro &AMP; Co. analyst Campbell Chaney. ``Heaberlin was the fall
guy.``
</P>
<P>
   Bay View Chief Executive Officer Edward Sondker said the reasons
for Heaberlin's departure are confidential, but he emphatically
denied Heaberlin had been forced out. ``When (we're) getting beat
up, I'm the one who is accountable for that,'' Sondker said.
</P>
<P>
   With Heaberlin going, analysts said they expect Bay View's board
to give Sondker time to fix the bank's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Sondker and Heaberlin, both longtime financial services
executives, came to Bay View in 1995 when shareholders were
clamoring for a turnaround at the then-underperforming thrift.
</P>
<P>
   To rev up profits, the two decided to jettison Bay View's
low-margin mortgage business and concentrate on more lucrative
types of loans. Among other purchases, the thrift bought a
commercial finance and an auto loan company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bay View built up its deposit franchise by buying
Foster City's EurekaBank in 1997. Two years later, signifying its
shift away from home loans, it converted from a thrift to a bank.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Bay View's purchases made money. But signs of trouble
emerged in 1998 when Bay View tried to buy a company that
specialized in high-risk loans to homeowners. The deal fell apart
when federal regulators proposed strict limits on the proportion of
such loans a thrift could hold.
</P>
<P>
   Investors ``were very nervous about that foray,'' said
PaineWebber analyst Gary Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in a deal analysts say Heaberlin pushed, Bay View
bought Franchise Mortgage Acceptance, which specialized in lending
money to buyers of chain restaurants and gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the purchase depended on Bay View's ability to
package the loans for sale to institutional investors. But the
institutional loan market has dried up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Bay View's failure to sell off its franchise loans pushed net
income down to $500,000 in the first quarter, far below Wall
Street's expectations and down 90 percent from the same period in
1999. The bank's stock, meanwhile, has plunged to $7, far below its
1998 high of $38.25.
</P>
<P>
   Bay View's shares were the victim of rising interest rates and
investor distaste for small banks, Sondker said. But, he admitted,
the bank's first-quarter performance was ``ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to get better performance or something has to
change,'' Sondker said. He predicted the bank's results will
improve once it finds a way to sell off its franchise loans.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
