<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-27 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN NO KINGDOM FOR VINCE THE PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All he needed was one stop. He could poke the ball
away, block the shot, knock it off Latrell Sprewell's leg,
anything. One stop, and Vince Carter could vanquish this two-game
nightmare at Madison Square Garden, quiet the people who jeered
him, put an end to the perception he's not quite ready.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the incomparable forward of the Toronto Raptors, had
helped the Knicks with their comeback, taking an off-balance jump
shot that missed with 9 seconds left on the shot clock and more
than 25 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He also had five fouls, so now he could not play Sprewell as
aggressively as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But if he could just get a hand on the ball, everything would be
all right. That's what he was thinking as Sprewell released a
pretty jump shot over Carter's outstretched left arm with 7 seconds
left, a shot that gave the Knicks their first lead since the early
moments of the game and all but sealed Carter's inhospitable
welcome to a Madison Square Garden postseason.
</P>
<P>
   He passed up a shot at the top of the 3-point arc on Toronto's
last possession, giving it up to Dee Brown for a potential
game-winning 3-pointer. Brown missed, and Carter fell backward,
holding his hands to his head as if Toronto's season had come to an
unofficial end.
</P>
<P>
   He had heard the Game 1 jeers on Sunday, the cracks, the futile
attempts at humor. Carter especially heard the dozen or so Knick
zealots under the basket, derisively serenading him as he stepped
to the free-throw line in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vi-ince! Vi-ince!''
</P>
<P>
   Everything he did, they mocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you see on TV and then you're a part of it,''
he said. ``I didn't really notice it until a little later in the
game. And then I was like, `Whoa.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two-0. Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto did not lose because of Carter. At times, he was
awesome. In the final minutes, he dropped in an impossible runner
with the shot clock about to expire. He rejected a Larry Johnson
layup and retrieved the ball. He penetrated and found Muggsy Bogues
for a critical late 3-pointer. And he made two clutch free throws
with 54.8 seconds left to keep the Raptors ahead by 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 27 points and passed to the open man when
double-teamed. He did everything an All-Star should, except win.
Gone was the 3-for-20 showing on Sunday, the forced shots and the
ill-advised passes into traffic. But the noise was still there, the
throaty roar of the Garden, unleashed on another young superstar
trying to undo the home team.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Carter was awed by the way the crowd treated him like a
regular villain, as if he were Reggie or Michael or Scottie, or
some other despised opponent who had gunned down the Knicks with a
raised, clenched fist.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of him was wondering where all those appreciative
souls were from the regular season, the people who applauded his
30-plus-points nights and gasped at his breathtaking dunks.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Michelle Carter-Robinson, felt her son was disturbed
enough by his Game 1 showing that she made sure she sent him an
encouraging note to his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew I was getting down on myself and thinking about it
too much,'' he said. ``It was just a nice reminder. You know when
everybody else in the world is against you, at least Mom is on your
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter shuffled his feet and smiled, showing his fallible side
like few players of his stature. He did not put his eye contacts
in, instead wearing wire-rimmed spectacles to the morning practice
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Looking more professorial than superhuman, the future of the
Toronto Raptors and the National Basketball Association took an
assortment of wild, off-kilter shots after practice ended, the kind
you want to get out of your system before the game begins.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he stood 10 rows back across from the Knicks
bench, throwing up a prayer from about 50 feet. It never touched
the rim, but he enjoyed merely seeing it come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about the history of the building and the Knicks,'' he
said. ``When you step in here, that's the first thing you think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy, who once labeled Jordan ``a con man,'' cannot
think of a disparaging thing to say about Carter. He was flattered
when the All-Star forward brought Van Gundy, the East coach, over
to meet his parents at the midseason event in February.
</P>
<P>
   Carter did not make excuses for his poor performance on Sunday.
Instead, he paid Latrell Sprewell numerous compliments after
Sprewell shadowed him in Game 1. Carter does not say, ``I hate the
Knicks,'' like Tim Hardaway did two years ago or refer to them as
``mental midgets'' as Scottie Pippen did in 1997 after several
players left the bench against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Gracious, genuine, unbelievably talented, this is your new
archenemy, New York _ the guy who went out of his way on Wednesdayy
to compliment the staff of the team hotel for its courtesy and
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   He would be so much easier to detest if he scowled like Alonzo
Mourning or shimmied like Mark Jackson or did something uniquely
annoying, like file suit against Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we get Vince the Prince, the player with notes from his
mother next to his pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Carter is expecting charity. He understands the
dynamics of playing on the road in the NBA; most of the time, he
relishes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what basketball is all about,'' he said. ``Having the
home crowd yell against you and it gets all loud and everything. I
enjoy that. I love that. You couldn't tell it last game, but I
think that's the beauty of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors started much faster on Wednesday night than in Game
1, going up 26-15 in the first quarter. Carter turned the ball over
the first time he touched the ball, but made his next two shots and
seemed to settle down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind,'' he had said of the Garden crowd getting on
him. ``I didn't really get to play here in college or in high
school. When I got the chance to play here, I enjoyed it. It's a
nice place to play. The history makes it so different.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if he could just make fun of the home team, curse or commit
a flagrant foul, he might deserve the villainous treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there he lay, his hands on his head, at the top of the
arc, wondering when, or if, his Garden nightmare will ever end. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
