u p BC-NY-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-N     04-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN HALL MEETING PRODUCES FAMILIAR QUESTIONS FOR MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.Y. _ Answering questions on topics ranging from
economic growth and agriculture to health care and the fate of
Elian Gonzalez, Hillary Rodham Clinton held the first of a series
of town hall meetings on Wednesday night that her aides said would
be a new way of bringing her campaign directly to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing relaxed, with her hands frequently clasped in front of
her, Clinton stood to respond to questions from an audience of 350
students, faculty members and residents at the State University of
New York at Buffalo. The first hour was broadcast live on CNN, but
she continued to take questions for 40 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, she offered responses that have become part
of the stock of her campaign appearances. At the outset, for
example, Clinton faced the question that has been frequently
raised, when Wolf Blitzer, the program's moderator, asked her to
respond to criticisms that she was a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 30 years, I've worked on issues concerning
children and families,'' Clinton said. ``Those are the concerns of
my lifetime. As I've visited with thousands of New Yorkers, those
are their concerns. To me, it's a commitment to continue a life's
work.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that, if she won the Senate race, she would not
run for president in 2004 and that, if she lost, she would continue
to make New York her home. Some conservative groups and her
Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City, have
said that Clinton is using the Senate campaign as a stepping stone
to be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to serve my six-year term as senator,'' she said.
``I owe it to the people of New York. I want to help make things
happen in the state. That's what motivates me.''
</P>
<P>
   In many instances during questioning, Clinton was able to
showcase her growing knowledge of the state's characteristics,
rattling off, for example, the names of highways or companies in
western New York.
</P>
<P>
   She repeated her proposal to make the cost of college tuition
tax deductible up to $10,000 and reiterated her support for
creating a national program that would offer scholarships for
students who agreed to teach upon graduation in schools facing a
shortage of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether her views had changed from her first years in the
White House, when she championed a health care plan that critics
called nationalized medicine, she said she had learned from those
days, ``and I'm now from the school of smaller steps.''
</P>
<P>
   She then listed several measures she favored, including
prescription drug coverage for Medicare recipients and having more
children and more of the underinsured covered by health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated her support for abortion rights, but also
said she could support legislation backed by President Clinton that
would outlaw a procedure that critics call partial-birth abortion,
except in cases where the woman's health or life was at stake. She
said that congressional Republicans have refused to let that
legislation come up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   She also reiterated her support for Attorney General Janet
Reno's decision to use armed law enforcement officers to enter the
home of Elian Gonzalez. Clinton said, ``I think everyone would
agree that it was unfortunate that that kind of activity had to
take place.'' But then she added, ``I understand the concern and
the frustration of the Justice Department when faced with
continuing recalcitrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly criticized the Clinton administration
this week for its handling of the situation, calling the agents who
took the boy from his relatives' home last Saturday ``storm
troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the meeting began, Giuliani's aides were attacking
it, asserting that the crowd and questions had been fixed to spare
Clinton from any difficult moments, pointing to an article in The
Buffalo News that suggested the event had been carefully
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her whole campaign is so heavily scripted and staged that Mrs.
Clinton's handlers must be confident that tonight's event is
safe,'' said Bruce J. Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Blitzer said in an interview before the show that Clinton
had not requested, and CNN would not have permitted her to have,
any control over what questions would be asked or who would be
admitted to the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer said that CNN reviewed questions from audience members
only to ensure variety and to avoid repetition, and screened the
audience to make certain that it included only registered voters
who lived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton has no ideas what the questions are,'' Blitzer
said. ``She has had no role in this whatsoever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
