<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-FONTANA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT HOPES CALIFORNIA GOOD TO HIM AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Dale Jarrett is hoping for a little deja vu
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR veteran used a strong showing at last year's
California 500 to spark his march to the Winston Cup championship.
Jarrett, who is currently seventh in points, wouldn't mind a
similar scenario when qualifying for Sunday's NAPA Auto Parts 500
begins Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's activities, which include the Busch Grand National
Auto Club 300 and the Winston West Pontiac WideTrack Grand Prix 200
on Saturday, begin today with practice and first-round qualifying
for those two support races. Today's sessions are not open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``California was definitely important to us last year,'' Jarrett
recalled. ``We had a lot of problems throughout the day, but to
fight back and finish fifth at the end of the day helped us. It
helped us mentally, and it helped us because we could have lost 60
or 70 points toward the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is in a similar situation this year. After winning the
season-opening Daytona 500 in February, he has struggled with
inconsistency and is more than 200 points behind leader Mark
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (weekend) is a big race for us, too,'' said Jarrett, one
of the nine different winners at the nine Winston Cup events this
season. ``As I look back on our season to this point, I (see) that
we have performed better this year than what we did last year to
this point. We just don't have the finishes to show that, yet we've
performed well. That gives me the confidence that we can get the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is going to be an important race to us. It's the
type of race track that we have done well in the past. We need a
boost right now and that boost is getting back to victory lane. I
realize that nobody has done that more than once to this point, but
that would help our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's main competition this week could come from three-time
Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who recently broke a 13-race winless streak by winning
the DieHard 500 two weeks ago, is one of only two drivers to finish
in the top five at all three Winston Cup events at California
Speedway. He won the race in 1997 and '99 and finished fourth two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other favorites include Jack Roush racing entries Martin and
Jeff Burton; Bobby Labonte and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Favorites in the Busch Auto Club 300, scheduled for noon
Saturday, are points leader Jeff Green and Palmdale native Ron
Hornaday, who is fifth in points with two top-five finishes.
Winston Cup rookie Matt Kenseth won the event last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston West race, scheduled for 3:30 p.m. on Saturday,
could be wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas resident Brendan Gaughan is first in points, but he is
one of three different winners in the regional series. Others are
Kevin Richards (Phoenix) and David Star, who won last week's race
at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup regulars Ken Schrader and Johnny Benson are also
entered in the 100-lap race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
