<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENFORMA-SETTLEMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT-LOSS FIRM TO PAY MILLIONS IN SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-ENFORMA.F (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENCINO, Calif. _ In the largest settlement of its kind, an
company that markets a weight-loss system claiming to block fat and
burn calories without exercise agreed Wednesday to pay $10 million
to settle government charges that they used deceptive advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said Enforma Natural Products Inc.
used false claims about scientific testing to promote a combination
of pills as The Enforma System. The complaint names the company,
Chief Executive Officer Andrew Grey and former executive Fred
Zinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand by our products and are settling the case to avoid
spending years battling the FTC,'' Grey said. ``We have been very
successful and helped a lot of people lose 10, 20, 30 and even 100
pounds. We have sold the product to over a million people.''
</P>
<P>
   By reaching a settlement with the government, Enforma doesn't
admit breaking any laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grey added that the controversial infomercials pitching the
weight-loss product were pulled from the airwaves last month and
replaced by 30-second conventional spots that were approved by the
FTC.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its 30-minute infomercials, featuring former Los
Angeles Dodger Steve Garvey, the company used the Internet to sell
the product, which costs about $70 for a two-month supply of
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lose weight without dieting? Not a chance,'' said Jodie
Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection, in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miracle weight loss claims prey on people who are overweight
or obese,'' Bernstein said. ``When marketers promise effortless
weight loss, it's bad business. The fact is, there's only one sure
way to lose weight and keep it off: eat less and exercise more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Enforma System consists of two dietary supplements with
ingredients that are becoming increasingly popular with people
searching for weight loss remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The Fat Trapper is a chitosan-based product that purports to
prevent the absorption of dietary fat, while a pyruvate product
named Exercise In A Bottle supposedly increases the body's capacity
to burn fat.
</P>
<P>
   The company also claimed that Exercise In A Bottle works on a
cellular level, forcing every cell in a person's body to work
whether he is exercising or not.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FTC complaint, the government challenged these
assertions and said the company's advertising falsely claimed
scientific proof of its weight-loss, fat-absorption and fat-burning
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Grey disputed the government's claims that Enforma falsified
facts about its products in their infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we can support the claims,'' he said. ``We have years
of scientific studies that support our claims. We also have
conducted clinical trials.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Grey said from his point of view the dispute with the
FTC was not about the product, it was about the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Grey and his company will pay the FTC $10
million, which will be refunded to consumers who bought the weight
loss product directly from the Enforma prior to March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Zinos isn't required to make any payments, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the FTC decides the refunds are not practical, the agency
may choose to distribute the money to the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement doesn't affect the sale of The Enforma System in
stores, he said. However, the bottles will carry a disclaimer that
reads, ``A reduced caloric intake is required to lose weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey said the company began selling its weight-loss system
earlier this year in stores nationwide, including Rite Aid and
General Nutrition Centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in retail (stores), because it works,'' Grey said. ``As
long as our customers continue to buy our products, which we think
they will, our retail trading partners will continue to be very
satisfied with Enforma.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
