u k BC-EDIT-ETHICS-NYT &LR;      04-27 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ETHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ETHICS ECLIPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   The House Ethics Committee has quietly rescinded a 10-year-old
reform that required the committee to issue a report on its
findings when an investigation fails to result in charges against a
lawmaker. Members of the committee play down the change as a
mundane ``housekeeping matter'' that merely institutes a rule
approved by the full House in 1997 that gave the committee
discretion to withhold findings in such cases. But an ethics
watchdog group, the Congressional Accountability Project, points to
conflicting disclosure provisions in House rules and suggests the
committee's change may be timed to avoid issuing a potentially
embarrassing report in the event no charges result in the case of
Rep. Bud Shuster, the powerful Transportation and Infrastructure
Committee chairman. The committee has been conducting a prolonged
review of Shuster's financial and legislative dealings with a major
transportation lobbyist, Ann Eppard.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the committee's motives were pure, it should not be in
the business of burying its findings. Full disclosure is essential
to ensure full accountability of the House. It also provides a
vital check on the conscientiousness of a committee known to
deadlock on ethics cases along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   When the committee finally concludes the Shuster investigation,
the public is entitled to a report detailing its findings and
explaining its decision on whether or not to bring charges.
Meanwhile the full House needs to revisit the 1997 rules revisions
that expanded secrecy and foreclosed the filing of ethics
complaints by citizens, thereby weakening an already weak ethics
process. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
