<HEADER>
A8457 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-BRAVES-LA     04-27 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BRAVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BATS QUIET AGAIN IN LOSS TO BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One well-pitched game turned into two, and at that
point it wasn't a big deal. But the Dodgers, who peppered
Cincinnati pitching last weekend, are now in a terrible slump in
which they've scored once in 30 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers stopped their scoreless streak at 24 innings
Wednesday night, but they mustered little else. They fell meekly to
the Atlanta Braves 5-1 at Turner Field as their losing streak
stretched to three. Atlanta has won nine in a row.
</P>
<P>
   After losing a pair of 1-0 games in which they had just three
hits in each, the Dodgers managed only five off Kevin Millwood
(2-0) in seven innings. Mike Remlinger and John Rocker, who walked
the bases loaded in the ninth, each pitched an inning of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of not hitting, combined with an erratic strike
zone the last two games, has left the Dodgers hitters confused. It
also was the reason left fielder Gary Sheffield became the second
Dodger in as many nights to be ejected. He was tossed by home-plate
umpire Tim Tschida after being called out on strikes in the eighth,
but it began with an at-bat earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I questioned the call and I have a right to my opinion,''
Sheffield said. ``I didn't say anything to him the first time, I
just ran off the field and back to the dugout. Obviously, I was
frustrated and I went up there being aggressive and swinging at bad
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I struck out, he gestured to get out of here. I just
said, `The reason I swung at it is you're so brutal.' I wasn't
going to say anything until he made that gesture. That's showing me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, who was ejected Tuesday for
arguing a call on the bases, said he didn't go out and argue
immediately after Sheffield was tossed because he would have been
ejected as well. Instead, Johnson waited until between innings to
talk to Tschida, and they had a lively discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing on Sheff, I kind of saw it coming,'' said Johnson,
already ejected twice this season. ``He felt like (Tschida) called
a bad pitch on him the previous at-bat. I knew I'd get thrown if I
went out so I went out later. (Sheffield) felt he had a bad call
and it's a close ballgame. Sheff knows the strike zone very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike-zone situation isn't isolated to this series, though
it aided Tom Glavine's three-hit shutout Tuesday. Complaints have
been ongoing for years about how Braves pitchers get strike calls a
few inches off each side of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said Eric Gagne (0-1) and Alan
Mills were also the beneficiaries of an expanded strike zone,
though they lacked the ability to hit spots effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called some pitches against them that were probably 12
inches out, but we couldn't hit it consistently,'' Hundley said.
``They kept hitting that spot consistently. The last two nights we
just had a tough time hitting. If we stay out there and hit it
consistently, we get those pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gagne allowed back-to-back homers to Andruw Jones and
Chipper Jones in the third and a solo homer to Andres Galarraga in
the sixth. Mills continued to have problems as he allowed a pair of
runs on four hits in two innings of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some big mistakes that cost us runs, especially home
runs,'' Gagne said. ``You can't afford to give up three home runs
in one game. That's really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who scored 36 runs in three games in sweeping the
Reds to begin the trip, need a win in today's series finale to end
the seven-game road trip with a winning record. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
