<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-1S     04-27 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TRADING HITS, KNICKS FLOOR THE RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the crescendo of noise began to bulge and push
against the pinwheel ceiling of Madison Square Garden on Wednesday
night, Vince Carter was standing under the weight of it all,
staring at his reflection in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was Latrell Sprewell, right in front of him, right where he
had been all night. For every flashbulb-drenched move Carter made,
Sprewell countered with one of his own. So it was only natural that
the game would come down to a one-on-one situation between two
players with career backgrounds in drama.
</P>
<P>
   Both understand one thing: It's how you exit a scene. With 14
seconds on the clock, it was Sprewell with the ball. As he waited
for the clock to spin down to 9 seconds, Sprewell darted from the
left sideline into the center of the paint, rose up over Carter and
hit a fallaway 6-footer with 7.9 seconds on the clock to give the
Knicks a 1-point lead, their first edge since the opening minutes
of Game 2. And it was Sprewell's 13th point of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was Carter's turn. He grabbed an inbound pass, stared
into the eyes of Sprewell at the top of the 3-point arc and leaped
into the air. But as he took flight with Sprewell under his chin,
and Chris Childs running toward him, he snapped the ball to an open
Dee Brown on the left wing. With Patrick Ewing closing in on him
like an afternoon shadow, Brown's 3-pointer to win the game banged
off the rim as the time expired .
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, the Knicks were using the court as their private
dance floor after winning, 84-83. They also took a 2-0 lead in
their first-round playoff series and left the Raptors drained for
their second tight finish, and perhaps demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be,'' said Sprewell, who scored 25 points _ including
11 straight in the fourth _ and left the Knicks one victory away
from taking the three-of-five series. ``I hope that's the case
because I am getting a little tired of chasing Vince around. He's
tough, really tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being there for your team and doing what you have to do
makes you feel good. It's an amazing matchup to be apart of. To
face Vince, it's a challenge. I hope everyone is enjoying it. When
it comes down to plays like tonight, it's what basketball is
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was riveting despite the numbing number of fouls called (60)
and despite the complacent Knicks, who found themselves down by 14
points with 11 minutes left in the game. Once the fourth quarter
got warm, the nervousness in the crowd was eased. Once Larry
Johnson established himself as a low-post threat with 8 points to
pull the Knicks back into the game during a 10-1 run, there was
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been in foul trouble, so I was just trying to get in there
and help in whatever way I could,'' said Johnson who finished with
8 of his 11 points in the fourth quarter before fouling out. ``We
were stagnate, so I wanted to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latrell was huge, though. Here's a cat that sat out a whole
year before coming to us and we got to the finals. He's a warrior.
I'd love to see how he used to do against Michael Jordan. Because
Latrell is fearless. I can't see Latrell backing down from
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   As the curtain closed, Carter was on his back with a his hands
over his eyes while Sprewell raised his arms in victory. His shot
with 7.9 seconds left was the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started hitting shots,'' said Carter, who finished with 27
points, including 7 in the fourth quarter. ``It's tough when a man
is feeling that confident to stop him. When he's in a zone, he can
hit from anywhere on the court. Once I got into foul trouble, it
was hard for me to judge how to play him. I have to give him
respect, he took a step back and hit that tough shot to ice the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks finished the game shooting 40.3; the Raptors shot
41.4 percent. Allan Houston, nonexistent all night, scored 12
points on a 2-for-8 night while Ewing added 19 points. The Knicks
made 28 of 38 free throws and the Raptors hit 33 of 41.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy worried about his
team's history of mishandling prosperity. Several players said he
was visibly angry about the team's bleary focus during Tuesday's
practice, and wondered out loud if his team could unearth the kind
of hunger they had to start Game1. Even as game time approached,
even after a successful shoot-around yesterday morning, he was
still concerned with the Knicks' energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in Game 2's, and you look at what team's did
yesterday, and it's interesting for a team that wins Game 1,'' said
Van Gundy, referring to San Antonio and Charlotte's ability to come
back and even their respective series. ``I think it's important
that we go for the win tonight. A lot of times at 1-0, you're
waiting for the other shoe to drop. What if Vince Carter has a
better night. All these things. We just have to go for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's pregame anxieties were justified. A sharper, more
prepared Raptors team took the floor with Muggsy Bogues inserted as
the starting point guard to guide them. With him, there was calm.
Carter was over his opening-night jitters, and his teammates were
ready for whatever the Knicks had. It wasn't much. As a result, the
Raptors opened up a 15-point lead midway through the second, an
edge aided after six straight turnovers by the clumsy Knicks. It's
a pattern that continued in the third quarter when the fell behind
by 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto played great,'' Van Gundy said after the game.
``Defense, offense, we knew they would play extremely well. We just
didn't pass to each other. If you miss open shots in this league,
the basketball gods deem they won't go in.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting the game shooting 15 percent, after looking as if
they would be overwhelmed by Carter's constant attacks on the
basket to get him to the free-throw line 16 times, the Knicks
regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Larry got us going, the crowd really started getting into
it,'' Sprewell said. ``I stared to feed off the crowd, my
adrenaline started to really pump, and I started to feel my game a
little. It was a tight finish. It could have gone either way.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have been another Carter moment. He passed, Sprewell
did not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
