<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     04-27 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BULLPEN STARTING TO FILL UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year ago, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson was watching
Mike Maddux throw a bullpen session and feeling giddy about adding
any kind of arm to a downtrodden bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gregg Olson and Antonio Osuna could each be ready to pitch
in two weeks or less, and the Dodgers have nowhere to put them. The
abundance of right-handed setup men _ Terry Adams, Alan Mills, Mike
Fetters and Matt Herges _ gives the Dodgers a position of strength
from which to deal.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Kevin Malone said a trade in the next few
weeks isn't an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that as viable,'' Malone said. ``I don't see a
trade at this point. You'd like to have that as a viable option,
and maybe that's what happens when you get deeper into the season,
but not now. In the next week or two, I don't see that as a
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The short-term fix is either go with 12 pitchers and lose a
position player or send down a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things could happen between now and then,'' Malone
said. ``Right now, there's not a lot of talk going on with anyone.
Everyone's still settling in.''
</P>
<P>
   But things can change. Dodgers officials believe as the season
moves into the middle and end of May, teams with holes in the
bullpen will begin scrambling for help. By moving one of the
right-handers _ Mills' name is perpetually mentioned _ the Dodgers
could fill gaps on their 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation the Dodgers aren't in any hurry to resolve.
Olson threw a bullpen session before Wednesday's game with Atlanta,
but Johnson said he'd like Olson to throw one or two more before he
either throws in a simulated game or on a rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Osuna is rehabbing with Triple-A Albuquerque and
Johnson said he needs a few more outings before he'll be ready to
go. And even then the Dodgers might not be willing to activate him
since he can only be optioned one more time.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the issue of the Dodgers needing a lefty in the
bullpen. They've already shipped out Onan Masaoka and Jeff Williams
after they both failed in the role.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, the Dodgers and Florida Marlins talked about a
trade involving lefty reliever Vic Darensbourg, but a match
couldn't be identified. With the Marlins coming to Los Angeles over
the weekend, it's likely Malone will again broach the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In his third season, left-handers are hitting .207 against
Darensbourg. Right-handers are batting .297.
</P>
<P>
   BACK WHERE BROWN BELONGS: The day after returning to the
Dodgers' rotation, right-hander Kevin Brown said his right pinkie
was a little stiff but added it was nothing that should keep him
from making his Sunday start against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He did say, however, how good it was to be back after spending
time on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't feel quite as guilty, I guess, when the team is
playing well,'' Brown said. ``It's always a matter of wanting to be
out there and trying to contribute and help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Jose Vizcaino started at shortstop and Todd
Hollandsworth was in center field against right-hander Kevin
Millwood, setting up Kevin Elster and Devon White to play against
lefty Terry Mullholland today. With it being a day game after a
night game, it's also likely Chad Kreuter will catch Chan Ho Park
while Todd Hundley rests. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
