<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8464 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
THE WOODLANDS _ The Tournament Players Course is pristine. The
weather has promised to cooperate, a pledge that comes with all the
assurances of a used-car guarantee.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Predictions of warm, rain-free weather have been accompanied by
expectations that scores will go lower than ever. Players are
licking their chops after witnessing velvet greens, flawless
fairways and a relative absence of wind during practice rounds.
Round One of the Shell Houston Open today could be a birdie buffet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a record score,'' Steve Elkington said Wednesday, and
he was echoed by Fred Couples, who said: ``This course is
beautiful. It's as nice as I've ever seen it. I think the scoring
is going to be extremely low.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not an indictment of the TPC but a compliment.
Considering the Shell Houston Open has produced a higher winning
score than most tournaments over the past few years, there is no
debating that, when the wind goes up, the TPC remains a good test
of golf for even the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
   But give them spinnable fairways and greens that are a lot
softer and smoother than Interstate 45, and these guys start to
salivate. A shootout will be a nice change of pace, if it comes to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   But before tournament officials post warning signs _ ``Danger:
falling scores'' _ they might want to consult the co-conspirators
at the 17th hole who are waiting to sabotage great rounds of golf.
They are known as the golf and water gods that call the Devil's
Bathtub home.
</P>
<P>
   The big lake on the 17th and the 382 yards players must
negotiate provide some of the most stressful moments on a TPC that,
unless the wind kicks up, will show its friendly side this week.
</P>
<P>
   Players at the SHO have a healthy respect for the 17th hole.
They know the past. They have seen or heard of Seve Ballesteros
making a fateful bogey there in 1990. And Hale Irwin plopped two
shots into the Bathtub in '85 to sink his hopes with a
quintuple-bogey 9, losing by five shots. Even last year, when Hal
Sutton came up short on his approach and made a bogey after Stuart
Appleby made birdie moments earlier, the 17th played a huge role in
determining the winner.
</P>
<P>
   And the players have no doubt that 17 will again be a focal
point of the 2000 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest impromptu line I've ever heard in a pro-am in 25
years of doing this was on that hole a few years ago,'' Bruce
Lietzke said. ``Bobby Rahal, the race-car driver, was one of my
partners, and he hit a perfect drive down the left side. He was in
great shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pin was over on that front-left corner, and Bobby had 140
yards left, and I went over to him and said, `OK, don't worry about
all that water. Just hit that 9-iron in there close.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So what does he do? He does what every other amateur would
have done. He bailed out over on the right into the middle of the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're walking up to the green, and Bobby is just steaming.
He's so mad at himself, he can't see straight. And I asked him what
he was so mad about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I drive race cars 240 mph for a living, and I was
scared to death that I was going to hit that ball in the water. I
was afraid I was going to lose a golf ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what No. 17 can do to you. It'll turn brave men into
cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be other subplots at the TPC starting today, such as
whether this might be the first time a player repeats as champion
in the 51-year history of the event.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Appleby's job to do something about the defending
champion having a successful encore. If nothing else, his focus is
in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it here, I'm not defending the title,'' he
said. ``I'm just trying to win it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby can't think of any reason why he shouldn't be able to do
well again this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten better each year on tour, which is a goal of
mine,'' he said. ``I'm just trying to keep myself tight and my game
in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   While the TPC might be receptive to low scores because of its
sensational condition, parts of the course have not changed. It's
still a shot-maker's course that rewards those who can hit fairways
and greens.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the reasons Sutton, who has won two of his last
three tournaments, is on the hook as the man to beat this week.
Hitting good golf shots is his strength, although his putting and
short game haven't been shabby of late, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a course where you pick out places that you don't want
to be,'' Sutton said. ``I like it when there are places where, if
you hit it there, the price is high. And if you hit it off line
here, the price can be very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Just watch the 17th hole, and that much is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
