<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE WOODLANDS _ There will be no Tiger prowling, no David Duval
wraparound shades, no Vijay Singh expressionless moments and no
pouty Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   So you say the field for today's Houston Open is a mere Shell of
itself?
</P>
<P>
   I say, sure, it could be better. Who doesn't want to see Tiger
Woods plop one into the hole from 160 yards away with a 9-iron, or
Phil Mickelson work wonders with that lob wedge of his?
</P>
<P>
   You say the cup is half-empty? I say, sure, the leader board on
Sunday figures to have fans scratching their heads, reaching for
their pairings sheet and asking, ``Who's he?''
</P>
<P>
   For every Fred Couples and Hal Sutton, there will be more names
in the field like Todd Rosetti and Brandt Jobe, the ones only
hard-core golf fans will know well. For every international name,
like a Carlos Franco, Stuart Appleby or Esteban Toledo, there will
be half a dozen Brent Schwarzrocks, Brett Wetteriches and Ryan
Howisons roaming the TPC.
</P>
<P>
   You'll recognize Jeff Maggert, Steve Elkington, Justin Leonard
and Craig Stadler. You probably won't know Jason Buha, Jeff Gove
and Glen Hnatiuk.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as you can Buy.com into the idea that much of the
field that opens the SHO today might be a mere lipped-out putt or
two away from going back to the minor leagues, the cup on No. 17
does figure to be filled with great golf shots.
</P>
<P>
   No one will strip you of your season pass for complaining that
you won't be able to find the usual number of big-name autographs
or cram yourself 10-deep around the green in hopes of catching a
glimpse of the top of Duval's hat. You're right. It could be
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always looking for guys to put out there and sell
tickets,'' University of Houston ex Billy Ray Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think the SHO has become a place for bottom-dwellers,
you haven't been paying attention. And you'll probably be in for a
big surprise come Sunday afternoon _ again.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the SHO has been the PGA's version of Star Search
more than Stars on Parade. And until the purse grows measurably or
a more attractive date in the tour season is scheduled, the biggest
names surely will continue to find better places to spend glorious
late-April weekends like the one in store for us now.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the likes of Duval and Mickelson have played here, SHO
winners often have been an assortment of ``Who's he?'' tour players
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Funk won his first PGA Tour event here. Jim McGovern
provided one of the best finishes ever in 1993 on the way to the
win. Mike Heinen posted his only PGA Tour victory here in 1994.
Fulton Allem, Tony Sills and Mike Sullivan have won here, while
Leonard, Couples, Elkington and Maggert have not.
</P>
<P>
   The name game, it seems, always gives way to a great golf game
when the tour arrives here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Tiger Woods isn't in the field, or Jim Furyk, David
Duval, Vijay Singh you hear that the field is not that strong,''
tour rookie Matt Gogel said. ``But these are the greatest players
in the world. Anyone can beat you any week. We've seen it happen
all the time. You're going to see great golf. No one can play 42
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tiger is not on the menu. Sure, we'll all miss him. But that
doesn't mean, as Brown put it, that the remaining SHO menu has been
reduced to ``chopped liver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It does bother me that there's that (perception),'' Brown
said. ``I look at this field, and I see 156 guys that can win it.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, without Woods, Duval and Singh, and with only
Sutton playing the kind of golf that could lead to a runaway
victory, the SHO figures to provide one of its best finishes, which
is saying something for a tournament known to be decided on the
71st or 72nd hole. And with the forecast calling for perfect
weather and conditions at the TPC by most accounts the best they've
ever been, the scores should flirt with record lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are perfect,'' Elkington said. ``In the past, this
tournament has had some bad weather and the greens weren't up to
standards. Everything comes into play when players are scheduling
tournaments. They might think the locker room is small or it was
bad timing. Some guys consider those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm sure when players that aren't here see the scores this
week and the conditions and everything else, they'll all be back.
You never know what the story is going to be here, and you don't
know how good the golf is going to be. I predict a great story will
come out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The story won't be Tiger sinking a snaking 60-footer. It won't
be Duval coming from five strokes back, or Mickelson chipping in
from the fringe on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   But a mere Shell of itself? No.
</P>
<P>
   The SHO will go on, and come Sunday the winner might not be a
name with which the casual fan will be familiar, but in this
tournament, what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever plays great golf is going to win,'' said Gogel, who is
among the hottest golfers on tour. ``We all have the same
opportunity. It's just going to come down to who gets hot and who's
making putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it always does.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
