r n BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-SFCHRO     04-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BUDGET EXPERTS FORECAST $5 BILLION EXTRA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ California tax revenues are pouring in so fast that
the state will be at least $5 billion richer than expected by the
end of the fiscal year, The Chronicle has learned.
</P>
<P>
   With that much ``surplus'' cash flowing to state coffers,
Capitol observers say, a fight is set up between ever-cautious Gov.
Gray Davis and his more liberal fellow Democrats, who control both
houses of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Personal income tax collections for the first 26 days of April
are $1.2 billion more than anticipated. At least another $1 billion
will pour in by the end of the month on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that cash infusion, together with other state tax
revenue, means the state will receive some $5 billion more than
previously anticipated by June 30, the end of the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state already has a budget for the current fiscal
year, the $5 billion ``surplus'' won't be spent until the next
fiscal year, which begins on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state's surging economy has already led Davis
to amend earlier estimates for next fiscal year. He now projects $2
billion more than expected coming in after July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the current $5 billion surplus and next fiscal year's
expected $2 billion means legislative budget writers have more than
$7 billion in unexpected cash to earmark in the next budget. That
spending plan must go to the governor by June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting new revenues (over two years) of at least $6
billion and perhaps significantly more than that,'' said Sandy
Harrison, a spokesman for Davis' Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   The lastest fiscal forecast is substantially more than a $4
billion prediction released in February by Elizabeth Hill, the
state's legislative analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The state's bloated bank account, which has posted
multibillion-dollar surpluses for the past three years, is in sharp
contrast with revenues in the cash-starved years of the early
1990s, when at one point California faced a deficit of more than
$14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's $5 billion is high even by surplus standards and
is more than the $4.3 billion combined surplus the state had for
the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   Having so much more money to play with will occupy Davis and his
Democratic colleagues in the Legislature for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, hyper-cautious in his spending, will want _ as he did
last year _ to devote much of the new cash to one-time expenditures
like transit projects or other capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leadership in the Legislature sees the added cash
as a way to boost state support for groups shorted by past
Republican administrations, such as welfare recipients, home-care
workers, the mentally ill and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that kind of dough, we should invest more in mental
health programs, aid to the developmentally disabled, bigger
payments to doctors and other Medi-Cal providers, more health care
for lower-income Californians and assistance to local
governments,'' said Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As they have in the past, GOP lawmakers will clamor for using
much of the money for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   One thing all sides are likely to agree on is using a good chunk
of the cash to increase spending for education, which Davis has
repeatedly said is his ``first, second and third'' spending
priority.
</P>
<P>
   There will be disagreement, though, over whether that money is
given to school districts to pay for specific programs or to use at
their own discretion, the concept Burton prefers.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the administration has acknowledged that there
will be a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do all our economic forecasts in November,'' said Harrison.
``This particular year the tech stocks went through the roof in
December so there were a lot of capital gains we had no way of
foreseeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Through March, state revenue collections were running $2.5
billion over the $65.2 billion in revenue that Davis estimated the
state would take in this year.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the biggest tax collection month of the year, personal
income tax revenue has already exceeded estimates by $1.2 billion
with a few days of counting still left.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the state logged $701 million in personal income tax
payments. On Tuesday, $724 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and corporations taxes were running $314 million ahead of
estimates by the end of March and will likely be $434 million over
by the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   Withholding _ the money employers take out of employee paychecks
_ has also given the state $150 million more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax, the third key part of the state's income stream,
won't be counted until the end of April. But its collections so far
this year have also exceeded administration estimates.
</P>
<P>
   And if revenue for May and June exceeds administration
expectations, that would push the cash balance even higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
