<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPURCROSS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPUR CROSS RANCH PRICE JUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cave Creek, Ariz.) - Cave Creek taxpayers could be asked to cover
a $6 million shortfall in the $21 million price owners are asking
for Spur Cross Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Some Town Council members are questioning what they claim is a
40 percent hike in the land's cost. &QL; 
On Monday, May 1, the Town Council will consider a plan backed by
Mayor Vincent Francia that would raise part of the $21 million
through a $6 million property tax. The tax would require the
approval of Cave Creek voters in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   That $6 million is on top of the $7.5 million pledged last year
by the Legislature and $7.5 million approved by Maricopa County.
The combined state and county contributions were widely believed to
be enough to buy the ranch and make it a park.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions ratcheted higher this week when Francia suggested that
the Attorney General's Office investigate whether information about
the proposed deal was illegally provided to The Arizona Republic.
He claimed council members were obligated to keep the information
confidential because they learned it in executive sessions by the
Town Council.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Councilman Dean Brewer has asked the attorney
general to investigate whether Francia and Town Attorney Gary
Birnbaum violated open-meetings laws by calling the closed
executive sessions. &QL; 
DIFFERING INTERESTS &QL; 
The shootout at Spur Cross Ranch is a case study in the risks
involved when governments attempt to buy private land to satisfy
the demands of preservation-hungry voters. Gov. Jane Hull staked
her prestige to the cause of preserving Spur Cross. In last year's
state of the state address, Hull called Spur Cross one of the
``natural areas that define the magnificence of our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Spur Cross, which lies just north of Phoenix, rolls across 2,220
acres of stunning high desert traversed by the lush green oasis of
Cave Creek, the Valley's largest remaining perennial stream.
Covered with broad stands of saguaros and ocotillos, it soars into
rugged uplands that hold the ruins of Hohokam farming settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can save Spur Cross, generations to come will understand
at least part of the magic of Arizona,'' said Hull, who helped
persuade the Legislature to act.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain, &QL; 
R-Ariz., also pushed the bill after he tried unsuccessfully to
engineer a swap of Spur Cross for federal land north of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   When Maricopa County agreed to match the state's contribution,
it seemed to be a done deal. Rep. Carolyn Allen, R-Scottsdale,
whose district includes Spur Cross, remembers the jubilation that
surrounded Hull's visit to Cave Creek last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We high-fived that night and the crowd was all excited,''
Allen said. ``I truly believed that the $15 million was going to
cover the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But something happened on the way to a sales contract. The
owners, Herb Dreiseszun of Phoenix and an insurance company
controlled by Cincinnati billionaire Karl Lindner, said it would
take more money to buy Spur Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the land was likely to be transformed into another
golf-course development lined by million-dollar homes with $50,000
SUVs parked next to BMWs. &QL; 
A CHANGE IN PLAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Augherton said he got the bad news immediately after the
Legislature passed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Augherton, who was Cave Creek's mayor at the time, recounted a
conversation with Ed Wren, lobbyist for Great American Insurance
Co., which owns 70 percent of the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Now, you realize, mayor, that this $15 million is
only for our share,' '' Augherton said. ``I was astonished,'' the
former mayor said. ``I felt we had been deceived. I felt they had
just pulled a big bait and switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Wren insists that Great American is not to blame for the
misunderstanding. ``Great American's position from day one was that
they needed to have $14.7 million out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A state Senate staff analysis supports Wren's position. It
reported that Great American had ``entered into discussions with
the Executive branch'' and had ``expressed willingness to sell its
portion of the property for between $14.7 million and $21
million.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate report made no mention of Spur Cross' other owner,
Herb Dreiseszun. He says he openly disagreed with the appraisal
that put the value of the entire ranch at $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is a fair process and a fair appraisal,'' said
Dreiseszun, who claims government officials ignored him as they
pursued negotiations with Great American. He said the state's
appraisal of $6,600 per acre flies in the face of nearby sales for
triple that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Dreiseszun said Francia's plan, developed by attorney Birnbaum,
``has some merit.'' Under the plan, Great American would receive
$14.7 million for its share, and Dreiseszun would get $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every intention of securing this property for the
community of Cave Creek and the state,'' Francia said.
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Dean Brewer claims that Francia and Birnbaum have
become too cozy with Great American, which is represented locally
by attorney Robert Kielty. ``It seems to me that things are
swinging too far in the direction of the property owners,'' Brewer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Laura Cox, puts it more bluntly, ``I think we're
being steamrollered.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Ralph Mozilo, a retired mortgage company executive
and an ally of Francia, says the sellers market is a product of
economic realities as well as political momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has been frozen in its tracks,'' Mozilo said. ``If
somebody has a better plan, I'm more than willing to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schmitt, a founder of Friends of Spur Cross, said the
political stakes are so high that politicians have become easy prey
for the landowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There too much of a seller's market,'' Schmitt said. ``The
politicians know there is such a strong will to save Spur Cross
that they've adopted this mentality of `Save Spur Cross at any
price.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
