<HEADLINE>
BELCHER'S BACK (WELL, ALMOST)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Pitcher Tim Belcher has two more rehab starts
for Triple-A Edmonton before he'll join the big-league club. So
what was he doing in Anaheim on Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's about 40 degrees warmer here,'' he said. ``And they
had an off-day today and I needed to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, recovering from offseason elbow surgery, made 68
pitches in five innings Tuesday night for Edmonton at Calgary,
allowing one run and five hits. He'll fly back to Edmonton on
Saturday and pitch Sunday. He'll make another start for Edmonton
five days later, after which he is expected to join the starting
rotation in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to get up to 100 pitches or so,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``We have to make sure he's at the level he needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said his elbow feels good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pitching with better stuff right now than at any point
last season,'' Belcher said. ``Granted, it's come against two
A-ball clubs and one Triple-A club. It's not the Yankees. But
mentally I feel good about where I'm at. I'm much more capable of
putting together some good innings at the big league level.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he feels better than he has in years, Belcher drew the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get past 34, 35, you've probably seen your best
days,'' said Belcher, 38. ``Some days you can perform like you're
younger, but as far as that invincible, 20-something feeling, it's
gone. Way gone.''
</P>
<P>
   FARM REPORT: The Angels are keeping an eye on lefty Jarrod
Washburn, who is pitching at Triple-A Edmonton. Washburn, who began
camp as a candidate for a spot in the starting rotation, was
sidelined by a strained muscle in his side for most of spring
training. He only now is beginning to build up strength and
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn is 1-0 with a 4.96 ERA in three starts for Edmonton,
but Scioscia said Washburn initially might be called up as a
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pen's a possibility,'' Scioscia said. ``But long range
he's definitely a starter. He'll be a force, give you 200 innings a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   MADDON'S SUPPORT: Bench coach Joe Maddon is wearing a neck brace
to help alleviate the symptoms caused by a pinched nerve in his
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Maddon went to the hospital during the last road trip because he
felt light-headed and short of breath. He has bone spurs in his
neck that doctors believe caused the pinched nerve. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
