<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCKOVICH-EXTORTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROCKOVICH TARGET OF REAL-LIFE EXTORTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID GREENBERG AND CECILIA CHAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ An ex-husband of Erin Brockovich, his attorney
and a former boyfriend were arrested Wednesday on suspicion of
trying to extort $310,000 from the subject of the recent Julia
Roberts hit movie and her boss.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects conspired to blackmail Brockovich and prominent
Westlake Village attorney Edward L. Masry with the threat that they
would go public with accusations that Brockovich was a bad mother
and that the now-famous legal duo was having an affair, according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   After a Wednesday morning meeting in which Masry and Brockovich
turned over the money, authorities moved in and arrested her
ex-husband, Shawn William Brown, 38, of Simi Valley; Century City
lawyer John Jeffrey Reiner, 53; and Jorg Lawrence Halaby, 46, of
Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   All three remained in custody with bail set at $50,000 each,
with their arraignment scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, this whole thing really makes me sick,'' said
Brockovich, an Agoura Hills resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give anybody a dime for going out saying lies
about me and Ed when we never did anything but be good to these ...
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich, director of research for Masry &AMP; Vititoe, accused
Brown of trying to avoid paying her $100,000 in back child support
and said the suspects' demand for money escalated over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back and forth with these guys for months,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a criminal complaint filed by the Ventura County
District Attorney's Office, Reiner called Masry on April 11, saying
Brown was ready to give news media interviews casting Masry and
Brockovich in a negative light.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure Brown's silence, Reiner said, his client wanted
$200,000. He reiterated the threat during an April 14 phone
conversation, this time claiming he also represented Halaby, a
former boyfriend of Brockovich's who was portrayed in the movie by
Aaron Eckhart, records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, Reiner faxed Masry a proposed agreement, this time
calling for $280,000 for Brown and $30,000 for Halaby to keep them
from publicly questioning Brockovich's devotion to her children or
from claiming that she and Masry had been romantically involved.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Brown and Halaby promised Masry over the phone
that if they received the money, they would never bother him or
Brockovich again, records show.
</P>
<P>
   But Masry had notified authorities, who began building a case
against the suspects. A meeting was set for Wednesday morning at
which Masry and Brockovich gave the trio checks totaling $310,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to Masry, Brown was going to turn around and pay
Brockovich $100,000 of the money as the child support he owed her.
Brown was the first of Brockovich's three husbands, and the father
of two of her three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been rumbling and threatening this,'' Masry said.
``And after the movie came out, it really got hot the last two
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Masry also said he and Brockovich had never had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no proof because Erin and I have never had a sexual
relationship,'' he said. ``They wouldn't need proof if they went to
the tabloids. It wouldn't matter if it were true or false.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County District Attorney Michael D. Bradbury said the
arrests culminated a two-week investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking for money not from the film, but from these
two individuals,'' said Bradbury. ``I don't recall in recent years
another extortion case in which we prosecuted a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury also termed the trio's threats a serious extortion
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case that is close to the line. I understand
it's not unusual in the entertainment industry for someone to try
to profit from some peripheral involvement in the making of a film.
Their efforts sometimes cross the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this prosecution will have a serious deterrent
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich,'' which has grossed more than $100 million
since its March 17 release, shows how the former beauty queen
joined Masry's firm as a down-on-her-luck file clerk and went on to
help him win a record $333 million settlement from corporate giant
Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric.
</P>
<P>
   The duo, portrayed in the film by Roberts and Albert Finney,
sued the utility on behalf of the residents of Hinkley, Calif.,
saying the company knowingly contaminated the community's water
supply.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Roberts had been notified of the arrest through
her talent agency, ICM in New York.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
