r a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHR     04-27 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ALASKA AIRLINES JET PLAGUED WITH HYDRAULIC DIFFICULTIES  &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ An Alaska Airlines plane in Oakland that was
found this month to have incomplete maintenance records reported
hydraulic problems on four separate flights, in some cases forcing
passengers to evacuate, according to Federal Aviation
Administration records.
</P>
<P>
   In three cases in 1995, crew members reported identical problems
with the hydraulic line to the left engine of the MD-80, tail
number N932AS. In each instance, Alaska mechanics reported
replacing the hydraulic line and servicing the hydraulic system,
FAA records obtained by The Chronicle show.
</P>
<P>
   The records also show that mechanics reported fixing a variety
of other mechanical problems since the plane was acquired by Alaska
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's records have come under review after a special FAA
inspection of the airline this month found that the aircraft was
prematurely cleared for a test flight in Oakland despite
unspecified irregularities with its paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The special FAA ``white glove'' audit of the airline, which came
in response to the January crash of Alaska Flight 261, also found
that records for a Boeing 737 in Seattle were missing a required
second signature.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures come as Alaska's maintenance facility in Oakland
remains under investigation by a federal grand jury over
allegations that mechanics there falsified records. Since 1998, FBI
agents have seized records for 11 MD-80s that have been serviced at
the hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Records for the Flight 261 jet, tail number N963A, were not
under grand jury review.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska spokesman Greg Witter said Wednesday that all of the
carrier's 89 planes are safe, even as the airline, in response to
the ``white glove'' audit, continues to inspect the records of most
of its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have the finest mechanics in the industry who
maintain our fleet in tip-top condition,'' Witter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flight 261 crash off the Southern California coast, which
killed all 88 people on board, remains under investigation by the
National Transportation Safety Board, the FBI and the Department of
Transportation's inspector general. The probe has focused on the
possible failure of the jackscrew, a key part of the plane's
horizontal stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   According to FAA records, the horizontal stabilizer was the
subject of a repair on the N932AS plane in November 1998. Corrosion
was found on part of the stabilizer, and the part was replaced,
records show. That same day, mechanics also re-welded a previously
repaired crack on that MD-80.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious problems with the plane's hydraulic system were
reported on three occasions in 1995 and once in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On July 25, 1995, passengers on a flight that landed at San
Francisco International Airport had to be evacuated after hydraulic
fluid fumes leaked into the cabin. A similar incident was reported
at Portland International Airport on Aug. 14, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 7, 1995, a low-pressure warning light went on after the
plane took off from Portland. After the plane landed without
incident, problems were again found with the hydraulic line.
</P>
<P>
   And on Dec. 17, 1997, passengers were evacuated after a
hydraulic line broke.
</P>
<P>
   Witter said the hydraulic problems ``happen periodically'' and
were unrelated to the paperwork problems highlighted by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The plane remains in service, as well as the 11 MD-80s for which
records are under review by the federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, the grand jury issued a subpoena for records
pertaining to three MD-80s in which mechanics alleged paperwork
discrepancies at the Oakland facility. In November 1999, the grand
jury issued a second subpoena for the records for eight additional
planes. The panel is continuing to meet in secret.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury probe began after John Liotine, 37, of Pittsburg,
who formerly worked as a lead mechanic at the Oakland facility,
came forward with allegations of misconduct. Liotine is on paid
leave. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-COSMOS-FLAT-SFCHRON &LR;      04-27 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMOS-FLAT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGES BACK NEW THEORY OF FLAT UNIVERSE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A balloon-born telescope that captured faint whispers of
radiation echoing from the ``Big Bang'' of 14 billion years ago has
confirmed an astonishing new view that the universe is flat and
expanding forever, not curved and closed in on itself.
</P>
<P>
   The observations, reported Wednesday, offer the first detailed
images of the universe as it existed shortly after its creation, a
vast and sizzling hot realm of gases that later cooled and
condensed into the galaxies, superclusters of galaxies and stars
that are visible today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow! Wow! and Wow!'' was the reaction Wednesday from Michael
Turner, a University of Chicago astrophysicist at a NASA press
conference in Washington. ``Euclid was right, and the pattern of
the images shows undeniably that the universe is flat.''
</P>
<P>
   The observations were captured by a sensitive telescope carried
23 miles over Antarctica for 10 days in late 1998 and early 1999. A
team of 36 astronomers and cosmologists from four nations were
involved in the mission, and the first detailed samples of their
images are being published today in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams of cosmic explorers _ using telescopes mounted on
balloons and mountain peaks as well as the orbiting Hubble Space
Telescope _ are gathering data and manipulating computer
calculations that confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   The images support theorists' predictions that the embryonic
universe, barely 300,000 years after it was created in the Big
Bang, was composed entirely of vast waves of radiation hotter than
the sun, with clumpy structures of hydrogen stretched far across
empty space.
</P>
<P>
   After the universe cooled and condensed, the radiation left a
faint afterglow, known as cosmic background radiation. That
afterglow is what the ultra-sensitive microwave telescope suspended
from the balloon has seen in unprecedented detailed.
</P>
<P>
   The telescope mission, code named Boomerang, was led by Paolo de
Bernardis of the University of Rome's La Sapienza campus and Andrew
Lange of the California Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the first clear images of the early universe we have
ever seen,'' Lange said Wednesday at the Washington, D.C., press
conference. ``It's a fantastic idea that our entire universe is
built from the seeds we can see and measure.''
</P>
<P>
   The telescope detected unimaginably faint wave patterns, or
ripples, in the temperature of the cosmic background radiation.
These waves are barely three degrees above absolute zero _ 459
degrees below zero Fahrenheit _ and they vary in temperature by
only 100 millionths of a degree.
</P>
<P>
   If the universe is flat, said Saul Perlmutter, the Berkeley,
Calif. leader of another scientific team studying the birth pangs
of the universe, then physics and mathematics say it must follow
that the universe will continue expanding forever and not someday
collapse onto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Perlmutter and his group are studying more than 80 of the most
distant detectable exploding stars, called supernovae. They are
finding that the flat universe is not only expanding forever, but
that the expansion is in fact accelerating, propelled by a
mysterious force that Perlmutter and his colleagues call ``dark
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the data from the Boomerang team's findings was analyzed
by team members Julian Borrill and Andrew H. Jaffe at the Lawrence
Berkeley National Laboratory's supercomputing center. Borrill
reflected Wednesday on the excitement the new findings are
generating:
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit at my computer for weeks and weeks, and finally I just
marvel at what we're seeing _ the universe is an awesome thing!''
</P>
<P>
   The cosmic background radiation is all around us; it contributes
to snow on television sets. But only when scientists place their
detectors high above Earth's interfering atmosphere can it be
measured and imaged.
</P>
<P>
   That radiation was first detected in 1965, but the first hints
of its tiny ripples were not found until NASA's Cosmic Background
Explorer satellite, known as COBE, detected them. The satellite
covered the entire sky but had only a very coarse view, far too
rough for scientists to discern any complex structures.
</P>
<P>
   The Boomerang experiment, by comparison, covered 2.5 percent of
the sky but with a resolution 35 times higher. So sensitive is the
Boomerang telescope that its detector caught the minute variations
and gathered them into images showing clearly the complex patterns
that the ripples formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really exciting to be able to see some of the
fundamental structures of the universe in their embryonic state,''
said de Bernardis. ``The light we have detected from them has
travelled across the entire universe before reaching us, and we are
perfectly able to distinguish it from the light generated in our
own galaxy.''
</P>
<P>
   The team that sent the Boomerang telescope aloft on its 10-day
mission plans to fly it again later this year, and other scientists
are planning to release new data within a few days on another
balloon-borne experiment called Maxima, which is also measuring the
cosmic background radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Berkeley astrophysicists Paul L. Richards and George
Smoot, the Maxima team launched its balloon on a 12-hour flight to
125,000 feet from the National Science Foundation's scientific
ballooning base at Palestine, Texas last June.
</P>
<P>
   Smoot said Tuesday that Maxima's data, which are still being
analyzed, will confirm the Boomerang team's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Information and images from the Boomerang observations are on
the Web at:  &UR; http://www.physics.ucsb.edu/boomerang/  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRO     04-27 1974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON(2NDTAKE) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND TAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   CONT FROM:  interviews for this story.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, city officials turned up the pressure on Hearst to
find a buyer for the Examiner, and it was beginning to leak out who
they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the new year, Ted Fang called Brown and asked
whether the mayor knew of any potential investors who might be
interested in purchasing the Examiner with the Fangs. Hellman and
Fang met with the mayor in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he began to ``shop the Fangs around.'' And for any
deal for the Examiner to work, Brown said, there would have to be
some kind of subsidy from the Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In his second inaugural address on January 8, Brown called the
Examiner a ``civic treasure'' and said he hoped to find investors
to buy it. The same day, Hallinan, also during his second inaugural
address, called saving the paper a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, on January 20, Brown called Examiner
editor and publisher Tim White and asked if they could meet. Later
that morning, Brown, Renne and Rep. Nancy Pelosi, who has been one
of the most outspoken members of the House of Representatives on
Chinese issues, drove to the Examiner building, and the delegation
met with White in the publisher's conference room.
</P>
<P>
   They made it clear that Hearst's first offer was simply not a
``viable one,'' according to Pelosi. If the Examiner was going to
survive, Hearst needed to sweeten the deal substantially.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 8 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  And the pressure to sell the paper to the Fangs grew even more
intense the next day, when Sen. Dianne Feinstein, whose husband,
Richard Blum, has long-standing business interests in China,
invited White and Florence Fang to lunch at Villa Taverna, a
private dining club in the Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pelosi, Feinstein has long enjoyed the support of the
Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Although no actual negotiations for the Examiner took place at
the Friday luncheon, the subtext was clear. White and Feinstein
listened as Fang described her life in China before immigrating to
the United States with her late husband.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, she said, from the time he attended UC Berkeley in
the 1950s, had dreamed of owning a daily metropolitan newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The next Tuesday, the Hearst Corp. put the Examiner up for sale
a second time.
</P>
<P>
   This time the ``turnkey'' offer included all the hard assets
needed to publish the newspaper, including a printing plant, the
Examiner building, trucks, news racks and editorial computer
system, as well as the paper's editorial staff and lists of
advertisers and subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But a wild card had slipped into the deck _ and his name was
Clint Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy San Francisco landlord and former political
consultant, Reilly had long-standing antipathy for the Examiner. In
1993, Reilly broke his ankle during a scuffle while meeting with
Bronstein at the Examiner. Reilly's assault-and-battery suit
eventually was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Reilly ran for mayor, but his campaign derailed when
Davis, Brown's top campaign strategist, accused Reilly of
``savagely mauling'' a women during a domestic violence incident 20
years ago. The allegations, which were widely reported in The
Chronicle, Examiner and other media, sank Reilly's campaign, and he
finished fourth in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   On January 11, Reilly filed a suit in federal court to block the
sale of The Chronicle. Within weeks, however, Reilly was angling to
buy the Examiner, and, to the surprise of some observers, he
appeared to be serious about running it.
</P>
<P>
   In early February, during settlement talks with Hearst officials
in New York, Reilly orally outlined an offer to buy the Examiner if
at least a share of the joint operating agreement was included,
according to his attorney Joseph M. Alioto.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-50 profit split provided for under the current JOA could
be adjusted, Alioto said, to reflect the difference in circulation
of the two papers. The Chronicle's circulation is more than four
times that of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst officials seemed willing to at least entertain the offer,
and shortly after the meeting in New York, according to a source
close to Reilly, he took his family on a vacation to Hong Kong and
Bali believing he was close to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department officials were still skeptical of
Hearst's new offer to sell the Examiner because it did not include
a piece of the JOA and they had refused to bless it. But the
prosecutors saw for the first time a sign of flexibility from the
Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And the strident political and community opposition in San
Francisco made it easier for the department to continue pressuring
Hearst officials to offer, if not a share of the JOA, at least a
subsidy that would help a new owner operate the Examiner for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   With the February 15 deadline for offers on the Examiner
approaching, the Hearst Corp. fielded a number of inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   The potential buyers ranged from the former owner of the Crazy
Carrot Juice Bar in Minneapolis, who said he was ``now ready for
the next thing,'' to Tony Ridder, chairman and CEO of Knight
Ridder, who was interested only if he could have a share of the
JOA.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only three qualified buyers presented detailed
offers for the Examiner: Reilly, the Fangs and Leucadia, which had
first expressed interest in acquiring the paper in August.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 9 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Over the next four weeks, negotiations among Hearst officials and
the three prospective buyers intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three potential buyers ``demanded subsidies in the
tens of millions of dollars as a condition to their acquisition,''
court records show. And according to a report in the Examiner,
Hearst told Reilly, the Fangs and Leucadia that it would be willing
to provide a ``substantial subsidy'' to operate the paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the amount of the subsidy was not high enough for Leucadia,
and negotiations soon narrowed to Reilly and Fang.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the Fangs, Hellman and his partner Joe Niehaus
continued to play a role in the negotiations. Shortly after the
Hearst Corp. put the Examiner back up for sale, Hellman talked with
White.
</P>
<P>
   He later formally notified the Hearst Corp. that he was working
with the Fangs and that any investment he made would be his
``personally'' rather than his investment firm's.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman also met with Justice Department officials, who were
impressed with his credentials, contacts and financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely added a luster to the Fangs,'' one Justice
Department source said.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, Ted Fang met with Hearst Vice President James
Asher to discuss the terms of a deal. Hearst offered a subsidy, but
it was interested in providing the lowest possible amount and the
shortest possible transition period.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, Fang sent Hearst a letter stating that he intended
to publish the Examiner six or seven mornings a week with home
delivery and newspaper rack sales primarily in San Francisco. He
presented options for a transition subsidy period of up to four
years, and said he wanted delivery trucks, news racks, editorial
computer systems, archives, subscription lists and the paper's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   He was not interested in the Examiner editorial office building
or a printing plant. And his proposal called for the Hearst Corp.
to keep the Examiner staff and honor ``all employee obligations''
such as union contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after returning from vacation, Reilly resumed
negotiations with Hearst in late February.
</P>
<P>
   He thought the discussions were going well, but by early March,
Reilly began to feel that Hearst officials were stalling him,
according to a source close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-March, Reilly was still waiting for Hearst to respond to
his latest offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still thought he had a deal with Hearst,`` said one source.
``He didn't know whether (Hearst officials) were bluffing or
negotiating with someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The word came down on St. Patrick's Day, March 17.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial staffs of the Examiner and Chronicle were invited
to gather at the Examiner shortly before noon. Standing in the hub
of the newsroom, White and George Irish, president of Hearst
Newspapers, announced that the Fangs had acquired the Examiner. The
sale would become final on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal were strikingly similar to the proposal
Fang had made in early March. The Fangs would acquire the
Examiner's name, Web site, archives and lists of advertisers and
subscribers. The Fangs would publish the Examiner at least six
mornings a week.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a four-month transition period, during which the
Fangs would own the Examiner but Hearst and its editorial staff
would continue to publish the paper before the operation was turned
over to the Fangs. Hearst would provide a subsidy of up to $66
million during the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our deal today is the fulfillment of a dream for my family,
for myself, for my late father,'' Ted Fang said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 10 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But the deal wasn't final yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Hearst Corp. and the Fangs had struck a deal for
the Examiner, they still needed approval from the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Justice Department would sign off, though, it wanted
to determine whether even with the Hearst subsidies the Fangs had
the financial backing to publish the Examiner _ and to compete with
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Justice Department sources, Hellman has an option
to provide future financing to the Fangs, if the family should need
it. Hellman says no such option exists.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Fangs have obtained investments from China, a
source close to the deal said, ``Let's just say they have
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, the day the sale was to become final, the Justice
Department formally approved the Hearst Corp.'s acquisition of The
Chronicle and the Fangs' purchase of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in 35 years, San Francisco will have two
independent daily papers,'' said Assistant Attorney General Klein.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the mayor bought himself a newspaper,'' said the
leader of one political watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the two sales were to close, Reilly, who a source
said was ``crushed'' when he learned the Hearst Corp. had sold the
Examiner to the Fangs, went to court asking for a temporary
restraining order to block the sales.
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, Reilly argues that the Fangs' acquisition of the
Examiner is a sham, and if the newspaper fails _ as Hearst knows it
will, Reilly contends _ Hearst will monopolize the daily newspaper
business in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker granted Reilly's
restraining order, temporarily blocking the newspaper sales. The
next week, with the agreement of Hearst and Reilly, Walker set May
1 as the start of the expedited antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   For some participants in the process, the possibility that the
deal could come undone in Walker's courtroom is a terrifying
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was a 15-round championship fight,'' said one key player,
``has now turned into a wild back-alley brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Few could have anticipated the trial when Hearst's Bennack first
walked into The Chronicle newsroom last August. But now, after
almost nine months of difficult negotiations and confounded
expectations, the fate of San Francisco's two daily newspapers will
be decided in a federal courtroom. And even the judge seemed
puzzled by how it got there.
</P>
<P>
   Told during a court hearing that no law required Hearst to
subsidize the Fangs' acquisition of the Examiner, Walker asked why
the company had agreed to such an extraordinary arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politics,'' said Hearst attorney Gary Halling.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 11 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
