<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRO     04-27 4848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON(2TAKES) </SLUG>
  
 POLITICS TANGLED UP S.F. NEWSPAPER DEALS  &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN and REYNOLDS HOLDING 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Frank A. Bennack Jr., president of the Hearst
Corp., strode into The Chronicle newsroom shortly after noon August
6 and announced to the staff that the New York media conglomerate,
publisher of the Examiner, had struck a deal to purchase The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   And because antitrust law probably would prohibit Hearst from
publishing both papers, Bennack said, the Examiner was up for sale,
effective immediately. If no buyer emerged in the next ``three to
six weeks,'' the company would shut the Examiner down.
</P>
<P>
   The newsroom announcement had the tenor of a done deal, a swift
and foregone conclusion to a newspaper rivalry that had endured for
more than a century. But if Bennack and other Hearst officials
thought the fate of the city's two daily newspapers would be
quickly resolved, they were in for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next nine months, Hearst's acquisition of The Chronicle
would be sidetracked by a convergence of political alliances,
hidden agendas and backroom negotiations that could not have
transpired anywhere but in San Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   -- The city's entrenched Democratic political machine
orchestrated a masterful campaign not only to preserve the two
daily newspapers but to serve its own political interests.
</P>
<P>
   -- Former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly filed a federal
antitrust lawsuit to block the sale and then used the suit to make
his own bid for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   -- The U.S. Justice Department, with a long record of routinely
signing off on newspaper mergers, suddenly felt emboldened to
challenge the deal after several successes in its antitrust battle
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   -- And in the center of it all was San Francisco's politically
connected Fang family, publishers of the Independent newspaper,
which campaigned against the sale of The Chronicle while quietly
doing everything possible to buy the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, in an extraordinary sequence of events watched from
Washington to China, the Hearst Corp. realized its best hope of
acquiring The Chronicle was to agree to pay the Fangs $66 million
for taking the Examiner off its hands.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a late-hour settlement of the Reilly suit, the final
chapter in this drama is expected to play out starting Monday in
the courtroom of U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker.
</P>
<P>
   From court documents, public records, published reports and
dozens of interviews, this is the untold story of Hearst's
unexpectedly difficult quest to acquire The Chronicle _ and how
members of the Fang family worked the corridors of power to win a
prize of their own.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, 1999, the descendants of M.H. de Young _ who with
his brother Charles founded The Daily Dramatic Chronicle in 1865 _
crowded into the newspaper's oak-paneled editorial conference room
on Fifth and Mission streets in downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After years of infighting, family members temporarily put aside
their differences and under the large gilt-framed portrait of
Michael de Young agreed to sell their newspapers, television
stations and other media holdings while the value of those
properties was at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision marked the beginning of the end of an era for one
of the nation's last family-owned metropolitan newspapers. With a
daily circulation of 456,742, The Chronicle is the 12th-largest
newspaper in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. immediately became the odds-on favorite to buy
The Chronicle. Although Hearst published 12 other papers, notably
the Houston Chronicle and the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, the
conglomerate has its roots in San Francisco, where founder William
Randolph Hearst published his first newspaper _ the Examiner. The
Chronicle was likely to become the corporation's new flagship
paper.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 35 years, The Chronicle and the Hearst-owned Examiner
have operated under an exemption to federal antitrust laws that
allowed the two newspapers to combine their business, production
and distribution operations under a joint operating agreement while
maintaining separate editorial departments. The JOA, which requires
the newspapers to split all profits, also gave each paper the right
to match any bid for the purchase of the other.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The likelihood that the Hearst Corp. would acquire The Chronicle
posed what the Fang family perceived to be a serious threat to the
Independent, their free, thrice-weekly newspaper. The family also
publishes Asian Week and several other Bay Area publications.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 12 years, the Independent has operated in the
shadow of the two dailies, protected, ironically, by the JOA, which
implicitly bars either daily from publishing a free neighborhood
newspaper without the other daily's consent. But if Hearst were to
acquire The Chronicle and close the Examiner, the JOA would
disappear, and the Independent could be exposed to new competition.
</P>
<P>
   To protect its business interests, the Fangs had sued The
Chronicle, Examiner and the San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which
manages noneditorial operations for the two papers, for allegedly
undercutting the Independent on prices for grocery ads and had sued
the Examiner and the agency for undercutting the Independent on
bids for the city's contract to publish legal and public notices.
</P>
<P>
   The first suit was settled out of court. In the second suit, the
Fangs won a $1.15 million award in 1996 _ plus $2.3 million in
legal fees _ but the verdict was eventually overturned on appeal
last year.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fangs learned that The Chronicle was up for sale, they
worried about what it could mean to them, and in July they began a
campaign to prevent the Hearst Corp. from buying the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   On July 13, the day before a Board of Supervisors' committee
urged the city attorney to investigate the sale, Independent
columnist Darrell Salomon demanded action from the U.S. Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When JOA newspapers in a city seek to merge to become a
monopoly,'' he wrote, ``the nation's antitrust enforcers need a
wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   But while publicly raising questions about Hearst acquiring The
Chronicle, the Fangs were also laying plans to acquire the Examiner
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, Hearst officials contacted Veronis, Suhler &AMP;
Associates, a New York investment bank that specializes in media
and communications industries. The officials told VSA that as soon
as the corporation had a deal to buy The Chronicle, they would put
the Examiner up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst told VSA that the sale would include the Examiner's
editorial staff, a list of its subscribers and advertisers, the
paper's archives and its name. No hard assets, such as printing
presses, office space, delivery trucks or news racks, were for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   On July 30, Hearst officials met with VSA to discuss a list of
prospective buyers, focusing on major newspaper publishing
companies. The list included the SF Bay Guardian, San Francisco
Magazine and the Independent as well as other Bay Area firms and
individuals that might be considered ``trophy buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   On August 6, Hearst announced that it had agreed to buy The
Chronicle. Hearst had offered $660 million for the paper, and the
de Young descendants had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 15 minutes after the announcement was posted on the
Examiner's Web site, VSA began contacting potential buyers for the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Ted Fang called San Francisco financier and
civic leader Warren Hellman in Hellman's office at One Maritime
Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Fang had known Hellman for several years. With offices in Hong
Kong and Sydney, Australia, Hellman and his firm were involved in
businesses throughout the Far East. The financier also had
investments in media properties in the United States and Australia
and recently acquired a small stake in San Francisco Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One of the Bay Area's most influential businessmen, Hellman had
helped keep the San Francisco Giants baseball team in the city,
advised Stanford and the University of California at San Francisco
on the merger of their respective hospitals and counseled The
Chronicle's owners on the company's business operations.
</P>
<P>
   When Fang called, Hellman was eager to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted said, `We think we ought to look at (buying) the Examiner.
What do you think?''' Hellman recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Sure.'''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Fang and Hellman, whose investment firm VSA would
contact as a potential buyer for the Examiner, discussed pursuing
the Examiner together, but Hellman declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying, `You're not going to need me,''' Hellman
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Hellman said he agreed to serve as a ``nonpaid adviser'' to
the Fangs and stressed that his investment firm was not involved in
any way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a deal junkie,'' he said. ``I thought this would be
interesting and very possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With one of the Bay Area's most respected financial minds in
their corner, the Fangs turned to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, the Fangs have been one of the most
prominent and outspoken families in the city's rapidly growing
Asian community.
</P>
<P>
   Family patriarch John Fang was a journalist in pre-Communist
China before he fled to Taiwan. He immigrated to San Francisco in
the early 1950s and in 1960 brought his wife, Florence, to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   After attending the University of California at Berkeley and
then establishing a printing business, Fang founded a national
weekly publication called Asian Week in 1979. Eight years later, he
bought a small neighborhood tabloid called the Lake Merced
Independent and gave it to his 24-year-old son Ted as a birthday
present.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, a longtime neighborhood newspaper called the
San Francisco Progress folded. Ted Fang moved quickly to snatch up
its advertisers and began increasing the Independent's circulation,
making it a citywide paper. Today the Independent says it delivers
379,000 copies of the free paper each week.
</P>
<P>
   John Fang died in 1992, but his widow, Florence, remains one of
the most powerful figures in the city's Asian community and is a
member of the city's Film and Video Commission. Their son James,
who is married to the daughter of the former mayor of Shanghai,
runs Asian Week and is an elected member of the BART board.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the Fangs have used the Independent and
the Asian community's increasing political clout to forge strong
and far-reaching political connections. The Independent practices
what it calls advocacy journalism, using news stories to advance
the Fang family's views.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's 1991 mayoral race, the Fangs threw their support
behind former Police Chief Frank Jordan. With the help of the
Independent's endorsement _ as well as $150,000 in contributions
raised by the Fangs _ Jordan defeated incumbent Mayor Art Agnos.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking office, Jordan appointed James Fang to the
$65,000-a-year post of international trade director. But when the
Examiner reported that Fang had lied on his resume, claiming a law
degree he didn't have, the appointment turned into an embarrassment
for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jordan could fire Fang, though, brother Ted marched into
the mayor's office and, according to Jordan's former press
secretary Stephen Bloom, ``looked the mayor straight in the face
and said, `Frank, if you are asking James to resign, that will not
happen. Our family will not allow that to happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, but the Fangs apparently never forgot Jordan's
hesitation to support James in the resume furor. And in 1995, when
Assembly Speaker Willie Brown announced he would run for mayor
against Jordan, the Fangs became early Brown supporters.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Fangs were not alone in shifting their allegiance to Brown.
Jordan's campaign manager Jack Davis, the flamboyant and often
controversial political strategist, signed on to run Brown's
campaign, and that December Brown easily defeated Jordan in a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had long been close to the Fang family, and with Brown's
election, the Fangs knew they could depend on two of the most
powerful men in the city's Democratic political machine to watch
out for their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``People perceive me, rightfully, as a warlord for the Fang
family interests,'' Davis told The Chronicle late last year. ``Look
out to anyone who tries to harm their interests. They have to come
through me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs' endorsements were not only shrewd politically, they
also made good business sense.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Fangs supported former Supervisor Terence Hallinan
in his successful campaign for the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   As a supervisor, Hallinan worked diligently to help the
Independent win the city's contract to publish legal and other
public notices, advertising that last year the city budgeted at
more than $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   With Hallinan's help, the Fangs placed a measure on the November
1994 ballot that allowed the city to consider minority status and
other criteria in addition to cost when awarding the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed, and the next year the Board of Supervisors
awarded the contract to the Independent, even though a bid by the
Examiner was more than $200,000 lower.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, the Fangs received more than $1 million in
federal job-generating loans through the mayor's community
development program. But after federal officials questioned whether
a sufficient number of jobs were created, the Fangs agreed to
reimburse a portion of the money.
</P>
<P>
   And last June the airport commission, whose members are
appointed by Brown, approved a $1 million, five-year lease for
office space in a Fang family building in Burlingame, even though
the airport terminal had space available. Airport officials said it
is often more economical to lease outside space for offices not
needed at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   When Hearst announced in August that it was buying The Chronicle
and selling the Examiner, the Fangs believed that they again could
count on City Hall for support.
</P>
<P>
   And Mayor Brown swung into action immediately, convinced that no
one would buy the Examiner under the terms offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard the news, I exploded,'' Brown said. ``I
said, `No way! This has to be a two-newspaper town.'''
</P>
<P>
   He called the White House, then fired off a letter to the
Justice Department, asking it not to approve The Chronicle's sale
until all anti-trust issues had been investigated and all options
for finding a buyer of the Examiner had been exhausted. He said he
was particularly worried about the deal's potential effect on the
Independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early termination of the Joint Operating Agreement,'' he wrote
in his August 20 letter, ``... would result not only in the
immediate closing of the city's second daily newspaper, but also
threaten the existence of the city's third major newspaper as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, the same day the Board of Supervisors
unanimously passed a resolution asking the Justice Department to
take a closer look at the deal, Attorney General Janet Reno called
Brown back.
</P>
<P>
   They talked twice that day, Brown recalled. ``She said that they
would investigate (the sale) thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 4 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In late August, Ted Fang spoke with San Francisco political
consultant Dennis Collins on the telephone. Fang told Collins he
wanted someone to organize community groups against the sale, and
he asked if Collins would be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was. One of his first moves was to form Stop the
Monopoly, an organization led unofficially by James Fang and
Supervisor Michael Yaki, a longtime Fang family friend and the
sponsor of the Board of Supervisor's resolution calling on the
Justice Department to take a hard look at the sale.
</P>
<P>
   On September 3, the Stop the Monopoly coalition held a press &LR; 
 &LR; news conference on the steps of City Hall, where Yaki, Supervisor
Mabel Teng and other Asian American leaders worried publicly that a
monopoly paper would give their community short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco deserves to know what kind of a newspaper they
(the Hearst Corp. and The Chronicle) are thinking about,'' Yaki
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fangs stepped up their crusade against the sale
in the Independent, which, they insisted, would be the Hearst
Corp.'s primary target.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Independent makes no bones about its self-preserving
instincts on this issue,'' read an editorial in the August 24
issue. ``The Hearst Corp. would use its postmerger monopoly power
to put out a free, home-delivered newspaper, once again attacking
the Independent, attempting to squash competing voices and
attempting to possess the only editorial voice in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several months, the paper and its sister
publication, Asian Week, would deliver the same theme in stories,
editorials and write-in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   On August 26, the Independent published a ``stop-the-monopoly
rainbow flag'' and a toll-free number for readers to call to
express support.
</P>
<P>
   On September 2, under a front-page banner headline ``Don't Let
Yellow Journalism Monopolize San Francisco,'' the Independent
printed three pre-addressed, clip-out letters _ one each in
English, Spanish and Chinese _ for readers to send to Reno, urging
the attorney general to block The Chronicle sale.
</P>
<P>
   And on September 7, the Independent debuted a full-page feature
titled ``The Hearst Chronicles,'' which included a new comic strip,
``The Life and Times of `Mr. Sharon Stone,''' an often vulgar
put-down of Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein, who is
married to actress Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   On their editorial pages, the Fangs continued to insist that the
motivation for their campaign to block The Chronicle sale was
survival. And they played down any interest in acquiring the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fangs haven't ruled out such a dream (of buying the
Examiner) for the long term,'' said a September 2 article in Asian
Week, ``but (the Fangs) say they've had little chance to
contemplate it. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, meanwhile, had been in telephone or written contact
with VSA, the investment bank retained by Hearst, since the day the
Chronicle sale was announced.
</P>
<P>
   During August, he had signed a standard confidentiality
agreement, had received a 47-page prospectus on all aspects of the
Examiner, and he had even made a tentative bid that was ``offering
a wide range of $1 million to $15 million,'' according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   By early September, VSA had contacted or had been contacted by
81 potential buyers for the Examiner, but only Fang and four others
sent VSA formal indications of interest.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interested parties, a private investor from
Philadelphia, quickly dropped out, according to court documents.
Two others, Spanish Broadcasting Systems and New Times Inc.,
publishers of SF Weekly, were interested in assets that were not
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 5 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A fourth interested party was Leucadia National Corp., a New York
company working with Forward Newspapers, a national Jewish
publication. But Leucadia dropped out when company officials and
Hearst could not agree on the length of an ``exclusive negotiating
period.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious interest was expressed by the Fangs'
Independent Newspaper Group.
</P>
<P>
   On September 8, Ted Fang visited a ``data room'' in the offices
of the Hearst Corp.'s lawyers and reviewed documents that described
virtually every aspect of the Examiner's operation, down to and
including the carrier routes used to deliver the papers.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Ted Fang and his lawyers met with Examiner
executives.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiations soon broke down. The Fangs, however, were not
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``All auctions usually start unrealistically,'' said Hellman,
their financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   By offering the Examiner for sale voluntarily, Hearst officials
believed they had done more than federal law required, and when no
buyer stepped forward, Hearst thought it would soon receive Justice
Department approval to complete the deal for The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But since June, City Attorney Louise Renne had been
investigating the proposed deal. She was determined to do
everything she could to preserve two editorial voices in the city
and wanted to get an early start on the legal implications of The
Chronicle sale.
</P>
<P>
   A former San Francisco supervisor, Renne was elected city
attorney in 1989 and had earned a reputation as a self-starter
willing to take on big business. She had been one of the first city
attorneys to sue the tobacco companies and had wrung a $187.5
million settlement for the city from the Bank of America in a
municipal bond fraud suit.
</P>
<P>
   Informed during the summer that Hearst was the most likely buyer
of The Chronicle, she assigned two of her top attorneys to look at
possible antitrust issues. She hired an outside law firm, San
Francisco's Townsend, Townsend and Crew, to help.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hearst announced on August 6 that it had an
agreement to purchase The Chronicle, Renne's office had already
researched many of the relevant legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of challenging the deal in court did not look good.
Time constraints, precedents and the law itself seemed to favor the
proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   Further, an antitrust lawsuit against Hearst would take enormous
resources that the city would not have without Justice Department
help. And in 12 previous cases in which joint operating agreements
between two papers were dissolved, the antitrust division of the
Justice Department had offered little opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the Justice Department's antitrust division
had clearly become more aggressive, led by a tough 53-year-old
assistant attorney general named Joel Klein. Since his appointment
as head of the division in 1996, Klein had stepped up federal
enforcement of antitrust law, taking on airlines, defense
contractors, credit card companies, agribusiness, even foreign
vitamin manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But Klein's biggest case was against software giant Microsoft,
and his prosecutors were winning it.
</P>
<P>
   Renne contacted Klein and they quickly developed a working
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renne had a good rapport with Klein,'' said one lawyer in the
city attorney's office. ``That helped a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But time was running short.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, the Justice Department had just 30 days after
receiving formal notification of The Chronicle sale to decide
whether to let the deal proceed. In early September, the department
sent a formal notice to the Hearst Corp. informing the company that
the agency intended to take a closer look at the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had thought it was on the fast track, but now the process
slowed to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 6 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Meanwhile, public opposition to the Hearst purchase of The
Chronicle was building steadily in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the Fangs, Collins continued to solicit support
from the city's neighborhood groups, merchants' organizations and
political clubs, prodding them to pass resolutions, write Attorney
General Reno, testify at public hearings and pressure local
officials.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen organizations eventually went on record
opposing the sale and supporting a federal antitrust investigation.
Those groups ranged from the San Francisco Democratic County
Central Committee to the city's Small Business Advisory Commission
and the Harvey Milk Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual Transgender Democratic
Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was an impressive coalition of disparate interests, but as it
leaked out that the Fang family was angling to buy the Examiner,
some members were outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``People felt used,'' said Gwenn Craig, a member of the Harvey
Milk club. ``I don't think this is what they had in mind when they
said they wanted a two-newspaper town.''
</P>
<P>
   The club had passed a resolution in September opposing a merger.
The club went so far as to later pass a second resolution harshly
criticizing the Independent for its biased political coverage
during the 1999 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics questioned whether Collins and the Stop the
Monopoly coalition had violated the city's ethics codes by
appearing before city agencies such as the Small Business Advisory
Commission and the Board of Supervisors, trying to persuade them to
oppose the merger but not registering as lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged that the appearances constituted lobbying under
the city's administrative code, which requires public disclosure of
the individuals behind the organization and the exact purpose of
their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are subject to interpretation, but according to the
San Francisco Ethics Commission, any entity that spends at least
$3,200 a quarter to influence local legislative or administrative
action must register and pay $300 _ or face fines of up to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs paid Collins more than $3,200 a quarter for his work
on their behalf, sources confirm.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Common Cause, a public-interest group, asked the
city's Ethics Commission to investigate. The commission has not
taken any action in the case and refuses to discuss it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Collins says it never occurred to him that he was lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not lobbying for any financial gain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., as it became clear that no one was
interested in buying the Examiner under the terms offered by the
Hearst Corp., the Justice Department's position began to harden.
</P>
<P>
   To attract a buyer for the Examiner, the government said, the
Hearst Corp. would have to offer a part of the JOA, which would
guarantee any new owner ``cash flow'' until the agreement ended in
2005 and prepare the new Examiner to compete with The Chronicle
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But Hearst officials resisted.
</P>
<P>
   They believed that under federal antitrust law no company could
be forced to keep a failing enterprise going. Without the revenues
from the JOA, the Examiner would have been a money-losing operation
for years, they said. And they were adamant that no buyer would be
allowed to acquire the Examiner's share of the JOA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was strictly nonnegotiable,'' said one Hearst official.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Justice Department, prosecutors agreed that the terms
of the Hearst offer of the Examiner were clearly insufficient to
attract a credible buyer. But there was considerable internal
debate about how hard the government could push Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 7 of SALE27 (27409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``This was not an easy one,'' one department insider said.
</P>
<P>
   But the department hard-liners were winning, and they were
building a case to block the deal. First, they looked at the
earlier cities where JOAs had been dissolved and one newspaper
remained. The economic data from those cities convinced them that
they could make a solid case that such deals resulted in higher
advertising rates and were anticompetitive under federal antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Then on October 15, their case grew stronger when a federal
judge in Hawaii blocked Gannett Pacific Corp. from buying a rival
newspaper in Honolulu and closing it. Though the Hawaii case
differed in many ways from the proposed Chronicle deal, said one
justice department official, the judge had issued an opinion that
supported several key positions in the department's case against
the Hearst Corp. And in November, a federal appeals court let the
judge's decision stand.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, seven Justice Department attorneys _ all but one
operating out of the Washington office _ were assigned to the
Hearst case, and the department began preparing for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In December, at the government's request, the Hearst Corp. and
Chronicle Publishing Co. turned over 174 boxes of documents.
Meanwhile, in New York and San Francisco, top executives from both
companies submitted to days of intensive questioning under oath
from Justice Department attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to rough them up,'' said one official inside the
department, ``and let them know we were going to play hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   As the end of the year approached, the issue came to a head.
Hearst officials were eager to conclude negotiations with the
government and complete their acquisition of The Chronicle. But the
federal prosecutors held firm, insisting that Hearst had to offer
better sale terms for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an outstanding case prepared, and we felt if we went to
trial we'd beat the hell out of (the Hearst Corp.),'' said one of
the government's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Christmas, Hearst told investment bank VSA to
prepare another sale offer for the Examiner on terms more favorable
to a potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been delicious on our part to take it to
trial,'' said a Hearst executive. ``But the government has all the
time in the world and unlimited resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials also were surprised by how informed key
players in San Francisco were about events in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just amazed at how much Jack Davis and the Fangs
seemed to know,'' said the Hearst executive. ``They were somehow
wired in.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Ted Fang did not respond to requests for interviews
for this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
