<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ART IS FINE, BUT NOT THE SEXY KINE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cowabunga, so to speak, there's an art
censorship story brewing in the wine country.
</P>
<P>
   The artist is Catherine Anderson, and she's big on cows. That's
not her only subject, but she paints a lot of cows.
</P>
<P>
   All of them naked.
</P>
<P>
   Bare-naked cows have helped make Anderson famous. Her paintings
hang in prestigious collections, galleries and museums all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But this is about where her paintings will  &UR; not  &LR; hang: in The
Lodge at Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   The Lodge at Sonoma, due to open this fall, is a four-star
resort that is part of Renaissance Hotels and Resorts, which is a
division of Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   The Lodge people are busy buying the work of local artists.
Anderson is a local artist. The Lodge first considered buying her
painting of a row of cows in a field, but someone upstairs decided
the painting was ... well, it just wasn't, you know, right. There
were too many bovine back porches involved.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel decided it wanted instead Anderson's painting of some
baby cows, faces forward. But that painting was sold, so Anderson
brought the hotel people a third work titled ``Fresh Air.''
</P>
<P>
   A hotel representative accepted the painting and gave Anderson a
check.
</P>
<P>
   But soon afterward, the woman phoned Anderson and told her that
the painting could not be hung at the hotel because one of the cows
is in a ``provocative position.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was stunned and flummoxed. She had never thought of her
paintings as cow porn.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's reply was, basically: ``Provocative?
 &UR; Provocative!? &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, said the hotel woman, we really want to hang your work,
but not this one. We want to swap.
</P>
<P>
   A representative for whoever makes final art decisions for the
hotel told me, ``We want to be careful not to have paintings that
might be construed as even slightly, remotely offensive to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   She also told me, ``The Lodge has guidelines for the artwork.
One of the guidelines is no animals in provocative positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a hotel that covers its, uh, bases.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says: ``It's sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist says she absolutely will not swap paintings. Her
artistic sensibility has been offended. She will not be cowed, so
to speak. She will not kowtow to the Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Now the hotel has a bigger problem. The cows Anderson painted
are still right there in Sonoma, moseying around their pastures,
naked, ready to do to Lodge guests what cows do: Mooooon.
</P>
<P>
   TAHOE JOLTED by big quake?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say it could happen, and it could cause 30-foot waves
to crush everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope that the big one hits during the watch of
current state Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   If insurance companies try to screw Tahoe policyholders, Chuck
will come to the rescue by demanding that the companies pay for
silly TV commercials featuring Chuck and Bay Area big-wave surfing
superstar Flea Virostko.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER WHEN the worst thing elected public officials did was
smoke crack?
</P>
<P>
   FLYING FROM LaPaz to Tijuana on Aero California, Chuck Brown
noticed the advertisement printed on his ticket envelope.
</P>
<P>
   It was an AT&AMP;T ad, bold red letters: ``Go down in history.''
</P>
<P>
   THE N.Y. TIMES calls El Camino Real in Palo Alto ``the Champs
Elysees of the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would make the historic old radio tower in front of
Dinah's Garden Hotel the Eiffel Tower of Hightechtown.
</P>
<P>
   Please be careful when home-shopping in Silicone Valley, where
there is no longer any connection between realty and reality. Jerry
Matters notes, ``Because of sticker shock, Realtors now carry
condiments _ smelling salts and pepper spray. No Mace as yet (he
adds gingerly), but give them thyme.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU KNOW you're old, and totally unhip, if you refer to
cinematic previews of coming attractions as ``previews.''
</P>
<P>
   The proper term, of course, is ``trailers,'' although they don't
trail anything.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Delacorte wonders, ``Are all trailers now aimed at 13- to
24-year-old males? Or do trailer producers simply compete with one
another to see how many images, how much violent action, how many
incredibly loud noises they can cram into three minutes? Not to
mention that the trailers tend to be cinematic Cliff Notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte had a lot more to say. That's just a preview.
</P>
<P>
   WELSH TEEN SONGBIRD Charlotte Church taped a concert for A&AMP;E at
the Masonic last week, and Haley Joe Osment served as the program's
host. Osment is the 12-year-old who was nominated for an Oscar for
``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Osment mentioned that although he's an L.A. guy, he loves the
Giants and the 49ers. He told Jeff Knollmiller that he has a
football autographed by Jerry Rice and would love to attend a 49ers
game.
</P>
<P>
   Nice young man, but wouldn't it be kind of creepy to have him in
the stands? You know the 49ers are going to struggle this year,
anyway, and here's a kid who sees dead people.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH CARE has gone to hell.
</P>
<P>
   In Contra Costa County, Dona Wilson s
</P>
</TEXT>
