<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, April 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-ORPHANS (Nadterechnoye, Russia) _ When Russian bombs
rained down on Grozny last fall, the city's only orphanage moved to
this small town in northern Chechnya. It was supposed to have been
a temporary stay. But seven months later the orphanage is still
here in a cramped former schoolhouse. And nobody can say when it
might move back. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MATH-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Three years ago, one of New York City's
most innovative school districts set out to tackle a nagging
problem: the math phobia that afflicts many students, and the
disparity between the test scores of white middle-class and Asian
students and their poorer black and Hispanic counterparts. The
district, stretching from the wealthy Upper East Side to immigrant
Chinatown, embraced a new ``constructivist'' curriculum without
textbooks, which preaches that it is more important for children to
construct their own solutions than to learn the standard
theoretical rules. Now the district is at the center of a rebellion
by parents, mathematicians and many mathematics teachers over how
to teach math that has shaken the education establishment from New
York City to Plano, Texas, and Lincoln, Mass. A special report by
Anemona Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COSMOLOGY (Undated) _ Astronomers are both elated and
puzzled over the first clear pictures ever taken of the infant
universe, before stars and galaxies formed and space was filled
with hot, turbulent gases. The images, produced by a balloon-borne
telescope that captured radiation emitted when the universe was a
mere 300,000 years old, were unveiled Wednesday at a NASA press
briefing. The images, which are being published in the journal
Nature, along with a separate commentary, hold both reassurance and
surprises for scientists trying to understand how the universe came
about in what they believe was a giant explosion, called the Big
Bang, some 13 billion years ago. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-MERRICK (Undated) _ David Merrick, the producer whose gift
for creating Broadway hits was matched only by his genius for
attracting publicity and making enemies, died Wednesday in his
sleep at St. George's Rest Home in London. He was 88. By Frank
Rich.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ After Elian: Who wins, who loses in
Miami? The mayors may have won with their constituents, but lost on
a national stage. The federal government did not trust them enough
to notify them of the raid. The Miami relatives will go into the
May 11 court hearing without the advantage of actually having Elian
in their possession. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   PASSOVER-RESORTS (Ft. Lauderdale, Fla.) _ They're a far cry and
a long way from the Catskills. Luxury resorts around the world a
now catering to the Passover trade and going to remarkable lengths
to make things kosher. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SPLIT (Undated) _ The government faces a formidable
legal challenge in trying to persuade a federal judge to split up
Microsoft, but not an insurmountable one by any means, according to
antitrust experts. ``It would be somewhat of a stretch, but I think
the breakup that has been suggested is consistent with the broad
and flexible historical legal standard in antitrust,'' said William
Kovacic, a professor at the George Washington University Law
School. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   TAUBMAN-AUCTION (Undated) _ A. Alfred Taubman, 75, the shopping
mall magnate who has made a second career out of rescuing
companies-in-distress from the arms of unwelcome suitors, resigned
in February as chairman and is now stepping down as a director of
Sotheby's, the venerable auction house. The Sotheby's story
threatens to overshadow a life that might well qualify as a Horatio
Alger story come true. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Individual investors who have been
frustrated in recent years as they have tried to buy into hot
initial offerings of high-technology stocks may be in for a
pleasant surprise Thursday. While AT&AMP;T's sale of shares meant to
track the company's far-flung wireless communications unit will be
the nation's richest initial offering yet, the sheer size of the
deal, 360 million shares, appears to have conspired with the recent
market turmoil to ensure that the offering will be warm at best. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   GRADS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Until recently, there was a
consensus among economists that students who attend more selective
colleges _ ones with tougher admissions standards _ land better
paying jobs as a result. Having smart, motivated classmates and a
prestigious degree were thought to enhance learning and give
students access to job networks. But is it true? By Alan B.
Krueger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Pork is still the other white meat
and beef is still for dinner, but the associations that created
those long-running campaigns are planning multimedia efforts to
help freshen them up. By Courtney Kane.
</P>
