<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-CHIVAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY, CHIVAS PLAY TO 1-1 DRAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ For a night at least, the Rose Bowl looked like
Jalisco Stadium _ the red, white and blue-dressed fans not decked
out because of American patriotism, but because Chivas Rayadas de
Guadalajara was in town Wednesday to face the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a surprise. Next to the Dodgers and Lakers, Chivas is
probably the most popular team in Los Angeles, having won 10
Mexican League championships and a pride that runs deep because
Guadalajara is known for fielding only Mexican players _ not highly
paid foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite playing in home-away-from-home conditions, Chivas
could only manage a 1-1 draw, failing to beat the Galaxy for the
third consecutive match, in front of 20,688.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy nearly won the game in regulation after Clint Mathis'
goal in the 22nd minute, but Chivas' Manuel Rios scored in the 90th
minute to tie the score. In two other matches, the Galaxy beat
Chivas 4-2 in penalty kicks in 1997 and 3-1 last year at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   On the international stage, the Galaxy record moved to 3-5-2 in
five seasons, which includes two victories over Chivas, a 4-1
victory over Santos Laguna (Mexico) and draws against El Salvador's
national team and Aston Villa of the English Premiership.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said that the difference between Chivas
and other Mexican clubs compared to MLS teams is closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year a lot of people felt we won against Chivas, but they
didn't bring their best players,'' said Schmid. ``Tonight they
played it like us, some guys in, some guys out; it was the same for
both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've shown we can play with teams like that and
compete. Now if we played five more times, who would win that
series? I don't know. But that's the nice point about it, I don't
know. It used to be that people assumed automatically that if a
U.S. team played a Mexican team the quality of Chivas, you had no
chance. I don't think that's the case anymore. We can hold our own
and play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS all-stars Cobi Jones and Robin Fraser were out of town
Wednesday, in Moscow as the U.S. national team lost to Russia 2-0.
Jones and Fraser will rejoin the team in time for Saturday's game
against New York/New Jersey and former coach Octavio Zambrano at
Giants Stadium. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-27 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUEEZE DIDN'T WORK BUT IT SHOWS HOW MARINERS ARE DIFFERENT TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mariners' first workday matinee at Safeco turned out to be a
long day's journey into night.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, what a night.
</P>
<P>
   And what a game.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we begin to tell the story?
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not at the end, which saw Cleveland score two runs in
the top of the 10th to beat the M's, 5-3. That doesn't matter,
really.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, let us start with the squeeze play. That is the heart
of the matter, since it is not every day you see a suicide squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in fact, was another such day.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners came close. Oh, so close. And there is a great
deal to be said for attempting the gutsy move.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Mariners are already racking up juicy TV and
radio ratings and why, if small ball and near-perfectly executed
games such as Wednesday's continue, this is going to be a summer of
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lay it down, you win the ballgame,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Dejected? Yes, the Mariners were a little quiet in their locker
room after their awesome, old-time baseball fantasia turned into a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite some low voices and a few hanging heads, nearly
everyone involved in the game was found to be capable of cracking a
smile, even when it came to talking about the failed squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having money on the red and the black on the
roulette table. You score on the squeeze play, you win. If you
don't, you've still got runners on second and third with another
chance to score,'' Piniella said, laughing in hindsight. ``And then
you come up with double zeroes.''
</P>
<P>
   If there has to be losing, the Mariners will take this kind of
losing.
</P>
<P>
   It was epic, with home run-robbing catches by Kenny Lofton,
double plays from Omar Vizquel and Roberto Alomar good enough for
Hall of Fame highlight reels. There was a no-hitter taken into the
seventh inning by Cleveland's Jaret Wright, whose father once
pitched a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It was eventful, with a homer from Alex Rodriguez and a
ninth-inning rally that had Safeco Field feeling like it was
playoff time.
</P>
<P>
   It was everything and more you could wish for in a big-league
affair, right down to the suicide squeeze _ a bit of baseball
trickery that Piniella has been aching to put in play. Now he can,
thanks to a suddenly versatile, patient, small ball-minded club.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella has been waiting a long time for days like Wednesday.
And the payoff was almost as sweet as it was exciting and tense.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth, with the Mariners having just tied
Cleveland at 3 on Jay Buhner's RBI single, the sacks were loaded
when Piniella sent Carlos Hernandez in to pinch run for John Olerud
at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew right away what it was. It was the squeeze play. It was
not too easy to bunt but it was the chance to do it. It was fun,''
Hernandez said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   With 37,086 spectators on their feet and every player on both
sides tingling in anticipation, Hernandez took the sign and waited
for Paul Shuey to deliver the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cleveland hurler released the ball, the Mariners rookie
was three-quarters the way down the line, his body straining toward
home, when the batter, David Bell, nudged his bat over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Time stood still.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ball landed in the catcher's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Uh oh, big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the bunt,'' said Bell, attempting to be stoic but
clearly feeling crummy for what happened, especially since he then
ended the inning by getting punched out on a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple to analyze. I didn't get the bunt down.
That's the point of a squeeze play,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had failed to make contact and Hernandez, almost falling
toward the plate, tried to scramble back. It was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nowhere to go,'' said Hernandez, who was tagged out
at third, where Buhner now occupied the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was asked if maybe the ball came in too high for Bell
to handle. The skipper smiled, not angry or upset, just still
racing with the idea that such a magnificent game almost ended on
the most exciting call he could make.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it was a good pitch to bunt. It was a curve. They're a
little softer pitch. You can really deaden the ball,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good play. It didn't work. What are you going to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the M's ended their second homestand of the season
with a 12-8 record and an early season competitive ability to keep
up with the Indians, the Yankees and the Red Sox, Piniella is
heartened.
</P>
<P>
   It's early, yes. But games like Wednesday's show the M's are
different, they're better, they're in it to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heck of a ballgame. The game was played well
defensively. The pitching was excellent. I saw as many great
defensive plays as I've seen in any game I've watched,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, that was fun to watch. This is what major league
baseball is all about. The pitchers weren't wild. They made the
hitters hit the ball. The players behind them made great plays.
There was power hitting. There was two-out hitting. We didn't lose
the game. We got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend the way my kids are playing their butts off,''
Piniella said. ``They're playing good, aggressive baseball and if
we continue to play the way we have, we're going to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, that squeeze play's going to work, which is why we'll
keep watching.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011 or
lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
