r s BC-BBA-TIGERS-ANGELS-LAD     04-27 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGERS-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON BACK IN FORM FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Garret Anderson simply needed a day to smell the,
well, the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   A reluctant but slumping Anderson was put in the designated
hitter spot Wednesday by Angels manager Mike Scioscia, a chance to
give him some rest but keep him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson looked refreshed in his first at-bat, slugging a pitch
from Detroit Tigers starter C.J. Nitkowski into the right-field
seats for a two-run homer in the second inning, sparking the Angels
to a 6-1 victory before 16,153 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's homer would have been enough for Angels starter Scott
Schoeneweis, who bounced back from a poor outing in Tampa Bay to
improve to 4-0. Schoeneweis went eight innings, gave up one run and
five hits and lowered his ERA to 3.06. He struck out three and
walked only one, the Tigers' only run scoring on Deivi Cruz's home
run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis got help from more than just Anderson. Troy Glaus
immediately followed Anderson's homer with one of his own, his
team-leading sixth of the season. And Mo Vaughn added a two-run
homer (No. 5) in the eighth inning for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis also benefited from the defense, particularly the
play on the left side of the infield by Glaus at third and Gary
DiSarcina at shortstop. They combined to field all 11 chances
cleanly. In all, 22 of the 24 outs Schoeneweis recorded didn't
leave the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson didn't miss much in the outfield _ Darin Erstad made
only one putout in center field all night. So Anderson got his
chance to relax, even though he instinctively grabbed his glove to
go to the outfield a couple times after the third out was made.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went into the game slumping, having gone hitless in 10
at-bats and his batting average dipping to .247. The reason for his
recent slide is open for debate, but whatever the reason, Scioscia
thought Wednesday would be a good day to put Anderson in the DH
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get his legs a little break,'' Scioscia said. ``I
think this guy has really been pushing himself to excel, probably a
little too much. It's a good time to get a little breather. The
beauty of it is he still can get his at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a discussion before the game that basically was along
the lines of, `Hey Garret. You don't have to hold the weight of the
whole club on your shoulders. Just relax and play the game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson recently signed a four-year, $20 million contract
extension, so he has nothing to prove other than showing the club
he's worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime you push against the wall, and you need to take a
step back so you can just walk through the door,'' Scioscia said.
``I don't want him to feel any pressure to carry the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, however, said an early-season slump isn't unusual and
he hasn't been feeling any added pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm pressing,'' said Anderson, whose three
homers have all come against lefties. ``I go through this every
year early in the season. But you guys know how it always ends
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went into the season with a lifetime average of .300,
and he's never hit below .285.
</P>
<P>
   For Schoeneweis, the game was typical of his other victories. He
kept the ball down and got batters to hit the ball on the ground.
However, his biggest out of the game was a fly ball in the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels led 3-1 but the Tigers had two on with two out and
Juan Gonzalez at the plate. Pitching coach Bud Black came to the
mound, and after a brief chat, Schoeneweis got Gonzalez to fly out
to right field to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's money,'' Schoeneweis said of Black. ``Every time he comes
out to talk like that, it seems there's a double play or a clutch
out. Let him keep coming out. He's like Merlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia is most impressed with Schoeneweis' demeanor on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is really impressing me with his ability to stick
with his game plan,'' Scioscia said. ``He'll make slight
adjustments, but even if he gets touched up, he comes back and
makes a good pitch. That consistency builds his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to keep doing what I'm doing, and stay locked
in,'' said Schoeneweis, whose four wins is tied for tops in the
American League with Pedro Martinez and Orlando Hernandez. ``The
team scores runs when I pitch and they play incredible defense for
me. That makes it real easy on me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
