<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8505 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS JAMMED IN GEM, LOSE TO INDIANS IN EXTRA INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A game for the ages? Maybe not. But close.
</P>
<P>
   A game for the aging? Absolutely. No question.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran infielders Omar Vizquel and Roberto Alomar, both 32
going on 22, put on a symposium of the infield arts Wednesday,
making plays that took the breath away from the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still from the Mariners' point of view, the
Omar-and-Roberto show took runs away from the Seattle offense. Runs
that kept the Mariners from putting the finishing touches on a
marvel of a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of winning in nine innings, the Mariners lost 5-3 in 10
innings when Cleveland scored twice off usually invulnerable
reliever Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   It's true David Bell missed a squeeze bunt that could have won
the game in the ninth. And it's true the M's bullpen could have
saved the day by posting zero on the scoreboard somewhere in the
late going.
</P>
<P>
   It's equally true, however, that without the seamless play of
Vizquel and Alomar, the Mariners wouldn't have needed all the other
parts of the game to click.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept hitting balls that I thought they had no chance on,''
outfielder Stan Javier said. ``Then they made the plays _
unbelievable plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Alex Rodriguez lost a hit when Vizquel
tracked down a grounder from behind, jumped to his feet like a
Pop-Tart ready for the feasting and gunned the surprised Rodriguez
out at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching them make plays like that makes a player like me
sick,'' M's second baseman Mark McLemore said, a wry grin spreading
over his face. ``They do it, and they make it look so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, John Olerud thought he'd given the Mariners the
lead with a homer, but Kenny Lofton climbed the wall to get his
glove into the fan zone, pulling the ball back into play. What
should have been two runs was nothing. But the plays that created
that nothing were something _ something spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lofton's shoulder may not be 100 percent, but there's nothing
wrong with his legs,'' McLemore said. ``The way he jumps, he can
create havoc out there. No one else on their roster can do what he
did right there. That changed the whole complexion of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Alomar saved his grace-under-fire performance
for the seventh inning, just after the Mariners, who'd been facing
a no-hitter at the hands of Cleveland's Jaret Wright for six
innings, had broken through to tie the score. Javier singled.
Rodriguez homered to center. Boom. Tie game, 2-all.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle didn't want to stop there. But Alomar stole a hit from
Olerud with a grass-grazing dive to stop a grounder for the first
out. Then, after Jay Buhner walked, Alomar went the other way,
diving in the dirt toward the middle of the diamond to scoop up a
Tom Lampkin grounder.
</P>
<P>
   He flipped the ball in the direction of the bag, where Vizquel
was floating. Vizquel held onto the ball only long enough to zip a
throw to first for an inning-ending double play so special that it
had the Mariners close to applauding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's great about those two is that they make all
the fundamental plays,'' Rodriguez said. ``Then, on top of that,
they make all the great plays like that one, too. But making the
fundamental plays is what separates them from guys who just make
the flashy plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland had a chance to win the game in regulation after Manny
Ramirez _ somehow when the Indians play the Mariners, it always
comes down to Ramirez _ homered off Jose Mesa in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle erased that deficit in the ninth. Rodriguez walked with
one out, and Olerud and Buhner singled, tying the game. When
Lampkin was hit by a Paul Shuey pitch, the bases were loaded. And
now, with just one out, it was the Mariners' chance to put the game
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our chance,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella put on the squeeze sign for the second pitch with Bell
batting. The Indians infield was in, but Cleveland seemed
completely unprepared for the squeeze. Bell, who'd put in hours of
time in spring training working on getting the bunt down, had a
curve from Shuey, a pitch that was all but grooved for bunting.
</P>
<P>
   Bell missed it. Pinch-runner Carlos Hernandez was out, caught in
a rundown between third and home. Suddenly the Indians were one out
away from forcing extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've got to do is put the ball in play,'' Bell said. ``I
didn't. I'm not going to go out and strangle myself over it. If I
get a hit, we still win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell didn't, taking a called third strike. And in the top of
10th, Rhodes fell victim to a series of just-out-of-each singles by
the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Vizquel and Alomar could have gotten to the hits the
Indians converted into victory. No one else could.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004 or
johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
