<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BO     04-27 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX THROW A BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Red Sox 14, Rangers 4)
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Long before Boston caught onto his act, Brian
Daubach knew all about Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played against him my very first year in pro baseball, 1990,
in my very first game,'' Daubach said. ``Tampa Yankees versus the
Sarasota Mets. I remember being overmatched in that game. I went 0
for 2 with two strikeouts. I don't remember what Carl did, but I
knew who he was. You always notice the first-round picks,
especially the year they got drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no overlooking Everett or Daubach Wednesday as they
led the Red Sox to 21 hits and a 14-4 beating of Texas. It gave the
Sox two wins in three games at The Ballpark, where they were mauled
three straight in their only visit last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Belleville Basher had four hits, including three doubles,
and scored three runs. The first double began a five-run rally with
two out in the first inning that set up Rangers starter Mark Clark
for a short workday, especially after he surrendered a three-run
home run to Everett, his seventh of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's last double instigated a four-run burst in the ninth
inning that included an RBI double by Everett, who also singled,
walked, and scored twice. The Sox center fielder also made an
over-the-shoulder backhand catch that mirrored the play he made the
night before. The only difference? The outfield fence was spared
having to absorb another body blow from the 6-foot, 215-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of performance expected from Everett from the
day he first put on a uniform as the Yankees' No. 1 pick 10 years
ago. Back then, Daubach, taken in the 19th round by the Mets the
same year, was just another guy hoping for some attention. What's
surprising, Daubach said, are the parallels in the routes that have
brought them both to the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say in a way he's like me, because it took him a while to
develop,'' said Daubach, who lifted his average to .373, placing
him just behind Nomar Garciaparra (.386 after a 3-for-5 day) and
Everett (.377) on the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he has a lot more tools, obviously, but things didn't
come easily for him, either. Now, he's to where the tools have just
taken over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox lefthander Jeff Fassero, whose career appeared to have
touched bottom last fall when the Rangers didn't invite him back
after acquiring him from Seattle, benefited from his teammates'
offensive largesse. Fassero (2-1) gave up hits in each of the six
innings he worked, including three doubles and a two-run home run
by Pudge Rodriguez in the fifth. Manager Jimy Williams lifted him
with a 9-3 lead after a leadoff single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the same as the other two guys (the brothers Martinez)
_ because of the layoff, he wasn't as sharp as he's going to be,''
said catcher Jason Varitek, who hit a 412-foot home run onto the
center-field lawn, singled, walked, and had a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he pitched well,'' said Varitek, pointing to the second
inning, when the Rangers had runners on second and third with no
out but failed to score. ``When your team scores some runs, and
then you're in a position to give up some runs and get out of a
jam, that's a total bust to the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who traded two-time American League MVP Juan
Gonzalez last winter, are reeling. They've lost 8 of 10, unsung
left fielder Rusty Greer is out after ankle surgery, outfielder
Gabe Kapler (who came from Detroit in the Gonzalez deal) is batting
.200, Clark has a 9.53 ERA after the shortest outing of his career
(1 1/3 innings), and the team's vaunted bullpen is 1-5 with just
two saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're struggling,'' Clark said, ``they hit everything.''
</P>
<P>
   No time to be in the Rangers' shoes. No time, it turns out, to
be in Daubach's shoes, either, after he hit three doubles in a game
for the first time in his career. Asked if he enjoyed the rare
opportunity to show off his wheels, he grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feet are hurting right now,'' he said. ``I broke in some
new shoes today. I guess that was a bad idea, because I ran the
bases so many times. But I'm not complaining. I'll take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
