<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV30-C     04-27 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE GOVERNMENT'S MICROSOFT STUMBLE
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, April 30.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More often than not, when you enter the 90-seat
chamber where U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson holds
court, you'll see a parade of prisoners in orange jumpsuits copping
pleas.
</P>
<P>
   During the 77 days when Jackson weighed the fate of the world's
largest software company, he would handle those criminal matters
early in the day, before the Microsoft antitrust trial convened and
the seats filled up.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors once foresaw Jackson juggling his
criminal docket for years to come. Under such a formula, the judge
would serve as a sort of corporate truant officer, monitoring
Microsoft's conduct to bar any further illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   The model for such a federal exercise could once be found just
down the hall from Jackson's courtroom, where in 1984 the late
Judge Harold Greene mapped out the negotiated breakup of the AT&AMP;T
telephone monopoly. Greene subsequently spent much of his time on
the bench framing the rules that the Baby Bells lived by.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the government switched gears, dropping its earlier
reliance on a ``conduct'' remedy in favor of a ``structural'' one _
a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the change: a feeling that even after Jackson
ruled that Microsoft had abused its monopoly, the company refused
to bow its head. If all its appeals left Microsoft a loser in the
end, prosecutors envisioned still-obstinate executives giving the
judge a hard time.
</P>
<P>
   The signal for such a potential dark victory came from Steve
Ballmer, the hard-charging Harvard classmate of Bill Gates who took
over this year as Microsoft's chief executive officer. Even as
prosecutors focused on what items to put on Jackson's menu, Ballmer
came to town for a series of sales meetings. (The U.S. government
is Microsoft's biggest customer.)
</P>
<P>
   Between sales pitches, Ballmer met with reporters to tell them
how little he thought of the government's case and Jackson's
scathing verdict. ``We continue to believe absolutely that our
position will be vindicated in the end,'' he also told Microsoft's
employees via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Such a blatant lack of contrition sat poorly with Joel Klein,
the top government honcho in antitrust matters.
</P>
<P>
   Klein fretted about the split within his own ranks over how to
punish Microsoft; about a tanking high-tech securities market, a
drop fueled at least in part by the case and one that worried the
White House; the chance that Jackson would toss out whatever Klein
came up with; the chance that the appeals' courts would toss out
whatever Jackson came up with, and the chance that Klein would be
tossed out by a Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with all these pressures, Klein opted for a clean break.
The solution is easy to fathom, although, to be sure, there's a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing in the verdict that suggests Jackson would favor
a breakup. The trial record fails to reflect the notion that
dividing Microsoft into separate Windows and Office suite firms
would solve the antitrust issues raised by the case.
</P>
<P>
   So, likely as not, down the road, the orange-suited defendants
may still have to give way to Jackson's heavy Microsoft calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 0938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
