<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flying stinks, and after two days, so did I
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I recently spent three of four weeks
traveling by airplane to various meetings across the country. We've
just ended the meeting season in my line of work, when we make
plans for the rest of the year, exchange ideas and do the corporate
thing. Lucky for me, this is not my everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   I average about five plane trips a year, and the more I do it
the less I like it, but not for what you might think. Dying in a
plane crash used to top my worries. I was a white-knuckled traveler
who had to knock back a libation or two before boarding. But I am
past that and don't really think about dying in a plane crash
anymore. It could happen, but there are an infinite number of ways
to meet the Grim Reaper, and flying is way down on the list of
likely ways to meet one's end.
</P>
<P>
   Getting past the worry of dying in a crash has opened my eyes to
the true horrors of air travel. Put simply, commercial flying
stinks. It is an unpleasant experience made tolerable only because
you get to where you're going quickly _ and cheaply if you plan
ahead. I flew to Atlanta, Raleigh, N.C., and Washington from Texas
on three trips, and no round-trip ticket cost more than $240.
That's cheap. You can't drive it for that amount of money if you
count hotel rooms and the time spent pounding the interstate,
dodging tractor-trailers and yuppie wackos talking on cell phones
and driving 20 miles over the speed limit. Talk about putting your
life in your hands.
</P>
<P>
   So we fly and put up with a system that reduces us to submissive
cattle, at the mercy of people who are highly stressed and on
occasion take it out on us passengers for not knowing the rules.
</P>
<P>
   I watched while stuck in one airport as a friend was berated
after standing in line for 30 minutes to re-book a flight after the
original one was canceled. He got to the counter with his driver's
license and two boarding passes _ one for him and one for his wife.
But he had neglected to bring his wife's driver's license. She was
sitting in a nearby chair, doing needlepoint. The clerk, as my
friend tells it, proceeded to lecture him sternly as if he were a
child, make him go get her driver's license and then wait for a
while before finally deigning to book him on a flight that had been
canceled through no fault of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants wake sleeping passengers to tell them to put
their seats upright as landing approaches, as if sitting upright
instead of at the approximate 9-degree angle of reclination allowed
in those miserable seats will mean the difference between life and
death if the plane misses the runway and lands in the Potomac
River. Upright or reclining, your obituary will be in the newspaper
if that happens.
</P>
<P>
   My personal travel nightmare came on the final trip, which went
from Shreveport to Dallas to Washington and then in reverse order
to return. We landed in Dallas just as a strong line of
thunderstorms arrived, canceling all flights and stranding hundreds
of us for hours. I understood and agreed. One does not want to get
in a small twin-prop that doesn't even have a bathroom when a Texas
trash-hauler is in the neighborhood. (One would think a
multi-million-dollar plane would have a bathroom, but there you
go). I hung around the terminal, reading and pacing, and after five
hours gave up and headed to Motel 6, luggageless.
</P>
<P>
   I talked the cab driver into stopping at a convenience store to
let me buy a toothbrush and deodorant. The sole choice was Old
Spice, which is the aromatic equivalent of Shlitz beer, both being
brands largely ignored in current culture. That reminds me of a
Robert Earl Keen story. A friend of the Austin singer/songwriter
was driving around a few years ago and spied a group of men
drinking Schlitz beer. ``Schlitz beer!'' Keen exclaimed. ``I
haven't had a Schlitz beer since elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I returned to the airport at 6 a.m. the next morning
reeking of a scent that isn't much better than Schlitz beer, hoping
it hid the funky smell of two-day-worn clothes that had been twice
soaked in the rain while trying to find a motel room. Luckily, most
of my fellow misfortunates were in the same boat. Flying stinks,
and so did we.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, I was struck by a hard truth. I would not
leave this airport by air on this day. It was still raining, softly
now, fog had set in, and flights on the puddle-jumpers had backed
up so badly it would have taken a C-41 to get everyone where they
were supposed to go, to the lesser airports in Shreveport,
Longview, Tyler and Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   So I rented a car and drove to Shreveport to get my luggage and
Jeep. I beat the plane by untold hours. I still don't understand
how my luggage arrived even though I couldn't get a ticket, but
there you go again.
</P>
<P>
   Heading down Interstate 20 after escaping DFW airport some 16
hours after arriving, I felt a heady sense of freedom. Once again,
I was in control of my own destiny, even if it was in a Chevy
Lumina that smelled of cigars. Sure I was once again trying to
escape the backdraft of trucks heading hellbent to somewhere at 80
mph, oblivious to the fog and rain. But the Dallas NPR station
featured an interesting interview with Jeremy Rifkin, an articulate
left-wing ecological doomsayer, and I was fueled with a cappuccino
and a package of oatmeal cookies.
</P>
<P>
   My seat was tilted back further than one can ever do in an
airplane, and the road was mine once again.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
