r t BC-DERBY28-COX     04-27 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERBY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Louisville dons its Derby
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ My mother was born three blocks from Churchill
Downs, but it wasn't until she was 44 that she attended her first
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled to be sitting in the grandstand, she asked me, then 14,
if I'd seen anyone famous while I wandered around. Some old guy was
attracting attention, I told her.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gregory Peck, and she hasn't stopped laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Natives love to complain about the traffic and pretend the horse
race isn't a big deal, but they relish the attention and the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are plenty of times to visit Kentucky and tour the
historic homes, the Louisville Slugger Museum or the horse farms of
Lexington. But you can't beat Derby time in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Lawns, already trim with the state's famous grass, look bluer
and trimmer around Derby time. Museum renovations and road projects
are timed to finish by the time the horses are running. Stores sell
cheap plastic racing hats and collectors' glasses and pre-mixed
mint juleps. Fancy women buy hats that will stand out at Derby
parties, even if they don't get to the actual race, which is May 6.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-age cousin said the Derby is just a feeling he gets every
spring, because the whole town is preparing for company.
</P>
<P>
   My grandparents, who lived above their drugstore three blocks
from Churchill Downs until the early 1950s, could listen to the
announcer if they stepped outside. Derby day was never much for
business anyway, because the street was open only to buses and
taxis. For them, the race was something other people attended but
nonetheless was a time to celebrate with friends.
</P>
<P>
   In May, even the novice begins earnest conversations about the
intricacies of breeding. Doctors' offices and beauty parlors become
low-stakes betting pools.
</P>
<P>
   Few events of mass culture, gambling and drinking comprise so
much dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The entire town parties before, during and after the Derby,
which is expected to draw more than 100,000 people. Some of the
better-known parties _ like the one held yearly for all the world's
Kentucky Colonels _ attract thousands of people. Those who aren't
invited or don't want to attend the big galas have backyard parties
or barbecues where they drink mint juleps and engage in small-time
gambling while they watch the race on television.
</P>
<P>
   The box seats in Churchill Downs are filled with gentry and
corporate sponsors, but regular people can make their way in, too.
Two years ago, my cousin won the right to buy yearly tickets, after
spending 22 years on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   These days, most of the celebrities at the race are second-tier
types. And rumor has it they're paid to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Even without celebrities, it's a great opportunity to see hats.
Local television news people devote large portions of their daylong
Derby coverage to this subject. The high, elegant hats with
feathers and flowers contrast nicely with the homemade miniature
racetracks some people affix to their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The back stalls aren't open to the public, just horse people.
But if you know someone in the business, it's a good way to gain
access to the people who actually know what it is to breed a horse.
</P>
<P>
   While it's wise to mail in requests for grandstand seats a year
in advance, Churchill Downs promises to sell unlimited infield
seats the day of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The infield is its own universe, a Mardi Gras with fewer
bathrooms. It's packed so densely, most in attendance cannot even
see the race. There are other attractions, though, like bare
breasts, for those who enjoy that sort of thing. I'm told I should
get there before my 20s expire, and then never go again.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid shuttle buses, clogged streets and impossible tickets,
locals have traditionally gone a day early and watched the Kentucky
Oaks, which features fillies (female horses). That, too, has become
a premier event _ with 100,000 people expected this year _ but it's
still more accessible than the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve rooms and restaurants early, of course. Many of the
popular restaurants and fun bars crowd Bardstown Road. Cafe Metro,
Club Grotto and the Uptown offer imaginative dishes with goat
cheese and the like. (Don't worry, just about every restaurant in
town offers a version of the patented Derby Pie, a pecan- and
bourbon-inspired confection.)
</P>
<P>
   Louisville's young adults will be drinking at the Phoenix Hill,
a multilevel, live music venue. Smaller bars, like O'Shea's, will
also be jammed tight. Poets and the people who dress like them will
sip coffee at Heine Bros. Coffee, a sure step up from Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   The area around Churchill Downs has boarded-up store windows and
other signs of urban decay. It's disappointing because Louisville
has so many lush parks and well-kept neighborhoods. But the
Churchill Downs Corp. is slowly redeveloping the surrounding
properties. The museum, which chronicles the history of the race
and the grounds, was being renovated when I visited in winter but
opened recently in time for this year's Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs also bought the land housing an old drugstore
called Wagner's. For years, jockeys and trainers ate at the lunch
counter and bought medicines for their horses there. The store
remains open, a few blocks away. But the horse supplies, which
include silks worn by jockeys, have moved to a second nearby store,
Becker and Durski Turf Goods.
</P>
<P>
   When you finally make it to the race, pause for a moment for a
private toast. Raise your glass of bourbon, take a swig and then
close your eyes and think about how lucky you are to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Then throw away that losing ticket and finish the glass.
</P>
<P>
   (sidebar) HOW TO MAKE A MINT JULEP
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're going to the Derby or a Derby party, you'll want
to drink one of these. Here's the Early Times recipe, found online
at www.kentuckyderby.com
</P>
<P>
   INGREDIENTS
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar, 2 cups water, fresh mint, crushed ice, bourbon,
silver cup
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Boil sugar and water 5 minutes into a syrup. Place in covered
container with 6-8 sprigs of mint and refrigerate overnight. Fill
each cup with crushed ice, 1 ounce of syrup, 2 ounces of bourbon
and another sprig of mint.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
