<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The war against dropouts needs youth
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The future got snarled in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   So, the buses delivering middle and high school students to last
week's Greater Austin Youth Symposium were late, but the kids
arrived in plenty of time to hear a collection of adults tell them
how important they are.
</P>
<P>
   But those who needed to hear it most likely weren't there. That
old saw about preaching to the choir springs to mind. But then,
it's not the sinners who routinely show up for the sermon.
</P>
<P>
   You have go to them and try to get them to listen. And that's
exactly what some of the participants at last week's event were
prepared to do, knowing that they are best positioned for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever other societal changes we have experienced, there is
one constant: Teen-agers are more prone to listen to each other
than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   More than one participant at the symposium who took time out to
talk to me said the value of the gathering was that it gave them
talking points to launch a conversation with their peers about the
importance of staying in school.
</P>
<P>
   And this is a battle in which we need as many allies as we can
put together.
</P>
<P>
   There are several ways to kill an economic boom. You can
strangle it in traffic. You can murder it with overconfidence, or
you can you dumb it to death.
</P>
<P>
   That is why it is essential that we as a community focus on
dropouts. It is an expensive problem that will keep sucking the
economic vitality out of the region. The overall dropout rate at
AISD is around 8 percent, but at some schools it is closer to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is a community scandal.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of moral arguments that can be made about
stanching that hemorrhage of potential, but let's just look at the
problem from an economic perspective.
</P>
<P>
   If we are losing half of a student population, that's that many
workers who are unprepared to participate in the boom. In fact,
that's that many citizens who will pick our pockets either
literally or with their needs for public assistance, including
housing and health care. And we all know that incarceration isn't
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't reach ``at-risk'' youngsters without help from
their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Thomas, who graduates next month from Gonzalo Garza High,
summed it up aptly. ``A $6 or $7 an hour job looks better than
teachers telling you that you're failing.''
</P>
<P>
   And dropping out is way too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Students just disappear, sometimes despite the best efforts and
arguments of their peers. Amy Haugval, a senior, recounted her
attempts to keep a friend from becoming a statistic. It didn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Amy learned early that life doesn't come with guarantees, but
she made the effort and for that she should be commended.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we can do our part to foster that by focusing serious time,
money and attention to this problem. And anyone who thinks there is
a quick fix is not living on the same planet as the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the problem is compounded by the school district's
shredded credibility on the issue. It will take a long time for the
district to recover from the indictment of falsifying data.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as the experience was, it should guide us all in
urging the district to share the bad news quickly and completely so
that we can attack the problem in ways that will get results.
</P>
<P>
   There are many recommendations that the 55-member task force on
dropouts looked at. They are expensive, but then so is the
situation. Dropouts never quit costing us money.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, we should keep encouraging Amy and others
like her to help us as much as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
