<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8606 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN28-COX     04-27 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A strategy that Democrats can love
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Al From, chairman of the Democratic Leadership
Council, recalled President Lyndon B. Johnson's lament on signing a
civil-rights bill in the 1960s ``that we're giving away the South
(to the Republicans) for a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   It came true. But a generation is up, From said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have recaptured Southern governorships they'd lost _
some thought forever _ in Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia, South
Carolina and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The key, From said, is ``we've finally figured out how to put
together a coalition of blacks, who vote in greater numbers now,
and basically moderate whites, who have appeal in the black
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The DLC was formed in the mid-1980s, after Republican Ronald
Reagan's landslide re-election. One of its first stalwarts was an
Arkansas governor named Bill Clinton. He combined business-friendly
economics with sensitivity to traditionally Democratic social
issues and won the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Those center-left politics also elected leaders in countries
such as England, Germany and others that a decade ago were led by
conservatives, From said.
</P>
<P>
   The DLC's success has been ``spectacular,'' particularly at the
presidential level, From said. ``Bill Clinton's sitting there with
approval ratings higher than when he took office, because the
economy's good, crime's down, welfare's down _ and all the stuff
that we set out to do, we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   And even as From seeks to elect another DLC stalwart, Vice
President Al Gore, as president over Texas' Republican governor,
George W. Bush, he's talking with Texans such as Austin Mayor Kirk
Watson and other Democrats from around the state about the party's
future here.
</P>
<P>
   From calls the DLC's success strategy ``the third way.'' It
drops the big-government approach Democrats carried forth from the
New Deal and World War II. As the industrial age has given way to
the information age, From said, centralized government often
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too slow,'' From said. ``It doesn't respond quickly
enough. And so you've got to modernize it, move control more to the
local level. It doesn't mean you have to lower standards, but you
have to increase flexibility. It's ideas like charter schools, like
community policing, like civic environmentalism _ where individual
communities can figure out how they implement environmental
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The third way stresses private-sector economic growth,
opportunity with responsibility, a global outlook that includes
free trade, and innovative and flexible government with as little
bureaucracy as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the key for Democrats is real simple: If you're credible
on fiscal discipline, crime and welfare, then you get to the agenda
that favors us _ which is education and health care and the
environment. Those are sort of threshold issues _ and if you think
about what Clinton did, that's what he did. I mean, we're going to
balance the budget, protect education, Medicaid, Medicare and the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Bush's recent stress on housing programs for
minorities, federal help to teach kids to read and cleaning up
industrial pollution seem like echoes of Clinton's 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But while Democrats have to overcome suspicion from voters that
they're just tax-and-spend big-government liberals, ``Bush has the
opposite problem,'' From said. ``That's why he has to call himself
a `compassionate conservative' _ because people don't trust the
Republicans to be compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   From believes the DLC's brand of politics appeals to the rapidly
growing number of upper-middle class ``wired'' workers who are
quickly becoming a political majority.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the DLC, From said, is ``whether we continue to
own the politics we've created'' and ``take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you have a candidate who runs on the new Democrat
message in Texas,'' From said, ``he or she can be the next governor
of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
