<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bourbon: Proof of a higher power
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Congress declared bourbon our national drink
in 1964 and Kentucky is the biggest producer in the country. Many
of the state's distilleries offer tours, but no samples.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beam, the largest bourbon distillery in the world, features
a promotional film laced with company propaganda, but several good
displays about the history and process of the drink. More than
anything you'll see there, it's nice to smell the charred oak
housed in huge warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's sweet limestone water and an aging process that
requires two years in charred white oak barrels that can be used
just once give the drink its color and sweet taste.
</P>
<P>
   A few facts about the drink:
</P>
<P>
   _ A couple of centuries ago, corn whiskey was popular currency
in trading because it was easier to store and to transport than
grain. Abraham Lincoln's father, among others, would accept it
instead of cash. The ``proof'' of its content was measured by its
ability to burn gunpowder. A steady blue flame was worth 100 proof.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bourbon is a kind of whiskey made from at least 51 percent
corn. To be called bourbon, it must be made in the United States.
Most bourbon is made in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rev. Elijah Craig of Georgetown, Ky., invented bourbon in 1789
when he accidentally charred his barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
