</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SFLORIDA-TOURISM28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials hopeful Elian furor won't turn off tourists
 &HT;    By Stephanie Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Police in riot armor standing guard as
trash bins and tires burn. Threats of citywide strikes and blocked
traffic by angry, defiant protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The violent images broadcast around the world as a result of
federal agents' removal of Elian Gonzalez from Miami's Little
Havana district are not the ``sun and fun'' pictures that sell
South Florida tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a region whose image is already as a powder keg, a region
in the news because of corrupt politicians, raging fires,
hurricanes, crime, I don't think the Elian case helped,'' said
hospitality industry analyst Mark Lunt of Ernst &AMP; Young in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   While the protests have been mostly peaceful, with few injuries
and little property damage, the images have not been.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just see the images, it looks like Miami was this huge
flaming protest,'' Lunt said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Warren ``Mac'' McLaughlin, president of Palm Beach County's
Convention and Visitors Bureau, said this week that any time
there's talk of strikes and protests, tourists are turned off.
</P>
<P>
   People like to avoid trouble spots on their vacations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a tourist, you darn sure wouldn't want to go
anywhere near where there was a citywide strike,'' McLaughlin said
Monday. ``Then there's the fires. All it really was was tires
burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, perception is not reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But perception is everything in tourism.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 Florida wildfires, tourism-related sales tax
collections dropped 34 percent statewide in June and July from the
previous year because tourists stayed away, thinking the entire
state was on fire, tourism officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, three separate killings of foreign tourists in Miami
caused a loss of 100,000 visitors over 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials said the weekend's tumultuous events
shouldn't hurt the state's $42 billion tourism industry. Even if it
did, there's little to be done about it, said Visit Florida
spokesman Tom Flanigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do? What do you say? It's a lose-lose
proposition,'' Flanigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Any effects should be limited to Miami-Dade County because 92
percent of visitors to Florida have been to the state before and
have some idea that Miami is near the southern tip of the state,
Flanigan said.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami itself so far, there has not been any measurable
effect, said Jeanne Sullivan, a spokeswoman for the Greater Miami
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really been seeing major cancellations or any major
concerns,'' Sullivan said. ``We have had people speculating ... and
I don't want to start fueling a fire that's not already there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
