<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CASSIDY28-COX     04-27 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CASSIDY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriller unmasks FBI's counterspy operation
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The best entry point to ``Cassidy's
Run'' may be, of all places, one of the jacket blurbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bag the novels,'' urges R. James Woolsey, ``Read `Cassidy's
Run'.'' Woolsey is a former director of the CIA. His approval means
David Wise isn't making this stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff'' is a long-running counterspy operation by the
FBI, an agency toward which former CIA directors tend to mumble
their praise.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy was an Army sergeant in a job that would interest the
Soviets. The FBI dangled him before a known spy in the Soviets'
Washington embassy. The spy _ in time, there were four, all calling
themselves ``Mike'' _ played volleyball at a YMCA. So Cassidy
played volleyball at the same YMCA, changing back into his uniform
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Playing led to conversation, to dinner, to Mike recruiting
Cassidy. It was a neat seduction, but Cassidy wasn't hard to get.
From the summer of 1959 until the summer of 1978, the Soviets
thought Cassidy was their guy.
</P>
<P>
   Through him, the FBI identified 10 Soviet spies, including a
``sleeper'' _ a book editor in New York whose only role was to take
the coded phone call if a Soviet agent needed to tell the Russians
the Pentagon was about to go on a war alert and pass on the
message.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was called Shocker. It gave the FBI a close look
at what the Soviets wanted to know and at their codes, invisible
inks and special cameras. The bureau learned how the Soviets made
fake rocks. Yes, spies actually drop hollow, rock-looking
containers holding documents for other spies to pick up. The book
has photos of a college professor and his wife picking up a fake
rock Cassidy left for them.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI also collected the $200,000 the Russians paid Cassidy
over the years for what they thought were his services. But the FBI
gave something in return.
</P>
<P>
   When Cassidy was dangled, he was working at the Edgewood
Arsenal, east of Baltimore, where top-secret nerve gas research was
carried out. The Kremlin wanted to know what the researchers were
learning. Cassidy was in a position to shed light.
</P>
<P>
   The papers he ``stole'' had to be real. Who knew what other
sources the Soviets had? The documents were cleared by a secret
committee so we would tell the Soviets only what we were pretty
sure they already knew. This is smoke and mirrors straight from
John LeCarre.
</P>
<P>
   Wise found a scary, ironic twist. He doesn't make an
open-and-shut case, but here is the outline:
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 4,500 documents slipped to the Soviet embassy
concerned a theoretical nerve gas that U.S. scientists were sure
couldn't be turned into a usable weapon. A huge fish die-off
followed a few years later, in 1965, on the Volga River close to
the Soviet equivalent of Edgewood.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1991, as communism collapsed, a scientist revealed that
his country has a top-secret gas it is telling no one about.
``Without access to the top-secret archives of the Soviet nerve-gas
program, it is not possible to know whether the nerve gas formulas
passed to the Russians by Operation Shocker led, directly or
indirectly, to the development of (the gas),'' Wise writes. ``But
there is evidence that information obtained by Soviet intelligence
about the American nerve-gas program did influence Moscow's own
decisions and efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wise is a veteran reporter with proven intelligence
sources. The FBI didn't give him the story of Operation Shocker. He
had to interview the men and women who were involved to get it.
There are no ``re-created'' quotes, so if you take Woolsey's advice
to ``bag the novel,'' you don't get dialogue. But you get a true
story of how the FBI spied on Russian diplomats and others while
they spied on the United States, and a feel for the personalities
involved. In the secret history of spying, Shocker must hold some
records. It ran longer than ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
