<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eire force: Liam O'Flaherty is back in print
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In this country, Liam O'Flaherty is
remembered, when he's remembered at all, as the author of ``The
Informer,'' the seminal story of the Irish troubles and of Gypo
Nolan, the confused boyo who turns a friend in for a few English
pounds. Even ``The Informer'' would have been forgotten if not for
John Ford's 1935 film, which won Victor McLaglen a Best Actor
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Flaherty has always been regarded as one of the major
Irish writers, and St. Martin's is bringing out his ``Collected
Stories'' in three volumes ($35 apiece). The stories span the years
from 1922 to '58, and they're often short, lyrical pieces about
rural Ireland, especially the forbidding Aran islands, where
O'Flaherty was born.
</P>
<P>
   The volumes include several stories that were written in Irish,
as well as some stories that have never been published until now.
</P>
<P>
   EVERYTHING OLD IS NEW AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   On the reissue front, Modern Library's War imprint is in high
gear with ``The Book of War'' ($18.95), which includes Sun-Tzu and
Von Clausewitz. In the same series, there's Teddy Roosevelt's ``The
Rough Riders'' ($12.95), with an introduction by Edmund Morris,
Roosevelt's best biographer and Reagan's worst. Both volumes
feature a few words from series editor Caleb Carr, and the texts
have been completely reset.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a real obscurity, Jack London's ``Before Adam,'' has
been issued by Bison Books, the pop-culture imprint of the
University of Nebraska Press. Originally written as a magazine
serial in 1906-07, it's a fantasia about a modern man who regresses
to the consciousness of an ancestor called Big Tooth, struggling to
survive in Africa during the Pleistocene era.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really very good, but it's really interesting _ London,
as anybody who's read ``The Call of the Wild'' knows, knew animals,
and infuses Big Tooth and the other cavemen with the empathetic
understanding he brought to his dog stories. ``Before Adam''
undoubtedly served as inspiration for a couple of D.W. Griffith
film shorts made at Biograph that centered on cavemen.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have skill and no imagination, it can nonetheless
result in very attractive and interesting things, like wickerwork
and picnic baskets _ usable, pleasant. On the other hand, if you've
got a great deal of imagination and no skill, what results is
modern art.'' _Tom Stoppard
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
