<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HAPPY28-COX     04-27 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HAPPY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Get Happy' goes deeper than just judging Judy
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The picture that emerges from Gerald
Clarke's biography of Judy Garland is not a radical departure _
she's the same more or less hopeless case she's always been.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Get Happy'' does go deeper, does have more simpatico with
its subject, perhaps because Clarke got access to the tape
recordings Garland made for a never-completed autobiography.
Garland's venomous ramblings give portions of his book a startling
immediacy, as she lashes out at her mother and all the other people
she believed failed her.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, whose previous biographical subject was Truman Capote,
thereby indicating a specialty in celebrity junkies, is a better
writer than many who till these particular fields.
</P>
<P>
   But, like most people who tackle Garland, he grows a little weak
in the knees in describing her talent: ``Her pipes, as Variety
called them, had ripened into the rutilant maturity of midsummer
...''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, David Begelman, usually known as a shyster agent and
embezzler, is here compared to one of Milton's fallen angels.
</P>
<P>
   But any serious book about Judy Garland has to attempt to span
the large gap between the fragmentary brilliance of her art and the
unholy mess of her life, and the process by which the latter
overwhelmed the former. Hyperbole is probably justified, for
Garland was greatly gifted, and greatly disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   She was the daughter of small-time vaudevillians. Her mother was
a joyless, slave-driving bitch who denied her daughter any
semblance of childhood or emotional warmth. It was Momma Ethel who
started giving the child pills to get her to the peak excitement
she thought the girl needed to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Garland's father was extremely loving, extremely warm and
extremely homosexual, always getting kicked out of towns because of
his behavior with the local boys.
</P>
<P>
   If everything else in Garland's life had gone right, it would
have been difficult to overcome such a dreadful environment, such
an irresponsible pair of parental influences.
</P>
<P>
   Even after she became a star, Garland had a series of
relationships with men who were either bisexual (Tyrone Power) or
homosexual (Vincente Minnelli). Her first suicide attempt came when
she discovered Minnelli, by then her husband, in bed with a male
friend.
</P>
<P>
   (That Garland's daughter Lizareenacted a similar pathology is
obvious. In one of Clarke's less-than-kind moments, he informs us
that Peter Allen, Liza Minnelli's first husband, was having an
affair with Mark Herron, Garland's fourth, while they were married
to their respective spouses.)
</P>
<P>
   After Minnelli, who was at least a top talent, Garland tended to
involve herself with hustlers who used her, separated her from her
money, then moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the last days, there was something ragged and
helpless about Garland. Joseph Mankiewicz was unlike many of her
men in that he was both heterosexual and smart. He was also
married, but you can't have everything. In any case, he and Garland
had a fairly serious romance, but, he told Clarke, ``I wasn't in
love that way. I was in love _ and I know this is a terrible
analogy _ the way you love an animal, a pet.''
</P>
<P>
   True masochists never have to search hard for the punishment
they believe they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   What justifies the morass of Garland's life? Well, there was
that spectacular voice, a great silver trumpet that she could
direct with discretion and a sense of drama second to none. (She
was like Sinatra in one aspect only _ she acted a song at least as
much as she sang it.) She could dance, she could act, she could, at
her best, be a machine for giving an audience joy.
</P>
<P>
   Her talent meant that she was born to be in show business,
except that show business was the worst possible business for
someone with Garland's neediness, her insecurity. No amount of
praise or love could ever ameliorate her desperation. Even the most
rapturous audience can applaud for only five or 10 minutes, and
then there's just more unnerving silence.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she was wildly unreliable; of the 135 days it took to
rehearse and shoot the MGM musical ``The Pirate,'' Garland was
absent for 99 of them. No wonder so many of her middle and late
films are strangely jagged and dramatically unsatisfying; the
filmmakers had to get what they could when they could. Shaping a
performance, a movie, was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   The ending was particularly grim, with Garland, looking 30 years
older than she was, one step ahead of the tax man, flogging her
deteriorated voice, unemployable in any venue except concerts,
where undiscriminating audiences gathered to watch a ghoulish
horror show.
</P>
<P>
   She was unhinged by now, years of booze and pills finally
eroding what seems to have been a warm, essentially decent person.
Finally, she OD'd on the toilet, a death that failed to serve as a
cautionary tale for Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Happy'' is not a salacious book, although there are
salacious things in it. Clarke seems to genuinely like Garland and
revere her talent, although he's stronger on her singing than on
her movies, which he gives short shrift. But he misses the humor
that people who knew Garland insist she had, and he fails to
communicate her capacity for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just me, but perhaps this is one story that doesn't
really benefit from repeated tellings. Perhaps it's better to leave
this ravaged spirit in peace, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
