</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EYMAN _ Scott Eyman's weekly books column ... In this
country, Liam O'Flaherty is remembered, when he's remembered at
all, as the author of The Informer, the seminal story of the Irish
troubles and of Gypo Nolan, the confused boyo who turns a friend in
for a few English pounds. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HAPPY _ Review of new Judy Garland biography ``Get
Happy.'' (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CASSIDY_ Review of ``Cassidy's Run'' by David Wise.
(Blackburn, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0425 -- Gail Evans is already feeling the effects
of her first book, ``Play Like a Man, Win Like a Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Her female subordinates at CNN, where she's executive vice
president, have been using tips from her book to negotiate better
perks for themselves: a bonus, a better office, a bigger car
allowance. Maybe that wasn't quite what Evans had in mind when she
wrote ``Play Like a Man.'' It's more like ``The Rules'' for women
on the corporate ladder, (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes a 3-column color photo of Gail Evans.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW GENIUS -- In ``A Heartbreaking Work of a Staggering
Genius,'' Dave Eggers comes across as overly obsessive, too
sarcastic and too thin-skinned. But you also leave grateful that
Eggers doesn't care whether you like him, because his honesty makes
the work more powerful (Ostrowski, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES -- Andre Schiffrin, formerly head of
Pantheon, now heading The New Press, has written ``The Business of
Books: How The International Conglomerates Took Over Publishing and
Changed the Way We Read.'' Verso will publish in August.
``Illiterate businessmen as the heads of publishing houses are not
a new phenomenon,'' he writes. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW RUNNING MATE -- In ``Primary Colors'' by Joe Klein
(aka ``Anonymous'') took a Clinton clone _ a fast-talking Southern
governor beset with bimbo eruptions and questions about his draft
record _ and starred him in a gossipy, extra-lite version of ``All
the King's Men.'' Klein's new novel, ``The Running Mate,'' morphs
John McCain with Spencer Tracy and Martin Sheen and stars him in a
glib made-for-TV variation on the 1948 Capra movie, ``State of the
Union.'' (Kakutani, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes a
1-column color photo of author and a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW ARMSTRONG -- You could have forgiven Lance
Armstrong if he had chosen a different, more dramatic title for his
book _ something like ``Miracle on the Champs Elysees.'' But that
might have put undue emphasis on Armstrong's 1999 Tour de France
win, an accomplishment that put an exclamation point on an already
thrilling and highly improbable tale of triumph. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AUTHOR PROFILE -- Like his first book, ``Anam Cara,''
(''Soul Friend,'') John O'Donohue plumbs Celtic wisdom in ``Eternal
Echoes'' to seek answers to contemporary spiritual ills. (Jesse,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Michael Skube on David Wise's ``Cassidy's Run:
The Secret Spy War over Nerve Gas,'' a true adventure.(Skube,
