<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28-CO     04-27 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: This book bag weighs heavy on me
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I'd been feeling low.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing _ 5,000 things _ I'm still sending out free books
for kids. I figure I'm about halfway done, but many of the
addresses are to schools, and the end of school is looming. It
looms, I'm doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Problem this year, in promising a book to any child who writes
in, the offer made it onto the Internet. We're swamped with letters
_ 5,000 still pending _ and teachers are beginning to write now
wanting to know where the books are.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I am alone in this titanic undertaking. My wife works
right along beside me, and never, never complains. Still, I'm
feeling low.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing, I had been watching a network prime-time news
program. One report was about a products test group that straps
umbrellas to cars and then determines at what speed the umbrella
will collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The next show coming up, which I didn't watch, was an
investigation into whether a beauty pageant was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   And a promo for the next day's show involved sending undercover
reporters into big cities in the guise of tourists, to stand on
street corners holding city maps and looking lost. The idea is to
reveal which cities are friendly to visitors and which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to running tests on cars to determine at what
speed they would collapse and kill their passengers?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to investigation whether public elections had
been rigged?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to sending undercover reporters into big
cities in the guise of the down-and-out to reveal in which cities
cops will shoot you if you look scary?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is modern journalism, and I don't know much
about modern journalism. Still I was feeling low.
</P>
<P>
   The closest I ever came to modern journalism was the newspaper
business, and that was a long time ago when life was simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Readers wanted to know what was going on _ particularly anything
that shouldn't be going on _ at their courthouse, schoolhouse and
city hall. Their umbrellas they could take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On a newspaper, the idea was that you got the news, you got it
right and you got it first.
</P>
<P>
   Radio and TV, eventually, made it difficult for papers to get
the news first.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that has changed in the past few years, thanks to the
Internet. Newspapers with their own web sites pop the news to their
readers at the speed of light, big improvement over the speed of a
linotype machine.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we have the technology working for us, I just hope we
remember what we're working for.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper business, we used to say, is not a complicated
business. What you do, you get some paper and put some news on it,
preferably stuff that everybody doesn't already know about.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven only knows what's going on at your courthouse, your
schoolhouse and your city hall that you don't know about. You make
book on it.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me ...
</P>
<P>
   I gotta get back to work mailing these books.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, people still want to read.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; web site, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
