<HEADER>
A8628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-25-VIETNAM27-COX     04-27 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-25-VIETNAM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories linger 25 years after Vietnam
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, April 30
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ho Chi Minh Trail, napalm and body bags, fragging, Khe Sanh,
the Tet Offensive. ...''
</P>
<P>
   To Americans over 40, certain words and phrases once seemed to
hang thick in the air we breathed, seemed suspended in the water we
drank. They were part of the atmosphere in which a generation came
of age, and in which the nation as a whole matured into something
wiser and perhaps stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent State, humping the boonies, Hendrix, gooks, draft cards,
4-F, the Americal Division. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the words retain the power to summon memories.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago today, Saigon fell to the Vietnamese
Communists, the consequence of a decision by President Nixon two
years earlier to pull all U.S. troops out of the country. Once the
last helicopter had lifted off Vietnamese rooftops, once the guns
had fallen quiet there, all those words that had seemed so fraught
with meaning suddenly ceased to matter, and ceased to be heard as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for a long time we didn't even talk about Vietnam much,
because any discussion tended to spiral into blame and
recrimination. Everyone had a theory, a favorite bad guy. The
politicians lied to us and misled us, miring the country in a war
they wouldn't let the military win. Or, the military lost the war
through sheer incompetence, trying to win a guerrilla conflict
through traditional means. Or, the peaceniks had betrayed the
country by demonstrating while American kids were fighting and
dying overseas. Or, the leftist media had confused the American
public by focusing only on what was going wrong in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the war, the United States and its people seemed
to go into an odd sort of sleepwalk, a ``malaise,'' as former
President Jimmy Carter infamously but accurately phrased it.
Vietnam _ and the division it inspired among us _ became the
unspoken, unacknowledged and unconfronted subtext to almost every
political dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, however, we found other, less confrontational means
of talking about it. Writers such as Michael Herr, in his
extraordinarily honest book ``Dispatches,'' depicted the moral
horror of life as a grunt. Stanley Karnow, Neil Sheehan and others
explored the policy mistakes and misconceptions that led us to
disaster. Novelist Tim O'Brien, a veteran himself, depicted 'Nam as
a surreal nightmare in ``The Things They Carried,'' and Bobbie Ann
Mason explored the reconciliation of veterans with their families
in the poignant ``In Country.'' Movie depictions ranged from the
operatic ``Apocalypse Now'' to the almost saccharine ``Forrest
Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that material, particularly the movies, failed as an
expression of truth about Vietnam. But it did at least expose the
nation to a complexity of viewpoints about the subject. Art
penetrates bias; it forces us to see as others might see. In this
case, however, the biggest contribution to understanding and
reconciliation came from the unlikeliest art of all, architecture.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, a 21-year-old student named Maya Lin won a design
contest for a Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington. Her concept,
as Lin described it in documents submitted to contest judges, was
eloquent and simple:
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking through this park, the memorial appears as a rift in
the earth. A long, polished, black stone wall, emerging from and
receding on either side, growing out of the earth, extend and
converge at a point below and ahead. Walking into this grassy site
contained by the walls of the Memorial, we can barely make out the
carved names upon the Memorial's walls. These names, seemingly
infinite in number, convey the sense of overwhelming numbers, while
unifying these individuals into a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   While initially controversial, Lin's memorial was quickly
recognized as a work of great power and beauty. It does not preach,
but its quiet simplicity forces visitors to think and to
contemplate. It's the perfect memorial to a war that still defies
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   We do agree now that those who fought in Vietnam were the
victims, not the villains, of a way gone awry. We understand now
that no democracy should engage in war without overwhelming public
support, and that U.S. power, however vast, still has limits.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of that last lesson is best expressed by the contrast
in two statements that bookended the American experience in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, President Kennedy pledged the United States ``to pay
any price, bear any burden, meet any hardship, support any friend,
oppose any foe to assure the survival and the success of liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1973, Nixon, in his second Inaugural Address, was expressing
a sadder wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has passed when America will make every other
nation's conflict our own, or make every other nation's future our
responsibility, or presume to tell the people of other nations how
to manage their own affairs,'' Nixon told the country.
</P>
<P>
   We acquired wisdom in Vietnam, hard-earned wisdom about
ourselves and the world around us. But it came at a high price:
58,000 dead soldiers; 58,000 promises never kept; 58,000 names on a
stark black wall. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Michael Allen; Willie Edward Mack; Ronald Alex Staley,
William Thomas Wallace Jr. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Those words too have the power to summon memories.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is an editorial writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
