<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8631 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      04-27 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING WHILE INTOXICATED CAN LAND YOU IN JAIL  
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we pulled into town that night we saw the flashing lights but
we were wrapped up in a conversation and didn't realize until it
was too late that we were at a sobriety check point.
</P>
<P>
   I had no time to rehearse, no time to grab the piece of gum my
friend was sliding across the seat to me before there was a uniform
at the window. The officer greeted us and then asked if I, the
driver, had had anything to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I said, because that was the truth and I had no time to
consider the wisdom of telling the truth. What time had I had
something to drink, he wondered. I said I had a glass of wine with
dinner, at 6 p.m. or so.
</P>
<P>
   And what time do you think it is now, he asked.
</P>
<P>
   This is when I started thinking there might be trick questions,
like when you're at a border stop on a foreign train and they bring
on the drug-sniffing dogs and ask for your passport. You're pretty
sure you're not guilty but are positive you look guilty anyhow and
hope they don't ask questions because no one's told you what you're
supposed to answer.
</P>
<P>
   The logical thing to do when asked the time is to look at one's
watch or one's dashboard clock, but my brain decided he wanted to
know if I had any sense of the actual hour. So I said probably
around 11 p.m. And then I looked over at the clock and saw I was 20
minutes off. My friend thought for sure I was a goner.
</P>
<P>
   But it satisfied the officer who waved us on and told us to have
a nice night.
</P>
<P>
   Did we scream with relief as soon as we turned the corner? Yes.
Had I lied?
</P>
<P>
   Well, I omitted parts of the truth. In the last hour I'd also
had a glass and a half of wine with some crackers and cheese. Was I
lucky? Incredibly so. Would I have failed a breathalyzer test? I
have no idea. Have I learned my lesson? Yes, yes, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend was not so lucky. She drove home from a dinner
party and was stopped by two officers who said she overshot the
stop sign. She explained that was the only way she could see
oncoming cars. They asked if she had been drinking. She said yes,
one glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   She says now, ``What was I going to say? Five?'' They asked her
to step up out of her car, tested her and took her to jail.
</P>
<P>
   I've been noticing that the imbibing world is divided into
believers and scoffers. The scoffers drink and drive like we used
to, not realizing that the cop who took a whiff but gave you only a
warning ``to get home now and be careful'' doesn't exist much
anymore. The believers have learned firsthand or from the chilling
account of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, who I'll call Betsy, had to walk a straight line,
follow a flashlight beam with her eyes and stand with her feet
together, head back with eyes closed, a feat she doubts she could
accomplish stone sober. Then they had her blow into a breathalyzer,
at which point they arrested her for drunk driving and handcuffed
her.
</P>
<P>
   In jail they told Betsy she was uncooperative. Her story is
while waiting to be processed her nose itched and she slipped her
hand from her cuffs to scratch it.
</P>
<P>
   Then she spoke up for her cell mate, a woman arrested driving
home from a baby shower where she drank a couple of beers. The
woman asked to call her husband and was refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `This isn't right. Her husband will think she had an
accident.' The officer basically said that I should mind my own
business. He said they don't cater to drunks and the next time we
ladies went out drinking we should remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy left the next morning after her boyfriend posted bail. She
went home and took a bath but that wasn't the end. She went to
court and pleaded no contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lawyer because I was guilty. I did what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   She attended drunk driving school for 16 weeks, two hours a
week, ``for which there are no excuses. You almost have to die to
miss a class.''
</P>
<P>
   One hour was spent watching videos on drug and alcohol abuse _
she liked the Bill Moyers' one. The other hour was for group
discussion ``in which we tried to figure out who really had an
alcohol problem and who didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She was given a suspended license which allowed her to drive
only to the class and to work. She ended up paying close to $2,000
in fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible experience. It messes you up financially.
And it messes your head up about drinking which maybe is a good
thing since I've had to look at how much I drink. The cops treat
you like scum, but I guess that's the point. You are risking other
people's lives when you do this and that makes you sort of a
crumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too. It was my wine that she drank that night. I remember
thinking when she pulled out of the driveway that I hoped she'd get
home OK.
</P>
<P>
   Do I feel guilty? Sure.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
