<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      04-27 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLBURY: HERE WE GO AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news Wednesday from Uniondale, N.Y., was that the Islanders
were sold. That should sound familiar. In fact, given the frequency
that it occurs, it almost doesn't qualify as news.
</P>
<P>
   A headline that read, ``Islander ownership refuses to sell,'' or
maybe ``Isles owner: I'm with this club to bitter end,'' now that
would be something to cause a stir out there in the forgotten spit
of a raggedy rink that once was hallowed Stanley Cup ground.
</P>
<P>
   But another Islander sale? Perhaps only Liz Taylor has seen more
partnerships dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it's been tough,'' said Islander general manager Mike
Milbury, who once was the heir apparent to take over Harry Sinden's
job in Boston. ``In fact, a lot of it through the years has been
uncomfortably tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Milbury this spring wrapped up his fifth year as the
Islanders' full-time GM. By his count, dating back to his arrival
on the Island in '95, the Islanders have been held by seven
ownership groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anybody,'' lamented the 47-year-old Milbury,
``who's gone through more changes and turmoil than this club.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly almost every nine months, a new bunch of millionaires
wash ashore on Long Island like some ``Gilligan's Island''
castaways, mistakingly identifying Nassau Coliseum as a lifeboat
that will sail them to even greater riches.
</P>
<P>
   It just hasn't been the case, of course. One after another the
owners have fallen by the wayside, often vacating Islander
headquarters at warp speed, left with egos bruised and wallets
battered. Meanwhile, Milbury has had to live out a mandate,
repeated by each owner, to make the team interesting and
competitive while shaving its payroll, which is now last in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Free economics being what it is, be it on Wall Street or along
the hockey highway, you usually get what you pay for. For the
Islanders, that has meant a product that barely brings fans to the
building anymore. They have missed the playoffs six consecutive
seasons, a streak that is three times longer than they had to
endure as an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Last in payroll. Last in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   And now, most likely, last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Into the breach this time wanders Charles Wang, a Long Island
computer executive who has ponied up some $190 million to purchase
the franchise that rattled off four straight Cups (1980-83). At
least he's bought that faint memory. For today, he's purchased a
money drain, knowing full well he'll lose millions of dollars in
the short-term.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's hope is that, with some seed money, Milbury can fill out
around a young nucleus of talent, prop up the dispirited franchise,
and get it moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury's contract has three years remaining. ``And if I can't
do it in three seasons, well then, off with my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury said he has been assured that he'll have money to spend.
He can shop for free agents, although, by his own admission,
``(this summer's group) is the worst free agent class in a few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders own the No. 5 pick in the June amateur draft, but
they could be enticed to deal it if a team wants to move a
high-ticket player.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury is well-versed in getting the dollars down. ``Last
summer, I had to get the payroll down,'' he said. ``I came back
with three plans, ways to get to $15 million, then $12.5 million,
and then $10 million. We got to $15 million and I said, `Well, we
can get rid, of (Felix) Potvin (ultimately dealt to Vancouver) and
that will put us around $12.5 million. But to get to $10 million,
you might as well get rid of everybody and just hire 20 guys off
the street and pay 'em $125,000 each.'''
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Hub, where the Bruins have been owned by Jeremy
Jacobs since the creation of fire, fans and media have railed
against the club's out-of-town, bottom-line ownership for years.
For the better part of 10 seasons, the club has been run as a real
budget operation, almost K Mart in context, and the result has been
a team that has failed to make the playoffs twice in the last four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on sports talk radio, be it noon or midnight, and it's a
virtual guarantee that someone will spew venom over Jacobs, then
move on to Sinden and Mike O'Connell, and eventually get to the
real culprits: the media who allow this sham to perpetuate.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the carnage on Causeway has not been pretty. Jacobs's
lean-and-mean approach has alienated a huge portion of the fan
base. Not since Bobby Orr left town as a free agent has Bruins
Nation been as hot to trot, so willing, almost eager to find
something else to do with their average $50-a-night game ticket.
Faithfully, they've waited 28 years for another Cup and some are
just now giving up their prime parade positions at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who seek some solace, all it takes is a look some
225 miles southwest for a touch of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, it can be worse,'' said Milbury, comparing the
situations. ``Look, Jeremy Jacobs has been what he's been since he
bought that team. He's made no bones about the fact that, `I've
invested a lot of money here, in the team and the building . . . Do
I want to make money? Yes! Do I want to lose money? No!' Most of
all, he's consistent, he's never wavered, and, by and large, the
club's benefited from that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think they've got a pretty good club there, when
everyone's healthy. They've got good management, a good coach _ I'm
glad that's all patched up _ and I'll betcha dollars to doughnuts
that they're back in the playoffs next year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one day since Charles Wang took control of the Islanders. A
quick check of the transactions this morning didn't turn up another
ownership swap. The club that once ruled the spring with the NHL's
most potent power play is going on 24 hours of granite-slab
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury, ex-defenseman, ex-minor league coach, ex-NHL coach,
ex-assistant GM, maintains his grip on what has been a very
unsteady wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still standing,'' he said, his voice a blend of the
wistful and whimsical. ``I'm still here. I'm not embarrassed to
tell you, I had the moving boxes ready to load. I'm just kidding,
but hey, in some ways . . . I was prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
