<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIM NEWS IN LATEST REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought Wednesday morning's snow was depressing, brace
yourself for what could be another rotten day.
</P>
<P>
   The government is releasing two economic reports _ one on
growth, the other on wages _ that have the potential to move the
markets in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get numbers that suggest booming growth and developing
labor-cost pressures, that could be a lethal combination,'' said
Mark Zandi, chief economist at RFA Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania
forecasting firm. ``It would support the case for much more
tightening by the Federal Reserve, and that would be difficult for
stocks and bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Fridays ago, an inflation report that came in higher than
expected sent the Nasdaq Composite index tumbling almost 10
percent. Both new- and old-economy stocks have since rallied, on
the belief that there really isn't much to worry about. The latest
reports may put that view to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go to the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the gross domestic product for the first quarter.
While estimates vary, forecasters agree on one thing: ``It will be
a big number,'' said Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The betting is that GDP will come in at an annual pace of around
6 percent. That follows 7.3 percent in the fourth quarter and 5.7
percent in the third quarter. These are numbers you would expect
from Singapore or South Korea, not from the world's largest
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Growth has been powered by consumer spending on houses, cars,
and just about everything else. Business investment has been
strong, too. Five rates hikes by the Fed have not done anything yet
to dent the economy's momentum. Wayne Ayers, chief economist at
FleetBoston Financial Corp., said the Fed would like to see growth
in the 3.5 to 4 percent range. A 6 percent number would not make
Greenspan and company happy.
</P>
<P>
   The GDP report also will measure first-quarter inflation. The
March consumer price index revealed that prices have started to
climb on items besides gasoline and heating oil. A big move up in
the price component of the GDP could add fuel to that fire.
</P>
<P>
   A more important guage of inflationary pressure will be this
morning's second report, the employment cost index. The ECI
measures the growth in wages and benefits. If you assume that labor
costs are the biggest expense a company faces, rising personnel
costs make it more likely that a company will consider raising
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters expect total compensation _ a blend of wages and
benefits _ to show a 1.1 percent gain for the quarter. That doesn't
sound like a big number, but it represents an increase from where
gains have been over the past few years. Potentially more troubling
is the fact that increases may come from both the wage and benefit
sides of the ledger.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years, corporate America got a break on the
benefit side because health care costs had flattened out. Those
costs are on the rise again _ health insurance premiums are up 8 to
10 percent this year _ and the ECI may reflect that trend.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up and what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the idea that the Fed has a lot more work to do,''
Zandi said. Conventional wisdom says the Fed will increase rates
two more times this year, and that will be enough to bring the
economy in for a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   That view, Zandi said, may be way too sanguine. He thinks it
could take as many as four more rates hikes to do the trick. If
he's right, and investors recognize it, the impact on the market
may not be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   New-economy fans will counter this doom and gloom by pointing to
productivity numbers that have been very strong for the past year.
Who cares if wages are rising, they will say, as long as workers
are producing more with less?
</P>
<P>
   They will also note that even if inflation is rising, the
increases are very modest. What's wrong with, say, 3 percent
inflation, if everything else is going so well?
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, the Fed is not likely to subscribe to that
benign view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   What does all this mean for investors?
</P>
<P>
   It may mean that there will be no safe place in the market to
hide. Over the past few weeks, investors have been rotating out of
technology stocks into more traditional holdings on the theory that
traditional stocks are less risky. But if rates are going up, maybe
substantially, those old-economy stocks will not offer much shelter
from the storm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
