<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-GIULIANI-CANCER-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY MAYOR RECEIVES DIAGNOSIS OF PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN and DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that he has
prostate cancer but that it was too early to know whether it would
affect his expected run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at City Hall, Giuliani said routine tests
during a physical examination a little more than two weeks
suggested he might have the disease. A biopsy of his prostate
Wednesday at Mount Sinai Medical Center confirmed a diagnosis of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani told reporters that ``The good news is that there
are lots of possible options.'' He said his form of cancer was in a
very early stage and was ``treatable.'' He also stressed that he
was otherwise in ``terrific'' health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' said the 55-year-old mayor, who appeared
relaxed and at times joked with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned repeatedly about whether the illness would
interfere with the Senate race, Giuliani said, ``I don't think it's
fair to answer questions about the Senate race right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some forms of treatment might require him to take time off,
Giuliani said. ``I may have to reschedule a few things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani will not change his schedule of campaign appearances
because of the cancer diagnosis, said a spokeswoman, Juleanna
Glover Weiss. ``We're proceeding ahead as planned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said it would be several weeks before he decided what
to do. ``I need to know what the course of treatment is before I
can do anything about it,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to a range of treatments, including radiation,
hormones and surgery to remove the prostate gland. The surgical
operation is called a radical prostatectomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to evaluate all of these different options,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the cancer had been caught early enough that
there was no need for emergency treatment, but he added, ``It
wouldn't be a good idea to extend it for a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, Giuliani's Democratic opponent in the
Senate race, said before a campaign stop in Penn Yan, N.Y., that
``Like all New Yorkers, my prayers and best wishes are with the
mayor for a full and speedy recovery, and I hope that everyone
joins me in wishing him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Political figures from both parties sought to separate
Giuliani's health problem from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, who had talked of challenging the mayor for the
Senate nomination, said that now should be a ``private time'' for
the mayor and his family. ``Issues that cut to the core of a
person's health and life transcend election campaigns and
politics,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state chairman of the Republican Party, William D.
Powers, said it was a day for prayers, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hopes and prayers are with Mayor Giuliani and his family,
and we are glad to hear that he has caught this in the early stages
and that the prognosis is good,'' Powers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as he had the strength and courage to turn New York City
around, I know he has the strength and courage to take on this
challenge and win,'' Powers said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani's father died of prostate cancer at the age of 73 in
1981. But Giuliani noted that his father lived until 73, and that
many advances had been made in treating the disease. The mayor said
that having prostate cancer in the family increased the likelihood
of contracting the disease by only 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On a philosophical note, Giuliani said that learning he had
cancer ``makes you think about what's important in life.'' But he
added, ``You should be doing that anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's cancer was detected through a P.S.A. test, which
measures the level of a protein in the prostate that would indicate
cancer. P.S.A. stands for prostate specific antigen. The protein
becomes detectable when cancerous tumors exist.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he took the test twice, and it confirmed an
elevated P.S.A. level. The doctor called him Wednesday with the
diagnosis. ``I kind of expected it,'' Giuliani said. ``The P.S.A.
was high twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the most commonly diagnosed malignancy in
American men, and the second leading cause of death from cancer in
American men. One out of four who are diagnosed with the disease
die of it.
</P>
<P>
   When the cancer has not spread beyond the prostate _ as Giuliani
said applied to his case _ it is generally curable. More than
179,000 U.S. men were diagnosed with prostate cancer last year.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Americans who have been treated successfully for
prostate cancer include former Sen. Bob Dole, Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf and Joe Torre, manager of the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, an avid Yankee fan, said he hoped to speak to Torre
because the Yankee manager had ``been through this.'' Giuliani
added that, `` I'm sure he'll be a source of strength and good
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the owner of the Yankees, George Steinbrenner,
had been among the first to call him to express support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
