<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKPOTS, BROUGHT TO YOU BY `BALANCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, investigative journalists gathered at Harvard
University to talk about their craft. The Associated Press's
Charles Hanley _ who unearthed the Pulitzer Prize-winning story of
the slaughter of civilians at No Gun Ri Bridge during the Korean
War _ explained that one obstacle to good reporting is the axiom
about ``two sides to every story.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after amassing overwhelming evidence of the massacre,
Hanley's team had to find and cite a retired officer who claimed no
knowledge of the event, ``exposing him as either a fool or liar or
whatever else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Always get the other side,'' Hanley added sardonically.
``That's the motto.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that there are two sides to every story can obscure
reality. The point took center stage after last weekend's dramatic
events in Miami as newspapers weighed the merits of balancing the
image of the federal agent brandishing the gun in front of Elian
Gonzalez with photos of him comfortably reuniting with his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Where the concept has truly distorted the media's mission of
clarity and accuracy is in the frantic world of 24/7 cable
coverage. There, the idea that there are two equal sides to every
aspect of the Gonzalez saga served to do what shouting-head TV does
best _ pour gasoline on a flammable situation.
</P>
<P>
   The belief that every issue requires two opposing viewpoints is
the first commandment of the cable news talk show. On any given
``Crossfire,'' ``Hardball,'' or ``Hannity &AMP; Colmes,'' and on any
given issue _ guns, abortion, or whether the sun rises in the east
_ ideological foes do battle without hint of resolution,
concession, or compromise.
</P>
<P>
   There were already enough legitimate angles to the Elian
Gonzalez story to launch 1,000 sensible sound bites. Echoes of the
Cold War, civil disobediance, and of course, family values are
subjects worth debating. But in the wake of Saturday's three-minute
raid to seize the boy, the rhetoric that flowed in the name of
balance hit an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN's ``Evans, Novak, Hunt &AMP; Shields,'' fuming congressman
Lincoln Diaz-Balart (R-Fla.) insisted the brainwashing and
``drugging'' of Elian had begun with his transfer. Appearing on
Larry King's program, Senator Bob Smith (R-N.H.) managed, in one
Evel Knievel-esque leap, to tie the Miami raid to the
administration's decision to renew diplomatic ties with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the host feels compelled to supply the other side of
the story. When Chuck Vance, a former Secret Service agent and CEO
of a large security firm, gave a calm and reasoned rationale for
the tactics used to grab the boy, King could only sputter that the
pictures sure looked ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   King's Saturday show was a model of ``journalistic balance.''
Four critics of the raid squared off against five defenders. When
the argue-fest had ended, the host hoped his viewers found the
program ``illuminating.'' With so much more heat than light?
</P>
<P>
   ``No rumor was too outlandish and no tale too silly to gain
credence,'' wrote Jane Sutton of Reuters. So it is in a media
culture where allegations of doctored photographs and a drugged
6-year-old command instant and equal footing with the denials.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the public seems increasingly immune to
the media sideshow. Polls consistently
</P>
<P>
   show citizens supporting the removal of the boy from the Miami
home, concurring that the government had exercised patience, and
disdaining the idea of congressional hearings on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   These people absorbed the emotional impact of the story. They
were concerned about the amount of force used to transfer Elian and
by a narrow ratio, believed the photograph of the armed agent
finding the boy was more powerful than that of the father-and-son
reunion. But unlike the TV debate shows that pass themselves off as
enlightened discussion, the public can separate emotion from
reason, rhetoric from rationality.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way. A CNN-Gallup poll indicates that by a
whopping 66-to-30 percent ratio, the public disapproves of the
media's performance in this saga. I'm afraid there aren't two sides
to that story, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday, the International Press Institute's World
Congress and 50th anniversary celebration brings a constellation of
media and policy heavyweights to Boston for five days. NBC anchor
Tom Brokaw will discuss broadcasting challenges, Brill's Content
founder Steven Brill will dissect the media's credibility problem,
and former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger will address the
nation's foreign policy priorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
