<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE FOR AN OLD BUTCHER BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My butcher-block countertop needs some TLC; it is badly
stained from food prepared on it. How would I clean and refinish it
_ with oil? The spouse says why not olive oil? She also wants a
nice shiny poly finish, while I'm at it
</P>
<P>
   NAME withheld to protect the guilty, Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Brother, you are on thin ice with She Who Must Be Obeyed, and
so is the handyman, who is about to disagree with her.
</P>
<P>
   The top was probably treated with oil, so to clean it, sand it
to the bare wood. Use a power sander. Then treat with mineral oil.
Do not use olive oil; as good as it is, it will turn rancid. The
mineral oil, less toxic than linseed oil, will not turn. The nice
thing about an oil finish is that you can prepare food on it. You
can even cut on it, but don't; use a cutting board instead. And,
you can apply more oil any time you feel like it.
</P>
<P>
   How about a nice shiny poly finish, asks the spouse? Coming up:
Use an oil-based, high-gloss polyurethane varnish _ two coats,
preferably three. It is a hard finish and will scratch, but still
will give good service. When it looks as if it needs TLC, sand and
refinish.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck to us all, AIGF (all in good faith).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My garage is made of clay blocks that look like concrete, but
are hollow. Some are broken, and sparrows and other small birds
nest in the cavities. I don't mind the birds, only the mess they
make on the wall and on the ground below. How can I fill or cover
those cavities?
</P>
<P>
   JEFF LEVITT, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could fill them with concrete or mortar, but be sure
there's a bottom and sides to those cavities; I would hate to think
of you filling up the whole wall and wondering where all that
mortar went.
</P>
<P>
   Or, stuff the cavities nearly full of wadded paper, then apply
mortar to that to fill. You can tint the mortar to match the clay
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another method is to cover everything: Attach vertical strapping
to the blocks, then apply cedar clapboards and stain them with a
semitransparent stain. Or, apply horizontal strapping and apply
white cedar shingles, letting them weather forever.
</P>
<P>
   Attach the strapping with molly bolts; predrilled holes are
necessary for that. Or, glue them on with construction adhesive.
Then nail on the clapboards or shingles _ carefully.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. One of the options for upgrading my kitchen is to change the
hardware on the cabinets. Trouble is, the handles are set on bolts
3 inches apart, while the replacements I can find at Home Depot are
only 2 3/4 inches apart. I don't like the idea of drilling new
holes and filling old ones. Where can I find new handles that will
fit?
</P>
<P>
   FREDA CANAVAN, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Stores and lumber places don't always have the widest of
selections, and unfortunately don't tell you where you can get what
you want. But try the Renovators catalog at 800-659-2211 or the
Rockler catalog (formerly the Woodworkers' Store) at 800-279-4441.
</P>
<P>
   Both have 3-inch boring handles, and large selections.
Renovators has mostly traditional with some modern; Rockler has a
lot of both.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am building a hardwood bookcase 12 feet long and 7 feet
high, which I will stain and finish. I would like the shelves to be
more than 3/4-inch thick, but am not sure how to do that. Thicker
hardwood shelves would cost a lot more for an already pricey
project. I was thinking of plywood with a hardwood veneer, but how
would I make the shelves thicker?
</P>
<P>
   RALPH LeBLANC, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That should be relatively easy. Don't make the shelves
thicker, only make them look thicker by applying a piece of 1 x 2
hardwood or a fancier molding 1 1/2 inches thick. This is a common
practice, and no disgrace to cabinetmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, support your shelves every 3 feet. You don't want
them sagging after having spent so much labor and cash. Nothing
spoils the looks of a bookcase like a sagging shelf. That 3-foot
span may sound conservative, but I would not take the chance of
anything wider.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I left a rubber bath mat on a white vinyl bathroom floor.
When I picked it up, it left a yellow stain on the vinyl Can I
remove it? I have tried a few things without success.
</P>
<P>
   KELLY MAJOR, Upton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Oops, the old yellow stain on vinyl _ again. It's a plague,
caused by water. And because it's a chemical stain, it's permanent.
Even the white vinyl flooring people have no real answer. But, you
might try sanding the spots with fine sandpaper. If the stain
disappears, then coat the whole floor with Future. Sometimes, the
stain is caused by water trapped on top of the vinyl (as under the
bath mat), sometimes when the water is under the vinyl, but no
matter how it got there, removal is almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
