<HEADLINE>
MEN'S GROUPS TAKING A STAND AGAINST ABUSE, SEXUAL ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Mass. _ Waving signs (``Hands Are Not for Hitting,''
``Strong Men Don't Bully'') condemning domestic violence, a group
of men was marching down Main Street during last year's July Fourth
parade here when a woman caught Ted Hoague's attention.
</P>
<P>
   She was in her 70s, Hoague guessed, and a stranger to him,
although Hoague, one of the group's organizers, has lived and
worked in this community for decades. She stood well back in the
crowd, one face in a rolling sea of faces taking in a festive
holiday parade on a sunny summer morning.
</P>
<P>
   The woman stared at Hoague, her eyes locked on his. The whole
transaction lasted _ what? _ a couple of seconds, at most. Her
mouth opened as he and the other marchers passed by.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Thank you,(unitals) the woman said silently.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Thank you.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Hoague trembled as he walked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I talked to afterwards had experiences like that,''
Hoague recalls. ``Maybe the women didn't say anything because they
were standing beside a husband or boyfriend, but they made eye
contact. You could tell what they were feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoague, a 55-year-old carpenter and father of two, belongs to a
scattered but growing army of volunteers: men who are taking a
public stand against domestic violence and sexual assault and are
encouraging other men to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has quietly taken root from the North Shore to the
South Shore, from the streets of Gloucester to the State House and
beyond. Though often perceived as a ``women's issue,'' violence
against women and children _ and in some instances against men, too
_ affects everyone, Hoague and others in the movement say. And
while batterers and rapists are often forced by the criminal
justice system to face the consequences of their actions, these men
are in the fight because they want to be. As sons, brothers,
husbands, and fathers, they choose not to remain silent on the
issue, even at the risk of being ridiculed as ``unmanly'' for
speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are men everywhere waiting to do something,''
says William Greenbaum, a Gloucester art dealer who was the prime
catalyst behind last summer's march here. ``They just don't know
what's appropriate to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum in many ways epitomizes the initiative's grass-roots
nature. The son of a Russian immigrant, he is an ex-journalist with
a PhD from Harvard whose professional and social circles flow
across class, race, and gender boundaries. Five years ago, says
Greenbaum, a close woman friend who had been sexually abused as a
teenager began to experience severe post-trauma symptoms. At the
same time, another friend was opening the Cape Ann office of Help
for Abused Women and Their Children (HAWC), a Salem-based
organization that serves an estimated 11,000 clients annually.
Greenbaum wondered if there was some way he could help. Something
beyond a consoling arm around a shoulder or a check sent to a
worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``As men, we haven't really been doing anything,'' reflects
Greenbaum, a lanky, balding man with three grown daughters of his
own. ``There was a feeling that our silence had been condoning the
violence, that the culture reinforces that message. It's like drunk
driving was 20 years ago. Nobody said much about it then, but
attitudes have changed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum approached a handful of men he knew locally and asked
them, one on one, if they would be willing to march against
violence in the upcoming holiday parade. The men, mostly in their
40s and 50s, included Greenbaum's car mechanic and barber, several
fishermen, a local bar owner, and a power company lineman. His
strategy, which he has come to embrace with a near-religious
fervor, was to stay within the boundaries of Gloucester itself,
recruiting men well known to their neighbors. Just by virtue of
being there, Greenbaum reasoned, these men would make a powerful
statement to the larger community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mainly looking for men who'd had to make a choice in
their lives somewhere along the line _ about anger, about alcohol,
about their marriages, whatever,'' Greenbaum says. ``Some guys who
said they believed in the cause said they weren't ready to march,
and that was OK. Guys in the trades don't usually associate
themselves with this sort of action. It did take some courage to
risk being called a sissy or unmasculine.''
</P>
<P>
   Few mentioned to Greenbaum any direct connection to domestic
violence, such as having grown up with an abusive parent. Most
simply acknowledged that it was the right time and place to make
the statement. The holiday parade typically draws about 25,000
spectators to the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   On parade day, 86 men _ bankers, clergymen, and artists, too _
turned up to march. They called their ad hoc group Gloucester Men
Against Domestic Abuse and opted for a consciously funky, homegrown
look, marching with props that were in keeping with the event's
lighthearted atmosphere. A few hecklers took verbal shots at the
group, says Greenbaum, but not many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not being accusatory,'' notes Greenbaum, who through a
support group called Men for HAWC is helping similar efforts get
under way in Lynn and Danvers. He will also march in a Walk for
HAWC rally in Salem on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The display of giant papier-mache hands ``symbolized our
reaching out to other men,'' Greenbaum adds. ``The message was that
this mechanic, this plumber doesn't want to hear any of this sexist
stuff anymore. On the job or anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the marchers was Dennis Flavin, who owns the Halibut Point
restaurant here. Flavin, a self-described ``old hippie who believes
in nonviolence,'' had already begun to notice a change in the way
men talk about domestic violence cases.
</P>
<P>
   Around the bar in his restaurant, says Flavin, where men often
gather to watch sports, the conversation kept drifting to a number
of high-profile assault cases involving star athletes, including
ex-Red Sox Wilfredo Cordero and ex-Patriot Dave Meggett. These
cases, Flavin theorizes, caused men to talk with uncharacteristic
candor about what happens when a man loses control and lashes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it reaches what I'd call the normal person,'' says
Flavin, seated beside Greenbaum and Hoague during a recent luncheon
meeting. ``Guys may not want to talk to their friends about it, but
when something like this happens to their sports heroes, when a
football player'' _ Carolina Panthers receiver Rae Carruth _ ``gets
arrested for (allegedly) murdering his pregnant girlfriend, then
everyone talks about it. And the more conversation you get going,
the more people get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as the AIDS crisis forced men to talk about condom use more
frankly, adds Flavin, seeing athletes in handcuffs has had a
trickle-down effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you read about them, it's drugs or domestic
violence,'' says Flavin. ``For a lot of guys, the idea of men
hitting women or kids makes them sick.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
