<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-MEN-VIOLENCE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     04-27 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-VIOLENCE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 GLOUCESTER, Mass.: ... them sick.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another group of men sits around a conference table at the
Boston offices of the Massachusetts Coalition Against Sexual
Assault and Domestic Violence. The group was recruited over the
past few months by Jane Doe Inc. executive director Judith E.
Beals, and it includes, in addition to Greenbaum, a police officer,
a state legislator, a youth corps leader, and the board chairman of
a Cambridge, Mass. program for recovering batterers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To solve the problem,'' Beals says, ``you need boys and men
talking to other boys and men.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk this night drifts from the broadly political to the
intensely personal.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester police detective James Pierce mentions one ``horrific
incident'' in 1992, when a Winchester woman took out a restraining
order against her ex-boyfriend, a man named Ernest Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been an abusive relationship, but she thought she could
change him,'' recalls Pierce. ``Finally he smashed the windows of
her car. She was in my office that morning. We drew up a safety
plan. At 5 o'clock that afternoon, he put a gun to the mother's
head, executed the mother in her driveway, kidnapped the
ex-girlfriend, and took her to Florida, where he eventually killed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude was, things like that don't happen in
Winchester,'' Pierce continues. ``But that case proved it could
happen anywhere. And with something as horrific as that, you
couldn't help but be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Peter Koutoujian of Newton, a former
Middlesex County assistant district attorney who prosecuted
hundreds of abuse cases, tells the group he was somewhat taken
aback when he sent a letter to each male legislator late last year,
asking for his pledge to neither commit nor condone domestic
violence. The pledge is taken from the White Ribbon Campaign, an
antiviolence initiative that began in Canada nearly a decade ago
and has since spread worldwide. So far only 40 legislators have
committed their signatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be immediately embraced,'' says Koutoujian.
``But even close friends who cared about their families razzed me
about it. They said this was political correctness, a women's
issue. It's not. It's really a public health issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men may say it's jumping ship to oppose violence, but I'm a
father, too,'' adds Craig Norberg-Bohm, board chairman of Emerge, a
program for batterers. ``Being perceived in our work as hating men
is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 12 years old, Norberg-Bohm says, he was sexually
assaulted by an older man whom he had admired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awful start to my sexual history,'' he says, ``so
this is a good place to start for men like me. My closest friend
was also sexually assaulted. A woman in my apartment building was
raped. It's on our street, it's among our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Amir Femi, another group member, agrees. Femi, 41, grew up in
Dorchester and Roxbury, raised mostly by his mother and a
stepfather who struggled with violent tendencies of his own. Femi
not only witnessed the effect of abuse on his mother but also saw
its more crippling impact on the households and lives of his
childhood friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the whole cycle laid out,'' recalls Femi, who runs a
City Year program focused on educating schoolchildren about
domestic violence. ``The belittling, the economic control, the
verbal threats, the physical assault. I saw guns, knives, even an
ax come out on one occasion. I witnessed one bloody knife fight
between two men over my mother. It didn't take much to see how
destructive it was, to the women, the children, even the men
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For the women Femi knew growing up, the physical and emotional
battery ``made their worlds smaller and smaller. Could they have
friends? And if so, which ones? What could they talk about? Some of
these women lived like shut-ins. They would doubt themselves, or
feel the violence was their fault, like they somehow deserved it.
It made me wonder how could they negotiate in life when they felt
so demoralized.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more insidious, Femi adds, is the effect violence and abuse
have on the men involved, including himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part that's generally overlooked,'' he says. ``I
mean, we all struggle with this distorted view of what it means to
be a man. With what's appropriate in a relationship with someone
who's smaller and weaker than you are. The suppressor role is well
learned. We all have it, including myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Femi harbored a fear of getting married and having
children, a fear that one day, despite his best intentions, he
would resort to violence against the people he most loved. That
fear haunted his relationships with women, he says, until one day
in his mid-20s when he was talking to a woman friend on the phone
and the thought floated into his head, (itals)I'm a monster. A
no-good monster.(unitals) Femi began to sob. And then, he says, a
revelation came to him.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)I will never do that,(unitals) he thought to himself.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)I don't have to do that.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Femi got married. He and his wife hope to start
a family someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that my peer group will be the end of the line for
this family violence stuff,'' Femi murmurs. ``My father, the
stepfather who's been in my life for 31 years, he's wrestled with
it. He grew up with violence in his home. I don't see anyone's life
improved one micron by it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
