<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSENT AT YOUR PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my favorite young women was in the thick of the battle
against the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie's one of those people who stick out in a crowd. I've known
her since her parents began bringing her to our
Unitarian-Universalist church as a child, and I always thought she
was just about everything you'd ever want in a daughter: outspoken
yet constructive, independent yet cooperative, friendly, kind, and
thoughtful. There's a special light in Sadie's eyes that expresses
her undampened curiosity, and she still has an idealistic streak
that most kids have crushed out of them by the time they get to
college. Sadie spent her teen years feeding the homeless, acting in
school plays, and studying hard enough to rank at the top of her
class. Our whole church was delighted when she got into Wesleyan.
</P>
<P>
   I knew she'd gone to Washington because she wrote a letter that
was printed in our church newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over this semester,'' Sadie wrote, ``I have learned bits and
pieces about world economic inequality and globalization. My
roommate Jess was organizing a group to go to D.C. for a protest,
and I went to a Road Show with street performers who are trying to
spread the message about why we should protest against what the IMF
and World Bank are doing. I went more in support of Jess than
because I knew a lot about the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that exactly the way your four years at college unfolded?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Show covered the environment, human rights,
sweatshops, capital globalization, the damage of high interest
rates to struggling third-world countries, and the real effects of
the IMF and World Bank. I learned not one country has had their
poverty level decrease. The atmosphere was full of energy and hope
for change and I realized that this was something I wanted to be
part of. I've signed petitions and been to student rallies on
campus, but I've never done anything like this before. There will
be thousands of people there, and cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't it amaze you that year after year, young people have
hope for a better future? Doesn't it warm your heart that a new
generation can still be inspired to work on behalf of those less
fortunate than themselves? Because they believe they have a
responsibility to improve the world, Sadie and about 150 other
Wesleyan students crowded into dormitories at American University
and joined affinity groups to form human blockades, to document
what was happening, to call lawyers and parents if necessary, and,
above all, to keep one another safe.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie signed up to be part of a blockade that would move if so
directed by the police. She reassured us all that this was not a
``directly arrestable action,'' but she was wrong. The police
surrounded and then arrested 600 students who were doing nothing
more provocative than walking peacefully along a sidewalk. The
police also shut down the group's headquarters as a ``fire hazard''
so that the internal discipline the protesters were counting on to
show the world their seriousness of purpose would be disrupted.
Clearly, the police were attempting to discredit the demonstration
by provoking confusion and violence. This is hard for mothers to
accept. After all, we're the ones who taught our kids that the
police were good guys who protected citizens who'd done nothing
wrong. Now they're learning that the police are there to protect
the status quo and are willing to bend the rules to do so. We
raised our kids to believe dissent was a precious aspect of
democracy, cherished by all. Now they're finding out that the
highest priority of people in power is to hold on to it, despite
paying lip service to the democratic process. Having ripped away
the veneer of a free society, they now see that capitalism is
indifferent to everything but its own advancement.
</P>
<P>
   This painful disillusionment is what radicalized us in the '60s.
Repeating our experience, Sadie and her friends must now rethink
whether a government subservient to corporate interests is worthy
of their trust. When those who want to improve the system are
labeled troublemakers and those who look out solely for their own
interests are admired, we turn idealistic people like Sadie into
cynics and end up with a generation whose loftiest goal is its own
affluence.
</P>
<P>
   We can't let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie ended her letter, ``I'm excited about going and am glad to
have so much support from those I care about and who care about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Include me on your list. Sadie. You go, girl!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
