<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-YEMEN-BOS &LR;      04-27 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-YEMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAND WHERE REALITY AND MIRAGE MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
YEMEN 
The Unknown Arabia 
By Tim Mackintosh-Smith 
Overlook, 280 pp., $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yemen, a small poor country at the lonely tip of the Arabian
peninsula, is one of those places that seem to exist in a dimension
all their own _ in sight of the modern world, yet somehow removed
from it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a country where landcapes are either overwhelmingly lush or
terrifyingly barren, where cities seem to be baked out of
gingerbread rather than built of bricks, and where rigid codes of
hospitality and social conduct coexist with official brutality and
tolerated lawlessness. (Tourists are frequently kidnapped by
tribesmen.) The Middle Ages can seem like the day before yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might willingly pay to avoid a prolonged stay in
Yemen, but Tim Mackintosh-Smith _ an engagingly eccentric and
erudite Briton _ could hardly wait to get there. Armchair travelers
have reason to be grateful.
</P>
<P>
   It began when he studied Arabic at Oxford and became hooked on a
language in which a word usually meant ``itself, the opposite and
some kind of camel.'' He began fantasizing about what he calls
``Dictionary Land,'' a surreal lexical kingdom in which a puppy is
also a demon and a rotten walnut also an uncircumcised person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exotic beckoned,'' Mackintosh-Smith decided. When he told
an Oxford professor that he was considering a trip to Yemen and was
urged to go ``somewhere respectable'' instead, his choice was
clear. That was 1982, and Mackintosh-Smith has lived in Yemen ever
since. He is now so thoroughly assimilated that he regularly chews
qat, the mildly stimulating green leaf that in strictly Muslim
Yemen replaces alcohol as a social icebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a beguiling hybrid, a combination memoir, guide,
history, and love letter to his adopted homeland and its prickly
but poetic people. Love, of course, is a state of mind: Even
getting caught in a civil war in 1994 couldn't diminish
Mackintosh-Smith's enthusiasm for Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   With British understatement, he describes the country's history
as ``complex.'' It's certainly long: San'a, the capital and chief
city, claims it was founded after the biblical flood by Noah's son
Shem. Given Yemen's stormy past, it's a miracle that sprawling
San'a still exists. As recently as 1948, an army of 250,000
tribesmen descended on the city after a military coup and, like the
Visigoths sacking Rome, spent a week looting it. ``They vandalized
and plundered, taking anything moveable,'' Mackintosh-Smith writes,
adding that ``some of the plunderers were themselves plundered by
late comers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he writes wonderfully lucid prose, it is sometimes hard
to keep track of which century, bloody uprising, or ruthless and/or
peculiar leader (they come in both monarchist and Marxist
varieties) Mackintosh-Smith is describing.
</P>
<P>
   The most lyrical parts of the book are accounts of the author's
travels around Yemen, journeys that took him into the country's
interior, its multilayered past, and its unique national psyche.
His descriptions are vivid and insightful when he's introducing us
to places like Marib, where the remains of a massive dam built in
the eighth century BCE still stand (according to legend a rat
gnawed a hole in it, causing both dam and the kingdom it irrigated
to collapse); Shibam, the Manhattan of the desert, where hundreds
of tightly packed mud-brick towers rise abruptly out of a flat
plain; and Tarim, ``the Venice of Sand,'' where the grand palaces
of vanished merchant princes are slowly sinking into the desert.
</P>
<P>
   In the great stiff-upper-lip tradition of travel writing,
Mackintosh-Smith maintains a cheery, mustn't-grumble tone while
describing arduous and sometimes dangerous expeditions by foot,
donkey, rattletrap truck, and leaky wooden sailboats of the sort
Sinbad the sailor captained. On one particularly harrowing hike he
had to be on the lookout for both scorpions and the local tahish, a
monster ``the size of a cow, but it's got a head like a hyena's,
with a wide jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time you get to the final pages, an affectionate portrait
of his San'a neighborhood, the reasons that Yemen remains
relatively unknown are clear _ and so are the attractions that hold
the author there. Not many of his readers are likely to follow
Mackintosh-Smith's example and set off for Dictionary Land, but we
should all be glad that he did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
