<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUDGE LEAVES PLENTY OF DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To judge from his performance under cross-examination, Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. is in a tight spot.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to say that he didn't quite tell the truth six years
ago, before his most famous patient died, but that he's telling the
truth now. He knew when he made his memorable declaration that
Celtics captain Reggie Lewis had a ``normal athlete's heart'' his
diagnosis might be wrong, but he said it anyway. But he is
definitely telling the whole truth now when he says the Lewises
were well aware that the verdict on his ailment was not clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   Of course that is not how the eminent cardiologist put it. In
explaining the hugely divergent views doctors had formed of Lewis's
condition, he said there was a ``differential diagnosis'' between
the original Dream Team of doctors who treated Lewis at New England
Baptist Hospital and his own judgment that Lewis could eventually
resume his playing career.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he and the Lewises had agreed on the spin of the
memorable press conference in which he insisted that Lewis's
condition was benign. He said they had agreed it would be best not
to reveal any detailed medical information, which apparently
extended to the detail that he was not sure his diagnosis was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was originally diagnosed as having a life-threatening
arrhythmia, but Mudge, at least publicly, declared that he suffered
from a far less serious condition that he could live with, and
probably play with.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge reiterated on the stand Wednesday that Lewis confided in
him 15 days before he died that he had used cocaine. He added that
he had never given Lewis permission to play basketball or to
heavily exert himself. Yet that account seemed at odds with his
other statements about Lewis's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours before Lewis died, Mudge told the Globe's
Will McDonough in an interview that Lewis was doing the things an
athlete normally does to prepare for a basketball season and that
there would likely be an escalation of those activities in the
``next two weeks.'' But he claimed on the stand he didn't mean that
Lewis was to go anywhere near a basketball. He said he had signed
off on tai chi, stretching, and lifting five-pound weights. That is
hardly the regimen an NBA player follows to prepare for a season.
But Mudge explained that his comments to McDonough were just part
of the plan, which was to answer questions vaguely and put the best
public face on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those statements were entirely consistent with what I said to
other sportswriters,'' Mudge testified. But they were not
consistent with his own insistence on the stand that he had ordered
Lewis not to exert himself.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most damaging, Mudge admitted that he did not directly
tell Lewis he had a potentially life-threatening condition when he
left the hospital. He said Lewis knew doctors were trying to
reconcile different opinions _ and, indeed, the Lewises did
eventually travel to California, where Reggie Lewis was examined by
four other doctors, one of whom said he should immediately retire.
Still, it seems reasonable to conclude that Mudge could have left
his patient more comfortable than he should have been, through both
his public and private reassurances.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means Mudge will lose, of course. It is easy in
retrospect to say that a doctor whose patient died did not get
proper care. That isn't necessarily true, and it's far below the
standard Harris-Lewis's attorneys must reach to prove malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lewis II feels like less of a can't-lose proposition for
Mudge than its predecessor. The doctor didn't help himself in the
course of his testy sparring with Neil Rossman, Harris-Lewis's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't recall some statements he made in depositions, or in
the previous trial. He didn't recall what he said to McDonough,
although he took no issue with the account of the conversation the
Globe published. At times he said he didn't remember exactly what
he said to Reggie and Donna, or what they said to him. He
remembered every detail of the conversation with no witnesses,
though, the conversation about cocaine use that he now says
thwarted his ability to properly diagnose Reggie's condition.
</P>
<P>
   The best doctors in the world lose patients. But it is hard to
square the cocksure Mudge of the press conference six years ago
with the witness taking refuge in talk about divergent diagnoses.
On one point, at least, there is no divergence at all. A man who
seemed to be in the prime of life fell suddenly ill, and the most
celebrated medical care in town failed to save him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker'se-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
