<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-NEW-CLUB-BOS &LR;      04-27 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEW-CLUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE E-CLUB TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Bamberger never doubted his concept, not for one minute.
But try moving a concept _ even a well-developed one _ through a
maze as daunting as the golf equipment industry, where open arms
and welcome mats are hardly part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   So in his hands Bamberger held his idea, a golf club that he
wasn't promoting as revolutionary but merely as a new tool that
could help tens of thousands _ perhaps millions _ of players. He
called it the E-club _ part 3-wood, part putter _ and if Tiger
Woods, the world's greatest player, could bump delicate little
shots around the green with his fairway metal, Bamberger was sure
the average golfer could find a way to use it.
</P>
<P>
   On these finesse shots around the green, the E-club is easier to
control than a fairway metal, for what Bamberger has done is give
you a putter with the head of a 3-wood on a 35-inch shaft (as
opposed to 44- and 45-inch shafts). With 19-degree loft, the club
has a weighted, sole plate to easily lift the ball off of fringe or
out of light rough, and the 72-degree lie allows you a closer
stance and gets your eyes over the ball as you do when you putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the tradition of a utility club,'' said Bamberger,
whose fascination with the concept goes back to the early 1990s,
when he pursued a dream and headed to Europe to explore the soul of
golf. He absorbed its essence, visited its roots, and spent weeks
upon weeks as a caddie on the European Tour, much of the time for
Duxbury native Peter Teravainen.
</P>
<P>
   His experience produced ``To the Linksland,'' a superb book that
captured the game's spirit. But it also planted the seeds for the
E-club as Bamberger vividly remembered watching players negotiate
fragile little shots around the greens on courses where it was best
to keep the ball on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen Day (who now is on the American PGA Tour) is the one I
remember,'' said Bamberger. ``He would chip with a Ping 3-wood, and
I was intrigued by how he would play that shot. I'd try it, but you
stood so far away (because of the long shaft to a 3-wood) that it
was easy to ground your club. I preferred my putter for my recovery
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he eventually reasoned, why not a combination 3-wood and
putter? ``It just took a lot less skill to hit the E-club'' than
try and finesse a Woods-like 3-wood from around the green.
</P>
<P>
   The concept having been planted, all Bamberger had to do was
come up with the design, get a patent, receive USGA approval, find
financial backing, and sell it to the public. He laughs, for
shooting 62 in the final round of a US Open would perhaps be easier
than the route he has traveled with the E-club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nowhere that simple,'' he said. But the setbacks _ such
as the marquee PGA Tour name set to lend credibility to the club
until his equipment company squashed the deal _ have given way to
success: Bamberger's E-club is on the market, and in just five
weeks, 10,000 of them have been purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' said Bamberger, who readily concedes that not
everything went against him. There is the matter of meeting
Weston's Tim Neher, who eventually backed the E-club with about
$400,000 to help produce a 30-minute infomercial _ starring Nick
Price, no less _ that moved the product into public view.
</P>
<P>
   That Bamberger, a veteran golf writer with Sports Illustrated,
would form a partnership with Neher, a hugely successful executive
from the cable television industry, is a twist to the story that
makes both of them chuckle. They had never met, but they had a
mutual friend _ Brian Roberts, the CEO of Comcast, which owns two
pro teams in Philadelphia (76ers, Flyers), where Bamberger lives.
</P>
<P>
   Neher, for 25 years the president of Continental Cablevision
before it was sold to MediaOne, had a guiding hand in the birth of
The Golf Channel along with Arnold Palmer and cable TV mogul Joe
Gibbs. Through business he became friendly with Roberts, who one
day called on behalf of his friend, Bamberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me the story,'' said Neher, ``that he had this friend
who had designed a golf club, but didn't know where to go with it.
Would I help him? I told him I wasn't sure I knew what to do
either, so why was he calling me?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I enjoy the game and have always had a hand in golf, but
I had no interest in golf equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't say no to Roberts, so the E-club was mailed to
his home in Weston, Mass. ``I didn't necessarily buy into the club
right away,'' said Neher, ``but I knew that Michael had done a lot
of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bamberger had already secured a patent and received
affirmation from the USGA that it conformed to its rules. He had
also been turned down by some big equipment makers, but then again,
those equipment makers didn't have Tory Neher testing their club.
</P>
<P>
   Tory is Neher's 25-year-old daughter, a 20-handicap who has
played the game for more than 10 years. When Neher decided to test
the E-club, he handed it to Tory. ``She said to me, `You, of all
people, to give me this club,' '' said Neher, laughing. True, he
wasn't one for gimmicks, but what happened next was not done with
mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first hole at Weston (Golf Club), the pin was stuck back
right of the green. She was off the green and knocked it in,'' said
Neher, who turned to his wife, Molly, and said, ``It was lucky, but
it tells me something.''
</P>
<P>
   It told him that he should meet Bamberger, who flew to Boston
and sat down with Neher. ``I was so intrigued, so charmed by
Michael,'' said Neher.
</P>
<P>
   They formed Bantam Golf and had some immediate pipelines _
Q-Direct, which is a division of Comcast, would sell the club, and
Neher guided the project toward a California infomercial company
called Script to Screen. In recent weeks, deals have been signed
with Carbite Golf and chipshot.com, a popular Web site for on-line
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael gets all the credit,'' said Neher. ``My involvement
after the business side of it was I thought it would be fun to do
for two primary reasons. I would learn about informercials, which
is a new phenomenon; and I think it's a club of enormous help. The
club is so unique in a lot of different respects.''
</P>
<P>
   The response, said Bamberger, has been positive. At first,
people thought he was re-inventing the old chipper, but ``you can
hit this club out of bunkers without lips, from underneath trees,
for long bump-and-runs. It's not a chipper.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's the E-club. And why the E-club?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can hit it from everywhere,'' said Bamberger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
