<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT SPARS WITH LEWIS OVER CHOICE OF GLOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fight isn't for three more days, but the
hand-to-hand combat has already begun.
</P>
<P>
   Undisputed heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis is set to fight
Michael Grant Saturday night at Madison Square Garden in a battle
that has been dubbed ``Two Big'' because Lewis stands nearly 6 feet
6 inches and weighs approximately 250 pounds while Grant stands 6-7
and weighs about the same. Too Big, as things have turned out, has
become a problem because Wednesday Grant insisted his left hand was
too big to fit into the gloves the champion has demanded he wear.
</P>
<P>
   As champion, Lewis has the right to dictate what brand of
mashing mitts the fighters wear. He has opted for Reyes gloves, a
Mexican-made product known to do serious damage if properly used.
But Grant has always worn Grant gloves, a brand made by Elvis
Phillips. Reyes gloves, in the vernacular of the sport, are
considered punchers gloves. The bulk of their 10 ounces of padding
is around the wrist, while the business portion (the knuckles) are
tightly formed around the fist, which allows a power puncher to do
more damage because there is less padding between his knuckles and
his opponent's bridge work.
</P>
<P>
   That the gloves will weigh the same would seem to make this a
bit of a moot point when you are throwing your hands around with
250 pounds of fury behind them, but Grant insisted he had a more
direct problem. He insisted that if Johnnie Cochran were pressing
his case, he would have to tell Lewis and the New York State
Athletic Commission, ``If the gloves don't fit, you must outfit my
man with something else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, according to Grant, his left hand does not fit
inside a Reyes glove, a situation he described as ``a health
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My right hand fits fine,'' Grant said. ``I admit that. But I
can't make a proper fist with my left hand. I can't make a fist at
all. And if you can't make a fist, that's a broken hand right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant claims to have tried on 16 pairs of Reyes gloves, all with
the same result. Although he said he would continue to try to find
a pair that fits, he added, ``If you sit me and Lennox down and I
say, `If you couldn't make a fist, would you fight?' I'm sure he'd
say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a discussion of the issue during a press
conference Wednesday at the Garden, Lewis suddenly stood up and put
his large left hand into the air, palm stretched wide. He hovered
over Grant for several minutes as more than 100 reporters watched
to see what would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Grant got up and put his left palm to Lewis's.
``Same size!'' Lewis scoffed before sitting down, a grin on his
face. ``Michael says they don't fit his hand, but I find that very
hard to believe. He doesn't have bigger hands than I have. He
better stop his noise. He's just saying that because he doesn't
want to wear Reyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this is a psychological ploy by Grant or the beginning
of a psychological meltdown will remain unknown until the opening
bell. But one thing is sure: Reyes gloves or no Reyes gloves, Grant
will fight Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has 4 million reasons to do this. He will surely be
reminded of that by his manager, Craig Hamilton, who negotiated the
purse in US dollars. To get it, he would fight wearing Isotoner
gloves if he had to, a fact Hamilton half acknowledged even as he
tried to defend his man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commission has asked us to wear conforming gloves,''
Hamilton said. ``Lennox Lewis is the champion so he picks the
gloves. Lennox says his hand is bigger than Michael's. Well, he's
the only one who will get an up-close-and-personal view of how big
that hand is and how powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, his guy's gonna fight. The question is, will he
fight with confidence or has his mental breakdown already begun
over a nonissue like this?
</P>
<P>
   Grant appeared tight Wednesday when asked to speak in front of
Lewis. He spoke haltingly of how he was destined to win and that
the skeptics picking Lewis would ``see the truth and the light.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, Lewis said, ``Michael sounded a bit upset there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he did, and not about the brand of gloves he'd be
wearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
