<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     04-27 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARRA'S DREAMS ARE UNDERSTOOD IN ANY LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He left West Africa three years ago, arriving at New York's JFK
Airport with bloodshot eyes, a single piece of luggage, and no
comprehension of English.
</P>
<P>
   Modibo Diarra was easy for his basketball coach, John Kelly, to
recognize. He was the 6-foot-10-inch kid with the brilliant smile.
And he was smiling on that autumn day in New York, even though a
severe case of malaria had him close to death.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a sad story about an athlete who lost his way.
Far from it. Diarra is one of the most intriguing young people I
have ever met. Maybe I'm breaking the rules by saying this, but
I've quietly rooted for him since 1998 when I interviewed him at
Notre Dame Academy in Fitchburg. After you realize what he's done
in three years, you'll want to root for him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Diarra couldn't articulate his plan _ in English _ when he came
to the United States, but he knew what he wanted. He would go to
prep school, educate himself in college, and then move on to the
NBA so he could make money for his family. He is one of 14
children. He is from historic Mali, the land that introduced the
world to Timbuktu and Songhai kings. He believes that all children
should submit to their parents and negate the self. ``He's told me
so much about his family and his culture,'' Kelly said Wednesday.
``He's an extraordinary person. I don't think I'll appreciate him
fully until he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Diarra will be gone in the fall. He will play for John Calipari
at the University of Memphis. Calipari said he expects the center
to play immediately. He'll be eligible because he surpassed the
minimum SAT standard (820) required to participate. He wants to
major in a field that allows him to work with computers.
</P>
<P>
   None of this seemed probable a few months ago. Some major
schools shied away from Diarra because they didn't think he would
be able to pass the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bright kid,'' Calipari said. ``You have to understand
that English is his third language. I told him that one of our
goals, before he leaves here, is to make English his second
language (he also speaks French and a native language).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great person. I asked him about his family and he told
me about his brothers and sisters. Then he wrote down all their
names and ages. Just like that. How about that?''
</P>
<P>
   If you meet Diarra, you will notice that he is teeming with joy.
Because of his constant smile, he was given the nickname ``Good
Man.'' He made friends quickly at Notre Dame, a school with fewer
than 100 students. His intelligence and sense of humor were
obvious. Really, how could a guy with a smile like that not have a
sense of humor?
</P>
<P>
   He also knows how to work. When he arrived at JFK in '97, all he
could do was nod. A couple months later, the only English word he
knew was ``yes.'' When I interviewed him late in '98, he insisted
on struggling through the session without interpreters. He did a
terrific job for 20 minutes. When I showed him a map of Mali, he
took the printout and schooled me on the land's languages and
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasized that, yes, it was about the money. For his
parents. Diarra may have picked up some of the habits of American
teenagers _ such as playing video games and listening to hip-hop _
but he was not interested in following the parent-child
relationships in the United States. In his mind, there is no such
thing as his job and his income. It's more like his job and their
income. ``He's selfless,'' Kelly said. ``His idea of a good life is
being religious, sharing, taking care of his parents, and never
saying a bad word about anybody. He's not a complainer.''
</P>
<P>
   In late '98, his English comprehension had improved enough for
him to use American slang, but he was still reading English at a
grade-school level. Bill Barton, his coach last season, tutored him
in English for four classes. Craig DeLisle and Jeff Hammond tutored
him in math. Last summer, Diarra went to Philadelphia and
participated in a two-week English as a Second Language program. As
he became more comfortable with his words, his game got better as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me that he didn't have an offensive game,''
Calipari said. ``They're full of it. He has a jump hook. He's
strong. He can drop step. He can make a shot from 10 to 15 feet. He
has more skills than some people believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Diarra should be an immediate shot-blocking and rebounding
threat at Memphis. He is quicker than most big men and has superior
jumping ability.
</P>
<P>
   I think he will be a good player. I also think he will play in
the NBA. But that's not why I root for him.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when people talk about kids focusing on the NBA, there
seems to be dismay and condescension at the thought; Diarra takes
the taint away from that discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there are days when you hope that anarchists dismantle
the NCAA; Diarra takes the taint away from the organization, too,
reminding you of how significant it is for some athletes to get a
college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there are depressing lectures on what people _ young,
old, African or American _ cannot do; Diarra makes that chatter
irrelevant, too. That's why, earlier this week, Notre Dame retired
his No. 44 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We retired it because of his character,'' Barton said. ``I
talked to the headmaster about it. This is for the way _ the
nonbasketball way _ he pulled the whole community together. People
love him here, all around town.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night his jersey was retired, Diarra stood at a podium
and thanked about 20 people. There were tears as he spoke. His
English was coherent, although there were still snags in his verb
tenses. But he still read a speech, which he wrote by himself. He
wrote it in English.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
