u f BC-NETGENESIS-SHAKEOUT-B     04-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETGENESIS-SHAKEOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETGENESIS TELLS RETAILERS WHERE THE SHOPPING IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives at SmarterKids.com were tickled by the sudden deluge
of customer traffic generated by their product search box on
Microsoft's Encarta reference site last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Just as suddenly, the back-patting ended. Using
customer-tracking software from NetGenesis Corp., the online
education store discovered that many of the people clicking into
the online education store were immediately clicking off.
</P>
<P>
   NetGenesis analysis revealed that users believed the search
button belonged to Encarta. And in their confusion, they were
asking SmarterKids.com about Anaconda snakes and Uruguay rather
than its Monopoly games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seemed good on the surface was not all that great,'' said
Al Noyes, executive vice president of SmarterKids.com Inc. ``We
redesigned everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Noyes said his company would have had a hard time spotting the
glitch without NetGenesis, a developer of sophisticated software
that has helped revolutionize the way companies run their
electronic businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants such as barnesandnoble.com (bn.com) and the Gap Inc.
use NetGenesis software to figure out why online shoppers avoid
certain aisles and balk at check-out counters. The information has
helped them fine-tune marketing campaigns, convert browsers into
buyers and offer more personalized content.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a revelation that NetGenesis executives have made:
Developing a groundbreaking technology doesn't necessarily lead to
market stardom. The company now needs to get big fast through
acquisitions and alliances, analysts said. And it has to prove it
has a product that will enable it to grow even as investors grow
impatient with money-losing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Any grand expansion plans may have to be shelved, however.
Technology stocks have cooled in recent weeks, and NetGenesis'
escent on the Nasdaq Stock Market has been particularly drastic.
The company's shares more than tripled to $56.8125 on its first day
of trading in February. Wednesday, NetGenesis stock closed at
$15.125 a share, up $1.25 for the day but still below its $18
offering price two months ago. NetGenesis announces its
first-quarter earnings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started in 1994, when two MIT students, Matt
Cutler and Eric Richard, discovered they could do fun things with
the Web. Through their start-up firm, then called net.Genesis, they
began building software that followed customers as they clicked
through Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   But signing up clients was more difficult than the founders had
anticipated. NetGenesis, they discovered, had zoomed so far ahead
of the curve that most businesses had not yet recognized the
importance of analyzing activity on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if the whole market hadn't built stores yet,'' said
Cutler, now the firm's chief e-business intelligence officer.
``They're looking for someone to build shelves to hold merchandise.
They were saying, `That's interesting, guys. But we need cash
registers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The founders grew frustrated with their attempts to grow the
business. ``We had sort of plateaued,'' Cutler said. ``Our head
count was flat and our sales were flat. High-tech companies need to
be growing like gangbusters. . . . At the time, it seemed like it
was harder than it should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep the business alive, NetGenesis' founders realized they
needed to attract more capital and a sophisticated chief executive
officer. They lured Charles River Ventures, a Waltham, Mass.
venture capital firm, and then Larry Bohn, an executive who was
experienced in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the company in 1998, Bohn opted for rapid change.
The new chief executive expanded the company's services, and raised
prices. Previously, the company was charging less than $10,000 for
its software. Now, the average price is more than $100,000, but the
package includes an array of analytical and consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   He also took the dot out of net.Genesis, concluding it wasn't
such a cute name, after all. Search engines, particularly those on
financial information and news sites, have had trouble recognizing
the company's dotted name.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bohn, sales at NetGenesis more than quadrupled to $6.5
million last year, though its losses ballooned to $17.9 million. In
February, he helped take NetGenesis public, raising $76.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But NetGenesis faces new challenges. Rivals such as Accrue
Software Inc., WebTrends Corp. and Macromedia Inc. have deeper
pockets. Each is racing to get bigger by gobbling up software firms
and joining forces with giant service providers that help
businesses build Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better mousetrap might not always win,'' said Rob DeSisto,
an analyst with the Gartner Group. ``You either need to acquire or
really deepen your ties.''
</P>
<P>
   NetGenesis has heeded that advice. It has been cozying up to
IBM, Proxicom Inc. and other large providers of software and
consulting services. The agreements will give NetGenesis access to
the companies' extensive client lists.
</P>
<P>
   But with Internet stocks falling back to earth, technology
companies are increasingly tabling more aggressive expansion plans.
NetGenesis, for instance, will now grow ``more organically,'' Bohn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market for NetGenesis' products is clearly growing.
The growth in online business-to-business trade has a steady line
of new clients knocking on NetGenesis' doors. The company now
counts Bell Atlantic Corp., General Electric Co.'s aircraft-engine
division and Akamai Technologies Inc. as customers.
</P>
<P>
   Often, companies say they were flying in the dark until they
began tracking their customers. Then, they uncovered all sorts of
snags: dead ends built into sites, hidden check-out buttons and
confusing storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a classic one,'' Bohn said. ``A retailer of consumer
goods complained that the average (customer) stay was one page. You
look at the site and say, `I understand why. Your site stinks.'''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the merchant said he visited the site all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' said Bohn, snorting with laughter as he
recalled the conversation. ``Because no one else does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
