<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALL IN THE CUBICLE COPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to the dilemma of limited San
Francisco real estate and the crushing demand for dot-com
commercial space, there are plenty of valid points for debate.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is NOT whether dot-com working areas constitute
``offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad no one has been able to convey this truth to the dot-com
cheerleaders. Just as they argue that Internet goods and services
providers should not have to pay sales taxes the way
bricks-and-mortar companies do, they contend they should be exempt
from many of the planning and zoning rules everyone else must
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Well, because dot-coms are special. They sell stuff in
cyberspace, you see. They are cutting edge. Revolutionary. The
future.
</P>
<P>
   As for adherence to Proposition M, San Francisco's 14-year-old
law limiting office space development _ why, that's like using an
apple limit for oranges, they say. Old-fashioned businesses have
offices; dot-coms have, um, WORK SPACES, and oughtn't to be subject
to the city's development cap.
</P>
<P>
   This almost-touching arrogance surfaced repeatedly during a
recent hot hour on Michael Krasny's excellent ``Forum'' on KQED-FM
here.
</P>
<P>
   The topic was dot-com needs vs. city planning laws.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner were neighborhood activist David Maltz and
longtime slow-growth advocate Calvin Welch, of the Council of
Community Housing Organizations. In the other corner was former San
Francisco Supervisor Jim Gonzalez, now the executive director of a
powerful dot-com lobbying group called Information Technology
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle (sort of) was Supervisor Leslie Katz, who has been
promising for awhile now some curative legislation for the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   (Naturally, though invited, no one from the actual Planning
Commission showed up.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides arguing that dot-coms are an unappreciated economic
godsend to San Francisco, Gonzalez (and several callers to the
program) reasoned that the companies' unique nature distinguishes
them from traditional businesses.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do to see that dot-commers don't work in mere
offices, said Gonzalez, is just walk through any new Internet
commerce company's space and look around.
</P>
<P>
   What Gonzalez then described _ partitioned cubicles instead of
rows of desks, common conference areas instead of walled-off
meeting rooms, lots of open, common space and computers _ sounded
exactly like thousands of other regular old offices in this town.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Welch (as usual) had come armed with the letter of
the law. He read the official, legal definition of ``office space''
from the City Planning Code, or Master Plan. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ```Office space' shall mean space within a structure intended or
primarily suitable for occupancy by persons or entities which
perform for their own benefit, or provide to others, services at
that location, including, but not limited to, professional,
banking, insurance, management, consulting, technical, sales and
design, or the office function of manufacturing and warehousing
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, with Proposition M, the voters of San Francisco chose
to limit development of the above-described space to 950,000 square
feet each year.
</P>
<P>
   Until the voters choose to repeal that law, everybody who works
in any room, complex, suite or converted barn that matches the
definition should have to obey the law. No matter how much revenue
nor how many jobs they supposedly generate.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can we get on with the legitimate issues around dot-com
development and see if we can mitigate this mess before the whole
city's wrecked and we're all irrevocably at each other's throats?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
