<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-RACE-HNS &LR;      04-27 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DOWNSIDE OF DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The liberal argument that bias is senseless
because we're all the same under the skin always struck me as a
weak rebuttal to the Klansmen and Nazis of the world, who thrive on
our manifest differences.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out the liberals weren't lily-livered apologists
for racial and ethnic peculiarities after all. They were correct.
Genetically, we are the same under the skin _ so much so,
scientists now tell us, that a concept as fundamental as ``race''
may be meaningless. The bushman in the Kalahari Desert of Namibia,
in other words, is the brother of the white Anglo-Saxon Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it? Well, the fact is many experts think we're all
descended from a few small bands of Homo sapiens who first arose in
Africa about 100,000 years ago and began to go exploring, in groups
of up to 100 individuals, some 50 millennia later. These people
looked just like us because they are us.
</P>
<P>
   The chief proponent of this theory is Stanford University
population geneticist Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza, whose name is
almost as big as his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   A near-octogenarian who divides his time between Palo Alto,
Calif., and Milan, Italy, Cavalli-Sforza is the author of the newly
published ``Genes, People, and Languages'' (North Point
Press/Farrar, Straus and Giroux).
</P>
<P>
   The book is a succinct recapitulation of a controversial theory
he has been propounding for half a century, most of it spent at a
Stanford lab where his staff has been looking at DNA samples from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cavalli-Sforza, there are indeed molecular
differences, but they are few and far between and often due to what
are known as ``founder effects.''
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of the gene that predisposes some Ashkenazi Jewish
women to breast cancer, for example, results from a natural
reduction in the original population _ due to famine? flood?
disease? _ that accidentally spared women with the bad gene,
creating a kind of bottleneck. The remaining population was the
only genetic game in town.
</P>
<P>
   But once you get back out to the surface of the organism, you
find that differences (skin color, size and the like) are only
adaptations to the local material conditions of our existence and
to accidents of geographic and climatological history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is because they are external that these racial differences
strike us so forcibly,'' Cavalli-Sforza has written, ``and we
automatically assume that differences of similar magnitude exist
below the surface, in the rest of our genetic makeup. This is
simply not so: the remainder of our genetic makeup hardly differs
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from his home in Milan last week,
Cavalli-Sforza expanded on this, drawing from his own experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I settled in the States when I was 49 years old and I now have
great problems recognizing Italian-Americans,'' he said.
``Sometimes I can recognize one for some superficial behavior, but
it is extremely rare. There are differences of social origin, but
in the long run, they disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Cavalli-Sforza added, they should, for the sake
of the broader community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are differences in ethical beliefs that can be
dangerous,'' he said. ``For example, in the Sicilian code of honor,
you have almost a duty to kill your wife if she is unfaithful, and
until not long ago, the Italian legal code treated a crime of
murder for reasons of `honor' very leniently.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavalli-Sforza's dismissal or minimalization of things such as
skin color and social custom as truly distinguishing
characteristics surely will come as a disappointment to people like
Joerg Haider, the Austrian anti-immigrant politician.
</P>
<P>
   However, it should make every man, woman and child who has ever
faced discrimination feel as good as anyone else on the face of the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luca's position is that there really are no such things as
races, just racism,'' said his top assistant, molecular biologist
Peter Underhill. ``These people in the Balkans, the Kosovars and
the Serbs, are killing each other like crazy, because they have
different religions and cultural practices and suspicions, but they
are very closely related genetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the family of man is validated more and more by
genetic research. Some people find this offensive. You might find
some neo-Nazi idiot up in Idaho and if I did a genetic profile of
him, I might find that he has a lot of Ashkenazi Jewish genes.''
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me that all this science has to cast doubt on the
value of diversity programs in the workplace, in education and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   We make a very big deal about diversity today. Certainly,
celebrating the cultural diversity of differing racial and ethnic
groups seems like a good idea, in so far as it teaches us to be
tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder if tolerance always is the byproduct. Diversity
programs also inevitably draw attention to our significant
differences, and in that sense they may be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're better off with the old family-of-man concept.
</P>
<P>
   Underhill says: ``One of the strengths of our country is
diversity, but it creates tensions, because people aren't familiar
with each other, they look different, they have different languages
and customs. There's this dynamic that goes back a long way. But it
has nothing to do with genetics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
