<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GET READY FOR A TV MARATHON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the reward you get for sitting through 30 weeks of
reruns repackaged as ``encore presentations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time the networks truck out their best movies and
miniseries, and the sitcoms and dramas wrap up their seasons with
weddings and deaths and guest stars _ not to mention more than a
few pink slips as the dead meat limp off to the butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the May sweeps (Through May 24), when the best
programs are clumped together like a tightly packed snowball. Like
November and February, it's a time when viewership is closely
gauged so advertising rates can be set for local affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite, or rather because of, all the specials and special
episodes and finales, the May sweeps are frustrating. Not only does
this time of year leave us trying to figure out how to tape two
shows and watch a third all at once, but it's a stark reminder of
how we've been force-fed weeks upon weeks of reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at Sunday night, for example: ABC is offering
``Arabian Nights,'' as NBC counters with its own miniseries, ``The
'70s,'' and Fox features a unique episode of ``The X-Files.'' (CBS
serves ``Take Me Home: The John Denver Story,'' but it's not very
good and blows my argument, so let's ignore it.) On most nights you
could comfortably watch any of these three and be happy; sweeps
forces you to make a choice. (Our choice in a runaway: ``Arabian
Nights.'')
</P>
<P>
   But don't blame the networks for the sweeps: These seasonal
surveys are for the sole benefit of the local affiliates (national
ratings are compiled throughout the year). To be sure, it's a
stupid system, one that forces the networks to keep running repeats
of many shows for extended periods to ensure enough new material is
saved up for the ratings periods.
</P>
<P>
   Here are just some of the highlights the networks will air in
the coming weeks before reverting to the rerun rut:
</P>
<P>
   In a twist for Fox this year, the network says goodbye to a pair
of shows that actually lasted more than a couple of episodes.
``Party of Five'' departs for good on Wednesday, while ``Beverly
Hills, 90210'' ends its run on May 17 with a two-hour finale
featuring many former cast members.
</P>
<P>
   Julianna Marguilies, whose Nurse Hathaway almost died in the
first episode of ``ER,'' departs the medical drama on May 11.
Michael J. Fox leaves ``Spin City'' on ABC on May 24. And Andrea
Thompson's Jill Kirkendall leaves ``NYPD Blue'' on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Boy Meets World'' is another show going off the air, and
certainly others will follow when the networks announce their fall
schedules next month.
</P>
<P>
   After NBC's lackluster ``Mary, Mother of Jesus,'' CBS takes a
stab at the divine with ``Jesus'' on May 14 and 17. CBS will tackle
a more worldly subject Sunday in ``Take Me Home: The John Denver
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with that Me Generation theme is ``The '70s,'' an NBC
miniseries (Sunday and Monday) founded in the spirit of last year's
miniseries ``The '60s.'' Look for ``The '80s,'' ``The '90s'' and
``The Decade Yet to Be Named'' to go into production in the months
to come.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Robert Halmi productions are slated: ``Arabian
Nights'' (Sunday and Monday) and the NBC ``Jason and the
Argonauts'' (May 7-8). Also on May 7, Drew Carey will star in the
ABC ``Wonderful World of Disney'' movie ``Gepetto,'' a different
take on the Pinocchio tale.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those battling Bradys. NBC presents ``Growing
Up Brady'' (May 21), based on the book by Barry Williams, a k a
Greg. Fox has an hourlong behind-the-scenes ``Brady Bunch'' movie
slated for May 16, the same night it has scheduled an hourlong
behind-the-scenes ``Diff'rent Strokes'' movie. As of last week,
that movie had yet to go into production, a Fox spokeswoman said:
Hmmm _ sounds like a real winner.
</P>
<P>
   And we know you've been waiting for this: CBS has a ``Dukes of
Hazzard'' reunion slated for May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis will guest-star for three episodes on ``Friends,''
which will also see the return of Tom Selleck. This Sunday on ``The
X-Files,'' Garry Shandling and Tea Leoni (real-life wife of David
Duchovny) star in a movie based on Mulder and Scully.
</P>
<P>
   And as if it needs help, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' will
feature celebrities Monday through Wednesday playing for charity.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy it while you can: Months of reruns are only weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
