<HEADLINE>
DOWNTOWN REBOUND: MARKETING DRIVE AIMS TO BRING BACK PATRONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDRA BAKER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Saying they won't let a ``stiff breeze'' get
them down, Fort Worth business and civic leaders have launched a
marketing campaign that takes a humorous approach to letting people
know that downtown is open for activity after the deadly tornado a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads are fun in spirit, but they are no way intended to
downplay the losses,'' said John Stevenson, chairman of Downtown
Fort Worth Inc., the business booster group. Downtown businesses
need ``our business to stay in business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In unveiling the campaign Wednesday, the leaders also announced
that they formed a coalition called Fort Worth TUFF, or Team United
for the Future.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-member group includes representatives from the city, Fort
Worth Chamber of Commerce, Downtown Fort Worth Inc., the Fort Worth
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, and Sundance Square. They will meet
regularly to develop programs and events to attract people downtown
while repairs and renovations are being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plans are on the drawing board,'' said Stevenson, who will be
chairman. He declined to say what kinds of events the group is
discussing.
</P>
<P>
   Storms heavily damaged parts of the city March 28, killing five
people, causing damage estimated at more than $450 million, and
paralyzing downtown for several days. Streets once closed for
cleanup have reopened, but business owners have said they believe
that many people are staying away and mistakenly think it is not
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the case anymore,'' Mayor Kenneth Barr said,
calling the tornado a ``stiff breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown is on the rebound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the hardest-hit office buildings are also reopening. The
UPR Plaza at Seventh and Commerce streets became fully accessible
again late last week, and Bank One officials said they expect
operations to reopen this week in the Bank One tower at Fifth and
Throckmorton streets. The building will be open to tenants in about
three weeks and the Reata restaurant, at the top of the tower,
should open by May 9, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that is really good news,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon &AMP; Associates, a Fort Worth ad and public relations
agency whose downtown offices were heavily damaged, created the ad
campaign. Witherspoon has temporarily moved to offices on the
city's west side while its downtown building is repaired.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will carry the tagline ``Making It Better Than
Ever,'' a logo of the downtown skyline, and the Fort Worth TUFF
acronym. Ads will carry text such as ``You Can't Judge a Town By
Its Plywood,'' ``When Life Hands You Tornadoes, Play Twister,''
``No Gusts, No Glory'' and ``It's Been a Whirlwind Few Weeks. But
Now We're Ready for Company.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will include ads in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram
and The Business Press, and advertising on bus benches and the T
buses.
</P>
<P>
   Both newspapers are donating space for the advertising, the
business group said. The group declined to say how much the
campaign will cost or how long it will run. The group is bearing
any costs outside of contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Harman, president of the Fort Worth Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau, said the campaign is on target. He said he has had
inquiries nationwide from groups looking for convention space,
wondering if it is all right to come to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know downtown is safe,'' Harman said. ``We've
had those kinds of questions raised. That's the kind of thing we've
had to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Boecker, president of Sundance Square Management, said
downtown has lost some momentum, even though many restaurants and
businesses opened within days after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody pulled together in a hurry,'' Boecker said. ``We've
largely been open from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Brenneman, executive director of the Sid Richardson
Collection on Main Street, said she is pleased with the
post-tornado publicity campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're on the right track,'' she said, adding that
``we need to promote the trolley service'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   Since the tornado, attendance has crept back to about two-thirds
of what it was before the storm, Brenneman said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
