<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-VIET-WRITER-$ADV30-BO     04-27 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIET-WRITER-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT WAS A SHEER CRIME. HOW CAN I FORGET THAT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THAI BA TAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI -- Twenty-five years have passed since Vietnam's war with
America ended. But is 25 years long enough for people who lived
through the war, experienced its hardships and cruelties, to forget
it? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   I was one of the few lucky young Vietnamese to be sent abroad by
my government for studies during that difficult time. I left for
Moscow in August 1967, and when I came back, in June 1974, the war
was over, at least in the North. Perhaps I have no right to judge a
war I didn't participate in, let alone speak for those who died or
became permanently disabled. But I did see a lot of the war's
horrors, and I had a brother killed by American bombs. Strangely
enough, as time passes, the memories of those days don't fade. More
often, I find myself thinking about them.
</P>
<P>
   I still remember when the United States started its destruction
of North Vietnam. It was shortly after the so-called Gulf of Tonkin
incident in August 1964. A group of about five American fighter
planes were coming from the sea to bomb Vinh, the provincial center
of Nghe An. That's less than 200 miles south of Hanoi and 19 miles
from the village where we lived. All the villagers, especially the
children like me, went out to watch the planes from a distance.
Some of us even waved at them cheerfully, unaware of what would
come later.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, our quiet village, located on the bank of a
small river used to transport food and military supplies from the
North to the South, became a strategic target for the US Navy's
Seventh Fleet. We were shelled regularly from the sea and bombed by
planes from the air. One morning we were asleep when a rocket hit
our house. Fortunately, no one was killed or wounded, but we were
bombed several more times later, so we had to move to another
village, further from the river.
</P>
<P>
   It was during this time that I saw my first American. Actually,
it was the silhouette of a pilot in his cockpit, diving down to
bomb a small boat in the river. He got so low that the bamboos bent
down and the roofs on thatched houses flew away. For years that
image has stuck with me and influenced the way I think of
Americans. You can imagine the destruction and losses our poor
village suffered as well as the hatred we felt toward the invaders.
In those days, we called them the ``devil Americans,'' the
``murdererous Americans,'' or the ``death sowers.''
</P>
<P>
   The official line here now is to put the war behind us, to look
forward to a friendly future with the United States. It makes
sense. No one is against that, really. It's an imperative of the
times. But in our hearts it's not so simple and clear-cut. Look
toward a friendly future, yes, but forget the war? That's not easy,
because it simply doesn't let you do that.
</P>
<P>
   The war is still present everywhere, every day in Vietnam, and
probably will be for years to come. We have no national cemetery
like Arlington, but every community has a small cemetery for fallen
soldiers. People go there every day to tend the graves of their
relatives, to burn incense, to make kow-tows, to live with the war
again and again. In almost every Vietnamese family there is someone
who died or is missing from the war. How can we forget that?
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996, as part of a delegation of Vietnamese writers, I
spent a month visiting the United States, including Boston. I
enjoyed your city. I also enjoyed meeting Americans who had fought
in the war. They are good people, those veterans, but each time I
shook one of their hands a painful thought struck my mind: that
maybe this very hand, at about 3 o'clock one morning in mid-1968,
had been the one that dropped bombs onto the new village our family
was evacuated to.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs killed my 14-year-old brother, Thai Ba Qui, all eight
members of a family nearby, and many others. Everything can be said
to justify wartime atrocities, but bombing a small village with
absolutely no military targets, with only rice fields, water
buffaloes, and barefoot peasants, was not warfare. It was a sheer
crime. How can I forget that?
</P>
<P>
   When in Washington, I forced myself to stand before the Pentagon
and the State Department to ponder the past and the present. I
resisted the temptation to go inside the White House, where
Presidents Johnson and Nixon ordered the war escalated.
</P>
<P>
   During my stay in the United States, I came to understand it
better. I admired the nation for its dynamism, its great economic
and technological achievements. I do see the differences between
politicians and ordinary people. I've even started saving to send
my daughter to study in America some time in the future. Of course,
she'll have her own way of thinking about the war and those
Americans who took part in it. But I feel it my duty to tell her
all that happened. After all, knowing the past sometimes helps
better prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thai Ba Tan is a poet, short story writer, and translator. He
lives in Hanoi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
