<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GAY-MARCH-$ADV29-COX     04-27 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARCH-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DIVIDED HOMOSEXUAL MOVEMENT PREPARES FOR WASHINGTON MARCH
 &HT;    620&AMP;adds. With GAY-MARCH-GARCIA. For release Saturday, April 29.
 &HT;    Eds: 2nd optional add can stand as a separate graphic.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a rift within their movement, multitudes of
gay and lesbian activists are gathering in the nation's capital for
a long weekend of crusade and celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say this Millennium March on Washington for Equality
is aimed at ``galvanizing and energizing'' the homosexual community
into an effective voting bloc for the November elections and at
inspiring more people to actively support ``our civil rights
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Parties are planned as well as protests and parades. On
Saturday, there is a mass same-sex wedding at the Lincoln Memorial
and a concert starring Garth Brooks, Melissa Etheridge, k.d. lang,
George Michael, Queen Latifah and the Pet Shop Boys at RFK Stadium.
On Sunday, a morning street march will be followed by a rally on
the National Mall, where Ellen DeGeneres and Anne Heche will be
among the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Such national assemblies ``strengthen our movement,'' said
Dianne Hardy-Garcia, director of the march and of the Lesbian/Gay
Rights Lobby of Texas. ``If we are to win our fight for full
equality, we must get stronger and involve more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had predicted this fourth national rally for gay and
lesbian rights would be the biggest ever, attracting up to a
million participants. But some homosexual political groups are
disturbed about the timing and leadership of the march and will
boycott the activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been undemocratic from the get-go,'' said Henry Moses, a
spokesman for the boycott coalition and an officer for the
Washington, D.C., local of Pride at Work, a labor organization that
he said ``represents working-class queers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called things like 'traitor,' but at some point you
have to take a stand and say, 'No one or two organizations can
speak for the community','' said Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not supporting the march,'' said Matt Foreman, a
spokesman for the Empire State Pride Agenda in New York. ``We're
focusing our attentions on where we believe the key battleground
for our movement is _ the local, county and state level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we been asked, we would have said it doesn't make a lot of
sense to have a national march with a lame-duck Congress and a
lame-duck president six months out from the fall election at a time
when the majority of state legislatures are in session,'' said
Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have organized an Ad Hoc Committee for an Open Process
to urge people to ``sit this one out.'' Eleven gay and lesbian
groups from Illinois are boycotting. The national leadership of
Pride at Work, which is affiliated with the AFL-CIO, has urged all
unions ``to neither endorse nor fund this event.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics charge that grassroots groups were ignored in
planning the event.
</P>
<P>
   The march was announced by two major groups: The Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay political organization, and the
Metropolitan Community Church, which welcomes gays and lesbians
into its congregations. Its corporate sponsors include America
Online Inc., the Showtime cable network and United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the planning process as inclusive, Hardy-Garcia said
organizers are not surprised that some comrades oppose the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always dissenting voices. People have varying
opinions,'' she said. ``It's the nature of a movement to have
disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Many state and local organizations are sending delegations to
the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for movements to get together every so often to
celebrate their victories and be emboldened and encouraged for the
future,'' said Harry Knox of the Georgia Equality Project.
</P>
<P>
   National gatherings are especially helpful for young gays and
lesbians who often feel isolated in small Georgia towns, said Knox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle for full equality in Atlanta very different than it
is in Cordele and Statesboro and Rome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The march comes at a time of historic progress and presence for
the gay and lesbian community. This week, Vermont became the first
state to give homosexual couples all the rights and benefits of
marriage. Gay and lesbian characters regularly appear in movies,
network TV programs and other segments of the popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have attained a certain level of visibility,'' said
Hardy-Garcia. ``But visibility isn't civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for political action was dramatized recently when
voters in ``liberal California'' passed a referendum that bans gay
marriages, she said. Other states may enact legislation to prevent
gay and lesbian couples from adopting children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 'Will &AMP; Grace' on TV, but people are fired every day''
for being gay or lesbian, she said. In the fight for equality,
``we're not nearly there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The director said the march will be judged to have been
successful if it helps generate the largest-ever gay and lesbian
voter turnout in the fall elections and motivates a new generation
of activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``To build a civil rights movement,'' she explained, people have
to ``be inspired to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   A national march can turn hundreds of thousands of people into
activists, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first such march came in 1979 and was ``all about being
visible,'' she recalled. The second march was in 1987 and
articulated the community's legislative aims. The 1993 march, which
brought hundreds of thousands of people to Washington, demonstrated
a potential for political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we have to do more,'' she said. ``We have to
prove that we are a powerful voting bloc.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to the gay and lesbian community, Hardy-Garcia
said that internal debates over the march detract from ``the larger
reasons we must work together as a movement.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The platform for the march calls for:
</P>
<P>
   _ Congress and state legislatures to pass legislation providing
protection against hate crimes based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Links between the movements for racial and sexual justice.
</P>
<P>
   _ The right for gays and lesbians to serve openly in the armed
forces and an end to the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' military
policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laws protecting against workplace discrimination on the basis
of sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Equal marriage rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funding for AIDS research, prevention and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.mmow.org, www.foranopenprocess.org,
www.millennium-productions.net
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
