<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIE-ADAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `APARTMENT' ACRTRESS ENJOYS HER FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It doesn't seem real that 40 years ago she
starred with Jack Lemmon and Shirley MacLaine in Billy Wilder's
``The Apartment,'' said Edie Adams, who will appear at Friday
night's gala showing of ``The Apartment'' at the Castro Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're very young, you don't think you're ever going to
get old, you think you're going to live forever,'' Adams said in a
telephone interview from Los Angeles. ``And it almost seems like
some of us do.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, whose age has been reported as 73, scoffs at that,
saying, ``I'm older than Madonna, younger than Katharine Hepburn.
At this age I can't jump up and sing those high C's, but there is
really no such thing as age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only birthday that really bothered me was turning 30. You
get so trapped in this image of perfection. But I'm able to relax
now, don't have to be so perfect. I want to paint next. I want to
be George Burns when I grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   As Adams kicks off the 7 p.m. gala honoring ``The Apartment,''
complete with film clips, an autograph session and a greeting from
Lemmon, Wilder, 93, will remain in Westwood, at the apartment
building he has lived in for decades. Adams will offer a series of
songs, including her renowned Muriel cigar commercials, and footage
of TV shows with her comedian husband, Ernie Kovacs _ but she'll
miss having Wilder there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy can do no wrong as far as I'm concerned,'' Adams said.
``He was way ahead of everyone in his times. Look at `The
Apartment.' Corporate America was running things when he was taking
his shots at them. . . . I pulled down the script the other day and
it's every bit as effective today as it was then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the movie . . . getting lost in that corporate
set, the size of a football field, shots of all these huge, block
buildings . . . and (Wilder) had this all in mind before putting
one word on paper. It was beautifully done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was already edited down by the time it got on the page.
From the very first page I was amazed how carefully everything had
been written, the business of buttoning up the vest with one button
off . . . it was shot exactly as described, not like some lovely
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   To Adams, Wilder ``saw life as it was. He saw the humor of
everyday life. He put it into a movie and made everybody laugh and
say, `Yes, this is how it is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Adams talked of regular screenings at the Kovacs house on Broad
Beach, north of Malibu, with production heads like Sam Goldwyn
asking candidly what actors should be recruited for what roles.
``Here I was, getting to see all these first-run movies on our home
projection room, telling these studio heads `That's a terrible
idea' or `He's all wrong for that.' But I was always brought up to
say what I thought. I don't know if that was good or bad, but it's
what I've always done.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days when Noel Coward would come by for dinner,
said Adams, to mix with a younger generation that ``tried to look
old and sophisticated and Noel Coward-ly. Not one of us wanted to
be a waif. We all wanted to be sophisticated, stylish.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder's last picture, ``Buddy Buddy,'' was made 19 years ago,
finishing off a career that included four classics listed among the
American Film Institute's best 100 movies of all time _ ``Sunset
Boulevard'' at No. 12, ``Some Like It Hot'' at No. 14, ``Double
Indemnity'' at 38 and ``The Apartment'' at No. 93. But Wilder
acknowledged he never was able to recapture his creative spark
after ``The Apartment,'' saying, ``I tried, but I failed in that.
It is a tremendous drop, because I got a little bit confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams wasn't sure why Wilder lost his touch after ``The
Apartment,'' except that it was hard to recapture the camaraderie
of a cast that included Lemmon, Adams and MacLaine, all good
friends. Laughing over the phone, she remembered the scene of
Lemmon straining spaghetti through a tennis racket, the rightness
of it, and said, ``It was a magic time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``A Tribute to Billy Wilder'' with Edie Adams, presented by
Marc Huestis, will be held at 7 p.m. Friday at the Castro Theatre,
429 Castro St. in San Francisco. A personal greeting from Lemmon
and clips and songs from Adams will be offered, followed by a
screening of ``The Apartment.'' Tickets are $15 for the gala, $7.50
for the 10:45 p.m. screening. For more information, call
415-863-0611, or Different Light Books at 415-431-0891.)
</P>
</TEXT>
