<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY LAW SCHOOL PLANS CLINIC ON TECHNOLOGY ISSUES  
STOCK MARKET TURMOIL HURTS ONLINE CONSUMER CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of California at Berkeley law school plans Monday
to announce the formation of a high-technology law clinic that will
work on civil liberties and public policy issues involved in areas
like Internet privacy, encryption and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Samuelson Law, Technology and Public Policy Clinic will be
the nation's first public interest, high-technology law clinic,
according to its founder, Pamela Samuelson. She is a professor at
Berkeley who has a joint teaching appointment at the law school and
at the university's School of Information Management and Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The program's initial financing will come from two $300,000
grants _ one from Mitchell D. Kapor, founder of Lotus Development,
and one from the Markle Foundation _ as well as a $2 million
endowment from Samuelson and her husband, Robert Glushko. Glushko
is an executive at Commerce One, a Silicon Valley Internet software
company that acquired Glushko's own start-up software company
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program grew out of a conversation I had with Berkeley law
students,'' Samuelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the best intellectual property programs in the
country,'' she added. ``This seemed to be a good way to mobilize
students to do things like file public interest lawsuits and amicus
briefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The expanding role of technology in society, she said, is
raising public policy issues that have not previously been faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have inexpensive technologies that are widely available
that allow you to collect and process personal information in ways
that haven't been possible previously,'' Samuelson said.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to other law clinics already in place at the
Berkeley law school, like one that focuses on human rights issues.
These clinics, she said, offer students opportunities to gain
real-world legal experience before they become professional
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The program will concentrate on topics like the privacy issues
raised by Internet surveillance conducted by e-commerce companies;
free speech restrictions on the Internet; Internet-related libel
lawsuits; and the restricting of Internet access by public
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which is to begin in the fall or next spring, will
be run by a faculty member to be hired by the law school.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   STOCK MARKET TURMOIL HURTS ONLINE CONSUMER CONFIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   The recent Wall Street sell-off has shaken consumer confidence,
at least among online consumers, according to a survey to be
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NPD Group, a research firm in Port Washington, N.Y., surveyed
5,000 Internet users nationwide online, and gauged their confidence
in the overall economy and local job markets. It also asked
consumers and assess their own families' financial health and to
forecast their households' online spending for the next three
months.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents said they planned to spend less money on purchases
made over the Internet in the coming months, although NPD said that
at least some of the expected downturn might be attributable to
seasonal swings in online categories like books and music.
</P>
<P>
   The respondents, surveyed on and immediately after April 14, the
day of the stock market's steepest recent drop, reported the lowest
confidence in the economy since the monthly study began in January.
</P>
<P>
   Using January as a benchmark of 100, the confidence index was
95.8, down a half-point from the March poll.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, while respondents indicated that their own families'
financial situations were slightly worse than in March, they tended
to say they were better off than at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between respondents' assessment of the overall economy
and their own families' situations, may ``confirm the wealth
effect'' that economists like the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan
Greenspan, have cited, in the view of Karl Irons, NPD's president
of online research.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really do think they're wealthier than they are, and
that they're insulated from the economy,'' Irons said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BOB TEDESCHI
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-23-00 1836EDT &QL;
</P>
