<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-CHIP-PHOTO-ART-NY     04-27 1751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CHIP-PHOTO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPS PROMISE DIGITAL IMAGES AT LOWER COST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRENOBLE, France _ Eleven years ago, Peter Denyer, who was then
an Edinburgh University electronic engineering professor,
painstakingly pried the cap off a computer memory chip and, by
exposing it to light, was able to capture a rudimentary monochrome
digital image, displayable on a computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not realize it at the time, Denyer was repeating
an experiment others had performed several years earlier at the
California Institute of Technology. But it was he who first
recognized the commercial possibility: A memory chip might serve as
an inexpensive digital imaging system, one that could transform the
worlds of photography and video.
</P>
<P>
   And last year when Vision Group LLG, Denyer's chip design firm,
was purchased for $39 million by STMicroelectronics NV, the world's
seventh-largest chip maker, the stage was set. By combining Vision
Group's technology with the manufacturing and distribution
capabilities of STMicroelectronics, Denyer hopes to create a new
generation of chips that might soon lead to inexpensive,
high-resolution still and video cameras.
</P>
<P>
   STMicroelectronics predicts that within several years the cost
of high-resolution digital cameras, now typically in the hundreds
of dollars, will fall to near that of today's computer memory chips
_ a few dollars apiece.
</P>
<P>
   And once that happens, Denyer and his colleagues promise,
digital photo capabilities will find their way into all sorts of
consumer electronics _ whether cell phones that could take and send
snapshots, hand-held digital assistants that could double as video
camcorders or portable computers that might enable traveling sales
executives to shoot and edit entire multimedia presentations on the
fly.
</P>
<P>
   Between today's reality and tomorrow's vision, though, lies an
international technology battle, one that pits Denyer and others
against the makers of the more costly sensors that now dominate
digital cameras. Called charged coupled devices, or CCDs, these
sensors require a set of several chips and components. They are
made chiefly by the same Japanese companies, like Sony and
Matsushita, that are among the leading makers of digital cameras
and video camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with these companies are STMicroelectronics, as well
as Motorola and other American companies that have built factories
to produce the kind of less-expensive sensors that Denyer has long
championed: complimentary metal oxide semiconductor, or CMOS,
chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably a little ahead of the market,'' Denyer said,
recalling his experiment of more than a decade ago. He is now
director of technology for STMicroelectronics' imaging division,
dividing his time between his lab in Edinburgh and the division's
operation here in Grenoble. ``It's harder than it looks,'' he said
of the company's CMOS work, ``but we've done a lot of research.''
</P>
<P>
   CMOS (pronounced SEE-moss) imaging chips, which are made with
the same basic techniques as conventional computer chips, are
already widely used in low-cost Web cameras, sold by Logitech
International and others, as attachments for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   While CCD sensors remain the foundation of both the digital
photography and video markets, CMOS makers plan to mount increasing
competitive pressure through a variety of new digital imaging
products that take advantage of the lower-cost sensor chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental advantage of CMOS is you can integrate
computing and sensor functions,'' said Willy Shih, president of
Eastman Kodak's digital applied imaging division. Kodak produces
CCD sensors for its own digital cameras and under contract to
various government agencies. But the company has also introduced
its first CMOS-based camera _ an attachment for Palm hand-held
devices. ``If you want to make a single-chip digital camera,'' Shih
said, ``you will have to use CMOS.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike CCD sensors, with their multiple components and their
vast arrays of light-sensitive electronic capacitors, CMOS sensors
can be made using the same high-volume lithographic process as
other kinds of solid-state semiconductors. Advocates of CMOS say
their single-chip production advantage will enble them to overwhelm
their opponents with price advantages and high-volume
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But executives in the CCD camp, along with some analysts, point
out that CMOS proponents have long failed to live up to such
forecasts, because of the inferior quality of CMOS-produced images.
</P>
<P>
   ``CMOS hasn't made inroads into the CCD market as much as its
supporters have predicted,'' said Mark Kirstein, vice president for
research at the Cahners In-Stat Group, a semiconductor market
research firm in Scottsdale, Ariz. ``But it has resulted in a
significant reduction in price in CCDs and a huge influx of capital
into CCD development, as the Japanese manufacturers have started
lowering their prices and pouring in R&AMP;D money.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter, say CMOS adherents. They note that a new wave of
investment, driven by new applications like image-capture systems
for cell phones and Web cameras and other imaging devices for
personal computer, has led to an explosion of CMOS development
among big chip makers like ST Microsystems, Motorola and Agilent,
the new Hewlett-Packard spinoff, as well as smaller start-ups like
Photobit, Conexant and Y-Media.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the potential of CMOS, some small start-ups are
even attacking a part of the CCD market that many had considered
unassailable: high-quality digital imaging, like that used for
fashion and advertising photography.
</P>
<P>
   The upstarts include Foveon, in Santa Clara, Calif., a maker of
photo-studio cameras that sell for as much as $50,000 and offer
stunning resolution. The company was founded in 1997 by Carver
Mead, a physicist and semiconductor industry pioneer who did early
work in artificial silicon retinas at the California Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be left out of any market where quality is
an issue,'' Mead said. Foveon's sensors employ a three-chip system
_ for red, green and blue sensitivity _ made through a CMOS process
but incorporating the company's ``own secret sauce on top of
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Mead toils in the market's higher reaches, Denyer and the
STMicroelectronics design team are more intent on mass-market
applications. Executives at STMicrosystems and other chip companies
now predict that an imaging chip will become a standard feature of
a digital cellular phone as soon as 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, phones will soon have the capability to send and
receive still images, while in Japan plans are now under way to
make video a standard cellular phone feature,'' said Jean-Pierre
Lusinchi, group vice president of the STMicroelectronics' consumer
and microcontroller products division.
</P>
<P>
   CMOS sensors are also finding their way into a diverse range of
low-cost applications that require digital imaging. An optical
mouse recently introduced by Microsoft, for example, uses a CMOS
sensor made by Agilent. Besides having no moving parts, the mouse
is more precise than conventional roller-ball models, the maker
says, because its motion sensor can capture up to 1,000 images per
second as it is moved across a flat surface; by comparing images,
software in the chip determines the mouse's speed and direction.
</P>
<P>
   The optical mouse has joined the Web camera as an add-on device
that analysts expect to become a standard accessory with many of
the 150 million or more computers sold worldwide each year.
</P>
<P>
   Web cameras, almost all of which use CMOS chips, are based on
sensors that have 100,000 to 300,000 picture elements, or pixels.
That allows a resolution acceptable on the screen of a hand-held
device or in a small window on a computer monitor _ though hardly
comparable with the resolution of 2 million or 3 million pixels
from CCD cameras, which are fast approaching the clarity of
35-millimeter photographic film.
</P>
<P>
   But Web cameras, used for all sorts of video voyeurism, have
caught on with PC users much more quickly than most analysts had
predicted. ``Our plan is to become the eyes of the Internet,'' said
Neal Carney, a marketing manager in Agilent's semiconductor
products group.
</P>
<P>
   Other CMOS sensors are cropping up in intriguing new
applications, like one from Photobit, a CMOS imaging company in
Pasadena, Calif., that was founded by scientists who pioneered the
technology at the California Institute of Technology's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory. Photobit has developed a CMOS sensor that
its executives say can be used to reduce the costs and health risks
of dental X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   The system does away with photographic film, displaying the
X-ray instead on a video monitor. And for the patient, it requires
only about one-tenth the exposure to the dangerous rays as a
conventional X-ray, according to Photobit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such developments, CCD supporters are skeptical that
CMOS will penetrate the heart of the CCD market _ consumer video
and still-picture digital cameras. Besides the big Japanese
manufacturers and Kodak, CCD makers include some small American
companies like Pixel Vision Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while I go to Kmart to see if CMOS is showing
up in the video camera market,'' said James Janesick, executive
vice president and chief scientific officer for Pixel Vision, which
is based in Huntington Beach, Calif. ``So far, they haven't made
any inroads.'' But Janesick acknowledges that CMOS is appearing in
the market for digital still cameras priced below $500. Polaroid
has begun offering a digital camera that sells for less than $200
and uses a CMOS sensor, and similar consumer-quality products from
other companies are expected to fall below to $100 before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Janesick expects the CCD makers to defend their territory with a
vengeance, resisting new technologies with fierce price
competition. But Denyer, predicts that CMOS will create vast new
markets beyond the reach of CCD and then eventually pose a head-on
challenge to CCD's higher-resolution applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been predicting the arrival of CMOS for years, and now
it's coming true,'' Denyer said. ``I feel like saying loudly, `I
told you so.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-     04-27 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: WEB RETAILERS FACE DEMANDS FOR EFFICIENCY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the dismal performance of dot-com retailers on Wall Street
and in the offices of venture capitalists lately, investors have
had their fill of e-books, e-pets, e-drugs and other Web retail
operations that burn through cash at Internet speed. What the
market seems to be in the mood for now is some old-fashioned
e-fficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to executives and industry analysts, is
that investors had been treating electronic commerce as a
popularity contest, giving the sites with the most visitors the
highest stock valuations. As a result, many Internet merchants have
concentrated more on their Web-traffic figures than on the standard
measures of long-term retail success, like gross margins, customer
acquisition costs and customer retention rates.
</P>
<P>
   But now that investors are seeking evidence that dot-coms can
show profits at some point, many Web retailers are getting down to
the dirty work of squeezing income from their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, the focus is now on what will drive near-term
revenue,'' said John Hagel, a partner at McKinsey &AMP; Co., the
management consultants. ``There's clearly a sense of urgency around
the efficiency side of the equation, which for a long time was
ignored quite explicitly.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, that urgency translates to difficult decisions
about where to devote staff resources _ for example, whether to
shift employees from long-term projects to those with more
short-term relevance to the bottom line. In others, it means
actually using the mountains of data that e-tailers have said all
along will help speed their earnings growth _ by allowing them to
make better decisions about which customers are the most
profitable, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the new tensions can mean even harder work for
employees who may have been hoping by now to ease into a 9-to-5
routine as the value of their stock options appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel and others said the focus on near-term revenue probably
meant the temporary abandonment of some prominent retail
initiatives, like building sites devoted to wireless Internet users
or new sites designed to take advantage of high-speed Internet
access. ``A lot of e-tailers had aggressive plans to expand into
related categories that they've put off,'' Hagel said, ``because
that would require a big near-term investment with no revenue
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bowman, chief executive of Cyberian Outpost
(www.outpost.com), a Web retailer that sells computers and
electronic goods, said his company was intensifying its efforts
toward making a profit, a goal he predicted the company would
achieve ``by the middle of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach that goal, Bowman said Cyberian Outpost would have to
increase the rate at which buyers returned to the site to an
average of 3.5 times a year, from the current 2.7 times. Twelve
months ago, average visits occurred 1.7 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   The return-rate statistic is particularly important for Internet
retailers because they typically spend substantial amounts to
attract new customers _ $80 to $100 each, on average. So the more
revenue they can glean from their existing customers, the faster
the profits will come.
</P>
<P>
   To retain its existing customer base, Bowman said his company
had increased its focus on e-mail marketing and stayed with a
policy of offering free overnight shipping, while it also tweaked
the Web site's performance.
</P>
<P>
   This month, ``four of our engineers wanted to work on WAP,''
Bowman said, referring to the company's wireless-access initiative.
``I said, fine, but you have to work on the site's search first,
because after the checkout page, it's the No. 1 most abandoned part
of the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can move that needle 5 percent,'' he added, ``that's
significant dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other retailers, Cyberian Outpost has shunned
television advertising in favor of print and Internet ads. This
represents a shift for Cyberian, which gained attention last year _
and for some, notoriety _ with a TV ad depicting gerbils being shot
from a cannon. The ads were shown before Bowman became chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of television ad spending last year, Bowman said
that the company had been paying $90 to attract each new customer,
a cost that is now $40 and dropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell our people this isn't some online fraternity or
sorority,'' he said. ``It's a business that's publicly traded, and
it has to be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Morris, executive vice president of Bluefly, an
Internet-only discount apparel retailer, said that because his
company started with $4 million, ``we never really had the luxury
of a war chest, so we were forced to be more disciplined about
costs from early on.'' Bluefly began as a division of Pivot Rules;
that company changed its name to Bluefly when it sold its other
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Morris said, Blue-fly has found new ways to
squeeze dollars from several areas inside the business, including
order fulfillment. For example, the company now calculates the
efficiency of using different carriers to send packages to
different regions, rather than depending on one carrier. ``That can
play a huge role in lowering costs,'' he said, adding that
fulfillment managers _ whether inside the company or outside
contractors _ ``are getting smarter about this, because they're
being forced to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Profitability is not unheard of in Internet retailing, according
to James Vogtle, director of e-commerce research at the Boston
Consulting Group. Vogtle's firm recently surveyed 412 online
retailers on behalf of Shop.org, an industry trade group, and found
that 24 percent of Web-only retailers were profitable last year.
But according to Shop.org, none of the large, publicly traded
e-tailers were among them. Those companies were still spending
large amounts of money on marketing to reach as wide an audience as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the trend, a few Internet companies are finding sources
of revenue inside their own marketing departments. David
Friedensohn, chief executive of BigStar Entertainment, an
online-only retailer of videos and DVDs, said that instead of the
``spray-and-pray advertising approach,'' the company's primary
marketing vehicle had been its own database of 1.7 million customer
e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   BigStar built content features into its Web site like interviews
with celebrities _ features that, when monitored, give the company
a better idea of individual customers' movie tastes. In addition to
tracking usage and buying patterns, BigStar designed software that
could sift through customer profiles before sending an e-mail
marketing letter, and could tailor each note to a customer's
entertainment preferences.
</P>
<P>
   That approach has not only stabilized the company's marketing
costs, Friedensohn said, but has also generated revenue, since
BigStar now sells its e-mail personalization service to other
companies. Such efficiency is important, he said, if BigStar is to
survive in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that you anticipate failure,'' Friedensohn said,
``but because things change so quickly on the Web, you want to
build flexibility into the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel, at McKinsey, said that unlike BigStar, most e-tailers had
done nothing with the vast amounts of customer data they had
collected. ``In many cases they don't have the tools in place, or
the skills to use the tools,'' he said. ``But you don't even need
sophisticated systems. A lot of this is back-of-the-envelope
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the case of one McKinsey client, an online financial
services company that was retaining customers at what was
considered a good rate by industry standards. ``But they never
bothered to look at who was actually leaving and why,'' Hagel said.
</P>
<P>
   After some rudimentary sampling, it turned out that the
company's most profitable customers were leaving. ``Economically,
it was a disaster,'' he said. ``This refocused the company
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable why companies have not focused on the
bottom line until now, Hagel added, since ``growth has been the
biggest imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the market's now saying pretty clearly that it's not just
growth anymore,'' he said. ``It's about overall efficiency of
operations. The only problem is, in most cases, the skill sets to
get that done are sadly lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-23-00 1628EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-     04-27 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAK THE LOCK ON NET CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I am having a major problem with Internet
Explorer's Content Advisor. I cannot access any Web pages due to
the lack of a ``supervisor password,'' which I do not remember
entering. I tried to uninstall Explorer and then reinstall, but I
still receive this message. _ Webless
</P>
<P>
   Dear Webless: Gosh, you wouldn't be just another teen-ager
trying to pull the wool over the ol' doc's eyes, now would you? Mom
caught you spending a little too much recreational time on the
Jennicam site?
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, I wouldn't answer a question like this, but, since
the solution is already well-known, it gives me yet another chance
to wag my finger at parents. Besides, I locked myself out of IE the
same way once, so I know it can happen to nonteen-agers too.
</P>
<P>
   The newest versions of Internet Explorer allow conscientious
parents to deny access to sites that voluntarily rate themselves as
adult-oriented or just plain naughty. The only problem with this
system is that it gives parents the idea that their kids can't
figure a way around the roadblock. Wrong. This particular feature
is easy to defeat, as a quick Yahoo! search can show.
</P>
<P>
   There are actually two solutions. One is to wipe your hard drive
clean and start over with a fresh installation of Windows. The
second is to twiddle with the Registry. That's why uninstalling IE
didn't work. The setting was still in the Registry, waiting to lock
you out again.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think Microsoft would have the answer on their support
site, but the people there aren't real big on helping users poke
holes in their ``security'' features. You can call them at (425)
635-7123 for help, but why? It's a simple hack as long as you don't
mind taking a chance clobbering your system by editing the
Registry.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the Start menu, then select Run. Type Regedit in the blank
and press Enter. Now you're in the Registry Editor. Go to
HKEY(underscore)LOCAL(underscore)MACHINE, then Software, then
Microsoft, then Windows, then Current Version, then Policies, then
Ratings. Delete the key you find there. Now use Windows Explorer to
delete the file Ratings.pol in the System folder (within the
Windows folder). You'll be back watching Jenni in no time.
</P>
<P>
   And, parents, don't trust software to do your job.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Please tell people about the open-source
revolution, which includes Linux. _ Open Sesame
</P>
<P>
   Dear Open: Sigh. I can always tell when I'm about to generate
hate mail. The one thing Linux needs to turn it into a commercially
viable alternative to other operating systems is Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is admirable: a free, stable operating system, with
source code available to all. The reality is dreadful: thousands of
programmers of widely varying skills going in a hundred different
directions. The result: a difficult-to-learn system that works
correctly with only a fraction of the hardware available to users.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun to play with, but until some corporate giant decides to
build the ultimate user-friendly super-compatible Linux
distribution, there's no way it can dislodge Windows or the Mac OS.
Granted, installation has gotten easier in the past few years. Red
Hat, Caldera and Corel have done a great job making Linux more
accessible to us non-Poindexters, but I still can't get Soldier of
Fortune to run on a Linux box. Even with all its goofy ways of
crashing, I'll stick with Windows for a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. Linux-heads may
direct their flames to drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail:
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax:
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-23-00 1819EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
