<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     04-27 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK EXAMINES HOW CISCO HAS BECOME ONE OF THE WORLD'S MOST VALUABLE
COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Teresa McUsic 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Systems probably qualifies as the biggest company you've
never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the Internet boom, the fast-growing maker of
communications network equipment became the world's most valuable
company this year _ at least on Wall Street. For a time, it was
worth more than General Electric. Its shares tumbled a bit during
the stock market turmoil of the past month, but Cisco remains more
valuable than Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Cisco remains a mystery even to many who follow
business. Sure, most readers are probably familiar with the
exploits of celebrity CEOs such as GE's Jack Welch or Microsoft's
Bill Gates. But can you name the chief executive of Cisco _ a
company still worth more than $400 billion after the most recent
market shake-up?
</P>
<P>
   He is John Chambers, a former IBM salesman who also worked as a
key executive of Wang Laboratories. A recently published book
provides the best glimpse of the management techniques and
strategies that Chambers used in catapulting Cisco from a niche
maker of networking gear into the dominant player in developing the
systems that push data around the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Making the Cisco Connection: The Story Behind the Real
Internet Superpower,'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 218 pages, $24.95),
David Bunnell reviews Cisco's history and shows how the company has
integrated an enviable corporate culture with an aggressive
acquisition strategy to lead in Internet development.
</P>
<P>
   For Cisco managers, no price is too high for the right
acquisition. It acquires companies _ and their employees _ to grab
a head start in key technology sectors that could position Cisco as
a single source for heavy-duty computer networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Cisco spent $6.9 billion to acquire
Cerent, a fiber-optic technology developer that employed 275 people
and generated just $15 million in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Bunnell writes, is not to acquire companies just for
the sake of deals. Cisco's goal is to establish itself as a leading
player in every market sector it touches, no matter the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core philosophy was to aim at the future,'' Bunnell
writes. ``The price tag of the acquisition was a secondary
condition to Chambers, who would pay whatever it took to get the
right company.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell also describes Cisco's work environment through several
lower-level employees, detailing how each interacts with their
managers.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell gets bogged down trying to explain the technical details
of Cisco's strategy, but the technology lessons help in explaining
Chambers' long-term vision of developing Internet-style systems.
</P>
<P>
   If Chambers succeeds, the Internet will be the primary network
for carrying all types of communications, including long-distance
telephone calls and video chats. It may be a long shot to believe
that the telephone companies will change the century of work they
have put into building their networks to embrace the Cisco vision.
But if Chambers is right, Cisco would reap a windfall as the
leading developer of equipment used in Internet networks.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Bunnell cautions readers not to get too carried away
in believing the Cisco vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small innovative company,'' Bunnell writes, ``could come
along _ unburdened by hype, huge product lines and an organization
of thousands _ to become the next company of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``J.K. Lasser's How to Protect Your Retirement Savings from the
IRS''
</P>
<P>
   By Seymour Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Many IRS rules deal with retirement plan accounts either while
you are alive or after your death, warns author, attorney and CPA
Seymour Goldberg. This book covers most of those rules, including
tax law changes that apply to retirement, including a chapter on
the new Roth IRA. The book is totally in a question and answer
format, which may make studying it less taxing. In addition to IRS
rules, tax-planning strategies and income tax-deferral techniques
are discussed. A valuable resource when considering retirement
savings.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Intuitive Businesswoman: Achieve Success Through the Power
of Your Personality''
</P>
<P>
   By Judy George and Todd Lyon
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson Potter, $25
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, more than 70 percent of all new U.S. businesses were
started by women, and women own nearly half the small businesses in
this country. Among them is Judy George, who, after being fired as
president of a major furniture chain, started her own chain. She
covers her experience and others in her book, which seeks to
inspire and support the businesswoman somewhere inside nearly all
women.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perils of Imprudent Writing: How to Watch What You Write
and Stay Out of Court!''
</P>
<P>
   By Edward P. Ahrens Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buren Books, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   Now in its second edition, this book could turn out to the
Strunk and White ``Elements of Style'' writing handbook of its day.
Author Edward Ahrens Jr. is a Miami attorney and court mediator
with experience in corporate counseling. He's seen all types of
legal messes created from poor communication, written or oral, and
shows how to avoid costly legal mistakes from poor use of words.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
