<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TECHNO-CISCO-BOS &LR;      04-27 1981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNO-CISCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONTINUING ADVENTURES OF THE CISCO KID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX PHAM   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ After a speech to 600 children several years
ago, John T. Chambers found himself facing a young girl with a
stutter so severe she couldn't articulate her question. Mute and
frustrated, she cried before the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers then made a rare, uncharacteristic move. He showed his
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Cisco Systems Inc., one of Silicon
Valley's most visible success stories of the 1990s, told a stunned
audience of his employees and their children that he had a learning
disability. It is a form of dyslexia that continues to plague him
in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was dumb,'' Chambers reflected in an interview
with the Globe. ``But my parents were physicians, and they knew
better. So with their encouragement, I was able to work around it.
Education was the equalizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, 50, a former Wang Laboratories Inc. executive who
still has difficulty reading, is evangelizing about what he thinks
is the next big trend on the Internet: e-learning.
</P>
<P>
   When Chambers talks, Wall Street listens _ especially because
he's head of a company that makes the physical nuts and bolts of
the Internet, a company that's now worth more than Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley also pays attention, because his prophecies tend
to come true. In the early 1990s, Chambers talked about the e-mail
revolution. In the mid-1990s, he championed e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Today it's e-learning, the notion that people can use the
Internet to master almost any subject, from algebra and physics to
management theory and corporate finance. Chambers believes
e-learning is far more efficient than traditional classroom
techniques because students can learn anytime, at their own pace,
with lower cost and more accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the next big killer application on the Internet,''
Chambers said. ``It's so big, it's going to make e-mail look like a
rounding error.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is moving to make Chambers's e-learning vision a reality.
The company has spent more than $18 million in the last three years
developing what Chambers calls ``the largest e-learning laboratory
in the world,'' one that currently counts 60,000 students in 51
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which sets up ``networking academies,'' teaches
pupils how to become network technicians _ people who physically
wire computers together and link them to the Internet. The
Cisco-developed curriculum is distributed via the Internet to 3,108
high schools and community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   So fanatical is Chambers about e-learning that his speeches
sound like the sermons of a Southern minister, peppered with
rousing rhetoric and catchy phrases. He proselytizes about the
virtues of e-learning as a tool to help poor or disadvantaged
students throughout the world get the educations they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Networking academies create a level playing field,'' Chambers
said. ``It's turning a digital divide into an Internet bridge.
Education and the Internet are going to be the great global
equalizers.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Both elements worked for Chambers, who plowed
through law school and business school _ in spite of his reading
disability _ and whose fortunes rose with the explosion of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's academies train legions of young people who can help
build the world's Internet highways, using Cisco products. They
promote a particularly intense use of the Internet, one that calls
for video streaming, teleconferencing, and online testing, as well
as text, music, and animated graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit to Cisco is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Internet traffic there is, the better it is for
Cisco,'' which sells routers and switches used to build the
information superhighway, said Michael Neiberg, managing director
of Chase Hambrect &AMP; Quist in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: Is Chambers a zealous philanthropist or
a cunning businessman?
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence, scattered throughout his career, that
Chambers is both.
</P>
<P>
   After overcompensating for an early distaste for academics with
a law degree from West Virginia University and an master's in
business administration from Indiana University in Bloomington,
Chambers went to work for IBM Corp., where he developed and honed
his sales skills. He learned that selling technology wasn't about
moving machines; it was about ``selling a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Chambers joined Wang, when the minicomputer
firm looked invincible. He became its top sales executive, a
position that in its final days came with a heavy price. When the
Massachusetts computer company began its downward spiral in the
late 1980s, it was Chambers's job to lay off thousands of workers.
Rather than finish his grim task, he quit in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second or third round of layoffs, he began to feel
personally responsible,'' said Gary Daichendt, a Cisco executive
vice president who worked at Wang with Chambers. ``It tore him
apart. It's one of the only times I've seen him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers landed at Cisco in 1991. At the time, the company had
just $70 million in annual sales and was often confused with Sysco,
the Houston food-distribution company. Chambers became president
and CEO in January 1995, after careful grooming by John P.
Morgridge, the company's leader prior to Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and Morgridge proceeded to make Cisco employees and
shareholders wealthy through a bold bet on the Internet, a
relentless sales culture, and an aggressive acquisition strategy.
</P>
<P>
   A $1,000 investment in Cisco stock on Jan. 24, 1991, the day
Chambers arrived, would yield nearly $370,000 today. The average
nonmanagement Cisco employee has Cisco stock options worth almost
$300,000, thanks to a company policy that distributes 42 percent of
employee stock options to the rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Cisco is on track to becoming a $17 billion company,
measured in revenue. Its high-flying stock gives Cisco a market
capitalization of $451.8 billion, the second-highest value for a
public company in the world, after General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Chambers is trying not to rest on his laurels. Having
emerged from the ashes of Wang and other troubled technology
companies, Chambers and many on his executive team say they operate
under what they call ``healthy paranoia,'' the assumption that
things could come crashing down at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about not moving fast enough,'' said Chambers. ``I
worry about getting away from our customers, like we did at Wang.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, friends and associates are quick to note his intense
drive. ``John has two moods: up and slightly up,'' said Daichendt.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Redfield, who worked at Digital Equipment Corp. for 18
years before joining Cisco in 1993, summed it up this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of us here have come from places that have experienced
failure that we all have a paranoia. But we've also developed a
sense for things that you shouldn't do, and John developed that at
Wang.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson, managing director of Yankee Group in Boston,
also noted that Chambers's drive is rooted in adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind that very proper, Southern-gentleman attitude is one of
the most competitive people in the communications industry,''
Anderson said. ``He's got an iron will that is unbelievable. The
defining moment for John was when he had to participate in
dismantling Wang. In his mind, he decided he never wanted to do
that again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly why Chambers works hard to promote e-learning as
the next big trend on the Internet, positioning Cisco as a company
that is ahead of the curve, or at least appears to be. He envisions
a day when not only schools but companies and all sorts of
institutions will use the Internet to teach and train individuals.
</P>
<P>
   To show that it walks the talk, Cisco trains the majority of its
sales staff on the Internet. As a result, the company says it saves
more than $50 million a year on travel expenses associated with
bringing far-flung sales staff to company headquarters in San Jose
for classroom instruction, said Thomas M. Kelly, Cisco's director
of worldwide training.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly insisted, however, that cost savings is the least
important of the reasons for using online training. Employees
retain more because they're engaging the curriculum at their own
pace, Kelly said, and Cisco can more easily maintain and instantly
update the curriculum without the logistical hassles of reprinting
handouts and retraining instructors. It's also easier for Cisco
supervisors to check on the progress of individual employees, since
tests are taken online and scores are instantly tabulated.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for networking academies, which Chambers touts
every chance he gets, from meetings with Wall Street analysts and
shareholders to geeks at the Comdex technology convention last
November in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stars of this program is Jacob Picart, an 18-year-old
senior at Wilcox High School in Santa Clara, Calif. Picart was
invited last year to a Cisco shareholders' meeting to help Chambers
show off the networking academies curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taught me a lot,'' Picart said. ``When I'm done, it will
open doors for me. I'll be able to build your network for you.
That's what it amounts to.''
</P>
<P>
   It could also amount to a job paying a starting salary of more
than $30,000 a year, even if Picart chooses not to continue in
college. At the end of the two-year curriculum, students have the
option of taking an exam to become a Cisco Certified Networking
Associate, a distinction companies frequently look for when hiring
technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certification is a nice supplement,'' said Leo Carey, a
networking academies instructor at Charlestown High School, which
enrolls about 120 students this year. ``But what's important is the
fact that these students, many of whom have never had computer
experience before, are now selecting career pathways. They're all
motivated to go to two- and four-year colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgridge, the chairman of Cisco's board and its former CEO,
calls the three-year-old program, which is on the verge of
graduating close to 60,000 students worldwide this year,
``enlightened self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought it would grow to this scale,'' Morgridge
said. ``But now that it has, it has the potential to address the
manpower shortage in this industry, not only for Cisco but for our
customers as well. It's also enabled schools to buy and use our
equipment. So it's really been a win-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Cisco's focus on training, Anderson noted: ``John
says the biggest impediment to Cisco's growth is that there aren't
enough people out there to install their equipment. There is an
enormous need for network people throughout the entire industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco doesn't make money selling switches and routers to
schools. In fact, it gives much of its equipment away to schools.
What Cisco gets in return is a chance to impress thousands of
future engineers who are likely to develop a connection with the
company's products.
</P>
<P>
   It's a formula pioneered by Apple Computer Inc., which for
decades has given deep discounts to universities and their students
in the hopes that the students will develop a lifelong preference
for its Macintosh products. Intel Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc.
are among other computer companies pursuing the same route.
</P>
<P>
   So Chambers, the sensitive philanthropist, is spending millions
of dollars promoting a socially conscious agenda that may turn out
to reward the company better than any stock return it has seen to
date.
</P>
<P>
   What will drive the world towards e-learning? The same thing
that drove Chambers to spend two years in elementary school with
tutors to deal with his dyslexia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survival,'' Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-25-00 1051EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
