<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CYBERTIMES-SHOPPING-M     04-27 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-SHOPPING-MALLS-INTERNET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING MALLS DEVELOP INTERNET STRATEGIES 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BOB TEDESCHI &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, amid the hype of dot-com retailing and the
run-up in e-commerce stocks, Web merchants had a lot of fun at the
expense of shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   When they were not explicitly stating that mall shopping was a
complete waste of time and money, they implied it. Analysts piled
on as well, some predicting that e-tailers would bring about the
demise of the mall altogether. Mall developers could do little but
watch their stock prices sink, and hope people came to their
senses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the airwaves less crowded by consumer e-commerce
advertisements and with investors fleeing Web merchants en masse,
Internet retailers suddenly seem a lot more vulnerable _ and malls
are poised for a counteroffensive.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' biggest mall developers, like General Growth
Properties and Simon Property Group, have ratcheted up their own
e-commerce strategies in recent months. Putting a new spin on
so-called clicks-and-mortar strategies, they are vying to fill the
gaps left by both traditional and Internet retailers, in areas like
electronic ordering and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts may not slow the Internet shopping trend, but they
will at least ensure that the malls get a piece of the e-commerce
pie, and perhaps guarantee malls' continued relevance in the retail
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that among all mall owners, Simon Property Group
has been the most aggressive in pushing its e-commerce strategies.
The Indianapolis-based company is the nation's largest mall
developer, with more than 200 shopping malls, including the
behemoth Mall of America near Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Simon created two separate business units,
Clixnmortar and TenantConnect.net, to enable shoppers to integrate
e-commerce into their trips to the mall. Through TenantConnect,
Simon is installing broadband Internet connections inside its own
malls and those of other developers, so that store merchants can
have high-speed access to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, retailers may take part in two Clixnmortar
initiatives now under development: FastFrog.com, which is designed
for teen-agers, and YourSherpa.com, which is intended for adult
users.
</P>
<P>
   In both programs, shoppers carry hand-held scanners through the
mall, zapping items they are interested in buying. When shoppers
are finished, the items appear on a wish list in a mall Internet
kiosk for FastFrog, or on a shopper's check-out page at a different
Internet kiosk for YourSherpa.
</P>
<P>
   From the FastFrog kiosks, teen-agers can forward their wish
lists to friends and relatives. At the YourSherpa kiosks, users can
type in their credit-card numbers and check out immediately, or
delay the final purchase until they go home and log onto a
YourSherpa Web site. Either way, YourSherpa shoppers are given the
option of picking up the items at the mall or having them wrapped
and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, mall owners get no cut of the sale, as the proceeds
go entirely to the merchant whose store sells the product.
According to Shannon Haslund, vice president of operations for
Clixnmortar, the compensation details could change later. But for
now, mall owners are operating the kiosks primarily to generate
foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Haslund said FastFrog had been in tests at two Atlanta malls
since November, while a test run of YourSherpa.com began in
December in Atlanta's Lenox Square Mall, with one retailer, FAO
Schwarz. Based on the success of both programs, the company hopes
to roll them out nationally by the end of the year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Condon, manager of the FAO Schwarz in the Lenox Square
Mall, said YourSherpa had been ``tremendously valuable'' to the
store. Nearly all of the 700 shoppers who picked up a scanning
device from the YourSherpa kiosk have made purchases. The average
YourSherpa order, Condon said, was between $180 and $200, compared
with about $60 for an average store order.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he said, no merchandise had been returned from
YourSherpa purchases, compared with an average return rate of about
8 percent for store purchases. ``People don't have to finalize the
purchase right then,'' Condon said. ``It gives you a little more
time to decide. And you're not constrained by how much you can
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   General Growth Properties, the nation's second-largest mall
developer, is also moving quickly to capitalize on the Internet,
according to John Bucksbaum, the company's chief executive. ``We
were fairly certain that the Internet wouldn't result in our
demise, since we didn't think people would quit going out to do
their shopping,'' he said. ``So we asked, 'How can we turn this
into an opportunity?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was Mallibu.com. The Web site will eventually link to
retailers in each of the company's 136 malls, allowing shoppers to
buy goods online directly from those retailers and have them
dropped off by a delivery service. Mallibu, which will begin
offering transactions online in June, also enables General Growth
to capitalize on one of the Internet's strengths: data tracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon knows more about one customer after one trip than we do
about a person who comes in year after year,'' Bucksbaum said. By
tracking purchases online and obtaining e-mail addresses through
registrations, he said, ``we'll be able to e-mail a person about
new items coming into the store, or sales.''
</P>
<P>
   General Growth will charge retailers an amount not yet
determined for plugging into the malls' Mallibu.com Internet
systems, which are being installed, but it will not take a
commission from each sale. Still, the company could benefit from
any incremental Web sales, Bucksbaum said, since General Growth,
like other mall developers, takes between 4 percent and 8 percent
of a retailer's total sales beyond a certain level.
</P>
<P>
   According to Elaine Rubin, chairwoman of Shop.org, an Internet
retailing trade group, the efforts of Simon and General Growth
Properties ``are enlightening many other folks in the real estate
business.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes nonmall shopping centers. According to Charlotte
Ellis, senior vice president of Konover Property Trust, one of the
nation's largest developers of shopping centers that are not
enclosed malls, the company has begun to install high-speed
Internet lines in its 152 retail centers across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Konover plans to offer free Internet service
by year-end to users who agree to have their local shopping center
serve as their home page. Ellis said the border of the user's
screen would probably include advertisements and links to those
local retailers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers might eventually order goods from the local retailers,
she said, and then pick them up or have them delivered. And while
Konover is passing along some of the costs of the program to its
retailers, the company is making a ``large'' undisclosed investment
upfront to start things off. ``In the meantime, it immediately sets
us apart from our competition,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort also continues to stretch the notion of Internet
shopping into something that few thought it would be even six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping really hasn't changed much in 5,000 years,'' Ellis
said. ``We know there are going to be some big changes because of
the Internet, but ultimately it'll all be about saving time.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   Related Sites
</P>
<P>
   Simon Property Group: http://www.simon.com
</P>
<P>
   General Growth Properties: http://www.generalgrowth.com
</P>
<P>
   Shop.org: http://www.shop.org
</P>
<P>
   Konover Property Trust: http://www.konovertrust.com
</P>
<P>
   YourSherpa.com: http://www.yoursherpa.com
</P>
<P>
   FastFrog.com: http://www.fastfrog.com
</P>
<P>
   Mallibu: http://www.mallibu.com
</P>
<P>
   Clixnmortar: http://www.clixnmortar.com
</P>
<P>
   TenantConnect.net: http://www.tenantconnect.net
</P>
