<HEADLINE>
MONOPOLY HELPS SEND YOUR E-MAIL, FOR FREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX PHAM   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMERYVILLE, Calif. _ One of the Internet's biggest monopolies is
a little outfit called Sendmail. Its software powers more than 75
percent of all e-mail servers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And there's nothing the Justice Department can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Sendmail's core software is free. It always has
been, from the day in 1979 that graduate student Eric Allman wrote
the program in the computer science department at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine today, but before Sendmail came around, there
were islands of separate computer systems that had no way of
``talking'' to each other.
</P>
<P>
   To send a message to someone on a different system, a person had
to get up and move to a computer that was hooked into the other
system. Sendmail became the glue that pieced all these networks
together.
</P>
<P>
   The program became so popular that Allman found himself spending
all of his time answering questions from Sendmail users.
Eventually, he became so swamped with queries that in the late
1980s he set up an organization of volunteers, Sendmail.org, to
help out.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Allman never made a dime from Sendmail, apart
from the occassional speaking engagement. But after years of giving
free support on his own time to Sendmail users, many of whom were
Fortune 500 companies, Allman decided to try to scrape enough money
together to give himself a salary and hire a couple of engineers to
improve the software. Hat in hand, Allman asked half a dozen large
companies that used Sendmail to donate $50,000 each to the project.
Nearly all refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies all said, `Why should we pay for something
that's free?' It was the tragedy of the commons,'' Allman recalled
with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Allman then ran into a former colleague, Greg Olsen. A
gregarious graduate of Cornell University and a former Boston taxi
driver, Olsen listened to Allman's story and concluded that there
was a business opportunity in Sendmail. But Allman insisted that
the core Sendmail software remain a free product and that its
source code continue to be available to everyone, very much like
way the Linux operating system is distributed.
</P>
<P>
   So in March 1998, the two came up with Sendmail Inc., a
``hybrid'' company.
</P>
<P>
   Plain vanilla versions of Sendmail remain free of charge and are
supported by Sendmail.org, a band of seven core volunteers
connected via a server in Allman's Berkeley home.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sendmail Inc. sells customized, souped-up,
easy-to-use versions of Sendmail software. It also sells support
and technical services, such as software installation and
trouble-shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen and Allman predicted the company would employ a maximum of
50 people. But Sendmail has more than 160 employees and is still
growing. Olsen is chief executive, still using the people skills he
developed as a Beantown taxi driver. Allman spends his days as
chief technical officer, happily tinkering with the Sendmail
program.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in Sendmail's seemingly unfettered growth: the
explosion of e-mail. About 3.4 trillion e-mails were sent in 1998,
according to rough estimates by eMarketer, a technology research
firm in New York City. That's about 9.4 billion messages a day, the
vast majority of which go through servers running Sendmail.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers could only have grown last year, because the number
of e-mailboxes spiked 73 percent, to 569.2 million, from 333.5
million in 1998, according to Messaging Online, an industry
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Though not yet profitable, Sendmail has attracted $53 million in
funding from the likes of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Private
Equity; Bill Joy and Andy Bechtolsheim, cofounders of Sun
Microsystems Inc.; and Eric Schmidt, chief executive of Novell.
</P>
<P>
   All of this amuses Allman, who sports a ``rat tail,'' over a
foot of neatly braided hair that hangs from the nape of his neck.
Allman said he never expected to be one of the many dot-coms of
Silicon Valley. He had even decided to locate his company in
Emeryville, nestled just south of Berkeley, because he ``wanted to
talk about things other than our stock options.''
</P>
<P>
   Confesses Allman, ``I haven't really structured my life to get
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-25-00 1047EDT &QL;
</P>
