<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNO-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM'S LOSING NO SLEEP OVER DOT-COMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BETH HEALY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, bragging rights went to the venture capitalists
with the longest lists of dot-coms waiting to go public. Now, the
bragging about IPO potential has quieted significantly.
</P>
<P>
   William Thorndike Jr. is one VC who hasn't had to change his
tune over the past few weeks. He and his colleagues at Boston's
Housatonic Partners _ ``value'' guys of the venture arena _ are
singing the same tune they have had since starting out in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find no flashy consumer Web sites in Housatonic's
portfolio. No online peddlers of pet food or lipstick. No petroleum
exchanges or auction sites. And the firm is rarely dependent on
IPOs to cash out of its investments.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Thorndike wasn't gnashing his teeth, as some rivals
were, during the Nasdaq's vicious plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reasonably well insulated from those moves,'' he says.
It's welcome payback for resisting the dot-com bandwagon, he adds.
``The pendulum swung hard in the other direction for quite some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Housatonic's main fare might be called humdrum in technology
circles. There's roadside rescue for cell-phone customers, cable
TV, and nonhazardous liquid waste management. One of its greatest
successes was a file storage company. That's right, storage of good
old paper files.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Thorndike says, ``at some point, you exceed your
filing cabinet's capacity. So you put it in a box and send it
away.''
</P>
<P>
   These businesses have one thing in common that Housatonic looks
for in all its investments: a regular fee stream, or ``recurring
revenues,'' as Thorndike says. Whether it's TV watchers paying
cable bills or restaurant owners paying waste haulers to clean
their grease traps each week, it's money in the door on a
dependable basis. The firm likes real revenues and customer lists,
not wish lists on how sales and profits might materialize.
</P>
<P>
   As you might imagine, this rules out fresh-faced start-ups.
Housatonic tends to back later-stage companies. And it often
finances buyouts, where it takes investment control of a company
and gets directly involved with management, with an eye to growing
the business and reselling it, Tom Lee-style.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely does Housatonic consider an IPO as an exit from an
investment; the norm is a sale. Last year, for example, it sold the
paper storage company First American Records Management of San
Jose, Calif., for nearly $41.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent investments show that Housatonic is willing to
invest in newer technology, if the revenue stream is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the firm put $3 million into USData Centers.com, a
Web-hosting company, in a deal led by BancBoston Capital. The
investment was somewhat smaller than Housatonic's usual range of $5
million to $10 million. But Housatonic liked the monthly fees that
go with hosting Web sites. The deal came through an angel investor
and cable entrepreneur, Bob Fanch. And Housatonic had done deals
with BancBoston before.
</P>
<P>
   Two other recent deals include a niche publisher in Washington,
the Governance Institute, and a second-tier player in the DSL
market, bringing high-speed Internet access to suburban areas in
central California.
</P>
<P>
   The latter company, Arrival Communications, is a start-up, a
company that's just acquired a license to switch existing Internet
clients to DSL. Says Thorndike, ``Telecom is an area where we're
willing to go in slightly earlier than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   If Housatonic's portfolio doesn't seem to have a lot of zing,
its returns sure do. The firm is on track to hand its investors a
return exceeding 60 percent for the sixth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Housatonic oversees a modest $200 million in two funds. A third
is being mulled for later this year. But that doesn't mean the five
partners are setting out to raise a billion-dollar portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   When you raise big piles of money, you've got to put them to
work. The venture firms that have amassed mammoth funds of late
will be facing significant pressure to invest that money both fast
and wisely. And their investors may have to get used to less lavish
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in the riskier sectors of the venture market,
Thorndike says financing deals were falling apart. ``There were
term sheets all over America being revisited,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-25-00 1044EDT &QL;
</P>
