u a BC-CPT-CAR-INTERNET26-CO     04-27 2392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CAR-INTERNET26-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Six easy steps to Web-shop for a car &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They see you long before you see them,
darting out from the shadows beneath the ``Buy Here, Pay Here''
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Are those really Ray-Bans, or do car salesmen get some kind of
deal on sucker-seeking lenses?
</P>
<P>
   In their quest for a detour around this daunting dash to the
showroom door, millions of car buyers are turning to the Internet.
The numbers are growing by the month, with nearly 60 percent of all
buyers doing at least some Web research before taking the plunge,
according to one survey. That's up from 25 percent just two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the auto industry agrees that the Internet will
revolutionize car sales and that the number of Web-surfing buyers
will continue to rise. But the number of people who actually buy
cars directly through the Internet is still tiny, less than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, for all the hoopla about cybersales, automobiles
are not like books or compact discs or holiday fruit baskets.
There's more paperwork, for one thing. Plus, people still want to
drive before they buy. Even if you're comfortable with the idea of
pointing, clicking and waiting for UPS to drop an Oldsmobile on
your stoop, it's not quite that simple _ particularly if you have a
trade-in, if you're financing the car or if you're not absolutely
certain which car you want.
</P>
<P>
   But what Internet auto-buying services advertise is still
impressive: Find a car, negotiate a price and get a head start on
figuring out how to pay for it. It was enough to entice me, and I'm
one of those odd people who once enjoyed the joust.
</P>
<P>
   I sold cars briefly during my wayward youth and for years
afterward fancied myself something of an expert. I had fun turning
the car seller's script around whenever I went car shopping. I'd
rush up, shake a salesman's hand and say, ``What do I have to do to
make you sell me a car today?''
</P>
<P>
   My expertise let me make some great deals. Unfortunately, they
were almost always on awful cars. (My wife once asked on the way
home: ``Why does this car already sound like it's falling apart?''
The answer was soon obvious: It was falling apart.)
</P>
<P>
   I finally started buying Hondas, which so far have lived up to
their fail-safe reputation. This introduced me to a new negotiating
technique. I learned to pay whatever the dealer wanted, even if it
was more than the sticker price. Even if it was more than Donald
Trump's annual hairstyling bill.
</P>
<P>
   This time, I decided to try keeping an open mind and a closed
wallet. I started with a stroll through the Web's virtual showroom
for reliable but possibly less-dear Honda alternatives. Economic
reality helped. I just got a new sport utility a few months ago,
but my daughter snatched it up and took it off to college. She did
not take the payment book.
</P>
<P>
   So there'd be no need for my PC to swap cookies with some
hoity-toity microchip at Lexus or BMW. I set my Web browser on
``cheap'' and began the hunt. I started at a site called
CarPrices.com. It was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Like many sites, CarPrices offers lots of info-choices. Click a
make and model, and you can get prices (what the dealer supposedly
pays, as well as the sticker price), including a breakdown of
options. You can also get a list of standard equipment for each
sub-model and find out what comes in option packages.
</P>
<P>
   There are reviews of most models, plus a list of rebates and
factory-subsidized lease deals. There's also a search form for used
cars. There's even a form that CarPrices promises to forward to
dealers who want to bid for your business.
</P>
<P>
   For that, you have to put down a $50 deposit by typing in a
credit card number. I wasn't ready to think about deposits just
yet. I checked a few more sites, including manufacturers and online
magazines. The volume of information was staggering, and a good
deal of it even appeared useful. Many of the reviews were more
critical and detailed than those found in traditional ``car buff'
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   With a few clicks on ``print,'' I soon had a neat pile of specs,
pictures and stories. I was able to compare features, crash-test
results and, at least to some extent, reputations for reliability.
A list of prime candidates emerged swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   By lucky coincidence, it was time for the annual Fort Lauderdale
International Auto Show, which gave me a chance for some
seat-of-the-pants impressions. The limitations of shop-at-home auto
comparison became obvious the moment I banged my head getting into
one of the cars on my list. That was no digital headache.
</P>
<P>
   Some cars were easier to get into but made me eager to get out.
My computer-room chair turned out to be a lot more comfortable (and
wider) than several driver's seats. A number of price-leading
models that looked sharp in Web scans looked shabby in the metal.
Some appeared to have been painted with a roller and upholstered in
material that resembled a pair of velour pants I threw away in
1977. One car had a trunk opening the size of a mail slot.
</P>
<P>
   So although I hadn't so much as turned a key, my choices were
going down. And the prices were going up. I focused on two cars
that I felt most comfortable squeezing into, physically as well as
financially: the Volkswagen Golf and the Mazda Protege.
</P>
<P>
   My research made me lean toward the Golf for a couple of
reasons: It's a hatchback, which adds utility to a small car, and
it has standard anti-lock brakes. I like the idea of being able to
stop on rain-slick Interstate 95 before I slide under the
tractor-trailer up ahead. I decided to e-mail for a price on the
Golf and then drive one.
</P>
<P>
   For the price, I tried a service called Autobytel.com, which
claims to be No. 1 in online auto sales. In the first quarter of
this year, it claims $3.4 billion in sales through dealers, which
pay the service for sending customers their way. I found Autobytel
at a catch-all car site called Edmunds.com, which offers a range of
information and services similar to CarPrices.
</P>
<P>
   I filled out a detailed form, providing my e-mail address, my
phone number and information about the make and model I wanted.
Autobytel promised a call-back and price quote within 48 hours.
Meanwhile, I went to a dealership for a test drive and some
old-fashioned haggling.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter was home for a visit, so I took her along. I wanted
her opinion, and I was hoping she'd like the Golf enough to swap my
sport utility back. The Golf seemed well-made and nicely finished,
but we felt a little cramped, and I wanted more power. My daughter
still wanted my car. The salesman was professional and polite but
sensed our lack of commitment. He let us out the door without
offering any inducement other than the sticker price: $17,925.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I got a phone message from a salesman at another
dealership, referred by Autobytel. He said he wanted to talk about
what I wanted in a car. He did not leave a price. I called back and
told him I'd given all the information requested. He suggested I
drop by and see if I liked one of the cars in his stock. He clearly
didn't want to give me a price unless I pressed for it. I told him
I'd look around and let him know.
</P>
<P>
   That left my other choice, the Mazda. My wife and I went to a
dealer, drove two of them (a standard model and an upscale version)
and were pretty much bowled over. The car easily passed the head,
trunk and butt tests. This time, it was easier getting a price than
a car.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman couldn't find one in stock with anti-lock brakes,
and I wouldn't consider a car without them. And even with all my
computer-aided research, I'd missed an important detail: The
upgraded brakes were available only as part of a $1,580 option
package on the most expensive model. I'd have to buy the moon roof
to get better brakes. (What sense does that make? None, of course,
unless you're selling cars rather than buying them.)
</P>
<P>
   The salesman did make an offer: $17,150 (reduced from $17,870),
assuming a car with the right options could be found. I'd also get
a $1,000 factory rebate, bringing my price down to $16,150 _ below
the dealer's cost, which Web sites agreed was $16,471.
</P>
<P>
   (No need to cry for the dealer. Since my rebate was coming from
the factory, he would make nearly $700 off me immediately. He'd
also get the ``holdback'' _ a percentage of the cost that car
manufacturers refund to dealers after a car is sold. That's one way
dealers can sell a car ``at invoice'' but still make a profit. Most
Web sites note the holdback. In the Protege's case, it's 2 percent.
Manufacturers occasionally offer additional dealer incentives on
some models, usually slow sellers. Some Web sites note these, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Since the first dealer didn't have an actual car to sell me yet,
and I was pretty sure I wanted a Protege, I decided to see if the
Internet would help me find one. It did, and at a better price.
</P>
<P>
   This time, I tried a site called CarPoint.com, which offers its
own quotes-by-e-mail service. The service, free to consumers,
offered a choice of two dealers in my ZIP code. The not-so-small
print warned that really good deals might not be available on the
most in-demand models. Luckily, I couldn't afford any of those.
</P>
<P>
   I filled out a form and clicked the send button. I got a call in
under an hour from Richie, another dealer's ``Internet sales
manager.'' He told me he'd search his inventory for the car I
wanted and get back to me with a price at 10 a.m. the next day. I
told him I'd already started looking and pricing similar cars. He
said he was sure he'd satisfy me.
</P>
<P>
   He called back right at the appointed time to tell me he had a
car. It was white (which I liked), and it had an additional option
(a $250 cassette tape player, which I didn't need). He gave me a
price right off the bat: $16,788. With rebate, it came to $15,788.
That's against a sticker price of $18,120. I drove over to take a
look.
</P>
<P>
   (If I'd had a trade-in, I'd have lingered on the Web to find out
the wholesale value of my car to help prepare for negotiations. If
I wanted to finance the car, I'd also have been able to compare
finance rates from the manufacturer, banks and other lenders. Plus
use an on-line calculator to figure my loan payments.)
</P>
<P>
   When I got to the dealer's lot, the Ray-Ban brigade was waiting.
But they cleared a path when I mentioned Richie's name. He handed
me the key and let me drive off to make certain the car was what I
wanted. It was. I didn't see any point in further browsing. I
signed the papers and came back later that afternoon to pick up my
new car.
</P>
<P>
   So I did it: I bought a car online. Sort of. What I really did
is save some time and, maybe, some money. Has anyone come up with a
better use for the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) CAR-SHOPPING WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   _ Big catch-all sites: It's impossible to catalog them, because
they're growing and changing by the week. They include
Kelleybluebook.com, Edmunds.com, Carprices.com, CarPoint.com,
Cars.com and many more. Most include information about used as well
as new cars. Most let you research nearly all makes and models for
features, crash ratings, driving impressions and price. There are
also optional for-fee services, such as a title search, that may
show whether a specific car has been returned as a lemon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Potential drawbacks: A recent survey found that some dealer
prices listed on these sites were inaccurate, possibly leading
buyers to overpay. Other information can also be wrong or
misleading, so it's useful to compare several sites for
discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Manufacturer sites: Like nearly all businesses, car companies
have their own Web sites. Most are easy to find (Chevrolet.com,
Honda.com). All include up-to-date information about rebates, lease
deals and special finance rates. Many offer quotes-by-e-mail. Among
the most sophisticated, GMBuyPower allows consumers to check dealer
inventory anywhere in the country, then e-mail for prices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dealer sites: You can link to them from manufacturer sites or
look for the Web addresses in local car ads. An increasing number
of dealer sites allow you to search their inventory for a car with
the options and colors you want. Some even include prices _ but
they're almost always sticker. E-mail to find out if the dealer's
interested in making an offer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online buying services: Many, like Autobytel.com, are
essentially dealer-referral services. When you e-mail for a quote,
you're giving your name, phone number and e-mail address to a car
salesman, who will call you. Then you handle any negotiations.
Other services, such as CarsDirect.com and DriveOff.com, are
brokers that promise a more hands-on role in finding a car and
negotiating a firm price on your behalf. For that, you'll probably
have to put down a deposit. At least one on-line service,
Priceline.com, lets you submit an offer to a number of dealers
anonymously. If a dealer accepts your price and you buy the car,
you pay Priceline $50.
</P>
<P>
   _ Advantages: A J.D. Power survey of dealers released this month
found that consumers who used an on-line buying service saved an
average of $490 on new cars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Potential drawbacks: While most services are ``free'' to the
buyer, the dealer usually pays the service a fee when a sale is
made. The services also pay Web site operators a bounty for each
sale. Somebody has to pay for all this.
</P>
<P>
   DOS AND DON'TS FOR ONLINE CAR SHOPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Do:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take plenty of time to browse the Web; it's faster than
driving to dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check several catch-all sites and consider using more than one
quote service.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look at the manufacturer's Web site for up-to-date information
on rebates or discounted financing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect calls from salespeople if you use a referral service.
</P>
<P>
   Don't:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to buy a car without leaving home. You may find a
dealer willing to deliver, but you'll probably want to see and
drive several models before buying.
</P>
<P>
   _ Believe everything you read. Prices can be wrong, rebates
lapsed, models mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assume that because you got the price over the Internet that
it's the lowest possible.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
