r s BC-BKN-BUTCH-CARTER-HNS &LR;      04-27 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BUTCH-CARTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUTCH CARTER, QUICK WITH A LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Butch Carter is definitely a wimp, certifiably a pest, probably
a fool and quite possibly a liar and a phony. Other than that, his
prospects for a long and fruitful coaching career are excellent.
</P>
<P>
   So sue me.
</P>
<P>
   Carter certainly has been known to sue for less. Just before the
NBA playoffs began, Carter hit New York Knicks forward Marcus Camby
with a $5 million defamation lawsuit. Carter claimed that was the
damage done his reputation because Camby uttered the words ``he's a
liar'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   Which immediately raises the question: What reputation? Carter
coaches the Toronto Raptors, and he's not even the most prominent
Carter on the team. As near as anybody can tell, Butch Carter's job
amounts to keeping a seat warm on the bench while Vince Carter does
all the Raptors' heavy lifting.
</P>
<P>
   North America wouldn't know or care that Butch Carter exists if
not for a lawsuit that gives frivolous a bad name. It seems Camby
told a New York newspaper last week that just before a trade to the
Knicks two seasons ago, he and John Wallace had received assurances
they would be the cornerstone of the Toronto franchise. The
assurances, Camby said, came from one Butch Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Camby did call Butch Carter a liar. He added, ``No one likes
him, and no one wants to play for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sticks and stones. Any self-respecting man would respond
in one of two ways. He either ignores the words, or he offers his
side of the story. He doesn't run to the courthouse like a little
boy tattling to mommy because the kid next door gave him a boo-boo.
Butch Carter dropped the suit on Tuesday, which obligates no one to
forget his foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm not going to allow my three sons to wake up and see in the
national media that I'm a liar,'' Butch Carter said the other day,
insisting he would drop the matter in return for an apology.
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   First, Butch Carter's relationship with his sons is doomed if
their opinion of him can be undermined by the bitter words of a
scorned player.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Butch Carter later gave the ``my three sons''
explanation the reek of insincerity by crowing that he managed to
take the heat off his players entering the first playoff series in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Butch Carter is hardly above reproach when it comes to
slinging mud at convenient targets. When Carter isn't making
allegations _ so far unsubstantiated, two decades after the fact or
fiction _ that Indiana coach Bob Knight is a racist, he is
threatening to smear Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drafted Marcus; we know a lot about Marcus that's bad,''
Butch Carter said, the slime dripping from his words. ``If I wanted
to open that file up...''
</P>
<P>
   While Butch Carter was peddling nonsense, Jeff Van Gundy went
about his job of coaching the Knicks. Van Gundy put in a
double-teaming defense in a victory that rendered the only relevant
Carter on the Raptors, Vince, as useless as a thong bikini on the
North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto players would have to be blind, deaf and too dumb to
spell IQ if they didn't pick up on the panic their coach is trying
to pass off as either gamesmanship or righteous indignation. How is
a visiting team supposed to withstand an environment as hostile as
Madison Square Garden when the coach comes down with a case of
rabbit ears?
</P>
<P>
   Players aren't about to follow a coach like that into battle.
They'll shoot him in the back when he's not looking just to give
themselves a fighting chance. NBA players and coaches alike spot
and exploit weakness the way a shark senses blood in the water.
Push back or be pushed around forever. Put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Karl Malone characterized the new generation of
NBA players as ``knuckleheads.'' Imagine the mocking laughter that
would have ensued if Malone had been slapped with a class-action
defamation suit.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of buffoon territory that Butch Carter has
staked out for himself. P.J. Carlesimo didn't do this kind of
caterwauling after he got choked by Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter should have thought through the strategy of filing
frivolous defamation suits a little more carefully. He may find
himself on the receiving end of a legitimate defamation suit soon
enough. He recently finished a book alleging that while he was
playing at Indiana, he heard Knight direct racial slurs at a
teammate. The implication was that the teammate was Isiah Thomas,
who vehemently denies the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Knight subsequently offered an explanation of why Butch Carter
may not be the most reliable of witnesses. It seems that Butch
Carter fell out of favor after scamming the Indiana athletic
department out of more than $1,000 in long-distance calls. When
Knight heard about it, he told Butch Carter to never, ever ask for
help in landing a job.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter is going to need help landing a job soon enough. He
is finished as a viable NBA coach before he established any
credentials worth mentioning. The day he commands respect is the
day players take to a coach who is definitely a wimp, certifiably a
pest, probably a fool and quite possibly a liar and a phony.
</P>
</TEXT>
