<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-VISAS-Q&AMP;A26-     04-27 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-VISAS-Q&AMP;A26-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    PROTECTIONS FOR U.S. TECH WORKERS LAG, CONGRESSMAN SAYS
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Protections for American tech workers are in play
as the House and Senate near a decision on whether to boost the
number of visas granted to highly skilled foreigners, such as
computer programmers and electrical engineers.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies say they desperately need the foreign
employees to continue expanding rapidly in this time of low
unemployment. But the three main bills now moving through Congress
have significant differences, and it is not clear which will emerge
as the final legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Technology Worker Temporary Relief Act appears to give
high-tech businesses exactly what they want _ an unlimited supply
of H-1B visas for foreign workers over the next three years. Yet
industry has responded coolly to the bill, written by Rep. Lamar
Smith, R-Texas, and approved this month by the House immigration
subcommittee he chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry spokesmen say it is filled with anti-business
provisions, such as language requiring companies seeking H-1B visas
to prove they have increased their U.S. work force and raised
salaries for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   They also object to a requirement that companies seeking the
visas file public reports on their foreign workers, including their
salaries. They also oppose a provision that would give the visas
only to full-time workers earning at least $40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the bill would expand visas only if the Labor
Department issues long-delayed regulations for the H-1B program.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies generally are backing a bipartisan bill
introduced by Reps. David Dreier, R-Calif., and Zoe Lofgren,
D-Calif. Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, is another co-sponsor of that
measure, which would boost the number of H-1B visas to 200,000
annually over three years. Companies would have to pay a $1,000 fee
per visa, with those funds going towards scholarships for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies also like a Senate bill that already has cleared
the Judiciary Committee. That one would boost the H-1B visas to
195,000 annually over three years. This bill would have an
education fee of $500 per visa.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Congress temporarily hiked the number of H-1B
visas from an annual limit of 65,000. This fiscal year's cap stands
at 115,000. If Congress does not act, the cap will drop to 107,500
next fiscal year, and revert to 65,000 in fiscal 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Here are excerpts from an interview with Smith:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last month, you introduced a bill to give the H-1B program a
one-time annual boost of 45,000 visas. But this month, you
introduced a much broader bill granting unlimited visas. Why the
switch?
</P>
<P>
   A. The primary reason was because of recent figures we got from
the (Immigration and Naturalization Service). The demand for H-1B
visas is running about 50,000 ahead of last year, which was more
than we expected.
</P>
<P>
   We also didn't know until after that first bill that the INS had
miscounted ... and in fact had handed out 21,000 more visas than
they should have last year.
</P>
<P>
   So you had the combination of 71,000 visas projected greater
demand this year over last, so we just decided to allow for those
numbers. ... We thought that by also having a balanced bill that
benefitted workers, it would be acceptable to not have a cap.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do you think high-tech businesses object to your latest
bill?
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, we've gotten a lot of support, but (some people)
seem to oppose it. I'm disappointed that they don't support a
balanced bill. It seems like they care more about the industry than
American workers. And I think that is regrettable.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In your bill, you require the Labor Department to issue and
implement regulations for the H-1B program that has been in effect
for two years. Why has the Clinton administration has been slow to
develop these regulations?
</P>
<P>
   A. The 1998 bill had a balance, where we made an effort to meet
the needs of the high-tech industry, but also protect the interests
of the American worker. But half of that legislation has never been
implemented and there is absolutely no good excuse for the White
House not to have issued regulations yet. I don't know what excuse
there could possibly be.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the Dreier-Lofgren bill more likely to make it through the
full House than your bill?
</P>
<P>
   A. I've talked to David Dreier and ... he supports (my bill) and
hopes it gets out of subcommittee, which it did.
</P>
<P>
   I believe (my) bill probably will be the vehicle until we get to
the House floor. The reason is, it's a more narrow bill. We crafted
it so that the Judiciary Committee would have jurisdiction over the
bill and we wouldn't need to have it referred to several other
committees, as the Dreier bill has been. We're really trying to
streamline the process.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will the final version incorporate some of Dreier's
provisions?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's certainly possible. We have two options: something could
be added to this underlying bill on the House floor, or we can move
a separate piece of legislation that, perhaps, adds some of the
educational provisions (that the Dreier-Lofgren bill includes).
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can your bill and Hatch's Senate bill be reconciled by a
House-Senate conference committee?
</P>
<P>
   A. Quite frankly, by our having no limits and letting the free
market determine the number of these high-tech visas, that
eliminates a lot of the details of the Senate bill. (Hatch) still
has some education provisions in there, but like I say, either in
conference or on the House floor may be where to address some of
those provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why not hold off legislation until October when the National
Science Foundation is scheduled to release its study of high-tech
job needs?
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, we've already reached the cap this year on the
high-tech visas and quite frankly, my perception was that there was
a sense of urgency in the industry itself. As a practical matter,
it was going to be difficult to wait until after next October.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you expect some form of H-1B visa legislation to pass this
year?
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh yes, very easily. ... The question is what will be the
final shape of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.house.gov/lamarsmith
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
