<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE0425-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Language translation sites inexact but helpful
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Medan europeer ofta kan tala flera sprak flytande, de
flesta amerikaner ar okunniga i andra sprak.
</P>
<P>
   If that Swedish doesn't make sense to you, you're not alone. The
translation is: ``While Europeans often are fluent in several
languages, most Americans are ignorant of other languages.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be the World Wide Web, but when it comes to reading
information in other languages, most of us are at a loss. Even if
you took Spanish or French in school, most of us are awkward at
best when it comes to following the conversational language you are
likely to find on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   There is help for that, right on the Web. If you're an
experienced user, you probably know that there are free online
translation services available. One of the best known is called
BabelFish, a service provided by the AltaVista Web site
(www.altavista.com). You can either click on the link called
``translation'' on that page, or go directly to
babelfish.altavista.digital.com/cgi-bin/translate?.
</P>
<P>
   Just as is true with some of the other, less well known sites
that we'll visit in this column, you need to manage expectations
when you use the service. Don't expect the sort of letter-perfect
translation you'd get from a professional translator. This
translation is done by software, and the results can vary between
pretty good and really funny. But the text, in most cases, will be
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of BabelFish, you'll have a choice of French,
German, Italian, Portuguese and Spanish. You can translate from
English into one of those languages, or from any of those languages
into English.
</P>
<P>
   Some other sites offer a broader selection of languages. One is
Inter-Tran, located at www.tranexp.com:2000/InterTran. There are
too many languages available here to list them all but _ besides
those found at AltaVista _ you can add Swedish, Dutch, Finnish,
Japanese, Russian, Icelandic and Croatian, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   At both sites, you can either type or paste in the text you want
to translate or list the URL for the Web page that needs
translating.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a quick laugh _ and also a demonstration of the
relative lack of sophistication of the software _ translate an easy
sentence from English to another language and then use the
translator to return that translation to English. You'll see why
these services would not be good enough for a final translation of
an important business letter or a marriage proposal.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to learn a little bit about the language and to
try it yourself if you already have some skill in that particular
language. The Web also offers online dictionaries in other
languages that can help you over the rough spots. One to check out
is the Logos dictionary at www.logos.it/dictionary/owa/sp?lg &QC; EN.
You'll find a wide selection of languages and can use the
dictionary to translate both words and brief phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Also at that site you'll find games such as crossword puzzles
and anagrams that can help make learning or practicing another
language fun.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, instead of a translation, you are preparing for a trip
to another country and would like to be able to speak and
understand a few basic phrases in the language. Knowing even a
little of the host country's language can open up people's hearts
and make for a more enjoyable trip.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent site for this type of work is called Foreign
Languages for Travelers and can be found at
www.travlang.com/languages/.
</P>
<P>
   There's a broad selection of languages to choose from here, more
than can be listed. Once you settle on a language, you can take
easy online lessons that teach you the basics: how to say hello and
goodbye, ask for directions (understanding them when spoken fast in
an unfamiliar language is another matter), book a room in a hotel
or order a simple meal.
</P>
<P>
   One feature that is especially helpful _ since words in another
language often follow different rules for pronunciation than in
English _ is the use of audio so that you can hear a native speaker
say the word or phrase you are learning. You'll also find quizzes
that test you on your new-found knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-24-00 1036EDT &QL;
</P>
