<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-IRS-GAO28-COX     04-27 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-GAO28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS WORKERS CLEARED OF CRIMINAL WRONGDOING
 &HT;    390&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than two years after a Senate hearing aired
sensational charges of abuses by the Internal Revenue Service,
congressional investigators have been unable to corroborate
allegations of criminal wrongdoing by federal tax collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office, in a report written a year
ago and made partially public this week, said it could not back up
accusations that IRS officials canceled tax debts for corporations
in return for jobs or that they initiated criminal probes against
taxpayers based solely on personal vendettas.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited numerous shortcomings in IRS operations, but it
blamed the ``complexity and vagueness'' of the tax code, not
illegal actions by officials.
</P>
<P>
   The findings by the GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, have
been a source of some embarrassment for Republicans, who sponsored
IRS hearings in 1997 to spark a major overhaul of the IRS that was
enacted the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The reform was based on two sets of hearings that outlined
problems at the agency, stressed Ginny Flynn, spokesperson for
Senate Finance Committee chairman William V. Roth Jr., R-Del. The
aide noted that the GAO investigation, which had been ordered by
Roth, covered only one of those forums.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn added that the IRS itself had issued reports conceding
that many liens, levies and seizures had been carried out
inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Since passage of the 1998 IRS reform to strengthen taxpayer
protections, tax audits have been cut back, property seizures have
been reduced by 98 percent, and some observers have even suggested
that the IRS has now become too lenient toward recalcitrant
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard back from constituents that they have noticed a
difference at the IRS,'' Flynn said. ``I think between this law and
(IRS) Commissioner (Charles O.) Rossotti, the agency is beginning
to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers of the tax collecting agency argue that the GAO
report has been misread as a complete clean bill of health for the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminal behavior has always been rare in government
agencies,'' said Pete Sepp, spokesman for the National Taxpayers
Union, a private non-partisan watchdog group. ``It's one thing to
say 'great, we don't have employees involved in extortion.' But
what about hounding small business that they think are
disrespectful?''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS ``whistle-blowers'' who spoke against their agency at
the Senate hearings have stood by their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't have made such allegations if I weren't
prepared to prove them,'' Michael Ayala, an IRS worker at the
Atlanta regional office, said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He had detailed allegations of cases that were closed
improperly, favoritism by a supervisor toward an employee because
of a personal liaison, as well as improper use of a chart that
rated IRS agents by the number of property seizures they made
through the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   In these and several cases, the GAO did not dispute the facts,
but also found no criminal wrongdoing. The allegations were based
``on an incomplete awareness of the total circumstances surrounding
the matters,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said he has been the target for retaliation since the GAO
findings were made public. ``It certainly leaves us out hanging in
the wind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That view was also expressed by Ginny Jarvis, a New York worker
for the IRS, who had alleged that the agency overlooked millions of
dollars in ``laundered'' funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I provided in excess of 100 pages of documentations to the
investigative reporters for GAO,'' she said. She said she now fears
retribution at her agency.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Servi
</P>
