Japan in 1947, the foreign ministry ousted him for his wartime
``insubordination,'' offering him a small pension.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Sugihara lived in obscurity, selling light bulbs.
Then, in 1969, Yehoshua Nishri, an Israeli diplomat based in Tokyo
and one of the refugees he had rescued, found him and aired his
deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Praised by the Israeli government as one of ``the righteous
among nations'' _ the phrase used for non-Jews who helped save Jews
in the Holocaust _ Sugihara won the same honors that had been
bestowed upon Wallenberg and German businessman Oskar Schindler.
</P>
<P>
   Born Jan. 1, 1900, Sugihara died in 1986, still all but unknown
in his native land. In the year before his death, 45 years after
his visas had saved our lives, Sugihara was asked why he did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were human beings and they needed help,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: U.S. Holocaust Museum, www.ushmm.org; Sugihara
Database, www.jewishgen.org/databases/sugihara.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is senior correspondent of Cox Newspapers in
Washington. His e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
