<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBIN-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROBERT TOBIN, PATRON OF THE ARTS, DIES AT 66 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CARMINA DANINI and NICOLE FOY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Robert Tobin, a nationally prominent patron of the
arts and renowned art collector, died Wednesday at North East
Baptist Hospital of complications of cancer and respiratory
failure. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   A multimillionaire who had been battling cancer for a decade,
Tobin was a tall man with a long, silver mane of hair. He was as
Texan as his Lucchese alligator boots. He prided himself in being a
yellow-dog Democrat and a inveterate Dallas Cowboys fan.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin was equally at home working on behalf of indigent children
as he was dealing with the staff of the Spoleto Festival of Two
Worlds in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   An inveterate collector, his collections reflected his main
interests: stage design, opera, theater, art, architecture and
books.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was a generous benefactor of the Metropolitan Opera
and Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Santa Fe Opera, Tobin
was more closely linked to San Antonio's McNay Art Museum. The
museum's world-class Collection of Theater Arts, was donated by
Tobin, who had been chairman of the board of trustees since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 20, Tobin became president of the Children's
Service Bureau. A few years later, the staunch supporter of serving
the health needs of San Antonio's poor became the youngest chairman
of the board of managers of the Bexar County Hospital District.
</P>
<P>
   A pitched battle over the location of a new medical school
soured his involvement in San Antonio public life more than 30
years ago. He wanted it closer to downtown, where the needy people
were.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues said Tobin's dedication to the issue was
so fierce that he felt scorned and dejected when the University of
Texas Board of Regents, after intense political wrangling, decided
to locate the school and a subsequent teaching hospital at its
current location in Northwest San Antonio. Shortly after the
decision, Tobin began to recede from San Antonio and turn instead
to New York and Santa Fe, N.M., where he also had homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse H. Oppenheimer, a lawyer and friend, said the medical
school experience changed Tobin's perception of his beloved
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely generous and civic-minded,'' he said. ``But
he became a little soured over the ordeal and of doing things in
San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his ties to the McNay remained strong. Included in his
donated Collection of Theatre Arts are original Broadway production
designs from ``My Fair Lady,'' ``South Pacific'' and ``West Side
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin also gave the McNay more than 8,000 books, many of them
quite rare, to establish the Tobin Library.
</P>
<P>
   The McNay's $1.5 million, two-story Tobin Wing, opened in 1984,
was a gift from Tobin's mother in honor of her late parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The books and items are dead objects. They will be awakened by
use,'' Tobin said shortly before the Tobin Wing opened.
</P>
<P>
   McNay director William J. Chiego said Wednesday: ``Robert Tobin
was an extraordinary friend of the museum, and many of us here feel
like we've lost our best friend. He was a rare individual who
wanted to share what he loved the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Tobin combined his epic collection of
20th-century American theater designs with his major collection of
30 American paintings in a gift to the McNay. Last year, he donated
his $3 million Russian theater design collection to the San Antonio
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's connection to the New York City cultural scene stemmed
mostly from his longtime involvement with the Metropolitan Opera.
His mother had served on the board of the opera and was a key
financier of seasonal productions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Tobin donated $1 million to the capital campaign to
renovate the Santa Fe Opera's amphitheater and grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``More important was the courage he showed,'' said John Crosby,
general director of the Santa Fe Opera. ``If we wanted to undertake
some experimental opera, he was the first to get behind the opera
and give it a push.''
</P>
<P>
   McNay trustee E.H. Corrigan of Laredo, Texas, a friend of
Tobin's for more than 40 years, said many of his closest friends
last saw him on his birthday, March 12.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1934, Robert Lynn Batts Tobin was the son of Edgar
Gardner Tobin, a World War I flying ace, and Margaret Batts,
daughter of Robert Lynn Batts, chief judge of the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, Edgar Tobin began taking aerial photographs of
potential oil fields in West Texas for the Humble Oil Co. That work
led to his founding the Tobin Aerial Mapping Co., which later
evolved into Tobin Aerial Surveys. Because it was the only company
of its kind, it made Tobin immensely wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Tobin was 19 and a sophomore at the University of Texas
at Austin when his father and aviation pioneer Tom Braniff were
killed in an airplane crash in Louisiana. Robert Tobin took over
the business and led it through unprecedented growth.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, a lifelong bachelor, is survived by his dog, Samantha,
and cousins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
