<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-ELIAN-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T LET THAT PHOTO CHANGE YOUR MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing. For use Tuesday, April 25, or
thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought Elian Gonzalez belonged with his father last
week, don't allow yourself to be swayed by that admittedly
heart-stopping picture of the armed federal agent confronting the
frightened little boy and the fisherman who had plucked him from
the water five months ago and who was still clinging to the kid,
literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Finger not on the trigger. Weapon pointing down. Arm reaching
out in a non-hostile manner. That's all worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   What were these eight agents supposed to do, tap on the door and
say, ``Can Elian come out to play?'' They had to be ready for
confrontation, given the hostile mood permeating Little Havana for
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``ELIAN SEIZED!'' read the headlines in newspapers across the
country. ``ELIAN SAVED!'' might have been more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what brought us to that moment. Remember what led to
the shocking but violence-free, three-minute operation that finally
extracted Elian from the home where he was essentially being held
hostage by his well-intentioned but misguided distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Not every episode in this made-for-television drama has been
captured on film, but remember that Elian has endured much more
traumatic experiences than even the Holy Saturday seizure. What's a
``soldier man'' with a gun when you've already seen your mother
drown?
</P>
<P>
   Sad as the death of Elizabeth Brotons was, let us not forget
that she came close to signing a death warrant for her son when
(without his father's knowledge) she took him along as she and more
than a dozen others boarded a rusty, battered, patched-up, 16-foot
aluminum boat on the shoreline of Cardenas, Cuba, and set off for
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   She was not on a valiant quest for freedom and a better way of
life for her little boy. She was escaping with her young boyfriend,
who had fled to Florida several months earlier but had returned to
Cuba because he missed his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   As I said in November, had Elian's mother made it to American
soil with her son, a case could have been made against her as an
unfit mother who had recklessly endangered her child's life.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't make it. The boat capsized and fell apart, and 11
of the 15 passengers eventually were swallowed by the sea. There
weren't any cameras around to capture that lengthy medley of
horrors, but rest assured those days of death at sea will bruise
Elian's psyche more deeply than the scary few minutes when he was
grabbed by U.S. agents and whisked away in a mini-van.
</P>
<P>
   That Elian survived was a miracle. What happened to him in the
months to follow was a debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Let's remember too that the family members who took Elian in
were relatives in the same way that your second cousins and
granduncles in Italy or Mexico or Poland or Ireland are relatives.
They didn't know this boy. They didn't even know his mom. I'm not
saying they didn't come to love him, but they had no claim to him
that legally superseded the rights of his father.
</P>
<P>
   They defied the law and wouldn't let him go. They cradled him
like a political football and they basked in the glow of the
media's overblown attention, and they encouraged the emotional
displays outside their house, and the spoiling of Elian with
presents and parades and clowns in favor of helping the boy grieve
and deal with the death of his mom.
</P>
<P>
   As for the protesters who were waving blown-up versions of that
seizure photo, along with signs that said, ``Child Abuse!'' and
``F--- Clinton!,'' I'm wondering why so many of them also were
hoisting Cuban flags. Isn't that the wrong country?
</P>
<P>
   By midday Saturday, we were seeing another set of photos: Elian,
his father, his stepmother, his half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   Reunited with his real family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
RICHARD ROEPER column and other features. &QL;
</P>
