<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRAINWAVES28-COX     04-27 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAINWAVES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tricks to kick-start your creativity
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Remember the tale of how Isaac Newton
discovered gravity?
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting under a tree when an apple fell on his head and
everything became clear.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great if we could find something like that to
loosen our thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   It's not such a nutty concept.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes our best ideas come when we are relaxed or distracted.
</P>
<P>
   So, while we're sitting here daydreaming, we've come up with
five ways to get your brain out of neutral and encourage your
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1) Eat more protein and complex carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have cobwebs? Stay away from simple sugars and fats.
They'll gobble you up,'' says Dr. Pierce J. Howard, author of ``The
Owner's Manual for The Brain,'' ($24.95, Bard Press) an 800-page
tome. Your brain activity will be stimulated just by thumbing
through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And drink plenty of water. That's very trendy these days, both
caffeine and alcohol dehydrate. So cut back. I recommend 1
milligram of caffeine per pound of body weight per dose once every
seven hours if needed. That's just under two mugs of coffee for me.
You just don't need it, you get the jitters, you still can't focus
on what you're trying to do. Lethargy and hyperactivity, both of
them prevent focus. Your mind starts wandering or is unable to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two cups of caffeine a day, and he's got a BIG brain.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2) Relax, don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't force it. You won't ever get a block if you don't
force yourself to come up with something when it's not naturally
coming out,'' says Nina L. Diamond, a Miami musician and author of
``Voices of Truth, Conversations with Scientists, Thinkers and
Healers'' ($24.95, Lotus Press.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd never dream of going into the bathroom when you didn't
have to go. When something wants to come out of you, you will know
it. If you sit down before anything's ready to come out, nothing's
going to happen. Stop sitting down when you don't have something to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 3) Try something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do something utterly different from your normal routine,''
writes Martha Beck in the March issue of Mademoiselle. ``Children
are more creative than adults because their knowledge base is so
limited that they can't help running into brand new experiences ...
the result is extraordinarily heightened creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 4) Create a mind map.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind map is a real good way to get started,'' Howard says.
``It's a real free-flowing way to get going on a project. It's an
alternative to the traditional linear outline. The object is to get
ideas on paper without worrying how they're organized. It's like
personal brainstorming.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you write down a problem in the middle of a page,
circle it, and just jot down ideas all around it that could be
useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's modeled on the image we have of neural networks in the
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 5) Stare blankly into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Focus on an object. Right now, I see a tree with kudzu at some
distance,'' Howard said. ``Focus for about 30 seconds, then I'll
close my eyes and try to reconstruct in my mind's eye what I see.
You're refreshed. It kind of relaxes your eye muscles. They get you
a fresh perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is: Try anything that gets you out of your mental box.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to develop something that transports you from the
ordinary,'' adds Howard. ``I have an ugly pink cap that says, `The
50-year-old Boy.' When I put that on, I am a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Diamond: ``Get yourself absorbed completely in something
else. I rent two or three movies and watch them back to back.
You're transported visually, emotionally, all the way around. It
really breaks the trance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
