<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-990&AMP;ADD-(TR     04-27 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-990&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS RAID ON HOME OF ELIAN'S RELATIVES WAS NECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Elian Gonzalez began settling into a life surrounded by
familiar faces from his homeland, Attorney General Janet Reno on
Thursday again offered justification for the tactics used to seize
the boy from his Miami relatives, saying that a ``show of force''
had been necessary after negotiations for a peaceful transfer began
to falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't going to get any better,'' Reno said Thursday
morning at a news conference in Washington. ``Clearly, the agents
had to be in force. Elian was being held by this person, and there
had to be a show of force, not a use of force, to show that we were
in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the federal agents stormed the Miami home in a
three-minute, pre-dawn raid on Saturday because most of the
protesters outside the house had dispersed, and that it ``seemed to
be the safest time possible to effect the transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   The agents, some armed with automatic rifles, stormed into the
home where Elian had been staying since late November with his
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and other relatives. The family had
defied government orders to turn the 6-year-old boy over to federal
officials and his father because, like thousands of Cuban-American
exiles, they did not want to see Elian returned to a Cuba ruled by
President Fidel Castro. After federal agents seized him, the boy
was flown to Washington, where he was reunited with his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Although President Clinton has supported Reno's actions, the
attorney general has received a barrage of criticism, mostly from
Republican lawmakers, over her handling of the raid. Several
senators have called for congressional hearings into the incident.
And Vice-President Al Gore said he would have handled things
``differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Reno vigorously continued to defend her decisions,
saying that the Miami relatives had appeared to be waffling during
last-minute negotiations. She said that Aaron Podhurst, a
negotiator for the Miami family, told told her at 4 a.m. on April
22 that the family refused to let Elian reunite with his father
anywhere outside of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling that we were in the same position that we
had been in, with the goalposts changing,'' Reno said. ``At this
point, if it were a deal-breaker, we should bring the negotiations
to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the controversy over the raid has centered on
contradictory accounts of the negotiations. While Reno has
maintained that the Miami relatives were refusing to budge,
Podhurst has said that he felt the parties were within ``minutes''
or ``an hour'' of reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As the raid began, Reno said, people outside the home tried to
throw ropes around the agents. The family inside the house pushed a
couch against the door, she said, forcing the agents to batter
through the entryway. When Betty Mills, an agent from the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, carried Elian out the door,
people grabbed at her, and she almost fell before being helped by
another agent, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also addressed criticism of the manner in
which agents had brandished automatic rifles in front of Elian as
the terrified boy hid inside a closet, a scene that was captured in
a widely circulated photograph taken by a photographer for The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at everything that we could do to make sure that it
was done safely and yet with the least impact on Elian,'' Reno
said. She added that she has been told that the agent confronting
the boy had the safety catch on his rifle. The agents did not yell
and curse at the family, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno acknowledged that Elian had grown close to his cousin and
caretaker, Marisleysis Gonzalez, and that perhaps the two could
visit each other after the government consulted psychiatrists. One
child psychiatrist retained by the government filed an evaluation
on Wednesday that said that Elian did not view Marisleysis Gonzalez
as a mother figure, but had more of a ``romantic'' attachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that Marisleysis will be out of his life,''
Reno said. ``I mean, you could look at them and see a connection.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government has moved quickly to surround Elian with
people who were close to him in Cuba. On Wednesday night, one of
the boy's teachers and a favorite cousin, a 10-year-old, flew to
Washington to keep the boy company through what is expected to be a
prolonged legal battle over Elian's asylum application. Thursday
morning, the State Department approved entry visas for four of
Elian's schoolmates and four adult chaperones. They were expected
to fly to the United States Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On arriving in this country three weeks ago, Elian's father
asked the State Department to grant visas to an entourage of 25
Cubans who would stay in the United States with him through the
appeals process. That proposed entourage, assembled by Castro,
included Elian's classmates, teachers and close relatives, as well
as doctors and a high-ranking government official.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Elian is staying with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez's wife
and their 6-month-old son, on a farmhouse on the 1,100-acre Wye
River estate that has been used for Middle East peace talks. Juan
Miguel Gonzalez flew from Cuba on April 6 to claim his son, but
Elian cannot leave the country before the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta decides whether to make the INS grant the boy
an asylum hearing. On Tuesday, the court also said Elian cannot
visit any place that has diplomatic immunity, effectively barring
him from spending time at the home of a Cuban diplomat in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The court is scheduled to hear oral arguments beginning May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle recently asked the court to place the boy
under the care of an independent party while the appeals process
plays out. But on Wednesday, both the boy's father and the Justice
Department made separate filings with the court, asking it to keep
Elian in John Miguel Gonzalez's custody.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The emergency motion filed by the father asked the court to let
him intervene in his son's asylum case and asserted that the
great-uncle no longer had any legal basis to speak for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The legal maneuverings are only the latest in an international
custody battle that has reached operatic proportions for many of
the people involved. The saga that has embroiled two governments, a
sprawling family and thousands of political exiles began last
November, when Elian and his mother attempted to reach the United
States on a smuggling boat. When the vessel capsized, the mother
and 10 other Cubans drowned. But two fishermen discovered Elian
clinging to an inner-tube on Nov. 25 off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was given ``parole'' status by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service and placed in the custody of his great-uncle
in Miami. At the time, no one could predict the fury of the
oncoming storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have peace in my heart and peace in my mind when
everybody is home,'' Reno said Thursday, ``wherever home will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
