<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEACHERS-HOMES-HNS &LR;      04-27 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-HOMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA WEIGHS HOME LOANS FOR TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis and state lawmakers are
moving to provide teachers with cash to buy homes in San Francisco,
the Silicon Valley and other areas with high housing costs.
</P>
<P>
   An Assembly committee on Wednesday approved a measure that would
grant teachers up to $20,000 to buy a home within the school
district. The teacher would have to stay on the job for at least
five years, after which the loan would vanish. If the teacher left
the job early, loan payments would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, is working on a variety of incentives for
teachers who are finding it nearly impossible to buy homes in the
San Francisco Bay Area and other markets, where the median housing
prices are close to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davis proposes to offer a maximum of $10,000 in forgivable loans
for teachers to buy a house. Teachers would be required to work in
public schools that are having the hardest time attracting
teachers, typically those with low-income students and low test
scores. The most recent figures show California's 268,000 teachers
make an average of $44,500 per year, far below the amount needed to
finance a large home loan.
</P>
<P>
   The omnibus teacher-recruitment bill Davis supports would also
grant teachers in low performing schools $2,000 to buy school
supplies, since many teachers have to take money out of their own
pockets. Lawmakers are looking at giving teachers help with student
loans and granted tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   A bill sponsored by Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, a Democrat from
San Francisco, is offering up to $20,000 in forgivable loans in his
measure. Shelley said there may be room for compromise with the
governor before the Legislature finishes its work this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't educate our kids if the teachers aren't around to
provide the education,'' Shelley said.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Philip Angelides also is proposing a $150
million program to offer teachers tax credits equal to 15 percent
of their annual mortgage interest payments, if they teach for five
years in schools with the lowest scores on state achievement tests.
Angelides hopes to start it by September, and he is asking the
Legislature for a five-year commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' proposal is a laundry list that includes the housing loan
and money for supplies. It would also give up to $30,000 in grants
to teachers who are certified by the National Board for
Professional Teaching Standards and agree to teach for at least
four years in a low performing school.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, written by state Sen. Richard Alarcon, a Democrat from
Van Nuys, would also eliminate a law that retired teachers who
return to work cannot make more than $19,600 per year and retain
their retirement benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1523EDT &QL; 
