<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-VIET-HANOI-$ADV30-BOS     04-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIET-HANOI-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EMBALMED REMINDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D.S. GREENWAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anticommunism would be a useless tool unless the problem of
nationalism is resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   _ General Jacques Philippe Leclerc, Hanoi, 1947 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HANOI _ In the midst of this capital city sits a squat,
Soviet-style Mausoleum. It houses the body of Ho Chi Minh who, like
Lenin and Mao, lies forever in an embalmed state. It is said that a
team of Russian experts keeps him presentable.
</P>
<P>
   Ho did not ask for this. He asked that his ashes be divided into
three parts and scattered over the three regions of Vietnam, which
he spent his life trying to unite. He died in 1969, six years
before his dream came true, and the Party overruled him regarding
his resting place.
</P>
<P>
   Ho came from a family that, although poor, had been mandarins in
the court in Hue. As a young man, he traveled the world, shipping
out from Saigon on a French freighter. He spent time in Brooklyn,
Boston, and San Francisco, as well as London and Paris, where he
tried to hand President Wilson an anticolonial petition in 1919.
But anticolonialism was not part of Wilson's concept of self
determination.
</P>
<P>
   When the French Communist party was formed, Ho joined it, seeing
in the writings of Lenin the means to end his country's colonial
bondage. He learned political organization in Russia and visited
Mao in China before he slipped back into Vietnam in 1941 after an
absence of 30 years. He organized resistance to both the Japanese
occupiers and their temporary allies, the Vichy French.
</P>
<P>
   When World War II ended, Ho seized upon the political vacuum to
declare independence here in Hanoi. He had made contact with the
American OSS _ the predecessor to the CIA _ in the jungle during
the war. He hoped that President Roosevelt would support him as
Wilson had not. But Roosevelt vacillated, and the Truman
administration didn't want to undermine the French with the cold
war beginning. The US backed the return of the French.
</P>
<P>
   A brief accommodation with the French fell apart, and Ho
retreated to the forests to start a guerrilla war that ended nine
years later with the French defeat at Dien Bien Phu in 1954. The US
ended up spending more money supporting the French war effort than
it had on the Marshall Plan to help rebuild France after World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   The country was partitioned between north and south, communist
and noncommunist, with the United States supporting the south. Ho
set about defeating the United States as he had the French, by
accepting losses that would be unimaginable in the West in order to
wear his enemy down until it tired of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Without foreign help, the anticommunist Vietnamese weren't equal
to the task for the very reason Leclerc had warned in 1947: They
never captured the nationalist cause, which Ho had made his own,
because they were too obviously dependent on foreigners, because
they stood for the status quo, which was both corrupt and venal,
and they were never able to reform themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Militarily, the Americans engaged in a war of attrition in which
they sought to grind down the enemy until he gave up. But, given
the losses Ho was willing to take, and given that the Communists
could always retreat into Laos, Cambodia, or North Vietnam, the war
of attrition worked against the United States. Bombing the North
couldn't tip the balance because most of the war materiel was made
in China or Russia, and the United States did not want to invade
the North, fearing the Chinese would enter the war as had happened
in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the Americans tired of the war, as had the
French, and in 1973 allowed the North Vietnamese to keep their
armies in the South while agreeing to remove their own troops. The
South Vietnamese had come to depend on the Americans, and now that
they were on their own, their days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Hanoi today, although still second in size, energy, and
commercial importance to Saigon, now called Ho Chi Minh City, is
the undisputed capital of a united country. It is no longer the
grim, low-watt-bulb town of the early '80s with barren shops, dark
streets, and nothing but the hiss of bicycle tires in the mornings.
Today it bustles with traffic. There is a new Hanoi Hilton that is
actually a hotel, and the old prison that bore that ironic name for
a generation of Americans is gone except for a wing maintained as a
museum. It has been replaced by an office and apartment tower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
