<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u k BC-ROEPER-ELIAN-REVISITE     04-27 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-ELIAN-REVISITED-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELIAN GONZALEZ SAGA COMES TO A CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, April 27, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's the dumbest thing I've ever covered.'' _ Rick Bragg,
Miami bureau chief of the New York Times, on the Elian Gonzalez
saga.
</P>
<P>
   Was that like a bad episode of ``Cops'' or what?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing from that grainy, jiggly video of the
Holy Saturday seizure of Elian Gonzalez was the sound of ``Bad
Boys'' on the soundtrack as agents grabbed the boy and whisked him
away in a mini-van, while hysterical friends and family members
screamed and cried and lunged for the kid.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm joining the knee-jerk chorus of naive protesters
who are invoking the ``jack-booted thugs'' cliche and bellowing
about the ham-handed management tactics of Janet Reno and Billy
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Ruby Ridge. This wasn't Waco. This was a
justifiable, well-executed tactical operation, carried out with
efficiency by federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, they came in with pepper gas and guns and riot gear,
shouting threats and issuing commands. Guess what? That's how these
things work. Intimidation is a key element in any raid, whether
we're talking about an INS seizure or a bunch of cops bursting into
a murder suspect's house or a crack den in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   You don't tiptoe in and shake hands and ask everyone if they're
in a good mood. You take control.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, that kid was essentially being held hostage by
those glory-hound distant relatives, who were defying American law
and refusing to let the boy even see his father. What were the feds
supposed to do, say ``Pretty please can we have the kid?''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone claiming there had to be another way to expedite the
transfer of Elian to his nuclear family hasn't been paying
attention these last several months. That circus in Little Havana
was growing increasingly hostile, and Elian's caretakers weren't
helping matters by defiantly clinging to their pre-school-age
political football instead of considering what was best for the boy
_ i.e., reuniting him with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Elian is now where he should be, he continues to
be exploited. Hours after ``The Taking Of Elian,'' as Fox News
titled it in their instant graphics, a seller on eBay was offering
$3 buttons featuring the infamous photo of the armed agent
confronting Elian and his fisherman-rescuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CLINTON-GORE LEGACY,'' reads the message above the
picture. Below it: ``Send a Message in November Never Again!''
</P>
<P>
   I love this notion that under a Republican administration, we'll
have kinder, less-intrusive federal agencies. How funny.
</P>
<P>
   Other Elian-related items, available on the Internet or from
enterprising vendors in Little Havana:
</P>
<P>
   Bumper stickers. Posters. Comic books. A coffee mug with a
picture of Fidel Castro and the sarcastic inscription, ``World's
Greatest Dad!'' T-shirts. Rubber stamps with Elian's photo. Gag
license plates, with a cartoon Elian, um, squirting in Castro's
face.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet pranksters have periodically put Elian himself on
the auction block: ``Cuban boy for sale,'' stuff like that. But try
to bid and you'll be told the auction is ``invalid.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. I picture Hugh Hefner making a $1 million bid and
turning Elian into his own version of Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Hillary Clinton can make a claim for the poor kid.
Wasn't there some noise about her adopting a child a few years
back? Accessorizing with an Elian might be enough to swing New York
in her direction.
</P>
<P>
   As for the media, shame on us. We've started the 21st century by
turning an admittedly compelling but relatively small
human-interest drama into a typically overblown spectacle.
Conducting exploitative interviews with the child, endless playing
of that disturbing ``Papa'' video, sending news choppers into the
sky to hover above the scene, establishing a ``Camp Elian'' outside
his temporary home, treating Saturday's handover as if it were the
most momentous development this side of global nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't just report on this story, we fueled its momentum with
rocket-jets of hype. According to the Center for Media and Public
Affairs, as of last week there had been more Elian stories on the
network newscasts (261) than there were about the deaths of
Princess Diana (200) and JFK Jr. (161), over a similar chunk of
time. Elian's even closing in on O.J., who warranted 431 stories
from the networks in the last six months of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before the events of Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A mom died. Her son miraculously survived. His dad got him back.
</P>
<P>
   End of story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
RICHARD ROEPER column and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
