<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8895 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KIDHEALTH-COX     04-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDHEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Helping mothers with a challenging pregnancy
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVERCREEK, Ohio _ The routine ultrasound was taking awfully
long, Laurie Hamlin thought. She knew the technician couldn't tell
her why, but she didn't like the way the tech kept saying things
like, ``Gosh, this baby's not doing much.'' Eventually, the
obstetrician came into the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Well this is really bad,''' said Hamlin. ``'Your
placenta is just in the wrong place. There's nothing we can do
about this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The placenta's location was not the problem, Hamlin learned
later. But the 18-week fetuses' blood vessels were intertwined in
their shared placenta, sending too much blood to one and not enough
to the other.
</P>
<P>
   The condition, twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome (TTTS), usually
causes miscarriage or brain damage unless treated. The doctor sent
Laurie and her husband, Jeff, to their family doctor that night,
but only to recommend a counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were given zero hope,'' Laurie said of that night in early
1996, raising her voice slightly to be heard over the noise of her
twin daughters dashing through the house.
</P>
<P>
   Julianne and Leah Hamlin will turn 4 next week, named for the
doctor who gave them life with a rare surgical procedure inside the
womb 16 weeks before they were born. Dr. Julian De Lia of Milwaukee
separated their blood supplies by killing the connected blood
vessels. He cooked that part of the placenta with a laser light, a
procedure he has done 110 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamlins, with their 5-year-old son, Alex, are the March of
Dimes' ambassador family for a WalkAmerica event. Laurie wants to
raise awareness ``with wonderful information and help whether you
have a challenging pregnancy or a healthy one,'' and also to call
attention to De Lia and TTTS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought Julian would be here by now,'' she said of De
Lia's 18-month effort to establish an international treatment and
research center for birth defects in Dayton. But after being turned
away by Miami Valley Hospital, he is awaiting a decision from
Kettering Medical Center while being courted in Milwaukee and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin wants more people to know about the 3,000 TTTS
pregnancies a year in this country because she feels fortunate to
have found Dr. Jiri Sonek, a fetal specialist who knew how it
should be treated. Her obstetrician's plan was to keep draining
excess amniotic fluid from the sac of the recipient fetus, which
often leads to miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have kept me pregnant but it wasn't going to fix
the problem,'' she said. She learned of De Lia's better alternative
because her mother worked at The Children's Medical Center's unit
for newborns, where Dr. Jeffrey Pietz referred her to Sonek, then
at Franciscan Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sonek, now De Lia's prospective associate, appreciated the value
of De Lia's procedure because his own research had shown how badly
things turned out for babies treated only with amniotic draining.
Twenty years ago, De Lia said the death rate for TTTS was at least
95 percent, and half of the survivors had brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The condition begins with ``random events'' between the fourth
and eighth days of pregnancy, De Lia explained on one of his many
visits to Dayton in recent months. ``The babies are normal. It's
the placentas that are abnormal.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of identical twins share a placenta, which connects a
pregnant woman with the umbilical cord through which a fetus is
nourished. But for some reason 15 percent of them develop TTTS.
</P>
<P>
   De Lia began exploring ways to separate the circulatory systems
in 1983, began operating on humans in 1988 and said ``really hit
the end of the learning curve'' in April 1995. An abdominal
incision allows him to guide the laser through a scope to the
placenta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always go in with the intention of saving both babies,'' he
said. ``But you can't see until you're in there the type and number
of vessels involved, or how the placenta is shared.'' The
operation, now done in several countries, normally occurs at 21
weeks, although Hamlin's was at 20.
</P>
<P>
   TTTS babies treated with amniotic draining have a 50 percent
survival rate, but De Lia's survival rate for both twins is 65
percent to 75 percent, said Ann Klonicki of the TTTS Foundation.
The rate for a single survival is 10 percent higher, and the
disability rate for survivors is below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he doesn't just do the surgery and send you home,'' Hamlin
said. He called her at least once a week for the remaining 16 weeks
of her pregnancy. ``When everybody else was calling the girls
fetuses, they were kids to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The drama involved in these cases is exhausting,'' De Lia
said. ``I went into this business initially because obstetrics is a
happy specialty. This has a lot more ups and downs, but I also know
I'm saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites: www.tttsfoundation.com for the Twin-to-Twin
Transfusion Syndrome Foundation, www.twinhope.com for the TwinHope
Foundation and www.twin2twin.org for the United Kingdom's TTTS
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
