<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-ART (New York) _ In ``Art and Oracle: Spirit Voices of
Africa,'' installed in the special exhibitions galleries just off
the Greek and Roman wing of the Metropolitan Museum, Africa,
symbolically at least, has taken its place in that exclusive
museological club known as the classical tradition. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM-CONCEPTUAL-PHOTOS (New York) _ When Conceptual Art
came along in the 1960s, with its idealistic aim of emphasizing art
as notion or process rather than product, Conceptual photography
sprang up as its handmaiden. In ``Postmedia: Conceptual Photography
in the Guggenheim Museum's Permanent Collection,'' the museum
considers the ways in which the cool Conceptualist radicals of the
'60s and '70s used photography to ``extend and transgress'' the
boundaries of more conventional art. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ More than 150 years ago, San
Antonio gave Texas its enduring symbol of us-against-them pride and
courage, the Alamo. Austin's moment in the sun is now. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISS-SAIGON-CLOSE (New York) _ The longrunning Broadway musical
``Miss Saigon'' is closing. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICMAN-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews the
Broadway revival of ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   BOSSA-MOVIE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Bruno Barreto's ``Bossa Nova''
may leave you exhausted, if only because your toes and knees have
been bouncing along to the friendly bossa nova grooves of the songs
selected for the soundtrack. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IDIOTS-MOVIE-REVIEW (Undated) ``The Idiots,'' the newest
offering by Danish director Lars von Trier. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
