<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACK-ATH     04-27 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACK-ATHLETES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE ATHLETES OF AFRICAN DESCENT SUPERIOR?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By AKILAH MONIFA  
 &HT;    March Madness is over, and the process of deciding which college
athletes will be drafted by the NBA has begun. In the NBA
approximately 80 percent of the players are of African descent. In
the WNBA, 70 percent of the female team members are black. Given
these statistics, the NBA and WNBA pose questions about race and
sport.
 &HT;    Jon Entine, a white journalist, addresses the subject of the
alleged predominance of black athletes, ``Taboo: Why Black Athletes
Dominate Sports and Why We're Afraid to Talk About It''
(PublicAffairs, LLC 1999). The book jacket reads, in part:
``Drawing on the latest scientific research, Entine persuasively
shows why biology and ancestry are significant components of the
stunning ascension of black athletes ...''
 &HT;    Entine hopes his book will produce a dialogue. He wants us to
examine why black athletes dominate sports and why we are afraid to
talk about it.
 &HT;    Fine, let's have a dialogue, but let's begin with some facts.
The reality, according to sociologist and professor Harry Edwards,
is that white athletes dominate 95 percent of all sports.
 &HT;    White athletes dominate archery, auto racing, badminton,
bicycling, discus, diving, extreme sports, fencing, golf,
gymnastics, hockey, horse racing, javelin, pole vault, rowing,
shot-put, skiing, soccer, swimming, tennis, walking, water polo,
yachting, and all of the winter sports.
 &HT;    Entine's thinks we are afraid to discuss the possibility that
people of African descent have some genetic predisposition to
athleticism. The subject is hardly new. Decades ago, scientists
examined black athletes to determine if there were any anatomical
reasons for their athletic success. They found none.
 &HT;    In 1936, Jesse Owens was poked and prodded for evidence of
racial superiority. At that time, researchers were unconvinced that
``Negroid physical characters are anatomically concerned with the
present dominance of Negro athletes.''
 &HT;    Is it nearly impossible to determine the genetic factors that
may or may not be involved in a black athlete's performance. How
can you prove how much of a trait is shaped by genes or the
environment? What other variables that contribute to an athlete's
success should we consider as well?
 &HT;    John Phillips, who is quoted in Entine's book, offers a counter
view to the notion of black athletic predominance, which raises
different and, perhaps, more relevant questions.
 &HT;    ``Black athletes are concentrated in those sports in which
blacks in general have access _ in terms of coaching, facilities
and competitions. For sports in which blacks are rare, the best
facilities, coaching and competition are found in private clubs. If
blacks were dispersed across all sports, their apparent superiority
would largely disappear,'' Phillips said.
 &HT;    Instead of asking if athletes of African descent are superior,
perhaps we should ask simpler questions. For instance, why aren't
more people of color involved in sports like swimming? And why
aren't blacks more involved in coaching, management and ownership
of sports teams at all levels?
 &HT;    These are questions that speak not only to race and sports, but
to class and opportunity.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa is a free-lance writer in Oakland, Calif.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    
 c.2000 AKILAH MONIFA 
