<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NEW-AMERICA-CONFEDERA     04-27 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-CONTROVERSY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE REBEL FLAG A RACIST EMBLEM? JUST ASK THE CONFEDERATES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VERNON JARRETT  
 &HT;    Nearly 150 years after the Confederate battle flag last flew
above a rebel army, the meaning of that bit of cloth is still
controversial.
 &HT;    Is it an innocent, harmless symbol of a region's cultural
heritage, without political or racial implications?
 &HT;    Or is it the most sacred symbol of slavery, the
institutionalized essence of racism?
 &HT;    Suspend the debate. Go to the archives and read, and let the
Confederates themselves supply the answer.
 &HT;    First let's consult one of the Confederacy's most articulate
founding fathers, Alexander Hamilton Stephens of Georgia, who
served under Jefferson Davis as vice president of the Confederate
States of America.
 &HT;    Addressing his fellow Georgians in Savannah on March 21, 1861 _
less than a month before Confederates gathered in South Carolina at
Charleston Bay and fired on Fort Sumter _ Stephens began by
disclosing that the Union's founding fathers were privately
convinced that slavery was ``wrong in principal, socially, morally
and politically,'' and that ``the institution would be evanescent
and pass away.''
 &HT;    Speaking on behalf of the Confederacy, Stephens begged to
differ.
 &HT;    ``Our government is founded upon exactly the opposite idea,'' he
declared. ``Its foundations are laid, its cornerstone rests upon
the great truth that the negro is not equal to the white man. That
slavery, subordination to the superior race, is his natural and
normal condition.''
 &HT;    Describing the embryonic Confederate States of America, Stephens
made clear that racism was part and parcel of its conception.
 &HT;    ``This, our new government, is the first in the history of the
world based upon this great physical and moral truth'' that the
``negro, by nature or by the curse of Canaan, is fitted for the
condition which he occupies in our system.''
 &HT;    He went on to explain that blacks were held in slavery in a
fulfilment of nothing less than the will of God.
 &HT;    ``The substratum of our society is made of the material fitted
by nature for it,'' Stephens said, ``and by experience we know that
it is best, not only for the superior but for the inferior race,
that it should be so. It is indeed in conformity with the ordinance
of the Creator.''
 &HT;    Stephens also criticized the United States Constitution, under
which we live today, holding that it was not racist enough to
guarantee the durability of slavery.
 &HT;    While the old Constitution embraced a fugitive-slave clause and
specified that blacks should count as three-fifths of a white man
for tax purposes, the leaders of the new Confederate government
felt that it did not spell out white superiority boldly and
directly enough.
 &HT;    The rebellion leaders were for real. Driven by a racist
philosophy not widely at odds with the anti-Semitism preached by
Hitler. rebel leaders wanted to make their racial views universal,
endowing themselves with a messianic racial mission.
 &HT;    ``The progress of disintegration in the old Union may be
expected to go on with almost absolute certainty,'' Stephens
announced. ``We are now the nucleus of a growing power, which, if
we are true to ourselves, our destiny and high mission, will become
the controlling power on this continent.''
 &HT;    But the Confederates did not limit their racial goals to this
continent alone. Like Hitler's dream of Aryan superiority, theirs
was a ``tomorrow the world'' ideology.
 &HT;    ``It is upon this (that) our actual fabric is firmly planted,''
Stephens proclaimed, ``and I cannot permit myself to doubt the
ultimate success of a full recognition of this principle throughout
the civilized and enlightened world.''
 &HT;    Yes, the man said ``enlightened world.''
 &HT;    But please don't write off Stephens as an oddball. His racial
views were typically Confederate.
 &HT;    When Texas leaders, meeting at a Secession Convention on
February 1, 1861, voted to became the seventh state to join the
rebellion, for example, they accused the North of ``hostility to
these Southern states and their beneficent and patriarchal system
of African slavery, proclaiming the debasing doctrine of equality
of all men, irrespective of race or color.''
 &HT;    To Texas secessionists, racial equality was ``a doctrine at war
with nature,'' and they insisted that ``the servitude of the
African race ... is abundantly authorized and justified by the
experience of mankind and the revealed will of the Almighty
Creator, as recognized by all Christian nations.''
 &HT;    The banner under which that ideology marched off to war, fired
its guns, drew swords and filled hundreds of thousands of graves
was the Confederate battle flag. It is that flag which today
insults all blacks citizens in South Carolina and Georgia,
declaring the survival of a doctrine still at war with human
decency.
 &HT;    When will enough Americans summon the guts to state, with firm
resolution, the simple truth that the Confederates themselves had
no difficulty enunciating: The Confederate battle flag is no simple
emblem of an ``honorable regional cultural heritage,'' but the
embodiment of a sentiment and mission only marginally better than
that expressed, not so long ago, by the swastika.
 &HT;    That flag has no place waving above or on the grounds of any
city, county, state or federal building in the United States.
 c.2000 Vernon Jarrett 
<TEXT>
