<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WIRELESS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN EARNS MORE THAN $35 BILLION FROM AUCTION OF WIRELESS
LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After 150 rounds of frenzied bidding that pushed prices
seven times beyond expectations, an auction for licenses to operate
new generation wireless devices linked to the Internet came to a
close Thursday, reaping the British government a huge $35.5 billion
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, which began nearly eight weeks ago with 13 bidders
in the field, ended when a British subsidiary of NTL Inc., backed
by France Telecom, withdrew. That left the winners as Britain's
four existing mobile telephone operators and one newcomer _ TIW
UMTS, backed by fast-growing Telesystem International Wireless of
Canada and Hutchison Whampoa of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest single bid of $9.42 billion came from Vodafone
AirTouch PLC, the global wireless giant, which dueled with British
Telecommunications PLC for license B _ a license with the broadest
capacity available to existing wireless operators.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected scale of the bidding has raised worries among
analysts and consumers that the prices for the 20-year licenses,
which come into use in 2002, are too high, adding to corporate debt
and risking an increase in consumer prices that will ultimately
restrict the market for mobile e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's chief executive, Chris Gent, said that by winning the
new license, his company would be able to offer its services to
``more customers than any other operator.'' But British
Telecommunications said the premium paid for the broadest license
was too high and that it would be able to offer cheaper services.
The technology for the new generation of devices is supposed to
increase Internet access speed for mobile gadgets by between 40 and
200 times, opening up what operators insist will be a bonanza in
the rapidly expanding wireless market, where Europe has established
an early lead over the United States. Operators argue that the
technology will yield new vistas of Internet access and e-commerce
from mobile phones and hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter Bonfield, the chief executive of British
Telecommunications, said, for instance, that wireless services
would produce ``explosive growth.'' Stephen Byers, the trade and
industry minister, said the early licensing of new generation
operators was a vital step toward making Britain ``the best place
in the world for e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain has said it will use the proceeds from the auction to
reduce the national debt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the auction over, the spotlight in telecommunications now
swings to Orange, Britain's third mobile operator, which Vodafone
acquired with its acquisition of Mannesmann A.G. earlier this year.
British and European regulators have insisted that Vodafone shed
the smaller company to avoid unfair dominance of Britain's mobile
phone market.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Trade and Industry, a British regulator, said
Vodafone's new license would not be granted irrevocably until it
had disposed of Orange. With predators circling the smaller British
mobile company, France Telecom said again Thursday that it had a
``strong interest'' in buying Orange. ``We're just waiting to know
how, when _ and whether _Orange will be sold,'' a spokeswoman for
France Telecom said.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone has spoken in the past of floating Orange as a separate
company, but is known to be concerned about the tax implications of
such a spinoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-27 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: LUCITE FORMS TURNING UP ALL OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hollywood and Lucite was a marriage made in heaven.
In the 1930s, when polyacrylics, a group of transparent
thermoplastics, came into wide use, designers chose Lucite as a way
to add panache to the homes of glamorous clients. You see it in old
photographs of the houses of movie stars like Claudette Colbert,
who carefully displayed her Oscar for ``It Happened One Night'' on
a Lucite table in her living room.
</P>
<P>
   Lucite was trademarked by DuPont in the 1930s (it is also called
Plexiglas and Perspex) and was first used as a glass substitute for
industrial purposes like boat windshields and aircraft windows.
Cast in a mold while hot, it can be formed into clear sheets, rods,
tubes or blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Plexicraft still make Lucite furniture, but
collectors prefer the vintage designs. Several pieces showed up at
the Kips Bay Boys and Girls Club Decorator Show House, which opened
this week at 1 E. 94th St. and runs through May 21. David Barrett,
for example, included Lucite in his decor there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the see-through look the first time I saw it in the
1950s,'' said Barrett, who is celebrating his 50th year as a
decorator, ``and I think it's still very young today.'' He has a
Lucite desk with a leather top and transparent legs that was
inspired by an antique French bureau plat, which he said was made
by the fashionable Paris decorating firm Jansen in about 1940.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucite furniture doesn't seem to take up space,'' he said. He
also has a vintage chandelier that looks a bit like an Indian
headdress except that the ``feathers'' are Lucite; two vintage
Lucite armchairs, and a pair of Art Deco-style candelabra with
three intertwined Lucite arms from the 1950s. Barrett borrowed them
all from Newel Art Galleries in Manhattan, which has a large stock
of Lucite.
</P>
<P>
   DeBare Saunders and Ronald Mayne, designers in Watertown, Conn.,
whose firm is called Stingray Hornsby (after Saunders' uncle, a
Corvette Stingray racer), created a man's dressing room at Kips Bay
with a pair of 1930s brass-and-Lucite fluorescent 5-foot-tall ocean
liner sconces, also from Newel. ``They are out of scale and larger
than life,'' Saunders said. ``They were made at a time when
fluorescent light was new.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Lucite is also showing up in shops specializing in
midcentury modern design. Form and Function, at 95 Vandam St. in
SoHo, is selling a rare 1957 Lucite Daffodil chair, designed by
Estelle and Erwine Laverne, for $3,800. (The chair is shown on an
antiques Web site, www.Circline.com.) Mike Cannamela of Form and
Function said that vintage Laverne pieces were classics. ``Lucite
used to be seen as 1960s kitsch,'' he said, ``but now the
well-designed pieces are becoming more popular.'' The Lavernes,
proponents of the modern look, opened their New York company in
1938.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous Laverne design is a 1957 Lucite dining room seat
called the Champagne chair. On May 21, Los Angeles Modern Auctions,
or LAMA, is selling a similar Laverne Buttercup chair, also from
1957. (The auction house's Web site is www.lamodern.com.) ``The
Lavernes named most of their chairs after flowers,'' said Peter
Loughery, who owns the auction house. ``The lines are very
progressive-looking, as opposed to Lucite furniture made in the
1980s, which doesn't have much design merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles sale also includes a 1960s Lucite table lamp in
the shape of a bird's wing designed by Joe Colombo, a Milanese
architect born in 1930, and a 1954 vanity stool with Lucite legs
designed by Paul Laszlo, a Viennese architect who settled in
Beverly Hills in the 1930s. ``Laszlo's furniture was custom made,''
Loughery said. ``He was a modernist but not a minimalist. This
stool has a flowery cushion.''
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo Lucite can also be found at Becker Arts, a gallery on
White Street in TriBeCa. ``If a Lazslo piece is outstanding, we buy
it,'' said the owner, Paul Donzella.
</P>
<P>
   Icon20, an auction Web site that specializes in 20th-century
works (www.Icon20.com), is selling a 1987 Max sideboard with Lucite
designed by Ettore Sottsass, the founder of the Milanese design
cooperative Memphis. Sottsass is one of the few avant-garde
designers attracted to the material. The architect Frank O. Gehry
said in an interview last week that he had experimented with Lucite
many years ago but ``found it too difficult a material to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Some old Lucite designs are so popular that they are being
reproduced. Peter Vaughn, a New York designer, has brought back a
line of Lucite furniture and objects created in the 1960s by Baron
Alessandro Albrizzi, a Venetian architect. ``Albrizzi collaborated
a lot with David Hicks in the 1960s,'' Vaughn said, referring to
the British designer. ``They invented the swinging London style.
Albrizzi made Lucite chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McDonald, the owner of Gansevoort Gallery at 72 Gansevoort
St. in the West Village, is selling a Lucite chair that was
designed as a prototype for the furniture company Herman Miller by
Gilbert Rohde in 1939. ``It was never put into production,''
McDonald said, ``probably because of the advent of World War II and
the ensuing scarcity of Plexiglas, which was reserved for military
use.'' The price is $45,000; he said the chair is one of two in
existence that once belonged to Rohde's widow.
</P>
<P>
   Rohde made his mark in the 1934 ``Machine Art'' exhibition at
the Museum of Modern Art in New York. His Lucite creations are
featured in a new book, ``American Modern, 1925-1940: Design for a
New Age'' by J. Stewart Johnson (Harry N. Abrams).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is a curator of an exhibition of the same name that
opens at the Metropolitan Museum of Art on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   A Botanical Benefit
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four dealers, including an antiquarian bookseller, are
showing their wares at the eighth Antique Garden Furniture Show at
the New York Botanical Garden. The show opens with a benefit party
on Thursday and continues through May 7. Tickets to the benefit,
with an auction of rare plants supplied by private growers, are
$150. ``Every penny from the auction goes to buy plants for the
botanical garden's curatorial people,'' said Susan Burke, one of
the organizers. Information: (718) 817-8773.
</P>
<P>
   The party will have a sneak preview of a show of 100 Chinese
tree peony specimens.
</P>
<P>
   The garden has acres of tulips, daffodils, crab apple and cherry
trees in bloom. Gregory Long, its president, said, ``The fair is
another way to enjoy a garden without having to be great at
horticulture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
