<HEADER>
A8939 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SAIGON-PHOTO-TRUTH-IN     04-27 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIGON-PHOTO-TRUTH-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHER TELLS TRUTH BEHIND FAMOUS VIETNAM SHOT    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for this weekend's 25th anniv., Fall of Saigon)   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)     
 By FIONA BELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY _ Saigon was in chaos. The Americans were
finally ending their disastrous military adventure in Vietnam.
Thousands of Americans and South Vietnamese alike were scrambling
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most celebrated photographs of a war which gave the
world so many haunting images was taken during the last few hours
of April 29, 1975, regarded as capturing the final chaotic moments
before the American evacuation was complete.
</P>
<P>
   It is a photograph that has been published countless thousands
of times, with a caption describing a desperate crowd of Americans
on the roof of the United States Embassy to board a waiting
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   But as with so many things about the Vietnam war, even this
cannot be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main thrust of the evacuation was indeed from the
U.S. Embassy, there were other assembly points for evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 25 years after the photograph was taken, it has emerged
that the building in the picture is actually an apartment block,
some distance away from the embassy compound. Most of the people in
the photograph were Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Van Es, the United Press International photographer in
Vietnam who took the picture, said Thursday: ``As much of the
evacuation was from the U.S. Embassy my picture editors assumed the
picture was of the embassy, even though it was actually from a
downtown building about a mile way from the embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sent the picture to the agency in the last few hours
before the American withdrawal, it was with the correct caption. I
said it was the evacuation from an apartment building, 22 Gia Long
Street in Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously editors do not read picture captions; this is par
for the course.''
</P>
<P>
   The building pictured by Van Es, a Dutchman who has been based
in Hong Kong since the war, was largely reserved for the employees
of the United States Agency for International Development (USAID).
But the top floor was set aside for the top brass of the CIA in
Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the evacuation, the station chief, Thomas
Polgar, had phoned a group of those South Vietnamese who had been
friends of the CIA and told them they should gather at the building
with their families so that they could be evacuated. These people
included generals, police officers and politicians who had been
helpful during the years of the war.
</P>
<P>
   But it was soon clear that the area was at risk from the
approaching North Vietnamese army and Polger would have to come up
with an idea to get his South Vietnamese friends out of the
building as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   His inspired plan was to land a helicopter on top of the
building's elevator shaft. He ordered in a Huey helicopter operated
by Air America, the CIA's airline for its operation in Southeast
Asia, to collect the Vietnamese officials and their families, and
he asked a CIA employee, O. B. Harnage, to direct the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Harnage stood by the ladder to the roof and directed the
families to the Huey. He says he is the man at the top of the
ladder in the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Van Es was well aware of who the people in the photograph
were at the time it was taken. ``The people in the picture are
mostly South Vietnamese government workers, people working for
USAID, some CIA, but mostly officials and politicians from South
Vietnam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told many people over the years since the war about the
mistake but it has never changed the way the picture is presented.
I have no control over that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time I am not even credited by name as having
taken it. It just runs with the agency caption made at the time and
the UPI tag. Since the war it has been published in a number of
U.S. history books and always with the wrong caption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time/Life are the only ones who have ever captioned the
picture correctly. When they use the picture they do not describe
it as the embassy evacuation and they always credit me by name.''
</P>
<P>
   And so this picture has become a metaphor for many of the
misunderstandings that afflicted Vietnam, of how America imposed
its own ideas depending on its view of the war. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
