<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8940 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-CATALINAISLAND-840(2T     04-27 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATALINAISLAND-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALINA AFTER-HOURS IS AN ISLAND OF TRANQUILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVALON, Calif. _ As we left San Pedro harbor, we were surrounded
by the odd combination of gritty industrial warehouses on one side
and Carnival cruise ships on the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect symbol of what we were leaving behind _
overcrowded Los Angeles _ and where we were headed _ a quick
getaway to Catalina Island.
</P>
<P>
   A little over an hour later, as the town of Avalon began to
appear like a mirage through the gray skies, the change was a bit
unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Avalon did look like a Mediterranean coastal town from a
distance _ some California-ized hybrid of Capri and Portofino. Its
landmark Casino building that flanks one end of the harbor was as
eye-catching as the brochures proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   The town, with homes climbing the hillsides, is where almost all
of Catalina Island's population of 3,500 reside. But if you just
spent a few hours strolling along its waterfront _ as many do
before catching a return ferry _ you might think there was little
the island had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Avalon, for example, doesn't quite hold up to its
jaw-dropping entrance upon closer inspection. It takes a little
more digging _ and the departure of the day-trippers _ for its
charms to sink in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the shops along the waterfront were of the T-shirt and
tacky souvenir variety. Our meal at a waterfront restaurant proved
to be hit-and-miss. (The seared tuna was fresh and flavorful; the
leathery, tasteless calamari produced indigestion.)
</P>
<P>
   Our accommodations and the island's natural beauty were our
saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the inns close to the water appeared devoid of
charm, the Zane Grey Hotel, on a cliff above The Casino, rewarded
our impulse to stay the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pueblo-style hotel was built in 1926 and was once the home
of Grey, the famed western writer. The million-dollar view outside
our room overlooked the Casino below and the lights of the
California coastline 22 miles away glowed on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Our sparsely decorated room, Wandering Star, was named after one
of Grey's novels, as were all of the rooms. Dusty old paperbacks of
his novels can be borrowed from the front desk. An open-air balcony
on one end of the hotel provides a view of Avalon's harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The inn also provides free taxis into town several times a day _
the ride from the ferry dock when you arrive to the hotel is free _
but the 10-minute walk into town was worthwhile to get a sense of
the homes and guest houses lining the town's cliffside streets.
</P>
<P>
   The inn evokes an earlier era on Catalina when movie stars were
commonplace. The islands' boosters like to recall that John Wayne,
Cecil B. DeMille and Winston Churchill came for the sport fishing.
Laurel and Hardy and Big Band artists like Woody Herman and Jimmy
Dorsey also made the trek.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of town, the Casino Building, where those Big Band
artists performed, is worth checking out for its architecture and
entertainment. The 12-story Art Deco structure, which was completed
in 1929, includes a ballroom with a massive dance floor and a movie
theater designed to look like an underwater scene.
</P>
<P>
   On the night we stopped by, organ music could be heard from the
theater before the night's showing of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''
and a Valentine's Day dance was under way upstairs in the ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   But while many day-trippers see only Avalon, there is far more
to the island. It would be possible, in fact, to spend days
exploring Catalina's rugged interior.
</P>
<P>
   The island, purchased by William Wrigley Jr. in 1919, was
largely left undeveloped under his control. The undeveloped portion
still resembles the island Portuguese navigator Don Juan Rodriquez
Cabrillo stumbled upon in 1542.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   It didn't become known as Catalina until 60 years later when a
Spanish expedition arrived on Nov. 24, 1602. It was the eve of the
feast of St. Catherine of Alexandria, so they named the island
Santa Catalina.
</P>
<P>
   North American sailors showed up in the early 1800s. At the end
of the Mexican War in 1848, the island was bought by Californian
Thomas Robbins of Santa Barbara, purportedly in exchange for a
silver saddle. A few years later, a brief mining boom came to the
island that ended with the occupation by Union troops in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Although visitors made it to the island in the late 1800s,
Wrigley's purchase led the island on its path to a tourist
destination and a preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the island's interior and 48 miles of coastline were
placed in the control of Catalina Island Conservancy in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy controls about 42,000 acres _ roughly 86 percent
of the island. Bison, which were originally brought to the island
in 1924 for the filming of Grey's novel ``The Vanishing American,''
can be seen, as well as wild goats, wild pigs and deer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeep eco-tours, horseback riding and hiking allow both high-end
and economical ways to explore the interior, which features
valleys, remote bays and 2,000-foot peaks
</P>
<P>
   Snorkeling is also a popular activity. The island has been
touted as one of the top destinations in North America and Casino
Point Marine Park, just offshore from the Casino, is an underwater
city park. For those who don't dive, glass-bottom boat and
submarine tours are available.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, there has been an effort to replant native
grasses and trees and to reintroduce the bald eagle.
</P>
<P>
   If we make a return trip, we would be tempted to stay at Two
Harbors, an isthmus 14 miles from Avalon. The rustic village has an
inn, a general store and a restaurant, and is popular with hikers
and mountain bikers. Ferries run from San Pedro and Long Beach to
Two Harbors. Shuttle buses also run between Avalon and San Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Many Californians prefer this low-key alternative to Avalon,
which is also popular with yachters because it is the only natural,
all-weather harbor between San Francisco and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Some campers also camp between the two towns at one of three
seaside coastal campgrounds or one mountaintop campsite.
</P>
<P>
   The weather is generally temperate on Catalina throughout the
year, though rain hampered some activities during our February
visit. Many of the tours run only from spring to fall.
</P>
<P>
   One plus of our off-season visit was the tranquility. Once the
ferry boats left Avalon for the night, we had sections of the
harbor to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   What could be a better respite from a visit to car-mad LA?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Island isn't LA, but it still has Southern California
prices. Many of the tours and hotels are not bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Two-hour Jeep tours run $65.
</P>
<P>
   A four-hour sundown cruise between Avalon and Two Harbors
(between April and October) is $30. Dinner is extra.
</P>
<P>
   Our room at the Zane Grey was $103, including taxes and a
poolside continental breakfast. Prices are higher on weekends and
during the summer but can drop dramatically for midweek visits
during the winter. The Zane Grey has dramatic views of the island
and a laid-back atmosphere, but can be too austere for some. Some
guests complained about the lack of televisions or phones in the
spartan rooms. Dinner for two, including two beers, cost $40.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Catalina, we took the Catalina Express for $38 per
person roundtrip out of San Pedro. The island can also be reached
from Long Beach, Newport Beach and Dana Point. Helicopter service
is also available. There are also combination packages that combine
hotel and transportation that may save money, depending on the time
of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are not available for rent on the island. Golf carts can be
rented in Avalon for $40 to $60 an hour. This works in town _ the
golf carts are everywhere _ but it's not a way to see the island.
Plenty of tour packages are also available to see Catalina.
Although Catalina has been a favorite haunt of Hollywood stars, it
is also known for the death of actress Natalie Wood. She drowned
just off the coast of the island in 1981. The mystery surrounding
her death was the subject of a recent Vanity Fair magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Check out Catalina's Web site at www.catalina.com
or call the visitors and convention bureau at (310) 510-1520.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
