<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-SOLOMON-SPI &LR;      04-27 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOLOMON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAX TURNS TO THE POWER OF SOLOMON FOR RATINGS MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the second night of ``Solomon,'' the first miniseries
presented by Pax TV, a trusted friend says to King Solomon: ``The
ship of state needs someone at the steering oar. There are matters
which demand your attention other than the queen of Sheba's
thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Knock me over with a palm frond. What kind of language is
this from the family entertainment network?
</P>
<P>
   Call it the lingua franca of May sweeps. Even Pax TV, the
network most people don't know exists, craves more viewers during a
ratings-sweep period, which networks and affiliates use to help set
advertising rates. If a network can attract more eyeballs with
compelling (read: sexy) entertainment, it can charge higher ad
rates, and that ultimately means more shekels for the network.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Bill Scott, president of programming,
``Solomon'' possesses ``all the ingredients of great entertainment:
passion, rivalry, pride, envy, failure and triumph.'' Not to
mention the queen of Sheba skinny-dipping with the king of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   OK, aside from a glimpse of Ben Cross' bare bottom and a
brief-but-steamy bedroom scene involving Cross and Vivica A. Fox,
Pax TV's ``Solomon,'' airing Sunday and Monday, is a fairly chaste
affair, considering that the man reportedly had 700 wives, 300
concubines and a hedonist's appetite for the finer things in life,
such as they were 3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though scholars doubt that Solomon actually wrote the
biblical erotica variously known as Song of Solomon, Song of Songs
and Canticle of Canticles, the film has Solomon using some of its
language, ostensibly to convey the overt sensuality of his 40-year
reign over the tribes of Israel that were united by his revered
father, David.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Solomon was a good and popular king, the wise and
fair monarch of legend, and the film has no trouble imparting as
much. But his strategic marriage to a pharaoh's daughter, solely to
avoid war with Egypt, sets Solomon on the slippery slope to loose
living and the worship _ or at least the accommodation _ of deities
other than the one God of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This slippage from monotheistic piety to flesh-indulging vanity
is explained in a long-winded exchange between Solomon and Jereboam
(Richard Dinnane), the same confidant who has the gall to suggest
his highness should be paying more attention to statesmanship and
less to swordsmanship. But director Roger Young, who also did the
miniseries ``Jesus,'' airing on CBS in two weeks, is hamstrung by a
script that never lets us see the depravity of Solomon's latter
reign. It is glimpsed, it is suggested, but never convincingly
displayed in all its debauched excess.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such graphic extravagance would make it hard to
peddle ``Solomon'' to mainstream television. (Filmed in 1997,
``Solomon'' is from the same Italian-German combine that has been
producing biblical stories since 1993 for a pool of worldwide TV
networks, including TNT cable, which ran several a few years back.)
Absent an R-rated Hollywood version, Pax TV presents Solomon-lite:
not as sinfully rich as it might have been, not as filling, either,
but reasonably satisfying in that low-calorie,
this-isn't-going-to-kill-me sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   As King Solomon, Cross is suitably regal. He looks august and
virile _ a real catch, if you will _ and his
emotional-but-not-overwrought performance sustains the film across
the two-night arc that dooms most miniseries. Cross gets splendid
support from Annouk Aimee, who plays Bathsheba, Solomon's mother
and the power behind the throne in the early years of his reign.
Max von Sydow, as Solomon's aged father, King David, lends some of
that old blockbuster bluster the film could use even more of. And
as Makeda, the queen of Sheba, Fox has no trouble conveying the
woman's stunning physical beauty. But she doesn't quite achieve the
passion, the gravitas, the intellectual maturity that one suspects
made her Solomon's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, ``Solomon'' manages to tell one of the Bible's
more fascinating stories stylishly and intelligently. And
considering that the sins of Solomon resulted in the political
re-fracturing of Israel's tribes, demanding that it be randier for
the sake of accuracy probably isn't a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon. Four-hour miniseries about the legendary king of
Israel. Starring Ben Cross, Vivica A. Fox, Annouk Aimee, Max von
Sydow, David Suchet, Ivan Kaye and Richard Dillane. Sunday and
Monday on Pax TV. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
