<HEADER>
A8961 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-FREQUENCY-SPI &LR;      04-27 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FREQUENCY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND A WACKY PREMISE, `FREQUENCY' SIGNALS DANDY TIME-TRAVEL
MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B+  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Frequency'' has an outlandish premise and a script that
depends on a few too many amazing coincidences. But if you can
swallow them, it's dandy little time-travel movie that has a lot of
the audience appeal of ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a Queens firefighter (Dennis Quaid) who, as
sun spots are doing funny things to the atmosphere in the fall of
1969, turns on his ham radio and contacts his son (Jim Caviezel) _
talking on the same ham radio exactly 30 years in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the voice of his now-grown son warns him that
he is about to die in a blazing warehouse fire the very next day!
And if he avoids a certain tactical mistake, he can save his life
and spare his wife and son three decades of misery.
</P>
<P>
   He does it, but there's a catch: Monkeying with fate initiates a
chain reaction of changes down through the years that ultimately
makes their family's life even more miserable, and puts them on a
collision course with a brutal serial murderer.
</P>
<P>
   From here on, the movie crosscuts between the two eras as father
and son get to know each other, struggle to comprehend what's
happening and what they've done to their personal destinies, and
work together to stop this murderer who is a threat to them in both
1969 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a big gulp. But, except for one obvious flaw in its
ending, writer Toby Emmerich and director Gregory Hoblit (``Primal
Fear'') do an extraordinarily good job of staying within their
film's own peculiar logic and of gradually breaking down our
resistance to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency'' is never particularly original; it incorporates
familiar plot elements of ``Time After Time,'' ``Somewhere in
Time'' and even ``It's a Wonderful Life.'' But it's also a
suspenseful and fascinating movie that milks the premise for all
it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a wonderfully oblique way, it also works as a heart-warming
relationship drama. Quaid and Caviezel are both excellent, building
a father-son chemistry that's touching and rather profound.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Sixth Sense'' (an obvious inspiration), ``Frequency''
avoids gimmicky visual effects, builds an irresistibly eerie mood,
constantly challenges us to stay with it intellectually, and relies
on a clever premise and character relationships to carry its load.
It's an equally refreshing movie, and could well become a
word-of-mouth hit.
</P>
<P>
   Frequency. Directed by Gregory Hoblit. Written by Toby Emmerich.
Cast: Dennis Quaid, Jim Caviezel, Andre Braugher, Elizabeth
Mitchell. New Line Cinema. 120 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
