<HEADER>
A8965 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-FLINTSTONES-SPI &LR;      04-27 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FLINTSTONES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLINTSTONES' SPOOF BETTER LEFT UNDER A ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: D  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost an hour into the movie Ann-Margret sings the theme song,
a souped-up, ragged out version of ``Viva Las Vegas.'' It's a funky
tribute to her own appearance on the original cartoon (as
Ann-Margrock, natch), and though her voice is thin and scratchy,
she growls it out with pure sass and showgirl style.
</P>
<P>
   If only the rest of the picture had her attitude. Or any
attitude for that matter. ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas,'' a
prequel to the 1994 blockbuster (itself a live action remake of the
1960s animated sitcom), is constructed almost solely on pop culture
spoofs in stone and animal skins and ponderous sight gags more
impressive than funny.
</P>
<P>
   The original cast members are jettisoned for younger faces and
smaller marquee names. Mark Addy (``The Full Monty'') finds his
inner Fred Flintstone with a gentle rumble in his voice and a
confident swagger in his walk: a Stone Age proto-Jackie Gleason.
Stephen Baldwin mugs mercilessly when he's not perfecting his
blank, slack-jawed look of bewilderment as Fred's bubble-headed pal
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The two working-class buddies meet flirty Betty (Jane Krakowski
from ``Ally McBeal'') and her pal Wilma (Kristen Johnston, ``3rd
Rock From the Sun''), a poor little rich girl running from a
manipulative mother (Joan Collins).
</P>
<P>
   It's your basic ``boys meet girls, boys lose girls, boys get
girls'' story with a touch of class conflict and a little help from
a sarcastic green cupid named The Great Gazoo (played with snotty
superiority by Alan Cummings' head on a computer-generated,
doll-size body).
</P>
<P>
   The script, full of leaden one-liners and dull puns, feels more
designed than written, better able to show off the details of a
cartoon come to life. The humor is aimed squarely at an adolescent
audience and director Brian Levant turns up the slapstick, double
takes, and epic fart jokes to a tortured extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Addy captures the bluster and the hearty sincerity of his
cartoon counterpart, and Krakowski is a perky, sexy Betty. But
Johnston and Baldwin overplay their parts. They should have taken a
lesson from the cast's master class: A doddering Harvey Korman (who
voiced Gazoo in the original series) hilariously barks nonsense
orders as Wilma's shell-shocked Dad, Cummings preens and poses as
peacock rock star Mick Jagged, and Collins delivers a perfect
spit-take like a comic pro.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's Levant who should have taken notes: It's all in the
delivery. These Flintstones may have left two-dimensional cartoons
for the 3-D world, but his direction is strictly flat.
</P>
<P>
   Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas. Directed by Brian Levant.
Written by Deborah Kaplan, Harry Elfont, Jim Cash, and Jack Epps
Jr. Cast: Mark Addy, Stephen Baldwin, Kristen Johnston, Jane
Krakowski, Thomas Gibson, Alan Cumming. Universal Pictures. 100
minutes. Rated PG for mild sexual humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
