<SLUG> BC-EXODUS-MICROSOFT-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT DOUBLES SHARE OPTIONS TO STEM STAFF EXODUS    
</HEADLINE>
   (This 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news files.)     
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the Justice Department looking at a breakup
of its operations, its share price taking a battering and senior
company executives running for the exit, Microsoft has launched a
last-ditch campaign to keep itself intact.
</P>
<P>
   It is showering its employees with financial incentives,
lobbying local politicians and issuing defiant statements insisting
it has done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The company's president and chief executive, Steve Ballmer, sent
an e-mail to Microsoft's 34,000 employees announcing a doubling of
their stock options, offered at Monday's all-time low closing price
of $66.63 per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for all of us to recognize that
ultimately, taking the long-term view is the path to future success
and prosperity _ for Microsoft and for each of you,'' Ballmer
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The internal memo, entitled ``Bullish About The Future,'' stated
bluntly that the company ``will not be broken up.'' Ballmer said
Microsoft had done ``great things for consumers and for the
American economy'' and had every reason to be left intact.
</P>
<P>
   His pitch won the support of two prominent politicians in
Washington state, Governor Gary Locke, a Democrat, and Senator
Slade Gorton, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support what the Justice Department is doing. I
believe what Microsoft is doing is good for the economy, good for
people,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Gorton suggested that a Republican in the White House
might slow down or halt the antitrust suit brought by the Justice
Department and 19 U.S. states.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such support can help Microsoft at this late hour _ a
breakup proposal is expected to be made by the end of the week _ is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of senior executives has left the company in recent
months, including Dan Rosen, general manager of new technology, who
announced his departure on Monday. That was the day Microsoft's
stock plunged 16 percent to barely more than half the $120 value
held last December.
</P>
<P>
   Several reports suggest the Justice Department wants to split
Microsoft in two, separating its Windows operating system from
software applications like Word and Excel.
</P>
<P>
   Although both units would remain monopolies in the first
instance, the theory is that the split would provide the incentive
for the mini-companies to make their products compatible with other
systems and software and so open up the market. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
