<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8970 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-48HOURS-NC1STTAKE30-C     04-27 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-48HOURS-NC1STTAKE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Museums, lush green spaces and a breakfast of biscuits and
red-eye gravy at Big Ed's _ it all comes together in this Piedmont
city that offers large dishes of Southern charm
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH _ Sir Walter would be proud. The North Carolina capital
city that bears his surname is positioning itself as a major
Southeastern cultural mecca this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the stunning $71 million North Carolina
Museum of Natural Sciences _ the largest natural history museum in
the Southeast _ opened downtown with a 24-hour bash that drew
45,000 mostly local visitors. Bicentennial Plaza links the new
building to the North Carolina Museum of History, where a new
exhibit, ``North Carolina Legends,'' delves into the colorful lives
of characters such as the pirate Blackbeard and
patriot-in-petticoats Mary Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a major exhibition of more than 110 Rodin sculptures
moved into _ and outside _ the suburban North Carolina Museum of
the Arts, launching a four-month citywide Festival Rodin that's
sure to bring a French accent to the Triangle area that includes
Durham and Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   And just six months ago, the $40.2 million Exploris _ an
interactive museum that celebrates cultural diversity _ brought the
world to Raleigh's doorstep. Families and school groups have been
beating a path to the 84,000-square-foot learning center ever since
to connect with people and places around the globe using advanced
technology.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you think Raleigh has gone uppity on us, take a
stroll across oak-shaded Moore Square to Big Ed's City Market
Restaurant, where the overalls-clad good ol' boy owner will quickly
bring you back down to the rich soil of the Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in town does down-home meet uptown with such agreeable
results. Big Ed's serves up country-cured ham, chicken and
dumplings and collards in the same block that encompasses not only
the City Market, which has been selling the land's bounty since
1914, but the trendy Moore Square Art District and restaurants
including the Greenshields Brewery and Pub.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent whirlwind 48 hours in the city of nearly
600,000, I was struck by its vitality and eager-to-impress attitude
as well as its abundant green space and immaculate appearance _
thanks in great part to the ubiquitous Clean and Safe Bicycle
Patrol, neatly attired in uniforms of yellow shirts and black
slacks.
</P>
<P>
   With all that's happening here, there's never been a better time
to lace up your sneakers and experience this wonderfully walkable
city _ whether for a weekend getaway or a couple of hooky-playing
weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon:
</P>
<P>
   Dig those dinos
</P>
<P>
   After jetting into Raleigh-Durham International Airport and
making a beeline along I-40 east into the city, I checked into the
Sheraton Capital Center, which is within walking distance of all
the downtown sites.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, I was whisked away to the Irish countryside for
lunch at Tir na Nog, a traditional pub named for the fabled
``County of Youth,'' where corned beef and cabbage, shepherd's pie
and Irish bread pudding share the menu with all-American fare. The
interior evokes the Old Sod with a stacked-stone wall, a
thatched-roof crofter's cottage and a wooden bar from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Once we were stoked for the afternoon, it was a six-block walk
to the 200,000-square-foot North Carolina Museum of Natural
Sciences for an encounter with a snarly character called the
Acrocanthosaurus _ Acro for short. Not to fear. It's just this bad
boy's 110-year-old fossilized bones. The only giant North American
carnivore of its time is the star of the new museum's piece de
resistance: ``Terror of the South,'' a dino battle scene complete
with sounds and special effects. Acro is attacking a massive
plant-eating sauropod _ eek! see the nasty gash on the flank of the
fleshed-out model _ as swooping pterosaurs soar overhead in the
three-story glass dome. The attack was re-created with the help of
actual track patterns that are displayed on the floor under glass.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Terror'' is the most dramatic exhibit in the seven-story
building, the museum's four exhibit floors are filled with wondrous
sights _ from the tiny ruby-throated hummingbird in the Natural
Treasures of North Carolina exhibit to the 65-foot-long blue whale
skeleton that hangs over the coastal exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Six days after opening, the place was crawling with
schoolchildren who learned about the biodiversity of their state as
they explored realistic dioramas that take visitors through five
habitats: hardwood swamps, coastal plain, Piedmont, mountains and
Alpine forest. The museum's ``Prehistoric North Carolina'' gallery
is home to the world's first dinosaur specimen with a heart. The
recent and much-ballyhooed discovery by museum scientists of a
66-million-year-old Thescelasaurus with a fossilized heart has shed
light on the hypothesis that dinosaurs were warm-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the 17-minute high-definition film ``Wilderness,'' an
amazing eye-to-eye encounter with the plants and animals of the
region with ambient sound that is perfectly in sync with the
images. The footage includes intimate views of a sea turtle laying
her eggs in a sand nest and a butterfly emerging from its cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night:
</P>
<P>
   Beefing up at the barn
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the Acro, but the meat-eater in me was in full
throttle as we pulled into the parking lot of the Angus Barn. There
was a filet mignon with my name on it in that big red barn on U.S.
70 west of downtown. The 40-year-old institution seats 650 and
fills up night after night. Don't let the rustic woods, blue and
white checked tablecloths, vintage quilts, straw-filled mangers on
the walls and barrels of red apples by the door fool you _ this is
an upscale steakhouse that boasts an 82-page wine list and holds
Wine Spectator magazine's Grand Award.
</P>
<P>
   Homemade crackers, pots of spreadable cheeses and a plate of
pickles, celery and olives arrive at the table to tide you over
until the meal arrives. Besides the de rigueur beef
($21.95-$34.95), there's barbecued little pig spare ribs, smoked
pork tenderloin and seafood.
</P>
<P>
   When the dessert tray arrived, it was hard to resist. We shared
chocolate chess pie and hot blackberry cobbler topped with ice
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, we toured the 55,000-bottle wine cellar and
popped into the Wild Turkey Lounge, where hundreds of turkey
whiskey decanters collected by late owner Thad Eure Jr. are
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning:
</P>
<P>
   Of mansions and men
</P>
<P>
   Docent Genelle Dail, a gracious Southern lady, was about to lead
us through the Executive Mansion, a grand Queen Anne Victorian
house built in 1891 and currently the home of Gov. Jim Hunt. But
first she just had to ask: ``Have you seen the new science museum?
Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's talking about the new kid in town, but even on a
rainy morning, a dozen or so were visiting the historic
34,806-square-foot mansion on five acres downtown. Entering the
home, we first noted the grand staircase of native heart pine and
16-foot ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Dail told us that the crimson and gold carpet in the Grand
Hallway was custom-made in Georgia. Names of North Carolina
governors are woven into the borders. Although upstairs is off
limits, we saw the elegant dining room with huge crystal
chandelier, the pink-toned ladies parlor and green gentlemen's
parlor across the hall, and the ballroom with ornate French
mirrors, gilded walls and a pair of Sheffield chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   While on tour I met Connie Winstead and her children Anna, 13,
and Daniel, 11, of nearby Greensboro, who were spending the week
exploring their capital. They had already hit the big museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to hear about Blackbeard,'' said Daniel
enthusiastically of his visit to the North Carolina Museum of
History.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and I love history,'' said Connie, ``so this has been
really neat to see. We've really enjoyed it.'' Added Anna: ``I like
all the old, fancy buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   She had certainly come to the right place _ this one's as fancy
as they come.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday morning:
</P>
<P>
   Rendezvous with Rodin
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the North Carolina Museum of Art on the curving
driveway that leads to the parking lot, we caught the first glimpse
of ``The Thinker'' on the front lawn. It was an exciting moment,
fueling my anticipation for the show inside: ``Rodin: Sculpture
From the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor Collection and Additional
Works.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of a 2,500-pound bronze cast of ``The Monument
to Victor Hugo'' _ one of only two in the world _ museum director
Lawrence J. Wheeler couldn't help but indulge in a bit of
boosterism during a preview showing. ``The most extraordinary
exhibition this museum has ever presented,'' he called it.
</P>
<P>
   He has a right to boast. More than 250,000 are expected to view
the most comprehensive selection of the French sculptor's work ever
seen in the Southeast _ and largest in the United States in two
decades _ during its four-month run.
</P>
<P>
   From my perspective _ as one who appreciates fine art but is no
art scholar _ the exhibition's power lies in the context its
organizers have provided.
</P>
<P>
   Selected Rodin works are juxtaposed with other sculptures from
the museum's permanent collection to illustrate how much the French
master was in tune with classicism.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the main Rodin exhibition gallery, several pieces are
shown alongside classical counterparts. For example, Rodin's
headless, handless ``Walking Man'' stands beside an eerily similar
Egyptian striding figure that was created 4,300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first piece inside the exhibition is ``The Age of Bronze,''
which is so naturalistic that Rodin was accused of making the mold
from a human body.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the curators have provided context with an enlarged
photograph of Rodin's ``Gates of Hell,'' inspired by Dante's
``Divine Comedy.'' The gates incorporate the well-known images of
``The Thinker,'' ``The Three Shades,'' frustrated lovers ``Paolo
and Francesca'' and ``The Creator,'' a self-portrait _ all
displayed in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case you can't bear to leave the Rodins behind, you
can take home a 12-inch ``Thinker'' bronze replica for $95. (A
``Get Bronzed'' beach towel will run you $32.)
</P>
<P>
   Playing the French theme to the hilt, Blue Ridge, The Museum
Restaurant, is featuring a special French menu with entrees ranging
from Poulet en Croute (chicken salad in a puff pastry) to Hoppin'
Jacques (a vegetarian black-eyed pea and rice burger).
</P>
<P>
   Too soon, it was time to go. C'est la vie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
