<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-48HOURS-NC2NDTAKE30-C     04-27 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-48HOURS-NC2NDTAKE30-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon:
</P>
<P>
   To market and beyond
</P>
<P>
   The 75-acre North Carolina State Farmer's Market is a rich
palette of red strawberries, yellow apples, orange Beauregard sweet
potatoes and green spears of fresh asparagus. We dropped in on our
way back to town and sampled slices of Pink Lady and Fuji apples.
</P>
<P>
   We were sorry that we had so little time to wander through the
North Carolina Museum of History _ I could have spent hours
exploring the folk life, the Civil War and ``Health and Healing''
exhibits. The new exhibit ``North Carolina Legends'' will appeal to
children who can turn oversize storybook pages to learn about the
first English child born in the New World (Virginia Dare), a
Cherokee fugitive who refused to walk the Trail of Tears (Tsali),
and a frontiersman you probably thought was a Kentucky native
(Daniel Boone).
</P>
<P>
   Tearing ourselves from the fabulous gift shop that features art
and crafts by North Carolina artists, we crossed the street to
visit the 1840 Greek Revival state Capitol, where a copy of Antonio
Canova's seated sculpture of George Washington wears a Roman
general's tunic, tightly fitted body armor and sandals. The General
Assembly has convened at the nearby State Legislature Building
since 1963, but the governor, his lieutenant governor and their
staffs still occupy the fortress-like Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon ended with a spin through the historic Oakwood
neighborhood, which reminded me of Atlanta's Grant Park and Inman
Park. Dozens of homes have been _ and are being _ renovated in this
National Historic District.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night:
</P>
<P>
   Anchors aweigh
</P>
<P>
   The 42nd Street Oyster Bar &AMP; Seafood Grill is another cavernous
eatery with something like 400 seats. It started humbly enough in
1931 as a grocery store that served oysters and beer on the side.
It's known as the place politicians chow down. The warehouse-like
setting features high ceilings, steel rafters and dark wood
furnishings and paneling. And the seafood couldn't be fresher. My
shrimp and scallop combo _ ``Norfolk style,'' sauteed in white
wine, butter and lemon juice _ was simple and simply delightful. Go
for a 42nd Street Cheese Potato as a side. And don't spoil your
appetite by popping too many of those hot hush puppies.
</P>
<P>
   The 42nd Street is located in the Powerhouse Square
entertainment district, home of an old power plant whose
out-of-service transformers are bathed in a purple glow. The area
has evolved into a yuppie dining mecca with popular spots such as
Ri-Ra Irish Pub, 518 West (Italian) and the Southend Brewery.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning:
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast at Big Ed's
</P>
<P>
   Big Ed's City Market Restaurant is the heart, if not the soul,
of the downtown entertainment district. The area is known not only
for its farmer's market (much smaller than the state market) but
for an eclectic mix of restaurants, a brew pub, gift and specialty
shops, galleries and Artspace, which holds artist studios and three
exhibition galleries in a former car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ed's is something of a museum itself, with farm implements,
gourds, baskets, tin signs and other bits of rural Americana
decking the walls and hanging from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But the real attraction is Big Ed himself _ Ed Watkins _ who
informed a diner, ``See all those plows out front? I've used every
one of them with a mule pulling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Ed concocts his own vinegar and pepper sauce and ``bottles''
it in rinsed-out plastic dishwashing detergent bottles. And if you
don't care for the blackstrap molasses he serves, he'll mix some up
with grape jelly and butter and insist that you dip a biscuit in
the concoction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about something that's gonna be good,'' he said as he
stirred his sticky creation. Before a breakfast of eggs and country
ham, biscuits and red-eye gravy was done, he was ordering up
samples of chicken and dumplings and collards being prepared for
lunch. When I mentioned I've never liked collards, he made me
squirt some of his pepper-vinegar on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody from out of town comes in here,'' he says, ``I
bust their belly open.''
</P>
<P>
   Still don't like collards, but the country ham's a winner _ and
I told him so. ``I have it cured to my great-granddaddy's recipe.
And I use his sausage recipe, too. He was a mess sergeant in the
Rebel Army. Name was Ransom Gully.''
</P>
<P>
   No big surprise that Big Ed has had his arteries unclogged
several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cardiologist says, `You stop 'em up, I clean 'em out,''' he
said, before hollering for the waitress to bring over more
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday morning:
</P>
<P>
   We are the world
</P>
<P>
   After feasting at Big Ed's trough, we lumbered across Moore
Square to Exploris and in minutes we were transported from the farm
to the far-flung corners of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The hands-on science center with a cultural focus opened in
October, with the mission to help young people respect differences,
appreciate similarities and make connections.
</P>
<P>
   Kids (and adults, too) can poke through Culture Boxes, giant
drawers filled with objects from the daily lives of people around
the world _ a pair of rubber thongs, school supplies, a piece of
clothing, a toy. The idea is to guess where the person lives whose
belongings are in the drawer. They can weave a pattern on a loom,
write poetry and create a Web site. In the environmental area, they
can see how Exploris' Living Machine cleans water using plants and
fish. And they can stop by vending machines that feature
international snacks and beverages.
</P>
<P>
   In Many Voices, kids learn how to make their voice heard and
make a difference in the world. Interactive stations provide them
with the resources to get involved with issues in the news and vote
on matters of global importance. Live news broadcasts from 42
countries can be viewed. Here, too, visitors can look at a 4-ton
section of the Berlin Wall and ponder whether they've ever ``broken
through a wall'' of any kind. In June, a special exhibition, ``From
the Pen of Anne Frank,'' will open in the One Voice Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday afternoon:
</P>
<P>
   The finish line
</P>
<P>
   Time to leave Raleigh was nearing, but we had two more
restaurants we wanted to check out. Still bustin' at the seams from
Big Ed's, three of us decided to sample a pork and chicken platter
at Clyde Cooper's Barbecue, which has been serving up the vinegary
North Carolina-style 'cue since 1938. We bellied up to the Formica
counter, had two bites each and were on our way.
</P>
<P>
   At Caffe Luna, a little corner of Tuscany with sun-splash yellow
and terra-cotta walls, we tried an Insalata del Pastore (warm goat
cheese with walnuts over mesclun greens) and a serving of tiramisu.
</P>
<P>
   By then, we were waving our white napkins in surrender to
cultural overload and excessive cuisine. Raleigh, we decided,
really is a city of plenty.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   The 14-day advance purchase fare is $112 round trip on AirTran,
Delta and Midway.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOMMODATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Sheraton Capital Center is a good choice if you want to stay
downtown (421 S. Salisbury St., 919-834-9900); Crabtree Summit
Hotel, a small boutique hotel near Crabtree Village shopping area,
is a suburban jewel (3908 Arrow Drive, 1-800-521-7521). Most
national chains are represented in the area.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Greater Raleigh Convention and Visitors Bureau, 1-800-849-8499;
www.raleighcvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS/ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences: 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Mondays-
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays. Free. 11 W. Jones St.
919-733-1573; www.naturalsciences.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Carolina Museum of History: 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays. Free. 5 E. Edenton St.
919-733-8655; nchistory.dcr.state.nc.us/museums.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Carolina Museum of Art: 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Thursdays; 9 a.m.-10 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays; 11 a.m.-7
p.m. Sundays. $7.50; $5.50 senior citizens and students; free for
12 and under. To charge by phone: 919-715-5923 (add $2 per ticket
on credit card orders). 2110 Blue Ridge Road. 919-839-6262;
www.ncartmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exploris: 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays, noon-5 p.m.
Sundays. $6.95 adults; $5.95 senior citizens; $4.95 ages 4-11. 201
