<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-RODIN30-COX     04-27 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODIN30-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodin festivities accent celebration of arts
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 30.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Crouch Thrasher
</P>
<P>
   The slogan for Festival Rodin is ``Come for the exhibition _
stay for the celebration.'' And with just about every cultural
institution in the Triangle area involved, it has shaped up to be
quite a party.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-week Festival Rodin _ including opera, symphony, theater,
film, dance, lectures and even a French circus _ began April 15
with the opening of ``Rodin: Sculpture From the Iris and B. Gerald
Cantor Collection and Other Works'' at the North Carolina Museum of
Art. The festivities continue until the exhibition closes Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Second Annual Louisiana Dance Party: Singer-songwriter Marcia
Ball leads the festivities, which also feature the Zydeco rhythms
of Geno Delafose and French Rockin' Boogie. 7:30 p.m. May 19.
Joseph M. Bryan Jr. Theater in Museum Park. $15. At Ticketmaster or
by calling 919-834-4000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jean-Luc Ponty: The Triangle's Lenny Marcus Trio opens for the
noted jazz violinist. 8 p.m. June 2. Joseph M. Bryan Jr. Theater in
Museum Park. $15-$20. At Ticketmaster or by calling 919-834-4000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Movies on the Lawn: The museum's summer outdoor film series
takes a French twist with screenings of Francois Truffaut's ``The
400 Blows'' on May 20; ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' (the 1999 remake
in which a blase billionaire steals a Monet) on May 26-27; and
Jacques Tati's ``Mr. Hulot's Holiday'' on June 3. 9 p.m. Tickets
are $4 and $2. 919-715-5923.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cabaret &AMP; Rodin, Mis en Vie'': In this presentation of the
Carolina Ballet, cabaret singer Andrea Marcovicci teams with
choreographer Lynne Taylor-Corbett on a new show. Then, Rodin's
sculptures come to life with Margo Sappington's choreography for
``Rodin, Mis en Vie.'' $10-$56. 8 p.m. June 1-4; 3 p.m. June 3-4.
Raleigh Memorial Auditorium. 919-303-6303; www.carolinaballet.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Les Colporteurs presents ``Filao'': The intimate Cirque de
Soleil-style French circus _ a one-ring ``nouveau cirque'' from
Paris _ puts up its 50-foot-tall candy-striped tent on the museum
grounds. Based on Italo Calvino's novella ``The Roosted Baron,''
the production literally explores the precariousness of life ``at
the top'' as it tells the tale of a lonely anarchist who has
shunned society to live in the treetops. 8 p.m. June 18-July 2
(except June 21, 26 and 30). $35. At Ticketmaster or by calling
919-834-4000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Madama Butterfly'': The Opera Company of North Carolina
presents the Puccini masterpiece featuring Maryanne Telese as the
beautiful young geisha who sacrifices everything to marry an
American naval officer. 8 p.m. June 23 and 2 p.m. June 25. Raleigh
Memorial Auditorium. $14-$56.50. At Ticketmaster or by calling
919-834-4000.
</P>
<P>
   For a list of festival events, visit www.FestivalRodin.com or
call 1-877-627-6346. Ask for a brochure detailing special value
Festival Rodin Weekend Getaways, two-night packages starting at $70
per person. To book, call AAA Vacations at 1-800-933-2621.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
