<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The great `Run' of Joe Cassidy, cold warrior
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 30.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day in February of 1959 an Army sergeant named Joe Cassidy
crushed an orange crayon beneath his heel on the sidewalk in front
of a photography store in Washington. The next day he walked along
a residential street in suburban Maryland, a pipe in his mouth, a
book in his hand. A passer-by was to ask him if there was a theater
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Once he did, contact would be made.
</P>
<P>
   Before any dead drops are made, the dance of espionage proceeds
by what looks like chance encounter and signals as inconspicuous as
a smashed crayon. As it happened, Cassidy had to crush rather a lot
of crayons and stroll along that street in Maryland with his pipe
and his book for many days running, with no one asking directions
to the movie. A mole gets used to being stood up. Traffic might be
heavy. The telephone can't be trusted. Precaution, sometimes,
forces cancellation of plans without notice.
</P>
<P>
   Delicately, other means are pursued, but in Cassidy's case it
was as direct as a note dropped off at the Soviet embassy in
Washington. ``There were some kids, maybe 10 or 12 years old,'' he
told David Wise, ``playing on the street.'' Don Gruentzel, an FBI
agent, called one of them to the car, gave him the note and asked
him to take it to the embassy door. ``Don gave him 50 cents,''
Cassidy told Wise. ``I said, `Maybe you should have given him the
50 cents when he came back.'''
</P>
<P>
   The note said, ``I'm back from Korea. I'm the person you were
involved with at (Fort) Belvoir.'' And there was a telephone
number. A few days later, Cassidy's phone rang at Edgewood Arsenal.
Contact was re-established.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy, a man who was never trained as a spy, who in 1959
earned a high school equivalency degree 24 years after dropping out
of the ninth grade, was back in business, a double agent spying on
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of living a double life
</P>
<P>
   ``Cassidy's Run: The Secret Spy War Over Nerve Gas'' is less a
story about biological warfare than the improbable tale of a man
who had the Soviet Union's confidence for more than 20 years.
During that time, the FBI _ through Cassidy _ piece by piece gave
the Soviets nerve gas information, some of it real, some of it
fake. The aim was to learn who the Soviet Union's spies in the
United States were and to throw its intelligence operations off
track. Cassidy was the dangled bait, working in a U.S. defense
plant, steadily promoted to more responsible jobs, living a double
life. When he left it, 10 Soviet spies had been flushed out and two
FBI agents had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Espionage has been called the world's second oldest profession,
and the end of cold war did not put spies all out of work. But Cold
War espionage had a dramatic quality hard to duplicate. In the
seamless, morally ambiguous worlds of John le Carre and Len
Deighton, mole and handler understood that betrayal was relative
and trust contingent.
</P>
<P>
   It did not always work that way in real life. Ordinary people
like Joe Cassidy went through divorces, worried about appearing
nervous and never, for one moment, doubted the rightness of what
they were doing. Wives, like Julie Kirkland and Letitia Basford,
grieved for 20 years after the small plane in which their husbands
were monitoring the movements of a University of Minnesota
professor spying for the Soviet Union crashed into a lake, killing
Mark Kirkland and another FBI agent, Tren Basford.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting this tangled tale, Wise goes forward and backward and
then forward again, the seams of his narrative as jarring as speed
bumps. But between one bump and the next, it's taut with
straightforward reportage about code encryption, ``hollow rocks''
hiding classified material and Cassidy's relationship with a
succession of Mikes _ Soviets who trusted him so completely that
one of them, on leaving for reassignment back to the Soviet Union,
kissed him on the cheek with tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition after 15 years
</P>
<P>
   If Cassidy's double life had its harrowing side, it had its
bizarre moments as well. Outside the government, no one besides
Cassidy's second wife knew. But those few in the government who
knew decided, after 15 years, that Cassidy's service merited
recognition. The problem was that recognition would have to be
secret, like everything else in Cassidy's life. Nonetheless,
arrangements were made for Cassidy to be quietly presented a medal
in the White House by President Nixon. But Nixon resigned and
Cassidy had to settle for Gen. Creighton Abrams, chief of staff of
the U.S. Army. ``I didn't care it wasn't the president,'' Cassidy,
79, and living in Florida, told Wise. ``I was surprised I was going
to get anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would, briefly. Abrams pinned the medal on Cassidy and
congratulated him. With five FBI agents who had been his handlers
for 15 years, Cassidy and his wife stood for a photograph.
``Everyone was smiling,'' Wise writes.
</P>
<P>
   And then Abrams took the medal back. The spy was returned to the
cold, where he remained, unsuspected, another six years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cassidy's Run: The Secret Spy War Over Nerve Gas. By David
Wise. Random House. $25. 228 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
