<HEADER>
A8975 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-     04-27 2790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``28 Days'' PG-13 (profanity, substance
</P>
<P>
   abuse and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Viggo Mortensen.
</P>
<P>
   The cinema's chipper girl next door (Sandra Bullock) goes clean
and sober in an addiction and rehab movie that, thankfully, isn't
an appalling clinical ``comedy'' like ``Patch Adams.'' It's a
professional, appealing comedy-drama, but in trying to be all
things to all viewers (to beer-loving Bullock fans as well as
devoted 12-steppers), it never really comes into focus. (SM)1 hour,
43 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``All About My Mother'' R (profanity, sexuality, drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cecilia Roth,
</P>
<P>
   Marisa Paredes,
</P>
<P>
   and Penelope Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar: foreign film. Spain's bad-boy filmmaker Pedro Almodovar
grows up with this humane celebration of nurturing women. A tribute
to actresses (of all kinds), ``All About My Mother'' is a virtually
male-free fable with a title inspired by that backstage classic,
``All About Eve.'' Dark and tender in equal measures, the movie
beautifully balances humor and heartache. In Spanish with
subtitles. (SM)1 hour, 41 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' R (strong sexuality, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   violence and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey
</P>
<P>
   and Annette Bening.
</P>
<P>
   5 Oscars: picture, actor (Kevin Spacey), director, original
screenplay, cinematography. The ever-more-remarkable Spacey plays a
man caught in a midlife limbo in this scarily disturbing, daringly
hilarious, well-written and well-acted comedy-drama. It's a
hauntingly optimistic elegy for America the Beautifully Screwed Up.
(ERG) 1 hour, 58 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``American Psycho'' R (profanity, violence, sexuality,
</P>
<P>
   and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christian Bale
</P>
<P>
   and Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   Director Mary Harron (``I Shot Andy Warhol'') has taken Bret
Easton Ellis' controversial book about a Wall Street serial killer
and created a visually chilly but often very funny satire of
American greed. It's a critique of '80s me-first narcissism,
embodied by an antihero (a well-chiseled Christian Bale) whose
refined taste in clothing and health-care products is matched by
his extensive repertoire as a killer. (SM) 1 hour, 40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and White'' R (violence, sexuality and language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bijou Phillips,
</P>
<P>
   Robert Downey Jr., Brooke Shields
</P>
<P>
   and Ben Stiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and White'' is the latest from writer-director James
Toback, a hit-or-miss auteur. Hit: the screenplay for ``Bugsy.''
Miss: his last movie, ``Two Guys and a Girl.'' He gives you energy,
attitude and a big sloppy mess of a movie in ``Black.'' It's not a
very good or intelligent movie, but it's a topical powder keg
likely to launch arguments and discussions more complex and
sophisticated than the film. (SM) 1 hour 40 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' PG-13 (nudity,
</P>
<P>
   substance abuse, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Caine
</P>
<P>
   and Tobey Maguire.
</P>
<P>
   2 Oscars: adapted screenplay, supporting actor (Michael Caine).
John Irving adapted his own novel. In the first half, Dr. Larch
(Caine) delivers babies and performs illegal abortions in his Maine
orphanage. In the second, less-engaging half, Larch's protege,
Homer Wells (Tobey Maguire), runs off to learn about the world.
(ERG)2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``East Is East'' R (profanity
</P>
<P>
   and domestic violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Om Puri
</P>
<P>
   and Linda Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   Set in working-class Britain in 1971, this uneven but energetic
film focuses on a boisterous Anglo-Pakistani family. The father is
a tyrannical type, while the mother is a grounded fish-and-chips
Englishwoman. And the kids are totally caught up in the exploding
England Swings pop-culture surrounding them. The very good cast,
headed by Om Puri and Linda Bassett, is a huge asset. (ERG)1 hour,
36 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Roberts
</P>
<P>
   and Albert Finney.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts delivers in a funny, down-to-earth film about an
everyday mom with business spunk who, without a law degree but with
a lot of pluck, helps crash a big-time company responsible for
devastating health problems in a small, dirt-poor town. Call it
``Working-Class Girl.'' (Bob Longino)2 hours, 11 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency'' PG-13 (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Dennis Quaid
</P>
<P>
   and Jim Caviezel.
</P>
<P>
   John Sullivan (Jim Caviezel) hears dead people. Specifically, he
hooks up to his dad's old ham radio set in 1999 and finds himself
talking to his dad (Dennis Quaid) in 1969. More crucially, John
knows his dad, a fireman, will be killed in a failed heroic rescue
the next day. Although over-plotted, the sentimental film has that
``what if?'' fascination. It's also a mind-bender and especially
savvy about emotional button-pushing. (ERG)2 hours. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gendernauts'' Unrated (contains frank sexual
</P>
<P>
   talk, nudity and sexual footage)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   by Monika Treut.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet but shallow look at the Bay Area's transgendered
community, preaching entirely to the converted. (SM) Noon, 2, 4, 6,
8 and 10 p.m.; $3, $5 after 6 p.m. Cinefest (Georgia State
University). 404-651-2463. 1 hour, 27 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gossip'' R (sexual content,
</P>
<P>
   profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Lena Headey
</P>
<P>
   and James Marsden.
</P>
<P>
   Don't waste your breath or your time. The latest cynical bid for
</P>
<P>
   teenagers' pocket change, this film features the requisite hot
WB star (Joshua Jackson) backed by hunky/pretty co-stars as college
students whose class project on slander snowballs into a rape
charge. It wants to be a mix of ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' ``Shallow
Grave'' and ``Disclosure,'' but it's tin-eared and shallow. (SM)1
hour, 30 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on Earth'' PG-13 (sensuality
</P>
<P>
   and thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chris Klein,
</P>
<P>
   Leelee Sobieski and Josh Hartnett.
</P>
<P>
   A limp and clueless variation on ``Love Story.'' Leelee
Sobieski, Chris Klein and Josh Hartnett star as kids in a love
triangle. Trapped in this hermetically sealed setting, with a
script that would run 10 minutes if the cliches were yanked out of
it, they can't win. (SM)1 hour, 37 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack,
</P>
<P>
   Iben Hjejle and Jack Black.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly dumped by his longtime girlfriend, record-store owner
Rob (John Cusack) rhetorically asks himself, ``What came first _
music or the misery?'' In other words, does he listen to songs
about heartbreak because he's miserable, or is he miserable because
he's listening to these songs? ``High Fidelity'' is as smart as it
is enjoyable. It's a great date movie about dating. (SM)1 hour, 54
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' R ( language and brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian Holm
</P>
<P>
   and Stanley Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gould was a colorful eccentric, who roamed the streets in
the '40s, dividing his time between flophouses and an in-circuit of
celebrity parties, all the while going on about his great work.
Gould became ``famous'' when he was profiled by genteel New Yorker
essayist Joe Mitchell. The overall impression is a kind of New
Yorker sketch of a movie. Spare, mystifying, yet with a lingering
impact. (ERG) 1 hour, 48 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping the Faith'' PG-13 (profanity, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Stiller,
</P>
<P>
   Edward Norton and Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, it's a sweet-natured hymn to love and longtime
friendship. Edward Norton (as a priest) and Ben Stiller (as a
rabbi) are pals whose childhood friend (Jenna Elfman) returns to
catch both their eyes in more than a friendly way. The first 90
minutes have charm, a sophisticated sexiness and some nice, offbeat
bits. Then things start to crash. (SM) 2 hours, 9 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last September'' R (brief sexuality and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Maggie Smith,
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gambon and Keeley Hawes.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1920s, this movie is a charming, well-dressed mess.
As the clashes between the Irish rebels and the British soldiers
grow worse, Sir Richard and Lady Myra (Michael Gambon and Maggie
Smith) and their assorted house guests keep holding their tennis
parties. Meanwhile their niece (Keeley Hawes) becomes romantically
involved with both sides of the conflict. (ERG)1 hour, 44 minutes.
C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Basketball'' PG-13 (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Omar Epps
</P>
<P>
   and Sanaa Lathan.
</P>
<P>
   All's not fair in love or basketball is one of several themes in
this flawed but appealing romance. Q (Omar Epps) and Monica (Sanaa
Lathan) meet as kids and rival basketball players. They realize
throughout the film that they love each other as much as the game.
Director Gina Price-Bythewood (her producer is Spike Lee) may not
have scored a slam dunk, but she comes close thanks to her engaging
stars. (ERG) 1 hour, 58 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Me Myself I'' R (sexuality and language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Rachel Griffiths
</P>
<P>
   and David Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   An engaging ``what-if?'' fantasy about the life not lived.
Rachel Griffiths (an Oscar nominee for ``Hilary and Jackie'') makes
an art of benumbed comic reaction as she finds herself trapped in a
nightmare of domesticity, trapped in one of two parallel lives.
``Me'' could be called a chick flick. But it gives its heroine
intelligence, self analysis and a healthy sex drive that leads to
some of the movie's funnier scenes. (SM)1 hour, 44 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Mifune'' R (profanity, violence, and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Iben Hjejle
</P>
<P>
   and Anders W. Berthelsen.
</P>
<P>
   In Danish with subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   An engaging Danish comedy/drama about an unusual household.
Think of mixing ``Pretty Woman'' and ``Snow White and the Seven
Dwarfs,'' and you've get an idea of the quirky tone. Shot only with
available light and natural sound _ with no special effects or
extreme action _ it's a solid reminder that good movies don't need
gimmicks, just an interesting story and appealing actors. (SM) 1
hour, 39 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' PG ( sci-fi violence and mild language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gary Sinise,
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins and Don Cheadle.
</P>
<P>
   Brian De Palma's Red Planet opus is too much like other films
(``Contact,'' ``The Abyss'' and, especially, ``2001: A Space
Odyssey''), but it's still a decent popcorn movie packed with
thrills and sharp special effects. Gary Sinise, Tim Robbins, Connie
Nielsen and Jerry O'Connell are part of an astronaut team trying to
rescue others lost on Mars. (SM) 1 hour, 53 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip'' PG (violent content and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Frankie Muniz,
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lane and Kevin Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the late Willie Morris' memoir about growing up in
small-town 1940s Mississippi, this family film is aremembrance of
how things can pass from our lives but never really leave us.
Nine-year-old Willie (``Malcolm in the Middle's'' Frankie Muniz) is
a shy only child whose life changes when his mom (Diane Lane) gives
him a Jack Russell terrier puppy, despite dad's (Kevin Bacon)
objection. (ERG)1 hour, 35 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' R (profanity and sci-fi violence and gore)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vin Diesel
</P>
<P>
   and Radha Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry aliens, stupid humans: the usual. ``Pitch Black'' is just
the latest sci-fi rip-off of ``Aliens,'' packed with caricatures.
In the movie's last hour, writer-director David Twohy pretends to
explore his stick figures' moral choices, and he forgets to deliver
the thrills. (SM)1 hour, 47 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Me'' PG (mild violence and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Duchovny
</P>
<P>
   and Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be Hollywood's first organ-transplant romance,
bereaved widower David Duchovny falls for shy heart-transplant
recipient Minnie Driver, unaware that his beloved first wife's
ticker is beating inside her chest. Duchovny is actually rather
wonderful here, with a sweet pensive romanticism. But Driver
herself just doesn't seem worthy of Duchovny. (ERG)1 hour, 56
minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' PG (mild thematic material
</P>
<P>
   and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Animated film featuring the voices
</P>
<P>
   of Kevin Kline and Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Not cute enough for kids, not clever enough for adults,
DreamWorks' latest animated feature is gorgeous but curiously dull.
Kenneth Branagh and Kevin Kline are the voices of a couple of
16th-century scam artists looking for the Lost City of Gold in the
New World. The movie fuses visual splendor with unsteady
storytelling and tone. The waterfalls are beautiful, but the movie
is a washout. (SM)1 hour, 23 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement'' R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tommy Lee Jones
</P>
<P>
   and Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement'' is another military flick that climaxes
in a courtroom, where soldiers shout out conflicting reports of
what really happened in the heat of battle. ``Rules'' is laughable,
but it's watchable thanks to the leads. Tommy Lee Jones is the
flick's anchor. And Samuel L. Jackson delivers an on-the-stand
blow-up like Jack Nicholson's ``You-can't-handle-the-truth''
bluster from ``A Few Good Men.'' (SM)2 hours, 7 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' R (profanity and strong horror violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Arquette, Courteney Cox Arquette and Neve
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a scream anymore, but it's a decent wrap-up of the
series. Neve Campbell, Courteney Cox Arquette and David Arquette
are all back and on the Hollywood set of ``Stab 3,'' ducking the
knife-swings of a killer clad in the familiar Halloween get-up. The
new movie isn't as clever with its clues as the others, but it
manages to wheeze its way across the finish line, wrapping up the
trilogy in satisfying fashion. (SM) 1 hour, 56 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skulls'' PG-13 (violence and brief sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joshua Jackson
</P>
<P>
   and Paul Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In this conspiracy thriller for the Clearasil set, the WB's
Joshua Jackson plays an average Joe sucked into an elite, monied
club. It comes with a price, though. Like he can't ever get out.
(SM)1 hour, 47 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tigger Movie'' G
</P>
<P>
   Animated feature with
</P>
<P>
   Tigger, Pooh, Baby Roo, Piglet, etc.
</P>
<P>
   This charming animated feature clearly knows its intended tot
audience and takes care of them. The irrepressible, ever-bouncing
Tigger goes searching for his family and discovers his real family
isn't necessarily other Tiggers. Pooh, Piglet, Baby Roo and the
whole A.A. Milne gang are back, as are the Sherman brothers (``Mary
Poppins''), who wrote the sprightly songs. As Tigger himself would
say, it's tiggerific. (ERG)1 hour, 16 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571'' PG-13 (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew McConaughey,
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel, Bill Paxton
</P>
<P>
   and Jon Bon Jovi.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey leads a reconnaissance mission to take over
a damaged German sub and capture the secret Nazi coding device
that's confounding U.S. efforts to win the war. Despite a
predictable script, blatant cliches and a penchant for
chest-beating fanfare music, ``U-571'' has plenty of furious
action, occasional suspense and lots of super-loud booms. It's no
``Das Boot,'' but it can suck you in. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 56
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Heart Is'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Natalie Portman
</P>
<P>
   and Ashley Judd.
</P>
<P>
   A cornpone comedy-drama about a single mom, made with enough
polish to be a guilty pleasure. Natalie Portman plays the pregnant
teen who heads for California and winds up becoming the Wal-Mart
Mom in Oklahoma. She gets good support from Stockard Channing,
Ashley Judd and Sally Field. (SM) 2 hours. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Money Is'' PG-13 (sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Paul Newman,
</P>
<P>
   Linda Fiorentino
</P>
<P>
   and Dermot Mulroney.
</P>
<P>
   This clever caper comedy is a wry, laid-back throwaway that's
surprisingly engaging. It probably helps that the leads are Paul
Newman and Linda Fiorentino, who have a delicious chemistry. He's a
convicted bank robber rendered catatonic by a stroke and
temporarily sent to a nursing home. She's the nurse assigned to him
who suspects he's pulling a fast one. On the whole the film is just
darn pleasant. (ERG) 1 hour, 30 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Is not Enough'' PG-13 (violence, sexuality
</P>
<P>
   and innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pierces Brosnan, Sophie Marceau and Robert Carlyle.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, even a game Pierce Brosnan and a classy director (Michael
Apted) aren't enough to save the 19th 007 movie from being more of
the same old same old. Bond is assigned by M (Judi Dench) to
protect an heiress (Sophie Marceau) and her oil pipeline from a
terrorist (Robert Carlyle). There's the usual eye-popping opening
stunt sequence. (ERG)2 hours, 8 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
