<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-1000(     04-27 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACROSS THE LONE STAR STATE, OLD HOTELS SHINE WITH A NEWLY POLISHED
PATINA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by OLD HOTELS-OTHERS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past two years, as new owners completed a $12 million
renovation of Houston's The Warwick hotel, they made room for many
of the accouterments acquired over the hotel's 75 years. In the
lobby, pieces of the heavy wood paneling _ actually, 1700s-era
carved woodwork brought over piece by piece from French chateaux _
were polished and restored and hung separately, like museum pieces,
with little lights framing each one just so.
</P>
<P>
   Antique settees and massive oak tables were restored to glory
and placed back in the lobby; ornate candelabras and an original
Remington sculpture were polished and displayed anew. The exterior
was returned from bland white to the original rich terra-cotta
color. And designers found a special place to hang an 18th-century
French tapestry, a museum-quality treasure that the wife of
one-time owner John Mecom had bought on a European shopping
expedition to upgrade the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But if you know where to look, you'll notice that the precious
artwork looks just a bit unbalanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got it over here, it just didn't fit the space they
intended it for,'' explains general manager Mark Peterson, with a
rueful chuckle. ``So they just cut a piece off.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably every hotel of a certain age has a few little quirks
like this _ a reason many travelers find historic hotels more
interesting than the cookie-cutter chain operations that dot every
interstate highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a resurgent interest in our older hotels, and
I think that's because of the great increase in heritage tourism,''
says Carter Schildknecht, president of Historic and Hospitality
Accommodations of Texas, which counts as members many of Texas'
smaller historic inns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk into one of these historic hotels, you get a
feel for where you are. It's just the fact that you can see what it
looked like back then, and you get a sense of how people lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has supported and preserved a number of its older hotels,
many surviving from the days before about 1930 when nearly all
towns had at least one hotel, Schildknecht says. Just in the last
two years, Austin's Driskill Hotel, Houston's The Warwick and
Galveston's Galvez have all undergone multimillion-dollar
face-lifts. Smaller hotels are part of the boom, too. In
Waxahachie, for instance, the once-grand Rogers Hotel, closed since
the '60s, is due to reopen this summer, with 27 upscale renovated
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   From San Antonio's Menger Hotel (where Teddy Roosevelt recruited
his Rough Riders in the bar) to Marfa's Paisano Hotel (where James
Dean and the rest of the cast stayed while filming ``Giant''),
these historic hotels are full of stories. Here's a look at our
favorite 10.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: The Warwick
</P>
<P>
   City: Houston
</P>
<P>
   Then: In continuous operation longer than any other hotel in
Houston (which loves to tear things down almost as much as Dallas
does), The Warwick was built in 1925. (Some accounts place it in
1926.) Its location, adjacent to leafy Hermann Park and the Museum
of Fine Arts, Houston, helped it attract an upscale following. But
it really bloomed in the late '50s when the John Mecom family
bought it, renovated it and fashioned it into a luxury property,
complete with French antiques and five-star service.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel fell on hard times in the '80s; it was foreclosed on
by its bank, sold to a foreign company and essentially ignored. By
the mid-'90s, it was tired and threadbare, and rooms were going for
the same rate as at a discount motel.
</P>
<P>
   Now: The hotel, purchased by a Dallas company in 1998 and now a
part of the Park Plaza International chain, emerged from a
two-year, $12 million renovation in the fall of 1999 with
completely overhauled guest rooms (including baths with the best
hotel showers we've found), a luxe new bar and an elegantly
refurbished pool on the second-floor deck.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Presidents Jimmy Carter, Gerald Ford and Lyndon
B. Johnson; the Duke and Duchess of Windsor; Princess Grace; Bill
Cosby; Bob Hope; Andy Warhol; Sonny and Cher; Ella Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 308 guest rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $189,
double. (800) 670-7275 or (713) 526-1991; www.parkhtls.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Driskill Hotel
</P>
<P>
   City: Austin
</P>
<P>
   Then: The pre-eminent hotel in Austin, this 1886 structure has,
as you'd expect, many political ties. Lyndon Johnson took Lady Bird
here for their first date, a breakfast in the dining room; LBJ
later made a tradition of waiting out election results here.
Governors from Ma Ferguson to Ann Richards staged their inaugural
balls in the hotel's lavish ballrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel was originally built as the ``frontier palace'' of
cattle baron Jesse Driskill, who owned the hotel for only a year
before selling it due to bankruptcy. A series of owners added
eccentric and/or elegant touches to the hotel, including a women's
spa and Turkish bath (1909) and the Maximilian Room (1930), named
for its crowning feature, eight gold-leaf framed mirrors that were
wedding gifts from the emperor of Mexico to his wife. But the
hotel's fortunes rose and fell; in 1969, it was literally saved
from the wrecking ball by a last-minute grassroots effort by Austin
residents. Through the '70s and '80s, it underwent a series of
small-scale renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Now: A sweeping $35 million restoration, begun three years ago,
has resulted in a stunning hotel, combining turn-of-the century
decor with new features. The lobby's new, intricate marble floor
contrasts with antique oil paintings, the original 3-story columns
and a stained-glass domed ceiling. Public spaces are filled with
new overstuffed leather sofas and Texas-themed lamps and tables but
retain the pressed-tin ceilings. The final touches, a fitness
center and a rooftop pool, are due to open in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 205 rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $205, double;
(512) 474-5911; www.driskillhotel.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
