<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SHOWS CONTINUED STRONG ECONOMIC GROWTH, WORRYING INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, we expect a writethru lede later in the evening)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The American economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual
rate in the first three months of the year, federal officials said
Thursday in an announcement that produced some jitters.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the Commerce Department's latest data was yet
another indication of what most people already knew: The economy is
vibrant, and people have money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts worry that the economy needs to be reined in
to prevent a sharp rise in inflation. Their fears were heightened
by another government report, from the Labor Department, which
showed that wages and benefits for American workers went up 4.3
percent between March 1999 and last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department report said the 5.4 percent rise in the
gross domestic product, or the total output of goods and services,
was fueled in part by an increase in consumer spending and by sharp
increases in energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   At the Labor Department, the increase in the Employment Cost
Index, which measures employers' costs for benefits to their
employees as well as wages and salaries, was the largest in eight
years _ good news for workers in general, perhaps, but perhaps not
for those who worry about the economy from a broader perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that runaway growth could worsen inflation, the Federal
Reserve has raised interest rates a quarter-point several times in
recent months, and few economists would be surprised if it raised
them again when it meets on May 16, and perhaps again in June.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's economic news may have contributed to pessimism on
Wall Street, where both the Dow Jones industrial average and the
Nasdaq index were off sharply by midday, though Nasdaq closed the
day with a good gain.
</P>
<P>
   As for the prediction that Thursday's indicators would cause
indigestion at the Fed, that was not immediately apparent. The Fed
chairman, Alan Greenspan, whose every utterance is weighed for
possible hints about interest rates, offered no clues Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was in Kansas City speaking at a conference on the
future of rural America. His remarks did not seem tailored to raise
fear, or any other emotion, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite apart from the effects of a changing farm economy, rural
towns and villages are likely to experience, within their local
jurisdictions, a good bit of change in economic structure'' because
of new technologies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-THEATER-REVIEW-AIDA-H     04-27 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-AIDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISNEY LOOKS FOR OLD MAGIC OF `LION KING,' BUT COMES UP SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT HURWITT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walt Disney and Julie Taymor are back on Broadway
again,
</P>
<P>
   but not together this time. Not, of course, unless you count the
continued presence of their joint blockbuster ``The Lion King,''
which will still be prowling the Pridelands long after their
current projects have revolved out of sight in the Circle of Life.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's disappointing ``Aida,'' which opened in March at the
Palace Theatre (where Walt Disney Productions broke into Broadway
in '94 with ``Beauty and the Beast''), is actually the newer of the
two ventures. And it could more accurately be labeled a cub of the
``Lion,'' given the repeat participation of composer Elton John,
lyricist Tim Rice, co-author Linda Woolverton, producers Peter
Schneider and Thomas Schumacher and the show's dynamic star,
Heather Headley.
</P>
<P>
   Taymor's ``The Green Bird,'' which opened last week at the Cort,
is a remounting of a show she's staged before with most of the same
collaborators _ in '96 at the New Victory Theater, just across the
street from the New Amsterdam where ``Lion`` reigns. It isn't a
great ``Bird,`` but it flies a lot higher than it did before.
</P>
<P>
   A Broadway debut for original producer Theatre for a New
Audience (co-presenting with Ostar Enterprises), it's very much the
same show with some script tweaking by Eric Overmyer, new
choreography by Daniel Ezralow and some heightened production
values. It's still pretty thin, but it contains more of Taymor's
trademark stage magic. And it's highly entertaining for most of its
two hours and 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of its problems are inherent in the script, a late 18th
century Venetian fable by Carlo Gozzi in a colloquial translation
by Albert Bermel and Ted Emery. A wildly fanciful sequel to his
``The Love of Three Oranges,' it was written to satirize the French
philosophers of the Enlightenment and promote faith in the Church
and aristocracy. Much of that material, and some of Gozzi's comedy,
doesn't translate very well from his time to ours.
</P>
<P>
   What does work very well in Taymor's hands, is Gozzi's penchant
for imaginative fantasy. The story is impossibly complicated,
involving lost twins, mistaken identities, statues that come to
life, singing apples, an almost incestuous marriage and many
magical transformations. But the more outlandish Gozzi gets, the
more scope Taymor has to create wondrous effects.
</P>
<P>
   A broad wall of mystic graffiti turns into a digestive system in
compartments that open like an Advent calendar. Large red apples
(three now, instead of one) float high above the stage on long
green dress-stalks and cut themselves open to reveal Harlow-blond
lookalikes singing opera and torch songs as smaller apples dance
along ropes like bouncing musical notes. A massive granite head
speaks and blinks, and a naked marble woman comes to life. A
traffic jam of souped-up sedans on dancers heads (one of the new
effects) bustles about the stage.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fabulous assortment of eye-dazzling and rib-tickling
images derived from simple imaginative stagecraft: Christine Jones'
transformative sets, Constance Hoffman's brightly colorful and
burlesque-patterned black-and-white costumes, Donald Holder's
magical lights and Taymor's wondrous small and enormous puppets and
comically expressive masks. It's infused with energy and comic
mystery by Elliot Goldenthal's eclectic score and enlivened by
Ezralow's bright rag- and Charleston-based choreography, especially
in the new closing production number.
</P>
<P>
   And it's beautifully performed by Taymor's now larger cast.
Derek Smith is a particular standout, repeating and refining his
role as the self-conscious melancholy king with a knack for
sarcastic asides. But the entire cast is superb, from original
members Didi Conn's busybody Smeraldina, Andrew Weems' softhearted
Pantalone, Ned Eisenberg's hustler Truffaldino, Sophia Salguero's
seductive apple and Bruce Turk's protective Green Bird to Reg
Cathey's mercurial soothsayer, Katie MacNichol's plaintive-selfish
heroine and Edward Hibbert's voraciously evil queen in a black
bustle like an elongated carapace.
</P>
<P>
   As inventive as the packaging is, however, and as much fun is
its execution, the contents of ``Bird'' remain pretty ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   For Disney, ``Aida'' is a departure from a winning formula, the
company's first Broadway venture not adapted from one of its
popular animated features. It's the first show under the banner of
Hyperion Theatricals, to distinguish Disney's more high-brow
entertainments from those produced by Schneider and Schumacher
under Disney Theatricals. And it's certainly the first Disney
production to risk serious comparison with the opera it was, as the
program has it, ``suggested by.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also, though visually spectacular aplenty, the first
Broadway show from the company in which the magic of stagecraft
takes a backseat to such basics as story and the performances of
its primary roles. Which is its principal problem. Though the leads
are exceptionally strong, except for a badly miscast Adam Pascal,
the material with which they have to work is not. The famously
expensive _ and even more famously malfunctioning _ massive
levitating pyramid was scrapped following the show's $10 million
1998 trial run in Atlanta. So, too, were its designer, director and
some of Linda Woolverton's book (she'd previously written the
screenplay and book for ``Beauty,'' and co-written the screenplay
for ``Lion''). New director Robert Falls, the artistic director of
Chicago's Goodman Theatre who staged last season's Broadway smash
``Death of a Salesman,'' reshaped the text with the help of
playwright David Henry Hwang (``M. Butterfly'').
</P>
<P>
   Bob Crowley's set and costume redesign is stunning, from the
grand Eye of Horus emblazoned on the curtain (which dilates open
like a camera lens) to the playfully outrageous fashion show of the
princess Amneris' high-tech-chic wardrobe. Vast red sails,
parchment maps and temple facades cover the stage _ even, in a bit
of overkill, a shimmering pool, as seen from above, with airborne
handmaidens ``swimming'' within. A chorus of soldiers and slaves
erupts in Wayne Cilento's magnetic jazz-hieroglyphic-bellydance
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   But Falls and Crowley keep a tight focus on the principals,
isolated by Natasha Katz's sculptural lights in fields of black or
red. (The only pyramid in sight is built of shafts of light.) And
whenever that focus is on Heather Headley's Aida, the Nubian
princess enslaved in Egypt, or on Sherie Ren Scott's Amneris, the
pharaoh's daughter, the show takes flight.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the third leg of the fatal love pyramid doesn't
measure up. Pascal, dynamic in ``Rent,'' plays Radames _ the
Egyptian general, betrothed to Amneris and in love with Aida _ with
all the authority of an East Village trust-fund garage-band wannabe
with a pleasant and forceful country-rocker voice. But then,
Radames' problems are not central to this ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John and Tim Rice's take on Verdi, perhaps not
surprisingly, is that this is a story about the tragic fate and
true nobility of princesses. The banal songs, which take up most of
the almost 2 1/2-hour show, set its tenor and proclaim its theme
with an opening ``Every Story is a Love Story,'' powerfully
rendered by Scott. And the songs determine the story's course, from
an astonishingly superficial take on Aida and Radames' dilemma
(``We All Lead Such Elaborate Lives'') to its wistful appreciation
of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Aida is _ guess what _ the people's princess, reminded of her
true calling by the chorus of devoted slaves singing ``And all we
ask of you is a lifetime of service.'' So, oddly enough, is Amneris
(hey, she's a princess too), who evolves from a self-centered
fashion ditz to understand how unattractive exploitation is and, in
the end, ascends the throne to usher in ``a reign of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   This is pretty mawkish stuff, not helped by the generic nature
of John's score and Rice's uninspired lyrics. Fortunately, Scott
can invest just about any song with real Broadway pizzazz. And
Headley absolutely transcends the material.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, slender and regal in bearing, Headley is the true find of
``Aida.'' Her still, thoughtful or anguished silences alone are
compelling. Her lithe hands are powerfully expressive. And she
sings with enormous, expertly controlled forcefulness, styling each
note to make it her own, infusing John's most banal melodies with
the seductive longing of the blues or the soul-stirring rapture of
a spiritual. With any luck, her next show will be something more
substantial than an inflated ``Candle in the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elton John and Tim Rice's ``Aida'' is at the Palace Theatre,
1554 Broadway New York, N.Y. (800-755-4000, 212-307-4747 or
www.ticketmaster.com). Julie Taymor's ``The Green Bird;; is at the
Cort Theatre, 138 W. 48th St. (212-239-6200 or
www.thegreenbird.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
