<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FLINTSTONES-FILM-REVI     04-27 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLINTSTONES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FLINTSTONES IN VIVA ROCK VEGAS': CAVEMAN COURTSHIP, WITHOUT
CLUBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Primitive humor coupled with high-tech moviemaking turn ``The
Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' into a sputtering vehicle for the
return of the popular Stone Age characters who first emerged from
their cave as Hanna-Barbera cartoon figures on television 40 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   This sequel to the 1994 live-action ``Flintstones'' is actually
a prequel to the saga of Fred Flintstone, his pal Barney Rubble and
their respective wives, the former Wilma Slag and Betty O'Shale.
</P>
<P>
   But as directed by Brian Levant in an encore from 1994 and
written by the teams of Deborah Kaplan and Harry Elfont and Jim
Cash and Jack Epps Jr., ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas''
stumbles at its outset by setting up an adult premise inevitably
undone by the film's aspirations to family entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   What results is a candy-colored broad comedy with noteworthy
performances by Mark Addy (of ``The Full Monty,'' no less) as a
Jackie Gleason-like Fred; Jane Krakowski (of ``Ally McBeal'') as
Betty; and Alan Cumming (of ``Cabaret'' et al.) as the preening
British rock star Mick Jagged. The young Dino, the purple
Flintstone pet hatched from an egg won at a carnival, proves a
lovable, slobbering bundle of saurian energy.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's framing device, with Cumming (again) as the Great
Gazoo, an extraterrestrial from a species that reproduces by
division who is sent to Earth to study the mating habits of humans,
fails to capitalize on its comic potential.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, thanks to the effects of Jim Henson's Creature
Shop and the animation and visual effects of Rhythm and Hues
Studios, there is plenty to fill the eye and poke the ribs, if
little to tickle a well-evolved funny bone.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, wordplay abounds, in prehistoric automobiles like the
Maserocki and in garish resort hotels like the Tardust, the Saharoc
and the Molten Nugget. Modern means find their counterparts in a
gigantic bridge and a roller coaster along the backs and tails of
brontosauruses, clamshell gambling chips and an octopus that can
massage two clients at once.
</P>
<P>
   As for plot, it goes something like this: Around the time that
Fred and his dimwitted pal Barney (Stephen Baldwin) graduate from
the Bronto Crane Academy, qualifying them for work in the Bedrock
quarry, Gazoo arrives to study mating habits. But Fred and Barney,
the first earthlings whom Gazoo encounters, have no mates.
</P>
<P>
   On an outing to the local Bronto Burger, they encounter Betty,
one of the roller-skating waitresses, and Wilma (Kristen Johnston),
who has run away from the snooty castle and empty-headed social
circle she was reared in. The softhearted Betty has fixed up the
klutzy Wilma with a job, believing her to be penniless and
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Betty is unaware of Wilma's high-fashion mother, the
overweening, over-the-top Pearl Slaghoople (Joan Collins), ``a
regular Joan Crawfish''; her father, the dotty Colonel Slaghoople
(Harvey Korman); and the handsome, hissable Chip Rockefeller
(Thomas Gibson), a supposedly wealthy Rock Vegas resort owner.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Slaghoople is pushing Wilma to marry Chip, and while he
seems determined to win her heart, his emotions are actually fixed
on her money because criminal creditors are after his life.
</P>
<P>
   On a double date at an amusement park (Fred to Barney, in
preparation: ``Barney, tonight we shower''), the pals realize they
are with the wrong partners, and after a switch, Fred pairs off
with Wilma and Barney with Betty.
</P>
<P>
   But when Fred is humiliated at a lavish party at Slaghoople
Manor, Chip pretends to make amends by inviting the four friends to
the opening of his casino in Rock Vegas, where trouble and
misunderstandings await.
</P>
<P>
   In the guise of hospitality, the rotten Chip intends to extend
credit and then bankrupt Fred at the gaming tables, frame him as
the thief who stole Wilma's famous pearls and have Wilma for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   And Betty, who has seen Barney with Chip's voluptuous playmate,
Roxie (Alex Meneses), will assuage her grief with Mick Jagged.
</P>
<P>
   But the Great Gazoo, who has been absent for large stretches of
this adventure, is about to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   So after a turn with Barney dressed as a showgirl, Fred will be
able to yell ``Yabba-dabba-doo,'' and if enough people pay enough
money, another ``Flintstones'' will be chiseled out of Bedrock in a
few more years.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' is rated PG
(Parental guidance suggested). It includes some comic sexual
suggestiveness and comic violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FLINTSTONES IN VIVA ROCK VEGAS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian Levant; written by Deborah Kaplan, Harry
Elfont, Jim Cash and Jack Epps Jr., based on the Hanna-Barbera
Productions characters; director of photography, Jamie Anderson;
edited by Kent Beyda; music by David Newman, with ``Viva Rock
Vegas'' theme song written by Doc Pomus and sung by Ann-Margret and
Alan Cumming; production designer, Christopher Burian-Mohr;
produced by Bruce Cohen; released by Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Mark Addy (Fred Flintstone), Stephen Baldwin (Barney
Rubble), Kristen Johnston (Wilma Slaghoople), Jane Krakowski (Betty
O'Shale), Thomas Gibson (Chip Rockefeller), Joan Collins (Pearl
Slaghoople), Alan Cumming (Gazoo/Mick Jagged), Harvey Korman
(Colonel Slaghoople) and Alex Meneses (Roxie).
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Mel Blanc (Puppy Dino) and Rosie O'Donnell
(Octopus Masseuse).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
