<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-2ndTa     04-27 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: www.driskillhotel.com 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Stockyards Hotel
</P>
<P>
   City: Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   Then: In 1907, the hotel was created to give cattle barons a
respectable place to stay when doing business in the Stockyards.
The original wood structure was replaced in two stages by the
current brick building, beginning in 1913; you can still see some
of the original window frames. But as business moved away from the
Stockyards, the hotel suffered. By the '60s, it had turned into a
flophouse where $5 bought you a room with a communal bathroom down
the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Now: The hotel's fortunes turned in 1984, when new owners turned
it into an elegant Southwestern-style inn. A second massive
renovation was undertaken in 1996 by the current owners, who added
the adjacent H3 Ranch restaurant and played up the Cowtown
connection. A new Old West decor features antique and reproduction
Texas-style furniture, Remington reproductions, suede
wall-coverings, and carpeting with longhorns woven into the design.
The wild-West theme plays particularly convincingly with Yankees
and Europeans; in fact, guests often ask if those are gunshot holes
in the antique window shutters. (Nope, that's just what the
original wormwood looks like.)
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Wild Bill Hickok, Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 52 rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $110, double.
(817) 625-6427. www.stockyardshotel.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Hotel Paisano
</P>
<P>
   City: Marfa
</P>
<P>
   Then: Opened in 1930 as a resting spot for travelers between El
Paso and San Antonio, the Paisano's pink Santa Fe stucco exterior
housed a hotel that soon became a favorite location for proms and
weddings. But it would likely today be considered just another nice
old Texas hotel if not for an event in 1955 _ Elizabeth Taylor,
James Dean, Rock Hudson and the rest of the cast of ``Giant'' holed
up there for six months, making the Texas epic. (It was to be
Dean's last film.) The antique-filled lobby became a repository for
``Giant'' memorabilia, such as autographed star pictures, movie
stills, magazine clippings and stray props.
</P>
<P>
   Now: In 1979, rooms were converted into suites, each with a
small sitting area and kitchenette and a theme. There are
Southwestern rooms; a '60s room with kitschy shag carpeting; and
the James Dean room, which is No. 5, the one Dean actually stayed
in. The hotel still attracts Dean fans, and it sells movie-themed
T-shirts and postcards.
</P>
<P>
   They stayed here: Sylvester Stallone, Meg Ryan and Dennis Quaid,
Melissa Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 16 rooms. Rooms from $55, double; (915) 729-3145
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Menger Hotel
</P>
<P>
   City: San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   Then: Dating to 1859, what's considered Texas' oldest
continuously operating hotel has an appropriately oversized
history. Gen. Robert E. Lee once rode his horse Traveller into the
lobby. O. Henry frequently mentioned it in his short stories. And,
most famously, in 1898 Teddy Roosevelt recruited his Rough Riders
at the dark, clubby Menger Bar, an exact replica of the House of
Lords pub in London, complete with paneled cherry-wood ceiling and
beveled French mirrors. (Later, during Prohibition, the bar was
dismantled and moved piece by piece to its current location in the
hotel.)
</P>
<P>
   Now: Between 1988 and 1992, the hotel was extensively renovated;
a new ballroom and 33 rooms and suites were added, and the original
1859 building was renovated. Antique paintings, clocks and
Victorian-era furnishings were retained in much of the redesign.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Oscar Wilde, President Dwight D. Eisenhower,
Ulysses S. Grant, Sarah Bernhardt, Mae West.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 350 rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $135, double.
(210) 223-4361; www.mengerhotel.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Gage Hotel
</P>
<P>
   City: Marathon
</P>
<P>
   Then: Opened in 1927 by a Vermont refugee who had become a rich
banker and cattle baron, the Gage immediately became the meeting
spot for ranchers and miners. It also hosted many dances and the
occasional tourist who came out looking for Big Bend beauty. But
slowly, ``modernizations'' _ linoleum coverings pasted atop
beautiful oak floors, lowered ceilings _ began to ruin the
once-proud hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Now: Renovation began in the late 1970s, when the hotel was one
of the first to capitalize on the popularity of western chic. It
was redecorated with upscale furnishings mixing cowboy, Mexican and
Indian influences. An adjacent inn, Los Portales, came along later,
overlooking the pool; last year, a 1900-era guest house was
restored and opened.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the Gage is also known as the place that launched star
chef Grady Spears, now of Reata of Fort Worth, Alpine and Beverly
Hills; he was managing the restaurant there a few years ago when
the chef walked out in the middle of dinner, and Spears jumped in
and started cooking.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Zane Grey, Dwight Yoakam, Tracy Byrd, Tom
Brokaw, Dan Rather, Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 43 rooms, restaurant and bar. Rooms from $85, double.
(915) 386-4205; www.gagehotel.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Hotel Limpia
</P>
<P>
   City: Fort Davis
</P>
<P>
   Then: The original pink limestone hotel was built in 1912,
replacing an 1884 Limpia Hotel that had become a private residence
perhaps 20 years earlier. By the '30s, the hotel was popular not
only with local ranchers, who stayed there while in town on
business, but also with doctors and lawyers and businessmen from
Houston and San Antonio, who installed their families there for
summer vacations. The hotel was also a gathering point for the
community, the place where election returns were announced to
citizens and meetings were held. But like many little inns in small
Texas towns, it had become somewhat run-down by the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now: Nine years ago, Joe and Lanna Duncan left Dallas and bought
the hotel, which had been in the family for years, from relatives
and set about restoring it. First, they redid the kitchen and
dining room; then they renovated the rooms and the common areas
from top to bottom, leaving the original tin ceilings and filling
the rooms with a combination of reproduction furnishings and their
own Victorian antiques. Next, they added a second gift shop and
added 16 suites in two nearby Victorian houses that they also
renovated. Original features were saved when possible; for
instance, the original walk-in icebox in the hotel basement became
a wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Meg Ryan and Dennis Quaid, James Garner, Larry
Gatlin, Tommy Lee Jones, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 39 rooms, restaurant and private club/bar. Rooms from
$79; (915) 426-3241; www.hotellimpia.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
