<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Literary talk show joins WABE's lineup
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several weeks, Atlanta radio listeners have been getting an
opportunity to hear authors such as Ha Jin, Carl Hiaasen and Pearl
Cleage talk about their work. The half-hour program ``Between the
Lines'' airs at 7:30 p.m. Thursdays on WABE-FM 90.1 and at 5:30
p.m. on select Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Jackson, host of the local talk show ``Prime Time,'' has
teamed with Daren Wang, producer of last year's radio series
``Porches: The South and Her Writers,'' to create the literary
forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do our homework,'' Wang said. ``We take pride in knowing
the authors and their books. This is not just a matter of
personality, but an attempt to get some real insight into an
author's work. We also like to find hidden gems, like `Bugs and
Critters I Have Known,' a book of children's poetry that has
received little attention but is a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, wife of former Atlanta mayor Maynard Jackson, says they
plan to continue to tap into visiting authors as well as local
writers. ``The caliber of talent coming through Atlanta in any
given week is a little overwhelming,'' she said, ``but I have
enjoyed reading these books and getting to know the writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 11 Discount Books, a sponsor of the program, will host a
party with Jackson and Wang from 6 to 7:30 p.m. May 4 at the
chain's Peachtree Battle store. 2345 Peachtree Road, 404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All in the family: The filming of St. Simons Island author
Tina McElroy Ansa's novel ``Baby of the Family'' has turned into a
real family affair. The upcoming feature will be produced by Ansa,
and her husband, Jonee, and daughter Afrika will produce the
soundtrack and score.
</P>
<P>
   Recently chosen as the first film project of the newly formed
Macon Film and Music Commission, ``Baby of the Family'' is also the
first feature film of the Ansas' production company, DownSouth
Filmworks Inc., which is based on St. Simons. Author William Diehl
(``Primal Fear'') served as script consultant. Exteriors for the
film are being shot in and around Macon next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby of the Family'' is a supernatural dramatic comedy set in
the mythical middle Georgia town of Mulberry in the 1950s and '60s.
It tells the story of Lena McPherson, a child born with mystical
powers. The film, starring Emmy Award-winning actress Alfre
Woodard, will be released next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ansa's fourth novel, ``You Know Better,'' also comes out next
spring, from William Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Documenting history: The newly published ``The Papers of
Martin Luther King Jr., Volume IV: Symbol of the Movement, January
1957-December 1958'' (University of California Press, $50) probably
will be used primarily by scholars, and that's a shame.
Non-academics will find this 637-page book a fascinating glimpse
behind the scenes of the early stages of the civil rights movement.
With the Montgomery bus boycott at an end, this is the period when
King confronts the sudden demands of celebrity, establishes the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference and refines his nonviolent
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
