<HEADLINE>
AETNA BEATS EXPECTATIONS BY 17 CENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN KOO   
 TheStreet.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aetna (AET:NYSE), the troubled U.S. health insurer
currently undergoing a radical restructuring, surpassed Wall
Street's quarterly earnings expectations by 17 cents Thursday on
healthy performances from its three business divisions.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter ended March 31, operating earnings rose to
$184 million, or $1.29 a diluted share, from $158.4 million, or
$1.01 a share a year earlier. The consensus estimate of analysts
polled by First Call/Thomson Financial was $1.12.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose to $6.4 billion from $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Aetna U.S. Healthcare division produced operating earnings
that rose 24 percent to $131.8 million, mostly because earnings
from Prudential HealthCare were included. The Aetna Financial
Services business reported that operating earnings rose 27 percent
to $60 million, primarily because of higher fee income.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna International, which sells life insurance, health and
pension products in emerging markets, reported that operating
earnings rose 14 percent to $48.9 million, reflecting business
growth and an improved economic environment in Asia and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Results for the first quarter of 1999 and all comparisons
reflect the restatements that were announced on Feb. 1 after the
completion of a review by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
Disclosed in October 1999, the review examined public filings
related to the company's acquisitions and divestitures.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna said it would separate
its global health and global financial services businesses into two
independent publicly traded companies. The company said Thursday
that it is searching for a chief executive of the health business.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the SEC review, Aetna has suffered from a plunging stock
price that forced chief executive Richard Huber to resign. He was
replaced at the end of February by William Donaldson, a board
member of the company since 1977 and the co-founder of the
investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna closed up 4 3/4, or 8.61 percent, to 59 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)
</P>
</TEXT>
