<HEADLINE>
`ARABIAN NIGHTS': A THOUSAND AND ONE NIGHTS IN TWO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Aladdin'' is a tale so perfectly conceived it is nearly
impossible to mess up. The latest telling, the centerpiece of ABC's
miniseries ``Arabian Nights,'' is a witty and sumptuous version,
with Jason Scott Lee tremendously engaging as the poor young con
man who finds a magic lantern.
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo goes delightfully over the top playing two
genies, a cheerful roly-poly and his cousin, a growling demon (more
of a softy than he sounds). And though the genies change Aladdin's
fortunes with trunks of jewels and a palace that appears and
vanishes in a flash, the tale is irresistible because of its
good-hearted, scheming hero. Aladdin falls for a princess and
learns that magic is nothing without love.
</P>
<P>
   Which, naturally, brings us to special effects, the magic that
is to mini-series what the genie was to Aladdin. Many series have
flopped because they failed to learn Aladdin's lesson: Visual
wizardry is nothing without characters. (Think ``Leprechauns.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabian Nights'' is about storytelling, so it's no surprise
that its creators allow the effects to serve the tales. Yet the six
stories in this two-part series are uneven. At its best, as in
Aladdin's story, ``Arabian Nights'' allows viewers to share the
hero's wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the weaker segments include the narrative frame
tale in which Scheherazade spins bedtime stories to save her life,
scenes woven in and out of the four hours. At its worst, ``Arabian
Nights'' is an ordinary example of its special-effects genre.
</P>
<P>
   Aladdin's tale is the one left hanging between the first
installment on Sunday and the second on Monday. That seems a clever
mirroring of Scheherazade's own keep-him-in-suspense technique, but
there's not much suspense generated here. Instead, the story's
antic spirit draws viewers back.
</P>
<P>
   Lee brings a streetwise skepticism to Aladdin, as well as a pure
longing for his princess. Leguizamo does not try to compete with
Robin Williams' genie in the Disney ``Aladdin,'' which goes a long
way toward giving this version its own identity as it whooshes from
comedy to menace to sweetness. And there is a spectacular duel
between the two genies that has animals shifting shapes with
eye-blinking speed.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the first night is flatter than any ``Arabian
Nights'' should be, even though it has Ali Baba (Rufus Sewell)
fighting the 40 thieves. The best time to get a snack is during the
second story, about Bacbac the hunchback, a strained comedy about
the death of the court jester. Throughout, the series makes clunky
attempts at wit by dropping in contemporary language. ``I have
three blockheads for sons,'' one sultan says.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's installment picks up and ends with the swiftly
told, appealing tale of three princes sent to search for the most
wondrous object on earth. It features a flying carpet, swordfights
and a swordfight (italics)on(end italics) a flying carpet.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Arabian Nights'' flounders where it should be strongest,
with Scheherazade. As in the classic tale, Sultan Schariar,
betrayed by his wife, vows to take a new wife each night and kill
her the next morning. Scheherazade marries him and tells stories so
alluring that her life is spared every morning so she can finish
her tale, only to start a new one that night.
</P>
<P>
   Mili Avital's Scheherazade is not a mesmerizing enough
storyteller and Dougray Scott not a menacing enough sultan to make
this device engaging. Alan Bates, as a master storyteller, gives
perfect advice to Scheherazade: ``If your audience isn't hooked,
you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabian Nights'' defies mini-series death, though its
shakiness suggests that the special-effects genre itself is wearing
thin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The X-Files' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on Fox (Channel 5 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by David Duchovny, Sunday's episode of
``The X-Files'' is one of the most entertaining ever, an extremely
funny, light-handed satire about Hollywood and ``The X-Files''
itself. Here, Tea Leoni ( Duchovny's wife) and Garry Shandling play
Scully and Mulder in a movie. In a flashback, we see the case that
inspired it, and a film producer who is following the agents
around. The case, as the producer says, is ```Silence of the Lambs'
meets `The Greatest Story Ever Told.'''
</P>
<P>
   It involves the Lazarus Bowl, a ceramic dish from early
Christianity that Scully (Gillian Anderson) thinks may have a
singing message built into its grooves. One expert thinks the
lyrics say, ``I am the walrus,'' but he could be wrong about that.
The bowl is part of a plot involving a sacred text and a '70s
terrorist who literally goes underground, into a crypt.
</P>
<P>
   The episode leans heavily on show-biz in-jokes, including the
hilariously droll scenes on ``The Larry Sanders Show'' in which
Duchovny's character flirted with Shandling's. There are also
loving homages to the classically bad Ed Wood movie ``Plan Nine
From Outer Space.''
</P>
<P>
   This tongue-in-cheek episode is especially fun for people who
don't take their ``X-Files'' mythology seriously. Apparently, that
group includes David Duchovny, which says a lot about why the
series has flourished, its wryness intact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ARABIAN NIGHTS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday and 9 p.m. Monday on ABC (Channel 7 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Halmi Sr. and Robert Halmi Jr., executive producers;
Dyson Lovell, producer; Steve Barron, director. Written by Peter
Barnes. A production of Hallmark Entertainment Inc. in association
with RTL Television and Babelsberg International Film Produktion.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mili Avital (Scheherazade), Alan Bates (Storyteller),
James Frain (Schahzenan), Tcheky Karyo (Black Coda/Nasrudin), Jason
Scott Lee (Aladdin), John Leguizamo (Genie), Vanessa Mae (Princess
Zobeide), Dougray Scott (Schariar/Amin), Rufus Sewell (Ali Baba). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
