<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FREQUENCY-MOVIE-REVIE     04-27 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREQUENCY-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURING TIME WARP IN QUEENS, DEAD DAD RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to plot, ``Frequency'' throws in a lot more than
the proverbial kitchen sink. For good measure, it piles on the
refrigerator, the stove, the floor boards and even the plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Before this entertaining science-fiction tear-jerker ends, that
plumbing has produced several floods of emotion as it gushes forth
the story of a mournful grownup boy who unexpectedly contacts his
beloved dead dad on a ham radio broadcasting from the great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The great beyond turns out to be not so far away. It is the same
house in which the son grew up and still lives in a state of
wistful adoration for his father who died 30 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Mystically reunited by short-wave radio, father and son
collaborate on averting family tragedies and on preventing and
solving some murders committed three decades earlier. Paced at a
gallop, these overlapping adventures tap into our wildest fantasies
of time travel, of communing with dead loved ones, of reliving our
lives knowing what we know now and of blood ties so deep and true
and lasting they make all-American households like the Cleavers'
look like vipers' nests.
</P>
<P>
   If it all sounds horribly icky, ``Frequency'' gets away with
much of its sentimentality simply by piling it on so aggressively.
And Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel, who play the father and son,
imbue their roles with a winning mixture of pained intensity and
macho heartiness, as Quaid puts on a perfect New York accent.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's spiritual center of gravity is an idyllic
baseball-crazed neighborhood in Queens, N.Y., populated mostly by
policemen and firefighters and their families in 1969. This Norman
Rockwell fantasy world of blue-collar solidarity and afternoon ball
games has just enough reality to make us wonder if such a cozy
little world ever did or might even still exist.
</P>
<P>
   Where most filmmakers would have been happy to stretch the
heart-tugging vignette in the movie's first 40 minutes into a
two-hour feature, ``Frequency'' isn't content to tell just one
story. As it relentlessly charges forward, it warps the initial
tale of a son who miraculously saves his dead father's life into
two weaker spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For having changed one crucial element of the past, our brooding
young policeman discovers that other things are different in the
altered (or alternate) reality he's helped create. One story
involves several unsolved murders by a serial killer who is still
alive in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That word ``warp'' is the narrative key to this nostalgic
cinematic mush pot. You can imagine it having been pitched by its
director, Gregory Hoblit (``Primal Fear''), and screenwriter, Toby
Emmerich (his first screenplay), as something on the order of
``Back to the Future'' meets ``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a
Wonderful Life'' meets ``The Sixth Sense.'' ``Frequency'' even has
an ``I see dead people''-like tag line in the father's reiterated
declaration to his son from Out There, ``I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   The time warp on which the story rides has something to do with
the mystical interaction of ham radio wavelengths and the aurora
borealis glowing floridly over a house in Queens on Oct. 12, 1999.
That's the evening John Sullivan (Caviezel), a morose New York
policeman who lives alone in the house where he grew up, begins
fiddling with the short-wave radio owned by his father, Frank
(Quaid), a firefighter who died heroically in a warehouse blaze 30
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In flashbacks, we see Frank teaching the 6-year-old Johnny
(Daniel Henson), whom he calls Little Chief, to ride a bicycle
while his wife Julia (Elizabeth Mitchell), a nurse, looks on
adoringly. We can't help but notice that the sky on Oct. 12, 1969,
glows with the same eerie radiance as it does now.
</P>
<P>
   As John chats with an affable stranger on the ham radio, it
dawns on him that through some incredible cosmic trick he is in
touch with his own father broadcasting from the same house the
night before his death. The New York Mets are in the midst of the
1969 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   While John (incredibly) even now can still reel off the
play-by-play of every game in the series, Frank, who died the
following day, doesn't know how it turned out. Seizing the
opportunity to change the past, John warns his father of his
impending death. And when the movie races to the warehouse fire in
which Frank lost his life while rescuing a young woman, the outcome
is different.
</P>
<P>
   From Little Chief, to its solemn, misty-eyed ``I love you's,''
to its fet-ishistically detailed baseball trivia, ``Frequency''
pours it on so thick that at moments you could almost gag. But it
also has a sense of humor. It slyly slips an Internet stock tip to
Little Chief's childhood playmate.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Frequency'' work despite is shamelessness is the
surreal aura that imbues almost every scene with a sense of
heightened feeling. Whether fire-fighting, or crime-busting or
swapping baseball lore, the characters seem to be living in dream
time where emotions run high, colors are sharper and everything is
tinged with subliminal import.
</P>
<P>
   As real as the Sullivan family members may be, they're also
archetypes we long to believe in. ``Frequency'' may be a good yarn,
but it is also a bereft little boy's dream of power over death that
leaves a biting tang of poignancy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FREQUENCY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gregory Hoblit; written by Toby Emmerich; director
of photography, Alar Kivilo; edited by David Rosenbloom; music by
Michael Kamen; production designer, Paul Eads; produced by Hawk
Koch, Hoblit, Bill Carraro and Emmerich; released by New Line
Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   With: Dennis Quaid (Frank Sullivan), Jim Caviezel (John
Sullivan), Shawn Doyle (Jack Shepard), Elizabeth Mitchell (Julia
Sullivan), Andre Braugher (Satch DeLeon), Noah Emmerich (Gordo
Hersch), Melissa Errico (Samantha Thomas), Daniel Henson (Johnny
Sullivan, 6 years old) and Jordan Bridges (Graham Gibson).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 100 minutes. `Frequency' is rated PG-13 (parents
strongly cautioned). It has scenes of violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
