<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LAMA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-27 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEARCH FOR THE PANCHEN LAMA': SEEKING A MISSING PAWN IN A LOADED
CHESS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May 1996, the official Chinese news agency reported joyfully
on the visit of the Panchen Lama, Tibet's second-most revered
religious figure, to the monastery where the Panchen Lama has
traditionally lived. The news agency said that the Tibetans at the
monastery were so happy that they ``sang and danced hand in hand in
the courtyard to express their heartfelt gratitude for the care for
Tibetan Buddhism from the central government and the Communist
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   This report of Tibetan love for the Chinese authorities,
recounted in Isabel Hilton's informative new book on China's
repression of Tibet, would seem to indicate that China remains
capable of inventing reality when the uninvented sort is deemed
unsuitable. The visitor in question was a 6-year-old boy named
Gyaltsen Norbu who in 1995 was chosen by the officially atheistic
Communist Party as the latest reincarnation of the Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of the young boy was, as Hilton makes clear in ``The
Search for the Panchen Lama,'' a major event in recent Chinese
history, which explains the efforts by China's official media to
depict the whole matter as a cause of singing and dancing by
Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
   The Panchen Lama has been revered by Tibetans for about 300
years. Most important for Tibet's current political fate, he plays
a central role in sanctioning the choice of the most revered
figure, the Dalai Lama, who lives in a kind of celebrated exile as
the embodiment of resistance to Chinese domination. If the Chinese
control the Panchen Lama, Hilton argues, they will control the
choice of the successor to the current Dalai Lama, and thereby
``the future of Tibet and her unique religion.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a way does Hilton explain the stakes in one of the more
bizarre episodes of recent international politics. In 1995, six
years after the death of the 10th Panchen Lama, a group of
traditional Tibetan religious leaders chose a boy named Gedhun
Choekyi Nyima as the 11th Panchen Lama, a choice that was, perhaps
unwisely, announced by the Dalai Lama from his Indian exile. China,
which portrays the Dalai Lama as a renegade and a traitor, rejected
that choice, arresting the Tibetan monks who secretly made it in
collaboration with the Dalai Lama and taking young Gedhun Choekyi
Nyima into custody, from which he has still not emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Chinese engineered a sort of politico-religious charade
in which their candidate was selected instead. The whole incident,
described in intimate detail by Hilton, would seem almost comical _
atheistic Communist bureaucrats talking about miraculous events
surrounding the birth of their preferred boy _ but, of course, the
blatant fakery of China's actions, persuasively exposed in Hilton's
study, are not funny at all.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton, a British journalist who was granted special access to
the Dalai Lama during the entire Panchen crisis, manages to retain
her status as an independent observer of the Tibetan-Chinese
tragedy even while making no secret of her sympathies for Tibet.
She avoids the temptation, to which other writers have succumbed,
of presenting the oppressed Tibetans as living saints untainted by
the usual human vices of greed and mendacity. She depicts
traditional Tibetan society as a feudal theocracy dominated by
large, often wealthy monasteries living off the labor of serfs, and
she makes no secret of her sense that much of current Tibetan lore
is rank superstition. More to the immediate point, her history is
full of religious factionalism, power plays and Tibetan appeals to
outside intervention that make China's recent actions not less
repellent but at least not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton, for example, devotes several chapters to a complex
quarrel between the 13th Dalai Lama and the ninth Panchen Lama
that, during the course of the 1920s and '30s, drew China deeply
into Tibet's religious processes. The ninth Panchen Lama, who spent
the last 14 years of his life in China, tried to promote a Chinese
military expedition to Tibet to enable him to defeat his rivals
there. When the ninth Panchen Lama died in 1937, the search for his
reincarnation evoked just about as much political rivalry as the
more recent choice of the 11th Panchen Lama. That person, the 10th
Panchen Lama, eventually became a fierce and courageous critic of
Chinese actions in Tibet, but when he first arrived in Tibet in
1951, he was accompanied by a large detachment of Chinese troops.
</P>
<P>
   If Hilton's account makes clear the precedents for Chinese
interference in Tibet's religious affairs, she demonstrates also
that the most recent effort to control the selection of the Panchen
Lama is qualitatively different, a threat to almost any semblance
of religious autonomy for Tibet. Hilton's account of the
complicated backgrounds to the current situation is not always
crystal clear; indeed there seems to have been a haste in the
writing of this book that here and there makes the thread difficult
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Hilton has written a compelling and disturbing account
of a little-understood continuing political struggle, one that pits
the vast material advantage of China over the moral and spiritual
authority of the Dalai Lama. When Hilton comes to the latest battle
over the Panchen Lama, her narrative has the grip of a political
thriller, one involving secret messengers, Chinese spies and double
agents, anguished indecision on the part of the Dalai Lama and a
courageous resistance to Chinese control inside Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Some heroes emerge here, most conspicuously Chadrel Rinpoche,
the head of the Tashilhunpo Monastery in Tibet, who like many monks
stood up to China's threats regarding the Panchen Lama selection.
Chadrel Rinpoche was arrested in 1995 and has not been seen or
heard from since.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton clarifies a great deal about the nature of Tibetan
culture and history and the complexities of Tibet's relationship
with China. Her most graphic passages depict the extraordinary
lengths to which China's authorities were willing to go to make it
seem as if their domination of Tibet was taking place at the behest
of the Tibetans themselves. Her valuable account of this recent
history serves the purpose not of sanctifying the Tibetans but of
telling the truth at a time when the might of China has gone into
an effort to falsify it.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE SEARCH FOR THE PANCHEN LAMA'
</P>
<P>
   By Isabel Hilton
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 336 pages. W.W. Norton. $25.95
</P>
</TEXT>
