<HEADLINE>
MCI WORLDCOM, NOKIA POST STRONG RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN MAX   
 TheStreet.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MCI WorldCom (WCOM:Nasdaq) and Finnish cell phone
maker Nokia (NOK:NYSE), two leaders in wireless communications,
reported strong quarterly earnings Thursday and forecast a robust
year ahead.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom said net income jumped 80 percent to $1.3 billion, or
44 cents a diluted share, from $720 million, or 24 cents a share,
from the first quarter in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat First Call/Thomson Financial's consensus
expectation of 43 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose 4 1/2, or 11 percent, to 45 3/8 in trading
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Clinton, Miss., said profits were
propelled by strong Internet and data services, international
revenues, and declining access and technology costs.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 14 percent to $10 billion from $8.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``On an annualized basis, data, Internet and international
services represent more than $18 billion of annualized revenue
growing at 32 percent,'' Bernard Ebbers, president and chief
executive of WorldCom, said in a statement. ``We are clearly
leading the communications industry into a new era dominated by
data- and Internet-based services.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nokia said operating profit rose 71 percent to $1.27
billion, while sales rose 69 percent to $6.31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange-listed shares of the Helsinki,
Finland-based company rose 4 3/4, or 9.16 percent, to 56 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Jorma Ollila, Nokia chairman and chief executive, said in a
statement that he was confident the company would increase revenue
by at least the previously forecast range of 30 percent to 40
percent, based on current market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
