<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH AS NICE GUY? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's sudden desire to
``restore civility and respect to our national politics'' strikes a
welcome chord after so many years of partisan hostility in the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   If only he meant it. But it's a real stretch to believe that he
actually intends to follow his own advice and stop trashing
opponents and distorting their records.
</P>
<P>
   Civility, after all, is a two-way street. But Bush's campaign
has shown no inclination to be polite to political rivals, let
alone play fair in the fights over competing policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore isn't respectful towards Bush, either,
and both men are practiced at personal insults and low blows. Nor
is Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., any patsy; he gave Bush nearly as
good as he got in their heated primary contest.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to think that Bush really would like to lower
the political decibel level. It would also be naove.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still trying to shake the negative image from the South
Carolina primary of cozying up to the hard right, the source of
some of the nastiest and most intolerant rhetoric in recent years.
Now Bush wants to create the impression that he's a moderate fellow
who can get along with Democrats and independents. He thinks we
have short memories.
</P>
<P>
   Softening his language is a start, but only a start. Bush
deplored ``eight years of excessive partisanship and finger
pointing and eight years of attempts to exploit fear and foster
division.'' His description of Washington's hostile political
climate is accurate. But the deteriorating mood didn't begin eight
years ago with President Clinton. It has gone on longer than that,
but to reach farther back would _ oops _ include his father's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Bush blamed President Clinton for creating most of
the bitterness. But Bush did concede that ``some in our party have
responded in kind,'' a mild poke at Republican congressional
leaders, who have devoted themselves to discrediting and harassing
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   That was putting it mildly _ but it was as far as Bush could
reasonably be expected to go before a Republican fund-raising
dinner. As it was, his comments were received coolly by the big
givers who had coughed up $21.3 million to dine with him.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is sincere about nibbling away at the present cycle of
political cynicism, he has his work cut out for him. The distrust
between Bush and Gore as well as between the congressional
Democrats and Republicans is so deeply rooted that neither side is
likely to be the first to be nice, a quality often confused with
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush included in his so-called outreach speech an attack
on Gore's character, claiming Gore was ``stretching the truth and
exaggerating.'' Was the conciliatory part supposed to be the
absence of the actual word ``liar''?
</P>
<P>
   Gore immediately ``responded in kind'' by attacking Bush for
pandering to selfish big business interests which have issues
before the government. Gore claimed they donated to the Bush
campaign to get favors from their pal that would harm consumers.
Among the biggest donors were insurance giants, the gun lobby,
tobacco companies and the oil and gas industry. Bush's public
policy positions side with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   George W. is picking up a theme of his father, who promised in
his 1989 presidential inaugural address to ``make kinder the face
of the nation and gentler the face of the world.'' Bush senior
added, ``We need compromise; we've had dissension. We need harmony;
we've had a chorus of discordant voices...not each other's ideas
are challenged, but each other's motives.''
</P>
<P>
   This was widely applauded as a signal that Bush would move away
from the divisive, uncompromising conservatism of Ronald Reagan's
years. It set a good tone early in the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing changed. The ideological struggles went on, as rigid
and intemperate as before.
</P>
<P>
   A tax hike, in fact, is the only issue for which Bush the elder
is remembered for his cooperation with the then-Democratic
Congress. It cost him dearly within his party when he ran for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the son clearly understands that he must persuade voters
who are not Republican that he will be ``president of all the
people,'' as Lyndon Johnson used to say, if he is to win the White
House. To that end, Bush will finally meet with McCain on May 9 to
discuss their differences and try to smooth over their mutual
antagonism. Whatever platitudes they issue in public, their private
session is bound to be uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain is the GOP's most popular figure with the
independents that Bush is now pursuing. Any groveling would have to
be done by Bush, not McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidency is in the air, perhaps. And perhaps not. If
it is offered, it will be a measure of how serious Bush takes the
need to moderate his image. Words alone won't do the trick, but
McCain at his side could.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
