<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GAY-MARCH-GARCIA-$ADV     04-27 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARCH-GARCIA-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GAY MARCH'S TOP ORGANIZER SHRUGS OFF CRITICISM, FOCUSES ON CAUSE
 &HT;    With GAY-MARCH. For release Saturday, April 29.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid the chaos, Dianne Hardy-Garcia was a
lavender-clad oasis of calm.
</P>
<P>
   Her Palm Pilot was beeping and aides were scurrying in and out
of her cluttered office and tens of thousands of gay and lesbian
activists were descending on the nation's capital for a
mobilization that she is leading and some of her supposed comrades
within the homosexual rights movement were calling for a boycott of
the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep my eye on the bigger prize and not get involved
in these little skirmishes,'' said Hardy-Garcia, a Texas lobbyist
turned demonstration director.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Hardy-Garcia, executive director of the Lesbian/Gay
Rights Lobby of Texas, was recruited to direct the Millennium March
on Washington for Equality that will be held this weekend. Almost
from its inception the previous year, this proposed rally of a
million gay and lesbian activists and supporters had been beset by
organizational problems and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The march was announced by the Human Rights Campaign and the
Metropolitan Community Church, two national organizations,
``without any real community consensus'' from grassroots groups,
said Bill Dobbs, a spokesman for a gay and lesbian coalition
calling for a boycott. ``They alienated many constituencies, ...
replacing democracy and accountability with Hollywood celebrities
and back-room dealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The march's 34-year-old executive director disputed the
criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some mistakes with the original organizing, but we
all make mistakes,'' she said. ``It's a fallacy to say all previous
marches were decided by some huge democratic process. They
weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually the powerful groups in New York and California called
for a march and the gay and lesbian activists from the rest of the
country attended, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you try to organize a big march on this scale, there
is a diversity of opinions on how to do it and why to do it and
when to do it,'' she said. ``What's most important to me is why we
need to march.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy-Garcia was born and reared in San Antonio and educated in
Catholic schools all the way through her graduation from Incarnate
Word College in her home town. It was after college that she
determined that she was a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to where I thought that gay and lesbian people would be
and that was New York City,'' she said. ``I couldn't be a gay
person and live in a closet. ... A lot of gay and lesbian people
flee to urban areas so that we can find acceptance and find some
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Her partner, Mary Anne Messina, moved with her from Texas.
Fourteen years later, they're still together. Both grew up in
conservative Catholic families, so telling relatives ``was tough,''
Hardy-Garcia recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to realize, as I've gotten older, that I wasn't only
victim of homophobia. My parents were too,'' she said. ``My parents
have always been such good parents. For them to feel that in any
way that they did something wrong or have society tell them that
they did something wrong was very painful for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after a couple of years as a social worker in New York,
Hardy-Garcia returned to Texas for graduate study. While attending
the University of Texas at Austin, she worked for state
representative Elliot Naishtat and was bitten by the political bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be crazy enough to say that I fell in love with the Texas
legislature,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She delights at how dozens of disparate interests are fit
together into a political mosaic. Uvalda needs a water bill. Gays
want a hate crime bill. Parents want better schools. Lubbock needs
a new road. Compromise is the only course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give a little to get a little,'' she said.
``People come together from all walks of life in Texas and have to
pass a budget. ...And there are so many great characters in the
Texas legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   As a gay rights advocate, she believes her background has helped
her appreciate cultural differences and create coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have said to me, 'Well you've got three strikes
against you. You're a woman. You're brown. And you're gay.' But on
the other hand that was sort of a gift,'' said Hardy-Garcia. ``I'm
able to bridge a lot of communities and feel comfortable in a lot
of communities.''
</P>
<P>
   She is anxious to return to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to be done here on June 15,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So why march now?
</P>
<P>
   With the fall elections approaching, the gay and lesbian
community must be mobilized into an effective voting bloc, she
said. A national march spawns activists who return to their home
towns with passion for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the gay rights movement, we've tended to focus on the two
coasts,'' she said. ``Those of us in the middle of the country need
more resources. I shouldn't have had to leave Texas to feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   There is civil rights legislation to pass in Congress and state
legislatures, she said. ``I'm sick and tired of telling people I
can't do anything about the fact that they lost their jobs because
they were gay.''
</P>
<P>
   She is frustrated that gay couples are often denied economic
benefits like health insurance that are granted to married
straights. Having lost two friends to AIDS in the past year, she is
outraged about the controversy over funding for HIV research.
</P>
<P>
   For months, critics of the march have been sounding off in the
gay press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to say, but this has caused a big rift and in some
ways set us back,'' said Dobbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to criticize. It's harder to do something about
it,'' said Hardy-Garcia. ``I try to be a doer.''
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.mmow.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
