<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Next Thing, After DVD
</P>
<P>
   Now that we're getting acquainted with digital videodisc, or
DVD, have you heard about digital videotape? The abbreviation is
D-VHS, and it is a whole other system. A new device is promised.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, you say, yet another video format. Of the reasons cited,
one is security. This month Victor Co. of Japan Ltd., better known
as JVC, announced that it has developed a copy-protection system
that will allow high-definition movies and television programming
to be released or recorded on digital videotape, or D-VHS, with a
greatly reduced (never say nonexistent) danger of its being
pirated.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, appeals to the movie studios, which would
ultimately like to release their property on the Internet and by
other electronic methods without risk of its being stolen. DVD has
a measure of copy protection, but recently the disc security system
was compromised and proved vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   For the consumer the biggest news is that D-VHS will record.
Furthermore, it will record in high definition, which obviously
would be an advantage when high-definition television becomes
prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   At present DVD players can't record at all, though DVD-R, or DVD
recordable, is coming. ``I'm hearing a year or a year and a half,''
said Dick Kelly, president of Cambridge Associates, a consultant on
video replication matters.
</P>
<P>
   JVC says it will have a D-VHS player-recorder on the market by
the end of the year. The cassette is the same size as standard VHS
but, being digital, it requires a new machine, initially priced
around $1,000, some industry people say.
</P>
<P>
   D-VHS is said to have about the same level of picture clarity as
DVD and about 10 times the storage capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with expanded electronic delivery systems drawing nearer,
will studios commit films to still another packaged-goods format,
especially with DVD enjoying substantial and growing success?
(Eleven million players are expected to be in use by the end of the
year.) Also, with D-VHS retailers might have to carry two cassette
versions of every movie, the D-VHS and the usual VHS tape for
people without D-VHS players. How likely are they to do that?
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Seeing John Malkovich
</P>
<P>
   Other films won the Oscars, but for months a lot of people's
favorite movie has been ``Being John Malkovich,'' Spike Jonze's
film about a puppeteer (John Cusack) who discovers that he and his
wife and anybody else can crawl into a little door in the wall and
take a sloppy slide into the head of the actor.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the film will be released on tape and disc by USA
Home Entertainment. The screenwriter Charlie Kaufman had the idea
four years ago, but the script sat around until Jonze discovered
it. ``I never thought it would be made, so I went about my
business,'' Kaufman said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   The film has enjoyed repeat audiences of all ages, which is
unusual. ``My sister has seen it several times,'' Kaufman said,
``and whenever she went, there were very old people and very young
people, and everybody was enjoying it sort of equally, which is so
great. I love to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight Club
</P>
<P>
   Mistaken for a simple slugfest by some, David Fincher's film
takes a complicated look at the lure of violence in a regimented,
dehumanized culture. Life erupts for a nameless white-collar worker
(Edward Norton) after he meets the strangely charismatic Tyler
Durden (Brad Pitt), who goads the worker into fighting. Soon
dispossessed young men are brawling and being molded into an
anarchic cadre. Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times that in
his phantasmagorical search for lost masculine authority, Fincher
``finds subject matter audacious enough to suit his lightning-fast
visual sophistication.''
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Fox. $108.97; DVD, $34.98. 135 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   Flawless
</P>
<P>
   After having a stroke, a retired New York policeman named Walt
Koontz (Robert De Niro) is given speech therapy in the form of
singing lessons by his drag-queen neighbor, Rusty (Philip Seymour
Hoffman). All in all, that might make a workable dramatic setup for
De Niro, whose quiet brooding adds dimension to the homophobic
Koontz, and Hoffman, who brings heat to a larger-than-life
performance. But gay stereotypes and recycled cliches do in a
garish, message-laden comedy that ``is so awful it just might put
an end to Hollywood's hypocritical infatuation with men in drag as
symbols of its own supposedly liberated sexual attitudes'' (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. MGM. $104.16; DVD, $24.98. 110 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Dwarf
</P>
<P>
   The message here is that in the heart of every man is an angry,
persecuted dwarf and that only when we realize everybody is in the
same fix do we find redemption. Anyway, in a surreal setting, a
dwarf-size law clerk (Jean-Yves Thual) strangles a mountainous diva
(Anita Ekberg) with whom he has been having relations. Later he
joins a circus, receives the unconditional love of a 12-year-old
acrobat and helps the slain diva's husband form a successful clown
act. Although it has plenty of narrative energy, ``what is
glaringly missing in the film is a compelling central performance''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $27.95. 104 minutes.
French with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   House on Haunted Hill
</P>
<P>
   In a sorry reincarnation of William Castle's 1959 horror film
(which was pretty sorry to begin with), five strangers are offered
$1 million each to spend a night in a spooky mansion. (The original
offer was $10,000, but these days no one would spend five minutes
for that kind of money.) A fire in the 1930s destroyed the Vanacutt
Psychiatric Institute for the Criminally Insane, and now a nasty
theme-park magnate (Geoffrey Rush) wants to have a party with the
chosen five as entertainment. The idea was junk in 1959. ``And it
is still junk.'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Warner. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   DAY OF WRATH, ORDET, GERTRUD. Three late films by Carl Dreyer
follow the release of ``The Passion of Joan of Arc'' last year. In
``Day of Wrath'' (1943, 110 minutes), the young widow of a
17th-century Danish pastor becomes the witch she is accused of
being. In ``Ordet'' (1955, 126 minutes), ``Romeo and Juliet'' takes
on a religious connotation as two rural families face their
spiritual differences when their children fall in love. Dreyer's
last film, ``Gertrud'' (1964, 119 minutes), follows an idealistic
woman who is on a quest for perfect love and finds a good deal less
with a young musician. $29.95 each. Danish with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREAT LOCOMOTIVE CHASE. Reaching for authenticity, Francis
D. Lyons shipped old railroad cars across the country for his film
about an attempted train hijacking by Union raiders foiled by a
Confederate conductor. 1956. Anchor Bay. $9.98; DVD, $24.98. 87
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   POIROT 3. David Suchet is Agatha Christie's spiffily attired
Belgian detective in three more episodes of the PBS detective
series. A rose is named after Poirot in ``How Does Your Garden
Grow?'' Twin diamonds, large and lustrous, and a Belgian film star,
also lustrous, involve the sleuth in ``The Adventure of the Western
Star.'' And a head of state is the object of concern in ``The
Kidnapped Prime Minister.'' 1999. Acorn Media. Three cassettes;
$39.95. 51 minutes each. Information: (800) 999-0212. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
