<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HEART-SPI </SLUG>
  
 DOWN-HOME `WHERE THE HEART IS' HARD TO RESIST
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deserted by her no-good boyfriend at an Oklahoma Wal-Mart,
Novalee Nation has just $7 in her pocket and a baby on the way in
``Where the Heart Is.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Portman's Novalee secretly moves into the store, hiding
in the restroom as the store closes, sleeping in the camping supply
section at night. When her baby is born there, she gets her 15
minutes of fame, followed by a full-time job from the kindly
Wal-Mart folks and a place to live with a saintly woman (Stockard
Channing).
</P>
<P>
   The movie traces her life over the next five years as she finds
a rewarding career and learns something about the nature of true
love.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the film chronicles the parallel story of her
rat of a boyfriend, Willy Jack Pickens (Dylan Bruno). He spends
some time in jail before hooking up with a hard-nosed country music
agent (Joan Cusack) and beginning to rise as a songwriter-singer.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a brief appearance by Sally Field as Novalee's
long-missing floozy of a mother who drops into her life again after
her Wal-Mart baby fame; and a larger one from Ashley Judd as
Novalee's best friend, a good-hearted hospital worker and mother of
five who keeps meeting the wrong men.
</P>
<P>
   In no way is this a serious movie. The southern milieu is as
phony as an episode of ``Green Acres,'' the script (by the prolific
team of Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel) is as fast and slick as a
Nike commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Portman _ the Natalie Wood of the new millennium _ is some kind
of wonderful, but just too super-model gorgeous to be credible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to resist. With director Matt Williams throwing
in a dandy special-effects tornado, a tear-jerking tragedy of some
kind in every reel, and constant threats from fiendish child
molesters and crazed religious fanatics, it plays like a downhome
version of the old Connie Stevens romance-weepie, ``Susan Slade.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Heart Is. Directed by Matt Williams. Screenplay by
Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel. Cast: Natalie Portman, Ashley Judd,
Stockard Channing, Dylan Bruno, Joan Cusack. 20th Century-Fox. 120
minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references and some violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
