<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOSSA-MOVIE-REVIEW-NY     04-27 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSSA-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING TO DREAMY RHYTHMS IN SUMPTUOUS RIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruno Barreto dedicates ``Bossa Nova'' to Antonio Carlos Jobim
and Francois Truffaut. He is out to create a film that has a
similar becalmed magic, the subtleties of rhythm that pull you
slowly but deftly into Jobim's music and Truffaut's films.
</P>
<P>
   But Barreto's film is too wan to achieve a rhythm. This
anonymous romantic farce may leave you exhausted, if only because
your toes and knees have been bouncing along to the friendly bossa
nova grooves of the songs selected for the soundtrack. It includes
one of those world music tunes from Sting (who performs ``How
Insensitive,'' a Jobim song), who apparently has a contractual
obligation to include one such song on each of his albums.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a name for a picture so inconsequential, in which
the music provides so much of the chemistry that you get the
feeling ``Bossa Nova'' would be funereal without it. The picture
seems to be lacking a regular pulse as it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's great to look at, with the vivid colors of the Brazilian
countryside captured by Pascal Rabaud's alluring cinematography.
But when that's all a movie has to offer _ and these days, what
film doesn't look good? _ it means the visuals take on a life of
their own instead of blending into the whole. In other words, why
not just play a Jobim CD while watching a Truffaut film on video?
</P>
<P>
   What you're waiting for is the love connection between the two
principals, which begins to take on a grim inevitability. Amy
Irving, who looks as if she's using a rather heavy astringent,
plays Mary Ann, an American living in Brazil. Antonio Fagundes is
Pedro Paulo, a suave lawyer whose wife, as they used to say in the
opening of ``The Odd Couple,'' has kicked him out, asking that he
never return, since she's living with another man.
</P>
<P>
   And when a romantic comedy has you idly reminiscing about Jack
Klugman and Tony Randall _ when even Brazil's seductive landscapes
and music can't hold your attention _ it's time to start eyeing the
exits or longing for the intrusive trill of a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   An airline pilot's widow, Mary Ann takes a swim every day and
communes with his spirit in the soothing blue coastal water. To
support herself, she teaches English to a motley group of
Brazilians, including Acacio (Alexandre Borges, who looks like a
Latin John Cusack), a revved-up soccer star who is more physically
interested in Mary Ann than in polishing up his rudimentary English
so that he can understand the contract that's going to take him to
London.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann wanders through Brazil in a daze, though not so much of
one that she can't slip into a tight-fitting Campari-colored dress.
That's what she's wearing when Pedro Paulo sees her for the first
time. It seems that through being a dish comes healing for Mary
Ann.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bossa Nova'' has a few sophisticated moments. Pedro Paulo's
father (Alberto de Mendoza), who seems to be only a couple of years
older than his son, is a master tailor. And when a smitten Pedro
Paulo stands behind Mary Ann in an elevator, he surreptitiously
uses his hand to measure her without touching, so he can make her a
blouse with the tailoring skills he learned from his dad.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the movie sleepwalks through the empty hectic farce
complications. Pedro Paulo's shy younger half-brother (Pedro
Cardoso) falls in love with Sharon (Giovanna Antonelli), the
ambitious and cute-as-a-bug legal intern who has also been pursued
by Acacio.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann's friend Nadine (Drica Moraes) is conducting an e-mail
romance with a man who says he is a strapping downtown Manhattan
artist with a ponytail. (Judging from this description, one guesses
that his e-mails have been trapped in a time warp since 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the difference between Brazil and Colombia or
Venezuela, Pedro Paulo proudly tells a friend that ``they invented
mambo; we invented bossa nova.'' Lines like that make this movie
seem the product of a frustrated tourist out to blame the bossa
nova. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BOSSA NOVA' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bruno Barreto; written (in English and Portuguese,
with English subtitles) by Alexandre Machado and Fernanda Young,
based on the novel ``Simpson'' by Sergio Sant'Anna; director of
photography, Pascal Rabaud; edited by Ray Hubley; music by Eumir
Deodato; art directors, Cassio Amarante and Carla Caffe; produced
by Lucy and Luiz Carlos Barreto; released by Sony Pictures
Classics. WITH: Amy Irving (Mary Ann), Antonio Fagundes (Pedro
Paulo), Alexandre Borges (Acacio), Debora Bloch (Tania), Drica
Moraes (Nadine), Giovanna Antonelli (Sharon), Pedro Cardoso
(Roberto), Rogerio Cardoso (Vermont), Sergio Loroza (Gordo),
Stephen Tobolowsky (Trevor) and Alberto de Mendoza (Juan).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes. `Bossa Nova' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes soccer
hooligan language and steamy clinches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
