<P>
   AIRFOOD _Food is an issue as Delta negotiates a new deal with
its pilots' union. Delta has been one of the few airlines that
doesn't routinely provide meals for flight crews, now will change
that policy. The union says they want it in the contract that they
get fed. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DEPOT-TOYS _Toys ``R'' Us Inc., the largest U.S. toy chain, will
sell Home Depot Inc.-branded tools for children and OshKosh B'Gosh
Inc.-branded baby products as part of a plan to differentiate
itself from rivals. The company will sell tools, kits and replicas
of tools starting in May under a partnership with Home Depot, the
largest U.S. home-improvement store, according to the Toys ``R'' Us
annual report. It also has signed a licensing agreement with
OshKosh B'Gosh, a seller of children's clothing, to offer
developmental toys, dolls and other items carrying the OshKosh name
starting in August. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL_ In New York, Intel Corp. explains to Wall Street analysts
why it still remains comfortably on top of the chip industry, in
spite of nagging production problems, revived competition from
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and a lack of a noticeable payoff from
the billions it has spent trying to get into the communications and
networking business. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Michael Capellas presides over the
Houston computer maker's first annual meeting since he took over
day to day control of the company nine months ago. He'll likely be
asked by shareholders why the company's stock is stuck around $25 a
share, why it can't gain any marketshare, why it can't make a
profit on PCs - and why companies like Dell are doing so much
better. (Pletz, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   HOOVERS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Online biz information company skedded
to release its first full year earnings since going public after
the market closes. We'll chat up CEO Patrick Spain about where the
company is, where it's going. (Schatz, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   UPS (TENTATIVE) _ Shipping company is expected to announce
Thursday that it will make a big addition to its Austin operations.
It also may give details on plans for a venture capital fund for
Austin-area startups.(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
