<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-FIXES28-COX     04-27 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FIXES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stuggling TV shows and how to fix them
 &HT;    Palm Beach Post TV reporter Kevin D. Thompson's offers these
prescriptions for
 &HT;    ailing TV shows
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH Fla. _ You can handle traffic tie-ups.
Insensitive bosses. Nosy neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you cope when your favorite TV show is no longer the
rare gem it used to be?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's bound to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Think of your favorite show. OK, now, try to imagine that show
five years from now. Will it be just as good? Probably not. Few
shows can consistently churn out quality episodes. It's not a
pretty sight when a fine TV series gets creaky and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   With the start of May sweeps, I figured now would be a great
time to analyze five once-good programs. I'll tell you what made
them good, what went wrong and, most important, how they can be
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Ally McBeal
</P>
<P>
   Mondays, 9 p.m., Fox
</P>
<P>
   _ What was good about it: Three words _ Ally, Billy, Georgia.
That thorny love triangle was the show's core. ``Ally'' was also a
refreshing series with a distinctive point of view. There was no
other series like it on television. You were crying one minute
(remember Jennifer Holiday's touching performance as a jilted
lover?) and falling down laughing the next.
</P>
<P>
   _ What went wrong: Hmmm ... How much time do you have? The cases
got strange (women who turned orange!), and the characters got even
stranger (Billy's macho posturing; a forever horny Elaine turning
down sex; any scene with the goofy Cage). The series stopped being
poignant and tender. ``Ally McBeal'' is now better suited for The
Cartoon Network than Fox.
</P>
<P>
   _ How I'd fix it: Ditch the kooky humor. We never need to see
Cage's nose whistling in court again. I'm getting sick of Al Green
and Barry White, too. Keep Billy's ghost around. Since he's dead
and no longer a blond-haired creep, his scenes with Ally are
achingly sweet and moving. Continue adding new cast members _ but
the jury's still out on teeth-obsessed Mark. Most important, get
back to telling heartfelt relationship stories.
</P>
<P>
   ER
</P>
<P>
   Thursdays, 10 p.m., NBC
</P>
<P>
   _ What was good about it: The fast-paced action, rapid-fire
dialogue and compelling cases put us in the operating room with
those heroic doctors. It was exhausting, yet totally exhilarating.
Such fleshed-out characters as the naive Carter, somber Benton,
suicidal Hathaway, hot-tempered Ross and down-to-earth Greene made
for one of TV's best dramatic ensembles _ ever.
</P>
<P>
   _ What went wrong: Familiarity may breed contempt, but in
``ER'''s case, it resulted in boredom. Maybe we got to know these
characters too well. The medical stories also have a been-there,
done-that feel. Misguided plots (Benton's affair with Corday;
Carter's infatuation with Lucy) helped put ``ER'' in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   _ How I'd fix it: Trim the cast size _ STAT! ``ER'' has an
amazing 12 characters. That's not a TV show _ it's a football team!
You can easily lose half the cast, and no one would notice. You
don't miss Lucy, right? Start with the annoying Dr. Dave. Cocky is
not lovable. Cleo can go, too. She just seems to be around as
Benton's love interest. Let Weaver and Romano go at it more often _
they sizzle together. Break up TV's most boring couple: Greene and
Corday. Their parents are more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD Blue
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdays, 10 p.m., ABC
</P>
<P>
   _ What was good about it: ``NYPD Blue'' ushered in a new breed
of cop show. Quick edits. Jittery camera movements. Raw,
in-your-face situations we've never seen on TV. Add to that a
terrific Dennis Franz and a smoldering David Caruso and you had the
makings of a hit. ``Blue'' told stories with edge and attitude. It
tackled sensitive race-related issues with sheer intensity and
gritty realism.
</P>
<P>
   _ What went wrong: Cop dramas are tough to keep fresh. After
all, how many baby-found-in-a-dumpster stories can you tell? What
was riveting in season one is just plain stale today. This year's
mundane plots include: a home invasion robbery of an elderly
couple, stolen artwork, and a woman killed by her husband.
Zzzzzzzzzzz. It also doesn't help that ``Blue'' is no longer the
pink elephant it used to be. Today, just about every cop show rips
off ``Blue'''s signature style.
</P>
<P>
   _ How I'd fix it: Add a new detective every other season. Just
when I'm about to give up on ``Blue,'' a new character jump-starts
this tired series. Jimmy Smits did it. Rick Schroder, too. So has
Henry Simmons. As the barrel-chested Baldwin Jones, Simmons demands
your attention whenever he's on screen. He can slap around low-life
skels with the best of 'em. Make sure Simmons gets major face time.
Also, show more of Sipowicz's vulnerable side. Scenes with his kid
work. So do awkward dates. Watching a scowling Sipowicz is now a
major chore. And someone, please give these maddeningly routine
cases a twist. My 5 1/2-year-old daughter can solve these crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Providence
</P>
<P>
   Fridays, 8 p.m., NBC
</P>
<P>
   _ What was good about it: In a TV landscape littered with silly
sitcoms and cookie-cutter dramas, ``Providence'' was like a breath
of fresh air. It was a sappy, feel-good family drama that pretended
to be nothing more than what it was _ a sappy, feel-good drama. As
a thriving plastic surgeon who chucks her career to move back home
with her family, Melina Kanakaredes is a bona-fide TV star. The
smile! The hair! The smile!
</P>
<P>
   _ What went wrong: Sappy can't last forever. Stories are now too
predictable. Hey, did you really think Joanie (does she have the
biggest eyes on TV, or what?) wasn't going to get her baby when she
was trapped alone under a fallen tree? Of course you didn't. These
characters started out cute and lovable, but now most of them are
downright grating.
</P>
<P>
   Dog Boy is at the top of the list. Pet-loving dad runs a close
second. Watching him prowl the streets for a blind basset hound in
a storm was cute, but dad's a tad too much in love with animals.
Don't be surprised to see him necking on the couch with a pooch in
a sweeps episode.
</P>
<P>
   _ How I'd fix it: Syd needs to start dating _ now. Giving this
fine doctor a love life would only make her _ and the show _ more
appealing. She did have a crush on a 19-year-old Russian art
prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? The guy had a brain tumor. Also, pink-slip Dog
Boy and ditzy Heather. Finally, let Syd suffer a major setback at
the clinic. No doctor can cure everyone, can she?
</P>
<P>
   Dawson's Creek
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdays, 8 p.m., WB
</P>
<P>
   _ What was good about it: Originally pegged as an over-sexed,
silly teen soap, ``Dawson's Creek'' was actually a wonderfully
acted series that beautifully mirrored the teen-angst experience.
Stories about failing to fit in, homosexuality and coping with
mental illness were often handled with care and intelligence. A
standout episode was the one in which a driven-to-be-perfect Andie
admitted she had cheated on a high school exam. Fine acting turns
by Katie Holmes as tomboyish Joey, Joshua Jackson as wisecracking
Pacey and Kerr Smith as sensitive Jack also made ``Dawson's Creek''
worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ What went wrong: Kevin Williamson left. ``Dawson's Creek''
suffered a major blow when Williamson, the show's creator and
driving force, bailed to concentrate on his new baby: ABC's
``Wasteland.'' For months, several writers attempted to capture
Williamson's distinctive voice. The result? The show felt lost _
and so did I.
</P>
<P>
   _ How I'd fix it: Make Pacey the star. That might be tough,
though, since Dawson's name is in the title. But Pacey has always
been the more interesting character. I still remember when he spit
on an obnoxious teacher. I'd let boring Dawson lose his virginity
in a ``very special'' two-part episode. And I'd make sure he lost
it with Eve _ the mysterious hottie Dawson wrecked his dad's boat
with. Get Pacey and Joey together ... finally! They're becoming the
new Niles and Daphne.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
