<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-NSF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOW CHEMICAL TO HELP NATIONAL SCIENCE FOUNDATION PROMOTE
SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Dow Chemical Co. announced Thursday it will
help fund a National Science Foundation program to bring famous
scientists to middle schools nationwide and to alert Congress about
science issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dow said its $600,000 grant to the science foundation would help
bring more than 240 award-winning scientists into schools around
the country in the coming year. Dow has also made a $100,000 grant
to Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., for a conference this July
where leaders from academia, industry and government will meet for
five days and draft recommendations to Congress and other
government agencies on science and technology policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view science and technology as a means by which we can
contribute to society,'' said Rick Gross, vice president for
research and development at Dow, at a news conference here. ``Dow
is investing in the future of science and technology, a future that
will increasingly require science literacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by Gross and officials from Dartmouth
and the foundation, which is a federal agency that funds science
and engineering research and education.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is sponsoring the programs in celebration of its
50th year. It also announced the launch of a web site,
www.nsfoutreach.org, to demonstrate the foundation's role in aiding
innovations and discoveries such as Internet browsers, Doppler
radar and fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   The web site is meant ``to demonstrate how findings of basic
science and engineering and technology have helped bring (important
innovations) to fruition,'' said foundation spokesman Bill Line in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes it will ``let the American public know this is
what their tax dollars are helping to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle schools in at least 37 states will receive visits from
individual scientists and engineers, who will contact school
administrators to arrange meetings. Line said the foundation hopes
to have scientists visit schools in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   The schools will include public and private institutions, and
there will be no particular curriculum. Line said the foundation
hopes the scientists will provide anecdotes about the reasons they
became interested in science to encourage the interest of the
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort by scientists and engineers to go into
schools to focus attention on science and technology and
engineering . . . as a possible career choice,'' Line said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
