<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDHOTELS-OTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T OVERLOOK THESE SMALL GEMS WHEN SEEKING OUT HISTORIC HOTELS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TEXAS-OLD HOTELS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years ago, nearly every Texas town of any size had a hotel _
partly because the state was so large that those traveling across
it needed many places to stop for the night. And many of those
smaller lodgings have been supported and preserved by Texans over
the years, particularly during the past decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a resurgent interest in our older hotels, and
I think that's because of the great increase in heritage tourism,''
says Carter Schildknecht, president of Historic and Hospitality
Accommodations of Texas, or HAT.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk into one of these historic hotels, you get a
feel for where you are. It's just the fact that you can see what it
looked like back then, and you get a sense of how people lived.''
</P>
<P>
   HAT counts as members a number of small inns, hotels and
bed-and-breakfasts that are housed in buildings built as hotels
more than 100 years ago. Some of our favorites from Schildknecht's
list:
</P>
<P>
   BOERNE: Ye Kendall Inn. A residence when built in 1859, it
became the Boerne Hotel when wings were added in 1878. It was a
stagecoach inn during the 1880s. (830) 249-2138;
www.yekendallinn.com
</P>
<P>
   CASTROVILLE: Landmark Inn. Dating to 1849, it became the Vance
Hotel during the 1870s. It was rechristened the Landmark Inn during
the 1940s after a restoration. Now part of the state park system,
the 2-story inn, surrounded by wildflowers, operates as kind of a
living, working museum. (830) 931-2133; www.tpwd.state.tx.us
</P>
<P>
   COMFORT: The Meyer B&AMP;B on Cypress Creek. The 2-story frame
building dates to 1872, when it was built to accommodate railroad
passengers. It replaced an older building that had hosted
stagecoach riders from 1862 to 1872. (830) 995-2304
</P>
<P>
   D'HANIS: J.M. Koch Hotel. Nearly 100 years old, this old
railroad hotel was renovated and reopened about two years ago and
now is a five-guestroom bed-and-breakfast. (830) 363-7500;
www.texassleepaways.com/jmkoch
</P>
<P>
   FORT DAVIS: Indian Lodge. The original part of this lodge,
located in Davis Mountains State Park and owned by the state park
system, was built by the Civilian Conservation Corps. It was
modeled after Southwestern Indian pueblos, with adobe walls more
than 18 inches thick. (915) 426-3254; www.tpwd.state.tx.us
</P>
<P>
   FORT DAVIS: The Veranda. Starting out as the Lempert Hotel in
1883, this adobe inn has been used continuously as a public
lodging, making it the oldest such inn west of the Pecos. (888)
383-2847; www.theveranda.com
</P>
<P>
   GLEN ROSE: Inn on the River. Set on the banks of the Paluxy
River, this inn was once a resort spa known as Dr. Snyder's
Drugless Health Sanatarium, where guests came to take restorative
waters. Today, it's a restored 22-room inn with a restaurant
serving three-course gourmet dinners. (254) 897-2929;
www.innontheriver.com
</P>
<P>
   MADISONVILLE: The Woodbine Hotel. This hotel, consisting of two
``kit houses'' (probably from Sears, Roebuck) joined by an upstairs
and downstairs parlor, was built in 1904. It changed hands several
times before reopening as a bed-and-breakfast, with full
restaurant, last fall. (409) 348-3333; www.woodbinehoteltexas.com
</P>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS: Prince Solms Inn. Originally named the Comal
Hotel, for the river that runs through town, the brick-and-stone
hotel dates to 1889, when it was built by a German craftsman. Many
antique-filled rooms are named for their decorative, old-fashioned
wallpaper. (830) 625-9169; www.princesolmsinn.com
</P>
<P>
   PORT ISABEL: The Historic Queen Isabel Inn. The oldest seaside
resort in the Valley, the Queen Isabel was built at the turn of the
century as an exclusive hunting and fishing resort, located on the
Laguna Madre Bay. (956) 943-1468; www.queenisabelinn.com
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO: The Fairmount Hotel. A small but lovely hotel
dating to 1906, The Fairmount made history in 1985 when the whole
thing was moved six blocks, through downtown San Antonio, to its
current location. Moving the 42-foot-tall building took six days
and involved crossing the River Walk. (210) 224-8800;
www.wyndham.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
