<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-KENTSTATE-2TA     04-27 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-KENTSTATE-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM TODAY: KENT STATE KEEPS ITS MEMORIES OF VIETNAM ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This is one in a series of articles marking 25 years since
the end of the Vietnam War.) 
(See also VIETNAM-WESTPOINT) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENT, Ohio _ The sense of history's turning is strong this
spring here at Kent State University as a campus meadow of 58,175
carefully planted daffodils bursts to life once more in memory of
America's body count in the convulsive war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The power of that memory is at a definitive point for the
nation. For it was a generation ago _ 25 years _ that the war was
brought to an inglorious end, its meaning left to the encroaching
forces of history.
</P>
<P>
   And it was 30 years ago that the home front of that war _ the
running confrontation between government authority and popular
resistance _ was made shockingly clear as civilian casualties fell
here on this prototypical American campus. National Guardsmen,
confronting students in one of the countless protest pavanes of
that time, unexpectedly wheeled and opened fire down a hillside,
killing four students and wounding nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings back this flood of memories that stay very real,''
said Laura L. Davis, a freshman at the time who cowered in
witnessing that 13-second, 61-shot volley and still tries to come
to terms with its meaning as an English professor and assistant
dean at Kent State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson from it that I tried to teach was to emphasize the
power of language, how people are manipulated through language, and
how to see through the language to reality,'' she said, recalling
the furious debate over patriotism and free speech between
government officials and student protesters that spilled over into
blood back in that fast-fading time.
</P>
<P>
   Across campus, her 20-year-old son, Jesse Clapper, a sophomore
at the university, looks back upon the Vietnam era with none of his
mother's sense of immediacy and, in fact, with a vagueness that
many students readily admit to.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation doesn't have a strong understanding of that
era,'' he said. ``The Vietnam time really isn't a big topic of
conversation around here,'' Jesse Clapper said, even as the
university prepared a memorial conference on freedom of expression
and students readied their annual all-night vigil to mark the May 4
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never once till college did I get past World War II in
history,'' Clapper said. ``That's ridiculous. I mean, it's
important to be able to look back and see how, if people band
together, change can occur, to see how ultimately the students of
that day won.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, as anywhere else in the nation, there are multifarious
answers to the question of what the lingering lessons of Vietnam
are. Older teachers emphasize the dangers of government hubris in
enlarging a disastrously unpopular war. Students with fresh campus
causes are clearly becoming fascinated by the era's lessons in the
power of organized protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still seems inconceivable,'' David Halberstam, the former
Vietnam War correspondent, said recently of soldiers actually
marching here to cut down American students. He presented a richly
detailed review of the era to an attentive crowd of young and old
here in a memorial address, doggedly recalling that bloody past to
penetrate ``the inexplicable quality of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Canfora, a 51-year-old veteran of a category of Americana
once known as ``campus radical,'' is one of the Kent State
casualties. He was shot that May 4 as he brazenly stepped forward
to wave a black flag of anti-war protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good number of students nowadays that are still very
active across this country in the student movement, and they want
to learn the lessons of the antiwar movement in the '60s,'' said
Canfora, who belonged to the militant Students for a Democratic
Society. Now, he is a bullet-scarred, discreetly ponytailed alumnus
who never really left the campus. He founded the Kent May 4 Center,
a private information outlet (www.may4.org) on the shootings, the
war and its escalation when President Nixon began the bombing of
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   That was an event that ignited Kent State and countless other
protest sites in spring 1970. The ROTC building was torched here on
campus. Nixon rallied his supporters nationally by denouncing
campus ``bums.'' And the Ohio state government sent in the National
Guard with battlefield gear and live ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the war protest, Canfora finds, are being
consulted increasingly by a dedicated, if relatively unnoticed
minority of concerned students. They lack a singular rallying cause
but have a portfolio of protest issues, from global trade to
capital punishment, from literacy to animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority we're hearing from are from middle school,
high school and college,'' said Canfora. He noted that the teachers
and parents with influence over those students are from the
baby-boom generation who, before their power ebbs, are trying to
pass on eye-witness lessons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Thus here, as on many campuses, the Vietnam era has gradually
become an elective, often driven by faculty members who lived
through the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we leave, who's going to do it?'' asked Gayle L.
Ormiston, who witnessed the shootings while a student and is now
chairman of the philosophy department. ``But these days there's a
great emphasis from students demanding to know the relevancy'' of
Vietnam to their career hopes, he said. He worries that, a
generation after the war, universities are more than ever job
hatcheries rather than sanctuaries for studying history's lessons.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For decades, two professors who witnessed the shootings, Jerry
M. Lewis, a sociologist, and Thomas R. Hensley, a political
scientist, have made a meticulous, passionate academic specialty of
the subject as a focal point on the Vietnam era. Dozens of students
recently took notes in room 224 at Bowman Hall as Lewis lectured on
what has come to be known as the ``Pieta'' photo _ _ the memorable
photograph of a young woman keening with upraised hands as she
knelt by a mortally wounded campus victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about Beirut or Berlin; we're talking about
200 yards from here,'' he declared as the class looked back upon
one of that time's definitive images. In the back of the room, Sean
Wheeler, 22, explained that his war curiosity had little to do with
student activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a relevant event, not only because of the war but
also because kids my age are interested in that period for the
surrounding culture in terms of music and film,'' he said. ``That's
where we get our information _ like Jimi Hendrix playing the
national anthem at Woodstock. But I don't think you can really
understand it unless you were there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Across the years, it has been a small group of students, far
more than the university administration, who have forced some
candid remembrance of the May 4 shootings and their historic
context of Vietnam protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a pain in the university's side,'' Jeffery
Ritter, a 21-year-old senior majoring in public relations, said
proudly as a leader of the May 4 Task Force. This is a student
group, decades old, with freshman members taught about the Vietnam
era and the dynamics of protest by departing seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the task force organized demonstrations and succeeded
in having parking lot sites near the places where the four students
were killed cordoned off with plaques and memorial lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those children hadn't applied pressure nothing would have
happened,'' said Doris Krause, whose daughter, Allison, was one of
those four students. ``It would have been well forgotten, but those
children had a cause and were seeking justice,'' she added,
describing the task force's willingness to protest as the ultimate
memorial in this time of more passive campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Critics rate the university administration's history as spotty
on the issue. Officials enraged much of the campus to large-scale
protest in 1977 when a new gym was built on some of the land where
the shootings occurred. In 1990, after long controversy, the
university finally built a formal hillside memorial with four
pylons representing the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some mixed feelings about the events back then
and the university's role within world history,'' said the
university president, Carol A. Cartwright, who feels the passage of
time finally is allowing a more scholarly approach to this
commemoration. ``I want people to begin to turn their eyes
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, visitors who look beyond the daffodils can notice
one telling sign of change, the return of the full ``Kent State''
to campus building logos, a title that was expunged after the
shootings. A simpler declaration of ``KENT'' had been attempted
across the 30 years. But now the familiar title is being restored,
as if the university were more fully coming to terms with its own
dark tableau in the history of the Vietnam War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
