<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO SAYS `FORCE' WAS NEEDED TO SEIZE CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Thursday defended
the government's ``show of force'' in seizing Elian Gonzalez,
saying the possibility of resistance from the boy's relatives and
their supporters in Miami made it necessary for her to end talks
and order the armed raid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a federal appeals court in Atlanta denied a request
by the Miami relatives to visit the boy, accepting instead the
government's offer of regular reports from a psychiatrist and a
social worker.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected a series of
requests from the 6-year-old boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez,
whose family cared for Elian for five months until federal agents
returned him to his father on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Florida relatives had asked the court, which is
now weighing whether to reinstate a claim of political asylum they
filed on Elian's behalf, for a series of orders giving them access
to Elian, who is staying with his father, stepmother and half
brother at a retreat in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials, who had opposed the relatives'
moves, did not immediately comment.
</P>
<P>
   During her weekly news conference on Thursday, Reno said the
pre-dawn hours of Saturday were ``the most appropriate time with
the least crowd'' for federal agents to conduct the raid. ``This
appeared to be the safest time possible to effect the transfer,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at everything that we could do to make sure that it
was done safely and yet with the least impact on Elian,'' she said
of the government's seizure of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Top Republicans in Congress have accused the attorney general of
using excessive force to take custody of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's raid of the home of Lazaro Gonzalez home followed
overnight negotiations with Miami intermediaries who were in
telephone contact with Reno in Washington. The attorney general
said threats from the family forced her to end the talks and order
an armed raid.
</P>
<P>
   Reno indicated the family at first promised not to resist the
removal of Elian, but they ``then started talking in the last days
about, `You're going to have to use force to take the child.'''
</P>
<P>
   She added that sending a small group of unarmed agents to the
house to retrieve the boy ``almost certainly'' would have failed
and that it would have tipped off the community that another,
larger group of government agents would be coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the situation where, if we did not go (in force),
people were sure to find out that we were prepared to go, and the
crowd would gather and keep a vigil and make it more difficult in
the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the agents knocked twice, waiting 30 seconds, before
breaking through the front door, which was blocked by a couch.
</P>
<P>
   She said people outside the Miami home ``tried to throw ropes
around the agents as they came up to the house.'' However, a
Justice official later said what appeared to be rope to the agents
may have been cable belonging to a television cameraman who raced
into the house before the agents, but tripped as his cable got
caught in the door.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, she said, the agents followed procedure by using a
display of overwhelming force to prevent the family from attempting
anything that could put them or the agents in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the agents had to be in force,'' she said. ``Elian
was being held by this person, and there had to be a show of force,
not a use of force, to show that we were in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surprise raid, Reno said she believed Elian would
not hold any permanent emotional scars from the night.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, she said, ``has had a lot of bad luck along the way. He's
still resilient, he's still strong, he's still a smiling little
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was one of three survivors of a shipwreck in which his
mother, her boyfriend and nine others drowned when their boat sank
as they were trying to flee Cuba for the United States last
November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials said the Elian Gonzalez case, including the
raid, had cost more than $578,000 from Thanksgiving Day, when Elian
was found, through Monday. This preliminary estimate does not
include the costs of the family's stay at Andrews Air Force Base
from Saturday until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest figure was $374,000 for the INS and included the
cost of training and housing 131 immigration agents who
participated in the raid and Elian's flight to Washington aboard a
government plane.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Marshals Service, which provided 20 deputies for the
raid and security for Elian's father in Washington and the entire
family since Saturday, spent $161,000. The figures included
overtime but not regular salaries that would have been paid anyway.
Other amounts were spent on legal work, mediators and conciliators,
and expenses for psychiatric consultants.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
