<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: GIULIANI DIAGNOSED WITH PROSTATE CANCER
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani announced Thursday he has prostate cancer, and
said the disease could affect his Senate campaign against Hillary
Rodham Clinton. Giuliani, 55, sounded upbeat: ``It's a treatable
form of prostate cancer. It was found at an early stage.'' He said
a biopsy was performed Wednesday, 2 1/2 weeks after a screening
test indicated the follow-up test was necessary. Treatment options,
which include radiation and chemotherapy, have not yet been
decided. Asked how it would affect his Senate run: ``I have no
idea.'' Giuliani said he couldn't answer that until he decides on a
course of treatment. Clinton said that, ``like all New Yorkers,''
she's hoping and praying for his speedy recovery. Giuliani's father
died of prostate cancer in 1981, before the latest screening tests
that catch it early.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE A LITTLE MORE THAN THEY WANTED TO HEAR
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush proved once again he's a master fund-raiser,
bringing in $21.3 million for his party at a black-tie Republican
Party dinner that was a who's who of lobbyists and businesses with
interests before the government. Those represented included AT&AMP;T,
Chevron, Philip Morris, the National Rifle Association and the Blue
Cross and Blue Shield Association. Yet, even as he was being
toasted by the Washington establishment, Bush tried to create some
distance from it, criticizing ``eight years of excessive
partisanship and fingerpointing.'' Bush: ``The Clinton-Gore
administration has been the most relentlessly partisan
administration in our nation's history. But sometimes some in our
own party have responded in kind.'' Reaction to that last sentence
from the 1,500 in attendance? Stone silence.
</P>
<P>
   INFLUENCE COSTS MONEY ON BOTH SIDES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore excoriated George W. Bush for his ties to the tobacco,
health insurance and gun industries, suggesting their huge campaign
contributions influenced Bush to take positions sympathetic to the
donors _ and perhaps contrary to his own ``basic common sense.''
Why does Bush always do what the National Rifle Association want
him to? Gore asked. The Bush campaign fired right back with this
statement: ``Less than one week after the FBI questioned the vice
president about the Democrats'
</P>
<P>
   potentially illegal fund-raising practices, Al Gore once again
showed his lack of credibility by criticizing Gov. Bush for
(Wednesday night's) completely legal fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   AGREEMENT ON FIRST NEW YORK DEBATE _ BUT
</P>
<P>
   A day before Rudy Giuliani disclosed his prostate cancer, he and
Hillary Rodham Clinton agreed to the first of what aides for both
said would be a series of debates. The two New York Senate
candidates accepted an invitation for a statewide forum with ``Meet
the Press'' host Tim Russert to be broadcast this fall on MSNBC
cable and NBC affiliates across New York. If it comes off now, it
would be held Sept. 11 in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   TOWN HALLS WORKED FOR MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions on topics ranging from economic growth and
agriculture to health care and the fate of Elian Gonzalez, Hillary
Rodham Clinton held the first of a series of town hall meetings
that her aides said would be a new way of bringing her campaign
directly to New Yorkers. She also vowed not to run for president in
four years if elected to the Senate and a Republican is in the
White House. ``I am going to serve my six-year term as senator. I
owe it to the people of New York,'' she said. Relaxed, with hands
frequently clasped, Clinton stood to respond to questions from an
audience of 350 students, faculty members and residents at the
State University of New York at Buffalo. The first hour was
broadcast live on CNN, but she continued to take questions for 40
more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN CAN DO WITHOUT MEETING
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, after reading a newspaper column by Robert Novak
that cited George W. Bush advisers grousing about the planned May 9
Bush-McCain meeting, reportedly told his political director, John
Weaver, to scrub the meeting. The meeting, according to online
magazine Salon, was always more important to Bush, who seeks the
independent voters who backed McCain's candidacy, than to McCain.
Salon says that while a meeting between the two may eventually take
place, for the time being it's off.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S MORE THAN 7 CENTS A MINUTE
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which is awaiting government approval of a $59 billion
purchase of MediaOne and is in a high-stakes race with cable
companies to provide high-speed internet connections, contributed
$651,050 to both political parties in the first quarter of this
year. The donations pushed AT&AMP;T's total since the beginning of 1999
to $2.03 million. That's $760,000 more than any other company
contributed in the same period, Bloomberg News reports. The
Republicans got 52 percent of it; the Democrats 48 percent,
according to Federal Election Commission data.
</P>
<P>
   BUT ENQUIRING MINDS WANT TO KNOW
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said he was surprised to hear that his aides refused to
tell reporters where he was one weekend in March when it turned out
that he and wife Tipper went to Florida for a post-primary-season
respite. He says he's resigned to an ever-present news media
trailing him. Gore told reporters he understands there is a greater
public right to know where he is and what he's doing since he is
not only the vice president but also effectively the Democratic
presidential nominee. ``Let's say I'm resigned to it. Personally I
would prefer to have more of an ability to, you know, go to the
store by myself,'' Gore said. ``But I understand it and I don't
chafe under it _ much.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE OFF TO THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and his father, George H.W. Bush, the former
president, will attend the Kentucky Derby on May 6. They're
expected to be in Louisville only for the race. Bush the elder has
been a Derby visitor before, most often as the guest of close
friend Wil Farish, who owns Lane's End Farm in horse country's
Woodford County. Al Gore attended the 1999 Derby as a guest of
Democratic Gov. Paul Patton, but is not expected at Churchill Downs
this year.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-TESTED FOR QUALITY
</P>
<P>
   Guess which presidential candidate received the highest net
favorability rating among the four tested presidential candidates
in an Ohio Poll: George Bush, Al Gore, Ralph Nader, or Pat
Buchanan? Nader's net favorability was 24 percent, higher than Bush
at 22 percent, Gore at minus 3 percent and Buchanan at minus 36
percent. Net favorability was calculated by subtracting the
unfavorability rating from the favorability rating received for
each candidate. The Ohio Poll, conducted by the Institute for
Policy Research at the University of Cincinnati (4.3 percentage
point margin of error) also showed Nader to be the only candidate
tested who received a positive net favorability rating among
Democrats (40 percent), independents (20 percent) and Republicans
(10 percent) alike.
</P>
<P>
   COUPS DON'T ALWAYS OCCUR WITH TANKS
</P>
<P>
   To Pat Buchanan, his tour of 23 Reform Party state convention
sites is a legitimate, if aggressive, bid for the group's
presidential nomination. But to supporters of party founder Ross
Perot, Buchanan's march across the country looks more like a quiet
coup. ``They want to elect their own chairmen, take over the party
and make sure all of the delegates vote for Pat Buchanan,'' said
Charles Dodge, who resigned as Wisconsin chairman amid a ruckus
between factions this month. ``We're a democratic group; we don't
work that way.'' Buchanan's sister and campaign manager, Bay
Buchanan, said problems arise only when when state parties try to
amend the rules to exclude Buchanan supporters from participating
or running for party offices, which influence delegate selection.
</P>
<P>
   OUSTER OF BUSH APPOINTEE DEMANDED
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights groups and the Congressional Hispanic Caucus say
George W. Bush should ask the Texas state health commissioner to
resign over his comments about teen pregnancy and Hispanics. Dr.
Reyn Archer, a Bush appointee, has been under fire since telling
The New York Times that Hispanics are culturally resistant to the
idea that ``getting pregnant is a bad thing.'' He has apologized,
in writing and in person, to state legislators. But the Texas
Freedom Network, League of United Latin American Citizens,
Mexican-American Legal Defense &AMP; Educational Fund, and Rainbow
Coalition said apologies aren't enough and they want him gone.
``Archer's comments only fuel questions about Governor Bush's
tolerance of racism and sexism,'' said Samantha Smoot, director of
the Texas Freedom Network.
</P>
<P>
   THE KIDS' CIVICS LESSON FOR THE DAY
</P>
<P>
   Pre-cancer announcement Rudy Giuliani called a reporter a
``jerk'' outside New York City Hall as a group of English
schoolchildren looked on. Giuliani had been chatting with the
children about New York's tourist attractions when the reporter
interrupted and asked whether new City Hall security measures _
airport-style metal detectors _ w
</P>
