<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APPLES-TEXAS-ART-3TAK     04-27 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TEXAS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTIN AND SAN ANTONIO: BOOMING IN SIZE AND BRIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than 150 years ago, San Antonio gave Texas
its enduring symbol of us-against-them pride and courage, the
Alamo. Austin's moment in the sun is now. Its technology boom has
generated fortunes that surpass even the staggering riches earned
by the state's cattle and oil barons.
</P>
<P>
   The two cities are only 80 miles apart, not much more than an
hour's drive down I-35 for lead-footed local drivers, and their
metropolitan areas are slowly growing together. They share the
equable south-central Texas climate; close proximity to the Hill
Country, an area of easy, unspoiled rustic beauty; a compactness
envied by sprawling Dallas and Houston; an unhurried approach to
life, and an unusual ethnic flavor, arising from the interaction of
Hispanic culture with that of the early settlers from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Both take much of their character from modest rivers that they
have turned to great effect. But no one would ever confuse them.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is defined by the enormous University of Texas, with
50,000 students on a single campus, and by the state government,
headed at the moment by an up-and-coming politician named George W.
Bush. Plus the vast chip and computer plants just outside the city
and one of the country's liveliest, most varied popular music
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Nelson lives here, and Lady Bird Johnson, the president's
farsighted widow, who has enriched Austin, Texas and the whole
nation with her beautification projects. So do Ann Richards and
Molly Ivins, a pair of bright, witty women, one a former governor,
the other a syndicated newspaper columnist, who find plenty of
targets hereabouts for their barbs.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's population has grown by a third and its work force by
almost two-thirds in the last decade. But George Christian, Lyndon
B. Johnson's press secretary, who was born here, said that the city
retains its essential character, despite traffic jams and rocketing
real estate prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a tolerant, casual, laid-back place, different from
most of the rest of the state,'' he told me over a lunch of meat
loaf, black-eyed peas and deep-fried pickles at Threadgill's, Janis
Joplin's old hangout. ``Nothing changes that.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio is older, poorer and slightly larger, with 1.5
million people vs. Austin's 1.1 million _ a margin that is
shrinking fast. It is a city of fiestas, especially the nine-day
Fiesta, an annual wingding every bit as flamboyant as, if somewhat
less boozy than, Mardi Gras in New Orleans. This year's edition
comes to a clamorous conclusion on April 30.
</P>
<P>
   The city has turned its evident charms into a significant
economic asset, luring dozens of big conventions every year. It
earns further millions from three major Air Force bases, including
Randolph Field, where many pilots were trained in World War II, and
from the Army's Fort Sam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio is also much more heavily Hispanic. It is, in fact,
the largest Hispanic-majority city in the country, represented in
Congress for 37 years by Henry B. Gonzalez, a power on the House
Banking Committee who brought home plenty of federal bacon, and now
by his son Charles. Much of its modern momentum was imparted by
another Hispanic politician, Henry G. Cisneros, who served as mayor
from 1982 to 1990, before heading to Washington, where he served
the Clinton administration as secretary of housing and urban
development. He later resigned during a scandal involving a former
lover.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Antonio,'' Graham Greene wrote in 1939, ``is more Mexican
than American _ not quite genuine Mexican (it is far too clean for
that) but picture-postcard Mexican.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Neither city, in truth, can claim to be a national or even a
regional cultural capital. Neither has a museum in the same league
as the Kimbell in Fort Worth or a symphony orchestra that can
compete with the excellent ensemble built in Houston by Christoph
Eschenbach. But scratch the surface a little, and discover that
Nelson A. Rockefeller's wonderful collection of Latin American art
has found a home in San Antonio, and that the University of Texas
houses one of the world's greatest troves of 20th-century
manuscripts, including important items by Joyce, Shaw and Waugh.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio boasts a stunning new library designed by the
Mexican master Roberto Legorreta. A series of boxes piled one on
another, with a breathtaking six-story atrium, it is painted an
eye-popping color known to locals as ``enchilada red.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin's own architectural spectacular, a new building for the
university's Jack S. Blanton Museum, was stalled when hidebound
members of the Board of Regents raised so many objections that the
architects, Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, probably the hottest firm in the
world at the moment, threw up their hands and quit. The dean of the
architecture school resigned, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, while the search for a new designer continues,
the Blanton's interesting collection is split between two campus
buildings, neither of them adequate. The most important holdings
are the 20th-century American pictures donated by the author James
A. Michener and his wife, Mari (ranging from the Ashcan School
through a jaunty yellow oil by Arthur G. Dove called ``Good
Breeze'' to Sam Gilliam and Larry Rivers), and the recently
acquired Suida-Manning collection, parts of which had been on
long-term loan to the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Among its notable
paintings are works by Poussin, Guercino and Simon Vouet, plus a
Veronese ``Annunciation'' showing the virgin, swathed in luminous
pink, turning modestly away from the Angel Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Museum of Art, which is still amassing a permanent
collection, is moving ahead with its new building, to be designed
by Richard Gluckman, the New Yorker who adapted older buildings for
the Andy Warhol Museum in Pittsburgh and the Georgia O'Keeffe
Museum in Santa Fe. The small but solid Austin Symphony Orchestra
and Austin Lyric Opera (13 performances of three productions this
season) continue to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Residual conservatism and insularity have done nothing to
inhibit the development of dozens of active theater companies in
Austin. Nor has it slowed the seemingly unstoppable expansion of
the popular music business here, which now extends to 810 recording
artists and 150 clubs and other stages, featuring everything from
rockabilly to Texas swing to Tejano. Every March, music journalists
and record-company executives flock here for the Southwest Music
and Media Conference, known as SXSW, to look for future stars. This
year almost 1,000 acts from all over the world showed up, each
allotted a mere 40 minutes to sell itself to the bigwigs.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, a significant effort has been made to build
artistic links to Mexico and Latin America as a whole, as Ron
Bechtel, a local architect and food critic, explained to me.
</P>
<P>
   The commission for Legorreta, who won the American Institute of
Architects Gold Medal for 1999, is one instance; another is a
continuing effort by Christopher Wilkins, the music director of the
60-year-old San Antonio Symphony, to program works by Latin
composers, often interpreted by Latin conductors or soloists. Works
by many contemporary Hispanic artists are displayed in galleries in
the old warehouse district that is anchored by the The strongest
element in this linkage, however, must be the Rockefeller Latin
American Art Center at the San Antonio Museum of Art. The main part
of the museum is housed in a castellated converted brewery dating
from 1904, a fine example of the city's unusually imaginative reuse
of intriguing old buildings. The Rockefeller center, which includes
not only the collection of the onetime New York governor but
material from other sources as well, was opened in October 1998, in
a well-conceived addition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Aztec, Mixtec and other pre-Columbian art,
Spanish colonial silver and altarpieces and contemporary Latin
American painting, the Rockefeller wing owns a riotously
uninhibited collection of Mexican folk art, including dozens of
masks, an elegant crane fashioned from a gourd and brightly colored
ceramic churches, trucks, trains and planes.
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of the museum's other collections is Martin Johnson
Heade's tiny ``Passion Flowers and Hummingbirds,'' which a wall
label aptly described as ``a very private vision of the Garden of
Eden.'' He painted it, appropriately enough, in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is full of small museums too little known outside the
state, like the Ima Hogg decorative-arts collection in Houston and
the Trammell Crow Museum of Asian Art in Dallas. In San Antonio,
the sleeper is the McNay Art Museum, in a parklike sitting on the
north side of town, where the Richie Riches of San Antonio live.
</P>
<P>
   It has one of the nation's premier theater arts collections,
which is augmented this spring by a special showing of treasures
from the St. Petersburg State Museum of Theater and Music. The
splendor of Aleksandr Golovin's costumes for ``The Firebird'' came
as no surprise, but I was amazed to see the sketches by Kasimir
Malevich done in 1913 for a production of the now-forgotten
experimental opera ``Victory Over the Sun,'' and the captivatingly
witty Constructivist costumes designed in 1931 by Tatyana Bruni for
an early Shostakovich ballet, ``Bolt.'' Keen Shostakovich fan
though I am, I confess I had never before encountered the ballet or
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   If you go to the McNay, do not miss the permanent collection,
especially the van Goghs and Gauguins, Matisse's ``Red Blouse'' and
a memorable Redon, but also superb graphics by Edward Hopper and
John Marin.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you happen to be a circus junkie like me, you will
enjoy the Hertzberg Circus Museum, which houses the 20,000-object
collection of a former state senator from San Antonio. What might
be called, in circus-speak, A Peerless Panorama of Posters, recalls
a simpler, more credulous era: Frank Buck (``Bring 'em Back
Alive''), Gargantua the Great and the Giraffe-Women of Burma! The
best carries a portrait of P.T. Barnum himself _ without his name,
just the words ``I Am Coming.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
