<HEADER>
A9034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HOLOCAUST-RESCUE-$ADV     04-27 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-RESCUE-$ADV30-1STLD- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOLOCAUST MUSEUM EXHIBIT HONORS JAPANESE 'SCHINDLER'
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects ``parental'' to ``paternal'' in 6th graf from end.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories for
release Sunday, April 30.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Nazis began a campaign of genocide that
would claim the lives of 6 million Jews, a few thousand refugees
from Poland found temporary shelter in Japan, a nation then allied
with Germany. I was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   My parents and I survived the Holocaust because two diplomats _
one Dutch and the other Japanese _ issued life-saving visas that
let us dodge Nazi death camps and the Soviet Gulag.
</P>
<P>
   We were among a band of refugees who journeyed from Poland,
which was overrun by Germany and the Soviet Union in September
1939, to Lithuania, occupied by Soviet troops in June 1940.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it took nearly two weeks on the Trans-Siberian
railway to reach the Far East port of Vladivostok. After a
storm-tossed voyage across the Sea of Japan, the escapees arrived
in Kobe a few months before the attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Those who found immigration visas and could afford to travel
dispersed around the globe. A few, including our family, came
directly to the United States. After World War II broke out, the
Japanese interned about half the escapees in Shanghai, China.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later, the story of the refugees' escape from
Europe, called ``Flight and Rescue,'' is being told in an exhibit
opening May 4 at the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum. It runs
through Oct. 21, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit documents the 6,000-mile odyssey of about 2,000
Polish Jews with artifacts, films, photos and testaments, said
David Marwell, the Holocaust Museum's associate director for
special projects.
</P>
<P>
   The key figure who made the journey possible was Chiune
Sugihara, the first Japanese diplomat to be posted to Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   For 29 days _ from July 31 to Aug. 28, 1940 _ Sugihara and his
wife, Yukiko, wrote visas by hand for many hours, charging no fees.
When refugees who had been standing in line in front of his
consulate in Kaunas for days began climbing the compound wall in
despair, he came out to calm them and assure them that he would do
his best to help. In all, he issued 2,139 visas.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Raoul Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat in Hungary whose
chief purpose in 1944 was to save Jews, Sugihara had no apparent
reason to rescue Jews. By doing so, he openly violated repeated
written orders from Tokyo, which was aligned with Berlin and Rome
in the Axis pact.
</P>
<P>
   Said Masha Leon, a fellow survivor: ``Even when he was at the
train station (on his way to Berlin) after the consulate had been
closed down, he was writing these hand-written visas and throwing
them out of the train window. It was an extraordinary act, it was
extraordinary heroism, but he was an extraordinary man.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3.1 million Jews lived in Poland before the 1939
blitzkrieg. About 100,000 survived the war.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nazis and the Communists carved up a vanquished Poland,
some 15,000 Jews bolted the Soviet-controlled area into neighboring
Lithuania in the vain hope that the small Baltic nation could
remain neutral.
</P>
<P>
   My family headed east from Warsaw with a Catholic taxi driver
whom my late father, then 28, befriended as the two cleared
bombed-out rubble. We left only hours before German troops ringed
the Polish capital and made escape all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   In Lithuania, during a month-long window in 1940, there opened a
four-step chance to attain asylum.
</P>
<P>
   _ First, the Polish government-in-exile took our word for it
that we were Polish citizens. Moscow classified Lithuanian Jews as
Soviet citizens, barring them from leaving. Some 225,000 of them
later perished.
</P>
<P>
   _ Then, Jan Zwartendijk, an electronics importer and a part-time
acting Dutch counsel, issued a unique document. It stated that
visas weren't needed to enter Curacao, a Dutch possession in the
Caribbean. Zwartendijk ignored the fact that it was up to the
colonial governor to approve each entrant, which he rarely did.
</P>
<P>
   Between July 26 and Aug. 2, 1940, Zwartendijk gave out 2,400
``Curacao visas.'' His rescue operation was shut down when the
Soviet government nationalized his company and sent back to Holland
the man known to Polish Jews as ``Mr. Philips Radio.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Next, with the key Dutch document in hand, we applied for
transit visas from Sugihara. Fluent in Russian, he was sent there
in 1939 to spy on German and Russian troop movements. Although
Sugihara never met Zwartendijk, his entry papers gave Sugihara the
cover to act.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kremlin posed the last hurdle. Wanda Glass, my 87-year-old
mother, recalls that the new Soviet masters of Lithuania allowed
some Polish Jews to depart while barring the way to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly everyone who had travel papers from Zwartendijk and
Sugihara was interrogated by the (Soviet) authorities and asked
whether we would work for them if we left,'' she said. ``They
wanted us to be spies.''
</P>
<P>
   Would-be emigrants also faced a Catch-22: The Soviets would
accept only U.S. dollars in payment for travel charges. But any
Pole caught with dollars was subject to arrest and exile in
Siberia. My father took the risk by handing a Soviet official a
sealed envelope on which he had written: ``Dollars to be Used Only
for Travel in the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Sugihara's records, preserved in Tokyo, show that my father,
Marian, was issued visa No. 160 while my mother received No. 165.
As a boy of 4, I traveled on my mother's visa.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes that other family members could flee across German
lines and join us, my father asked Sugihara for 10 more visas,
including ones for my paternal grandparents and for each of his
siblings. But none escaped Poland. All my relatives perished.
</P>
<P>
   As the war ended, Sugihara, by then posted in Romania, was
seized by the Russians and sent for 18 months to a concentration
camp with his wife and young son. On arriving in American-occupied
Japan in 1947, the foreign ministry ousted him for his wartime
``insubordination,'' offering him a small pension.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Sugihara lived in obscurity, selling light bulbs.
Then, in 1969, Yehoshua Nishri, an Israeli diplomat based in Tokyo
and one of the refugees he had rescued, found him and aired his
deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Praised by the Israeli government as one of ``the righteous
among nations'' _ the phrase used for non-Jews who helped save Jews
in the Holocaust _ Sugihara won the same honors that had been
bestowed upon Wallenberg and German businessman Oskar Schindler.
</P>
<P>
   Born Jan. 1, 1900, Sugihara died in 1986, still all but unknown
in his native land. In the year before his death, 45 years after
his visas had saved our lives, Sugihara was asked why he did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were human beings and they needed help,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: U.S. Holocaust Museum, www.ushmm.org; Sugihara
Database, www.jewishgen.org/databases/sugihara.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is senior correspondent of Cox Newspapers in
Washington. His e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
