<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-TEXAS-ART-3RDT     04-27 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-TEXAS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: Am Coming.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, Austin was a sleepy town, about as
vibrant as Carson City, Nev., with a couple of enormous buildings _
Texas Memorial Stadium, where the Longhorns roam, and the pink
granite state capitol, the largest and the most southerly in the
United States, except of course for Hawaii's, with a dome that
looks uncannily like the one in Washington. The political carnival
inside is similar, too.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few one- and two-story cow-town buildings still stand on
Congress Avenue and along the streets running off it, but that's
not where the action is. The action is out along Loop 360 and Loop
1, at the region's 2,100 high-tech companies. Austin's
Entrepreneurs' Association had 476 members at recent count, and the
entrepreneur-in-chief has to be Michael Dell, 35, the youngest
chief executive to lead a company onto the Fortune 500; the
sixth-richest person in America, according to Forbes; and the
richest Texan ever. No, that's not a misprint; Dell is richer than
the Basses of Fort Worth and the DeMenils of Houston, and richer by
far than H. Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   He made his money by grafting an old idea to a new business: he
eliminated the middleman (and avoided the inventory costs of his
rivals) by building computers to order and selling them direct to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That simple scheme made millionaires of many of Dell's early
employees, even secretaries and clerks, and it made billionaires of
some. Aided by federal research dollars funneled into the area by
its former congressman, the legendary J.J. Pickle, and by the
talent pool at the university, new companies sprang up like
wildflowers after a spring rain. Soon all of Austin was gossiping
about the new ``Dellionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   Which represents a big change, because until recently Austin was
a stranger to Dallas-size bankrolls. During the 1960s, in fact, it
was a counterculture center, a Haight-Ashbury with 10-gallon hats,
and some of that individualism lingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny, funky, outrageous town,'' said Ivins. ``Where
else do they have Spamarama? Spam with Chinese food, Spam
foo-young, for goodness sake. Where else do people celebrate
Eeyore's birthday?
</P>
<P>
   ``We do.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin doesn't have bats in its belfry. It keeps its bats under
the Congress Avenue Bridge, or rather they keep themselves there:
1.5 million Mexican free-tailed bats, who live beneath the bridge's
concrete arches from March until November, streaming out at dusk to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge crosses Town Lake, an idyllic sliver of water formed
by a dam on the Colorado River (the Texas Colorado, not the longer
one farther west). By some miracle of good sense, all motorboats
are banned, so the waters are roiled by nothing more modern than
sculls, canoes and a poky little excursion stern-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Austin climbs from the lake to the university, centered on the
307-foot tower of the Main Building. One of the richest state
universities, the fortunate owner of extensive oil lands in the
Permian Basin, U.T., as the students call it, has attracted
distinguished faculty members from other campuses. Steven Weinberg,
a physicist, won the Nobel Prize in 1979 and left Harvard for
Austin in 1983; now ``you couldn't blast him out of here with a
howitzer,'' a friend says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan and Berkeley are the ideals we aspire to,'' said
James S. Fishkin, ex-Yale and now a U.T. professor of ethics and
American society, with a chair improbably named for Darrell K.
Royall, an old Longhorn football coach. ``We're already there in
some areas, and we undoubtedly have the resources to get there in
most others.''
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the campus stands the Lyndon Baines Johnson
Library and Museum, an exemplary institution of its kind, which is
just one of the monuments, all well worth visiting, to the former
president and his family in this area. Another is the Lady Bird
Johnson Wildflower Center, where the magnificent bluebonnets
(Lupinus texensis) and the Indian paintbrush are ankle deep this
time of year. A third is the LBJ Ranch, out in the Hill Country
near Stonewall, Texas, hard by the Pedernales River (which Johnson,
in keeping with the local usage, always pronounced as
``Purdenales'').
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio is drenched in history. Its Hispanic past is
exemplified by the 18th-century missions along the San Antonio
River south of the center, notably Concepcion, a starkly beautiful,
twin-towered building that retains traces of its original frescoes,
and San Jose, with exquisite Churrigueresque ornamentation around
its windows and doors.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose gives a good impression of the privations of life in
what was then the wilderness, with its gun ports and defensive
walls, and of what must have been, then as now, the pleasures of
spring in the Southwest, with its feathery mesquite trees and
flame-colored pomegranate blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to downtown stands the King William District, full of
Victorian houses built of beautifully dressed pale limestone blocks
by German burghers in the mid-1800s. Once known for obvious reasons
as Sauerkraut Bend, the neighborhood is remarkably intact, although
some houses have been lovingly restored while others in the same
block remain decrepit. It reminded me a bit of Georgetown in the
late 1950s before it became compulsively chic.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Steves Homestead at 509 King William, with a fine
Mansard roof, and Groos house, an Italianate villa at 335, are very
handsome.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio boosters will remind you that theirs is a big-league
town; they are proud of the Spurs, National Basketball Association
Champions in the 1998-99 season, led by a pair of walking
skyscrapers named David Robinson and Tim Duncan. Me, I'm pretty
excited about the Class AA San Diego Missions, and especially their
mascots, the Puffy Taco and Ballapeno, a hot pepper with a
baseball-shaped head.
</P>
<P>
   For the average visitor, though, San Antonio is synonymous with
the Alamo and the Riverwalk. The former, where 188 heroic Texans,
including Jim Bowie and Davy Crockett, held off 5,000 Mexicans
under Santa Anna before perishing on March 6, 1836, is a shrine to
the Texas nationhood that for many Texans has never ceased to
exist. The Alamo itself, which was once a mission church, has a
somber dignity that quiets even the hordes of schoolchildren who
troop through every day. But the ``museum shop'' next door is a
travesty that sells Alamo butter-spreaders and other equally
tasteful goods.
</P>
<P>
   The Riverwalk, fashioned with WPA funds during the Depression,
consists of paths along the downtown reaches of the San Antonio,
overhung with cypresses, crossed by humpbacked footbridges,
sparklingly lighted at night. Hotels, restaurants and clubs, like
the Landing, where the joyously old-fashioned Jim Cullum Jazz Band
toots every night, open onto it. Commercial the walk may be;
resistible it isn't, not to the hardest of hearts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
