r t BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-3rdTa     04-27 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OLDHOTELS-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: www.hotellimpia.com 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Excelsior House Hotel
</P>
<P>
   City: Jefferson
</P>
<P>
   Then: Opened in the late 1850s _ allegedly just six months after
San Antonio's Menger Hotel _ the Excelsior House has hosted guests
continuously since that time. At the time, the East Texas town was
a steamboat port and one of the state's leading cities; the hotel
was built with the Southern ambience prevalent in the town and was
the city's leading inn for years.
</P>
<P>
   Now: After a period of decline, the hotel in the 1960s was
purchased by the Jessie Allen Wise garden club, whose members
decided to restore it and run it as a working hotel and not a
museum. Today it is a repository of period antiques, such as Jennie
Lind trundle beds, English porcelain, claw-foot tubs, marble-topped
dressers, Oriental rugs and rosewood Napoleon beds.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Presidents Ulysses S. Grant and Rutherford B.
Hayes, Lady Bird Johnson, Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 14 guest rooms; restaurant. Rooms from $75, double.
(903) 665-2513; www.jeffersontx.com/excelsior
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: Hotel Galvez
</P>
<P>
   City: Galveston
</P>
<P>
   Then: Named for Bernardo de Galvez, the Spanish governor from
whom Galveston also took its name, the 6-story hotel was the
grandest on the beach when it opened in 1911. During its early
years, it hosted the first ``bathing beauty'' contests in the
nation; contestants included Dorothy Lamour. During World War II,
it was used as a base for the U.S. Coast Guard, but it returned to
civilian use afterward, with several renovations keeping it fresh
between the '50s and the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Now: New owners completed another wholesale renovation in 1999,
working from historical photos. The grand circular entrance was
restored, and soaring original archways were uncovered in the music
hall. New light fixtures and furnishings were made to look like
those from the original era, and all rooms were completely redone.
Also added was a lushly landscaped pool, complete with swim-up bar,
which is lovely but seems more suited to an upscale Caribbean
resort.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: President Franklin D. Roosevelt, Frank Sinatra,
Howard Hughes, Jimmy Stewart, Gen. Douglas MacArthur.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 231 guest rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $230,
double. (409) 765-7721; www.wyndham.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hotel: The Tremont House
</P>
<P>
   City: Galveston
</P>
<P>
   Then: If you count all the Tremont House incarnations, which
date back to 1839, this hotel, located in Galveston's Strand
district, has one of the richest histories in the state. The
original 2-story hotel was built in 1839 and was the finest hotel
in Texas until it burned in 1865; seven years later, it was rebuilt
on the same site. This hotel hosted such disparate guests as a
group of Sioux Indian chiefs, six presidents, cotton barons and
Gen. Sam Houston, who delivered his last speech there. But the
hotel faltered after the turn of the century; it was demolished in
1928.
</P>
<P>
   Now: In 1984, developers George and Cynthia Mitchell
appropriated the Tremont House name for their historic hotel, for
which they renovated a former dry-goods store built in 1879. Period
furnishings _ such as enamel-and-brass beds and lace curtains,
ironwork balconies, bird-cage elevators and a great black marble
stairway _ evoke the town's Victorian heyday.
</P>
<P>
   They slept here: Ulysses S. Grant, Clara Barton, Edwin Booth,
Buffalo Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Details: 117 rooms, restaurant, bar. Rooms from $155, double.
(409) 763-0300; www.wyndham.com
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
