<P>
   PROPERTY SEIZURE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jim Spurlock is an unlikely activist. The
prosperous airplane broker is a private pilot and a lifelong
Republican. Since 1976, he has spent much of his time in an office
at Fort Worth Meacham Airport putting airplane buyers in touch with
owners, sometimes spending months arranging a single purchase. But
in 1991 and 1992, the U.S. Customs Service seized two of his
customers' jets because of a paperwork error. Spurlock said he
spent nine months and thousands of dollars getting them returned.
He said he learned that basic legal principles, such as presumption
of innocence, could be upended by federal asset forfeiture laws.
``The rule of law is disappearing. Something needs to be done to
change it back,'' said Spurlock, 57, of Fort Worth. By MIKE LEE and
SUSAN GILL VARDON. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-FORT WORTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Saying they won't let a ``stiff breeze'' get
them down, Fort Worth business and civic leaders have launched a
marketing campaign that takes a humorous approach to letting people
know that downtown is open for activity after the deadly tornado a
month ago. By SANDRA BAKER. Story has moved in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
