<HEADLINE>
`NOW AND AGAIN'S' ERIC CLOSE LIVES FOR NOW, HOPES FOR AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Eric Close
in a scene from ``Now and Again.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Eric Close hardly looks like an actor whose show is on the
bubble.
 &HT;    The amiable star of the freshman CBS series ``Now and Again,''
is sitting in the makeshift cafeteria at Silvercup Studios in Long
Island City, N.Y. He's sporting blue pajamas, chowing down on lunch
and smiling as he ponders the show's fate.
 &HT;    ``All I can say is I have no insider information _ but of all
the series I've done, I think this one has the best prospect of
being picked up,'' says Close, who counts ``The Magnificent
Seven,'' ``McKenna'' and the sci-fi hour ``Dark Skies'' among his
previous series stints.
 &HT;    ``It's the best show on television,'' he says matter-of-factly.
```Now and Again' is intelligent, clever, funny, romantic,
adventurous and downright original. More and more people are
discovering the show every week.''
 &HT;    All of that may be true, but CBS airs ``Now and Again'' on
Friday nights at 9, a death slot if ever there was one. And though
the show has performed well when measured against both its
competitors and its predecessors, the ratings are iffy,
jeopardizing its future.
 &HT;    Despite the pajamas, Close isn't losing sleep over the
situation. Instead, he and his colleagues in the ``Now and Again''
company are doing their damnedest to make the best episodes
possible and leaving the rest to fate _ and to CBS boss Leslie
Moonves.
 &HT;    Created by Glenn Gordon Caron of ``Moonlighting'' fame, the show
follows the adventures of Michael Wiseman (John Goodman), whose
brain was transplanted into a bioengineered superbody (Close) after
a deadly subway accident. Wiseman now works for the U.S. government
as an uberagent, answering to Dr. Theodore Morris (Dennis Haysbert)
and pining for his wife, Lisa (Margaret Colin), and their daughter
(Heather Matarazzo).
 &HT;    ``At this point, I think Michael is more confident in his
role,'' the actor says. ``He's starting to get more accustomed to
his situation. He's more confident and less depressed than he was
before.
 &HT;    ``I'm curious to see where Glenn takes him,'' Close says. ``I'm
curious to learn more about Michael's past, more about what went on
in his life back when he was John Goodman. I don't know if Michael
went to war. Did he fight in Vietnam? Where did he go to college?
Aside from Roger (Gerrit Graham), who were his friends?
 &HT;    ``Hopefully, as we move along, Glenn will bring out those things
that made Michael who he was,'' he concludes. ``And I mean things
aside from the fact that he likes Snickers bars.''
 &HT;    If there's a gripe to be made about ``Now and Again,'' it's that
too often Dr. Morris has gone from trading buddy-buddy banter with
Wiseman to threatening to kill him if he disobeys orders. It didn't
take long before such idle threats lost credibility.
 &HT;    ``We've actually had that conversation,'' Close says, nodding.
``Several episodes ago, when Lisa came to visit Michael at the
townhouse, Dr. Morris told Michael, `If you guys run, I will kill
you.'
 &HT;    ``Basically, the way I played that was, `Oh, yeah, well, I've
heard that before,''' he says. ``And I didn't pay it much mind. We
all realized that Dr. Morris is becoming the boy who cried wolf.
 &HT;    ``I made the suggestion to Glenn that he should have Dr. Morris
actually follow through on one of his threats and kill someone, or
he should just stop having him make threats. I don't know what
they'll do.''
 &HT;    Only a few more weeks remain in ``Now and Again's'' debut
season, and CBS likely won't decide whether or not to renew the
show until the ratings for the last batch of episodes have been
analyzed.
 &HT;    Whatever happens, however, Close sounds pleased simply to be
part of a show that has received critical accolades and attracted a
deeply loyal core of viewers.
 &HT;    In other words, even if ``Now and Again'' is over and done, it's
been a success for Close.
 &HT;    ``I think the most important thing is that it adds to your
confidence,'' he says. ``You know that your career is moving along
and moving in the right direction. You know that the hard work is
paying off.
 &HT;    ``The goals that I've set for myself are being achieved, and I'm
blessed that that's happening.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Now and Again,'' consult the
CBS Web site at www.cbs.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
