<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIME CODE': A DIGITAL PRISM REFRACTS REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toward the end of ``Time Code,'' Ana Pauls (Mia Maestro), a
fetching young avant-garde filmmaker in a minimal black dress,
arrives at the offices of Red Mullet Productions to pitch a project
to a roomful of harried executives. Accompanied by the spacey
hip-hop stylings of her boyfriend (Alessandro Nivola), she drops
names _ Leibniz, Eisenstein, Walter Gropius, Guy DeBord _ like a
highfalutin gossip columnist or a desperately trendy graduate
student giving her first paper at the Modern Language Association.
In her heart-stopping, unplaceable accent, Ana explains that the
advances of art and technology have made it necessary for
filmmakers ``to go beyond the paradigm of collage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Montage has created a fake reality,'' she declares, and she
asks her listeners to imagine a film made not by slicing and
splicing but by four digital video cameras recording four separate
stories simultaneously in real time without cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, she asks them to imagine the movie they inhabit:
the film we've been trying to absorb with our poor analog brains
and our low-resolution eyeballs for the previous hour or so. Alex
Green (Stellan Skarsgard), the Red Mullet honcho whose florid
dysfunction has bled upward and diagonally from the lower
right-hand quadrant of the screen for much of that time, pronounces
Ana's speech pretentious nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Some impatient critics and exhausted viewers may want to apply
his judgment to ``Time Code'' itself, but the way the film pauses
for this priceless moment of self-satire before moving on to darker
matters is evidence of its brilliance. It's amazing to see a film
so brazenly experimental, so committed to reflecting on the
circumstances and techniques of its making, that is at the same
time so intent upon delivering old-fashioned cinematic pleasures
like humor and pathos, character and plot.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 19 Mike Figgis set out with four digital cameras and a
good-humored, adventurous ensemble of actors to explore the
multiple realities of filmmaking. The stories that diverge and
crisscross for 90 minutes disclose a slice of Hollywood whose
governing social conventions are easily gleaned: The primary
function of public restrooms is to provide convenient places to
snort cocaine, the dispensing of which is the primary function of
security guards. Everybody has a cell phone, and nobody has only
one sexual partner. Irony is as indistinguishable from sincerity as
loneliness is from intimacy. The difference between fantasy and
reality is, of course, moot.
</P>
<P>
   Like Robert Altman's ``Player,'' ``Time Code'' is at once a
mordant satire of the hypocrisy and self-delusion of the film
industry and an earnest declaration of faith in the medium itself.
And like Altman, Figgis places unusual _ to some, perhaps,
intolerable _ demands on the audience's attention. It's always a
breach of decorum to give away the ending of a movie, but ``Time
Code'' could be spoiled by a careless disclosure of the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun is the swirling disorientation of the opening
scenes, in which each sector of the screen comes to life with a
perfectly ordinary, utterly mysterious situation, the relationships
among which are far from apparent. In the upper left-hand quadrant,
two women (Salma Hayek and Jeanne Tripplehorn) take a tense
limousine ride, which is juxtaposed with another woman's therapy
session in the upper right, the arrival at Red Mullet of a chatty
English masseur (Julian Sands) on the lower left and a rambling
morning meeting at the bottom right.
</P>
<P>
   As the film progresses, you learn to direct your attention
according to cues from the soundtrack, and to parse the complex
geometry that links the four story lines as the characters pass
through them.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it's over, you feel you've mastered the movie's
rhythms well enough to see it again. And when you do, it will be
apparent that beneath the impressive technical bravura lies some
wonderful improvisational acting, ranging from Stephen Weber and
Holly Hunter's low-key schtick to Richard Edson's careening anxiety
to the rich, strong emotionalism of Tripplehorn, Saffron Burrows
and Skarsgard, whose entwined destinies send this satire staggering
toward the precipice of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Well maybe not. Maybe, like Paul Thomas Anderson's ``Magnolia,''
another recent film to forsake the discipline of montage for the
reckless freedom of the long take, ``Time Code'' offers nothing
more than melodrama in the end. But both films leave you with the
exhilaration of having seen something genuinely and importantly
new.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis' recent films have been wildly overpraised (``Leaving Las
Vegas''), unfairly ridiculed (``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'') and
shockingly ignored (``Julie''). Each one presses, in different ways
and with varying degrees of success, against conventions of linear
storytelling and psychological exposition. In ``Time Code'' his
restless experimentalism at last yields completely satisfying
results.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it will ultimately be seen as bold prophecy of the new
digital dispensation or as a passionate, gimmicky curio is for the
future to decide. At present, it's hard to think of a more exciting
demonstration of the inexhaustible possibilities of film. Most
movies offer carefully calibrated insults to the intelligence. This
one just might make you smarter.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TIME CODE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Mike Figgis; director of photography,
Patrick Alexander Stewart; music by Figgis and Anthony Marinelli;
production designer, Charlotte Malmlof; produced by Figgis and
Annie Stewart; released by Screen Gems.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Xander Berkeley (Evan Watz), Golden Brooks (Onyx
Richardson), Saffron Burrows (Emma), Viveka Davis (Victoria Cohen),
Richard Edson (Lester Moore), Aimee Graham (Sikh nurse), Salma
Hayek (Rose), Glenne Headly (therapist), Holly Hunter (executive),
Danny Huston (Randy), Patrick Kearney (drug house owner), Elizabeth
Low (Penny), Kyle MacLachlan (Bunny Drysdale), Mia Maestro (Ana
Pauls), Leslie Mann (Cherine), Suzy Nakamura (Connie Ling),
Alessandro Nivola (Joey Z), Zuleikha Robinson (Lester Moore's
assistant), Julian Sands (Quentin), Stellan Skarsgard (Alex Green),
Jeanne Tripplehorn (Lauren Hathaway), Steven Weber (Darren Fetzer)
and Andrew Heckler and Daphna Kastner (auditioning actors).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Time Code'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It depicts sexual situations and the
routine abuse of illegal drugs and it exhibits a reckless disregard
for the limitations of the human retina.
</P>
</TEXT>
