<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _WASHINGTON _ U.S. Attorney General holds her weekly
news conference and we expect it will focus on the Elian Gonzalez
case. Meanwhile, Elian's four classmates and four adults
accompanying them, are expected to arrive in Washington on
Thursday. Two others arrived Wednesday night, in an effort to ease
the boy's expected transition back into Cuban society. But it's
still possible that the Miami relatives will prevail on appeal,
keeping the boy here. Do the Cubans know something that the rest of
us don't? Developing. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in both International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-COSTS WASHINGTON _ After five months of around-the-clock
police protection, some riot control and transportation costs, just
what has been the cost of the Elian Gonzalez case to U.S.
taxpayers? We take a look. Developing. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in both International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ZIMBABWE _ GWERU, Zimbabwe _ Farming is anything but the
``simple life'' here in Zimbabwe. (Roughton, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BOYCOTT _ Bob Holmes had to go to Columbia, S.C. for business,
but other than a night's stay in a hotel and breakfast, he kept his
money in his wallet. There have also been many times when the
director of the Southern Center for Studies in Public Policy at
Clark Atlanta University has driven by Texaco gas stations and
Shoney's, targets of past boycotts. ``The dollar is by far the most
effective weapon folks have,'' Holmes said. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO
</P>
