<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRFOOD28-COX     04-27 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFOOD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilots' beef: flying the hungry skies
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is the path to an airline pilot's heart through his
stomach?
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines is rolling out a new plan to ensure regular
in-flight meals for pilots, a move that could prevent a foodfight
from erupting in union contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Delta pilots now have no contractual provision for on-duty
meals, although the airline normally provides food for crews on
international routes. On domestic flights, which can last several
hours, surplus passenger meals are sometimes available but flight
attendants get first crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get food and sometimes we don't,'' said 757
captain Andy Deane. ``In my personal experience, more often we
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Deane added the issue is about more than just grumbling
stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's been on a long car trip or gone without a meal
knows it can have a physiological effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deane, who's also a spokesman for Delta's Air Line Pilots
Association unit, said pilot contracts at American and United
mandate pilot meals. He said ALPA will seek such a provision in
contract talks now under way at Delta.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue may not be that sticky, since Delta is moving
ahead with a plan to provide regular pilot meals. Cost to the
airline: $3 million to $5 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Bushy, senior vice president-flight operations at Delta,
said the plan isn't just a reaction to the potential contract
demand. A pilot himself, Bushy said it's long bothered him, too,
that there wasn't a system to ensure pilots maintain regular eating
habits. He said it's one of several ``quality of life issues'' he's
tried to address since taking the post.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots get expense money and can buy food in airports and take
it aboard. But long lines and tight connections often don't allow
time for a food court stop. That practice has another disadvantage,
Deane noted, recalling a co-pilot who brought aboard overstuffed
subs that he stowed away until lunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole cockpit smelled like a deli,'' Deane said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
