<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PUBLIX-ONLINE-NYTR &LR;      04-27 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIX-ONLINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIX CHAIN TO PROVIDE ONLINE FOOD PURCHASING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW SAUER   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herlad-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Publix Super Markets Inc has announced plans to
enter online grocery selling.
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket chain said it would create a subsidiary to
provide the service and make all of its grocery items available for
home delivery or store pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Publix's announcement Wednesday did not say when the service
would start, but a spokeswoman said ``the company is moving forward
quickly.'' The company also did not announce a site address or an
explanation of costs for customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is speeding up the way groceries are purchased,''
said Howard Jenkins, chairman and chief executive of Publix, in a
statement issued Wednesday. ``People want this convenient service,
and Publix is preparing to meet that demand. Customers will receive
the same premier quality service they experience in our stores, but
literally at their fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket chain is searching for locations for warehouses
from where the orders would be filled. Publix said it has looked at
locations in major Florida and Georgia markets.
</P>
<P>
   Publix's effort is not unique. A number of national players
already are trying to entice people to buy groceries through their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, the Internet company best known for letting you
``name your own price'' for airline tickets and hotels, has a dozen
supermarket chains and approximately 1,200 stores in Philadelphia
and parts of New York, New Jersey and Connecticut participating in
its grocery-shopping service. The Priceline.com groceries, however,
are not delivered, but are assembled for shoppers to pick up at
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan Inc. of Foster City, Calif., is working with Bechtel
Group, a global engineering and consulting company, to create
highly automated distribution centers to deliver customers'
groceries in 26 markets across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Other larger online-grocery players have struggled with the
concept.
</P>
<P>
   Peapod Inc., Skokie, Ill., is the largest online grocer but was
down to its last $3 million this year before Dutch grocery retailer
Royal Ahold came to the rescue. Royal Ahold gave Peapod $73 million
in cash in exchange for 51 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Publix, which is based in Lakeland, is owned and operated by its
119,500 employees. The supermarket chain had 1999 sales of $13.1
billion and has 625 stores in Florida, Georgia, South Carolina and
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Sauer writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
