<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-MAGAZINE-ART-     04-27 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-MAGAZINE-ART-(990&AMP;ADD)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ARAB ISRAELI WOMEN, A MAGAZINE WINDOW ONTO A LIBERATED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel _ In the very shadow of the Christian and
Muslim holy sites that define this sleepy city's conservatism, Yara
Mashour, a tall and willowy young Nazarene, was contemplating
orgasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has them, right?'' said Mashour, 26, the editor of a
slick new woman's magazine for Israeli Arabs, which is based here.
``So they shouldn't be taboo subjects. If people have sex and
people have orgasms, then they want to read about them _ even in
our community, or maybe especially in our community, where such
things are not discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashour's first issue of the magazine, Lilac, came out this
month, its Arabic logo plastered, in lilac, on buses. It is the
first magazine, she believes, produced by Israeli Arab women for
Israeli Arab women. A first printing of 18,000 copies, at $2.50
each, sold out almost overnight in Israel, the West Bank and
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The rose-pink cover features a pouty blond supermodel in a
slinky, revealing gown that is a long way from the local fashions.
</P>
<P>
   Decolletage and pink feather boas are not routine here. If there
is a look, it would best be described as covered-up. Even secular
Muslim and Christian women hesitate before revealing so much as an
upper arm, much less, like the cover model _ Esther Canadas, who is
Spanish _ an entire length of thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a far cry from our woman,'' said Afnan Safardi, a teacher
here, who looked at the cover once, averted his eyes, looked again,
and then turned the magazine over. ``It's hard for a lot of people
here to even look at this. It's not only that the woman is
half-naked. By our standards, she's ugly. She's bony and scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover image, which screams Cosmo Girl, hardly represents the
magazine's contents. The publication seems a bit confused about its
identity and comes across as a curious hybrid: Seventeen, People,
Ms. and The National Catholic Reporter, all rolled into one and
translated into an Arab setting.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the cover model, for instance, stands a far different
kind of tease, this one a promo for a long and sober portrait of a
Palestinian Catholic nun in Haifa: ``I don't feel the separation
between being a nun and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue also includes a profile of an Egyptian feminist _ ``A
woman's dignity does not reside in her hymen,'' she says daringly _
and an extensive article on plastic surgery, which, as one can
imagine, is as commonplace in Israeli Arab villages as Manolo
Blahnik mules. ( Not very, that is, although a Lilac survey of 525
local Arabs revealed a latent desire for nose jobs and tummy
tucks.)
</P>
<P>
   But Mashour, who is Catholic, is speaking to a minority within
the minority of Israeli Arabs, who make up 1.2 million out of
Israel's 6 million people.
</P>
<P>
   She is speaking to other young women like herself, who are
educated, Western-styled and determined to pursue a career or delay
marriage or otherwise assert themselves in both frivolous and
serious ways. About 20 percent of 600,000 Israeli Arab women work
outside the home; some are breaking barriers, like the first
Palestinian flight attendant for El Al, who is showcased in the
Israeli airline's advertisement in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided this is going to be a magazine for modern women,''
Mashour said. ``And I have a feeling it's going to be a magazine
for not-so-modern women either. We sold many, many issues in a
religious Muslim town.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashour and her sister Varia, 25, who runs their family's
advertising agency, are atypical, even for Westernized Israeli Arab
women.
</P>
<P>
   While they are rebels in their society, their rebellion is
fostered by their parents, Vida and Lutfi Mashour, who publish a
twice-weekly newspaper aimed at Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mashours took the rare step of sending their girls abroad to
study. The sisters traveled first to the United States, where they
graduated from Belmont Abbey College, a small Catholic liberal arts
school near Mashour relatives in North Carolina. Then they moved to
England, where they both earned master's degrees in political
theory from the London School of Economics and are pursuing
doctorates from King's College London.
</P>
<P>
   Both the sisters are single _ ``not over the hill, off the
map,'' Varia Mashour said _ and encouraged to stay that way by
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always advise them to wait and my husband gets mad,'' Mrs.
Mashour said.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to Israel partly because their dissertation topics
require research here, but also to try making a life for themselves
in a place where they don't feel entirely comfortable. They share
mixed feelings about Israeli Arab life. Well off and well scrubbed,
they are routinely grilled by Israeli security officials when they
leave the country. After years of being treated like intellectual
and social equals abroad, they say, they are outraged at being
treated like suspects in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day I do not feel 100 percent Israeli,'' Yara Mashour
said. ``I perceive myself to be a Palestinian Arab who lives here,
and there is no certainty that I will remain.``
</P>
<P>
   In Nazareth, though, where the sisters were raised and the
family is prominent, they are cocooned in the business. Lilac is a
family enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mashour writes editorials, and Mr. Mashour a column called
``Confessions of a Man.'' Another relative, Dr. Mary
Mashour-Haddad, who was the first Israeli Arab woman to become a
doctor, writes an advice column.
</P>
<P>
   (In this issue, under the headline ``He offered me a drink, I
woke up in his bedroom,'' Mashour-Haddad advises a young woman to
report a sexual assault to the police if she is brave enough. ``But
if you think publicizing this will create a scandal that harms your
reputation and might lead to acts that could be avoided'' _ a
reference to revenge by her relatives _ ``then I support your
decision not to file a complaint and I ask you to pay attention to
your health.'')
</P>
<P>
   (STORY MAY END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Although sexual politics permeate the magazine, other politics
are absent. Palestinian nationalism doesn't sell like it used to,
publishers say.
</P>
<P>
   Atalla Anjjar, who founded the first local Arab-language
magazine for women in 1987, started out with a very different kind
of publication.
</P>
<P>
   Abir, his Jerusalem-based magazine, used to feature a local
woman in traditional embroidered dress on every cover. The articles
ranged from interviews with female student leaders to interviews
with the mothers of ``martyrs,'' young men who died for the
Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Anjjar, too, is showing cleavage on his magazine
covers, and Palestinian nationalism has given way to what he calls
``fabricated tales of genies,'' and sensational rape stories, and
love stories including some ``sexual details.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger generation is so frustrated with the peace process
that they just want escapism,'' Anjjar said. ``And we feed them
what they want. We are like the owner of a shoe store who sees his
neighbor making lots of money selling drugs. We are closing down
our shoe store and getting into the drug business. We are
corrupting our society.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mashour, proud of what she considers the purely feminist
stories, is not guilt-racked at all by the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, isn't this rather shallow stuff?'' she said,
pointing to a story listing ``26 Reasons to Break Up with Him.''
(``If he's an addict; if he's a spendthrift; if his friends are
disgusting; if instead of talking about marriage, he turns to
sports.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you want deep, read a book!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
