<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS ON, CORRUPT CAPITALISM THRIVES IN VIETNAM    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for this weekend's 25th anniv., Fall of Saigon!)   (This TIMELY 925-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from
the International Herald Tribune.)     
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)     
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (EDITORS: Please note TWO optional trims, totaling 275 words. Story
uncut is 1,200 words.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)     
 By DON KIRK  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY _ The young businessman peered out of the large
open front of his restaurant and talked about the policemen who
drop in, pausing to drink, chat and, almost always, ask for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come every day,'' he said, gesturing with a smile toward
a local police station across a street crowded with small shops.
``They say they are collecting taxes, but they put it in their
wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Try to complain, he said, his smile turning into a grimace,
``and they follow you, step by step, or come and question you in
the middle of the night, or take you away.''
</P>
<P>
   The description typifies the sense of quiet discontent here 25
years after victorious North Vietnamese troops swept into the city,
driving the U.S.-backed Saigon government from power, sending
thousands into re-education camps and installing their own
officials at every layer of the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a largely hidden struggle in which people accept the need
for compromise, avoid political discussion, hustle for survival as
capitalists in a communist framework _ and reveal inner feelings
and complaints amid pleas for anonymity and furtive looks to see if
informants are listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we think about our lives, we just put our feelings
in our hearts,'' said an old schoolmate of the businessman. ``You
cannot say anything. All you say is the war is over for 25 years,
and you try to make money the best way you can.''
</P>
<P>
   While store windows are full of luxury goods, fresh produce
fills food markets and prices for necessities are far below those
of the rest of region, people here describe a two-tiered system in
which the victors reap the rewards while everyone else pays ``under
the table'' to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who work in the government can do anything they want,''
said Nguyen Thi Huong, wife of a former South Vietnamese soldier,
now working on a small farm on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have any rules,'' said the woman, talking as her
husband remained carefully silent. ``They have their own rules.
They can change them any time. If you worked with the Americans,
for the old government, it's very hard to find a job, and your
children cannot get good jobs either. The Communists don't trust
anyone from the previous army.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked enviously on the large families of party workers and
officials, some of them old-line liberation fighters given
influential bureaucratic posts as a reward for their years ``in the
jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them may have five or six children,'' she said. ``They
run large stores or work in government companies on joint ventures.
They grow more rich and powerful as time goes on. We just try to
stay where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Resourceful and cynical, the city and its people defy authority
partly by ignoring the ideology of communist rule, preferring to
live up to the culture left behind by the Americans and the French
colonialists before them.
</P>
<P>
   More so than in other one-time enclaves of U.S. influence in old
``South Vietnam,'' the legacy endures here in a mood of
hard-driving materialism that impresses a visitor as little changed
from the height of ``the American time'' that peaked in the decade
before April 30, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the phenomenon of corruption today echoes the
massive pilferage of a succession of American-backed South
Vietnamese government and military leaders, fattened economically
by U.S. aid and accustomed to extracting whatever they could from
local business people. ``Plus ca change, plus c'est la meme chose''
_ the more things change, the more they stay the same _ remarked
the French-educated son of a former high-ranking official from a
bygone era. ``Maybe the Communists are learning from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities respond to the corruption by occasional arrests,
along with denunciations of the evils of corruption, but no one in
business here seems to be listening. The overwhelming instinct is
to cling to old habits while fighting to adapt to new realities.  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 675) &LR;  &QC;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The need to pay off extends to all areas of life, from getting
into a university to graduating to finding a job to paying for
licenses and permissions to signing contracts to getting permits to
leave the country. ``Everything costs money,'' said Duong Pham, an
engineer with a construction company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to do anything, you must give money,'' said Pham.
``If you don't give money, maybe five or 10 years later, they sign
the form for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communists control the big companies. Maybe we make enough
to live, but we cannot put anything in the bank. The Communist
Party people, the government officials are the rich ones. They get
rich from bribes and from state trading companies.''
</P>
<P>
   That backstage view contrasted with the superficial image of a
society surging to expand as glistening glass-and-steel high-rises
loom above traditional neighborhoods that have changed little since
American military vehicles crowded the streets and U.S. officials,
GIs and contractors filled rambling villas and apartment buildings
behind sandbags and barbed wire. &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chic restaurants and souvenir shops now glitter from premises
once occupied by GI bars, and American advertising for Western
companies competes with billboards celebrating 25 years of
``liberty'' and ``reunification.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacious cars and sport-utility vehicles edge along streets
jammed with motor scooters and bicycles, while Western rap and rock
blares from radios and MTV, available by cable.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the seeming prosperity of this and lesser urban centers
may be attributed to funds sent to relatives back home by more than
2 million Vietnamese now living overseas. Remittances last year
were estimated at $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see middle-class people with much money, they
probably got it from overseas,'' said an elderly Vietnamese man
with two grown-up sons and a daughter in California. ``Some people
from abroad come back here just to live cheaply.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Ngoc Minh, a writer, laughed when reminded of the
appearance of exuberant capitalism in the center of a metropolitan
region of more than 5 million people that accounted for well over
50 percent of the country's gross domestic product of $28 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners come to Vietnam, and they always have the feeling
it is better than a few years ago, but it is wrong,'' he said. ``It
is just on the main roads with the many taxis. It is tough, it is
very hard to live. There are troubles everywhere, but people just
don't see it.'' &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,100, OR CONTINUE TO 1,200) &LR;  &QC;   &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Minh saw the rate of payoffs as having risen in recent years
while the government relaxed economic restrictions and extended
certain freedoms, including the right to worship.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged, however, when asked if pervasive bribery might
finally undermine the authority of the North, leaving the southern
region quasi-independent from central authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They control Saigon,'' he said, referring to the city by its
historic name rather than Ho Chi Minh City, the name given the
former capital and the surrounding area in honor of the legendary
Communist leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is there to take their place? No one.'' &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
