<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FLINTSTONES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bets are that `Viva Rock Vegas' isn't worth a yabba-dabba-doo
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Universal Pictures takes ``The Flintstones'''
appeal for
</P>
<P>
   ``granite.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio's Bronto-budgeted, live-action version of the popular
'60s cartoon was a critical dud, but the 1994 film made more than
$350 million at the box office worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, ``The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' _ a lame chip off
the ol' block.
</P>
<P>
   Again directed by Brian Levant, the corny romantic comedy is a
prequel that recounts how the modern Stone Age family first met.
The plot, which involves wealthy heiress Wilma Slaghoople falling
for blue-collar construction worker Fred Flintstone, doesn't run
much deeper than the two-dimensional cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Univershell,'' as the studio's lashed-bones logo appears
on-screen, has scaled back the production compared with the
original film. The colorful prehistoric sets aren't nearly as
elaborate, and the more youthful characters are portrayed by a
B-list cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Full Monty's'' Mark Addy replaces John Goodman as Fred.
Joan Collins takes over for Elizabeth Taylor as his disapproving
future mother-in-law, Pearl Slaghoople.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the rock-bottom casting is film's greatest asset.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baldwin (``The Usual Suspects'') is ideal as Fred's
blank-eyed buddy, Barney Rubble. Baldwin nails Barney's voice, as
well as his shoulder-shaking, ``heh-heh-heh'' laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cumming (``Titus'') is also perfect as the little green
alien, the Great Gazoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal's'' Jane Krakowski doesn't master Betty O'Shale's
giggle as well as Rosie O'Donnell did in the first film, but she is
the spitting-image of her cartoon counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their game performances, ``Viva Rock Vegas'' is hardly a
gay old time.
</P>
<P>
   More effort went into the cartoonish-looking costumes and sets
than into the story, which finds Fred vying for the affection of
Wilma (Kristen Johnston) with suave and debonair casino owner Chip
Rockefeller (Thomas Gibson). Gazoo has been sent to Earth to
observe the mating habits of primitive humans. At most, it's mildly
amusing.
</P>
<P>
   There are few big laughs, and the best of those will sail over
young viewers' heads.
</P>
<P>
   Barney takes an early leave from a double date, telling Fred
that Betty has offered to come back to their place and make him
breakfast in the morning. ``I don't know what we're going to do
until then, but I can't turn down a good meal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film's humor is of the juvenile pie-in-the-face,
spit-take variety.
</P>
<P>
   The funniest sight gags, such as the ``Polarock'' camera bird
that rapidly chisels the photographic image on stone, are lifted
straight from the television series.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Henson's Creature Shop again provides the dinosaur puppets,
including a rambunctious baby Dino. The visual highlights are
several computer-generated dinosaur sequences, such as a looping
Bronto Roller Coaster and a Bronto drawbridge.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Viva Rock Vegas,'' the ``Flintstones'' franchise should
go the way of the dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
