<HEADER>
A9060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     04-27 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T JUDGE THOMPSON RIGHT AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Justin Thompson had a 5.11 earned-run average
in 24 starts for the Detroit Tigers last year while pitching in
pain much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   He's healthy now and close to returning to the rotation, but the
Rangers will be lucky if Thompson has an ERA as low as 5.11 by the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   That's the harsh reality for pitchers coming back from surgery
and a major arm injury. They need time, lots of time. They need
time in the training room, in the weight room and on the mound, and
a handful of starts in the minor leagues isn't going to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   As eager as the Rangers are to get Thompson in their rotation,
it's foolish to think he's going to have an immediate impact. He is
not going to be the pitcher he was in 1997, when he made the
American League All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   At least not right away.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Perisho knows that as well as anybody. He underwent
shoulder surgery on Aug. 5, 1998, to repair a torn labrum and
rotator cuff, then bounced back to win 15 games at Triple-A
Oklahoma last year.
</P>
<P>
   But he said it took time for the aches, pain and soreness to go
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about 100 innings,'' Perisho said. ``I told Justin
eventually the burning goes away and you start feeling great again.
It will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho made 27 starts for Oklahoma last year. He was 7-6 with a
6.13 ERA in his first 17 games and 8-1 with a 2.71 ERA in his
remaining 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's what I've got to look forward to,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for Kerry Wood, Matt Morris, John Smoltz
and Scott Elarton, all of whom have undergone major arm surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would probably be best-served keeping Thompson in
the minors until his 30-day medical rehabilitation assignment runs
out May 15. But their thinking clearly seems to be that he doesn't
need to be Tom Glavine as long as he's better than Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   That might be the case right now, especially considering what
happened with Clark on Wednesday at The Ballpark. But the best-case
scenario is probably Thompson needing two months to build arm
strength and control, then doing in the second half for the Rangers
what Esteban Loaiza did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 2001, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a betting man, even as much as he pitches this
summer, he'll be better next summer,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``It's going to take a little longer for him to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is still the most-important player acquired in the Juan
Gonzalez trade, even if Francisco Cordero looks like the only
keeper right now. Who knows? Maybe in 20 years it will be known as
the Francisco Cordero trade.
</P>
<P>
   For all the post-trade garbage being spewed about Gonzalez being
moody, selfish and a distraction in the clubhouse, it's becoming
more and more obvious the Rangers miss that big bat in the middle
of the lineup. That's no indictment on Gabe Kapler, who's better
than what he has shown so far and should have a long and productive
stay in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   However, even with all the spring-training euphoria and the
``Attitude is Everything'' marketing campaign, it was stupid to
even suggest the Rangers wouldn't miss Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   He might not be much for diving for fly balls, but he didn't win
those two MVP awards for congeniality and looking good in a bathing
suit. Just wait until he shows up next year at The Ballpark looking
quite dapper in that Yankees uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler was never the central figure in that trade. Thompson was.
If the Rangers were going to trade a Hall of Fame run producer and
become a better team in the process, they needed to get a very good
starting pitcher in return.
</P>
<P>
   They did. He is. He just needs time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
