<SLUG> BC-MISS-SAIGON-CLOSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISS SAIGON' TO END 9-YEAR RUN ON BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Miss Saigon,'' the epic Vietnam War musical that
landed a helicopter onstage, sparked a fevered debate about race
and casting, and has now played the Broadway Theater for more than
nine years, will close its run on New Year's Eve, its producer said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, a loose adaptation of Puccini's opera ``Madama
Butterfly,'' will have played 4,063 performances, making it the
sixth longest-running show in Broadway history.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mackintosh, the British impresario who produced ``Miss
Saigon,'' said Thursday that the show had simply run its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an amazing run,'' Mackintosh said, speaking from
London. ``I'm very proud of the work, and very proud of the work
the actors and crew have given. It's a better show now than when we
opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened at a cost of $10.9 million, which made it the most
expensive show ever at the time, ``Miss Saigon'' is expected to
leave Broadway having grossed more than $280 million, and having
been seen by more than 6 million people, numbers that place it in
rare company in the theatrical world.
</P>
<P>
   But the news of its closing also comes at a time when the
splashy British megamusicals defined by works like ``Les
Miserables'' and ``Phantom of the Opera'' seem to be slowly giving
way to a new generation of shows.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fall of ``Saigon'' comes just two months after word
that ``Cats,'' the longest-running show in Broadway history (7,329
performances and counting), would close on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Derided by some critics as valuing flashy effects over
substance, musicals of this kind rely heavily on stage pyrotechics,
and ``Miss Saigon'' is no exception, with an elaborate sequence in
Act II depicting the evacuation of the U.S. Embassy in Saigon. In
it, a helicopter descends from the rafters, lands onstage, picks up
evacuees and lifts off again.
</P>
<P>
   The effect repeatedly wowed audiences, making the show a hot
ticket for fans of musicals and stage magic alike. But like
``Cats,'' the show had become increasingly dependent on tourists as
the years passed. Of late, that audience has diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had very few losing weeks,'' Mackintosh said. ``But as
with any show, the longer you go into your run, the harder it is to
maintain those levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Saigon,'' with music by Claude-Michel Schonberg and
lyrics by Alain Boublil, was a smash critical and popular hit in
London's West End in 1989. And it made headlines even before
opening in New York, but not necessarily the sort producers like.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh had decided to import his British stars, Jonathan
Pryce and Lea Salonga, to Broadway. Asian-American actors objected,
saying the roles should be recast with Asian-American performers.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Equity, the union of actors and stage managers, sided
with the U.S. actors and initially denied permission for Pryce to
perform, on the ground that a Caucasian actor should not play a
Eurasian. (His character, the Engineer, was French-Vietnamese.)
</P>
<P>
   Equity's decision caused a major outcry among union members and
prompted Mackintosh to cancel plans to transfer the production.
Equity quickly reversed its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, the controversy was reopened when Salonga,
who was born in the Philippines, was denied permission to perform.
That, too, prompted a hue and cry; the issue was eventually
resolved in Salonga's favor by an arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   The show, with a $100 top ticket, another Broadway high, finally
opened in April 1991 to strong reviews. Frank Rich, writing in The
New York Times, said the musical was ``gripping entertainment'' and
the ``most exciting of the so-called English musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Pryce and Salonga won Tony Awards for their work.
</P>
<P>
   The show paid back its investors in just 39 weeks, a nearly
unheard-of rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd ever dreamt of having one show as successful as `Miss
Saigon,''' Macintosh said, ``I'd be a happy man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
