<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building Rome By Computer
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ When Russell Crowe, dressed in full Roman regalia,
strides onto the dusty floor of the Colosseum, the camera follows
his gaze in a 360-degree sweep of the scene, taking in the three
tiers of cheering people, the rippling flags, the glinting armor.
It is all very big, very imposing and very real.
</P>
<P>
   Except it isn't real. At least, not all of it. The Colosseum as
recreated for Ridley Scott's ``Gladiator'' _ a sword-and-sandal
epic of the kind they didn't make anymore until he did _ appears to
be three massive stories high, but only the first story actually
existed on the set, which was built on the Mediterranean island of
Malta. The rest was painstakingly added with computer-generated
effects, one byte at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator,'' which opens on May 5, bringing the first big
blast of summer-movie spectacle, took upon itself the task of
recreating ancient Rome in the years after the death of Marcus
Aurelius in A.D. 180. Its main set was constructed around a
17th-century Spanish fort on Malta that Napoleon refurbished in a
classical style. Adding to images made of this set, the filmmakers
mixed in pictures of classical buildings from around Europe and
inserted computer-generated, or CG effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a firm believer in CG as a support for story and
character, absolutely,'' said John Nelson, senior visual-effects
supervisor on the film, who worked with the production designer,
Arthur Max, in recreating ancient Rome. ``I know with Ridley, he
could care less what's easy to do and what the computers are
capable of. What interests him is getting the shot the way he wants
it, to look right and to tell the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The 360-degree shot had its origin, Nelson said, in a question
he asked Scott: how would he shoot the scene if the Colosseum were
actually there in all its glory? Scott said he would have the
camera do the full sweep so the audience would get a good first
look at it. So the computer-effects team made that happen. ``We
didn't do the shot to show off the technology,'' Nelson said. ``We
did it because it was the way the director wanted to tell the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer-generated movie making has come a long way since George
Lucas had Darth Vader in a laser-saber duel with Alec Guinness back
in the first of the ``Star Wars'' movies. Now the effects teams are
as likely to be trying to create reality as fantasy, turning 500
real actors into an army of thousands or giving a sense of solidity
to pure wind.
</P>
<P>
   The gladiator sequences, which are at the heart of Scott's film,
were shot to mimic the way modern-day sporting events are shown on
television, Nelson said, to subliminally make them more real to
today's audiences. There is, for example, the ``blimp shot,'' a
favorite at the Super Bowl, in which the camera seems to float over
the top of the massive Colosseum. There is even what the filmmakers
called their ``Wembley shot.'' In every soccer event broadcast from
Wembley Stadium in London, Nelson said, there has always been a
shot from the uppermost rows looking down toward the stadium floor
over a sea of raised arms, so ``Gladiator'' has this perspective,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Ridley Scott likes are the big shots and the impressive
shots, so that's what we tried to give him,'' Nelson said. ``He
doesn't care for showy visual effects that call attention to
themselves. With this movie, our charge was to convey the size and
scale of Rome, and so our sets were huge, really huge, and our
effects made them seem even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Into Africa, Again
</P>
<P>
   When the director Hugh Hudson was looking for locations to shoot
``I Dreamed of Africa,'' his adaptation of Kuki Gallmann's memoirs
of the struggles that accompanied her aristocratic family's move
from Italy to a remote cattle ranch near the Great Rift Valley in
Kenya, he decided to shoot in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's considered more secure, and it certainly has a better
infrastructure for making movies,'' Hudson said. ``And the day we
started shooting, there was the explosion at the U.S. Embassy in
Nairobi.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opens on May 5, brought Hudson back to Africa
as a director for the first time in 16 years. In 1984 he shot
``Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes'' in the rain
forests of West Africa. ``But that's a whole different place, an
entirely different landscape,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   This time he selected a remote corner of Natal Province, in the
heart of the former Zulu homeland, which was sufficiently distant
yet not too far from hotels that could comfortably accommodate the
large crew and cast. Kim Basinger plays Gallmann. A second unit
eventually went to Kenya for shots of wildlife and the Great Rift
Valley, though most of the movie, set on Gallmann's ranch, was shot
in Natal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took our key people over with us, but as much as possible
we tried to use locals in the production, at every level,'' Hudson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between shooting in a high plains setting and
shooting in the rain forest of ``Greystoke'' were vast, he said.
But there was still something very similar and compelling about the
two African locations. ``I think we all feel it,'' Hudson said.
``Whether it's the Arab parts of the plains or the deepest forest,
you find yourself always drawn back to it once you have been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinkering With Destiny
</P>
<P>
   Some screenplays are told in long, flowing arcs. Others are
intricate interweavings of flashback and dream sequences. Still
others are posed like puzzles, almost daring audiences to try to
catch the filmmakers out. The director Gregory Hoblit said he and
the screenwriter of ``Frequency,'' Toby Emmerich, worked long hours
on the intricate plot, making sure every angle held firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the story is constructed,'' Hoblit said, ``every time
we made even a small change in one sequence, it could have
important effects on other scenes elsewhere in the movie, and we
had to be sure that everything came together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency,'' which opens on Friday, is a kind of time-travel
fantasy in which Jim Caviezel, as a New York police officer in
1999, finds himself talking on an old ham radio set to his father
(Dennis Quaid) in 1969. The kink is that the police officer uses
the moment to save the life of his father, a New York firefighter,
by warning him of his impending death, thus setting off a chain of
effects that multiply and must eventually be set right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we changed something, I would say, OK, what is the
elephant in the room?'' Hoblit said. ``What is it that we're
missing? If we change this moment, then how does that change the
past or change the future or change what the characters know? It's
sort of a puzzle piece, and every piece has to link up together or
the movie won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
