<SLUG> BC-AETNA-EARNINGS-275(ADD)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED AETNA PLEASES WALL STREET WITH A STRONG EARNINGS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A Street.Com version of this story moved earlier.) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aetna Inc., the nation's largest health insurance
company, said Thursday that its first-quarter operating profit rose
16 percent, helped by reduced losses at its Prudential Health Care
unit and a rebound in international business, including financial
services in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that important challenges still remained for the
company but that the results were generally positive and well above
their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, which has been under pressure to slim down from
disgruntled shareholders, said operating earnings were $184
million, or $1.29 a share, compared with $158.5 million, or $1.01 a
share, in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue rose 39 percent, to
$7.89 billion from $5.69 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn $1.12 a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent quarter, a $14.6 million charge made net
income $169.4 million, or $1.19 a share. In the period a year
earlier, a gain of $11.2 million made net income $169.6 million, or
$1.09 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna rose $4.75, or 8.6 percent, to $59.9375 Thursday
on the New York Stock Exchange, well above their $38.50 low on Feb.
18 but still 40 percent below their 52-week high of $99.875 last
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a large degree, all they had to do was not screw up because
expectations were so low'' said Joseph D. France, a health care
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``They did better than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sigh of relief,'' added James A. Lane at Salomon
Smith Barney. ``Some people thought this was going to be a
disaster.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The results strengthen the hand of William H. Donaldson, the
recently appointed chief executive, who was expected to face sharp
questioning by shareholders at the annual meeting Friday at Aetna
headquarters in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining their surprise, Wall Street analysts said Aetna had
provided scant guidance on its financial trends since last fall as
it wrestled with its $1 billion acquisition of Prudential Health
Care.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Aetna said Prudential losses had dropped to an annual
rate of $25 million after tax in the quarter, not counting paybacks
from the seller, the Prudential Insurance Co. of America, good will
and interest from the purchase. Prudential Health Care lost more
than $300 million in 1999, according to state insurance filings.
The paybacks, which partly shielded Aetna from Prudential's losses,
will end early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it had raised premiums 14 percent to 16 percent for
unprofitable Prudential customers and that they had been leaving
faster than Aetna had expected. Prudential membership plummeted to
5.1 million in December from 6 million in October 1998 and is
expected to drop to about 4 million this year, Aetna said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare covers 19.5 million people, including
about 700,000 in Medicare health plans for the elderly and
disabled. Robyn Walsh, a spokeswoman for the company, said Aetna
was losing money on half its Medicare members and would be
notifying Washington officials in July of plans to drop some of its
Medicare health plans next January.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting rising medical costs, the company's profit margins
slipped for both commercial and Medicare health maintenance
organizations, compared with figures in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said medical costs were rising 7 percent to 8 percent for
commercial HMOs, 9 percent to 10 percent for Medicare HMOs and 9
percent to 11 percent for preferred provider organizations.
</P>
<P>
   She said prescription drug costs were ``moderating'' after steep
increases. The company has raised the amount that members for many
higher priced drugs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost trends are continuing to rise,'' said Lori M. Price, an
analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q, making it hard for Aetna to increase profits.
``The price increases they are getting this year are not going to
be adequate to sustain improved margins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that they did show some improvement in the
first quarter,'' Price added. ``But they underestimated the rise in
expenses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
