<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KAHUNA-MOVIE-REVIEW-N     04-27 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAHUNA-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BIG KAHUNA': JUST A COUPLE OF SALESMEN, GOING NOWHERE, AND
SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Here's to the profound religious experience that
comes from doing a job well and being grossly underpaid,'' Larry
(Kevin Spacey) says to his fellow salesmen in ``The Big Kahuna,'' a
picture that from its low-budget looks guarantees the pleasure that
can come only from a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie looked any cheaper, you might think you were paying
more to get into the theater than was spent on making the film.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey, who is one of the movie's producers, breezes into the
picture as if he has the world on a string. It's his chance to
address his role in James Foley's ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' in which
he mostly stood in the corner and let everyone else blow through
like a force of nature. (It's almost as if he were doing Verbal
Kint, his fearful alter ego in ``The Usual Suspects.'')
</P>
<P>
   Spacey is the most theatrical of actors working today. He's the
rare actor who does not exclude audiences when he amuses himself.
Not many performers can pull this off; Eddie Murphy is one of the
few others who can. Spacey suggests a Satanic version of his idol,
Jack Lemmon. In ``American Beauty,' he seems to have gleefully
recycled Lemmon's turn in ``How to Murder Your Wife'' as much as
his work in ``The Apartment.'' Spacey was born to bark ``I rule!''
as he did in ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   As Larry, he definitely rules ``The Big Kahuna,'' which seems to
be some kind of Tae-Bo for actors, a way to keep trim until a role
that really demands a workout comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the action takes place in a hotel room in Kansas. It's a
cheap hospitality suite laid out with cheese slices and raw
vegetables that Larry shares with Phil (Danny DeVito), a member of
the walking wounded, recently separated from his wife and musing
about the death of a salesman, and Bob (Peter Facinelli), a
fresh-faced young Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke,'' Larry says to Phil. ``You don't drink, and
Bob here wouldn't think about lusting after another woman. Between
the three of us, we're practically Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys are camped out for one big customer to peddle their
wares _ industrial lubricants _ to, but Spacey is really the kahuna
here. While he has the showiest role, DeVito gets to build toward
something, though it is wholly unsurprising. The movie, which is
based on Roger Rueff's play ``Hospitality Suite,'' works best when
Larry decides ``not to get too deep'' and bite into the few good
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this worn material is a passed-over good from a
dramaturgical secondhand store. The guys are flawed, waiting to
sell to Godot in their one-ring circus. The director, John
Swanbeck, decided to keep most of the action in one room instead of
opening things up, but this choice doesn't give him the tension he
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, ``The Big Kahuna'' actually feels as if it is
taking place on a stage. Swanbeck lacks the resources to enhance
the action, and dust fills the set as the tired truths are aired
out. It's just hard to tell what would have served this play, which
was adapted by Rueff for the screen, better. It's so transparent
you could wrap sandwiches with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes competitive and salty
disgruntled-salesman language.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BIG KAHUNA' Directed by John Swanbeck; written by Roger
Rueff, based on his play ``Hospitality Suite''; director of
photography, Anastas Michos; edited by Peggy Davis; music by
Christopher Young; production designer, Kalina Ivanov; produced by
Elie Samaha, Kevin Spacey and Andrew Stevens; released by Lions
Gate Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kevin Spacey (Larry), Danny DeVito (Phil) and Peter
Facinelli (Bob).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
