<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AVITAL-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      04-27 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVITAL-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI ACTRESS LEARNS BY DOING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Replaces earlier version sent in error) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL; 
Once there was a beautiful young girl in Tel Aviv who attended a
professional arts high school. She began studying painting and then
switched to acting because she thought it was so easy.
</P>
<P>
   She soon was cast in a professional production of a play and
learned that acting is challenging work taken quite seriously by
others in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Movie stardom in Israel followed, but that was nothing compared
with what lay ahead ...
</P>
<P>
   Mili Avital says she always has held storytelling in high
regard, but she appreciates it even more now that she is portraying
perhaps the most legendary storyteller, Scheherazade, in the ABC
miniseries ``Arabian Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a little girl, I would literally make up a story and put on
a costume,'' Avital said. ``It wasn't as clean as Scheherazade does
it, but it was my version of storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Avital said she believes imagination is an individual's most
important asset. ``That's what makes your life, that's what makes
your future, that's what allows someone to heal, that's what gives
us hope. It's the one limitless thing in the world, our
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the two-part miniseries premiering 8 p.m. Sunday,
viewers will see the Middle Eastern folk tales processed through
the imagination of executive producer Robert Halmi Sr., complete
with buffoonish heroes, murderous thieves and as many
computer-generated effects as that famous magic lamp could hold.
</P>
<P>
   Avital's role is the framework, the well-modulated anchor for
all the adventure, calamity and even comedy in her stories about
Aladdin, Ali Baba and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Halmi said of this leading lady, ``It's casting a bit against
the grain. You think casting Scheherazade you would get the most
glamorous lady you ever saw in your life. But Mili has character
... and that's what's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Arabian Nights,'' the sultan of Baghdad, Schahriar, is
haunted by nightmares of his evil brother's ongoing plot to kill
him and seize the throne, and the sultan's betrayal by his own
bride, whom he killed while she was conspiring with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Scheherazade, a member of the sultan's harem, offers to marry
Schahriar to maintain his rightful claim to the throne, knowing
that the tormented sultan plans to have her killed hours after the
wedding because he fears any wife would murder him.
</P>
<P>
   She enters the marriage, not out of a sense of duty to her
country nor to be a martyr for the harem, but because she truly
loves the sultan _ her favorite childhood playmate _ and she
believes she can rescue him from his torment.
</P>
<P>
   On their wedding night, as the executioner hovers outside the
sultan's bedchamber, Scheherazade summons the lessons she learned
from the bazaar's best storyteller as well as her own vivid
imagination, and the stories begin, stories that will make her too
valued to slay, stories that will liberate the sultan from his
personal demons.
</P>
<P>
   While the cast and crew of 235 bounced from one locale to
another in Turkey or Morocco, creating action sequences and scenes
that would be embellished later with CGI dragons, genies and
giants, Avital was practically stationary, performing nearly all
her scenes with Dougray Scott (``Ever After'') in the sultan's
chamber or sitting at the feet of storyteller Alan Bates (``Women
in Love'') in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to basically sit demurely on the bed and tell the
stories. The director, Steve Barron, had a really specific vision
in his mind, and I knew he was right,'' she said. ``Every time I
start telling a story, then it cuts to a lot of action. When you
come back to me, it has to stay somewhat reserved, otherwise the
movie would be all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very active person, so it was really an incredible
experience to try to hold back everything,'' Avital said. ``It's
very scary for an actor because you're always try to bring in
activity _ you know, they're washing dishes as they're having the
conversation _ business. This had to be so clean, period-wise
because they just didn't do that stuff as they were talking, but
also aesthetically and dramatically it was very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Avital said her scenes with Bates, when Scheherazade seeks his
advice on how to keep the sultan captivated, rang true in her own
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scheherazade is going to the master storyteller, and in a way
I felt like the actress going to the master actor to ask, `How do
you do this? What do you do?''' she said. ``He was like the master
class.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her acting studies that brought Avital, now 28, to New
York in the early '90s, and she says she hadn't intended to stay.
After one year at Circle in the Square's school, she was discovered
by Myrna Jacoby, who is now Avital's manager, and two weeks later
was cast in Roland Emmerich's universe-crossing odyssey
``Stargate,'' opposite Kurt Russell and James Spader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shocking way to get into the industry,'' she said.
``I didn't think those stories existed, and I couldn't believe it
was happening to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was beside the point. When I actually arrived on the
set of a $60 million movie six years ago, I was just so
flabbergasted. I had never seen anything like it in my life. The
last movie I did in Israel before I came was, I would say, one of
the biggest productions in Israel, and the budget was $200,000 _
including my star salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have so many departments in American films, it's
amazing,'' she said. ``You have a water boy! In Israel, the
director gives you water if you're thirsty, or you go to the
nearest faucet, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Avital had a speaking role in ``Stargate,'' but as an ancient
Egyptian girl she conversed in an undocumented dialect _ gibberish
Avital made up herself. If she were required to speak English, she
surely would have lost the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke very little English when I first came,'' Avital said.
``Thank God I didn't have to speak English because I didn't even
understand what the script was about. I was just trying to figure
it out as I was going. The only words I recognized were 'action,'
'cut' and 'do it again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Avital speaks flawless English easily and
appears ready to merge into Hollywood's fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of this interview, she was in Belize filming Ernest
Hemingway's ``After the Storm'' with Benjamin Bratt and Armand
Assante, and another Avital movie, ``The Young Girl and the
Monsoon,'' with Diane Venora and Terry Kinney, was screened at the
recent Los Angeles Independent Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The West Hollywood resident has appeared on many red carpets
around town on the arm of ``Friends'' star David Schwimmer, her
boyfriend since they co-starred in the 1998 comedy ``Kissing a
Fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Avital does not want to lose her expatriate perspective
and says she would be happy to be a part of any project like
``Arabian Nights'' that can broaden viewers' horizons beyond their
own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in the States, I kind of got used to the fact that, oh,
I live in the biggest country in the world, why do I need to see
anything that's not American?'' Avital said. ``You really forget
that, and it's so important to be reminded of the entire world, and
the fact that we can bring another culture in. The point shouldn't
be just bringing the American culture to other cultures _ it should
also be vice versa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
