<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NIKE-VIETNAM-ART-900(     04-27 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-VIETNAM-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE FOR NIKE AND OTHER U.S. BUSINESSES IN VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIEN HOA, Vietnam _ Nguyen Anh Ha has never heard of the trade
talks between Vietnam and the United States. But Ha, a 26-year-old
migrant from northern Vietnam, knows all too well the fragility of
life as a factory worker in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been worried ever since I came here,'' said Ha, as he
rested after work in his bare one-room shelter, not far from the
sprawling Nike plant near Ho Chi Minh City where he makes
$120-a-pair athletic shoes. ``We keep hearing rumors that they
might reduce the number of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike executives insist they have no plans to slash their work
force in Vietnam, which numbers more than 45,000 at five factories
owned and operated by South Korean and Taiwanese contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they acknowledge that Nike's future here has grown cloudier
because of the Hanoi government's reluctance to sign a landmark
trade agreement with the United States. The deal, which was agreed
to in principle in July, has stalled since Vietnamese negotiators
began quibbling over various provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're missing out on the biggest market in the world,''
complains Lalit Monteiro, general manager of Nike's operations in
Vietnam. ``Our factories here are heavily dependent on the Asian
and European markets. If those markets go sour, we're going to feel
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Nike is banned from exporting products to the
United States. Nor have the attacks on Nike's labor practices in
its factories played a role in limiting U.S. purchases. But with
the United States imposing import duties of 18 percent to 35
percent on all goods made in Vietnam, the company says it is not
economical to use this country as a manufacturing base for the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, based in Beaverton, Ore., is one of dozens of foreign and
local companies in Vietnam whose fortunes would be affected by an
agreement. But as the largest private employer in the country, it
illustrates better than most the huge stakes of the deal for the
Vietnamese people. Countries like Vietnam can pay a high price if
they choose not to accede to the demands of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro estimated that Nike would increase the percentage of
its shoes made in Vietnam from 12 percent to 15 percent if the deal
is approved. That translates to more than 20,000 new jobs. Other
U.S. executives here said the company has talked about shifting as
many as 40,000 jobs from its plants in China. On the other hand,
some doubt that Nike will stay in Vietnam without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a risk,'' said Pete Peterson, the U.S.
ambassador to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, a retired Air Force pilot who was shot down in Vietnam
and spent more than six years as a prisoner of war here, has been
one of the trade agreement's most dogged proponents. In addition to
promoting its merits to the Vietnamese government, he has lobbied
the U.S. business community _ exhorting sometimes demoralized
business people not to give up on the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk for Vietnam is the missed opportunity,''
Peterson said. ``They have to find a way to create jobs. This trade
agreement would be a major job-creation vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Like trade pacts with other countries, the deal would guarantee
access to Vietnamese markets for U.S. companies. In return, the
United States would lift stiff duties on imports from Vietnam. In
Nike's case, that would slice 14 percent off the average cost of a
pair of shoes made here.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement also has some new provisions, including a
requirement that Hanoi disclose government procurement contracts.
Vietnamese officials protest that no other country has been asked
to do this. And they note that the World Trade Organization failed
to ratify such a requirement at its meeting in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where _ 25 years after the end of the Vietnam War
_suspicion toward Washington bubbles under the surface, some people
view the deal as a way for the United States to win economically
what it could not win militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vietnamese are driven by fear,'' said Thomas J. Vallely,
director of the Indochina program at the Harvard Institute for
International Development. ``They ask, `Is globalization destroying
us? Is this a political as well as an economic move on the part of
the Western world?'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Vallely and other experts said, a trade agreement would
benefit Vietnam far more than the United States. Vietnam exports
$650 million worth of goods to the United States, while U.S.
companies export only $350 million worth to Vietnam. While Nike
would be able to sell its shoes here, that would be a fraction of
what Nike's factories could export to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the U.S. market would expand Nike's business in
Vietnam by more than just the sneakers shipped to California, Texas
or New York. Because its Vietnamese factories export only to Asia
and Europe, they are limited in the number of models they make. A
model popular in the United States, as well as Europe, would be
made in China or Indonesia _ not Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing orders because we don't have the flexibility to
ship to the U.S. market,'' Monteiro said. Not surprisingly, Nike
produces fewer shoes in Vietnam than in China, Indonesia or
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   For Monteiro, who used to work in Nike's product development
division, the delay in the trade deal has been a frustrating
introduction to Vietnam.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
