<HEADLINE>
BALLOON CATHETER INVENTOR WINS $500,000 AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas J. Fogarty, who invented the world's first balloon
catheter for the cardiovascular system and holds 63 patents in
surgical instrumentation, has been awarded the $500,000 annual
Lemelson-MIT prize _ the world's largest single award for invention
and innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gross, the inventor of the walkie-talkie and the first
wireless pager, was honored with the Lemelson-MIT Lifetime
Achievement Award for invention and innovation. Gross, often called
the ``founding father' of wireless communication, developed the
walkie-talkie in 1938 when he was still in high school in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty's catheter marked the beginning of less invasive surgery
and was the precursor to the first device used for angioplasty _ a
standard treatment for blocked coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Other Fogarty inventions include surgical clips, clamps, and an
aortic stent-graft. He has founded several companies and teaches
surgery at Stanford University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Fogarty epitomizes American ingenuity and has made a
lasting and beneficial impact on society,'' said Lester C. Thurow,
an economist and Lemelson-MIT board chairman. The Massachusetts
Institute of Technology oversees the awards, which were established
in 1994 by inventor Jerome Lemelson and his wife, Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what excites me is making something work better,''
Fogarty said in a telephone interview Thursday. ``Part of the
process is acknowledging what does not work as well as what could
work. The first thing to determine is that it is a real problem and
not just an inadequacy on your part or other individuals, but it is
a pervasive problem. Then you have to apply technology to resolve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, 66, said of all his inventions, ``the one that brings
the most satisfaction is the orginal balloon catheter. It kind of
opened a whole new technology and a less invasive approach. It was
documented you could use a catether to correct problems and it also
led to the realization that you could do procedures much less
invasively and eliminate trauma to patients and avoid anesthesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, who lives in Portola Valley, Calif., founded or
cofounded 25 start-up companies that manufacture medical products
and cofounded Three Arch Partners, a venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not only remarkably inventive but is also a dedicated
mentor and inspiring role model for young scientists, engineers,
and clinicians,'' said Thurow.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, 82, said he became an amateur radio operator at an early
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most amateur radio operators had their radios in a room. I
wanted to be mobile, that was my desire _ and I worked hard to
figure out a transceiver,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   His handiwork caught the attention of the Office of Strategic
Services, the World War II precursor to the CIA, and he developed
for the agency a two-way air-to-ground communications system used
in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said he is astonished by the proliferation of wireless
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genie is out of the bottle'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
