<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NIKE-VIETNAM-ART-2NDT     04-27 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-VIETNAM-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BIEN HOA, Vietnam: to Vietnam.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And it comes at a time when Nike finally seems to have addressed
another chronic problem in its operations here: labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, Nike was stung by the release of an internal
report that documented unsafe conditions at one of its biggest
plants. The report, by the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young, said the
factory, also near Ho Chi Minh City, exposed workers to
unacceptably high levels of toxic chemicals. It also said 77
percent of the workers suffered respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nike said it was acting to improve conditions in the factory
even before the report was publicized. And even the company's
critics acknowledge that conditions are better. Dara O'Rourke, an
environmental consultant who helped distribute the report to the
news media, was allowed to conduct a follow-up inspection of the
factory, known as Tae Kwang Vina, in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt the heat, which has motivated them to do things,''
said O'Rourke, an assistant professor of environmental policy at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``They switched away
from the most toxic compounds. But they continue to work with
organic solvents and glues.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a visitor on a tour of Tae Kwang Vina recently, Nike
officials pointed out improvements that had been made since
O'Rourke's inspection. The factory, owned by a Korean company, now
uses water-based, as opposed to chemical, solvents everywhere on
its assembly line. It is introducing water solvents in the
stitching area, where the leather parts of the shoes are pieced
together.
</P>
<P>
   Above workers' heads, powerful fans circulated the air, fans
that Nike officials said had been installed since O'Rourke's visit.
In noisy parts of the factory, a vast majority of workers wore
rubber earplugs _ addressing another of his worries.
</P>
<P>
   Nike's contractors said they were prodded to improve conditions
by the storm of criticism in the United States. ``I had pride in my
factory,'' said C. T. Park, president of Tae Kwang Vina, which has
more than 10,000 workers. ``And then suddenly it was the worst
factory in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike has not been able to fix every problem in what are still
monotonous, taxing jobs that can require handling hazardous
material. Ha and two other workers in Nike's Chang Shin factory
complained of runny noses, which they said began soon after they
started there. Their job is to press synthetic rubber into a heavy
metal cast and heat it to create the contoured shape of a sole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I have good health,'' Ha said. ``But in five years,
I won't be able to work at this job anymore. It is too hard. I'll
have to look for lighter work at another factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha works 10-hour shifts, six days a week, plus overtime, earning
the equivalent of $50 a month. That is slightly below Nike's
declared average monthly wage of $55. But the company notes that it
is still well above Vietnam's average _ $26.
</P>
<P>
   Labor laws in Vietnam are stricter than in many Asian countries,
and Nike says it complies, or does even better, in every category.
For example, Vietnam's minimum age for factory workers is 15. In
Nike's footwear factories, workers must be 18; in its garment
factories, they can be 16.
</P>
<P>
   Employers cannot demand more than 48 hours a week from workers,
excluding overtime. But they can run their factories every day.
Even so, Nike said it ordered its factories to close on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Ha, however, said he had worked in the Chang Shin factory on a
few recent Sundays. After an investigation, Nike confirmed that the
plant had asked workers to do cleaning and maintenance on those
days. Looking perturbed, Monteiro said he would discourage the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous Nike executives in Vietnam, Monteiro is neither
secretive nor particularly defensive about the company's labor
practices. He says he welcomes inspections of the factories by
outside monitors like O'Rourke. ``We closed down after the
controversy,'' Monteiro said. ``In retrospect, it was a mistake.
But you learn and you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike has also learned there are some battles not worth joining.
The Vietnamese government, for example, is weighing whether to
reduce the work week to 40 hours from 48. The American Chamber of
Commerce has urged Nike, as the largest foreign employer, to lobby
against the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never come out in public and ask the Vietnamese
government not to have people work fewer hours,'' said Chris
Helzer, Nike's director of government affairs. ``We'd get strung
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, with the trade agreement hanging in the balance, Helzer
noted there were far more dire threats to Vietnam's
competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
