<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VIKINGS-AMERICA-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDINAVIAN LEADERS PUT SEAL OF APPROVAL ON SMITHSONIAN'S VIKING
EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Canada)   By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One thousand years after Leif Eriksson reached the
coast of North America _ apparently at Newfoundland and probably
elsewhere, too _ royalty and political leaders of Scandinavia
showed up here Thursday to put their seal of approval on what
promises to be the Year of the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Led by King Harald and Queen Sonja of Norway, the Scandinavian
visitors inspected a new exhibition, ``Vikings: The North Atlantic
Saga,'' at the Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History. The
show opens to the public on Saturday and will run through Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 300 objects on exhibit include silver and bronze
inlaid swords, battle axes and silver jewelry and other loot from
the raids on Europe and the British Isles that made Viking
marauders so feared between 750 and about 1050 and fixed their
pillage-and-plunder reputation down through history. A Swedish
ninth century ``picture stone'' depicts two Vikings battling with
swords in Valhalla, the warriors' heaven. A centerpiece of the show
is a replica of a classic Viking ``ship burial.''
</P>
<P>
   Another side of the Vikings, though, is reflected in samples of
textiles and carvings, a manuscript of the Iceland Sagas _ the only
written record of the Norse explorations in the North Atlantic _
and various artifacts found in their Greenland settlement and along
the shores of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William W. Fitzhugh, an archeologist and director of the
museum's Arctic Studies Center, said that previous exhibitions
``had failed to communicate the depths of Viking culture,
especially in lands west of Europe.'' Recent archeological finds
and new interpretations of historical documents, he said, cast a
new light on the Vikings, also known as the Norse, as more than
just horn-helmeted warriors but also as successful boat builders
and traders, canny navigators and explorers who planted colonies
across a northern arc of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   On entering the exhibition gallery, visitors read the message
the show strives to deliver: ``Say Vikings! and images leap to
mind, yet the well-worn stereotypes hardly tell the whole story.
Behind battle axes and dragon-prowed longships lay a bustling world
of keen traders, prosperous townsmen, diligent livestock farmers
and master shipbuilders. From their ranks came extraordinary,
legendary explorers and settlers _ men and women who expanded the
horizons of their world, and ours.''
</P>
<P>
   More than once, the royal visitors and curators pointedly
remarked that these westering mariners had made it to what would be
called America 500 years before Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   An honored guest Thursday at the exhibition was Helge Ingstad,
100 years old, who was the Norwegian explorer and writer who found
at L'Anse aux Meadows in Newfoundland what has turned out to be the
first established site of a Norse settlement around 1000. Excavated
in the 1960s, the ruins of sod houses and the location itself,
scholars say, fit the descriptions in the sagas of a base camp
Eriksson erected.
</P>
<P>
   King Harald praised Ingstad for discovering ``new knowledge
about our history.'' He said the exhibition had significance for
both Scandinavians and Americans as a reminder of ``our common
Viking past.''
</P>
<P>
   Other representatives from the Viking homelands at Thursday's
event included: Olfur Ragnar Grimsson, president of Iceland; Tarja
Halonen, president of Finland; Crown Princess Victoria of Sweden,
and Prince Joachim of Denmark. Like the others, Elsebeth Gerner
Nielson, chairwoman of the Nordic Council of Ministers for Cultural
Affairs, a sponsor of the exhibition, seemed cheerfully willing to
accept both the pillaging and heroic sides of the Viking image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we're not terrifying anyone anymore,'' she said, ``we
still like the comparison with Vikings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other support for the $3-million exhibition was provided by
Volvo. The curators, Fitzhugh and Elizabeth I. Ward, both of the
Smithsonian Institution, obtained artifacts from museums in Canada,
Denmark, Greenland, Iceland, Norway and Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   After its Smithsonian run, the exhibition will move to the
American Museum of Natural History in Manhattan, opening there on
Oct. 20 _ which happens to be eight days after Columbus Day _ and
closing next Jan. 20. Then it is to travel to Houston, Los Angeles
and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   The millennial anniversary of Norse explorations of North
America has inspired several other events, especially in Canada. A
Viking exhibit is to open in St. John's, Newfoundland, on June 2. A
re-enactment of the people, crafts and foods of the Viking era is
planned at L'Anse aux Meadows, the confirmed Norse settlement site.
And several replicas of Viking ships will be plying the coastal
waters of Newfoundland and Labrador, stopping at community
festivals marking the 1,000 years since Leif Eriksson passed this
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
