<HEADLINE>
GLOBE REPORTER WINS TOP AWARD FOR CHECHNYA COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boston Globe reporter David Filipov has won the
Overseas Press Club's Hal Boyle award for best newspaper or wire
service reporting from abroad for his coverage of Russia's war in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Filipov, the Globe's Moscow bureau chief, was cited Thursday for
the group's top prize by judges for his courage, persistence, and
vivid depictions of ``the ambiguity of a war in which Russian
troops fought Islamic militants, Russian bandits fought Russian
soldiers, and Chechen gangs fought Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This honor is richly deserved,'' Globe Editor Matthew V.
Storin said. ``David is not only a highly knowledgeable foreign
correspondent, aided by his fluent Russian capability, but also
he's courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other winners at the annual awards ceremony were The
Associated Press for its investigation of reports of widespread
killings by US troops during the start of the Korean War; Mark
Schoofs of the Village Voice for his examination of AIDS in Africa;
and several who were recognized for coverage of Kosovo: National
Public Radio, NBC Nightly News, Newsweek, Reuters photographer
Yannis Behrakis, and Magnum photographer Gilles Peress.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Herald reporter David Talbot won an award for reporting
on international environment on the price of oil development in
Ecuador, and Sebastian Rotella of the Los Angeles Times won the
best Latin American reporting award for his series on reform in the
region.
</P>
</TEXT>
