<SLUG> BC-GLF-RACHEL28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hetherington returns to defend Chick-fil-A title
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKBRIDGE, Ga. _ Rachel Hetherington no longer is a stranger
at Eagle's Landing Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Walking by the putting green or up the hill from the practice
range, fans and volunteers are quick to notice Hetherington, now
that she's the defending champion in the Chick-fil-A Charity
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now if Hetherington can just find a way to get noticed on the
LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm always `the other Australian,''' she said
Thursday, ``but that's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the Karrie Webb phenomena. Hetherington, 28, a native of
Queensland, Australia, is defending twice this spring _ today in
Stockbridge and in early June at Myrtle Beach, which last year fell
the week after the Chick-fil-A.
</P>
<P>
   But Webb, with four wins already this year and a domination of
Tiger Woods proportions, is the story of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will take another win here for Hetherington. Or a major
championship. It seems as if Rachel Hetherington is always feeling
a need to prove something. Hetherington's 1999 Chick-fil-A victory
came on the first hole of a sudden-death playoff. She won when
Lorie Kane missed a 4-foot putt at No. 18 and parred, to lose to
Hetherington's up-and-down birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Kane, famous for her second-place finishes, almost became a
bigger story by losing again. Lost in the post-tournament analysis,
however, was that Hetherington had birdied 16 and 18 to get into
the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people thought of it that way, because Lorie
has had so many near-misses,'' Hetherington said this week. ``It's
tough to see anybody miss a putt like that. I guess everybody would
have been more excited if I'd made a 30-foot putt, but it was still
a birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later came another win with a disclaimer. With rounds of
69-68 at Myrtle Beach, Hetherington managed her third career win
when rain shortened the event to 36 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chick-fil-A host Nancy Lopez, for one, notices how much
more confident Hetherington seems this year, the Aussie's
personality typically is as low-profile as her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a quiet player,'' Lopez said. ``She'll just kind of come
up there and win, all of a sudden. She just inches her way up
there, and the next thing you know, she's winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington, who tied for fourth last week in the Longs Drug
Challenge, will require all of her game to repeat this week. She
must conquer not only Webb but also the Eagle's Landing rough,
which thrived in a warm spring and has grown thicker and longer
than before. More than in past years, hitting the fairway earns a
reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember it being this thick last year,'' Hetherington
said, ``especially just off the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington is 24th on the current money list. Last year, in
her third full season on the LPGA Tour, she finished 12th, with
$538,034.
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington is experiencing a tournament as defending champion
for just the second time, and she isn't comfortable with the role.
But improvement seems likely: After a playoff win over Annika
Sorenstam in the 1998 Big Apple Classic, Hetherington missed the
cut the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to try and feed off the confidence of last
year,'' she said. ``I feel like I've already won the tournament, so
anything else is bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
