<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PINK-FLAMINGOS28-COX     04-27 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINK-FLAMINGOS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. _ They seemed harmless enough. Two plastic
pink flamingos stuck in the ground in front of a home in
Lawrenceville's Towne Park subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   For Ellen and Doug Henry, though, the pink flamingos added up to
more than just tacky yard decor. They added up to nearly $3,400 in
fines for violating the subdivision's covenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money for two little flamingos,'' said Ellen
Henry, a 37-year-old paralegal, who has refused to pay the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes over the proverbial pink flamingo are not uncommon
within the mass of metro Atlanta subdivisions where homeowners
associations enforce covenants. Such rules and regulations are
designed to stifle bad taste, motivate lazy homeowners and
eliminate creative additions to one's home, all in the name of
protecting fair market value. Yet they often end up pitting
neighbor against neighbor, with resolution coming from a judge.
</P>
<P>
   In the Henrys' case, the dispute actually is over pink
flamingos, birds that originally cost $15 for the pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally shocked,'' said Ellen Henry, who learned last
month that the Towne Park Homeowners Association had placed a lien
on her home after she and her husband put it up for sale. ``I
thought at first it was because of past homeowners' dues and that
they had the wrong address.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in October, Doug Henry had planted two bright pink
Flamingos next to the front door. He later placed them on either
side of a ``For Sale'' sign at the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had just kind of a thing for them,'' said Doug
Henry, a 51-year-old attorney, who bought the birds at an antique
market. ``I think they are a kin to yard art.''
</P>
<P>
   In late November, the homeowners association began fining the
Henrys $25 a day for breaking a covenant that prohibits ``exterior
lawn decorations'' unless approved by the association's board.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lien, the attorney who handled the sale of the
Henrys' home last week withheld the fine from the money the couple
was due. The closing attorney agreed to hold it in escrow until
today, however, while the couple attempted to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Henrys say they would have removed the offending flamingos
had someone knocked on their door, given them a call or sent them a
letter to inform them of the violation. The homeowners association
says it did write.
</P>
<P>
   George Nowack, who has made a specialty of representing
homeowners associations, said the board sent a certified letter
Oct. 14 giving the Henrys 30 days to remove the birds. The letter
came back undeliverable. A second certified letter Nov. 23 informed
the Henrys they would be fined $25 a day because they hadn't
complied. It, too, was returned by the post office as
undeliverable.
</P>
<P>
   The Henrys claim they never saw the letters, nor any notice of
them by the postal service. They wonder why no one bothered to find
out the reason for their silence.
</P>
<P>
   Nowack said the bylaws require only that the association send a
certified letter. Asking board members to personally visit every
home where there's a violation would put an undue burden on the
association's board, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Nowack said Thursday that the association will end
the matter for $374, which includes attorneys' fees. During a phone
call Thursday afternoon, Doug Henry said he's inclined to accept
the offer. Ellen Henry, who was on the line with him, abruptly cut
in and insisted they would pay no more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   If that turns out to be the case, Nowack said he'll just take
the $3,400 when it's released from escrow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
