</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CLONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS DEVELOP YOUNGER CLONE CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers say they have found a way to reverse the aging
process in the cells used to create cloned calves, potentially
overcoming one of the biggest obstacles to cloning human organs,
from replacement hearts to new brain cells for victims of
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, experiments such as the creation of Dolly the cloned
sheep have produced offspring whose cells were biologically as
``old'' as the original, raising fears that clones could be doomed
to premature decline and death.
</P>
<P>
   But the six young calves cloned by researchers at Advanced Cell
Technology in Worcester, Mass. not only show no signs of premature
aging, but their cells in fact appear to be 50 percent younger than
other calves born at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if the animals, now ranging in age from
several months to a year old, will have prolonged lifespans. But
the report in the current Science vastly reassures scientists who
had worried that clones might be born with prematurely aged cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important, cutting-edge work,'' said Huber Warner, a
research official at the National Institute on Aging. But, he
added, the researchers ``are very careful to not claim that this is
going to reverse aging'' in people.
</P>
<P>
   However, scientists at Advanced Cell Technology say the finding
is highly encouraging for the prospect of cloning human cells to
create healthy cells, tissues and organs to repair the damage of
illness and aging.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the new results, said Dr. Robert Lanza, vice
president for research at ACT, ``you might be able to produce
young, healthy cells by the billions or trillions _ enough to make
a patch for a damaged heart, or even a whole heart itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The key issue tackled by the ACT research has to do with the way
living cells age. The long strands of chromosomes inside each cell
are capped on each end by structures called telomeres, which
resemble the tips of shoelaces. Each time the cell reproduces, the
telomeres get shorter until they wear out completely and the cell
dies.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Dolly, her telomeres were shown to be the same
age as the six-year-old ewe from which she was cloned by the Roslin
Institute in Scotland. By comparison, the cells in ACT's calves
have telomeres 50 percent longer than the parent cells.
</P>
<P>
   Michael West, president and CEO of ACT, said the results confirm
``that cloning (from aged cells) is possible, and that you can run
the biology in reverse'' to transform old, worn-out cells into
pristine embryonic cells with a normal _ or perhaps even extended _
lifetime ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have this really elegant story that tells us we can
take cells from mature individuals and reset their telomere clock''
to rejuvenate them, added Dr. Ronald DePinho, a Harvard and
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute researcher.
</P>
<P>
   DePinho, a leading investigator of telomere function and aging,
said that chronic diseases like cirrhosis of the liver are caused
partly by speeded-up aging of cells' telomeres, and that the new
research might lead to better treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lanza and West, authors of the Science paper
include scientists from the Lankenau Institute for Medical Research
in Wynnewood, Pa., and Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia;
Terry Fox Laboratory in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada; and
the University of British Columbia. The animals themselves are
presently on a farm in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The cells used for cloning ACT's calves came originally from a
45-day-old calf fetus. These cells, from connective tissue, were
spurred in the laboratory to divide rapidly until they had reached
95 percent of their expected lifespan and showed many of the
typical signs of aging. The aim here was to show that the
age-reversing technique would work even in the oldest cells.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclei of those cells then were placed into cow eggs whose
own nuclei had been removed. Of the 1,896 embryos thus created, 79
were placed into the wombs of surrogate mother cows, resulting in
the birth of six identical heifers. The calves, named Persephone,
Lily, Daffodil, Crocus, Forsythia and Rose, now live on a farm in
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spate of cloning research in cows, mice, sheep and
pigs was touched off by the birth of Dolly, the first mammal ever
cloned from an adult cell, at the Roslin Institute in Edinburgh in
1996. Although Dolly's cells were found to be the same age as the
ewe from which she was cloned, the significance of that fact isn't
clear: Dolly has been healthy and given birth at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   The biological age of Dolly's cells was an estimate based on the
lengths of the telomeres in her cells.
</P>
<P>
   The ACT researchers aren't sure why the calves' telomeres were
reset when Dolly's weren't. But they used a different type of cell
than the one from which Dolly was cloned, and they combined it with
the egg at a different phase of the cell's life cycle. It was also
done in different species.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ian Wilmut of the Roslin Institute, credited with creating
Dolly, said in an e-mail comment that the ACT paper ``is very
interesting.'' But he added, ``there is no reason to suppose that
increasing telomere length in the calves will increase their
lifespan. Lifespan is determined by many factors of which telomere
length may be one under some circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar comments came from Dr. Jerry Shay, a cell biologist and
pioneer in telomere research at the University of Texas Southwest
Medical Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Shay was skeptical that the lengths of their telomeres meant all
that much either for Dolly or the new calves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dont think Dolly was a sheep in lamb's clothing and I don't
think these cows are younger than they look,'' said Shay who is on
the scientific advisory board of rival Geron Corp. of Menlo Park,
Calif. ``I believe aging is much more complex than just telomere
biology.''
</P>
<P>
   Geron is pursuing a different strategy for rejuvenating cells,
which relies on adding telomerase, an enzyme involved in rebuilding
telomeres, to cells to reverse their aging.
</P>
<P>
   West, the ACT president, emphasized that the company is not
interested in cloning whole human beings. ACT researchers are
currently continuing their efforts to clone human cells to create
embryos from which primitive stem cells can be harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Those stem cells, once scientists learn to manipulate them,
could give rise to specialized cells and tissues to be implanted
into patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
