<HEADER>
A9120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-COST-BOS &LR;      04-27 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-COST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS, PRIVATE GROUPS FINANCING GONZALEZ CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three days before the federal government forcibly
removed Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives, a
small plane passed over the house, carrying a banner that read,
``Send Elian home _ the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, taxpayers in Miami, and Boston and Washington for
that matter, are spending hundreds of thousands of dollars to
resolve the international custody battle, a dispute that has
occupied the nation's attention almost since the day the 6-year-old
Cuban was found floating in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Justice Department, providing the first
preliminary cost estimates, said the federal government had spent
more than $578,000 on the case through Monday, including Saturday's
dramatic raid. That does not include the cost for Elian and his
family's stay at Andrews Air Force Base in suburban Maryland from
Saturday to Tuesday, and it excludes normal salary and benefits for
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But, whenever the Elian matter is finally sorted out, the US
government's cost may be the easiest fact to figure. Far more
complicated is who is paying for what the government is not, and
how much that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since there are so many private entities involved and Cuba
itself is involved, it would be surprising if we ever find the cost
for some of this stuff,'' said Tom McClusky, senior policy analysis
with the National Taxpayers Union. ``Everything is so convoluted.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a United Methodist agency footing the legal bills for
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and a legal fund in Miami set
up by a Cuban-American, Armando Gutierrez, to help Elian's
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez in his fight to keep the child in the
United States. The Cuban-American National Foundation is paying for
Elian's Florida relatives' travels to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not exactly clear who is paying for Juan Miguel
Gonzalez's meals and other costs associated with living in the
United States while he awaits court action next month on whether he
can take his son back to Cuba, if he desires, and also who is
paying for friends and relatives traveling here from Cuba. US
government officials this week said that the Cuban government is
picking up some of those expenses, but specifics were hard to come
by.
</P>
<P>
   The General Board of the Church and Society of the United
Methodist Church has collected more than $50,000 in contributions
to pay Gonzalez's legal bills and hopes to raise $100,000. The
agency set up the fund at New York's Chase Manhattan Bank and it is
being administered by the National Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Hakola, an official with the United Methodist agency,
could not say for certain whether the money collected was being
used only for legal expenses or whether it was also helping finance
Elian's family's stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set up the fund to assist Juan Miguel,'' Hakola said. ``The
bank account is now in the hands of the National Council of
Churches and how that is being paid out _ we have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy McDowell, a spokeswoman with the council of churches, said
the group was only administering the legal fund and referred
questions about how the money was being spent to the United
Methodist agency. She said even if the fund succeeds in collecting
$100,000 that might not be enough to pay for Juan Miguel Gonzalez's
legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez, a spokesman for Elian's Miami relatives, said the
legal defense fund he set up for Lazaro Gonzalez had received more
than $200,000 in donations, including many checks for $5 and $10.
Most of that sum came from a weekend marathon in March sponsored by
four radio stations in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez said the fund had paid for at least one relative's
trip to Washington, but most of their trips were paid by the Cuban
American National Foundation, a lobbying group based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lawyers are working for free; they are only charging for
expenses, filing fees and secretaries,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of tending to the case has not been free for
taxpayers. The city of Miami has spent about $1 million patroling
the Little Havana neighborhood and keeping peace in the city during
the fight over Elian.
</P>
<P>
   And the $578,000 preliminary estimate for the US government is
likely to climb much higher. That figure covers $374,000 spent by
the Immigration and Naturalization Service, including the cost of
Elian's government airplane flight to Washington and the cost of
training and housing 131 immigration agents who participated in the
raid.
</P>
<P>
   US marshals, who provided 20 deputies for the raid and security
for Elian's father in Washington and his family since Saturday,
spent $161,000. Other amounts spent included psychiatric
consultants, mediators and conciliators and legal work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1913EDT &QL; 
