<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE PRESSURED TO RESTORE RULE OF LAW IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Chenjerai Hunzvi is the man behind the
growing state of anarchy in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans
Association, he is the general behind the campaign to confiscate
millions of acres of commercial farmland from whites. His
nom-de-guerre, dating back to the 1970's, is ``Hitler,'' but at
times he has also called himself ``Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   But prominent disaffected war veterans say he is little more
than a thug and a thief. Two internal probes by the association
have found he guilty of bilking hundreds of thousands of dollars
invested on behalf of the veterans, and he was jailed a year ago
for fraud. The case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   The High Court, meanwhile, charged him with contempt two weeks
ago for failing to end the farm invasions, which the court twice
ruled were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Hunzvi claims to be fighting for land on behalf of all his
comrades who risked their lives to liberate the country. In fact,
observers say, he is one half of the most important personal
relationship in Zimbabwe. The ties between Hunzvi and President
Robert Mugabe lie at the crux of the violence ripping through
Zimbabwe. Through the brutal exploitation of the masses, sources
close to the two men say, each meets the other's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two bedfellows,'' said a former official of the war
veterans, requesting anonymity. ``Hunzvi feels that if Mugabe stays
in power, the case against him will be dropped. And Mugabe feels
that with the war veterans on his side, he will remain in power.
They are fighting a common war.''
</P>
<P>
   As political violence escalates _ at least 15 people have been
killed and scores more have been badly beaten in recent weeks _
Mugabe faces growing international pressure to reestablish the rule
of law.
</P>
<P>
   British diplomats Thursday received a high-level Zimbabwean
delegation in London for talks on defusing the southern African
country's crisis. Britain had offered an additional $57 million for
land reform if Mugabe ends the farm attacks and takes steps to
ensure that upcoming parliamentary elections are free and fair. But
the delegation refused to provide those assurances and the talks
broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the end of eight hours of talks with the Zimbabwean
ministers, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said ``I made it crystal
clear there would be no further talks until the end of occupations.
. . . The ball is now in their court.''
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, meanwhile, Hunzvi told farmers again Thursday that
the invasions of their land would continue. Leashing the war
veterans, observers say, would mean that Mugabe would lose his
trump card ahead of the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 20-year reign, critics say, Mugabe has relied on
intimidation to retain power. By all appearances, he is doing so
again now. With his country facing its worst economic crisis in at
least a decade, however, Mugabe cannot completely ignore
international reaction. Zimbabwe has been ground to a halt by
chronic shortages fuel and foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe appeared Thursday to be appealing to Britain with a
different approach. Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri said he
would begin using special powers granted under the Law and Order
Maintenance Act to quell political violence. The provisions allow
the police to restrict political activities such as rallies and
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights lawyer Brian Kadoro viewed the announcement as both
an attempt to trip up the opposition and appease Britain on the day
his envoys sat down in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a public exercise in response to Britain's
insistence for a return to law and order, to create an impression
that war veterans are not being violent,'' Kadoro said. ``But
political parties are not the ones beating people on the farms.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's supporters have sown intimidation across nearly 1,000
farms, beating farmers and their workers and demanding their
allegiance to the ruling party. Hunzvi has vowed that the veterans
will start another war if Mugabe's party loses the elections.
</P>
<P>
   It may be bluster. Hunzvi represents only a small percentage of
the war veterans, who themselves number only about 50,000 in a
population of 12.5 million. Leaders of the Zimbabwean Defense
Forces and several prominent veterans have distanced themselves
from the association chairman. Others want him out.
</P>
<P>
   According to minutes of an extraordinary meetings of veteran
investors held in Harare last month, Hunzvi is guilty of grossly
mismanaging a joint fund set up with veterans' money to finance
development projects for ex-combatants and their families. The
minutes also allege that Hunzvi fired several association officers
who accused him of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   That follows a special association probe last year which found
that ``almost all the projects created to promote the welfare of
the members are almost bankrupt.'' A recent audit discovered huge
sums of money invested by veterans in the joint fund, which is
administered by Hunzvi, has gone missing.
</P>
<P>
   With fraud charges still pending, Hunzvi's motive for
orchestrating the farm attacks was simple to understand, Kadoro
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunzvi misappropriated funds,'' he said. ``Mugabe has that
against him, but he also has the power to pardon. So Hunzvi will
sing any song Mugabe asks him to sing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
