<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO IS BETTER THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates, founder of Microsoft, is unrepentant. Steven
Ballmer, the company president, will admit at worst to bad manners.
The inability of Gates and Ballmer to acknowledge that Microsoft
illegally wielded monopoly power suggests the government would be
wise to break up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft defenders argue that the government case is based on
5-year-old, stale allegations. However, the software at the heart
of the case is ubiquitous today. Microsoft Windows is the dominant
operating system in personal computers. Microsoft Office remains
the dominant set of programs for word processing, spreadsheets, and
slide presentations. And because the company gave it away and
pressured computer manufacturers to include it in their machines,
Microsoft Internet Explorer has become the dominant browser. Based
on recent interviews, Gates and Ballmer are ready to resume
bullying tactics if the government lessens the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   One way to control Microsoft would be to monitor its every
action, but that would require enormous time and expertise. The
government is focusing on a neater solution: Breaking Microsoft
into two companies, with one controlling Windows and the other in
charge of Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have Office and Windows and those groups working
together, thinking about users, there would be no Windows as we
know it today . . . ,'' Gates said in opposition. It might have
made sense a decade ago, for the sake of standardization, to have
the same company develop the operating system and key applications.
Nowadays this amalgam is a drag on competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Linux operating system will not be a true competitor to
Windows unless Microsoft Office programs can run on it, yet Ballmer
has no plans to develop this capability. Control over Windows and
Office cements Microsoft's monopoly position.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will use its enormous financial power to oppose a
break-up if, as expected, the Justice Department proposes one
Friday. ``My life is devoted to building great software,'' Gates
said this week. He ought to continue this work in the competitive
environment that a break-up would promote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
