<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REBOUND-NORRIS-COLUMN     04-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REBOUND-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN WILL STOCKS REALLY CRUMBLE? AFTER THE DOLLAR
DOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The money managers panicked. The people bought.
</P>
<P>
   That is the real story of the wild month that ends Friday. After
the worst week in Nasdaq history ended two weeks ago, Wall Street
braced for a wave of selling that did not arrive. Instead, there
was a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened time and again in recent years. Just as market
fundamentalists take heart from the collapse of highflying stocks
and proclaim that value now matters, the fall ends. The bears are
vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   If that pattern is repeating _ as I believe it is _ the most
interesting question for investors is how they will be able to tell
if the next plunge, whenever it comes, is the real thing or just
another buying opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: Check the dollar and the economy. One or both of
them are likely to get into trouble before the stock market suffers
a prolonged downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because professional money managers really don't matter
much in the current environment. They can move money from stock to
stock, but they cannot stay out of stocks for very long. The
pressures to be fully invested are too great. The managers may fear
the Federal Reserve, which is more likely than ever to raise
interest rates after the report Thursday that consumer spending is
rising at the fastest rate since 1983. But their customers are not
worried. The Nasdaq market fell Thursday morning because
professional investors feared rising interest rates. But the
amateurs were buying, and soon prices were up nicely.
</P>
<P>
   American investors are certain that stocks are the best
long-term investment. That lesson, learned over many years, will
not soon be unlearned.
</P>
<P>
   A recession would operate on many investors as margin calls
operated on some during the Nasdaq swoon this month; it would force
selling by people who needed to raise cash. The selling would be
slow and prolonged, bringing a gradual market erosion rather than a
crash. The stock market would follow the economy down.
</P>
<P>
   The other group of investors worth watching is foreigners,
particularly Europeans. If they were not eager to invest in this
country, the huge trade deficits caused by all that consumer
spending would have led to a dollar crisis. If foreign investors
turned negative, or even if they invested less than they are now, a
falling dollar would provide a warning of stock weakness.
</P>
<P>
   That is not happening now. Instead, it is the euro that is weak,
despite Europe's strong current account surpluses. For a variety of
reasons, few want to invest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans worried about their own currency have bought American
stocks, thus pushing up our stock prices and supporting the dollar.
Someday, perhaps when European investments begin to look more
attractive _ or American ones less so _ the circle will reverse,
and selling American stocks will damage the dollar, which will
damage the stock market, and so on. The euro is likely to rally
markedly at some point, to well above the current level.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, those who argue that technology stocks still
reflect ridiculous optimism may be proved right. But most investors
have not been scared off even as some Internet wonders have
collapsed. The Nasdaq composite is down 17 percent for April, and
its volatility _ measured as the standard deviation of daily
percentage changes _ is the greatest in Nasdaq history, surpassing
October 1987. But the Dow Jones industrial average is off less than
1 percent for the month, and Nasdaq is higher than it was in
mid-December. Investor faith is still alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EURO-INTEREST-RATES-5     04-27 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-INTEREST-RATES-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN CENTRAL BANK RAISES INTEREST RATES, BUT EURO PLUNGES
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The European Central Bank raised interest
rates Thursday for the fourth time in six months but Europe's
common currency, the euro, once again defied its guardians and
plunged to another record low against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase, from 3.5 to 3.75 percent, would normally tend
to support the euro's value. But in a display of the gloom that now
envelops the new currency, the euro sank to less than 91 cents from
92.15 cents before closing in New York at 91.01 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro is now in uncharted waters, and you don't know how
far it will go down,'' said Gerhard Grebe, an economist at Bank
Julius Baer in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Since its debut at the start of 1999, when it was worth $1.17,
the euro's value against the dollar has slid about 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While it once seemed to represent an unthinkable decline in the
euro's value, parity with the dollar now looks to many traders like
an impossibly high target, at least for the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the decline of the euro was more of a political
embarrassment than an economic problem. Indeed, the weak euro has
provided a major boost to European exporters by making their
products cheap in terms of dollars and creating windfall currency
profits from sales in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But European officials have become increasingly concerned that
the euro's weakness will fuel inflation here by raising the prices
of imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's plight has even begun to alarm some of its most
ardent supporters. Norbert Walter, chief economist at Deutsche
Bank, has long contended that the new currency would be a powerful
challenger to the world dominance of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Walter argued that European central bankers
should intervene if the euro's value slips meaningfully below 90
cents. In an interview with the German newspaper Die Welt, Walter
went on to argue that European central bankers ought to sell off
their reserves of dollars, which now total about $250 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't they sell now?'' Walter said. ``It would
simultaneously make an impression on international speculators and
support the euro.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopted by 11 European countries at the start of 1999, the euro
is on its way toward creating a single European economy as big as
that of the United States. Though the countries will continue to
have their own national currencies until 2002, their monetary
policies are now locked together under the control of the European
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the euro has been anemic ever since its birth, and the
problem has become more acute in the last several weeks. The German
mark is worth about 46 U.S. cents, its lowest level in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank said its primary concern Thursday was
about inflation rather than exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   But inflation is closely linked to the weakness of the euro,
which has already started to drive up import prices.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists and currency strategists had been expecting
Thursday's action, and most believe that the central bank will
raise rates at least once more in the months ahead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Far more puzzling is why the euro continues to fall so sharply
in value.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth in the 11-nation euro zone is expected to reach
3.4 percent this year, its fastest pace in years, and employment is
climbing rapidly for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inflation is lower in Europe than in the United
States. Investment and employment are both accelerating, and Europe
has a big trade surplus while the United States has a mammoth trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the United States continues to grow faster. The United
States Commerce Department reported Thursday that the U.S. gross
domestic product increased at annual rate of 5.4 percent in the
first quarter. Beyond statistics, the mystique associated with U.S.
technology has made it a magnet for foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists had been forecasting that the euro would start
to climb by the second half of 1999. Then they predicted it would
appreciate in the first few months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Dannesboe, a currency strategist at the Dutch bank ABN
Amro, said part of the euro's most recent distress stems from the
grievously optimistic views of many international fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced last fall that the euro would recover after tumbling
to $1.06 from $1.17, fund managers started buying up euros and
selling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States and the dollar both defied expectations,
as U.S. growth accelerated rather than slowed, and direct
investment continued to pour into the United States from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the fourth quarter, international fund managers
were massively overweight on the euros,'' Dannesboe said. The
result, he continued, is that investors are looking for at any
momentary rise in the euro as a chance to sell their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties were compounded earlier this month, after the
Nasdaq market plunged as a result of fears about overpriced U.S.
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors viewed the turbulence in U.S. stocks as a new
reason for believing that European assets and the euro would become
a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not happen. When the euro barely budged against the
dollar and then the Nasdaq market bounced back, the pressure to
sell euros intensified further.
</P>
<P>
   The entire life of the euro has left economists and currency
traders bewildered. But Ralf Schneider, an economist at Dresdner
Bank, noted that the violent currency swings are hardly
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1980 and 1985, the dollar nearly doubled in value
against the German mark _ the currency that continues to be at the
heart of the euro. The mark plunged to $3.45 from about $1.70,
largely because the U.S. economy underwent a powerful growth spurt
between 1983 and 1985. By 1988, the dollar had slumped back to
about $1.70.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that growth differentials are very important,''
Schneider said. ``My argument is that the euro has done better than
the D-mark would have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-UNIVERSAL-TOUR-FEATUR     04-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-TOUR-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOUR KEEPS EVOLVING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the challenges folks in charge of revamping the tram tour
at Universal Studios Hollywood had was what to do about Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   The great white shark from the 1975 hit ``Jaws'' had been
``attacking'' an unfortunate wooden fisherman (and tour
participants) for more than 20 years. But now the studio tired of
trying to out-thrill ride major amusement parks had decided to go
back to what they knew best _ the art of movie making _ and an
ultra phony mechanical fish just didn't looked like something
anybody would consider an example of cinematic magic.
</P>
<P>
   Or did it? Suppose, with the use of newly installed high tech
video and DVD equipment, you could show people a scary scene from
``Jaws'' immediately after their encounter with the mechanical big
mouth? Before your eyes, the clunky reality of Bruce is transformed
into movie wizardry. The implied message: Look how we can turn
wires, plastic etc. into the spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shark in the movie wasn't any more sophisticated than the
one we have out on the tour,'' says John Murdy, creative director
for the tour, and the man primarily responsible for its revamping.
And we've got (``Jaws'' director) Steven Spielberg talking about
how it never worked. We've got outtakes of the shark
malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is how a great filmmaker was able to overcome it and
use it as a positive, using the camera as a shark and making the
audience afraid of something they don't get to see. We're tying
things back into movie-making.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Murdy and his team have taken a close
look at every aspect of the studio tour. They concluded that any
park can offer roller coasters, food and souvenir shops, but guest
surveys indicated that Universal was getting the most out of the
park's most marketable commodity. What other attraction, after all,
actually takes its visitors onto a working movie studio?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we've added theme park type gags and attractions
to the tour that didn't have a lot to do with movie making,'' said
Murdy. ``The overall job is to put the focus back on the movie
making experience and the movies we've made to make this our
marquee attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a ton of research into the Universal archives and the
installation of video monitors in trams giving tour guides access
to hundreds of DVD clips. Spielberg is a part of every tour. So are
director Ron Howard (``Apollo 13'') and actor Jason Alexander (of
``Seinfeld'' fame), all of whom had memorable experiences on the
lot. Even while waiting in line, guests can study the Universe of
Stars, colorful boards with built in video displays featuring movie
stars from all film genres (Tom Hanks, Goldie Hawn, Meryl Streep,
Robert De Niro) and highlighting the movies they've made for
Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Studio archivist Jan-Christopher Horak went over the original
scripted tour (last refined in the 1980s), corrected several
inaccuracies. He also interviewed Carla Laemmle _ the oldest living
relative of former studio founder Carl Laemmle _ about her
recollections of working on the lot. Carla Laemmle had appeared in
both the 1931 ``Dracula'' and in 1925 version ``The Phantom of the
Opera''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did some polling,'' said Horak. ``Even after going on the
tour, a lot of the people didn't who had gone to the park didn't
know that films were still being made here or that they had been
made for as long as they have.
</P>
<P>
   Now, anybody who leaves the tour with that kind of ignorance
hasn't been paying attention. As the tram heads down the hill from
the theme park to the studio lot, the first thing guests will see
are number of movie posters from Universal classics dating from the
silent era to the present.
</P>
<P>
   With such feature as Courthouse Square, Little Europe and New
York Street, the Universal lot itself remains as much a star of the
tourist attraction as the rides. Film clips on the tour will now
show guests how a street they are passing has been used in movies
from three different decades. Courthouse Square, for example, was
part of ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' the ``Back to the Future''
movies and will be seen once again doubling for Beverly Hills in
the upcoming film version of ``Charlie's Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   The lot was a veritable playing ground for legendary director
Alfred Hitchcock who, after 1955, filmed parts of many of his
classics there. The Bates Motel, from his 1960 classic ``Psycho,''
remains another tour landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Tour stops can change depending on what project either is
currently shooting or has recently concluded. Recent visitors will
get a peek at the town of Whoville constructed for Ron Howard's
upcoming holiday release ``Dr. Seuss' How The Grinch Stole
Christmas,'' starring Jim Carrey. Four times a year, video clips
will be updated to keep the coming attractions current. And one of
the tour's final clips will be a trailer for an upcoming Universal
movie for ``Grinch'' or ``The Nutty Professor II.''
</P>
<P>
   There are new attractions as well, most notably The Curse of the
Mummy's Tomb and a new demonstration of weather special effects.
Inspired by the 1999 summer blockbuster ``The Mummy,'' the curse
plunges visitors into the sacred temple of Hamunaptra (it's the
former site of the ice tunnel and later Dante's Peak on previous
tours) where a bunch of flesh devouring scarabs attack the tram.
The King Kong attraction, one of the tour's most popular, now takes
place inside a sound stage.
</P>
<P>
   New features mean new blood _ a new crop of Universal Studios
Tour Guides who must audition and turn themselves into walking
encyclopedias of Universal lore before they're ever permitted to
grab the microphone and plunge their guests into cinematic peril.
Tour administrators have hired 30 new guides while retraining the
existing corp of 150 guides in the new routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more complicated tour now,'' says Murdy, a tour
guide himself 12 years ago. ``In addition to the tour, they have to
work the DVD. They're their own stage manager. I don't think I
could give this tour now, and I wrote the damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
