<HEADLINE>
IN NYC _ TRUCKS, TRUCKS, AND MORE TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many of you have asked, sometimes in anger over their
very existence or simply out of befuddlement over their popularity,
when the big truck/SUV craze will die down. Doesn't everybody who
wants a high-riding big rig have one by now? Won't rising gasoline
prices send consumers looking for smaller vehicles and
manufacturers back to the ramps for new products?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in a New York minute: Faggedaboudit.
</P>
<P>
   At the 100th year of the New York International Auto Show,
trucks and SUVs were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup trucks are becoming SUV-like. Some SUVs are becoming more
carlike _ downright station wagony, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Zarella, executive vice president at General Motors, said
the message from customers is clear: ``Give us more trucks. Give us
more trucks. And keep 'em coming.''
</P>
<P>
   So GM will comply, and this year, for the first time, Zarella
said, the company will sell more trucks than cars. And they'll
equip them with ever more powerful, Vortec 6000 V8 engines. After
all, you wouldn't want some whining little power plant under the
hood as you motor along in your Chevrolet Silverado 3500 Big Dooley
Crew Cab would you?
</P>
<P>
   Also notable from GM was the announcement that its Denali XL
(used to be the GMC Suburban) will get full-time all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, which got left behind without a big truck when the
big-truck/SUV wave arose, announced that it, too, will begin
building big trucks. Its first V8 pickup will be here in 2003. And
once you've got the big-truck platform and the engine, four-door
pickup trucks and a line of big SUVs obviously will not be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   For proof of that, look no further than Toyota's presentation at
this year's show.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota made big news last year with its highly acclaimed Toyota
Tundra, the first non-American V8 truck. Today, they can't build
them fast enough. But they aren't stopping there.
</P>
<P>
   The Tacoma pickup will now be offered with four doors _ just
like the Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   And with the unveiling of two new SUV models here this week,
Toyota now will offer five SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that Don Esmond, group vice president and general
manager for Toyota Motor Sales, boasted at the presentation that
America now has a Big Four group of auto manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the SUV lineup that already includes the Land Cruiser
and 4Runner will be a redesigned RAV4, a big SUV called the Sequoia
(based on the Tundra platform), and a ground-up model called the
Highlander.
</P>
<P>
   The new RAV4 is taller and bigger than previous models, looking
much like the BMW and Mercedes SUVs. Toyota is aiming this car at
younger buyers, a market that the company acknowledges it left
behind in recent years. That's why on the non-SUV front, Toyota is
also pushing its new MR2 sports car, a new Celica, and the all-new
Echo.
</P>
<P>
   The Sequoia, introduced earlier in Detroit, is a luxurious SUV,
and with the Lexus-based V8 that powers the Tundra under the
Sequoia's hood, it will be a silky, powerful vehicle. The
Highlander will be more carlike _ for those who want good driving
in bad weather, who want to sit a bit higher, and who want the
expansiveness of an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood before Toyota's lineup of five SUVs, Esmond was
upfront about the conflicting mission of trying to build cleaner,
more environmentally friendly cars while at the same time meeting
customer demand.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``no argument about what customers are demanding,''
Esmond said, referring to the demand for trucks and SUVs. So while
building its SUV and truck fleet, he said, Toyota will also begin
selling its hybrid gasoline-electric Prius this summer at under
$20,000. For the anti-SUV crowd, this is a chance to bolster the
manufacture of a car that not only runs clean, but gets more than
50 miles per gallon and seats five. If some folks can demand trucks
and SUVs, it will be up to others to show demand for hybrid
vehicles such as the Prius and Honda's Insight.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the demand for bigger, for more powerful, for
taller, longer, roomier continues unabated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the American market, V8 power rules,'' Esmond summarized.
``It gets you into the big games.''
</P>
<P>
   Other auto show highlights:
</P>
<P>
   --Oldsmobile showed off a new Bravada, promising that this
6-cylinder SUV will perform like it's got a V8. Interestingly, its
platform will be shared with Honda Passport, Isuzu Rodeo, Chevrolet
Blazer, and the GMC Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   --More on SUVs: Audi got into the
is-it-an-SUV-or-is-it-a-station-wagon game with the Audi 2.7
Allroad Quattro, which looked very much like a Volvo Cross Country
set higher off the road and made taller and more muscular.
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of Subaru, they introduced a new engine, the H6
3.0, a horizontally opposed engine that will deliver 212
horsepower. Slap that in your Outback and you're ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   --And finally, as that guy Fitzgerald said, writing about that
other guy Gatsby, we seem to be borne back ceaselessly to the past.
So it was with great pleasure that I toured a small exhibit of cars
that had been introduced down the years at earlier New York shows.
Among my favorites: A 1903 Olds Doctor's Coupe with a single
cylinder engine, a 1916 Cadillac Town Car, a 1927 Pierce Arrow
Limousine, a 1930 Franklin Sport Runabout, a 1955 Ford Thunderbird,
a 1958 Dual Ghia ``400'' prototype with a record player installed,
a 1948 Chelvrolet Fleetmaster ``Woody'' Station Wagon, and finally,
from among all of them, the car I would take home with me, if I
could: a 1929 Stutz Vertical 8 Black Hawk Speedster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
