<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SOUL-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD FOR THE SOUL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  East Texas church serves up a heap of home cooking _ and a little
of the Word _ for its faithful customers 
 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Attn: La.) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ARTHUR, Texas _ The Soul Food Kitchen is not an eatery that
many people just happen to stumble across by accident _ unless, of
course, as proprietor Mirinda Jacko puts it, ``it's God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's on one of Port Arthur's main streets all right, and
there is a sign out by the street. It's just that most people
aren't used to looking for a cafe inside a church.
</P>
<P>
   A letter-sized handwritten sign on a side door of Christian
Faith Church leads the hungry into a hallway, around a corner and
into the dining room and its six long tables and 36 metal folding
chairs. Sometimes a customer's nose will lead him on the more
direct route from the parking lot in back of the church _ through
the back door right into Jacko's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tell them to come on in and make themselves at home,''
said Sister Jacko, as she's known around the church where she's
been a member for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely not McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, this isn't fast food,'' chuckled Jacko during a rare
occasion when she could sit down. ``This isn't restaurant food.
This is home cooking. It's just good old home cooking like folks
used to eat at home before they had all of this fast food. It's
good, healthy food. I don't make it with all that grease like you
find in restaurant food.''
</P>
<P>
   She will fix a hamburger, if a customer really wants one, and
there is a real menu. But most customers just order a $5 plate
lunch special from the sign above the table that holds six
different kinds of hot sauce, ketchup and other condiments.
</P>
<P>
   What's on the special varies every weekday. There might be
country ribs, meatloaf, stuffed bell peppers, turkey necks or the
hen wings that Jacko explains are ``bigger and tougher than fryer
wings, so I have to cook 'em more.''
</P>
<P>
   Side orders vary from black-eyed peas, red beans and pinto beans
to cole slaw and macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Every day the menu includes pig's feet and oxtails. ``We sell a
lot of oxtails,'' Jacko said. ``People sure do like those
oxtails.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxtails aren't something found on the menus of ordinary cafes,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had oxtails in a long, long time,'' said 77-year-old
Vickie Falcon. ``My grandmother used to make them. Of course she
cooked them the Spanish way with hominy.'' Falcon, a widow, lives
alone and said she doesn't much care to cook just for herself, and
it's hard to find a good place to get home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Later, gnawing on the bones, she allowed that her grandmother
would have approved of Jacko's oxtails. ``I'll be back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko said she starts out with a roux, similar to one used to
make gumbo, and boils the oxtails for a good long time to make them
tender. Pig's feet start out with a roux, too, ``but it's a lighter
roux, and I put vinegar in it. Those people, they just like to suck
on those pig's feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Justice of the Peace Thurman Bartie looked at
the list of daily specials and said, ``I want it all. Like my
grandmother used to say, I get big eyes sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacko, a 49-year-old grandmother, learned her country cooking
skills from her mother, grandmother and especially one great-aunt
while she was growing up in Port Arthur and Lafayette, La. ``My
father died when I was 11 years old and us kids had to grow up
fast,'' she said of herself and her five brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   She remembered cooking stewed rabbit and greens called pepper
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jacko and Pastor J. Barrington Minix decided that
opening the cafe would cure her problem of what to do with her
time, while at the same time serving as a ministerial outreach for
the church and perhaps help raise money for church projects.
</P>
<P>
   Tammie Davis, a waitress, is also the church secretary. ``It's
all God's work,'' she said. Paul Anderson, who also helps out, is
the church gardener.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko bought an entire commercial kitchen from a closed
smokehouse restaurant that included everything from pots and pans
to a six-burner stove with a deep fryer.
</P>
<P>
   A portable tape player is constantly playing gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes you feel good,'' Jacko said. ``We leave all that
fuss and worry of the world outside. People come in here and they
get some good food and they go away feeling good. See, the people
who come in here are people of the world and this might be the only
place they hear the Word, so we give them the Word.''
</P>
<P>
   She's thinking of installing a television to play sermons and
gospel music from church services. There won't be any soap operas
or talk shows on that television, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening in November, the place hasn't made much of a
profit, but Jacko said she feels good that it's at least paying for
itself. The 36 chairs aren't often full.
</P>
<P>
   But every day there are more and more people who find their way
through the side door and down the hall to the Soul Food Kitchen,
where the heady scent of home cooking mingles with gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes those who come can't afford a meal. Jacko recalled one
man with a car so rickety that he kept it running while he dashed
inside and asked if he could get a breakfast for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fed him and gave him $5 for gas,'' she said. ``He came in
here with a great big Bible and sat right there and prayed. You
know, you never will know when God might send you an angel.''
</P>
<P>
