<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-TOYS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toys 'R' Us to sell children's tools with Home Depot logos
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot and Toys ``R'' Us are reaching out to
budding do-it-yourselfers with a new line of tools for tots.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest toy chain has begun selling Home
Depot-branded tools and kits.
</P>
<P>
   Scaled down in size for half-pints, a line of real tools for
ages 8 and up are working models of what you'd find at a Home
Depot. Hammers, screwdrivers, pliers and wrenches are sold in sets
with miniature goggles and tool belts.
</P>
<P>
   Kids as young as 2 years old can fire up a whirring
``Eco-Ranger'' toy chainsaw or a mini-jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   All of the tools, real or toy replicas, are emblazoned with the
bright orange Home Depot logo. Prices range from $9.99 to $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a branding standpoint, this is a big deal,'' said Karen
Parham, supervisor of community affairs for Home Depot. ``This
certainly is a chance to build brand loyalty at an early age.''
Parham is overseeing the new program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Toys ``R'' Us deal, Atlanta-based Home Depot receives
a royalty from the toy sales. This is the first time another
retailer has sold a product with Home Depot's name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys `R' Us came to us with the idea as an extension of our
kid's workshops,'' said Suzanne Apple, Home Depot's vice president
of community affairs. About 3 million children have taken the
how-to classes in the past three years, Apple said.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us is considering holding a ``product demo'' night
every week, said David Konigsberg, store director of the Alpharetta
store near North Point Mall. The retailers are also talking about
creating a line of Home Depot wheelbarrows and lawnmowers, Parham
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Depot partnership is part of a new push by Paramus,
N.J.-based Toys ``R'' Us to boost profits and take back its ranking
as the No. 1 toy seller. Toys ``R'' Us lost that spot to Wal-Mart
Stores two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us recently struck licensing deals with OshKosh
B'Gosh, a children's clothing line, and Animal Planet, a cable
channel, to develop exclusive products.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Depot tool displays will be rolled out to 16 Toys ``R''
Us stores next month and should arrive in 170 U.S. stores by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Christmas, this stuff is going to be a big hit,'' said
Konigsberg. ``We see it as a great gift idea for grandparents and
uncles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
