<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-COSTS-0428-COX     04-27 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-COSTS-0428-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAXPAYER COST FOR ELIAN SAGA SURGES PAST $2 MILLION
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0428.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE, MIKE WILLIAMS and SUE SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Elian Gonzalez and his dad get reacquainted
courtesy of the private owner of a 25-room mansion on Maryland's
Eastern Shore, the bill to the American taxpayers for the saga of
the 6-year-old Cuban refugee is soaring well beyond $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Costs include overtime for local and county police in Florida,
expenses for 151 federal agents who executed the raid to snatch
Elian from the home of his Miami relatives and $2,900 an hour to
fly Elian to the Washington area aboard an eight-seat Sabreliner
jet.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary tally, Justice Department officials Thursday
estimated their agency's costs through last Monday had reached
$578,000, most of it paid by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The total so far does not include expenses at Andrews Air Force
Base, outside Washington, where Elian his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, were first reunited on April 22 and spent three nights
subsequently.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Marshals Service said Thursday that it paid for five
suites on the high-security Air Force base, one for the Gonzalez
family and the rest for for marshals in their security detail. The
cost was $36 a night per suite, said Drew Wade, a spokesman for the
Marshals Service.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, law enforcement costs are continuing to mount, now
that the Gonzalez family reunion has moved to the Wye River
conference center, site of the 1998 Middle East Peace talks. The
family is staying as the guests of owner Nina Houghton, who chairs
the Wye Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But round-the-clock security is provided by the U.S. government.
Marshals guard the pastoral setting by land, and a 41-foot U.S.
Coast Guard rescue boat patrols the shores, shooing away curiosity
seekers or anyone else who tries to come too close. The boat costs
roughly $2,000 a day to operate, a Coast Guard spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Luis Fernandez, a spokesman in the Cuban Interests
Section, said he had ``no idea'' what the Cuban government costs
have been in regard to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   In the final tally, however, the heaviest load will be carried
in Florida, where the City of Miami and Miami-Dade County have paid
for overtime for police officers stationed at the Little Havana
home of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, to deal with protests
during the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Miami Police Department said Thursday that
no updated totals were available. But as of April 8, the city had
spent more than $800,000, mostly for overtime for police officers.
</P>
<P>
   That amount is sure to skyrocket when the city adds the expense
of the large protests after heavily armed INS agents and U.S.
Marshals took Elian in the pre-dawn hours of April 22. All
uniformed officers were called out on 12-hour shifts for the
protests that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Miami-Dade County has estimated its overtime costs
at $1 million for the entire period, including the April 22
disturbances, said Rhonda Barnett, a spokeswoman for the county
government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two state agencies _ the Florida Highway Patrol and
the Florida Department of Law Enforcement _ spent a combined
$105,000 through early April, mostly for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Beach police spent more than $28,000 dealing with crowds
at the home of Barry University President Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin,
who hosted Elian's reunion with his grandmothers and a meeting
between the Miami relatives and Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Even Florida's toll booths took a hit. The state lost about
$55,000 in Miami-Dade County, where road tolls were lifted in early
January when protests paralyzed traffic following the initial
federal decision to send Elian back to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County, Md., will pick up the security tab for Juan
Miguel's stay at the suburban home of the top Cuban envoy in the
United States. Early costs were $50,000, according to the
Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, local communities seek reimbursement from the federal
government for some of their law enforcement costs. Washington,
D.C., for example, has asked for $5 million to cover police costs
for dealing with a weekend of protests against the International
Monetary Fund earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   (Julia Malone's e-mail address is: juliam(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Sue Schultz's email address is: sues(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' email address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
