<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-FED-NYT &LR;      04-27 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-FED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG GROWTH COULD LEAD THE FED TO RAISE RATES A HALF-POINT IN
MAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ECON-REPORT) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The reports Thursday that the economy is flirting
with inflation were probably not enough on their own to lock the
Federal Reserve into adopting a more aggressive course of interest
rate increases when it meets on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   But the robust pace of growth in the first quarter and the clear
warning signs of an acceleration in wage and price increases all
but guarantee that Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, and his
colleagues at the central bank will seriously consider raising
rates by half a percentage point rather than by the quarter-point
that investors and economists have been anticipating.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fighting a phantom _ the theoretical possibility of
a pickup in inflation _ the Fed can now point for the first time to
specific if early evidence that the economy is overheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic data make an overwhelming case for picking up the
pace of tightening,'' said James F. O'Sullivan, an economist at
J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Fed has tended not to change policy on the basis of
one or two economic reports. Greenspan did not mention the latest
indicators in a speech today on the rural economy. But he has long
preferred to change monetary policy in gradual, consistent steps
that are well telegraphed to the markets, a practice he has
followed faithfully over the last 10 months in raising rates five
times in quarter-point increments.
</P>
<P>
   Because Greenspan has given no public indication that he is
ready to raise rates in bigger steps, some analysts think the Fed
is unlikely to opt for a half-point increase in May. The Fed's
benchmark federal funds target rate stands at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some Fed officials have also emphasized in recent months that
small rate increases are the most prudent course at a time when
there are so many unresolved questions about how fast the economy
can grow without igniting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has expressed hope about improvements in productivity,
the crucial factor in determining the economy's noninflationary
speed limit. But he has also said that at some point even
productivity cannot offset upward pressure on wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a fog, you take small steps,'' said Bill
Cheney, an economist at John Hancock, the life insurance company.
``One could argue strongly for a course of sticking to
25-basis-point increases.'' (A basis point is one-hundredth of a
percentage point.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if Greenspan sticks to his gradualist approach, he will
confront pressure from other members of the central bank's policy-
setting Federal Open Market Committee, some of whom have been
pushing for half-point increases since February.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes of the Feb. 1-2 meeting, when the Fed raised rates
by a quarter-point, indicated that a few members even then were
pressing for an increase of 50 basis points ``in order to provide
greater assurance against a buildup of inflationary expectations
and inflation'' in subsequent months. Other members, the minutes
said, acknowledged that more aggressive action might be needed if
the economy continued to roar along, as it has.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes of the meeting on March 21, when the Fed voted for
another quarter-point increase, have not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many of the committee's 10 voting members
would favor a half-point increase. But they are almost certain to
include Jerry Jordan, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of
Cleveland, who is perhaps the most vociferous inflation hawk on the
Fed. They are likely also to include Laurence H. Meyer, a Fed
governor who has long warned that the current combination of 4.1
percent unemployment and strong growth cannot continue indefinitely
without creating a cycle of rising wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainties about the economy's capacity to grow without
inflation have led to a monetary policy course that has been
``somewhat more gradualist, in my view, somewhat less pre-emptive
than it otherwise might have been,'' Meyer said in a speech several
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer added, pointedly, that ``there are limits to monetary
policy's tolerance for above-trend growth and for further labor
market tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Before making its decision, the Fed will have several more sets
of economic data to consider, including a report on job creation
and unemployment next Friday and the report on the Consumer Price
Index, which will be released on the morning of the Fed meeting on
May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Another wild card for the central bank is the stock market. A
stabilization or rebound in the market in coming weeks could add to
pressure on the Fed to raise rates more aggressively. Should the
market turn down again and stay down, it could help dampen consumer
spending and overall demand, reducing inflation pressures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
