<P>
   The appeals court said it would put off any action on the
request by Elian's father to substitute him for Lazaro Gonzalez,
the boy's great-uncle in Miami, as the one who speaks for the
child.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the federal appeals court in Atlanta denied
a series of requests from the Miami relatives for visits with Elian
and rejected their request to appoint a guardian for the boy as the
legal maneuverings head toward a May 11 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The court action highlighted a day that began with U.S. Attorney
General Janet Reno giving an emotional defense of the raid that
removed the boy from his Miami relatives's home and reunited him
with his father, who arrived in the United States three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   And while the appeals court denied the Miami relatives request
to visit Elian, Reno suggested that perhaps the boy and his Miami
cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, could visit each other at some point
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that Marisleysis will be out of his life,''
the attorney general said at her regular weekly news conference,
her first since Saturday's dramatic pre-dawn seizure of Elian. ``I
mean, you could look at them and see a connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez has said she has become a surrogate mother
for Elian, whose mother died in the tragic attempt to flee Cuba
last November. She and 10 other people died when their boat
capsized. Elian survived in an inner tube for two days until
rescued by fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed by the government with the court in Atlanta, a
psychiatrist, Dr. Paulina Kernberg of Cornell University, said
Elian's feelings for Marisleysis Gonzalez are ``similar to the
romantic feelings of a school boy for his teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrist, who examined Elian for nearly three hours,
said the boy displays a ``sense of well-being and happiness with
his father,'' adding, ``Whenever he made eye contact with his
father, his face brightened.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court rejected the request from Marisleysis Gonzalez
and her father, Lazaro Gonzalez, for ``regular and reasonable
access'' to Elian until the court decides whether to reinstate a
claim of political asylum they filed on Elian's behalf during the
legal tug-of-war with the father over custody of the child.
</P>
<P>
   But the court, in a brief order, accepted the government's offer
to supply it with biweekly reports on the boy from a psychiatrist
and a social worker hired to monitor Elian.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court also continued its order barring Elian from
any site in this country that has diplomatic immunity. His presence
at such a site would put him out of the legal reach of the U.S.
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez's wife and their
6-month-old son are staying in a two-story Maryland farmhouse owned
by the Aspen Institute. It is adjacent to the Wye River estate that
was used for Middle East peace talks by the Clinton administration
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One of Elian's teachers and a 10-year-old cousin from Cuba
arrived in the United States Wednesday night to keep the boy
company through what could be a prolonged legal battle over the
political asylum application from his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Elian's schoolmates and four adult chaperones arrived in
the Washington area late Thursday afternoon and were expected to be
reunited with Elian later in the day. Cuban President Fidel Castro
gave them a personal farewell in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez has asked the State Department to grant
visas to an entourage of 25 Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who ordered the raid on Lazaro Gonzalez's home in the
Little Havana area of Miami, fought back tears at one point during
her news conference Thursday as she recalled what went through her
mind as she made her final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``How he (Elian) would feel suddenly being put in the arms of a
stranger _ what would he think, how frightened would he be? And I
kept thinking, I wish that I could see him when his daddy gets on
the plane,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was transported to the Washington area on a government
aircraft after U.S. marshals and federal immigration agents removed
him from Lazaro Gonzalez's home following the breakdown of
negotiations between the attorney general and the Miami relatives's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   She said Elian ``has had a lot of bad luck along the way,'' but
added, ``He's still resilient, he's still strong, he's still a
smiling little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate hearings have been scheduled for next week to air
congressional criticism that Reno authorized excessive force in the
raid to seize Elian, but the attorney general said Thursday that a
show of force was necessary after negotiations for a peaceful
transfer to the father began to falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the agents had to be in force,'' she said. ``Elian
was being held by this person, and there had to be a show of force,
not a use of force, to show that we were in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the negotiations with the Miami relatives, she said, ``It
wasn't going to get any better.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the pre-dawn hours of Saturday were ``the most
appropriate time with the least crowd'' for the raid. ``This
appeared to be the safest time possible to effect the transfer,''
she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   She denied that the agents who conducted the raid used abusive
language, as the Miami relatives's have contended since the raid on
their home.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the anger Cuban Americans feel toward her would
prevent her from returning to Miami, her home, when her term as
attorney general is over, Reno said, ``Won't be difficult at all.''
When asked to elaborate, she replied, ``What is there to talk
about? It's my home.''
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's email address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
