A9160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-AILING-HMO-BOS &LR;      04-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HOLDS OFF ON   ENDING HMO'S RECEIVERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It will be at least two weeks before the Supreme
Judicial Court decides whether to end the state's first HMO
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Justice Francis Spina heard arguments about the future
of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, which was forced into state
receivership Jan. 4, but ended the 90-minute hearing without
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The most vociferous objections to ending the receivership came
from the advocacy group Health Care For All, which argued there's
not enough evidence the HMO is fixing its troubled finances.
</P>
<P>
   The organization criticized Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly
for not releasing details of Harvard Pilgrim's turnaround plan and
2000 business plan and demanded more consumer protection measures
in the state's proposed rehabilitation order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if the success of this plan depends on Harvard
Pilgrim increasing premiums, selling off assets, or leaving certain
markets,'' said Laurie Martinelli, executive director of Health Law
Advocates, which represents the consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   J. David Leslie, special assistant attorney general, said
regulators are protecting conumers by requiring that Harvard
Pilgrim submit monthly business plans and financial statements. The
HMO will remain under administrative supervision.
</P>
<P>
   But Leslie said regulators do not want to make public business
documents that other HMOs keep secret, which would put Harvard
Pilgrim at a competitive disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   He said Harvard Pilgrim is raising premiums _ as are most health
plans in Massachusetts _ but that decisions about selling assets
and leaving markets will require regulators' approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is a success,'' he said. ``That's why there is no
one in this courtroom filing objections from the Massachusetts
Hospital Association'' or from the state's doctors' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie said the health plan has paid the $300 million it owed
hospitals when the receivership began. He said it is paying current
hospital claims, too, though he acknowledged an ongoing dispute
about whether the plans pay claims fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators amended the rehabilitation proposal Thursday to say
Harvard Pilgrim's outstanding debts, for which the receiver must
approve payment, do not include routine claims from hospitals and
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In several days, regulators will file with the court a
settlement agreement for the HMO to pay Rhode Island providers $10
million for outstanding claims. Objections must be filed within 10
days, which means that Spina cannot make a ruling for at least two
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-WORKPLACE-FATALITI     04-27 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WORKPLACE-FATALITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE WORKPLACE FATALITIES DOUBLE IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The number of Massachusetts workers who died on the job
more than doubled last year to 91, from 41 in 1998, the biggest
increase in fatalities since the state started collecting such data
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, ``Dying for Work in Massachusetts: The Loss of
Life and Limb,'' the Massachusetts AFL-CIO attributed the increase
in deaths to poor safety measures and inadequate training. It also
pointed to low fines for offending companies and repeat offenses
that send the message that state and federal agencies are falling
down on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``One death is too many, but 91 is inconceivable,'' Robert
Haynes, president of the 400,000-member union federation, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, an additional 1,000 employees died from
occupational diseases such as cancer, lung disease, or renal
disease. Another 50,000 employees suffered injuries including
amputations, contusions, burns, repetitive stress syndrome, and
electric shock.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such injuries, fines assessed by the US Occupational
Safety and Health Administration, a unit of the Labor Department,
were reduced in 10 of 16 settled cases to $10,000 or less. In four
of those cases, companies were fined less than $5,000. Overall, the
average fine paid by employers for workplace safety violations last
year was $17,883, down from $19,316 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lessin, health and safety coordinator for the
Massachusetts AFL-CIO, attributed the increase in fatalities to
accidents involving several workers, as well as an increase in
forced overtime, downsizing, and work-rule changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is being restructured in ways that hurt workers,'' she
said. ``Mandatory overtime, not having enough people at the job
site, reorganizing work duties without the proper safety training
are all factors that contributed to workplace injuries and
deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   The data, gleaned from federal and state records, showed that
several companies had been fined or cited repeatedly for safety
violations. One firm, Revoli Construction Co. of North Reading, has
been cited for 56 violations over the last 13 years. At least 30 of
the citations involved failure to ensure the safety of construction
workers in trenches.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1998 two workers were buried in dirt and debris
up to their waists when a trench caved in at a Revoli work site. A
fine of $218,000 was recommended by local OSHA officials.
</P>
<P>
   In January, OSHA proposed an $81,000 fine against the firm after
an inspection revealed construction workers were working in an
unprotected 7-foot trench.
</P>
<P>
   Shawqui Alsarabi, president of Revoli Construction, said the
company was inspected recently by the agency and, aside from a
minor problem, ``was found to be taking precautions regarding our
safety program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall that we had 56 violations,'' Alsarabi said.
``We have run into situations where there has been employee
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA is responsible for inspecting and monitoring safety
measures at private companies across the country. In Massachusetts,
166,986 workplaces come under the purview of 45 inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar in other states. Last year, the agency
employed 2,145 inspectors around the country to monitor seven
million workplaces. At its current staffing levels, it would take
the agency 107 years to inspect each workplace under its
jurisdiction only once, according to a report released this week by
the AFL-CIO's parent in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend, however, that the agency could expand its reach
by increasing fines or referring more cases to the US attorney's
office for criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   John Chavez, a spokesman for the Labor Department's regional
office in Boston, said OSHA sometimes refers cases for prosecution,
but there is no guarantee they will be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Francis X. Flaherty, chief of the Fair Labor and Business
Practices Division of the attorney general's office, noted that in
most cases jurisdiction for workplace safety violations in the
private sector lies with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   When fatalities occur, however, the state attorney general could
determine in an egregious case that an employer's conduct led to
criminal recklessness and, as a result, manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is an extremely high standard to reach,'' said
Flaherty. ``Most cases just don't rise to that level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
