<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-ARCHER-HNS &LR;      04-27 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ARCHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEALTH OFFICIAL AGREES TO SENSITIVITY TRAINING AFTER ETHNIC
REMARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Stands for BUSH-APPOINTEE)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Health Commissioner William R. ``Reyn''
Archer III, under fire even after apologizing for remarks about
minorities and teen pregnancy, has agreed to top-to-bottom
sensitivity training at his agency, Hispanic lawmakers said after
meeting with him Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who said he believes he still can work productively with
minority leaders, also agreed to report on the number of Hispanics
and African-Americans in top positions at the Health Department and
to work on budget priorities of importance to minority lawmakers,
according to two who people attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he came away from this meeting knowing that he has no
rope left. He has to deliver to the state,'' said Rep. Robert
Puente, a San Antonio Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   While a number of minority groups and some other leaders have
called for Archer to resign, Puente said, ``Resignation for me is
not really an issue any more. It's just, `Do a good job.'''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the meeting, Archer said he has no intention of
resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were very willing to listen to what I had to say,
and I think they were very generous as people, and I look forward
to working with them,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are issues that we have very much in common that we want
to see happen in Texas,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's troubles have spilled over into the campaign of Gov.
George W. Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   While Archer wasn't appointed by Bush, the governor approved his
selection by the Board of Health. Some have urged Bush to call for
Archer's resignation; Bush has declined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Among comments drawing criticism, Archer was quoted in a New
York Times story as saying Texas' high teen-age pregnancy rate is
due to Hispanics lacking ``the belief in your culture that getting
pregnant is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to go to a Hispanic community and say, `Well, we
need to get you into family planning,' they say, `No, I want to be
pregnant,''' he said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Archer also was criticized for being described in the same story
as saying he doubted that insurance coverage made much real
difference to health.
</P>
<P>
   The furor intensified after a recent Houston Chronicle story
saying Archer made similar comments about African-Americans two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The story quoted Archer as saying ``we need to figure out why it
is when blacks were more segregated and had less opportunity that
they did better on cultural measures than they do in that sense
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The story said Archer also commented that black people ``don't
buy'' such cultural and legal institutions as marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made errors in my statements, and I'm sorry I made those
errors. But my intention is to create a state which can be an
inclusive state for everybody,'' Archer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Puente and Rep. Henry Cuellar, a Democrat from Laredo, said the
lawmakers didn't direct Archer to use a particular entity or group
to conduct the sensitivity training. Some agencies do such programs
in-house, Cuellar said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawmakers said it was important that Archer himself
attend the program, not just those who work under him.
</P>
<P>
   One issue Archer has committed to work on is reducing the rate
of teen-age pregnancy, Cuellar said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Cuellar and Puente, the meeting was attended by Reps.
John Longoria and Ruth Jones McClendon, both Democrats from San
Antonio; Pete Gallego, a Democrat from Alpine; and Glen Maxey, a
Democrat from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bledsoe, state president of the NAACP, also attended, as
did aides to other lawmakers who belong to the Mexican-American
caucus in the state House.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar said the lawmakers offered Archer a piece of advice:
Keep away from theory and ``just stick to the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were hurt by Archer's comments, and they intend to
hold him to his commitments, Gallego said. But there also was some
sympathy for a fellow public official making ill-advised,
much-reported comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some anguish in the room today, but do we want him
to quit? I think everybody in public life at one point or another
says something really stupid, and something they regret,'' Gallego
said. ``And I'm lucky that I haven't had those mistakes brought out
on the front page of every newspaper in this state every day for a
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
