<HEADLINE>
SERIES BRINGS EXPOSURE FOR DIRT RACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mark Martin had an observation for Billy
Moyer when the two saw each other last week at a restaurant in
Batesville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows our sport, and he said he can't believe the kind of
money there is in dirt racing,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, like many NASCAR Winston Cup drivers, is also a race
fan. But the stars of Dirt Late Model racing, such as Moyer, are
relatively unknown to casual motorsports fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Hav-A-Tampa Dirt Late Model Series is picking up some speed
in its chase for exposure with its debut at the Texas Motor
Speedway Dirt Track tonight and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer and others have been successful for more than 20 years in
a sport mainly popular at small dirt bullrings in the Southeast and
the Midwest. They have made money in their sport, but they also
have been racing outside of the motorsports mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were so geared to the outlaw way of racing,'' said
Mike Swims, president of the United Dirt Track Racing Association,
the sanctioning body for the Hav-A-Tampa series. ``That outlaw
image is very attractive to the fans where it is rough and on the
ragged edge of all-out racing. But it is not conducive to the
growth of our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   There are close to 5,000 Dirt Late Models in the United States,
but Dirt Late Model racing did not have a national series for the
best drivers to compete for the most money until Hav-A-Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters believed if they paid enough money they would get
enough cars and enough stars to attract fans without a sanctioning
body. Big money shows often were scheduled on top of each other,
and it was not uncommon for each show to have more than 100
entrants, but they split up the best drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never really been an organization pushing to get
successful stars and a traveling show,'' Ohio resident Donnie Moran
said. ``I have done Dirt Late Model racing for so long I want to
see it get some recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hav-A-Tampa series has been compared to the Pennzoil World
of Outlaws, a sprint-car dirt series that started in 1978. The
Hav-A-Tampa series debuted in 1990, and it took a while to convince
independent-minded Late Model drivers that following a series was
the best way to make a living. The efforts have paid off for the
drivers and the series.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, who is 15th in the Hav-A-Tampa points standings, has
earned $14,000 in 10 races this year. Rick Eckert, the points
leader, has made $43,000 this season with four victories.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports, Inc. is helping to make sure those top
drivers stay on the series. Three SMI tracks will be the host to
four events this season. Along with this weekend's event at the TMS
Dirt Track, the series will run two races at the Lowe's Motor
Speedway dirt track and at Bristol Motor Speedway. An event is also
scheduled at Houston Raceway Park in Baytown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tickled to see that people as high up as \RSMI chairman\S
Bruton \RSmith\S are getting into our kind of racing,'' Moyer said.
``It's important for our sport. Hav-A-Tampa is getting our purses
better and better each year. But we've got to get us some TV
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hav-A-Tampa television schedule with the Speedvision cable
network has been expanded, but races are still broadcast on a
tape-delay basis several weeks after a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the right people have not got a hold of the
sport,'' said Wendall Wallace, of Batesville, Ark., who finished
second in last year's Hav-A-Tampa points standings. ``Hav-A-Tampa
brought themselves up above everybody else, and it is the toughest
series out there. The best Late Model drivers are on that
circuit.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
