<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLOSERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
300 SAVES IMPRESSIVE, BUT NOT A TICKET TO THE HALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Cal Ripken achieved a major career milestone
a couple of weeks ago when he became the 23rd player since 1900 to
collect his 3,000th major-league hit. If his incredible consecutive
games streak wasn't enough, the liner up the middle all but
guaranteed the Baltimore Orioles' legend admission in the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland is on the verge of achieving a career milestone
of his own. The Rangers' reliever needs two saves to become the
12th player in major-league history with 300.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Wetteland, though, will only get into the Hall
of Fame if he buys a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball people agree that a quality closer, someone who
consistently can come in and preserve a slim lead in the ninth
inning, is an important ingredient for a successful team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about a save is they're all tough outings,'' Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin said. ``There are not many cheap
saves.''
</P>
<P>
   But while closing is an important piece of the modern game, it's
too modern to determine the closers' place in history. Saves didn't
become an official statistic until 1969, and the evolution of the
one-inning, only-with-a-lead reliever has occurred only in the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, it's too soon to say if 300 saves should be viewed
in the same light as 3,000 hits, 300 victories or 500 home runs,
the traditional statistical benchmarks for Hall of Fame inductions.
</P>
<P>
   The man who should become the next closer to reach 300 doesn't
think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that 300 is not going to be a benchmark,'' Wetteland
said. ``I'm talking in 20 years from now or so. There are guys now
with just incredible stuff, and guys are taking care of themselves
much better than before. I think in the future you're going to find
closers that get to 300 in no time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame voters apparently agree.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt Wilhelm and Rollie Fingers, who pre-date the
one-inning-closer era, are the only pitchers in baseball's shrine
who pitched the majority of their games in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Fingers is sixth on the career list of saves with 341. Wilhelm
pitched just four of his 21 seasons after the advent of the save
rule, but researchers going over records from past games have found
save totals for every reliever. He's credited with 227.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the players ahead of Fingers on the career list _ John
Franco, who's second with 416 and Randy Myers, who's fifth with 347
_ are active. Two more _ Lee Smith, the leader with 478, and Dennis
Eckersley, who's third with 390 _ haven't been retired long enough
to be eligible for the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth, Jeff Reardon, was on the ballot for the first time
last year. He won't be next year. Despite being fourth with 367
saves, he received only 24 votes, less than the required 5 percent
to remain on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Sutter and Rich ``Goose'' Gossage, two other relievers
considered among the best ever, did receive significant numbers of
votes. But Sutter with 192 and Gossage with 166 were well short of
the 375 needed to be inducted.
</P>
<P>
   That only 11 people have achieved the 300-save milestone hasn't
swayed the voters. Then again it doesn't impress Wetteland, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of a very shallow pool,'' Wetteland said. ``You talk
about people who have hit 400 homers, like Raffy \RRafael
Palmeiro\S is going to, and that's out of thousands of people over
the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not 300 saves is worthy of enshrinement in the Hall
of Fame, it's still considered a remarkable achievement by those
who know the mixture of physical and mental ability it takes to be
a big-league closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say you've only got to get three outs, but they're
pressure-packed outs every time out there,'' said Derek Lowe, who
is in his first season as the Boston Red Sox closer. ``Three
hundred is a milestone that a lot of closers want to get to. For me
to think about a number like that, I've got to do this for 10 years
or something like that. That's doing a very good job for a very
long time. You've got to tip your hat to guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland said the current group of talented young closers will
push the benchmark well beyond 300.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the likes of Ugueth Urbina, Matt Mantei, Billy
Wagner, Armando Benitez, Billy Koch, John Rocker and Lowe, who are
all under age 28, have the ability. But the past is littered with
closers with talent who weren't able to do it year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wohlers saved 72 games for the Braves in 1997-98, but
suddenly couldn't throw a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Rojas replaced Wetteland as the Montreal Expos' closer in
1995, and saved 66 games in two seasons. But he couldn't handle the
mental demands of the role, and lost his job. This week, he signed
a minor-league contract with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only his physical ability, the closer has a mental
strength to his game, too,'' Melvin said. ``If they blow it,
they've got to be able to handle it. Can they come back? Do they
walk out of the bullpen the next time and charge to the mound
because they want the ball again? There's no safety net for the
closer. Some guys can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes 300 saves a major achievement, even if it doesn't
punch a ticket to the Hall of Fame.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
