<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     04-27 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Go right ahead, puckheads. Rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   Continue to celebrate the Stars' good fortune. It's ``only'' San
Jose, heh, heh, heh. And don't try to hide your grin over how that
other Western Conference rumble is also an added blessing from the
hockey gods.
</P>
<P>
   Teeth and snot will be flying in a renewal of the Red
Wings-Avalanche hate-fest, which means the survivor will be
physically and mentally exhausted for the final-four round of the
Stanley Cup marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's only San Jose, thanks to Dr. Henry J. Heimlich
being unable to make a house call in St. Louis. Those choking Blues
gifted the Stars with excellent postseason field position after six
months of local fretting that Roman Turek had been the gift Bob
Gainey would forever regret. See what happens when we doubt Gainey?
</P>
<P>
   But as local glee runneth over, it might be best to pause for
one quick second to consider this echo:
</P>
<P>
   It's ``only'' the Stars. That's exactly what San Jose is
thinking. The glee is mutual. Come riding high out of St. Louis
after finalizing the first-round shocker against the top-seeded
Blues, and the Sharks had to conceal a few chuckles of their own
that Dallas was the next destination.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was only two weeks ago when the Sharks were all
mouth and teeth about wanting this exact matchup, except in the
first round. Only an el foldo by San Jose in the regular-season
finale prevented that, but things do have a way of working out.
</P>
<P>
   And while the local thought process is suddenly centered on,
``it's only San Jose,'' this is a complete reversal from two weeks
ago. A chorus of concern was heard then about having to open the
playoffs against a Sharks club that had spanked Dallas butts in
four of six regular-season games. Speaking of a blessing, that's
what stumbling into Edmonton in the first round was supposed to be.
As it turned out, it was a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose easy? Starting with Game 1 tonight at Reunion
Arena, there will be nothing easy. Of the four series remaining in
the NHL, this one will lead the league in three categories: (1)
Nasty. (2) Nasty. (3) Nasty. And you can also throw in ugly. As
high-profile as Red Wings-Avalanche will be, and should be, that
series is patty-cake compared to this one.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose stands alone as the cheap-shot kings of the NHL, led,
of course, by the pig of pigs, bryan marchment, a lower-case evil.
marchment is a small man in a large body who has a strange fetish
for other guy's knees.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, you can take the above paragraph,
substitute ``Stars'' for ``San Jose,'' and ``Derian Hatcher'' for
``bryan marchment'' and that's exactly the way the Sharks feel
about you-know-who. Except our man Derian rearranges jaws instead
of knees.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Sharks didn't skate their way to a first-round
shocker. They put the kill, not the skill, on St. Louis,
intimidating the Blues' forwards with muscle and mayhem. When the
Blues got around to responding, it was usually at the wrong time.
St. Louis was repeatedly suckered into bad penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, since it worked so well, you can imagine the feeding
frenzy San Jose will display tonight. Except...
</P>
<P>
   Rosterwise, the Stars are better-suited for this style of
confrontation than at any time since becoming a Stanley Cup threat.
Plus, there couldn't have been a better first-round opponent than
the testy Oilers in preparing for what awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Back to general manager Gainey, who has jumped off the hook on
the Turek trade, and now appears to have been one jump ahead with
his retooling of the team since October.
</P>
<P>
   Remember ``younger, faster, cheaper?'' Back in October, that was
Gainey's answer to Stanley Cup glory. That was how the Stars had
been restructured. But as the season opened, and Gainey watched a
listless effort night after night, he suddenly ditched the new
blueprint. New veterans started to show up, along with rookie
Brenden Morrow. And so did muscle and meanness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger, faster, cheaper'' became ``older, tougher,'' and for
the most part, ``more expensive.'' For example, consider this swap
of roster bodies: Scott Thornton for Juha Lind, Brenden Morrow for
Pavel Patera and Dave Manson for Kevin Dean. Those three changes
alone were made months ago for the sole purpose of handling
down-and-dirty San Jose in the second round of the playoffs. OK, so
that's a lie. There was no such plan. But it did work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are indeed fortunate,'' said forward Mike Keane, ``to have
an owner \RTom Hicks\S who allows his hockey people to add players,
regardless of cost. But that's only half of it. Adding people won't
work if the fit isn't there, teamwise, and if the chemistry isn't
right. New York \Rthe Rangers\S is a prime example of that. But the
changes made here, they have worked in all areas. The fit was
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   And certainly perfect for the hockey-in-combat-boots that starts
tonight.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
