<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-BRITAIN-NYT &LR;      04-27 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TIES MONEY FOR ZIMBABWE TO THE END OF LAND SEIZURES
</HEADLINE>
  By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Eight hours of tense negotiations on Zimbabwe's
deepening political crisis ended in impasse Thursday night after
Britain refused to provide extra money for land resettlement until
government-backed squatters end their occupation of hundreds of
white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's foreign secretary, Robin Cook, said he delivered the
message in talks with a delegation of three Zimbabwean ministers
and made clear that Britain would ``refuse to take any further
steps until the next step is taken, and that is for the occupations
to come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is now in their court,'' he said of the Zimbabwean
negotiators, led by John Nkomo, the minister of local government.
</P>
<P>
   The Zimbabwean negotiators offered no immediate public comment
on the farm occupations that have heralded a wave of political
violence against adversaries of President Robert Mugabe in advance
of elections scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
   Violence associated with the farm occupations and a campaign of
political intimidation by Mugabe's supporters have claimed 14 lives
in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has spilled into and beyond Zimbabwe's already
battered economy, with tobacco farmers, who earn one-third of
Zimbabwe's foreign exchange, withholding crops from the annual
auctions while neighboring countries like Botswana and South Africa
say they are becoming increasingly concerned about the impact on
the entire region.
</P>
<P>
   The South African currency, the rand, fell Thursday to its
lowest-ever level against the dollar and some experts blamed the
crisis in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   British officials said the Zimbabwean negotiators Thursday
wanted Britain to release some $56 million for land resettlement
without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
   As the former colonial power, Britain acknowledges a moral
obligation to help finance land redistribution in a country where
some 4,500 white farmers own the bulk of the fertile land while
hundreds of thousands of black peasants farm meager plots. Cook
said Britain was prepared to help pay for land reform and seek
further international aid for Zimbabwe. But, he said, ``I made it
clear we could not take any of these steps against a background of
occupations and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The farm occupations have been led by Chenjerai Hunzvi, head of
an organization representing veterans of Zimbabwe's seven-year
guerrilla war against white minority rule. ``Our stance on land has
not changed,'' he said Thursday in Harare, Zimbabwe's capital.
``When we are ready to move we will let you know.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Cook said in London that he had a ``clear
impression'' that the government negotiators in Thursday's talks
wanted to see an end to the farm occupations.
</P>
<P>
   Nkomo, the leader of the Zimbabwean team, sought to avoid the
impression that the negotiations had broken down altogether. ``We
have broken the ice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a colonial past dating to 1890, when white settlers
first pushed north of the Limpopo River from South Africa to seize
land in what became Rhodesia, Britain has a tense and ambiguous
relationship with Mugabe's government.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his 20 unbroken years in office, during which he has
been frequently accused of handing over expropriated white-owned
land to cronies rather than to poor peasants, Mugabe both holds
Britain responsible for his country's land problems and resents
British interference in Zimbabwe's affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
