<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COMMITTED-MOVIE-REVIE     04-27 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMITTED-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COMMITTED': LACKING THE COURAGE OF ITS CONVICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the minds of the editors of Esquire, who recently put her on
the cover of their magazine clad only in a pink towel and a quart
of eyeliner, Heather Graham is somebody the average American male
would do anything to get close to. In ``Committed,'' Miramax's
latest smiley, air-headed romantic comedy, Luke Wilson plays an
average American male who can't get far enough away. Not from the
lovely Graham herself, of course, but from Joline, the disturbingly
thin, strawberry-blond avatar of perkiness and pluck she portrays.
</P>
<P>
   And well he might. After fewer than 600 days of marriage to
Joline, all of which take place off-screen, Wilson's Carl decamps
for parts unknown, leaving a terse, vague note on the counter of
their New York loft. His stated reason for leaving is a
professional crisis. He's an aspiring photojournalist who has been
relegated to taking photographs of cheesecake: the high-cholesterol
dessert kind, not the towel-draped starlet kind. But it seems more
likely that Joline's monomaniacal devotion to her own goodness, in
particular her endlessly reiterated belief in the sanctity of her
marriage vows, drove him out into the desert in search of a little
peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Which, as it happens, he neither deserves nor gets. He doesn't
deserve such a loyal wife, either, which is clear long before he
opens his mouth, two-thirds of the way through the movie.
Indomitable and literal-minded, she tracks him to El Paso, Texas,
in a rented car, which she parks outside his blue trailerlike home.
Oddly enough, he never notices, but his neighbor (Goran Visnjic), a
suave sculptor with continental manners and a sexy European accent,
is quickly smitten with her. Since this is a romantic comedy, you
know, more or less, where it's all heading.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Committed'' reaches its generic destination by a
circuitous, unusual route, in which intriguing possibilities are
glimpsed like scenery through a car window. There is, for example,
an inkling of real satire in the film's premise, which is that in
today's casual sexual landscape marital fidelity is an inexplicable
anomaly. Joline's brother Jay (Casey Affleck), for instance,
happily lives in curious menage with a lesbian couple, one of whom
is also divorced. And Carl, once in El Paso, takes up with a
waitress named Carmen (Patricia Velasquez), who denies that the
jealous truck driver stalking her is her ex-boyfriend because she
slept with him only seven or eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck and Graham have an interesting, almost inappropriate
brother-sister chemistry (another interesting possibility the film
raises but declines to pursue), but they spend most of the movie
sitting around waiting for instructions. Lisa Kreuger, who wrote
and directed, relies heavily on voice-over narration and on comic
situations that take forever to establish and then never really pay
off. She and her cast seem uncertain about what the tone of the
exercise should be, and the result lacks both the heat of romantic
longing and the spark of comic invention.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``Committed'' lacks the courage of its convictions.
Intending to affirm the values of permanence and
stick-to-itiveness, it instead presents a world without emotional
consequences, in which relationships are frictionless, frivolous
and easily discarded. The point is not that a sense of human
complexity and risk would have made this movie more serious, but
that without the feeling that something is at stake, it fails to be
funny. Without the danger of real tears, there's no real laughter.
Comedy, like marriage, takes more work than this.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COMMITTED'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Lisa Krueger; director of photography,
Tom Krueger; edited by Curtiss Clayton and Colleen Sharp; music by
Calexico; production designer, Sharon Lomofsky; produced by Dean
Silvers and Marlen Hecht; released by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Heather Graham (Joline), Casey Affleck (Jay), Luke Wilson
(Carl), Goran Visnjic (Neil), Alfonso Arau (Grampy) and Patricia
Velasquez (Carmen). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes. ``Committed'' is rated R (under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes some
strong language and decorous references to complicated sexual
situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
