<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SWEEPS28-COX     04-27 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cosby bowing out tonight
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the first weekend of May sweeps, which means great big
heapin' slabs of entertainment served up piping hot. Or not so hot,
in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cosby'' (8 p.m. on CBS) _ There's sadly little fanfare for
the end of Bill Cosby's CBS series, but then there was sadly little
attention paid to it during its four years. Never anywhere near as
huge as his 1980s NBC series, ``Cosby'' was just-good-enough TV.
</P>
<P>
   For the finale tonight, Erica and Darien are worried about their
marriage, so ol' Hilton (the Cos) offers them his wisdom on how to
keep love alive in a marriage. Sounds like time to settle in for
some serious ruminating.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nelson Rockefeller: Passionate Millionaire'' (8 p.m. on A&AMP;E)
_ Interesting title for this episode of ``Biography.'' Perhaps it
refers to his love for art or politics, rather than the way he
died.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pajama Party'' (10 p.m. on Oxygen) _ Megan Mullaly (she's
wicked Karen on ``Will and Grace'') drops in; we can see how good
she is without her writers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``To Die For'' (5 p.m. on USA) _ Nicole Kidman is a local TV
news reporter who'll do anything to get ahead. Her station doesn't
know whether to fire her or make her a five-part series in sweeps:
``Did this ruthless redhead sexually manipulate an underage boy
into killing her husband? We'll tell you at 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Simpsons'' (8 p.m. on Fox) _ Homer discovers college
spring break in Florida. With guest voices Kid Rock and Charlie
Rose (those two go everywhere together).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Take Me Home: The John Denver Story'' (9 p.m. on CBS) _ Chad
Lowe (Mr. Hillary Swank) thanks God he's a country boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Solomon'' (9 p.m. on Pax, concluding 8 p.m. Monday) _ The
team that did all those biblical epics for Turner a few years back
now has one on the Pax Network, with Ben Cross as Solomon, Max Von
Sydow as his father, King David, and Vivica A. Fox as the Queen of
Sheba.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Arabian Nights'' (9 p.m. on ABC, concluding 9 p.m. Monday) _
Another fantasy and special-effects extravaganza from Robert Halmi,
who will soon have filmed everything ever written. Sometimes this
stuff just falls apart (``Noah's Ark''), but sometimes it dazzles,
and ``Nights'' has enough sparkle to warrant a look.
</P>
<P>
   In some vaguely long-ago Middle East (the original ``1,001
Nights'' stories date from the 10th century), beautiful
Scheherazade (Mili Avital) tells a never-ending series of stories
to her semicrazed new husband (Dougray Scott), a sultan who has
vowed to kill her. To keep him interested in her, she spins the
tales of Ali Baba (Rufus Sewell), Aladdin (Jason Scott Lee, with
John Leguizamo as the Genie) and others. There's belly dancing,
flying carpets, slapstick, magic, spitting camels and lots of cool
effects. The frame story and the stories themselves are smartly
interwoven.
</P>
<P>
   Although these fables have been retold for children in other
forms (Disney's ``Aladdin,'' for example), this version is
moderately sexy and occasionally violent. It has a touch of magic,
but it's a mature magic.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The X-Files'' (9 p.m. Sunday on Fox)
</P>
<P>
   David Duchovny wrote and directed this house-of-mirrors episode
that's aimed at fans who like inside jokes. In a
movie-within-a-TV-show feature film, Garry Shandling plays Mulder
and Tea Leoni plays Scully. The cognoscenti know that Leoni is
married to Duchovny in real life, and Duchovny did a couple of
memorable guest shots as himself on Shandling's ``Larry Sanders
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Mulder/Shandling and Scully/Leoni end up making
out (in a coffin), prompting Scully to utter the line, ``Is that a
flashlight in your pocket, Mulder, or are you just ... ?'' There's
also a little homage to old Doris Day/Rock Hudson movies, with a
split-screened Mulder and Scully (the ``real'' Mulder and Scully _
this gets a bit goofy) talking on the phone from respective bubble
baths.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the case they're trying to solve in the middle
of all this, a whimsical little muddle involving Jesus, ``Plan 9
From Outer Space,''
</P>
<P>
   ``I Am the Walrus'' and dancing zombies. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Worst Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The '70s'' (9 p.m. Sunday on NBC, concluding 9 p.m. Monday)
</P>
<P>
   That much-maligned decade is now a deserves-to-be-maligned
two-part movie that's as shallow as a smiley-face button and as
obvious as Richard Nixon's guilt (when they do the montage of
feminism news clips, for example, they play ``I Am Woman'').
</P>
<P>
   Four friends survive the National Guard at Kent State in 1970,
then go their separate, desperately cliched ways. Byron (Brad Pitt
look-alike Brad Rowe) is an obnoxous twit who works for Nixon and
gets caught up in Watergate. His sister Christie (Amy Smart, who's
Ruby on ``Felicity'') is a talentless blonde who becomes a fashion
model, then moves to California to mess with drugs, self-awareness
and a cult. Eileen (Vinessa Shaw, ``Eyes Wide Shut'') is a good
girl who works as a secretary and ends up suing her boss for sexual
discrimination. And Dexter (Guy Torry) gets caught up in Black
Power, then black entrepreneurship. There's more real truth in one
episode of Fox's ``That '70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s'' frantically tries to cram in everything _
streakers, pet rocks, Jimmy Carter, feminism, jogging, Mary Tyler
Moore, blaxploitation films, cocaine, and on and on _ so that
nothing is developed. And it can't even get its time line right:
``I'm OK, You're OK'' is called a ``new book'' in 1976, about seven
years too late.
</P>
<P>
   Not to give away the ending, but Ronald Reagan gets elected and
the '70s end. And none too soon, in this telling.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
