   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-US (Washington) _ A federal appeals court denies a request
by relatives of Elian Gonzalez for visits with him or for an
independent guardian. The court instead accepts the government's
offer of regular reports from a psychiatrist and a social worker.
By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno defends
the ``show of force'' to seize Elian Gonzalez, saying the
possibility of resistance from the boy's relatives and their
supporters in Miami made it necessary for her to end talks and
order the armed raid to take custody of the boy. By MARK HELM.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-MARRIAGE (Washington) _ The Senate turns back another
effort to force a vote on a bill to ease the tax burden on married
couples, but Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison and other sponsors of
the measure vow to bring it up again and again. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-VIEQUES (Washington) _ Defense officials say the Navy plans
to shell the target range on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques
with non-explosive munitions fired from surface ships as soon as
encamped demonstrators are arrested and removed. A Justice
Department-led task force, including 1,200 Marines, is moving into
position to carry out the raid at any time. By STEWART M. POWELL.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DOW-SCIENCE (Washington) _ The Dow Chemical Co. announces that
it will help fund a National Science Foundation program to bring
famous scientists to middle schools nationwide and to alert
Congress about science issues. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-McCAIN (Austin, Texas) _ Although neither side would
confirm it, an Internet news service reports that Sen. John McCain
has called off a much-touted meeting with Republican primary rival
George W. Bush. A McCain spokesman acknowledges that the meeting is
``tenuous,'' while Bush officials say only that they are still
hopeful that the gathering will take place. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARREST-INTERNET (Undated) _ An unemployed San Antonio man, 31,
is arrested in connection with the killing of a Texas A&AMP;M student
he apparently met and lured to a meeting via the Internet.
Officials apparently traced the Internet address of the mysterious
``Kelly,'' leading them to the suspect. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-SOUL-FOOD (Port Arthur, Texas) _ The Christian Faith
Church in Port Arthur serves soul food at breakfast and lunch every
weekday, providing a soulful place for a bite to eat and bringing
in money that can be spent on higher purposes. By RICHARD STEWART.
(Already filed. Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBIN-OBIT (San Antonio) _ Robert Tobin, a nationally prominent
patron of the arts and renowned art collector, dies at North East
Baptist Hospital of complications of cancer and respiratory
failure. He was 66. A generous benefactor of the Metropolitan Opera
and Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Santa Fe Opera, Tobin
also was a major contributor to the McNay Art Museum in San
Antonio. By CARMINA DANINI and NICOLE FOY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
