<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, April 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cool, unsettled weather will linger from the northern
Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic coast as a series of jet-stream
disturbances moves overhead. The strongest disturbance will be
surrounded by showers and some strong thunderstorms from the
eastern Tennessee Valley to the Southeast coast. Some storms,
particularly from northern Florida to the eastern Carolinas, will
have strong winds and large hail. The southern Middle Atlantic
states will have periods of rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will have some sunshine, but cold air aloft will
promote thickening clouds and scattered showers by afternoon,
especially over the hilly terrain. Thundershowers will occur near a
weak front in the western Great Lakes. A few potent thunderstorms
will form in West Texas and along the eastern slopes of the
southern Rockies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SHUTTLE SCRUB
</P>
<P>
   After two delays caused by wind in Florida, Wednesday's
scrubbing of the shuttle launching came from rain and wind at three
emergency landing cites in Spain and Morocco. These cites are south
of the typical path of most transient inclement systems that
frequent the middle latitudes. But a ``high amplitude'' upper-wind
pattern, which has extreme poleward swings of warm air and dramatic
equatorward bulges of cold air, has dominated North America and the
Atlantic. On Wednesday, an inclement cold pool aloft bulged far
south from Europe, forcing cancellation of the shuttle launching.
</P>
</TEXT>
