<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE AGAIN REJECTS MOVE TO FORCE VOTE ON MARRIAGE TAX PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate turned back another attempt Thursday to
force a vote on a marriage tax penalty relief bill, but Texas Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison and other sponsors of the measure vowed to
bring it up again.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-44 vote marked the second time in two weeks that
Hutchison and other Republicans had failed to muster the 60 votes
needed to bring the legislation up for final consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would provide $248 billion in tax cuts for
married couples and other taxpayers, is opposed by a solid block of
Democrats. They favor a smaller $150 billion measure that would
eliminate tax code provisions penalizing married couples but would
not provide breaks for other taxpayers who would benefit under the
GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that the Senate has been blocked from voting
for marriage penalty tax relief,'' Hutchison said, criticizing the
Democratic filibuster against her bill. ``This is really a needed
tax correction more than a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said her bill is aimed at correcting the provision in
the tax code that gives single taxpayers a $4,400 standard
deduction, but provides only a $7,350 deduction for couples filing
jointly. Her bill would raise the deduction for married couples
filing jointly to $8,800, providing them with the same deduction
they would get if they filed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Her bill would affect an estimated 21 million Americans. But
Democrats claim that their measure, though smaller in scope, would
provide relief for more married taxpayers because it would
eliminate dozens of other provisions _ in addition to increasing
the standard deduction _ that force couples to pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
