<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WAR-WIDOWS28-COX     04-27 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-WIDOWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Web memorial lets widows share pain
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 8:10 a.m. on a warm spring day when an Army captain
knocked softly on her front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and told me my husband had been killed in action,''
Atlantan Mattie Brown remembers. ``It seemed so unreal. I just
couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 31 years ago, during the height of the Vietnam War.
Brown, 54, still sees her late husband, Sgt. Preston Tribble Jr.,
in her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young,'' Brown says. ``Forever 22.''
</P>
<P>
   War widows, she says, have flashbacks, too, just like combat
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times,'' Brown says, ``when I think I see him, in
our son and daughter, and in other young people.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lucy Freeland, 59, of Fayetteville, the same thing happens
every time she sees a mailman. A glimpse of tall trees with high,
thick branches still evokes painful 55-year-old memories for Mary
Alice Giles, 84, of Avondale Estates.
</P>
<P>
   All three suffer the trauma of having lost a spouse to war. And
all three have posted remembrances of their dead husbands on a new
Web site, warwidows.org, the Widows of War Living Memorial, which
is being launched today to mark this weekend's 25th anniversary of
the end of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Call it group therapy for the high-tech age, the latest of many
Web sites that tap into people's need, amid a sometimes isolating
culture, to speak to someone about deep personal feelings. Like
sites inviting comment on, say, the death of Princess Diana or
memories of Vietnam, it's about as close as the Web comes to being
a virtual community.
</P>
<P>
   The new site's purpose is to provide women made widows in any
war a way to share their feelings. Already, remembrances also have
come in from women whose husbands died in Kosovo, Rwanda and
Afghanistan. And even one from a Vietnamese widow whose husband was
killed by American bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site was the brainchild of Barbara Sonneborn, 56, of San
Francisco, an artist and filmmaker whose first husband, Jeffery
Gurvitz, was killed in action in Vietnam in 1968. She finally dealt
with her lingering grief by producing an Oscar-nominated
documentary called ``Regret to Inform,'' which aired on public
television this year. Both the Web site and documentary have been
funded by San Francisco-based Sun Fountain Productions, a nonprofit
group founded in 1998 to help women fight against war, racism and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   She compares the new site to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial wall
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that one of the most powerful impressions they have
of the wall is imagining the stories behind each of the names
etched in granite,'' says Sonneborn. ``Now, the Widows of War
Living Memorial actually lets you read these stories. As visitors
wander through the site and read the stories, they will understand
war on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   If the wall is any indication, the War Widows site will be
heavily visited. A cyber version of the wall, thevirtualwall.org,
was launched in November 1998, and it has posted more than 15,000
remembrances, says Jan Scruggs, the Vietnam veteran who led the
efforts to build the wall and to put the virtual wall on the Web.
The site averages 600,000 hits a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything like this that helps people record their feelings and
keeps the issue alive is good,'' Scruggs says of the war widow
site. ``It doesn't end with a body, flag and casket,'' he says.
``The pain just continues. It's a valuable lesson, and that's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeland agrees. Her husband, Green Beret Capt. William W.
Walker, was killed in Vietnam in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you find the love of your life, and then they go
away,'' says Freeland, who, like Brown, has remarried. ``I had just
left him in Hawaii while he was on R&AMP;R. He died two weeks later. He
only had 30 days on his tour before he was coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   They wrote daily, but just before she received a ``regret to
inform'' telegram, she sensed something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part was seeing the postman pass my mailbox without
stopping,'' Freeland wrote in her remembrance. ``There had been
daily tapes and letters that passed between us and were the glue
that held us together.''
</P>
<P>
   At 84, Mary Alice Giles still sees her late husband, Harlan
Giles, in Atlanta's many trees. ``He'd always been so agile and
strong. He'd often climb to the tops of trees. I still think about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles was mortally wounded in the Battle of the Bulge in 1945,
where a German bullet made him a paraplegic. He lived in pain until
1953.
</P>
<P>
   In her remembrance, she described their life after he came home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was a very brave person,'' she wrote. ``He was
always cheerful during his long illness. He never complained even
though he was in much pain at times. I loved and admired Harlan
very much. I cherish great memories of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Atlantan who has posted is Grace Umutesi, 43, whose
husband was killed in 1994 in the Rwandan civil war. She won't talk
about it to anyone but Sonneborn's folks, but told them she had a
message for other war widows: ``Be strong, teach your children to
grow in peace, forgive. We must be peacemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonneborn says her Web site is ``a place for reconciliation,
healing, communication. You no longer have to hold in feelings that
are so powerful and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, that's what war widows have been
expected to do throughout history, Sonneborn says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has enormous potential for positive social change,'' says
Sonneborn. ``Now, even in corners of the world where women have no
power, via the Web they can communicate with other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``War has been an arena for men to speak out, not for women,''
she says. ``It was difficult to get funding at first for this
project because people didn't want to know what women thought about
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Until deciding in 1988 to start researching the Vietnam War,
Sonneborn says, ``I had met only one other woman in all those years
who was a war widow.''
</P>
<P>
   In producing her documentary, however, she learned that there
were many like her, and many who were suffering in isolation. With
Americans' distaste for the Vietnam War, she says, many widows were
not only cut off from others, but actually harassed. ``I talked to
women who had to leave their communities because they were told
their husbands were baby killers. Callers would tell some widows,
`he deserved to die.'''
</P>
<P>
   Men started veterans' organizations _ and there are many for the
Vietnam era _ but women ``had almost nowhere to go to deal with the
isolation. They were told, `You're young. You'll be fine.' But they
weren't, and a lot still aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Bourdage, 76, lost her husband Nelson Bourdage _ who'd
also fought in World War II and Korea _ in Vietnam of kidney
disease, which the Pentagon ruled was caused by Agent Orange, the
toxic defoliant widely sprayed over jungles by American forces to
clear the way for bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good thing,'' she says of the War Widows site. ``I
have heard so many say they didn't have any support. They wondered,
`What in the world am I going to do?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt real good writing about Preston,'' Brown says. ``It
was almost like talking to him again. And I'm very grateful for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : The Widows of War Living Memorial:
warwidows.org
</P>
<P>
   Regret to Inform: regrettoinform.org
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam Virtual Wall: thevirtualwall.org
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
