   CUBAN-BOY-VIEWS (Miami) _ In Cuba, playwright Carmen Duarte's
work was often censored, and she and the actors in her theater
troupe were once beaten by policemen. Now living in the nation's
largest and most potent Cuban-American enclave, Duarte is trying
once again to give voice to a point a view that many experts on
exile politics say can lead to ostracism. She believes that Elian
Gonzalez should have been reunited with his father, and she has
said so on her daily radio show. Such talk, though, has been met by
some of the same intransigence Duarte encountered in Cuba. By Juan
Forero. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,700
