<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOTTERY-FEVER28-COX     04-27 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-FEVER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Game fever hits Georgia with $105 million jackpot at stake
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Who wants to be a hundred-million-aire?
</P>
<P>
   The folks buying $12 million worth of Big Game tickets across
Georgia this week, that's who. Whether they are playing a variation
of the digits in Elian Gonzalez's birthday (6, 12, 93) or ``Quik
Pik'' numbers, all hope to be $105 million richer by 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After a Thursday conference call to the other six states in the
powerball-style game, Georgia Lottery Corp. President Rebecca Paul
announced that the jackpot would rise from the $100 million mark,
with a chance of another bump up today if sales continue to soar.
</P>
<P>
   And soar they do. The record-high $197 million jackpot was won a
year ago this month and Georgians appear to hope April lightning
will strike again. The Big Game averages $2.7 million a week, but
this week's sales stand at $12 million, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   As ticket outlets go, few in metro Atlanta can match the volume
sellers bordering Alabama and South Carolina, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   But Salim Virani, manager of a Shell Service Station in Atlanta,
said his store's sales will ``jump after 6 p.m., with some
customers spending $100 to $200.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul says the odds of winning the Big Game are one in
76,275,360, but why dwell on the unimaginable?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, do as Scott Ryan did. Thursday, in what may be the
ultimate test of employee loyalty, the Atlanta-based Incanta.net
CEO sprang for 100 tickets as a treat for his 37 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
