<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-WIRELESS-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T OFFERING BRINGS COMPANY $10 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They did not triple, double or even jump 50 percent.
But for AT&AMP;T, Thursday's 8 percent rise for new shares that are
meant to track the company's wireless unit was victory enough.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's biggest initial stock offering yet, AT&AMP;T agreed
Wednesday night to sell 360 million of the new wireless shares for
$29.50 each, just above the middle of the company's estimated
range. That brought in $10.6 billion (before paying more than $300
million to investment banks for underwriting the deal).
</P>
<P>
   The wireless shares opened for trading Thursday at $30.125
before rising to close at $31.6875 in torrential trading of 124.7
million shares on the New York Stock Exchange. That made for the
second-busiest trading day yet for an individual Big Board stock.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, some high-technology stocks could routinely be
expected to double in their first day of trading. By that
perhaps-unrealistic standard, AT&AMP;T's deal was disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   But because its offering was so huge and because the equity
markets are so unsettled now, AT&AMP;T could not realistically have
hoped for the shares to experience any sort of explosive first-day
gain. Even though the shares did not rise to the $32 figure that
had been the top of AT&AMP;T's estimated range for the offering, the
company's executives could still count the more than $10 billion
they had raised and point with pride to the wireless unit's new
market value of more than $73 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big vote of confidence in AT&AMP;T Wireless,'' John D.
Zeglis, the wireless unit's chief executive, said in an interview.
``This is a vote that wireless is the future and some encouragement
that we can take this to new places like mobile Internet and fixed
broadband communications to the home.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Zeglis was up-front in conceding that the market
turmoil of recent weeks did not help the offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have chosen this market to play into if we had our
choice,'' he said. Referring to trips that he and his team made in
recent weeks to present the offering to big institutional
investors, he added: ``Of course we had our eye on the market the
whole time, not that we could do anything about it. We were very
aware of what was going on around us and what the comparable
companies were trading at.''
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds, or roughly 234 million, of the 360 million
shares sold directly by AT&AMP;T went to institutional investors while
about 90 million were purchased by individual investors and roughly
36 million were bought by AT&AMP;T's employees.
</P>
<P>
   After selling the deal, AT&AMP;T retained about 84.4 percent of the
new wireless tracking shares, theoretically worth about $62
billion.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary when an older, slower-growing company offers
shares in a smaller, faster-growing subsidiary, AT&AMP;T is not
receiving full financial credit for that stake. AT&AMP;T's shares fell
$2.875 Thursday, to $47.875, shaving about $10 billion in market
value from the parent company and leaving it with a market value of
about $153.3 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Subtracting the value of AT&AMP;T's stake in the wireless unit would
imply that the rest of AT&AMP;T, including its big long-distance
telephone operation, is worth only about $91 billion. But it is
surely worth more than that. After all, AT&AMP;T enjoyed a market value
in the $150 billion range last fall, before it became known that
AT&AMP;T was planning to issue the new wireless shares.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T intends to distribute most (and will probably end up
distributing all) of its remaining wireless shares to the holders
of the company's common stock. But the value of that distribution
has been obscured, at least partly because the holders of those
common shares really have no way to know just what they will end up
getting.
</P>
<P>
   That is because AT&AMP;T will probably give the owners of its common
stock the option to exchange that stock for wireless shares
outright before distributing the remaining wireless shares to the
remaining owners of AT&AMP;T common stock.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's board has not made any final decisions on such a plan,
but such exchange offers are far from obscure to AT&AMP;T's top
leaders. John C. Malone, who sits on AT&AMP;T's board, has employed
exchange offers at his Liberty Media operation. Moreover, Charles
H. Noski, AT&AMP;T's chief financial officer, held that job at General
Motors' Hughes Electronics unit last year when GM began considering
a similar sort of exchange deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, GM announced the final details of its Hughes-GM share
exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
