<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COMPAQ28-COX     04-27 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By John Pletz
</P>
<P>
   c. 200 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Edward Yates came from across the country, and Felix
Ascolese came from across town.
</P>
<P>
   But the two Compaq Computer Corp. shareholders came to Houston's
J.W. Marriott hotel to see the same thing: Who is new Chief
Executive Michael Capellas, and can he turn things around?
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to see what Capellas is like in person,'' said
Ascolese, 55, who lives in the Houston suburb of Kingswood. ``He
came out of nowhere. He was a dark horse. It's the first time I've
ever been to an annual meeting before.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only been nine months since Capellas, then a little-known
Compaq chief information officer, took over the world's biggest PC
maker. But the early reviews at Thursday's annual meeting were
mostly positive or at least optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Yates flew in from North Haven, Conn., to hear Capellas tell his
story about rebuilding Compaq's brand, cutting costs and improving
profits, and becoming the company that will be the key provider of
every computing device of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical turnaround story,'' Yates said. ``But it's a
story that in the middle of the process, so we don't know if it's
going to be successful yet. I think they're on the right path.''
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, Capellas must do more than just overhaul Compaq's
organizational chart and product mix, he must also change the
28-year-old company's culture and its flagging image.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy, pride and enthusiasm is bouncing back and getting
stronger every day,'' Capellas said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Success in the eyes of investors will be judged by the company's
stock price, which has been treading water mainly in the $20s for
the past year. The stock price surged nearly 15 percent to $30.25
this week when Compaq announced first-quarter earnings Tuesday that
met analysts' relatively unambiguous estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Such reaction is less a statement about the tough times in the
PC business lately than how far Compaq had fallen under Eckhard
Pfeiffer, who was forced out a year ago. Earnings were falling,
expenses were out of control and Wall Street was angry.
</P>
<P>
   Capellas took the stage Thursday with a spring in his step and
wearing a dressed-down, open-collared shirt beneath a dark suit.
From the start, Capellas drew a sharp contrast to his buttoned-down
predecessor, German-born Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Capellas is in a difficult fight to make his mark. And he has
taken action. Since being named CEO on July 22, Capellas has
presided over a painful restructuring that will purge 6,000 to
8,000 of Compaq's 67,000 employees, including 450 people laid off
in Houston a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Operating expenses have dropped from about $2.2 billion in the
second quarter last year to 1.8 billion in the first quarter of
2000. Gross margin is rising from about 20 percent last June to 23
percent today.
</P>
<P>
   As he acknowledged several times Thursday, ``We're not there
yet. We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Symbolic of the company's fortunes, last year it was dethroned
by Dell Computer Corp. as the No. 1 PC seller in the United States.
Although it remains No. 1 worldwide, Compaq's grip on that title _
like that of the industry generally _ is slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been losing money on commercial desktops, although
the losses have narrowed dramatically from $179 million last
September. Profits from consumer PCs, despite runaway growth in
unit shipments, remains flat as margins continue to shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make money in the commercial personal computer
business,'' Capellas said emphatically after the meeting, adding
that the division should return to profitability in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the big hopes around Compaq these days are pinned to the
servers that power Web sites and business networks, and new devices
that will let people access the Internet from almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dell, IBM Corp. and others, Compaq is trying to redefine
itself as more than just a PC company by targeting back-office
systems and the so-called ``Internet infrastructure'' with server
and storage products where margins are higher than the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``As fate of that (enterprise) group goes, so goes the fate of
Compaq,'' said Amir Ahari, who follows the PC industry for U.S.
Bancorp Piper Jaffray. ``The commercial desktop group is not the
turnaround genie for Compaq. The days of those products being the
key for Compaq and everybody is just gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Capellas knows this and trumpets the company's
server-and-storage business as the key to its future. It has no
intention of surrendering its No. 1 position in the server market,
but the competition is getting tougher all the time.
</P>
<P>
   To compete, Compaq is introducing ultra-slim Windows/Intel
products and next month will unveil a high-end Unix server called
Wildfire designed to take the fight to Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The company is hoping for a boost from Internet-access devices,
too. It introduced the iPAQ, a stripped-down PC designed primarily
for Web access, and is launching a number of handheld devices in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also is planning a major advertising campaign to shore up
its image as a technology powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expect to see us get just a little edgy,'' Capellas said.
``The bad news is the brand is not well known for all the things
we're in. The good news is we've got really great stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Capellas has some breathing room _ probably until the end of the
year _ to prove himself. But there are still plenty of questions
and high expectations. Wall Street is anticipating earnings of
$1.07 per share for the year, or triple 1999's results of 34 cents
per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capellas should have it all together by the end of the fourth
quarter,'' Ahari said. ``The fourth quarter is going to be make or
break for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Compaq stock closed up 50 cents at $29.75.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
