<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOOVERS28-COX     04-27 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOVERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hoover's promises profit by March 2001
 &HT;    By Amy Schatz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Although Hoover's Inc. announced another year of
net losses Thursday, the company said it could be profitable by
March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin-based online business information and electronic
commerce portal said it expects to turn a profit in the fourth
quarter of its next fiscal year, which ends March 31, 2001. Faster
than expected growth in revenue and subscribers allowed the date to
be moved forward by several quarters, the company announced
Thursday afternoon when it released fourth quarter and annual
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's shares closed up a quarter a share to $9 on Thursday.
Earnings were released after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've outperformed what we thought we'd do when we went
public. It just became clear to us that it wouldn't take as long
for us to become profitable,'' said Chief Executive Officer Patrick
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported net losses of 13 cents a share for the
quarter ended March 31, beating analyst estimates by 6 cents a
share. The company's net loss for the fourth quarter was about $1.8
million, up from $347,000 last year. Revenue, however, more than
doubled to $6.6 million from $3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Hoover's reported a net loss of $9.5 million
compared to $2.3 million for the previous year. However, the
company also saw net revenues double to $19 million, compared to
just $9.2 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company will focus on providing content for
wireless devices such as personal digital assistants and cell
phones, expansion of European content, and services to keep
visitors at the Hoover's site for longer periods.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's went public in July and at one point reached a high of
$33 a share. But the company's stock quickly dropped and has
hovered in the $9 to $12 range for the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a little undervalued because we weren't sexy. Now,
people are looking for companies that are looking at becoming
profitable in the foreseeable future,'' Spain said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
