<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRI     04-27 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SHOWING CONTINUED STRONG GROWTH RAISES INFLATION FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, subs byline, rewrites throughout)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With lavish consumer spending providing the stimulus, the
American economy turned in another highly robust quarter, the
government reported Thursday, as new evidence emerged that today's
prosperity is finally pushing up labor costs, raising fear of
higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate, as measured by the Commerce Department,
jumped in the first three months of the year, mainly because of
higher gasoline and fuel oil prices. But Wall Street expressed the
worry that even as petroleum prices recede, labor costs will kick
in and keep the inflation rate rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, the economy is growing much too strongly to avoid
inflation,'' said Richard Rippe, chief economist at Prudential
Securities. ``There are too many little signs out there that the
Federal Reserve cannot ignore. It will have to continue to raise
interest rates; the increases so far have had no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong pace of growth and the fresh warning signs of an
acceleration in wage and price increases raised the possibility
that the Federal Reserve could raise short-term interest rates by
as much as half a percentage point next month in its effort to curb
inflationary pressures. But most analysts expect it to stick to a
more modest quarter point rate increase at its meeting on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, reacting to the hints of rising inflation and
the likelihood of more interest rate increases, plunged in the
first hour or so of trading. But it then bounced back as investors
focused on the prospects for higher profits from the growing
economy. The Nasdaq composite index rose a very healthy 143.94
points, or nearly 4 percent, to 3,774.03, and the Dow Jones
industrial average finished at 10,888.1, down only 57.4 points or
about 1/2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The gross domestic product, representing the value of all of the
goods and services produced in the nation from January through
March, rose at a 5.4 percent annual rate, the Commerce Department
reported. This was the quarter in which the expansion became the
longest in history, but Americans showed no signs of running out of
money or out of confidence that the good times will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on a variety of sources _ savings, bonuses and raises,
stock options and market gains, the wages from new jobs, as well as
income tax refunds and more borrowing _ people piled into the
marketplace during the first three months of the year at a pace not
seen in 17 years. Showing confidence that the good times will
continue, they spent most heavily on cars and trucks, but they also
increased their purchases of clothing, appliances, furniture,
sports events, casino gambling, computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication of all this is that people feel wealthier;
their assets are going up in value _ their stock portfolios and
their homes _ and they intend to spend more,'' said Robert Parker,
chief statistician at the Commerce Department's Bureau of Economic
Analysis, which prepares the GDP report.
</P>
<P>
   The rise exceeded the increase in spending in any quarter since
the spring of 1983. Then, the nation was just bouncing back from a
recession; now the expansion is more than nine years old. Even
politicians added to the bounty. The outlays by all the
presidential candidates added more than $235 million to the gross
domestic product from January through March _ or two-tenths of a
percentage in the growth rate of 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Business investment grew with equal abandon. Construction of
homes, schools, office buildings and highways rose by 12.1 percent.
Outlays for machinery and equipment, mainly computers and software,
rose a stunning 23.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firms rushed to purchase new computers last year in the runup
to Y2K,'' said Chris Varvares, a partner at Macroeconomic Partners
in St. Louis, ``and in the first quarter they resumed the process
of upgrading their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   What most alarmed Wall Street, which is always fearful that
rising inflation will undercut the public's enthusiasm for stocks
and bonds, was a separate report issued Thursday by the Bureau of
Labor Statistics. It said that labor costs rose at an unexpectedly
fast pace during the quarter _ partly from rising wages but mostly
from greater company outlays for employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau's Employment Cost Index rose 1.4 percent during the
quarter, up sharply from the 1 percent increase in the fourth
quarter, much of it due to a big rise in health insurance costs,
which have gone up gradually for two years. Company outlays for
health insurance rose by 7.6 percent in the year that ended last
month, or three times faster than the 2.5 percent increase in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If you are looking for where the potential upward pressure on
prices is coming from,'' said Jared Bernstein, a labor economist at
the Economic Policy Institute, ``it is energy and health
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The broad inflation measure published with the GDP report _ a
gauge that the Fed now watches more closely than the more popular
consumer price index _ rose by 3.2 percent compared with 2.5
percent in the fourth quarter. But when energy and food are
subtracted, the index was up only 1.8 percent, down slightly from
the fourth quarter's 2 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts argue that the economy cannot maintain a growth
rate above 3.5 percent or 4 percent without subjecting the country
to inflationary shortages. But strong economic growth is likely to
continue through the current quarter, which ends on June 30, some
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that cars and trucks were high on the shopping list
in the first quarter, but most were purchased out of back lot
inventories, which must be replenished as robust vehicle sales
continue. What's more, a strike at the Boeing Co. temporarily
interrupted production at the huge aircraft company, which
contributes significantly to the nation's output and exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
