u i BC-SENATE-AMBASSADORS-NY     04-27 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-AMBASSADORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMATS URGE SENATE TO APPROVE AMBASSADORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa) By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In an unusual step for the diplomatic
establishment, two major foreign service organizations are asking
the Senate to lift a politically instigated hold on two
ambassadorial appointments that have been blocked for nearly nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, in a deal that released another hold on the
nomination of Richard Holbrooke as U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee took three
``hostages'' in return. Among them was Peter Burleigh, a career
diplomat who had been designated ambassador to the Philippines, but
was filling in at the United Nations for the missing Holbrooke,
whose arrival was delayed for a year by investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh, a terrorism expert, is still waiting to go to the
Philippines, where this week a complicated series of abductions by
Islamic separatists is playing out. Among the victims are tourists
seized at a diving resort in neighboring Malaysia. Reports from the
Philippines say that the abductors are demanding the release of
Muslim prisoners in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments of Burleigh and of Carl Spielvogel to Slovakia,
another country with recent political tensions, remain locked in an
unrelated personnel dispute between Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa,
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. The third appointment,
that of J. Richard Fredericks as ambassador to Switzerland, was
freed after President Clinton was allowed to choose one name for
release and picked his.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks and Spielvogel were both political appointees and
contributors to the Democratic Party. The nomination of Burleigh, a
former ambassador to Sri Lanka was a career appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The American Foreign Service Association, which represents the
diplomatic corps, and the Academy of American Diplomacy, a support
organization that counts among its members all eight living former
secretaries of state, wrote two weeks ago to Grassley and Sen.
Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, to protest the continuing
hold on Burleigh's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Grassley, the foreign service association's
president, Marshall P. Adair, said: ``It is essential that we send
the most highly experienced and qualified people we have to promote
out interests around the world. ``Our ability to do that is
severely constrained when the nomination process becomes
irretrievably entangled in political bartering on other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Lott, the academy's chairman, Joseph L. Sisco,
and president, L. Bruce Laingen, expressed regret that the case
``should cause further delay in providing the leadership needed in
our missions in the Philippines and Slovakia in pursuing our
interests in those two important countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The case at the heart of the dispute involves Linda Shenwick, a
former State Department diplomat at the U.S. mission here, whom
Republicans view as a whistle-blower for her reports to Congress
outside diplomatic channels of allegations of financial
mismanagement in the United Nations, a prime target of
conservatives. When Shenwick was transferred back to the State
Department after what administration officials consider a normal
tour of duty, Grassley and others charged that the move was
political and that Shenwick was being persecuted unfairly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
