<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     04-27 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TALE OF TWO (BIG-TIME) CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the next few days, men from Toronto and men from New York
will be aggressing each other with sticks, elbows and the
occasional hard slide.
</P>
<P>
   This does not necessarily signal the start of a great
Toronto-New York border war. There is too much evidence of
worldliness, maturity and tolerance _ certainly on the Toronto
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a rivalry, both parties have to feel it,'' said Ken
Dryden, once a championship goaltender with the Montreal Canadiens,
now the general manager of the renewed Toronto Maple Leafs. ``I'm
not sure New Yorkers would buy a rivalry with Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they could work on it. New Yorkers delight in being hated
by the John Rockers of the world, but New Yorkers must sense that
Toronto, with its own subway and Chinatown and film festivals, does
not feel a threat to its pride, its dignity and the Canadian way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Through the vagaries of playoff pairings and regular-season
schedules, there is a trifecta of matchups this weekend between New
York and its cinematic stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays of baseball will be playing at Yankee Stadium
Friday night, tomorrow and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Knicks of basketball will be playing the Raptors
at the Air Canada Centre, which is so Canadian that it is indeed
officially spelled the British way, no matter how much it might
offend New York hubris.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday night at the aforementioned Toronto arena, the
hallowed Maple Leafs of hockey began a Stanley Cup playoff series
against the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The only trash talk emanating from Toronto came from a radio
station reviving the New Jersey stereotypes of ``swamplands,''
toxic waste and Jimmy Hoffa's alleged burial beneath Giants Stadium
_ in other words, nothing that New Yorkers do not indulge in for
our own cheap, provincial thrills.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some rumblings among the competitors themselves.
The Maple Leafs and the Devils were trading charges of viciousness,
if you can imagine such a thing in hockey, while the Raptors'
coach, Butch Carter, has been busy filing and withdrawing a lawsuit
against a former player, making unsubstantiated charges of racism
against his old college coach and sending in a rusty sub to take
the last desperation shot in Wednesday night's loss.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers may see Carter's distraction as a tribute to their
own obnoxious ways, but who is to say that Carter would not be just
as unfocused against Charlotte or some other burg?
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, there is no panic up north. John Coburn, a Toronto
artist who loves and draws New York, did not immediately join the
Yonge Street Irregulars for battles between the Devils' Czechs and
the Maple Leafs' Swedes, or the Yankees' Panamanians and the Blue
Jays' Dominicans.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Coburn was planning an imminent trip to Gotham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto people salivate over New York and everything it has to
offer,'' he said. ``They love the way New Yorkers will either tell
you to go to hell or say, `Let's have coffee.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn has lived in New York for months at a time, enough to
produce 160 pen-and-ink drawings for three books about its small
hotels, its neighborhoods and the high points of Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the quality of life is a little better in Toronto,''
he said, ``but you get back on the plane and you look down at New
York and you sigh a little.''
</P>
<P>
   These do not sound like the inflammatory charges that citizens
make when teams from small towns become involved in sports
playoffs. There are no silly mayoral wagers of local brews or
regional dishes going on.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto did not even bother to shut down the frontier last
weekend, when the Yankees were playing at the Skydome and more than
half the fans seemed to come from Buffalo, Rochester and points
downstate.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion is common. After the last game of the 1995 season,
when the Yanks clinched a wild-card berth, the last flight to La
Guardia was jammed with large and gruff New Yorkers who had been
Molson-ing their way around the ballpark all weekend. When the
flight attendant walked down the aisle with a plastic bag, asking,
``Trash?'' one of the louts shouted, ``Hey, she's talking about
us.''
</P>
<P>
   They were on relatively good behavior since there is no sporting
bad blood between any of these teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually the teams become the bitter rivals, like the Rangers
and Flyers or Knicks and Celtics,'' Dryden said. ``But I'm not sure
New York feels a rivalry with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto can afford a wry familiarity with New York since, for
some intents and purposes, it is New York.
</P>
<P>
   The cheap Canadian dollar, the eclectic architecture and the
cooperative citizenry make Toronto a viable alternative to New York
for film production, including the Brooklyn cheese shop in
``Moonstruck'' and the urban menace of Paterson, N.J., in ``The
Hurricane.'' The Ontario Film Development Corp. lists more than 50
television productions and 21 feature films in 1999 made by
foreigners, mostly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down near the lake where I live, a guy keeps a whole fleet of
New York city cabs and police cars because he knows they're needed
all the time,'' said Allen Abel, a son of Flatbush, Brooklyn, now a
prominent journalist with the CBC and The National Post.
</P>
<P>
   The daily proximity to New York street signs and artifacts and
emblems makes Canadians comfortable with the foibles of life down
south. Canada even got over it quickly when an American singer
mangled ``O Canada'' at Yankee Stadium before a tense game in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, not all New Yorkers are self-centered, jingoistic and
isolationist. We think Chancellor Trudeau is doing a great job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
