<SLUG> BC-VT-GAY-UNIONS-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT'S TOP JUDGE SOUGHT `COMMON HUMANITY' IN GAY UNIONS RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Hawaii)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. _ There is so much that Chief Justice Jeffrey L.
Amestoy of the Vermont Supreme Court cannot say.
</P>
<P>
   He can welcome a visitor into his small, paper-piled office in
the gray granite Supreme Court building here, looking a mere mortal
in brown chinos and loafers instead of black robes, and so low-key
in his manner that it almost seems normal to call the chief justice
Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   He can talk about his past as a seven-term state attorney
general, one with such stature that he was appointed chief justice
in 1997 by a Democratic governor, even though he was a Republican.
He can even talk about his idyllic childhood, fishing and playing
baseball in Rutland.
</P>
<P>
   But as a judge in an continuing case, he cannot discuss the
decision that makes him such a pivotal figure in Vermont now: His
court's ruling in December that gay couples were victims of
unconstitutional discrimination. That ruling put the onus of ending
the discrimination on the Legislature, and on Tuesday it led to the
passage of a first-in-the-nation bill creating marriage-like civil
unions for same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   So Amestoy (pronounced AM-eh-stoy) must apologetically decline
to answer what anyone following this case would most like to know:
Did he foresee how all this would play out, that the state would be
deeply divided over gay marriage but the Legislature would
successfully fashion such a compromise?
</P>
<P>
   Is the court satisfied that the bill to create same-sex civil
unions will end the discrimination it found, or is it contemplating
further action?
</P>
<P>
   And, ultimately, what difference did it make that it was
specifically he, Amestoy, who was head of the state's highest court
when this question came up?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for a man who must remain silent, there are plenty
of friends and colleagues who will speak for him. And what they
tend to say is that the 53-year-old chief justice, a history buff,
takes the long, broad view: that he is by nature moderate,
nondoctrinaire and deeply common-sensical, and that he loves
Vermont and would not cast it into turmoil any worse than could be
avoided, but wants to make a real difference here. All those
characteristics, his friends speculate, probably played a role in
the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jeff has a lot of wisdom,'' said Vermont's governor,
Howard Dean, who signed the civil unions bill into law on
Wednesday. ``I appointed him as a moderate, and I think this ruling
was a moderate ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, as well, Amestoy, who is married and the father of
three daughters, used to be able to talk much more freely, and
there are all kinds of hints in his speeches and professional
record about how his mind works.
</P>
<P>
   When he accepted his current post in 1997, he said in his
inauguration speech: ``I believe in `civility in public discourse
and constancy in private affection.' And I believe, with Learned
Hand, that `the spirit of liberty is the spirit that is not too
sure it is right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (``There is much to be said about that,'' he said in an
interview, ``but I'll leave it at that.'')
</P>
<P>
   Consider: In 1993, Hawaii's Supreme Court ruled, much like its
Vermont counterpart, that barring same-sex couples from marrying
was discrimination. But it did not leave it up to the Legislature
to decide the remedy, and the backlash against the ruling was so
powerful that in 1998, opponents passed a constitutional amendment
authorizing the Legislature to restrict marriage to heterosexual
couples. As a result, the marriage case has been dismissed as moot.
</P>
<P>
   Now take Vermont: Instead of simply decreeing that gay couples
should be allowed to marry, it sent the issue back to the Vermont
Legislature to work out a remedy, and left open the option of
stopping short of official marriage if virtually all the same
benefits were provided. Debate got rough at times, but the
Legislature did pass the civil unions bill, and voted down calls
for Hawaiian-style constitutional amendments.
</P>
<P>
   A group called ``Take It to the People'' and other opponents of
gay marriage here accuse Amestoy and the court of over-the-top
judicial activism and of forcing Vermonters to accept gay couples
even though many still disapprove of homosexuality. To them, the
civil unions bill is not a compromise but a virtual legalization of
gay marriage. They have called repeatedly for a constitutional
amendment, which would require a popular vote, or at least a
nonbinding referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Legislature rejected that idea. And, luckily for the
court, amendments are much harder to pass here than in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The court also chose another politically careful tactic: It
could have based its ruling on the principle that gay couples
deserved special protections because they belong to a persecuted
class. One justice argued as much, and another said the court
should simply grant marriage licenses to gay couples.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, another group of critics of Amestoy say that clear
evidence of homophobia in Vermont, made even clearer by the debate
on the issue, demonstrates the depth of persecution and the special
protections thus needed.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of talking about special protections, the ruling
stepped onto trickier legal ground, arguing that gay couples must
be granted the same rights as heterosexuals under a clause in the
Vermont Constitution that says the state should treat everyone
equally.
</P>
<P>
   The most ringing sentence of the decision, which Amestoy wrote,
said that granting equal rights to homosexual couples ``who seek
nothing more, nor less, than legal protection and security for
their avowed commitment to an intimate and lasting relationship is
simply, when all is said and done, a recognition of our common
humanity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some legal observers see the hand of Amestoy in that balancing
act and choice of tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he was the one who crafted the decision in a way that
would bring people together,'' said a former Maine attorney
general, James E. Tierney, a friend from the National Association
of Attorneys General, which the future chief justice led as
president in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sent it to the Legislature but he put them in a box,''
Tierney said. ``He knew the process; he's a great believer in the
process, and he knew the same process he led the court through
would then be gone through in the Legislature: You start with the
hatred and the reaction and the extremes, and you work on it and
work on it and you find your way. His bottom line is to do this
with dignity and respect. What would possibly be the sense of doing
this if you end up with a state that's divided and filled with hate
and anger?''
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders cannot know what exact process the chief justice led
the court through, but it would seem likely his leadership style
has not changed since his years as attorney general. Brian Burgess,
his deputy from 1985 to 1992 and now a Vermont district court
judge, said that the Supreme Court's decision to invite the
Legislature into the process ``reflects a recognition that the
court does not have a monopoly on right answers, which is his
approach to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Amestoy _ the name reflects his Basque heritage _ politely
deflected almost every question relating to gay marriage, including
whether any personal experience with gay couples had influenced
him. One little word did slip, however, when asked if the political
process had gone as he had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday,'' he said wistfully of a time in the future when he
would be able to talk freely again.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, however, the chief justice may not have all the
historical answers. In his inauguration speech, he quoted the late
Pennsylvania trial judge Curtis Bok as saying that being a judge
entailed a mystery that defied analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A judge's cases,'' he wrote, ``take hold of him and pull
things out of him,'' and ``it is his business to be sure to keep
the proper supplies on hand, so far as he can be master of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
