<SLUG> BC-BBA-PALMEIRO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO HELPS YOUNG PLAYERS COPE WITH STRUGGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Rafael Palmeiro invited Gabe Kapler to breakfast
Wednesday morning in the Rangers' clubhouse, although what he had
in mind wasn't exactly a feast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a doughnut together,'' Palmeiro told
Kapler. ``Not a plain doughnut. A glazed doughnut. Not one of those
with cream filling or sprinkles on it, just a good, old-fashioned,
glazed doughnut.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler, a nutritional fanatic, normally goes for the Triple Whey
shakes for breakfast, but he gladly accepted Palmeiro's invitation.
It wasn't that Kapler had a craving for a glazed doughnut; he just
wasn't going to pass up a chance to talk with one of his mentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Raffy's awesome,'' Kapler said later. ``He such a good
person, and he's a pretty-decent ballplayer. I watch him all the
time ... not really his swing, but the way he goes about his
business and the way he handles himself. He always conducts himself
as a professional. I respect him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a tough time for some of the Rangers' younger
players, Kapler foremost among them with his 9-for-66 slump.
Palmeiro has taken it upon himself to help guide them through it.
Palmeiro may one day get 3,000 hits, 500 home runs and induction
into the Hall of Fame, but he hasn't forgotten what it's like to be
young and struggling to make it in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you're a young player and you're trying to
establish yourself at this level,'' Palmeiro said. ``It doesn't
happen overnight. The key is to be patient, be positive and be
focused. Just because things aren't going your way, you can't just
give up. You make adjustments. It's a learning process, and it
takes awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to learn is to go out, play the game and learn
from your mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo: ``That's why it's good to
have guys like Raffy around. He has a lot of confidence as a
hitter. He trusts his skills, and he's very positive. He's a good
influence on some of these young guys.'
</P>
<P>
   Kapler said: ``It's not necessarily what he says but when he
says it. He goes out of his way to say something when you need it.
He's somebody that everybody in this clubhouse has a lot of respect
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro went through tough times in 1989, his first year with
the Rangers after being acquired from the Chicago Cubs. He actually
started hot, hitting .361 through May 28. But then the season
turned sour, as he batted .235 in the final 110 games. He had 17
runs batted in during his final 80 games, and the Rangers had
serious talks about trading him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad year,'' Palmeiro said. ``I was trying to
prove I belonged in this league. I pressed. ... I didn't handle it
the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro eventually pulled out of it, hitting .319 the next
year. But he had to fight a reputation for being moody and
self-absorbed. He said it wasn't until he signed with Baltimore
after the 1993 season that he learned how to handle things better.
</P>
<P>
   He did so by being around such veterans in Baltimore as Cal
Ripken Jr. and Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I sat down and talked to them all the time,''
Palmeiro said. ``I just watched them and saw how they handled
themselves, how they approached the game. They never got mad. You
never saw them throw bats, slam helmets or get down. To me that
showed a lot of class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have that the first time I was here. We had Nolan
Ryan, and he was our leader on the mound. But Nolan was quiet, and
he kept to himself. He wasn't the kind of guy you could go to and
talk hitting with. Everybody else was young; we were all just here
to learn the game and prove we belonged here. It was a hard thing
to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro doesn't want Kapler, Ruben Mateo and some of the
Rangers' other young players to go through the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of players are watching me if I come back to the
dugout with a negative attitude,'' Palmeiro said. ``But no matter
how good the other pitcher is or how bad you're struggling, you
have to remain positive. There are bad times, times when you don't
feel as good at the plate or that you feel you're being as
productive as you can be for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing these guys have to realize is every at-bat is
different. All it takes is one at-bat to turn things around. You
can be 0-for-3 but come up in the ninth inning with the game on the
line and get that hit that wins the game. Now, all of a sudden,
you're feeling pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's transformation has reached a point that ``I have
absolute confidence in my ability. There's no doubt in my mind when
I go up to the plate I can get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys will be fine. They have talent, and you can see
that they believe in themselves. As long as they keep working hard
and preparing themselves, things will turn around and they will get
better.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
