<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS TO FOCUS ON TUBERCULOSIS RATE IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Baylor College of Medicine has been awarded a $15.5
million contract by the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda,
Md., to research tuberculosis in Houston, where the rate of the
disease is among the highest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Principal investigator Edward Graviss, Baylor assistant
professor of pathology and medicine, said he hopes to identify on a
molecular level the numerous strains of the TB bacterium found in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should help us determine whether people who know each
other have the same type of TB bug, indicating a likelihood that
one person transmitted it to the other,'' Graviss said.
</P>
<P>
   During the next seven years, TB specimens and blood samples will
be collected from 500 patients in Harris County, which includes
most of Houston. The samples will be analyzed in labs at Baylor and
the National Institute for Allergy and Infectious Diseases, or
NIAID.
</P>
<P>
   Graviss said the information from his study might result in a
better test to diagnose TB, which kills 3 million people worldwide
each year, and provide insights into genetic susceptibility to TB.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's TB rate in 1998 was 19.1 cases per 100,000 population,
the same as New York City's rate and comparable to San Francisco's
rate of 18.2.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the rate was 6.8 cases per 100,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty and crowded living conditions are major contributors to
the spread of the disease, he said. People with compromised immune
systems, such as those with the human immunodeficiency virus, also
are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Graviss said TB data collected in Houston over five years
showed: 40 percent of TB patients were black; 17 percent of
patients were HIV-positive; and 50 percent had a history of
incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the NIAID contract, Baylor will collaborate with the
City of Houston Health Department, the Harris County Hospital
District and city clinicians, who will help identify patients with
TB.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the study will answer questions about their
exposure to TB and provide four to five blood samples for one year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to analyzing TB strains, investigators will use the
data to study how the patient's body is responding to the disease
and to treatment, which should be provided by the patient's
physician. Treatment usually consists of four drugs for nine
months. State funds cover the cost of medication for patients
without insurance.
</P>
<P>
   TB exposure is usually confirmed by symptoms, such as coughing,
fever and fatigue, a skin test and a chest X-ray.
</P>
<P>
