<SLUG> BC-ARK-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RETURNS HOME TO HONOR CIVIL RIGHTS HEROINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ President Clinton, approaching the twilight
of his presidency, returned to the warm embrace of his native
Arkansas Thursday to celebrate the life of Daisy Bates, a revered
civil rights figure who died last December.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of several hundred Arkansans, Clinton smiled
broadly as the Rev. Rufus T. King Jr. welcomed him back to Little
Rock by saying he was happy to see him in one piece and ``not torn
all to pieces'' by his opponents over the last 18 months in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one of the reasons they haven't been able to do that is
because you had so many black folks praying for you,'' King said to
loud applause to a mostly black audience. Clinton threw back his
head in a gesture of deep pleasure. ``I'm still in one piece,'' he
said, ``though grayer and a lot more jagged.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who died at the age of 85, was an important figure in the
battle to integrate Little Rock's Central High School in 1957. As
state president of the NAACP at the time, she helped select the
nine students to integrate the school and she counseled them and
their families throughout the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his difficulties in Washington, Clinton has often
looked home to Arkansas for emotional replenishment. ''I've had a
good time,'' Clinton said following his prepared remarks. ``I'm
really glad I came.''
</P>
<P>
   After the memorial service for Bates, the president attended a
ceremony to name the law school at the University of Arkansas at
Little Rock after an old friend, William Bowen, who served as his
chief of staff in Arkansas in 1991, the year he ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   This time a different audience, mostly lawyers and judges and
their families, showered Clinton with similar adulation. He
remained for nearly an hour to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the warm welcomes he received Thursday, Clinton's
relationship with Arkansas has become more complicated. The local
press reported that many of his friends have been angered by his
announcement that he intends to transfer his voter registration to
New York where he and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, have bought
a home to help her establish residency for her Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   And although it was decidedly unmentioned Thursday, Clinton is
nearing the final stages of a disciplinary hearing before state
authorities that could result in the suspension or revocation of
his license to practice law. Last week was the deadline for
Clinton's lawyers to respond to a special lawyers' committee which
is considering disciplinary action against Clinton for his
testimony before a federal judge in January 1998 that he did not
have a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
