<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLONES-LIFESPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAL LIFE SPAN EXPECTED FOR CLONED COWS, RESEARCHERS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)  By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cloned cows have youthful cells and should live at least as long
as ordinary animals, say researchers at Advanced Cell Technology, a
company interested in using cloning to treat human disease and
extend life.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, reported in Friday's issue of Science, is
significant because tests of Dolly, the cloned sheep, had shown
that the tips of her chromosomes, known as telomeres, were
unusually short, suggesting a severe and possibly life-shortening
drawback in the cloning process. Telomeres get shorter each time a
cell divides, so are shorter in the body cells of older animals.
</P>
<P>
   Cells with longer telomeres can divide more often and live
longer than normal. But no one yet knows if longer telomeres will
increase lifespan in whole organisms. If they do, the cloned cows
``could be the longest lived cows on the planet,'' said Dr. Robert
P. Lanza, lead author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. West, the chief executive of Advanced Cell
Technology, hopes to develop methods of creating replacement
tissues by cloning a patient's cells. The fear that such tissues
would have short telomeres and abbreviated lifetime now seems
dispelled by the news from the cloned cows, and makes Dolly's case
appear to be an unexplained anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the cloning process is that the nucleus of an
adult cell is reprogrammed to its embryonic state by the cytoplasm,
or inner fluids, of an egg cell. The process is ethically fraught
because cloning a patient's cell would create an entity with the
same potential as a fertilized human egg. The patient's
reprogrammed cell would be merely cultured in glassware, however,
and used to produce replacement cells for failing organs.
</P>
<P>
   Because of problems with using human egg cells, Advanced Cell
Technology has been working with cow eggs. The company, based in
Worcester, Mass., created a stir 15 months ago when a researcher,
Dr. Jose Cibelli, produced a hybrid embryo by cloning some of his
own cells in cow eggs. The embryos were allowed to grow in
glassware for only a few cell divisions and the process was then
halted.
</P>
<P>
   The new experiment is encouraging with respect to the telomere
problem because the cow cells being cloned were old and had short
telomeres. Yet the calves seem more youthful than normal as judged
by various measures of cellular aging, and their telomeres are
longer than the usual.
</P>
<P>
   Cows live for more than 20 years, however, so the only quick way
to an answer about telomeres and lifespan will be with mice. Lanza
said that in serially-cloned mice generated by other researchers
the telomeres were getting longer at each generation.
</P>
<P>
   Xiangzhong Yang, a cloning expert at the University of
Connecticut, said that the finding of longer than normal telomeres
in the cloned cows ``is a really interesting observation'' which
would spark another wave of interest in cloning.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Peter Mombaerts, a biologist at Rockefeller University,
noted that only one calf had been cloned for every 271 attempts,
and that the cloning process might have selected some specially
youthful class of cell.
</P>
<P>
   The inefficiency of the process is a general problem and one of
the obstacles facing Advanced Cell Technology's cloning plans. On
present evidence therapy would require hundreds of unfertilized
human egg cells, or oocytes, to successfully reprogram one skin
cell nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   The company's original idea of using cow oocytes for this task
is not as outlandish as such a cross-species hybrid might suggest,
because the human genes in the hybrid cell's nucleus would quickly
take over and generate human proteins to replace their bovine
counterparts. The major technical glitch is that cow mitochondria,
independent genetic entities that provide a cell's energy, are
probably incompatible with a human nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Mombaerts said that a way round this roadblock would be to
isolate some of the patient's mitochondria and inject these into
the cow oocyte carrying the patient's skin cell nucleus. If the
human mitochondria survived, the hybrid cow-human cell should
become fully human as the cow proteins were replaced by natural
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Another way round the oocyte problem would be to identify the
factors in the cytoplasm that make the skin cell's nucleus revert
to the embryonic state. Lanza said that the company was pursuing
this.
</P>
<P>
   The oocyte's factors that reset the telomere length might be of
particular interest in treating the many diseases, like cirrhosis
and AIDS, that require the body to replace stricken cells at a
furious and ultimately unsustainable rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that process is understood it could have enormous
implications for a whole class of diseases that account for
significant mortality worldwide,'' said Dr. Ronald A. DePinho, a
telomere expert at the Dana Farber Cancer Institute in Boston. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
