<HEADLINE>
STOOPS HOPES FOR IMPROVED RUNNING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The arrival of Oklahoma football coach Bob
Stoops and his high-octane passing offense was one of the
highlights of the 1999 Big 12 football season.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops did away with the Sooners' traditional ground game for a
lively passing game _ with good results. OU averaged 36.8 points
and 427 yards total offense per game on the way to a 7-4
regular-season record and a berth in the Independence Bowl, where
the Sooners lost to Mississippi, 27-25. But good can always be
better, as Stoops pointed out yesterday while visiting with members
of the OU Club of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops said he was not concerned about the lack of a consistent
running game to complement quarterback Josh Heupel's passing. But
he conceded he would like to see the Sooners improve on last
season's last-place standing among conference rushing attacks
(105.5 yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   ``The running game is not a concern,'' Stoops said. ``You'd be
concerned if you didn't score any points. But \Rthe running game\S
is something we're continually trying to develop, an area we want
to improve in. That was a part of \Rspring training\S we worked
hard on.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman running backs Quenton Griffin and Seth Littrell return.
But there is a great deal of anticipation regarding three backs who
will report in August _ freshmen Brian Odom, Jerald Estus and
Renaldo Works.
</P>
<P>
   Odom has attracted the most attention. A 6-foot, 195-pound back
out of Ada, Okla., Odom was regarded as the premier high school
running back in Oklahoma last season as he set school records for
career rushing (5,918 yards), total offense (6,379 yards) and
touchdowns (98).
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of anticipation about all three,'' Stoops said.
``All of them are good running backs. Strong, with good speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the defensive focus during spring training was on
replacing three starters in the secondary. But Stoops said he likes
the work he saw in that area and feels good about being able to
match next season's great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere across the board we have a chance to be better than
the year before because players have more experience in our system,
a better understanding of what we're asking them to do, Stoops
said. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
