<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES SEEK UNANIMITY IN SUPPORT OF PROPOSED SPLIT OF MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of the filing deadline, many of the 19
state attorneys general who are part of the antitrust suit against
the Microsoft Corp. were lobbying and cajoling a handful of their
colleagues Thursday to join the majority and ask the court to break
Microsoft into two parts.
</P>
<P>
   A few attorneys general view this remedy proposal, favored by
the Justice Department and most of the states involved, as too
extreme. But the others fear that a fractured decision could harm
the government's case and give power to any Microsoft argument that
not even the plaintiffs agree on this remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Klein, an assistant attorney general in Utah, said, ``The
more the final result represents a joint view, the more influence
it has.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eliot L. Spitzer, the attorney general for New York, was
bullish, saying: ``We have a great deal of support, and though
there may be a few who disagree, I don't think it includes any of
the major states that have been involved in this case. We are
absolutely convinced that this is the right approach to the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint federal-state plan calls for breaking Microsoft into
two separate and competing companies. One would own the Windows
operating system, and the other everything else _ including the
company's Web browser, word processing and spreadsheet software and
Internet properties.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also includes a range of restrictions on conduct
that would stay in place a short time if the breakup is implemented
and a longer time if it is not. The key states behind the suit have
been New York, Connecticut, Iowa, California and Wisconsin, and
Spitzer said all of them were strongly behind the joint proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible opponents, attention is centered on Betty D.
Montgomery, the attorney general of Ohio, and the two other
Republicans among the 19: Carla J. Stovall of Kansas and Jim Ryan
of Illinois. Other state officials said the three attorneys general
had been opposed to the majority view, but that could not be
confirmed. All three offices declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General J. Joseph Curran Jr. of Maryland has also
expressed public doubts about breaking up Microsoft. But his
office, too, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has made it clear that he would prefer to have a
single proposal from the plaintiffs but would accept a second
opinion if the federal government and the majority of the states
could not agree. He has never expressed an interest in receiving a
minority opinion from the states.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Microsoft has made much of divisions between the
partners in the lawsuit. The company blamed disagreements between
state and federal officials for the breakdown of settlement talks
early this month _ a charge all of the government officials denied.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a letter to Microsoft shareholders this month, William H.
Gates, Microsoft's chairman, wrote, ``The Department of Justice and
the states could not agree among themselves on what they should
seek from Microsoft, rendering a settlement all but impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiations with the holdout attorneys general
continued, Spitzer railed at Microsoft's leaders for recent public
statements and said they reinforced the view that remedies intended
to modify Microsoft's conduct were unlikely to work.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, both Gates and Steven A. Ballmer,
Microsoft's chief executive, have said in interviews that the
company ``has done absolutely nothing wrong,'' as Gates put it, and
has no intention of changing its business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said: ``Implicit in a conduct remedy is the notion that
the individual understands the nature of his misconduct and will
abide by the structure of the remedies that are imposed. But when
you see these statements that fundamentally reject the ruling of
the court, I am hard pressed to see how a conduct remedy would
work.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, said: ``We believe our
responses have been consistent from Day 1 of this lawsuit to today
_ that our actions are good for consumers and good for competition.
If new rules come into play after this decision has been reviewed
by the court of appeals, we will abide by them. But in the
meantime, this decision is yet to be reviewed, and we think we have
a strong case for appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   As the plaintiffs were concluding their consultations Thursday,
four leading academic economists filed a long and detailed legal
brief with the trial judge in the case, Thomas Penfield Jackson,
arguing that remedies that simply modify Microsoft's conduct do not
make sense from an economic point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The economists have no direct connection with Microsoft or the
government in this case. They are William D. Nordhaus of Yale
University, Roger G. Noll of Stanford, F. Michael Scherer of
Harvard and Robert E. Litan of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   They say ``this case provides an important test of how antitrust
law and remedies should be applied in the `new economy''' and add
that conduct remedies ``would be the least disruptive of all the
options'' but are also ``the least likely to remedy the core
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The economists say the proposed state-federal remedy is the
minimum that is required but add that it fails to break the Windows
monopoly. They call for ``monopoly dissolution'' by splitting the
operating system company into three competing entities.
</P>
<P>
   Litan, a former senior Justice Department official, organized
the effort to prepare the brief, and its recommendation is the one
he has been making in public for months.
</P>
</TEXT>
