<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUGGENHEIM-CONCEPTUAL     04-27 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUGGENHEIM-CONCEPTUAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING ART AS A MOMENT TO BE SEIZED AND X-RAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conceptual art, with its emphasis on language, ideas
and performance rather than fixed visual imagery, is nothing if not
ephemeral. Its best friend is the still or video camera, which
records and saves it for posterity. When Conceptual art came along
in the 1960s, with its idealistic aim of emphasizing art as notion
or process rather than product, Conceptual photography naturally
sprang up as its handmaiden. Both joined the more traditional
categories of painting, sculpture, printmaking and such as part of
the contemporary art repertory.
</P>
<P>
   In the show ``Postmedia: Conceptual Photography in the
Guggenheim Museum's Permanent Collection,'' the museum considers
the ways in which the cool Conceptualist radicals of the '60s and
'70s used photography to ``extend and transgress'' the boundaries
of more conventional art. The words in quotation marks are those of
Nancy Spector, curator of contemporary art at the Guggenheim, who
assembled this well-displayed show of works by 12 artists. Some are
part of the big Conceptual and Minimalist haul acquired in 1990
from the Italian collector Giuseppe Panza di Buomo; others are more
recent acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   As classified by Spector, the categories in the show include the
use of photography to record ephemeral or durational events; to
document art created outside gallery confines; to show the serial
patterns created by architecture and industry; to capture
performance and body art; and to make connections between image and
text. Like a festival of old films, the exhibition brings back some
classics of the era, from Joseph Kosuth's and Robert Barry's
explorations into the linguistic basis of art to the performer
Marina Abramovic's aggressive attacks on her own body as a kind of
spiritual purgation.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, despite the unkind views of some critics who
dismiss Conceptual art as more to be read than looked at, this is a
useful exhibition. Some of the work seems even more boring and
obsessive-compulsive today than it did back then, notably the
anti-object ``Duration'' and ``Location'' pieces of Douglas Huebler
(1924-1997), in which actions or events were mapped out in terms of
stated time frames. (In a 1970 project carried out in Paris, a
multi-part walk of one hour's duration as measured by Greenwich
Mean Time was documented by 12 photographs; each leg of the walk
was accomplished in half the time of that preceding it, starting
with a stroll of 30 minutes and ending in one lasting .0087
seconds.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, several works by the Dutch artist Jan Dibbets
are arrestingly visual, among them ``The Shortest Day of 1970
Photographed in My House Every Six Minutes.'' Mounted in a
filmstrip format, the photographs, taken from a fixed point through
the windows of his house, show the progress of the day in terms of
light from dawn to the descent of darkness, a majestic process that
only a camera could narrate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smithson (1938-1973), best known for his rugged site
piece ``Spiral Jetty'' (1970), a man-made curlicue of rocks and
earth in a remote corner of the Great Salt Lake in Utah made
viewable through film and photographs, is represented here by two
lesser endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   One that seems today to have a high quotient of so-whatness is
``Yucatan Mirror Displacement'' (1969), involving the installation
of foot-square mirrors at various sites on the Yucatan peninsula to
give different twists to the landscape, shown here in a series of
photographs that accompanied a fantastical travelogue Smithson
wrote for the magazine Artforum of that year.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting is his witty ``Hotel Palenque'' (1969), an
informal slide talk on a run-down tourist hostelry in Palenque,
Mexico, that was in a simultaneous state of decay and
rehabilitation. In his discourse, given to students at the
University of Utah in 1972 and replayed here, Smithson, in whose
art the notion of entropy played a crucial role, examines the
crumbling structure as if it were a Mayan ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural critiques were also made by Gordon Matta-Clark
(1943-1978) and Dan Graham. Operating on a grand scale, Matta-Clark
sliced up abandoned buildings as a form of social-architectural
protest. Among his several works here is ``Conical Intersect''
(1975), an attack on urban gentrification by means of a huge gaping
circle cut through two adjacent 17th-century buildings near the
Pompidou Center in Paris. This grand sculptural gesture, if you
will, is memorialized in photographs of a view of the hole and the
streetscape seen through it. But it and other photographs can only
hint at the disorienting experience of actually entering one of the
artist's deconstructions.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graham's quarrel with architecture focused on the white
Bauhaus cube that he saw as the source of a sterile seriality in
the American landscape and its reverberations in Minimalist
sculpture. In ``Back Porches, Marin County CA/`Ziggurat' Skyscraper
N.Y.'' (1974 and 1967) he juxtaposed the cookie-cutter repetition
of contemporary row housing with that of windows on the facade of a
New York skyscraper, a comment on the conforming formalism of an
architecture increasingly less responsive to the human need for
idiosyncracy.
</P>
<P>
   In true Conceptual spirit was the work of Ana Mendieta
(1948-1985), a Cuban exile who brought Afro-Cuban and Santeria
ritual into more secular pursuits like Earthworks and performance
art. In her ``Silueta'' series (1973-1980) done in Iowa and Mexico,
Mendieta left traces of her own body on earth materials: bowers of
flowers, mud, tree branches and such, as seen in a group of
poignant photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Even more body-conscious than Mendieta was the dyed-in-the-wool
Conceptual artist Vito Acconci, whose ``Conversions II: Insistence,
Adaptation, Groundwork, Display'' (1971), documents a willful
feminization of himself by concealing his genitals between his
legs, the better to experience a genderless identity. A far cry
from these concerns is the Wordsworthian work of the English
long-distance walkers Richard Long and Hamish Fulton, two of the
most usual suspects in any Conceptual show, whose perambulations
over the globe are chronicled here in photographs.
</P>
<P>
   By no means a full-blown show of Conceptual photography, which
would have to include a much larger cast, ``Postmedia'' (not a
winner as a title) will do as an introduction to an art that still
raises questions of what art is about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
