<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AUTO AMNESTY
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed a bill allowing owners of some two million
American-registered cars brought illegally into Mexico to register
them in Mexico, for a fee. The bill awaits Senate consideration.
President Ernesto Zedillo criticized lawmakers who voted for the
law as pandering to owners of illegal vehicles two months before
general elections. But his government recently decreed a similar
measure legalizing American-registered pickup trucks, most owned by
governing-party supporters.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: POSSIBLE BERENSON REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Without promising to release her from prison, the opposition
presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo held open the possibility
of a legal appeal for Lori Berenson, the American convicted four
years ago of helping the Tupac Amaru group. In New York, Toledo
said that under judicial reforms he favors, Berenson's lawyers
would be allowed to present evidence that she was judged unfairly.
Berenson's parents say she was convicted in a sham proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CONTEST TO LEAD RIGHTIST PARTY WIDENS
</P>
<P>
   Tom Long, a conservative strategist from Canada's most populous
province, Ontario, joined the race for the leadership of the new
opposition conservative party, the Canadian Alliance. Long promised
to cut taxes as part of a campaign to reverse Canada's brain drain
to the United States. The first round of balloting for party
members is June 24.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: HESELTINE BOWS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Michael Heseltine, 67, the high-profile Conservative politician
who served as deputy prime minister under John Major from 1995 to
1997 but never fulfilled his fierce ambition for the premiership
itself, will not run for reelection next year after 35 years in
parliament. Known as ``Tarzan'' for his flowing hair and robust
oratory, Heseltine led the 1990 Tory revolt that toppled Margaret
Thatcher but then failed in his bid to succeed her.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: LOCKERBIE TRIAL NEXT WEEK
</P>
<P>
   A court set May 3 as the opening date for the trial of two
Libyans accused in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing 270 people. Prosecutors had asked for more time
to study new plans presented by the defense, but the judges
refused, noting the trial was postponed twice before. The Lybians
will be tried under Scottish law in the Dutch city of Zeist.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TALKS ON HOME RULE
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers of Britain and Ireland, Tony Blair and
Bertie Ahern, will meet next week in London with Northern Ireland's
Catholic and Protestant political leaders in what a 10 Downing
Street spokesman called an ``intensification'' of the effort to
gain agreement on restoring home-rule government to Belfast.
Britain suspended the power-sharing assembly in February, blaming
the Irish Republican Army's failure to begin disarming.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: REFORMIST CANDIDATE HOLDS LEAD
</P>
<P>
   The reformist presidential candidate favored by political party
leaders, Ahmet Necdet Sezer, finished far ahead of other candidates
in the first ballot in Parliament, but fell short of the necessary
two-thirds majority. He is still considered likely to be chosen. A
second ballot is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: GEARING FOR KEY VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Designated-Prime Minister Giuliano Amato stressed economic
growth in a speech before parliament in anticipation of Friday's
confidence vote. He did not mention the environment, a sensitive
topic since one Green leader, former Environment Minister Edo
Ronchi, declined on Wednesday to enter Amato's reshuffled cabinet
after the environment post was awarded to another party. Approval
of Amato's government hangs on a few votes.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: NEW NUCLEAR DEATH
</P>
<P>
   A second person died in Japan's worst-ever nuclear accident,
eight months after a chain reaction spun out of control at a
uranium-processing plant. The victim, Masato Shinohara, was one of
several plant workers who were manually feeding uranium into
equipment used illegally to increase productivity. At least 439
people were exposed to dangerous radiation levels. The other
fatality was also a plant worker.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: NO PAROLE FOR RESEARCHER
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government rejected a request for medical parole for
a Chinese-born Stanford University researcher who has been jailed
in Beijing since 1998 on charges of revealing military secrets, a
Hong Kong human rights group said. Hua Di, a former Chinese weapons
scientist who is serving a 15-year prison term, has a rare form of
male breast cancer. A Beijing Court recently ordered that Hua be
retried, saying that his conviction was based on ``unclear facts.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: WITHDRAWAL COSTS
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal from southern Lebanon and redeployment along
its northern border will cost about $250 million, a senior Israeli
official said. That does not include the cost of relocating and
compensating officers of the Israeli-backed South Lebanese army,
said Amos Yaron, director general of the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: PHOTOGRAPHER HELD
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press photographer was arrested after police said
he matched the description of a person seen leaving the scene of a
firebombing at the country's only independent daily newspaper. A
lawyer for the photographer, Obed Zilwa of South Africa, said his
client heard the blast, went to investigate and then went to his
hotel to fetch his cameras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
