<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9228 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GIULIANI'S NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time when politicians didn't talk about
illness. When President Grover Cleveland discovered he had cancer
of the jaw, he kept it secret by having the surgery performed in a
yacht bobbing off the coast of Massachusetts. John Kennedy always
denied he had Addison's disease.
</P>
<P>
   People in public life never acknowledged cancer. Even if they
succumbed, funeral homes tried to avoid giving the newspapers a
cause of death. People were terrified of it, and there was a
suspicion that the disease, or at least the bad luck of having
caught it, might be contagious.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's less likely to be concealed than liposuction. When Rudy
Giuliani called a press conference Thursday to report that he had
prostate cancer, City Comptroller Alan Hevesi quickly responded
with some reminiscences about his own surgery last year. A
prominent upstate Republican county executive called the mayor's
office to talk about his recent course of radiation treatment.
Giuliani said he'd already reached out to the Yankees' manager, Joe
Torre, another high-profile survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer, the bane of middle-aged males, is a
particularly curable, and common, affliction among public
personages. If you put all the well-known prostate cancer survivors
in one place, you'd have a celebrity golf tour. ``It's Bob Dole,
it's Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf,'' said Hevesi.
</P>
<P>
   There's every reason to hope that the mayor will be fine. He
seemed strong and in good spirits at his press conference Thursday.
``It's at a very, very early stage of the disease,'' he said, in a
very, very Giuliani comment. Lest the press corps suspect he was
softening, he took time out to denounce the Civil Rights Commission
_ a current critic of the city Police Department _ as ``an
embarrassment'' and ``a big joke.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't follow the now-standard political route of
insisting that the disease would be nothing more than a minor
divergence in his life. He declined to vow that he would stay in
the race for the U.S. Senate. ``I think that my focus right now has
to be to figure out the best form of treatment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who get cancer have a chance to deal with it in
private first. Hevesi, who intends to run for mayor himself next
year, had worked out a plan of treatment with his doctors before he
held a press conference to simultaneously announce that he was
sick, that he was going to be fine, and that his career would go on
as usual. Giuliani had no sooner gotten his diagnosis than he was
spotted by a reporter at the hospital, and it took only one news
cycle before he was forced to let the whole world in on his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mayor has seemed off his game lately. He abruptly
canceled engagements with the ever-sensitive upstate Republicans in
order to go to the Yankees' home opener. He failed to visit the
family of a powerful politician whose father had died, and made
matters way, way worse by faxing a sympathy note. He seemed caught
off guard when his wife, an actress, announced she was taking a
part in ``The Vagina Monologues.'' He went over the top in his
comments on Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like this kind of diagnosis to jolt the
subconscious, sending it careening off into new territory.
Giuliani, whose father died of prostate cancer, knew that the
results of his earlier tests had been iffy. On some level he must
have been trying to decide whether this Senate race is something he
really wants.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, despite his new standing as a no-longer-certain
candidate, the mayor seemed more intent on the campaign than he has
in weeks. He said he would be going through with a series of events
in upstate New York and a televised town hall meeting. He's going
to meet with the loopy state Independence Party, which is seeking a
candidate to endorse in November. The ad people are shooting
footage for more commercials.
</P>
<P>
   He's a feisty guy, and pushing ahead would be the typical
feisty-guy scenario. Politicians are supposed to keep moving ever
upward. As mayor, Giuliani is term-limited, and when one door
closes, you're supposed to grab for the next opening. But this bad
news may offer him an opportunity to decide if the Senate is where
he really wants to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
