<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BEACH-HOUSE-TEXAS-HNS     04-27 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-HOUSE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREE'S BEACHFRONT HOME PLUNGES HER INTO LEGAL FIGHT AGAINST
TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ The owner of a resort house that ended up on
the public beach because of a tropical storm's erosion says she
will fight the state's efforts to make her move it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my attorney to tell them to go to hell in a bucket,''
retired real estate agent Jane Ebrom said Thursday. ``He is going
to counter their proposals. I'm not going to spend another dime on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebrom, who lives in nearby League City, said she can't afford to
comply with Attorney General John Cornyn's request that she move
the house off the beach within a year. It was left there because of
heavy erosion from Tropical Storm Francis in September 1998, less
than a year after she bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrom said the Attorney General's Office has asked her to
reimburse the state $56,000 in legal costs. She said she already
has spent $14,000 complying with state demands that she remove a
bulkhead under the house and other materials from her property.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Brown, a spokeswoman for Cornyn, said the removal and
reimbursement are parts of a new proposal sent to Ebrom's attorney
as a possible settlement of a lawsuit. Cornyn's office sued for
removal of the house in an Austin court in October, Ebrom said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, Cornyn said Ebrom's three-bedroom, two-bath
house in the Spanish Grant subdivision blocks public access to the
beach, Ebrom said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Gulf waters do creep all the way under her deck at high
tide, forcing people to pass under her home if they want to proceed
along the beach. Ebrom said she has had problems with people going
upstairs onto her deck.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrom's is one of more than 100 beachfront homes the Texas
General Land Office determined to be on the public beach after the
1998 storm's high tides and battering waves chewed away at the
Brazoria and Galveston county shorelines for two days. Under the
Texas Open Beaches Act, a structure is considered to be on the
public beach and subject to a state lawsuit for removal if erosion
leaves it seaward of the natural vegetation line.
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 Open Beaches Act was designed to give the public
unfettered access to Texas beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Ebrom is the only owner Cornyn's office has sued for
removal of a beach home.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners have moved other homes that were undermined by the
storm. Many homes remain partially on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Since Francis struck, Ebrom said, the vegetation line has crept
back seaward to the point where only about half of her house is on
the public beach.
</P>
<P>
   Until Francis struck, she said, she was able to rent the house
for $1,500 a week when she and her family weren't using it.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrom said it would cost $50,000 or more to move the house and
more than that to buy another lot. Despite her experience, she said
she would want another first-row lot, which would have the greatest
exposure to erosive storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an addiction,'' she said. ``Once you've had a
front-row lot, are you really going to be content to look at
someone else's back?''
</P>
<P>
   Ebrom said she paid $40,000 for the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought it for my grandbaby and for an eventual retirement
home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really feel it's a true invasion,'' she said of
Cornyn's proposal. ``They say this is in the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
