<SLUG> BC-HKN-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR TUNES OUT TAUNTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Since his arrest March 8, Stars goalie Ed
Belfour has eight victories, 345 saves and a big hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has been a target in opposing arenas forever, but his
arrest on suspicion of assault and resisting arrest last month at
The Mansion on Turtle Creek has provided opposing fans with new
ammunition. He has had to deflect as many jokes as pucks since.
</P>
<P>
   Do you hear what he hears?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty focused on the game itself, and I don't pay too
much attention to what is going on in the crowds,'' Belfour said
yesterday. ``I think it's just part of being a goalie. It's always
been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Western Conference quarterfinals in Edmonton, Belfour
had the last laugh with a 4-3 victory in Game 4 that allowed the
Stars to wrap up the best-of-seven series three nights later in
Dallas. Belfour gave up 11 goals and made 102 saves in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything worse than it was in Edmonton,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``If he can get by that scene in
Edmonton, he can get by anything. The whole atmosphere was almost
at times chaotic. It was volatile. It was emotional. He handled it
with no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, San Jose could be worse.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour knows the way to San Jose. He also knows the way out of
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour took advantage of free agency in 1997 and fled the
struggling Sharks for a chance to play for a contender. He rejected
a three-year, $10.5 million deal from the Sharks, who had
surrendered three players to acquire him at the trade deadline.
Instead, he called the Stars and offered to take $500,000 less to
play in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks fans have never forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans in San Jose have always been really loud
there and really support their team,'' said Belfour, who was 3-9 in
his short stint with the Sharks. ``Every time I've come back there,
they've always been hard on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour is 4-6-1 against the Sharks since coming to Dallas,
including 1-3 this season. He played in only one of three games at
San Jose Arena this season, a 5-2 loss on April 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have a challenge ahead of him to see if he can
maintain his competitive focus on the road,'' Hitchcock said. ``For
us to win in San Jose, he has to be a key player. That's a
challenge he will have to meet head on.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, 35, is hoping to hear only the sound of silence next
week when the series moves to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely makes it more satisfying when you have good
games in buildings where the fans are really on you,'' he said. ``I
like challenges, and I like to play my best in those types of
games.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
