A9244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MAGAZINE-CLOSE-NYT &LR;      04-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-CLOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACHETTE WILL CLOSE MIRABELLA MAGAZINE WITH JUNE ISSUE  
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jack Kliger, the chief executive of Hachette
Filipacchi Magazines, announced Thursday that he would close
Mirabella magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabella is aimed at women who are no longer 24 years old and
who care passionately about literary criticism and serious articles
about, say, contemporary philosophers _ and equally as passionately
about where to buy adorable hot-pink flared leather pants.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, there may not be enough women in the world who
care about both contemporary philosophers and hot-pink leather
pants to guarantee a magazine's success.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the staff and in a statement released Thursday,
Kliger cited the continuing lack of advertiser support as the
reason for closing the magazine. The last issue will be dated
June/July.
</P>
<P>
   The demise had been long rumored at the magazine, most ardently
since early 1999, when Hachette reduced the magazine's publication
schedule from monthly to 10 times a year. Several staff members
have resigned recently, including the magazine's publisher, who was
never replaced _ a signal to staff members, several of them said
earlier this week, that the magazine would be folded. This week,
staff members lunched had lunch together and speculated about how
many weekly cycles they had left on their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine employs about 40 people. Hachette is offering
severance packages that editorial employees described as
surprisingly generous; the company is also trying to place the
employees in other Hachette magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's editor in chief since April 1997, Roberta Myers,
did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabella's first issue appeared in May 1989, but the origins of
the magazine date to 1988, when Grace Mirabella _ who had been one
of the most powerful editors of women's magazines _ was dismissed
as editor in chief of Vogue. After Mirabella left Vogue, Rupert
Murdoch asked her to create a magazine. The magazine did not make
money for News Corp., nor did it turn a profit after Hachette
purchased it in 1995. Hachette is a unit of Lagardere.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabella's advertising pages and revenue have both dropped
dramatically in the last year. Ad pages have declined 48.8 percent
from 134 pages between January and March of 1999 to 68.6 pages for
the first three months of this year, according to the Publishers
Information Bureau. Revenue is down by 43 percent for the same
period, from a reported $5.5 million to $3.1 million, the bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not lack of advertising alone that led to Mirabella's
demise. The magazine has been dwarfed in the last year by the
success of other women's magazines, such as Meredith Corp.'s More
magazine, a monthly beauty and fashion title also aimed at older
women and that has a more single-minded editorial voice.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabella's newsstand sales have dropped dramatically in recent
months. For the six-month period ended Dec. 31, 1999, newsstand
sales _ often considered the best measure of a magazine's vitality
and its ability to capture consumer attention _ dropped by 39
percent, to an average of 80,790 copies a month from an average of
134,292 a month, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations. The
magazine had not raised its rate base _ the circulation guaranteed
to advertisers _ since 1995, and circulation had not moved from
about 550,000 since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising executives said that the editorial mix of the
magazine was never coherent. Roberta Garfinkle, director of print
advertising at McCann-Erickson, said that she was not surprised
Hachette was closing the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It vacillated between being a serious journalistic magazine, a
serious read, and a beauty and fashion magazine, and first it was
older, then it was younger, then it was a combination thereof,''
she said. ``For lack of desire or interest, and I do not know
which, Hachette was never able to invest the money or the time to
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Garfinkle also added that the marketing dollars that Hachette
has invested in George ate away at Mirabella's chances for
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hachette decided that with the money invested in George they
cannot be all things to all people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview earlier this week, Kliger said of his investing
in George magazine: ``I don't think our other children feel
neglected. Each one of them will have their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirabella, who still retains the title of founder on the
Mirabella masthead, said Thursday that she was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A magazine has to have a focus and stay with it,'' she said.
``I don't think you can dilute it or water down its vision, and
that is what happened.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
