<SLUG> BC-IVOR-RIDLEY-SCOTT-DIRECTS-GLADIATOR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDLEY SCOTT REBUILDS THE ROMAN EMPIRE FOR `GLADIATOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Ridley Scott
directing scenes from ``Gladiator.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In a Hollywood that thrives on the assembly-line production of
standardized mediocrity, Ridley Scott takes chances.
 &HT;    His flair for stunning visual imagery and his knack for casting
has earned the director a cult following for such films as the
original ``Alien'' (l979), ``Blade Runner'' (l982) and ``Thelma and
Louise'' (l991). And at 62 he's still taking risks _ he's soon to
tackle ``Hannibal,'' the controversial sequel to ``The Silence of
the Lambs'' (l991).
 &HT;    But his current film may be his biggest gamble, as he turns back
the clock to Hollywood's toga-and-sandals era for his new, $100
million epic, ``Gladiator,'' which will open May 5.
 &HT;    At the center of this extravagant, spectacular and at times even
elegant movie is Australian actor Russell Crowe, who plays Maximus,
a Roman general sold into slavery by his enemies and forced to
become a human killing machine to survive ... and to seek revenge
on those who murdered his wife and child.
 &HT;    The British-born Scott, with a mop of untidy ginger hair and a
graying beard, sits in a suite at Los Angeles' Century Plaza Hotel,
puffing on a fat cigar and looking rumpled after a long day of
interviews. Outwardly, at least, he seems unconcerned about how
audiences will respond to his vision of the greatest empire of them
all.
 &HT;    Gladiator movies enjoy a somewhat-less-than-exalted place in
Hollywood history. It's been 35 years since the genre died a
natural death, strangled by its own grandiosity. In recent years,
Biblical and historical epics have been primarily relegated to the
less-prestigious terrain of network miniseries and cable movies.
 &HT;    But Scott says he has fond memories of a childhood spent
watching those dust-and-glory sagas in his northern-England
hometown of Northumberland.
 &HT;    ```Spartacus' was 40 years ago,'' he says, ``and `Ben-Hur'
before that. Those movies were part of my cinema-going youth, but
at the dawn of a new millennium I thought this might be the ideal
time to revisit what may have been the most important period of the
last 2,000 years, if not in all of recorded history _ the apex and
the beginning of the decline of the greatest military and political
power the world has ever known.''
 &HT;    Scott, whose dark, apocalyptic ``Blade Runner'' is, for its
fans, the definitive vision of the future, is hoping that
``Gladiator'' will do the same for the past, imposing a sense of
realistic depth on the glory that was Rome.
 &HT;    His secret weapon in that effort is Crowe, best known for his
Oscar-nominated role as the paunchy, middle-aged title character in
``The Insider'' (l999) and as a maverick Los Angeles cop in ``L.A.
Confidential'' (l997).
 &HT;    Actually, Mel Gibson was Scott's first choice _ ``I'm too old
for the part, mate,'' Gibson reportedly told him. But Crowe dropped
50 pounds to become the lean, mean Roman fighting machine Scott
needed to play Maximus. Most important, perhaps, is that the
Australian actor has the chops to play the role without the stagey
histrionics that marred so many earlier Hollywood epics.
 &HT;    Another piece of offbeat casting was Scott's choice of Joaquin
Phoenix to play the evil, foppish Emperor Commodus, who takes the
Roman throne after throttling his aged father Marcus Aurelius
(Richard Harris).
 &HT;    If neither actor is whom you'd think of first for the role _ or
whom they'd think of, since Scott reports that, ``When we offered
him the part, the most surprised person was Joaquin himself'' _
chances are it will work out. Scott has long been known for his eye
for up-and-coming actors.
 &HT;    After all, he was the one who cast Sigourney Weaver in her
career-making role as Lt. Ripley in ``Alien.'' When he was looking
for a young actor to play a raffish hitchhiker in ``Thelma and
Louise,'' he picked an new face named Brad Pitt.
 &HT;    The Oscar-nominated Crowe is hardly in the ``unknown'' category,
but Scott says he's had his eye on him ever since the Australian
actor starred in ``Romper Stomper'' (l992) as an ultra-violent,
neo-Nazi skinhead.
 &HT;    ``When I see a good performance,'' Scott says, ``I think I'll
work with that person at some point. And sometimes they go away and
sometimes they keep coming. Russell keeps coming _ he's a big star,
and this part could easily have swamped him. But it didn't. He's a
very smart man.''
 &HT;    Crowe already has a reputation for being a perfectionist who can
drive directors to distraction, and Scott admits that he and the
actor had their ups and downs during filming.
 &HT;    Which, he says, was fine with him.
 &HT;    ``We're both similar down-to-earth, no-bull guys,'' he says.
``And I don't mind the perfectionism as long as it's for all the
right reasons, which his are. The nicest thing of all is that he
loves the finished movie.''
 &HT;    The film has an extraordinary visual sumptuousness. Scott's army
of craftsmen used state-of-the-art computer graphics, while his set
designers journeyed to the island nation of Malta to re-create
Rome's legendary Colosseum for the arena scenes. The film literally
had a cast of thousands, with 2,000 extras being
computer-supplemented by another 33,000.
 &HT;    Scott's background in design _ he was among the first of a
generation of directors who came from backgrounds in the visual
arts or advertising rather than from theater or movies _ serves
this film particularly well. A graduate of London's Royal College
of Art, he began by directing television commercials before making
his movie debut with the eye-catching, stylish ``The Duellists''
(l977).
 &HT;    In l984 he returned to advertising to direct one of the most
talked-about commercials of all time, ``1984,'' a George
Orwell-inspired ad which heralded the arrival of Apple's MacIntosh
computer. Shown only once, during the Super Bowl, it remains
influential to this day.
 &HT;    Like most directors, Scott has had his spotty periods, including
the Tom Cruise fantasy ``Legend'' (l985), the Japanese cop drama
``Black Rain'' (1989), the Columbus movie ``1492: Conquest of
Paradise'' (l992) and ``G.I. Jane'' (l997), which starred Demi
Moore as the first female Navy SEAL.
 &HT;    Still, Scott is a one-of-a-kind director, and expectations are
high for ``Hannibal.'' The task of taking over from Jonathan Demme,
who directed ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' was bound to be a
thankless one _ the original won Oscars for Best Actor (Anthony
Hopkins), Best Actress (Jodie Foster), Best Picture and Best
Director _ but if anyone can do it, Hollywood insiders say, Scott
might be the one.
 &HT;    The job got even more challenging, however, when Foster decided
to pass on reprising her role as FBI Agent Clarice Starling. Though
Hopkins will be back as that attractive nasty Hannibal Lecter, the
role of Clarice will be filled instead by Julianne Moore.
 &HT;    ``I think two things happened with Jodie,'' Scott says. ``She
suddenly got a film going she had wanted to direct for some time _
or maybe she thought she didn't want to go back to where she was 10
years ago. That's fair enough, and I respect it.''
 &HT;    The Hollywood rumor mill says that Foster also disliked Thomas
Harris' novel and didn't think it would make a good movie. Scott
doesn't entirely disagree, and notes that he and the reclusive
Harris have already spent a considerable amount of time working on
the script.
 &HT;    ``We weren't quite happy with a few things,'' the director says,
``including the final act. Harris spent nine years writing this
book, so we all sat down for five days _ because his mind is a
filing cabinet of information _ until we had a script we were happy
with.
 &HT;    ``Tom was very open about everything and said, `I know it's 600
pages and must be distilled to 110 pages.' And that's what we've
done.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Gladiator,'' consult the
official Web site at www.gladiator-thefilm.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
