<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-DODGERS28-     04-27 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-DODGERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves achieve The Perfect Stand
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surely, there have been better and more critical
homestands. England in World War II, for instance. Yet in a purely
baseball sense, this was The Perfect Stand.
</P>
<P>
   Perfection that strained credulity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say you can't sweep a nine-game homestand,'' insisted
Braves president Stan Kasten. ''It can't be done. I don't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ya gotta believe.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on for a 6-3 victory over Los Angeles on Thursday, the
Braves completed their most successful homestand ever, sweeping
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh and the Dodgers in three game sets.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Milwaukee, the Braves swept seven-game homestands in
1963 and '65. These Braves, in winning their 10th straight overall
and team record 11th in a row at home, became the first
major-league team to go unbeaten in a homestand of at least nine
games since May 1993, when the Dodgers also went 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   ''An unbelievable homestand,'' manager Bobby Cox said after a
third straight strong start from Terry Mulholland, a three-run home
run from Chipper Jones and another ninth-inning high-wire escape by
John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are unbeaten since Rocker came off the suspended list
and are three games short of the team record for consecutive
victories. Atlanta won 13 straight in 1982 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''Awesome,'' said Chipper Jones, whose 444-foot, three-run homer
off Chan Ho Park in the sixth inning guaranteed an enjoyable flight
to San Diego, where the Braves open a six-game road trip tonight.
''It's so hard to put together winning streaks like this in this
day and age. You're always going to run into someone's ace who
might stick it to you. We treaded on some thin ice, but things just
seem to be working out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta outscored the opposition 47-19 during the homestand,
hitting 11 homers and batting .286 while holding the Phillies,
Pirates and Dodgers to a collective .199. The Braves have trailed
for just 12 of 89 innings during their 10-game winning streak,
which began with Mulholland's 2-1 win April 16 in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish this stuff could go on forever,'' said Mulholland, who
earned his third win in the streak by working six shutout innings
before giving up a Kevin Elster homer in the seventh. After Kerry
Ligtenberg was battered in the eighth, Mulholland watched Rocker
load the bases in the ninth before striking out the side.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spent a few years with Mitch Williams in Philadelphia,''
Mulholland said. ''When he came in the game, (pitching coach)
Johnny Podres and I would look at each other and open our palms,
like, it's out of our hands. I'm not going to get any more gray
hairs over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Not during The Perfect Stand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
