<HEADLINE>
BLISTER PROBLEM LIMITS CHAN HO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Los Angeles Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park felt the
presence of his blister on every curveball he threw during a
bullpen session a few days ago and he took that memory to the mound
on Thursday against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And, eventually, Atlanta took it to Park in a 6-3 win at Turner
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Park said he worried how the blister on his right middle finger
would react every time he threw a curve. So he didn't throw many in
the first few innings, instead relying on a fastball and changeup.
It caused him to aim the ball, Park said, which worried him about a
new blister forming.
</P>
<P>
   Which neatly explains why Park (3-2) lasted 5 innings, getting
pulled after allowing a 444-foot three-run homer to Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're limited to two pitches, and he wasn't throwing his
curveball very sharply because (the blister) was still bothering
him, it kind of limits how you're going to attack guys,'' Dodgers
catcher Chad Kreuter said. ``He wasn't as sharp as he could be
because of the blister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer his finger is still bothering him. He was
out there battling, but you have a wounded soldier out there
battling.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the long ball that did in Park but rather the
seven walks that tied a career high. Park threw 54 strikes and 55
balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't throw a good curveball, but I'm not suppose to be
thinking about that,'' Park said. ``Obviously, it felt different,
which is normal with new skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Little new damage was done to the blistered area and Park is
slated to make his next start.
</P>
<P>
   __ Catching progress: Neither Todd Hundley nor Chad Kreuter have
thrown out a runner attempting to steal. All 15 were successful
against Hundley, and Kreuter is 0 for 2. But Dodgers pitchers have
picked off four, and with the numbers down markedly from last
season, manager Davey Johnson said he's pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we haven't been able to throw anybody out, in my
book we've thrown about four of them out,'' Johnson said. ``They
haven't been stealing them on the catcher. Hundley's throwing the
ball down there in 1.9 (seconds). Where that was broke, that's
fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad day, mate: Lefty Jeff Williams' velocity was down and he
wasn't getting the same reaction with his curveball he did last
season, and now the Dodgers know why. Williams, an Australian
native who had an 18.00 ERA in a brief stint with Dodgers this
season, has a weakness in his pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won't be able to pitch for a minimum of two weeks
because his hand will be in a splint. It further complicates the
Dodgers' left-handed situation in the bullpen. Williams and Onan
Masaoka are the only two lefties in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Dodgers utility player F.P. Santangelo is 1
for 13 this season, but he's not ready to panic since this is a
typical start. He began last season 1 for 14 and finished with a
.260 average. . . . The Braves have a 10-game winning streak,
ending their nine-game homestand undefeated. The last NL team to go
9-0 on a homestand was the Dodgers, who did it May 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
