<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH-McCAIN MEETING ON ROCKY GROUND 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A much-touted meeting between George W. Bush and
defeated Republican rival John McCain, which could prove important
to Bush's presidential bid, is now iffy, a McCain spokesman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign said it believes that the meeting,
initially scheduled for May 9 in Pittsburgh, can be salvaged,
despite a dispute over its focus.
</P>
<P>
   Top aides to Bush and McCain were scheduled to meet Friday in
Washington to try to work out differences between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would confirm or deny a report in the online news
service Salon.com that McCain had ordered the meeting scrubbed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain reportedly reacted after reading a column by political
commentator Robert Novak, in which some Bush advisers complained
that McCain would make demands on Bush before endorsing him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former prisoner of war, was in Vietnam on Thursday to
commemorate the 25th anniversary of the end of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But his spokesman, Todd Harris, said the meeting was ``tenuous''
because it appeared that Bush's main reason for attending was to
discuss whether McCain was interested in being his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a senator from Arizona who fought Bush for several
months for the Republican presidential nomination, has said that he
isn't interested in being vice president. But the Texas governor
announced last week that he would ask McCain in the meeting if he
would consider being his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that any meeting between Senator McCain and Governor
Bush ought to be a substantive one. But in order to have a
substantive meeting, you ought to have a substantive agenda in
advance,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not feel that a meeting to discuss whether Senator
McCain is interested in being vice president _ when everyone knows
that he's not _ should be considered substantive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said that any dispute was ``just
a misunderstanding.'' He said Bush looked forward to a
``substantive discussion of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said the two men would discuss ``how they can work
together on the reforms they agree upon.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strong pitch for significant changes in campaign
finance laws angered many in the Republican establishment. But his
insurgent message appealed to many independent and Democratic
voters, whose support could prove crucial to Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who returned to Austin from a three-day campaign swing
Thursday afternoon, said he was unaware the meeting was considered
in jeopardy. He said he was sure that, sooner or later, he and
McCain would meet and would decide for themselves what to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to think a column could cause a meeting to be
canceled,'' he said, referring to the report about the Novak
column.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, McCain's advisers were
preparing a list of suggested agenda items to propose to the Bush
campaign when the Novak column stirred up controversy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain reportedly wants to discuss campaign finance reform and
Social Security, issues that were dominant in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, the McCain spokesman, said John Weaver, the political
director for McCain's presidential campaign, would meet with Joe
Allbaugh, Bush's campaign manager, Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staff remains in close contact with Senator McCain's
staff,'' McClellan added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
