<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS-NY     04-27 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GIULIANI MUST MAKE POLITICAL AND MEDICAL DECISIONS
CONCURRENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-GIULIANI-CANCER, PROSTATE-CANCER) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The announcement by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on
Thursday that he has been struck with prostate cancer presents him
with a series of pressing medical decisions in the weeks ahead. But
the confluence of Giuliani's diagnosis and the state's election
calendar could force him to make some pivotal decisions about his
Senate candidacy rapidly, and over roughly the same difficult
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Republican Party is meeting in Buffalo on May 30 to
nominate its candidate, presumably Giuliani, to run against Hillary
Rodham Clinton. The mayor has approximately 10 days from then to
accept or decline formally the nomination. Once that is done,
Giuliani is essentially locked in place: Under state election law,
a candidate's name can be removed from the ballot if he or she
moves to another state, is nominated to run for another office, or
dies.
</P>
<P>
   What that means, Giuliani's advisers said, is that if he has any
thoughts about abandoning this race for Senate _ and at his news
conference on Thursday, he made clear that he does have such
thoughts _ he needs to act on them at almost the same time that he
is making decisions about his treatment. That, he estimated, would
take two or three weeks. Given this calendar, that is pretty much
all he has. At this late date, he does not have the luxury of
taking a few months to consider his medical options and then
returning to consider the future of his candidacy before the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And it was far from clear what Giuliani might end up doing as he
faced the difficult task of unweaving this tangle of medical and
political decisions, right in the middle of a searing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's political advisers took steps throughout the day to
battle a growing perception in city political circles that the
medical announcement presaged a decision by Giuliani to step out of
the race. His campaign issued a statement announcing that he would
not cancel any campaign appearances, at least for the next week.
His aides pointed out cases of other candidates who survived
life-threatening illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   One senior adviser volunteered the argument that the image of a
spirited and sympathetic Giuliani, fighting cancer and Clinton
simultaneously, might be the right antidote to the perception of
the mayor as bellicose. And his friends placed unsolicited calls to
reporters to declare that Giuliani was in the race to stay, no
matter how he sounded at his news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this personal challenge will only energize him even
more in his commitment to the race,'' Randy M. Mastro, a former
deputy mayor, said in one such call.
</P>
<P>
   That said, his announcement came at a time when there was
already concern among Republicans, taking note of Giuliani's
low-energy campaigning to date, that the mayor did not really have
his heart in a race that will force him to leave what he has
described as the best job he would ever have.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after the news conference, a number of Republicans
and Democrats had similar responses: This unfortunate turn for
Giuliani could allow him to make a graceful exit from an unwanted
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been lukewarm about making the race from the get-go,''
said Nelson Warfield, former press secretary to Bob Dole, the
Republican presidential candidate who survived prostate cancer.
``Yes, it's a very treatable cancer. It wouldn't require him to
drop out. But for God's sake, the guy has two jobs already, and
fighting cancer is a third.''
</P>
<P>
   Another New York consultant, who asked not to be identified,
said the development ``may be an easy way out if he decides not to
do this without a loss of face.'' The consultant added, ``Everyone
will understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's political aides repeatedly said on Thursday night
that there was little chance the mayor would back out of this race.
``We have a very active campaign schedule for the next seven days,
and the mayor fully intends to keep up that schedule, including
travels to upstate New York,'' said Bruce J. Teitelbaum, Giuliani's
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is a man who keeps his counsel and guards his privacy;
words of confidence from his campaign aides might, to some extent,
represent the hopeful thinking of loyal lieutenants who have been
working so hard on Giuliani's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But the election is still a little more than six months off. And
if the mayor, like Joe Torre, the New York Yankees manager, is able
to opt for surgery alone without other treatment regimens, he could
be fully recovered within two months or so. That timetable still
leaves him months to campaign strenuously, on a shorter schedule in
late summer and fall _ one that the mayor has long preferred, given
that he has full-time duties in the city.
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani was to decide not to make the race, several
Republicans said on Thursday, he should move as fast as possible to
assure that the Republicans can find a strong replacement to run
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, one party leader said, it would probably be best
if the Republicans had a candidate in place for the May 30
convention.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Giuliani will not be able simply to turn over the
$9 million or so he has in campaign funds to someone else; federal
law bars him from contributing any more than $2,000. A new
candidate, should that prove necessary, would have to start raising
funds somewhat from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republicans who were most mentioned on Thursday as
possible Senate candidates _ again, should that prove necessary _
were Rick A. Lazio, the Long Island Republican who has long
threatened to challenge Giuliani in a primary, and Gov. George
Pataki, notwithstanding his remark in December in 1998 that it was
more likely that ``the Hindenburg would come back together'' than
that he would run for Senate. Both men declined to comment, beyond
offering Giuliani their best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Giuliani's announcement encouraged supporters in
both camps to speculate about how his cancer diagnosis might affect
a Clinton-Giuliani contest, even as they acknowledged that those
discussions were in poor taste. Would Clinton now find it more
difficult to attack Giuliani, for example? Would she be better off
running against Giuliani or Lazio?
</P>
<P>
   Would Giuliani's disease prompt upstate Republicans, who have
been increasingly critical of his absence from their parts of the
state, to give him some slack?
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the state of the field should become very clear
very quickly. One senior adviser said Giuliani should know, within
the next week, what kind of treatment would be needed for the
cancer, and whether he would just join the long list of public
figures who have undergone treatment for prostate cancer and than
proceeded with their lives. His advisers are urging Giuliani to
move ahead quickly, to dispel any notion about weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``His head has not changed any about the Senate race at all,''
one associate said. ``This has not changed anything as far as his
thoughts about pursuing the Senate race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-RECORD28-COX     04-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Olympin is CQ
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How much are your Olympic memories worth? Not as much
as Billy Payne's.
</P>
<P>
   The latest batch of Atlanta Olympic records released to the
public Thursday includes an inventory of the $1.5 million William
Porter Payne Collection, a vast assortment of Olympic memorabilia
purchased from Payne by his private foundation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletic Foundation paid Payne, who was its
chairman, $975,000 for the collection. Payne created the nonprofit
foundation in 1987 to bid for the 1996 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   When the foundation bought Payne's collection, it intended to
display it in a major Olympic museum it hoped to build adjacent to
Centennial Olympic Park downtown. The foundation has significantly
scaled back its plans, and now is planning a much smaller exhibit
in a proposed addition to the Atlanta History Center in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's collection includes items collected from the early days
of the bid campaign to the 1996 Summer Games, including obvious
museum pieces such as the torch used in the lighting ceremony in
Athens, Greece, and the lantern used to transport the flame from
Athens to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee members were under fire last
year for accepting extravagant gifts. The inventory shows Payne
received his own share of gifts from many circles, including
national Olympic committees, the IOC and local sponsors and
licensees.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more valuable items, according to the appraisal, are
dozens of one-of-a-kind items presented personally to Payne. They
include the torch the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games
president used to light the cauldron in Los Angeles, valued at
$10,000; the Dream Team jersey worn by Michael Jordan, valued at
$2,500; and a Hanes Centennial Olympic Games T-shirt specially made
for Payne, valued at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are also thousands of items with questionable value to
collectors, such as a huge batch of framed photographs, valued at
an eye-opening $50,000; a thousand Coke lapel pins produced for the
Tokyo vote, valued at $20,000; and Payne's personal collection of
business letters and personal correspondence, assessed at $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic collectibles experts who got their first glimpse of the
inventory Thursday generally said the individual prices are
inflated and the majority of the collection would not even sell on
the open market.
</P>
<P>
   The memorabilia market would be hard pressed to find a buyer who
would pay $500 for three leftover boxes of Payne's business cards,
they suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid O'Neil, the Colorado-based Olympic and sports memorabilia
auctioneer who inventoried Payne's collection, defended her
appraisal Thursday. She praised the completeness of the collection.
``This is a unique situation in that Atlanta has the documentation
from the first idea through the completion of the Games and that
makes a difference,'' she said. ``You should look at the whole
picture. This is an outstanding collection.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the fact that Payne, the head of the organizing
committee, owned the torches, medals and stuffed Whatizits
increases the value of the individual items.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would carry a torch, that torch would be worth the same
as if anybody else paid it,'' she said. ``If somebody like Billy
Payne carried it, that would make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, it's unclear how much those Olympic torches hanging
on walls of torch relay participants all over Atlanta are worth.
Payne's torch collection was worth $78,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Payne had 39 of them. And that raises another
troubling issue for collectors when reviewing this deal. They ask
why many of the items in Payne's collection were his and not the
property of the non-profit group he founded.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Payne sold 25 leather-bound copies of the official
five-volume bid document presented to the IOC. The bid books were
produced by the foundation and paid for from corporate and
individual donations. Why then was Payne entitled to keep the
leftovers and sell them back to the foundation?
</P>
<P>
   Other records in the Olympic archives at the History Center
indicate Payne solicited personal samples of prototype merchandise
from all of ACOG's licensees. Those samples are represented in
volume in the inventory, stashed in cartons of bid bags, T-shirts,
watches, briefcases, Cabbage Patch dolls and jewelry. The
collection also includes a set of 10 sets of jeweled pins designed
to commemorate the countdown to the start of the Games, which were
valued at $320,000.
</P>
<P>
   The records detailing the purchase of the collection were not
released until they were reviewed by an independent law firm this
year. The attorneys concluded the deal was legitimate and violated
no tax laws, according to Ralph Jernigan, president of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy paid a significant amount of taxes on this transaction,
and did not take any tax deductions,'' said Jernigan. Payne would
have been entitled to a $528,000 tax deduction on the portion of
the collection he donated for which he received no money. It's not
clear why he declined to take the deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Jernigan and other foundation board members generally defend the
deal as a vehicle to pay Payne back for his volunteer efforts on
behalf of the bid campaign. During that period, he quit his job as
an attorney and took out a loan to support his family. Payne's
foundation assumed $500,000 of that loan in 1993. Payne paid the
loan back with interest from the proceeds of his memorabilia sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy gave his heart and soul to the Olympics,'' Jernigan
said. ``The purchase of his collections was unanimously supported
by the GAAF board _ we had no second thoughts whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with the development of the Olympic exhibition at the
Atlanta History Center, these collections and much more will be on
display for everyone to enjoy and cherish.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
