<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 30,
2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: SUMMER-FILMS and X-MEN-FILM. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHAFT-FILM (Undated) _ Gordon Park's groundbreaking detective
film ``Shaft'' in 1971 never got the respect it deserves; I
recently overheard a major filmmaker giving the picture short
shrift and claiming he could have done a much better job with the
material, given Isaac Hayes's score _ which some consider the true
star of the motion picture. In fact, the score builds a frame
around the likable cool of Parks's picture; it doesn't usurp it.
Now, with a new version of ``Shaft'' _ starring Samuel L. Jackson,
directed by John Singleton and written by Richard Price _ due for
release this summer, the original film will be scrutinized once
again. By Elvis Mitchell. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DARKSIDE-SUMMER-FILMS (Paris) _ So often in the movies, summer
is a time of flight and escape, romance and bliss; too brief in
real time but long in the memory, like all the things we love. But
films such as ``Lady in a Cage'' reveal the dark side of summer,
that season in which fights break out on the subway and lovers
sleep far apart in the bed and the heat tempts normally passive
mortals to madness. By Kristin Hohenadel. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAWS-FILM (Undated) _ Twenty-five years ago, Steven Spielberg's
``Jaws'' created the Summer Movie as we know it: the action-heavy,
``thrill ride'' sort of picture, aimed at sensation-hungry younger
audiences, which moves into theaters around Memorial Day and
remains there, partying hard, until the school year starts up again
in September. ``Jaws'' opened on June 20, 1975, and its phenomenal
popularity _ it was the first movie to relieve American audiences
of more than $100 million of their hard-earned money _ helped turn
Hollywood into what is now largely a summer-business town, sort of
like Amity, the New England beach resort where the film's dire
events take place. By Terrence Rafferty. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROCKY-BULLWINKLE-FILM (Undated) _ The ``Fractured Fairy Tale''
was one of the many wicked satires from ``Rocky and His Friends,''
the smartest, dumbest, simplest and most complex cartoon ever made
for television (and, yes, that includes ``The Simpsons''). On June
30, Universal Pictures will resuscitate the flying squirrel and his
pals on the big screen in ``The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle,'' what studio flacks are calling a
``live-action/animated comedy.'' By Franz Lidz. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLADIATOR-FILM (Undated) _ On Friday, ``Gladiator,'' directed by
Ridley Scott, resumes the dig for sunken metaphors on a scale not
seen since the late 1950s and early 1960s, when audiences lined up
for two-part spectaculars like William Wyler's ``Ben-Hur,'' Joseph
L. Mankiewicz's ``Cleopatra'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``Spartacus.''
In the spirit of these legendary epics, ``Gladiator'' is an
allegory of its own time. The first Roman cinema spectacular to be
made by Hollywood since the end of the Cold War, it is a meditation
on the perplexity of the world's sole surviving superpower. Quo
vadis? Where does America go from here? After expansion, implosion
_ this is the diagnosis set forth by ``Gladiator'' in period
costume. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEACH-FILMS (Undated) _ Although the beach movie genre is
generally considered to have begun with ``Gidget'' (1959) _
starring Sandra Dee as an affable, late-blooming teenager reluctant
to go on her first surf-and-sun ``manhunt'' _ it wasn't until the
successful release of American International Pictures' ``Beach
Party'' (1963) that film studios began to fully exploit the
economic rewards of niche marketing. And with two-thirds of all
filmgoers being between the ages of 16 and 24 by the late 1950s,
the intended target was clear. By David Bahr. (Moved) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-FILMS (Undated) _ The anticipated through-the-roof
success of the sequel to ``Mission Impossible,'' ``M: I-2,'' should
soothe any hurt feelings in the Tom Cruise camp over the actor's
Oscar loss for ``Magnolia.'' Generally the academy swoons over
beautiful stars who go into ugly mode to show they can act, but
Cruise's strutting, pelvis-jutting television sex guru, out to
seduce and destroy the female half of the species, was perhaps too
far off the empathy curve when compared with Michael Caine's kindly
doctor, patron of wayward women, in ``The Cider House Rules.''
While playing cocky upstarts too full of themselves to join the
team, in his best work as an actor Cruise has allowed co-stars and
supporting players to shine while his own subtler contributions
have gone relatively unheralded. Oscars have accrued, but not to
him. By Molly Haskell. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KISSES-FILMS (Undated) _ Let's face it, most movie kisses are
dull and predictable, about as titillating as a dental hygiene
appointment. But that makes the good ones even more memorable. I
apologize to everyone whose favorite kiss is absent here. By Lisa
Zeidner. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRISHA-BROWN-DANCE (New York) _ Sometimes the choreographer
Trisha Brown, 63, likes to dance an answer to a question. Looking
elegant in a long, simple black dress on a late March weekend, she
rises to her feet to show how close her dancers come to one another
in ``Five Part Weather Invention,'' the first section of a new
three-part collaboration with the jazz composer Dave Douglas, the
visual artist Terry Winters and the lighting designer Jennifer
Tipton. Both this piece and ``Rapture to Leon James,'' the second
part, will have their New York premieres when her 12-member troupe
celebrates its 30th anniversary with a two-week engagement at the
Joyce Theater, beginning on Tuesday. In June, the complete trilogy
will be presented at the American Dance Festival in North Carolina,
which commissioned ``Rapture'' and the last untitled section. By
Valerie Gladstone. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOMASSON-DANCE (Undated) _ Fifteen years ago, Helgi Tomasson,
the celebrated dancer from Iceland, stood onstage at the New York
State Theater for the last time as a member of the New York City
Ballet, accepting flowers and a resounding ovation for his final
performance. On Wednesday, if he goes against his innately modest
and reticent nature, he should be back on that stage, this time
taking a bow as the choreographer of a world premiere for the
company's spring gala program. Tomasson's ``Prism,'' set to
Beethoven's Piano Concerto No. 1, will be the closing work on a
program that includes the premieres of two Peter Martins ballets,
``Slonimsky's Earbox,'' to John Adams's score of the same name, and
``Todo Buenos Aires,'' to Adams's orchestrations of two Astor
Piazzolla compositions. Along with Christopher Wheeldon's
``Mercurial Manoeuvres,'' which opens the gala evening, these
ballets are all part of City Ballet's fourth Diamond Project, a
showcase for new choreography. By Susan Reiter. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-MAN-GROUP (Las Vegas) _ Blue Man Group is the three-man
performance troupe, the bald, blue-headed guys who, though
unspeaking (and occasionally unspeakable), have been wreaking havoc
on contemporary art in the intervals between playing their own
music on garbage pails and plumbing pipes at the Astor Place
Theater in Manhattan since 1991. The original Blue Men, Matt
Goldman, Phil Stanton and Chris Wink, were street performers who
established their own Club Nowhere on a sidewalk outside the
Copacabana in the late 1980s. By now, Blue Man has effected a
corporate merger with himself. Thirty other Blue Men have joined
the troupe, plus two in training. ``Blue Man: Tubes,'' the New York
show, is still going strong. In 1995 it opened in Boston; it's
still going strong there, too. In 1997 it was Chicago, where, yes,
it's still going strong. And last month, Messrs. Goldman, Stanton
and Wink opened in ``Blue Man Group: Live at Luxor'' in Las Vegas,
with a five-year contract. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIRTY-BLONDE-THEATER (New York) _ A Menage of muscle men and
drag queens flanked Mae West throughout her long career, both
onstage and off. They were her honor guard of sin, her ``boys,'' as
she liked to call them. In the play ``Dirty Blonde,'' a kind of
theatrical free-association on West, Kevin Chamberlin and Bob
Stillman bring a number of these ``boys'' to life. Written by
Claudia Shear, who conceived it with the director James Lapine,
``Dirty Blonde'' reopens Monday at the Helen Hayes Theater on
Broadway after a widely praised run at New York Theater Workshop.
By Barry Singer. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ Arnold Schoenberg waved the 12
commandments of serial music at a generation of composers
bewildered by the tower of Babel they had been forced to live in.
They were looking for an answer, and many were quick to follow. Few
realized the enormous breadth of skill and knowledge needed to make
serialism a truly musical experience. But here was someone with a
new idea. By Bernard Holland. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAWN-UPSHAW-MUSIC (New York) _ Hard as it may be to believe,
Dawn Upshaw turns 40 in July. By that age, most leading sopranos of
Upshaw's ilk have long since settled into a cushy routine. Yet no
sooner has Upshaw come up for air after the premiere of John
Harbison's ``Great Gatsby'' and a run of Debussy's ``Pelleas et
Melisande'' at the Metropolitan Opera than she takes up ``Images of
Dawn,'' an ambitious series of three programs produced by the Great
Performers series at Lincoln Center. It starts this Sunday
afternoon at Alice Tully Hall with ``The Composer's Oracle,'' a
recital of early 20th-century French songs written for the
mezzo-soprano Jane Bathori. By Cori Ellison. (Moved). WTIH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ART-NOUVEAU (London) _ A century after its heyday, the ornate
decorative style known as Art Nouveau remains so immediately
recognizable that debate over its merits often comes down to this:
do you love it or hate it? The Victoria and Albert Museum, however,
believes the time is ripe to revisit an earlier question: what
(italics)is(end italics) Art Nouveau? And to prove that the answer
is not obvious, it has put together ``Art Nouveau 1890-1914,'' the
largest exhibition on the subject since the last fin-de-siecle. The
premise of the show, which will travel to the National Gallery of
Art in Washington this fall after closing here on July 30, is that
Art Nouveau was not a flash-in-the-pan movement driven by press and
publicity. Rather it was a complex style, inspired by the idea of
total art, or Gesamtkunstwerk, as a political instrument, that had
roots in the mid-19th century and exercised influence well into the
20th century. By Alan Riding. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-ART-MUSEUM (New York) _ The main event at the Museum of
Modern Art these days is the Museum of Modern Art itself. Such has
been the case since last fall, when a project called MOMA 2000
kicked off with the first of what will be three successive
top-to-bottom reinstallations of the museum's permanent collection
galleries. The whole affair, spurred by the imminent expansion of
the museum's premises, has been billed a grand experiment, a
test-drive toward the future. By Holland Cotter. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-EMBROIDERY-ART (Washington) _ The glorious gardens of the
Ottoman Empire live on in the embroideries that Turkish women
produced over a 400-year period. They made these pictures in thread
to cover floors, walls, windows and furniture in their homes as
well as to edge sheets, towels, tablecloths and fabrics for gift
wrapping. More than a few of these exceptional works are now on
view in ``Flowers of Silk and Gold: Four Centuries of Ottoman
Embroidery,'' an exhibition at the Textile Museum here through July
30. By Rita Reif. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOTOFEST (Houston) _ While new media advance faster than the
century, photography, a 19th-century product of the Industrial
Revolution, continues to blanket the earth. Threatened repeatedly
by newer discoveries like moving pictures, television, video and
the Internet, it refuses to disappear. In March, Fotofest, the
biennial photography festival in Houston, presented strong evidence
that the still camera, and specifically a festival devoted to it,
continue to play important roles on both local and international
levels. By Vicki Goldberg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANTIQUES-ROADSHOW (Undated) _ There are a lot of guilty
pleasures on television these days _ ``Blind Date,'' ``The Man
Show,'' whatever HBO calls that program that appears occasionally
featuring nude programming from foreign countries. The oddest
member of this company is no doubt ``Antiques Roadshow,'' PBS's
wholesome tour of America's bric-a-brac. One of the things that's
neat about the ``Roadshow'' _ and that perhaps explains why the
show is a guilty pleasure for some (and, conversely, a must-see for
others) _ is that it celebrates a kind of person who ordinarily
does not get that much attention. For want of a better word, we're
talking about collectors. By Jamie Malanowski. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEST-WING (Undated) _ The most fun part of this season's
surprise hit drama ``The West Wing'' are the speeches, which fall
into one of the hoariest traditions of theater: the entrance. When,
in the pilot, President Josiah Bartlett, played by Martin Sheen,
trundles into a shot, bemusedly declaiming, ``Thou shalt have no
other God before me,'' Sheen's relish in acting a scene he knows
will play to the back of the house is just as affecting as the
speech itself. The show's creator and co-writer, Aaron Sorkin,
loves this stuff; he served up plenty of it in his stage drama ``A
Few Good Men.'' By Elvis Mitchell. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ISTANBUL (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Istanbul inaugurates a new
portal to the gateway. By Stephen Kinzer. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LOS-ANGELES (Undated) _ Three art-filled days in Los
Angeles. By Caryn James. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CASINO (Undated) _ Kings, queens and slot machines. By
Peter Marks. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGULAR FEATURES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ A Smithsonian tour of the Irish west;
A Tuscan villa comes back to life; Passenger complaints about
airlines rise; Horses step up to the triple crown; Photo ops that
cast a spell. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Question and answers on travel. This
week: Nepal treks; From Italy to Dubrovnik; Glasgow city tours. By
Suzanne Macneille. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Volunteering on vacation. By
Martha Stevenson Olson. (Moved).
</P>
