<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FOCUSING ON CORNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ After what owner Jerry Jones recently described
as the most extensive evaluation process ever by his coaches and
scouts on an NFL Draft, there obviously is nothing left for anyone
to learn about the three cornerbacks selected earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we know these guys, talent-wise,'' Cowboys defensive
coordinator Mike Zimmer said yesterday. ``But until you get them on
the field, in front of you, \Rmixed in\S with the rest of your
guys, there's really no way to know all their strengths and
deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will get their first chance during a three-day
minicamp held at Valley Ranch, beginning today, to see exactly how
cornerbacks Dwayne Goodrich of Tennessee, Kareem Larrimore of West
Texas A&AMP;M and Mario Edwards of Florida State fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from skill level, Zimmer will also be evaluating the
cornerbacks in three other areas:
</P>
<P>
   Ability to learn. ``How fast do they catch on? Although some of
them already have been sent a basic technique video, this will be
the first time that they find out what we expect of them,'' Zimmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ability to listen. ``How do they take to coaching? What's their
hot button?'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ability to relax. ``We \Rcoaches\S need to be careful that we
don't prejudge them too much at this point. This is their first
minicamp. They're going to be nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran cornerback Kevin Mathis, who had been a starter when
healthy _ he missed eight games in 1999 _ was traded to the New
Orleans Saints for third-year linebacker Chris Bordano on
Wednesday. This seemed to reinforce the belief that the Cowboys are
confident that Goodrich, Larrimore and Edwards all can make the
53-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely don't have the team made,'' Zimmer cautioned.
``I don't think we were trying to send a message \Rto the rookie
cornerbacks\S. If anything, \Rthe Mathis trade\S should've sent a
message to the older players.''  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Pro Bowl linebacker Dexter Coakley has signed the
Cowboys' one-year tender offer of $1.027 million. This represents
the second-highest tender allowed for an NFL restricted free agent.
It also set compensation at a first-round pick. Coakley did not
receive an offer sheet during the signing period from any other
team.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent kicker Jaret Greaser of Texas Tech was waived. Four
kickers remain on the Cowboys roster: Jon Hibert of Louisville,
Rian Lindee of Washington State, Cedric Ogelsby of South Carolina
State and Tim Seder of Ashland University, all undrafted rookie
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo has scheduled two minicamps and two quarterbacks
schools. Only the second minicamp _ June 12-14 _ is mandatory for
all players. The first of two quarterback schools begins Monday and
runs through Thursday. Quarterback School II is May 22-25.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
