<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9267 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-WESTPOINT-ART     04-27 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-WESTPOINT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WEST POINT, N.Y.: will be .'' 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Long Gray Line still marches in formation on the parade
ground called The Plain before the crenellated, fortress-like
barracks and classrooms set spectacularly above the Hudson, near
statues of Gens. George Patton `09, Douglas MacArthur `03, and
Dwight D. Eisenhower `15, and the trophy cannons captured in past
wars.
</P>
<P>
   But while the barracks are named for victorious generals and
their sally ports for their battles, the Vietnam war is marked only
by a memorial to the dead in Southeast Asia, donated by the classes
of 1960-1969, and athletic facilities named for three young
officers killed in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since Lt. Col. Conrad Crane `74, watched on
television here as the war wound down, a time he remembers ``almost
a siege mentality'' at West Point, when cadets couldn't wear their
uniforms off-campus for fear of being spat on.
</P>
<P>
   Now a history professor, Crane recalled that, back then, cadets
were issued a 46-page pamphlet with catechism-like answers, in case
somebody asked why America had become involved in a civil war.
``The conflict in Vietnam is not a civil war,'' it instructed.
``Rather, the conflict there is between two separate international
entities _ entities which resulted both from the provisional
military demarcation line separating the two and from their
real-world separation for a substantial period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 4,079 cadets include 630 women and, for more than 15
years now, have been able to choose majors, including history,
rather than follow the traditional engineering-oriented curriculum.
Still, Crane, for one, is dubious about the notion that the 1991
Persian Gulf war erased, as President George Bush said at the time,
the ``Vietnam Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Storm was the Anti-Vietnam,'' he said. ``In Desert
Storm, we got spoiled, a war with the roads already built, the
airports built. We are very blunt with the cadets, that in the
future their experiences will be closer to Vietnam than Desert
Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, for our policy makers, the Vietnam syndrome
is still there,'' he said. ``You can't suffer any casualties, that
is a legacy of Vietnam. It results in a kind of cruise-missile
diplomacy, a warfare so high-tech it's almost bloodless, not
risking any human life at all except where it lands.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like others at West Point, he sees the Army as likely to be
involved in peacekeeping operations on the ground, among a
population where distinctions between friend and foe may be
difficult or shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. David Toczek, `88, a lean, intense, can-do Ranger who with
Kingseed teaches a course on Korea and Vietnam that is the most
popular elective, is troubled, as a soldier, by the conclusion he
has been forced to draw from the Vietnam war. ``'Being an Army
officer, there's almost no such thing as `'can't be done',' '' he
said. ``It's not an option.'' But, he added, shaking his head after
a brief recounting of tactical debates, ``I don't know, I just
can't see a way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``. `'You can do attrition, do what you're good at _ kill a lot
of people,'' he said. ``But that doesn't solve the problem: a
corrupt government that doesn't serve the needs of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   For this younger generation of Vietnam scholars, the key to
North Vietnam's success against the United States was a concept
known as Dau Tranh, or protracted struggle. It meant waging
campaigns on both a political and military level, a willingness to
accept enormous casualties and, most importantly, flexible tactics,
shifting from guerrilla to conventional war to take advantage of
American deployments.
</P>
<P>
   In the course outline there is a quote from Douglas Pike, an
expert on Vietnam: ``Dau Tranh is a strategy for which there is no
proven counterstrategy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the reading lists here, Col. Harry G. Summers Jr.'s 1982
work, ``On Strategy: The Vietnam War in Context,'' which argued
that Americans won every battle on the ground but lost the war
through lack of political will, seems largely to have fallen out of
favor.
</P>
<P>
   More critical books are being assigned, including Philip
Caputo's ``A Rumor of War,'' a brutal account of his
disillusionment as a Marine lieutenant in Vietnam, where his
platoon, he wrote, ``carried along with our packs and rifles, the
implicit convictions that the Viet Cong would be quickly beaten and
that we were doing something altogether noble and good. We kept the
packs and rifles; the convictions we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The new scholarship perhaps most critical is ``Dereliction of
Duty'' (Harper Collins, 1997) by Col. H.R. McMillan, '84, who
taught history here and is now commanding an armored cavalry
squadron in Germany. He accuses the Army leadership of arrogance
and lying.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly the favorite book here is ``We Were Soldiers Once
and Young,'' by Lt. Gen. Harold Moore and Joseph Galloway (Harper
Perennial, 1992), which both celebrates the courage of American
soldiers in Vietnam while excoriating their top commanders and
their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In gripping detail, Moore, `45, tells the story tells of the
battle of Ia Drang in 1965, which in many ways defined the war.
</P>
<P>
   Then a lieutenant colonel and battalion commander, Moore
helicoptered his men into what turned out to be a major North
Vietnamese headquarters. Vastly outnumbered, the Americans called
in artillery, helicopter gunfire and finally all available aircraft
in Vietnam. When it was over, 634 North Vietnamese were dead and
more than 1,000 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Different lessons were drawn. For Westmoreland, it was a
validation of his ``search and destroy'' plan. To Moore and many
others, it was a warning of what a tenacious enemy they faced. To
the North Vietnamese, it was experience in how to fight the
Americans, newly arrived in force.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was here this week to speak to a packed auditorium of
cadets. Hundreds waited in line for hours at the bookstore for the
courtly old warrior to sign their books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came a way with a real definite feeling that everybody
caused it,'' said Matt Rasmussen, a junior history major. ``There
was no way to win that war.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
