<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-735&AMP;TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN AIDES PUT BUSH SESSION IN DOUBT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Texas)  By ALISON MITCHELL with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Even as he continued to reach out to
Democrats, Gov. George W. Bush suddenly had to deal with new strife
within his own party Thursday as aides to his onetime rival, Sen.
John McCain, threatened to cancel a scheduled reconciliation
session.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their bitter primary battle, the two men agreed a few
weeks ago to meet in Pittsburgh on May 9 and explore ways to put
their differences aside. But Todd Harris, a spokesman for McCain's
new political action committee, said Thursday, ``The status of the
meeting is tenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said aides to McCain, who in recent days had been touring
Vietnam, where he once was held as a prisoner of war, had had
trouble nailing down a serious agenda for the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that any meeting between the two should be a
substantive one,'' he said. ``We don't view a meeting where the
primary purpose is to go over once again whether John McCain wants
to be vice president _ when everybody knows he does not _ falls
into the substantive category.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the tensions between the two camps
would last long or how much Thursday's events were about gaining
the upper hand when the two men finally meet.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Allbaugh, Bush's campaign manager, and John Weaver, McCain's
political director, have been planning for several days to meet on
Friday in the office of former Sen. Bob Dole to pave the way for
the session. And such a meeting could defuse the tension. Dole will
not be present.
</P>
<P>
   The problems between the two camps surfaced as Bush was
stressing bipartisanship in a campaign appearance here, and Bush's
staff appeared to be taken by surprise. Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman
for Bush, said that Karl Rove, his senior strategist, was still
planning for the meeting and knew of no obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to McCain, however, said the senator wanted to have
discussions about education reform, Social Security and the
military. And he said it didn't ``help the situation'' that Sam
Wyly, a Bush backer who paid for last-minute attack ads against
McCain on the environment, had been one of the honorary
vice-chairmen of a Republican fund-raiser that featured Bush on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain apparently grew concerned that Bush was simply looking
for a meaningless photo opportunity after reading a column by
Robert Novak that said that some of Bush's advisers were dreading
the meeting but going ahead with it as a matter of ceremony.
According to a report in Salon, an Internet publication, McCain
decided to cancel the meeting for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Bush said that several officials with Bush's
campaign had talked on the telephone Thursday with McCain's
advisers to make sure there was not any misunderstanding about
Bush's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   They said that Bush indeed wanted a substantive discussion with
McCain and that they were conveying that to the senator's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said, ``The
governor is looking forward to the meeting as planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he defeated McCain and became virtually assured of
the Republican nomination, Bush has sought to return to the center
and put the contentious tone of the primary behind him. He
continued that effort Thursday, praising the Democratic governor of
North Carolina for his commitment to raising student performance
and for his appointment of a Republican to head North Carolina's
State Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's kind words for Gov. Jim Hunt, capped a week in which he
has repeatedly highlighted bipartisanship and reached out to
Democrats to show that he could break the gridlock in Washington.
He told his party at its $21.3 million fund-raiser Wednesday night
that ``Americans have have seen a cycle of bitterness _ an arms
race of anger'' in Washington, which he vowed to change if elected.
</P>
<P>
   The governor delivered his latest pledge to work with the
opposition party while at North Carolina's fourth annual state
conference on improving achievement of minority and disadvantaged
students, highlighting an issue he has made a hallmark of his
candidacy. ``We're part of a movement,'' Bush told a vast hall full
of teachers and principals, who gave him a polite but subdued
reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're part of a reform agenda,'' he said, ``which is by the
way a bipartisan agenda. We need to check partisanship at the door
when it comes to the education of our children.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that as governor he had worked closely with both parties
and noted that Democrats in Texas had helped him work to improve
student achievement. In fact, he had a Democrat at his side this
afternoon _ B. Alexander Kress, a former president of the Dallas
school board who has become an education adviser to the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had not been for cooperative Democrats in our
Legislature we wouldn't have gotten what we've gotten,'' Bush said,
telling the North Carolina audience, ``That's why it's easy for me
to say about your governor, he's an education governor. He set the
tone for other governors. He's done a fine job and he picked a
Republican at that to be the education man in this state of Texas _
I mean, North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Phillip J. Kirk, named by Hunt to be
chairman of North Carolina's State Board of Education. And Bush's
kind words for Hunt were particularly symbolic because the North
Carolina governor is sometimes mentioned as a possible running mate
for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also talked at some length Thursday about his call for
bipartisanship in an interview on the News Hour with Jim Lehrer,
the PBS program. Asked about reports that some Republicans had
chafed at his remarks at the fund-raiser Wednesday night, Bush
said, ``I want to make it clear to people in the Republican Party _
there were congressmen there _ there were senators there _ there
were, you know, contributors there _ there were hangers-on there; I
wanted to make it clear to them what my intentions are, and I
didn't ask at the door when people came in, you know, here's what
I'm going to say, do you think I should say it or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would take Tom DeLay, for example, aside and say,
``Cool it,'' if DeLay was being overly partisan in future, Bush
said, ``I think Tom, himself, would sometimes say, gosh, he may
have gotten a little carried away in his rhetoric. But I like Tom.
I can work with Tom, and if the situation got so bitter or it was
heading to being bitter, I'd call in members and say, `Let's tone
the rhetoric because America is more important.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
