<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-VW-BEETLE-I-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE BEETLES ARE MUTATING
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30)  
 (Eds: This article is in two parts)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ When Volkswagen introduced the New Beetle in
1998, the press and public went ga-ga. The Love Bug was back _ this
time with all the amenities that baby boomers never knew they
needed when they were young, poor and blissfully ignorant of the
risks of traveling 100 feet a second in a tin can on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only harsh words to be heard were aimed at its limp,
2-liter, 4-cylinder power plant, which pushed the 2,800-pound coupe
from zero to 60 mph in about 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   This defect was fixed last summer, when Volkswagen offered the
New Beetle with an optional turbo-charged engine, a 1.8-liter,
20-valve four-cylinder borrowed from the least expensive Audi A4
and the entry-level VW Passat. Does that make the Bug the perfect
people mover?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. I'm among the multitudes who took part in the initial
love fest, and I remain a fan. But now that the novelty of driving
a '60s icon morphed into an elegant postmodern runabout is wearing
off, the New Beetle's limitations as basic transportation and as
road performer are more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the good stuff. The silky turbo-charged engine found
on both the GLS 1.8T and the ``loaded'' GLX 1.8T, is a winner. With
150 horsepower _ 35 more than the 2-liter, normal-breathing base
engine _ the Beetle no longer feels sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   It reaches 60 mph from a stop in about 7.6 seconds, a very
respectable number for a car that can be had for less than $20,000.
More important, the modern little engine _ it has five valves for
each cylinder _ produces maximum torque (162 foot-pounds) at a
surprisingly low 2,200 rpm. That assures zippy acceleration when
you really need it _ say, if you are passing on a two-lane road _
with little ``turbo lag.'' With the five-speed manual, it means
less shifting in traffic. I found myself noodling along at 30 in
fourth gear with plenty of response in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention gas mileage? This engine barely sips the stuff _ a
notable virtue with California's extra-clean premium fuel running
$1.90 a gallon. I averaged 28 mpg on a real-life mix of mountain
roads, freeways and urban traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The GLS 1.8T that I drove is smooth, comfortable and quiet. The
safety systems include confidence-inspiring antilock brakes,
standard on all New Beetles, as well as a computerized traction
control that uses both the brakes and the throttle to maintain
stability in dicey situations.
</P>
<P>
   As with all New Beetles, front-seat passengers enjoy an interior
that is as practical as it is beautiful. The cabin feels roomy and
the controls (lit in a gorgeous red and blue) are easily
accessible. The very adjustable seats are complemented by a
steering wheel that both tilts and telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   The standard radio-cassette combo produces truly excellent
sound. The plastics and metal trim are a tactile delight. And the
fit-and-finish is simply the best to be found in a $20,000 car,
though Consumer Reports found the number of electrical problems on
'99 models to be way out of line.
</P>
<P>
   What else is there not to like? While the 1.8T has plenty of
engine to run with true sport coupes like the Honda Civic Si and
VW's own Golf-based GTI, it doesn't have the handling. The steering
is precise, but lacks road feel. The suspension, nicely tuned for
comfort, complains _ albeit politely _ on hard curves.
</P>
<P>
   And the modest turbo lag, which is hardly noticeable in
straight-line acceleration, makes it a bit tricky to accelerate
smoothly through a curve. A spoiler above the rear window is
supposed to pop out at 93 mph to counteract the car's tendency to
lose contact with the ground at high speed, but I never went fast
enough to see if it made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the exaggerated curves of the roof line and
trunk compartment that give the New Beetle its distinctive ``come
out and play with me'' look, undermine the car's value as practical
transportation. Thanks to wide doors and front seats that
automatically move forward as the backs are tilted, adults can
squeeze into the back seat with relatively little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But once ensconced in the rear, head room and leg room are
grossly inadequate. And while the rear seat does fold down to
expand the modest 12-square-foot capacity of the pass-through
trunk, no one would ever buy a New Beetle for the cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the New Beetle 1.8T is the perfect car for people who
get a kick out of driving a work of art, yet can live without great
handling or a real back seat. I'm still an admirer, but the bloom
is off the rose. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: An irresistible first date, but will you love it
in the morning? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
