<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh Evidence of Growth Stokes Fear of Inflation
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy turned in another robust quarter, the
government reported, as new evidence emerged that today's
prosperity is finally pushing up labor costs, raising fear of
higher inflation. The gross domestic product, representing the
value of all goods and services produced in the nation, rose at a
5.4 percent annual rate. The broad inflation measure published with
the G.D.P. report rose by 3.2 percent, mainly because of higher
gasoline and fuel oil prices. And a measure of labor costs, the
Employment Cost Index, rose 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The quick pace of growth and signs of an acceleration in wage
and price increases all but guarantee that the Federal Reserve will
seriously consider raising rates by half a percentage point instead
of a quarter-point.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Shares Lead a Rally
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks regained market leadership, rising sharply and
shaking off economic reports suggesting that more interest rate
increases were on the way. The Nasdaq composite index rose 143.94
points, or nearly 4 percent, to 3,774.03. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 57.40 points, or 0.5 percent, to 10,888.10. Earlier in
the session, the Dow was down as much as 197 points. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index increased 3.93 points, to 1,464.92.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless Shares Rise 8 Percent
</P>
<P>
   The tracking stock for AT&AMP;T's wireless unit opened at $30.125 a
share before closing up 8 percent, at $31.6875 in trading of 124.7
million shares on the New York Stock Exchange. That made for the
second-busiest trading day yet for an individual Big Board stock.
</P>
<P>
   WPP in Talks With Young &AMP; Rubicam
</P>
<P>
   In a deal that would combine two of the world's largest
advertising companies, WPP Group of Britain, which owns Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide and J. Walter Thompson, acknowledged that it was
in talks to buy Young &AMP; Rubicam. But Y&AMP;R is also discussing a
combination with Publicis of France.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom Earnings Rise 80 Percent
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom said that its first-quarter profit rose 80 percent,
to $1.3 billion, or 44 cents a share, just ahead of Wall Street
expectations, amid strong growth in its data, Internet and
international operations.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna Posts 16 Percent Gain in Profit
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurance company, said that
its first-quarter operating profit rose 16 percent, helped by
reduced losses at its Prudential Health Care unit and a rebound in
international business, including financial services in Asia and
Latin America. The results strengthen the hand of William
Donaldson, the recently appointed chief executive, who was expected
to face sharp questioning by shareholders at the annual meeting
Friday in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   New Head Named for ABC Network
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney has placed Robert Callahan, the president of its
radio and television stations division, in charge of the ABC
Television Network, which has been without a direct leader for
weeks but No. 1 in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   British Auction Raises $35.5 Billion
</P>
<P>
   An auction for licenses to operate a new generation of wireless
devices linked to the Internet came to a close, reaping the British
government a $35.5 billion windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Software to Protect Copyrights
</P>
<P>
   Xerox and Microsoft said that they would create a company,
ContentGuard, to produce and market software that protects
copyrighted materials like books, music and video distributed over
the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
