<HEADLINE>
300 PEOPLE FOUND STRANDED ON ISLAND IN BAHAMAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 300 people believed to be Haitian migrants were
discovered stranded on an uninhabited island in the southern
Bahamas on Wednesday evening, 14 of them dead and dozens severely
dehydrated and suffering from hypothermia, said a spokesman for the
U.S. Coast Guard, which sent boats and helicopters to rescue them
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The voyagers told Coast Guard officials that they had been in a
50-foot boat that ran aground near the island, Flamingo Cay, 150
miles southeast of Nassau in the Bahamas, said a Coast Guard
spokesman, Jibran Soto.
</P>
<P>
   The details of how the migrants were stranded remained sketchy
Thursday night, Soto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether the vessel sank or it just dropped them
off,'' he said. ``There was no vessel nearby, and we don't know how
long they were there.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was discovered Wednesday evening by three sailboats
passing the island, which then radioed the Coast Guard at 7:30
p.m., Soto said. A doctor aboard one of the sailboats went ashore
and described for officials a scene of death and desperate illness.
</P>
<P>
   Two helicopters arrived from the Bahamas 90 minutes later to
find more than 300 people, 14 dead. That night, 48 of the sickest
people were evacuated to hospitals in the Bahamas and Miami.
Thursday morning two Coast Guard cutters, the Farallon and the
Manitou, arrived from Miami Beach and helped to evacuate 17 more.
Two more cutters also left Miami Beach Thursday morning, equipped
with food, water and medicine, to join the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamian government also dispatched a cutter and planned to
take over the rescue efforts, since the island is in Bahamian
waters, between Flamingo Cay and the Ragged Island chain, said
Karen Kraushaar, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. The Coast Guard plans to keep rescue
vessels there until Bahamian officials can take over.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamas have become a common way station _ and their waters
a potential graveyard in recent years _ for Haitians fleeing to the
United States. Some have paid Bahamian smugglers for a spot on
dangerously overcrowded boats, which have sunk. And in 1995,
smugglers threw 100 Haitians overboard to lighten a boat headed for
the Bahamas. All those migrants were believed to have drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Political repression, violence and searing poverty have led
Haitians to flee in great numbers. Last year, the Coast Guard
intercepted 480 Haitians trying to enter the United States and
1,437 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
