<HEADER>
A9275 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOK-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      04-27 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOK-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK-SOLID VALUES AT REINVENTION'S CORE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Questions may be italicized) 
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David P. Pottruck, co-author of ``Clicks and Mortar,'' is
president and co-chief executive of Charles Schwab, the huge
securities firm widely recognized as a pioneer in embracing the
Internet. In a recent interview, he talked about the Internet and
corporate values. Following are excerpts from the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does the Internet make it harder to do business? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We used to reinvent the company about every 10 years. Now it
seems like we have to reinvent our company every two years. I heard
Warren Buffett give a speech two days ago. He said: ``I reward my
managers for building a moat around our castle and then making the
moat deeper, wider and filling it with alligators. I look at our
company as a castle, the castle of capital. Other people want to
take our castle away and take our capital away. And we want this
moat around the company.''
</P>
<P>
   And somebody said to me, ``What do you do?'' I said: ``Well, we
don't have a moat. I keep trying to move the castle. As people get
closer to my castle, I've got to move my castle over here. I've got
to constantly reinvent how we serve customers better, faster, more
value, more service _ reinvent what service means.''
</P>
<P>
   But in doing all that, the values of the company don't change.
So the employees, even the customers, feel that something is
constant, that they know what Schwab stands for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some Wall Street houses take pride that their best
``producers'' might earn more than the chief executive. Would that
fit Schwab? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No, no. One thing we don't have is a star system. We don't
have ``producers.'' We never use that phrase _ ever. The whole
notion of producers is that someone owns their own business and
operates within this larger context of a company, but they have
their own little customers.
</P>
<P>
   That's not how we operate at Schwab. It's much more of a
teamwork environment in which people work together. And they don't
own the customer _ the company owns the customer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But can pay promote teamwork? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the bonus pool is created by corporate success. So you
can be the biggest producer in the company; you can be the biggest
contributor. But if the corporation pool is zero, your bonus is
zero. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But if 75 people or 7 people are working on a project, does
their pay depend on their overall accomplishment? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. All the above. Corporate success, team success, then
individual contributions. So corporate success defines the pool.
Team success defines the team's pool, and individual contributions
to the team determine how the pool is divided among the team.
</P>
<P>
   We have a little fund, extra money, because if it all has to net
to zero, then if I give you more, I've got to take it from him. It
becomes a zero sum game, you against him. That doesn't work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's new, what's constant about the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Budgeting, planning, marketing, leadership, change
management, innovation _ these things have always mattered. Great
companies always did these things well. But in an Internet world,
the speed at which we do them and the impact of constant change
make those jobs different.
</P>
<P>
   Your budgeting system today can't be the same as the budgeting
system of a few years ago. It's got to be more flexible. We are
reinventing our budget every month.
</P>
<P>
   Priorities, competitive advantage, competitive situations change
with a speed we've never seen before. Decision-making, therefore,
must change at a speed we've never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   I've had people come to me from dot-com companies and say, ``We
don't use those old systems of measurement, project budgets; we
just make a decision and go.'' Companies that do that are going to
go down the drain. You still have to have measurements. You just
can't take months and months to figure it out. But you still need a
road map to go from here to there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
