<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA'S PRESIDENT WINS REFORM OF RIGID LABOR CODE
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The opposition-controlled Argentine
Senate has given President Fernando de la Rua a much-needed lift by
passing his labor reform bill, which is intended to lower the 14
percent unemployment rate by reducing labor costs for businesses
and curtailing the power of big labor.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming vote of approval on Wednesday night capped six
weeks of intense political maneuvering and sometimes violent labor
union protests that made the new de la Rua government look
increasingly inept as Cabinet ministers publicly second-guessed
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, de la Rua managed to persuade the opposition to
pass what is his most important legislative project. The law should
go a long way toward shaking up a rigid labor code that was
introduced in the 1950s by President Juan Domingo Peron. That code
invested most power in one big national labor confederation and
undercut any renegotiating of labor rules and salaries when
business conditions changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very content,'' de la Rua told reporters. ``It's a law
that will contribute to the development of small- and medium-sized
business and work in Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   The new labor code is intended to encourage businesses to hire
more people at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Large companies will be allowed to increase the probationary
period for new hires to up to six months from the current 30 days
and small businesses to one year, after which workers can be
dismissed without benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Payroll taxes on new hires will be reduced to 12 percent from
17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had been blocked four times in the Senate and seemed
again in jeopardy only last week. Leaders of the Peronist
opposition called off debate of the measure on April 19 after a
confrontation between federal police officers and labor union
dissidents in front of the Congress building left 35 union
supporters injured.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen police officers were arrested for brutality, and
contradictory comments by senior de la Rua aides made it appear
that the government was unable to control its own security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Moyano, a truck driver and union leader who led last week's
protests, threatened to shut down congressional debate again, but
was persuaded by political allies to hold a peaceful demonstration
instead. He has called for a national strike on May 5 to protest
the new measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only objective of this labor reform is to bring down the
salaries of the workers,'' Moyano said. He pledged that workers
would punish the senators who supported the bill by voting against
them in congressional elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   Moyano and other national labor leaders had more power under the
old labor code, which required that most labor negotiations be held
at the national level to include all workers of particular economic
sectors. That system will now be replaced by negotiations at the
local and company level and will take into consideration peculiar
regional conditions and the ability of individual firms to pay wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   The new law will also eliminate a system known here as
``ultra-activity,'' which stipulated that an old contract stands
when a business and a union cannot successfully negotiate a new
contract. This rule gave unions a major incentive not to negotiate
when companies were pushing for lower salaries or new work rules
because of a change in economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Peronists in the Senate agreed to pass the bill
only after including a provision that will prohibit wages from
being lowered for two years. But that clause could still be
excluded by the lower house of Congress by a two-thirds vote when
the bill is finally enacted into law in the next few days. The
lower house, which is controlled by de la Rua's coalition, has
already overwhelmingly passed a slightly different version of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate action was welcomed Thursday on Wall Street, where
enthusiasm for the Argentine economy and stock market have cooled
considerably because of two deep recessions in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will bring a major long-term structural benefit for the
Argentine economy,'' said Geoff Dennis, Smith Barney's Latin
American equity strategist. ``Argentina has had an extremely high
unemployment rate even when the economy was going well because of
all the costs of taking on new labor. This reform will encourage
unemployment to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Most economists say the new law will probably have only a modest
immediate impact on an economy that is fitfully emerging from a
deep two-year slump. Construction activity actually fell by 5.8
percent in March compared with the same month last year. And while
higher oil and farm prices have helped increase export earnings,
domestic spending remains in the doldrums, leaving a broad
perception that the economy is not responding to de la Rua's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, political analysts here said, the opposition
Peronists decided to go along with the labor reform rather than
risk being blamed for high unemployment in next year's
congressional election campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
