<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sharks captain and leading goal scorer Owen Nolan did
not skate at yesterday's team practice. He's not injured. He's just
a little sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still got the Al MacInnis shot block,'' Sharks coach
Darryl Sutter said laughing. ``It takes more than 24 hours to get
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan had six goals and eight points in helping the Sharks knock
off top-seeded St. Louis in seven games. But in the third period of
Game 7, with the Blues gaining momentum and on a power play, Nolan
went to the ice feet first to block a MacInnis `rocket.'
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis' slap shot slammed off the top of Nolan's skate. In
typical playoff form, Sutter was elusive as to what part of Nolan's
body was ailing and how badly, but he said Nolan won't miss any
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fine,'' Sutter said.  &QL; 
No hard feelings
</P>
<P>
   Sharks winger Todd Harvey, who played for the Stars from
1994-98, said it was disappointing not to be playing with the team
during last season's march to the Stanley Cup, but he holds no
grudges.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' he said. ``That's hockey and that's
business; that's in any professional sport. I've moved on and the
Stars have moved on. I'm happy to be in San Jose and getting the
chance to play in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey went from Dallas to the New York Rangers and then to San
Jose earlier this season in a three-way deal that sent Radek Dvorak
to New York and Sharks goalie Mike Vernon to Florida.
\Nsubheds:Goalie makes comeback Sharks goalie Steve Shields' clutch
performance in Game 7 against St. Louis not only quieted a lot of
critics, it also gave his teammates added confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time for me to see him react to a bad
performance \Rin the playoffs\S,'' center Vincent Damphousse said.
``He was able to put that aside and come back with a strong
performance. That says a lot for a goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Darryl Sutter said he always had faith in Shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big quandary was after Game 6, where they were going to
bury him in some unknown grave somewhere,'' Sutter joked. ``He was
ready for Game 7. You knew how he was going to play.''  &QL; 
No gambling here
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Stars are only 2-for-26 on the power play,
Darryl Sutter said that will not encourage his team to take
unnecessary chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I don't want to see Sergei Zubov, Darryl
Sydor, Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk and Brett Hull out on the ice
when we only have four guys.''  &QL; 
Staying put
</P>
<P>
   If Darryl Sutter keeps his lines intact from the first round,
veteran Dave Lowry will play left wing on the first line with
center Vincent Damphousse and right wing Owen Nolan. Sutter dropped
winger Jeff Friesen to the second line with center Marco Sturm and
Todd Harvey to make room for Lowry.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry's job against St. Louis: badger Chris Pronger. Get ready
Derian Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a huge part \Rof beating St. Louis\S. He really made
Chris Pronger come unglued quite a bit,'' defenseman Jeff Norton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Stern replaced Alexander Korolyuk on the fourth line to
bring a nastier edge in Games 6 and 7. He joined center Ron Sutter
and Tony Granato.Darryl Sutter was mum on how he would construct
his lines against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stick with it, we stick with it,'' he said. ``I don't
think we're that good a team that we can make the other team adjust
to us, we have to adjust to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
