<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-DIESEL-FUEL-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIESEL FUEL IS NOT NECESSARILY A BARGAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE DUNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prices may be dropping at the pump, but diesel fuel still isn't
the deal it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 2000, we've seen a huge increase in diesel prices, 40
percent in the past couple of months,'' said Bob Costello, chief
economist for the American Trucking Associations in Washington.
``We're in a situation where diesel inventories are extremely
tight. We have no room for mistakes. I think we're definitely in
for more increases.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, John Litchblau, chairman of the Petroleum
Industry Research Foundation in New York, predicted that diesel
prices would keep falling, as they have in recent weeks. ``Prices
will go down in the near future, not very drastically, but the
trend is now downward.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The national average was $1.43 a gallon last week, up 3 cents
after falling for five consecutive weeks, according to the Energy
Information Administration. That compared with $1.48 for regular
gasoline. Diesel reached a high of $1.50 in March. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the national average for diesel was $1.13, the trucking
group said.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel is more energy efficient than gasoline, and it produces
better mileage. But it concerns environmentalists because of its
high sulfur content. Sulfur levels and emissions for diesel fuel
are regulated by the Environmental Protection Agency and have
decreased by 90 percent since 1988. New regulations are about to be
proposed to reduce sulfur even more, to 30 parts per million, from
300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     04-27 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SWEPT BY BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A wonderful road trip turned horrid. An explosive
offense was rendered a dud. An energetic team is now thankful to be
heading home.
</P>
<P>
   Having mustered nothing offensively for 36 innings, the Los
Angeles Dodgers showed some life in their final three innings on
the road only to misfire at the most important time and fall to the
Atlanta Braves 6-3 Thursday at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, off to a fast 9-3 start on the road this season,
have crashed. They began this six-game trip with three straight
victories over Cincinnati, only to lose three to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlanta has won 10 straight games, including a
franchise-record 9-0 homestand.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the Dodgers, once 11-6, at 11-10 and longing for
traffic jams, smog and home-sweet-Dodger Stadium. They open a
nine-game homestand today, having matched the Chicago Cubs for most
road games played in the majors leagues at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the nine road wins are tops in baseball, most of the
players admitted to feeling fatigued, particularly mentally, and
wanting to go home. No wonder: They went from Cincinnati to New
York for a day before traveling to Atlanta for three games.
</P>
<P>
   That came after L.A. opened the season with a 10-game road trip
to Montreal, New York and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a little drained and it definitely showed,''
Grudzielanek said. ``We lacked probably a little enthusiasm and we
were beat, I guess. The trip was a tough one and it's going to be
good to go home for a little over a week now. We were flat the last
few days and it probably started in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   However, after snoozing through a pair of 1-0 shutouts and then
scoring just one run Wednesday, the Dodgers finally got a few
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   And then wasted them. They left a season-high 14 runners on
base, including the bases loaded in three of the last four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around baseball long enough to know if you go out
and kill somebody like we did the Reds over the weekend, you're
going to have a little lack of runs,'' Dodgers pitcher Jeff Shaw
said. ``Maybe we used them all up in Cincinnati, but it was bound
to happen. We're not going to score 12 runs a night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers didn't get a runner past first base until the sixth
inning. By then, the Braves had built a 2-0 lead off Chan Ho Park,
who was bothered by the blister that formed on the middle finger of
his right hand in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   Park (3-2) tied a career high with seven walks and was in
trouble throughout. He was hesitant to throw his curveball until
the middle innings. The Braves broke through with four runs in the
sixth, the final three of which came on Chipper Jones' one-out
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new skin was kind of a weak skin, so I was worried about a
new blister,'' Park said. ``I'm supposed to forget about that and
just concentrate, but I was thinking about two different things:
pitching and the blister.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers loaded the bases with two outs after Eric Karros'
two-run homer in the eighth pulled the Dodgers within 6-3, but
Grudzielanek grounded back to the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   It was worse in the ninth. The man everybody loves to hate
outside of Atlanta, John Rocker, allowed a leadoff single to Gary
Sheffield and walked Shawn Green and Karros to load the bases with
none out.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker then struck out Adrian Beltre, Chad Kreuter and Kevin
Elster for his fourth save. Terry Mulholland (3-2) pitched seven
innings for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame it; there's no fatigue,'' Kreuter said. ``It's
just that we didn't get it done. That's the bottom line. You can't
blame it on fatigue because we had a long road trip. That's
nothing. You get the same amount of rest here as you do anywhere
else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
