<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PROSTATE-CANCER-ART-N     04-27 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-CANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGERY OR RADIATION: GIULIANI'S CHOICES FOR TREATING HIS PROSTATE
CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-GIULIANI-CANCER) 
(ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT photo clients: One
graphic illustrates statistics on prostate cancer; the other shows
diagnostic steps. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whatever therapy Mayor Rudolph Giuliani chooses for
his early prostate cancer, it will probably interrupt his
campaigning temporarily but should not prevent him from running for
the Senate, cancer experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two basic choices are surgery to remove the prostate and
radiation. Some patients choose to wait for a much longer period
while the cancer is further monitored. But Giuliani indicted at a
news conference Thursday that he was unlikely to wait a substantial
time before initiating therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael J. Droller, chairman of urology at Mt. Sinai
Hospital, said that Giuliani ``could resume his mayoral duties and
campaigning efforts beginning about three weeks after surgery or
during radiation treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani could handle the office work, climb stairs and fly in
airplanes early on, but after surgery, physical activity like
lifting would be limited for about another month, Droller, who is
not involved in Giuliani's case, said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was two full months before Joe Torre, the manager
of the New York Yankees, returned to the dugout after undergoing
surgery for prostate cancer in St. Louis on March 18, 1999. But
experts said Thursday that, depending on circumstances, Giuliani's
recovery could be much shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David G. McLeod, the chief urologist at Walter Reed Army
Medical Center who operated on former Sen. Bob Dole for prostate
cancer in 1991 and is not involved in Giuliani's case, said that if
Giuliani is treated ``this early in the campaign schedule, by
mid-summer he should be able to hit his stride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the cancer is caught early enough, by this time next year
it will be a bad memory,'' said McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he will review his therapy options over the next
two to three weeks with his doctors and friends who have had the
disease. The delay is not significant because prostate cancer is
not an emergency like a heart attack and most such cancers are slow
growing. Many doctors advise individuals with newly diagnosed
prostate cancer to take time to weigh the risks and benefits of
each type of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 180,400 American men will be diagnosed with
prostate cancer this year, making it the second most common type of
cancer in men, following skin cancer. The prostate is a
walnut-sized gland anatomically situated behind the penis, in front
of the rectum and under the urinary bladder.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his cancer was detected at an early stage, chiefly
the result of a blood test known as PSA for prostate specific
antigen. The diagnosis was confirmed by a biopsy performed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of therapy depends in part on an individual's age,
general state of health, aggressiveness of the cancer and fear of
surgery. Another factor is the preference of the doctor advising a
patient; doctors tend to be biased in favor of what their specialty
does.
</P>
<P>
   For individuals in their fifties, Dr. Herbert Lepor, chief of
urology at New York University, said most urologists advise
surgical removal of the prostate because if the cancer is confined
to the gland, the problem is usually solved.
</P>
<P>
   As a white American male, Giuliani, who will be 56 on May 28,
has a life expectancy of another 23.5 years, according to the U.S.
Vital Statistics Report.
</P>
<P>
   Lepor said surgery to remove a prostate usually takes about one
and one-half hours. As part of the operation, surgeons usually
remove lymph nodes so a pathologist can look for evidence of
spread. Most individuals go home from the hospital in a few days
after removal of a cancerous prostate if there are no complications
like excessive bleeding or infection. Many can work during recovery
and resume unrestricted physical activity in about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The two main long-term complications of the operation are
urinary incontinence and impotence. To preserve sexual potency,
urologists take care to spare two vital nerves. Drugs like Viagra
help improve potency in those who have such problems after prostate
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation therapy for prostate cancer is generally given every
working day for eight weeks. The patient generally spends about an
hour in the hospital, can work the rest of the day, but needs to
stay in town unless the radiation is given in the form of seeds
that are implanted in the gland, said Dr. Silvia Formenti, the
chairman of radiation oncology at New York University. Radiation
spares the time needed for surgery and recuperation. Side effects
are usually mild, Formenti said.
</P>
<P>
   Chances of cure are high, in the 80 to 95 percent range for
early cancer, but depend on details that Giuliani and his
urologist, Alexander M. Kirschenbaum of Mt. Sinai Hospital of Mt.
Sinai NYU Health, did not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Among such details are the specific findings of the PSA test and
the Gleason score, a standard system that pathologists use to gauge
the aggressiveness of a prostate cancer. Because no single test
provides an accurate diagnosis or prognosis, doctors use a
combination of the PSA, Gleason score and how the texture of the
prostate feels to their fingertip when they perform a rectal
examination. Suspicions of a cancer are raised if a doctor feels a
nodule in the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   The PSA level is generally considered normal when it is below 4
nanograms per mililiter. But about one in four men with prostate
cancer have a low PSA, the American Cancer Society says.
</P>
<P>
   The Gleason score is measured on a scale from 2 to 10, and it is
based on a pathologist's evaluation of the cellular patterns of two
prominent types seen under the microscope. In general, the lower
the Gleason score, the better the chance of cure.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Thursday, Giuliani said that his PSA
level was elevated. A source familiar with the case said that the
mayor's Gleason score was in the middle range, and the prostate
felt normal.
</P>
<P>
   In monitoring a patient's prostate, doctors are more suspicious
of cancer if the PSA level in the blood rises quickly over time.
Giuliani did not say how often he has had a PSA test and did not
specify the last previous test before two and one-half weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Gleason score was calculated on the basis of a piece
of prostate that was removed in the biopsy and then examined by a
quick pathological technique known as a frozen section. Sometimes
the degree of aggressiveness and extent of prostate cancer differ
when the tissue is examined in a standard way after it is placed in
a chemical. Such results would be expected by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's situation is different than when his father was
diagnosed with prostate cancer about 30 years ago and died of it at
age 73. The PSA test was not widely used in medicine until the
1990s and there has been extensive debate about its value as a
screening test.
</P>
<P>
   Because many prostate cancers are believed to have a low
probability of spreading elsewhere in the body, many experts debate
whether widespread use of PSA is leading to more aggressive
prostate therapy in men who might otherwise not need it. Until the
question is answered scientifically, many doctors and patients are
choosing to undergo surgery or radiation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
