</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF CUBAN BOY GAINS RIGHT TO JOIN, NOT END, CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga.)   (SUBS for complete writethru including dateline and byline; see
also CUBAN-BOY-VIEWS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a mixed decision in the Elian Gonzalez case, a
federal appeals court Thursday put off a request by the boy's
father to serve as his sole legal representative, which would have
effectively ended the court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a blow to the boy's Miami relatives, the court also
denied the family's request for regular visits with the 6-year-old
Cuban boy and dismissed their request for the appointment of a
neutral guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a psychiatrist and a social worker, both appointed by
the government, will monitor the boy and send the court regular
reports on his condition and care, an arrangement that was first
suggested by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel also ruled that his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, had the right to intervene in the battle over whether his
son went back to Cuba or stayed here.
</P>
<P>
   By offering the twin rulings, the court made two points clear:
it did not want to dismiss the case before it had a full airing on
May 11, and it did not want the boy's Miami great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez to overstep his authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious that Craig attempted to get into the
ballgame,'' said Richard Sharpstein, a lawyer for the Miami
relatives, referring to Gregory Craig, who represents Juan Miguel
Gonzalez. ``But he also wanted to take the ball and go home, and
the court said no. At this time, they will defer on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater legal question surrounding the case _ whether Elian
has a right to apply for asylum on his own or whether his father
speaks for him _ will be presented before the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts offered mixed interpretations of Thursday's ruling
on the legal challenge brought by Lazaro Gonzalez. Some said the
ruling denying his request for a neutral guardian and regular
visitation did not bode well for his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of the death knell for Lazaro Gonzalez for a
couple of reasons,'' said Michael Maggio, an immigration lawyer in
Washington. ``By refusing to appoint a guardian, the court is
beginning to foreshadow that there is no standing in this case for
Lazaro Gonzalez. I think this case will be thrown out on the
standing issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said the rulings did not bear directly on the
substance of the case, and said little about the end result.
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, it does not answer any of the questions that are
pending,'' said Elliott Lichtman, an immigration lawyer in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the appellate court panel said it was
``hesitant'' to grant Juan Miguel Gonzalez the right to intervene
in the case at this late date, but agreed to the request because he
was the boy's father. One of the three judges dissented, arguing
that the request came too late and that the Immigration and
Naturalization Service ``adequately represents'' Juan Miguel
Gonzalez's interests.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said it would be ``premature'' to decide whether
the boy's father should serve as Elian's sole representative. That
motion, the judges ruled, will be wrapped into the overall case.
</P>
<P>
   With Elian cocooned at the Wye River estate on the Eastern Shore
of Maryland, about 70 miles outside Washington, along with his
father, stepmother and infant half brother, four of the boy's
kindergarten classmates arrived Thursday at Dulles International
Airport on a private plane to join him. Elian is not permitted to
leave the country until the appellate court rules on his
great-uncle's claim.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture underscoring Havana's interest in both the case and
Elian, Cuban President Fidel Castro bade the four children goodbye
just before they climbed aboard a jet bound from Havana to
Washington, Reuters reported. A pediatrician and the mothers of
three of the children accompanied them on their voyage, and one
child's father is scheduled to follow. The entourage arrived
wearing crimson blazers and waving Cuban flags, on the heels of two
other visitors, Elian's cousin and his kindergarten teacher.
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban government communique Thursday night said that one of
the physicians traveling with the schoolchilden had medication
confiscated by customs officials, and that Cuban officials in
Washington had sent a protest letter to President Clinton and the
immigration service.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate scheduled to hold a hearing on Wednesday on the
raid by armed federal agents who removed Elian from the house in
Little Havana where he was staying with some of his Miami
relatives, Attorney General Janet Reno again defended her decision
to order the predawn raid. The Justice Department also supplied
figures on how much the Elian case has cost the department,
something several senators wondered about this week.
</P>
<P>
   The case has cost more than $578,000 since Thanksgiving Day,
when Elian was picked up in the Atlantic off Florida. The
preliminary figures do not include costs for Elian's four-day stay
at Andrews Air Force Base.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who grew teary-eyed during the weekly news conference,
attempted to bolster her decision by suggesting that the heavily
armed agents faced a hostile crowd.
</P>
<P>
   One immigration agent, Betty Mills, the woman who rushed Elian
into a waiting van, was nearly thrown to the ground as she
approached the house, and someone inside the house locked the front
door and then slid a couch in front of it, Reno said. The agents
had no choice but to ram through the front door, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Had she not acted on Saturday before dawn, word of the raid
would have spread, Reno said, and the opportunity would have been
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they could ignore us, and we had tried to be very
patient with them to effect a voluntary transfer, and then the time
comes and the law must be enforced,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives in Miami, and their supporters, have provided
sharply different accounts of the raid, saying armed agents
barreled through the door without announcing themselves, sprayed
pepper gas on bystanders and held others inside the house at
gunpoint while they seized Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to sort out the various descriptions of the raid and
question its legality, the Senate Judiciary Committee is likely to
call Reno to testify, along with a group of civic leaders who were
involved in last-minute negotiations with the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami on Thursday, Mayor Joe Carollo fired the city manager,
Donald Warshaw, who refused to dismiss the Miami police chief for
not warning the mayor about the Saturday morning raid.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief, William O'Brien, learned of the raid just
before it happened but did not inform the mayor, who had made it
clear that he sided with the boy's Miami relatives in defiance of
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo said he had lost all confidence in his police chief, but
Warshaw balked at carrying out his wishes. The mayor added,
however, that he did not fire Warshaw because of the Elian raid,
but because he had been saying bad things about him to others in
City Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
