<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS SAY BLUES' DEMISE NO FLUKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Owen Nolan said the dirtiest F-word an underdog can
hear _ ``fluke''.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about his Game 7-winning goal. The knuckler from
near center ice buried Blues goalie Roman Turek and gave the San
Jose Sharks a 2-0 lead at the first-period siren in a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a fluke, a crazy goal,'' the Sharks' winger called it.
``Another fluky goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fluky goal in a long line of them in a fluky series. The
seemingly annual case of the seasonlong underachiever suddenly
overachieving and knocking off the complacent top seed. A nice
story, but welcome back to reality and to the defending champion
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   A fluke? The Sharks aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't beat the best team in hockey by luck,'' Sharks
center Vincent Damphousse said yesterday after the team's practice
at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win to prove we belonged, and now we have to do it
again,'' Sharks winger and former Stars player Todd Harvey said.
``We know we have to bring our A-game.''
</P>
<P>
   That game is the composed and disciplined, yet gritty and
abrasive style they shoved down the Blues' throats for much of that
seven-game series. It's the game plan Sharks players advertised
yesterday for tonight's Game 1 of the Western Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to frustrate them. We have to get in front of \RJoe\S
Nieuwendyk, in front of \RMike\S Modano and slow them down and clog
up that neutral zone, as they do, and play in their zone,'' Sharks
defenseman Jeff Norton said. ``We want to crash and bang and try to
rattle the \RDerian\S Hatchers and \RDarryl\S Sydors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not pretty hockey, but you know, we're capable of
frustrating and playing a real fast game out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis series is proof. The Sharks manhandled the Blues,
physically whipped them and got them on their heels. Grinders like
Bryan Marchment and Mike Ricci, and in Games 6 and 7, Ron Stern,
came off the bench to act like a nasty rash that badgered Blues
powerhouse defenseman Chris Pronger. And while the Sharks agitated,
Pronger and the Blues seemed to flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we won that series is because we played with more
composure than St. Louis,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger spent a playoff-leading 32 minutes in the penalty box.
He had seven points, but finished even in the plus-minus rating
after posting a mind-blowing, NHL-best plus-52 in the regular
season. The Sharks will try the same get-in-your-head routine on
Stars captain Hatcher and their top skill players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of battling along the boards,''
Hatcher said. ``They're not going to give us anything, I'll tell
you that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars forward Scott Thornton: ``They play desperate at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Norton: ``That's what it's all about, throwing the puck at
the net and getting ugly goals. That's when teams are successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks don't enter the series carrying any psychological
baggage against the Stars as Edmonton did. The Sharks took four of
six from the defending champs in the regular season, including two
of three at Reunion Arena, although both victories came in the
first three months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had gone 0-for-whatever against them, then we might be
thinking, `Geez, what do we have to do?''' Norton said. ``We know
that doesn't mean anything right now unless we execute. We have to
dictate our game. If we do that, we can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Flukier things have happened.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
