<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-R-CUBAN-BOY-VIEWS-114     04-27 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CUBAN-BOY-VIEWS-1145(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBANS WHO DISAGREE WITH MIAMI MAINSRTEAM ON ELIAN KEEP QUIET OR
FACE HOSTILITY
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating to add photo note.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT31 of Carmen Duarte is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(With CUBAN-BOY-NYT) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As a playwright in Cuba, Carmen Duarte knew all too well
what state-controlled repression meant. Her work was often
censored, Duarte said, and she and the actors in her theater troupe
were once beaten by policemen incensed by the scathing social
commentary in one of her plays.
</P>
<P>
   Now living here, in the heart of the nation's largest and most
potent Cuban-American enclave, Duarte is trying once again to give
voice to a point a view that many like her say can lead to
ostracism or even threats. She believes that Elian Gonzalez should
have been reunited with his father months ago, and has said so on
her daily radio show, ``Transitions,'' broadcast on a
Spanish-language station here.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk, though, has been met by a reverse form of the anger
that Duarte encountered in Cuba, with callers to the radio station
accusing her of being an agent of Fidel Castro's government, or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always calls,'' said Duarte, 40, who came to the
United States in 1993. ``There are always insults. You always see
it with any case that inflames the people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Cuban-Americans who favor more open relations with
Havana say that advocating an end to the U.S. embargo of Cuba or
closer ties to the island have always brought scorn and threats
and, in some cases, violence.
</P>
<P>
   But many here say that the federal raid that took Elian from
Miami has impassioned people as never before, to the consternation
of Cuban-Americans who, despite their own hatred of Castro, feel
their alternative ideas regarding Cuba are rarely aired in this
politically charged city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it so polarized,'' said Dr. Max Castro, a
senior research associate at the University of Miami who studies
the exile community. ``I've never seen such a situation where you
are accosted if you say the wrong thing. It's a very heart-rending
thing, and we can't stop talking about it, and once we get talking
about it we get very emotional and it can become ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Cossio Cohen, a legal assistant at a Miami law firm, found
out just how emotional people can get, a few days before Elian was
removed from the home of Miami relatives. After expressing support
for efforts to reunite Elian with his father, Cossio Cohen said, a
co-worker berated her as a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to voice your opinion in Dade County
because you will be branded,'' said Cossio Cohen, who fled Cuba
with her mother and two brothers in 1960. ``I work for a law firm,
but if I owned a business or tried to go into politics, I would be
blackballed forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Cossio Cohen, who believes that ending the embargo of Cuba would
be the best course for furthering democratic change in Cuba, said
she had been disheartened by what she saw as a widespread disregard
for the free flow of ideas since the Elian case began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing has set us back 40 years,'' she said.
``It's driven a wedge in the Cuban community. It's turned friends
against friends, family against family. I pity my Cuban people
because I truly think that we have pain in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the sentiments is, of course, difficult. In Miami, it
is unclear how many Cuban exiles have views divergent from those
that are most often heard on local airwaves and in newspapers.
Although some leaders of more liberal Cuban groups say they
constitute a silent majority of Cuban exiles, experts disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I'd like to see it,'' said Dr. Lisandro Perez,
director of the Cuban Research Center at Florida International
University, ``I don't think that there's any evidence to show that.
And you would expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls conducted by Florida International University to gauge
exile reaction to Cuban issues showed that, as recently as 1997, 78
percent of Cuban-Americans expressed support for the continuation
of the embargo. But at the same time, 25 percent believe it has not
worked well, and 51.6 percent said they supported a ``dialogue''
with the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   On the Elian matter, however, the exiles have appeared more
united against Cuba's government, with 83 percent of
Cuban-Americans in Dade County wanting to see the boy remain with
his Miami relatives, according to a Miami Herald poll published on
April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Many with minority views avoid nasty confrontations, they say,
by simply avoiding speaking out, even if it is at the office with
well-known co-workers or in a bar with friends. Some believe
sharing their views could hurt them professionally. Others simply
want to avoid the discomfort of angering someone they know. Some
even say they avoid voicing their opinions with relatives, fearing
a fissure with more conservative family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' said E. Rodriguez, a 48-year-old educator
who asked that she not be fully identified. ``Here, I could be
labeled a Communist. I could lose my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who arrived in Miami in the 1960s, said she had long
believed that closer ties with Cuba _ an end to the economic
embargo and the unfettered movement of tourists and others to the
island _ were more productive than the hard-line stand that has
defined 41 years of U.S. policy. She also believes that Elian was
manipulated by Cuban-American exile leaders looking for a symbol to
further their own cause, not because of concerns over the boy's
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But while she shares her views with close friends, she said, she
has been told to be careful what she says to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never made it public,'' she said. ``What is the story
here is the lack of freedom. I've been warned not to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lisandro Perez, director of the Cuban Research Center at
Florida International University said that those who took a less
hard-line stance against Castro feared being ostracized or
suffering the consequences at their workplace, a very real
possibility in a place where Cuban-Americans have influence in
everything from business to government to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want people to label you as sympathizing with the
enemy,'' Perez said. ``Anything less than a hard-line position is
seen as sympathizing with the Castro government, and the community
has a lot of institutions through which it can pressure people to
conformity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who favor an open channel to Cuba blame much of the
unbending nature of exile dialogue on Miami's Spanish-language
stations, whose talk-show hosts often label those with softer
positions as Communists and even give out home phone numbers of
people like Duarte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, this society has been converted into a society of
fear,'' said Angel Fernandez Varela, a retired bank chairman who
served in the Cuban Congress before the revolution. ``It's the way
people are attacked. And among the worst is that radio. There are
people, many people, who feel like I do, but they're terribly quiet
because they're scared.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; BC-CUBAN-BOY-VIEWS-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MIAMI: they're scared.'' &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Still, several groups that have for years lobbied Congress for a
softer stand on Cuba in order to improve the lives of ordinary
Cubans who they say are suffering under the embargo. While those
leaders have made a conscious decision to speak out publicly, they
say that it has been hard to gather public support because of both
the climate of fear and because of the difficulty in getting their
views aired in Miami's conservative media.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up to me all the time and say, `We feel exactly
the way you do, but we would never say this in public,''' said
Elena Freyre, executive director of the Cuban Committee for
Democracy, a group of Cuban-American professionals that lobbies
from Washington and Miami. ``I speak out to honor my father's
memory. My father left everything he cherished to live in a country
where his two daughters could speak out. I'll be darned if I ever
forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in well-known anti-Castro groups in Miami scoffed at
such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Rodriguez, vice president of Brigade 2506, an organization
composed of Bay of Pigs veterans, said that in Miami ``there is
liberty to say what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Rodriguez, a former CIA operative who wrote about his
anti-Castro experiences in a book, ``Shadow Warrior,'' said some
groups advocating relations with Cuba were controlled by Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are small groups that are being run from Cuba,'' he
said. ``Cuba has several groups that they handle here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans like Elisa Greenberg, who believes Elian should
be with his father, cringe at such comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that with some people, they felt that anyone speaking
out against them was in favor of the Communist regime and was a
Castro lover or a Castro agent,'' said Greenberg, 58, who came to
the United States before Castro took power. ``If you want to call
me anything, call me a Cuba lover because I believe in democracy
and I believe, in time, if we work towards it, good things will
happen over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she was invited to Ted Koppel's town hall meeting in
Miami earlier this month, a gathering broadcast on ABC's
``Nightline,'' she was afraid to speak up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there was apprehension on my part to speak my mind on the
matter,'' said Greenberg, noting that most of the exiles in the
audience were vocally supportive of keeping Elian in Miami. ``I was
afraid to speak up. I didn't feel comfortable and over there, I was
in the minority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9299 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOK-REVIEW-$ADV3     04-27 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOK-REVIEW-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLICKS AND MORTAR': HARD LESSONS LEARNED AT SCHWAB  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface sentence in 7th graf should be italicized.) 
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something endearing about a big man who confesses
fault. David S. Pottruck, the president and co-chief executive of
Charles Schwab, the huge financial services company, qualifies in
both size and professional stature.
</P>
<P>
   A star linebacker and heavyweight wrestler at the University of
Pennsylvania 30 years ago, Pottruck remains an imposing figure.
</P>
<P>
   And, wow, in ``Clicks and Mortar'' (Jossey-Bass, $26), does he
own up to some blunders: Nearing the apex of a sparkling career, he
was stunned when his boss observed that he was ``too persuasive.''
Blinded by his reflex to steamroll over any colleague who differed
with him, he was effectively suppressing any ideas but his own.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Pottruck writes that in therapy he came to
understand that he had been an inept husband, having lost two wives
to divorce through an inability to share his feelings or his life.
Following what he calls ``a good business model,'' he had treated
each spouse as if she were a colleague in another department. The
wife had her domain; he had his.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't changed, it would have sunk me,'' he writes.
``Unless I watch it, I can be overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   And change he did. Pottruck is the courageous risk-taker who
transformed Schwab into a pace-setting Internet enterprise. But he
first transformed himself into the antithesis of the dominant,
my-way-or-the-highway executive.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck writes that he has concentrated, with evident success,
on ``listening to hear rather than to answer.'' And in three
decades of financial journalism, I have never met his equal as a
listener. The experience is like being bathed in respectful,
intelligent attention.  &UR; Why is this man so attentive to little old
me? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   His new style has become essential for managing the
self-directed employees that Information Age companies must have.
Pottruck teaches that authentic caring is the touchstone, ``the
most important aspect of being trustworthy.'' Schwab depends on its
people for constant, creative innovation. It's his job to inspire
passionate commitment to Schwab's core values and goals.
</P>
<P>
   Listening, Pottruck writes, is not so much a skill but ``an
attitude with a single focus: the more I am known by those I want
to follow me, and the more I can know them, the greater will be our
ability to do great things together.'' To earn trust, he says,
leaders must reveal their true selves to an uncomfortable extent.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck has the generosity of spirit to tell his lessons at his
own expense. At one point, he offended female colleagues by
thoughtlessly reaching outside Schwab to fill new senior positions
with only men. Another time he ordered offices to open on Saturdays
with no consultation with the colleagues affected.
</P>
<P>
   He was skeptical of instituting no-fee individual retirement
accounts, which in fact would prove an enormous success. He got
Schwab out of the electronic payments business, a service that
Quicken has found enormously lucrative. (``Maybe this wasn't my
best recommendation!'')
</P>
<P>
   If there is a better handbook on adapting to the Internet
economy, I have yet to find it. Pottruck and his co-author, Terry
Pearce, have produced an eminently readable guide to building a
great enterprise in this era of relentless change and ephemeral
relationships. Pottruck found a calling in zealously guarding the
Schwab shrine, but his lessons are about clobbering the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce counsels Schwab on ``executive communication'' and
teaches leadership at the Haas School of Business at the University
of California at Berkeley, sometimes with Pottruck. He came to that
vocation after 17 years at IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Their account is remarkable in how deeply they seek to
understand the roots of a corporate culture and how
self-consciously they labor to shape and sustain Schwab's.
</P>
<P>
   Pottruck plays Michael Jordan to Pearce's Phil Jackson. Very
much the coach, Pearce opens each topic, from building cultural
commitment to managing technology, with a preface and closes it
with a cogent summation. In between, Pottruck reflects on his
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally Pearce steps out of his role, ruminating, for
instance, on a semiserious quip by Tom Peters that every chief
executive should look for a chief information officer who is under
15. Pearce reflects on his own sons' absolute comfort with the
Internet. ``I'm sure,'' he writes, ``that if a live cat walked out
of a video display into the living room, they would say something
like `cool!' while I was heading for the bomb shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion he draws: ``I had better find within myself the
courage and capacity to learn technology like a 15-year-old. I had
better redevelop the inquiring and `anything is possible' attitude
of a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   An informed dabbler in anthropology, Pearce applies its
teachings to business. Cultures, including business cultures, he
says, are spread and sustained through myth, image and ritual.
Schwab pointedly honors its rituals and celebrates its heroes. When
market volume soars, all hands _ ranking executives included _ turn
out to man the phones, a ritual known as ``market storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The best ``myths'' are always true, and one true tale at Schwab
centers on an elderly couple who went bust in the 1987 market
crash, owing Schwab a substantial sum. Rather than press the couple
to the wall, Schwab settled the debt by taking title to their home
but granting them lifetime occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, after the husband died, the house burned to the
ground. Rather than pocketing the insurance proceeds, Schwab had
the house rebuilt, and the widow lived in it until her death.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Clicks and Mortar'' theme is teamwork, total teamwork: In
offering bonuses or other incentives to top performers, companies
should never limit the rewards to a certain percentage of
employees. (After all, the more who succeed, the better.)
Department budgets should be set by performance ratios, encouraging
departments to outdo themselves, rather than scrap for larger
shares of a fixed pie.
</P>
<P>
   For an easy read, the book is sophisticated and well grounded in
academic findings. It can be read for grand themes or mined for
nuggets. At one point Schwab found itself taking two weeks to
answer customer complaints that reached the chairman's office,
mostly demands for refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Executives first asked: How do we cut that to 10 days? Answer:
some streamlining. So how do we cut it to a week, they asked? That
required closer analysis, yielding the innovation of responding by
phone instead of by mail.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, how to cut it to 48 hours? That took imagination.
Schwab dug out the average cost of pursuing a complaint _ and
decided to concede any claim for less. It accepted the cost as an
investment in keeping customers happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
