<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-COLLEGES-HNS &LR;      04-27 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COLLEGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COLLEGE FACULTY MEMBERS TO SEEK NEW MERIT RAISES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Faculty members at Texas colleges and
universities will vie for new merit raises in September from a $40
million sale of state assets, Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The money, raised from the sale of stock abandoned at financial
institutions and now in the state's possession, means university
administrators will receive 3 percent more than the Legislature
previously allocated for faculty salaries next fall, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to increase faculty salaries to help Texas' higher
education institutions attract, retain and reward the very best,
high quality instructors,`` Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said she is striving to help close a wage gap between
Texas faculty members and their counterparts elsewhere. With an
average salary of $53,360 in Texas, instructors of higher education
earn 10 percent less than in other large states, according to the
American Association of University Professors.
</P>
<P>
   A group representing Texas university faculty reacted with mixed
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the tradition of the Legislature preferring merit
increases. I think our organization would prefer an
across-the-board increase, particularly in light of Texas higher
education salaries being the lowest of the 11 most populous
states,'' said Chuck Hempstead, executive director of the Texas
Association of College Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year granted Rylander the authority to find
money for merit raises for higher education faculty. While public
school teachers had received automatic across-the-board pay raises
from Texas lawmakers, those in state colleges and universities were
left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here today to say I have found the money within my own
agency,'' Rylander said of the stock, which financial institutions
are required to turn over to the state if unclaimed for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller _ flanked by leading officials from the
University of Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, University of Houston and Texas
Tech _ emphasized that the pay raises go only to those deemed by
administrators as most worthy. Each university, college, technical
school or medical institution has total discretion over how to
distribute the money and to whom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge story for those in higher education, a huge
story for perhaps those in the business community,'' said Grover S.
Campbell, vice chancellor for government relations, University of
Houston System.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas System Chancellor William Cunningham said
that if universities can find an extra 1 percent to 2 percent in
other funding sources, it's possible the state can start to close
the disparity in faculty salaries between Texas and other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step for higher education,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   University officials attending the announcement said Texas
schools have the hardest time attracting and retaining professors
in the most competitive fields of business, law, computer science,
the sciences, information technology and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were not willing to reveal how they might distribute
the merit increases, or to whom. Campbell from UH noted that wage
disparities are quite large already, depending on specialities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A law professor in intellectual property is a pretty hot
commodity right now. If we've got him, he's probably making
$100,000 plus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the English departments, however, it's more like $35,000 to
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
