<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 AMERICA IS AN EQUAL OPPORTUNITY COUNTRY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's reassuring to know you don't have to live next to a Kennedy
compound to make a cottage industry out of renting your lawn to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of the house where &UR; Elian Gonzalez  &LR; lived in Miami, who
had been charging as much as $300 a day to rent driveways or spots
in their front yards to TV crews and other media, are taking
``financial hits,'' reports the Washington Post, as a result of the
circus leaving town.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The domain name  &LR; eliangonza &LR;   &LR; lez.com &LR;  is for sale on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TALKING UP TALK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tina Brown &LR;  of Talk magazine was in San Francisco on Wednesday,
April 26, for a screening of ``Takedown,'' a TalkMedia movie based
on the 1995 cross-country chase and arrest of computer hacker
 &UR; Kevin Mitnick &LR; . The movie, a product of the collaboration between
Brown's company and Miramax, has nothing to do with the magazine,
but copies were stacked everywhere, and much of the talk was about
Talk, which is what editors merrily refer to as ``buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Today's  &UR; Al Neuharth &LR;  gave the magazine a lukewarm B to
Oprah's A last week, while Salon noted that sales of more than a
million copies of issue No. 1 of Talk had dropped to just over
500,000 since then. Talk hopes the figure will be up to 600,000 by
August, the magazine's first anniversary, but Salon's  &UR; Sean &LR; 
 &UR; Elder &LR;  called those numbers ``grim.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Salon co-hosted the screening, and before the movie
rolled, Brown said laughingly that she hoped their partnership on
the event would prevent the online magazine from further Talk
trashing.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had admitted to the Independent of London a few weeks ago
that there might have been some problems. ``I probably made the
mistake of putting all the good stuff in the first issue,'' she
said, ``and didn't look forward enough to the next couple.'' But
she was seamlessly optimistic when Personals asked her about Talk's
troubles. The reports, she said, are ``wrong. The numbers are
excellent. We're growing every month, in numbers and in quality.
There's a growing groundswell, and we're very well on track. It's
very strong.'' She promised ``very hot'' stories in the next two
issues, but wouldn't say what they were, except to call them
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ANIMAL FARM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest issue of Washingtonian magazine headlines a story
about local attractions: ``Going Wild at the National Zoo.'' And at
the Double Tree Inn in Dana Point,  &UR; Jim &LR;   &UR; Adams &LR;  turned on the TV
and found he was watching a tour of a dildo factory in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ In ``Wash Your Hair With Whipped Cream'' (Hyperion; $8.95), &UR; Joey
Green &LR;  advises that applying Preparation H to the shaved skin of a
horse prevents the hair from growing back white. This tip may
result in more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ Vogue informs sagging readers of the Techno-Breastlift, which
uses `` `microcurrents' to firm your chest, promising perkiness.''
Getting zapped in the chest is a 12-session, $1,026 process.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _  &UR; Brad Rowe &LR; , who appeared in ``The '70s'' and is a former
finance manager for Republican senatorial campaigns, explains
himself, in a Vanity Fair interview forwarded by  &UR; Angela Weber &LR; :
``What the doctors said was that my umbilical cord was cut in a
certain place. And since I have a ridiculously low amount of body
fat, my belly button looks bigger than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ And all this time, the Kinsey Institute seemed to insist that
its studies of sex were dry and un-prurient. ``Peek,'' a very racy
collection of photographs from the institute's collections, is
being published by Arena ($60) this fall.
</P>
