<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROX-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT BUYS STAKE IN DIGITAL LICENSING  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chroncile 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hoping to tap into the increasing amount of
copyrighted content bubbling up on the Internet, Microsoft and
Xerox on Thursday joined forces to sell software that protects such
material distributed online.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture, ContentGuard Inc., relies on so-called digital
rights management (DRM) technology _ software that limits the
number of times a song, poem, movie or business document can be
viewed, downloaded or printed _ developed by Xerox. Microsoft will
take a minority stake in the company and be its largest initial
customer.
</P>
<P>
   For both Xerox and Microsoft, ContentGuard is an attempt to get
their products in on the ground floor of the growing market for
digital content, which they say will reach $275 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ContentGuard, which its backers plan to take public, expects to
make money by licensing the technology to other softwaremakers,
publishers and e-tailers, and by taking a portion of transaction
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Initially Microsoft will integrate ContentGuard into its Reader
technology, which presents text in booklike format on computer
screens and handheld devices. Eventually, the company will
integrate ContentGuard in Media Player, its viewer for online music
and video; WebTV, its Internet TV device; and its Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the companies are trying to create a de facto
standard in the increasingly crowded DRM industry as more writers,
musicians and filmmakers turn to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-profile example of the demand for online books
occurred last month, when horror author Stephen King made his
16,000-word novella ``Riding the Bullet'' available only via the
Internet. A flood of about 500,000 orders over three days swamped
the servers for several e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   That said, consumers have been leery of punching their credit
card numbers into a dialog box to read online content, and few Web
sites have succeeded with the pay-to-view model.
</P>
<P>
   ContentGuard, to be based in McLean, Va., is hoping it's a
chicken-and-egg issue. They say the consumers will come if popular
books, movies and music are online. And those will arrive only if
those distributing the content can do so securely and make a nickel
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-content economy is in its infancy,'' ContentGuard chief
executive Michael Miron said in an interview. ``Most of the best
stuff isn't on the Web because artists, authors and publishers
don't have the tools to manage what their work is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ContentGuard co-Chairman Dick Brass conceded that no
copyright protection is foolproof and that ``hackers are clever.
There are workarounds for dishonest people for all kinds of
media.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said Napster, the software that lets people
trade MP3-format music files online, has effectively wiped out the
potential to protect a whole generation of music. But they hope
record companies will use ContentGuard to protect new music.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock closed at $69.81, up $1.81. Xerox closed at
$27.06, down 94 cents.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
