r f BC-CISCO-KICKBACK-SFCHRO     04-27 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-KICKBACK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO ALLEGES KICKBACK DEAL BY 2 SALESMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cisco Systems, the world's largest data
networking company, said Thursday it fired, suspended or reassigned
a half-dozen workers after learning about an embarrassing kickback
scheme involving its sales force.
</P>
<P>
   In a complicated scheme, the San Jose, Calif., company says two
of its salesmen helped arrange the sale of more than $50 million in
equipment and services to American MetroComm, a Louisiana
telecommunications firm. As part of the deal, a Cisco reseller,
Worldwide Web Systems of Miami, was supposed to provide American
MetroComm with software and help set up the networking equipment.
Cisco agreed to finance the deal and began sending the equipment
and payments to Worldwide Web Systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisco alleges that every time it sent a check to Worldwide
Web Systems, Worldwide immediately sent part of the money _ the
``kickback'' _ to companies controlled by the salesmen, Kevin
Bennett of Cleveland and Vincent Rotondo of Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco says it found out about the scheme in December, after
Worldwide had a falling out with Bennett and Rotondo. Worldwide
sued the salesmen in federal court in Florida, accusing them of
extorting $5 million in payments. It also claimed Rotondo made
death threats against a Worldwide executive.
</P>
<P>
   American MetroComm also complained to Cisco that Worldwide never
provided the help it promised and demanded compensation from Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation, Cisco said it fired two workers,
including Rotondo, suspended another and reassigned three more,
including the salesmen's supervisor. Two more workers, including
Bennett, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal was first reported Thursday in the Wall Street
Journal. The matter has also sparked an FBI investigation and a
second lawsuit: Cisco sued Worldwide and American MetroComm on
Thursday in San Jose federal court, seeking repayment for its
loans. Neither Worldwide nor American MetroComm returned calls.
Cisco also filed arbitration claims against the salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI investigation is focused on the two salesmen, Cisco
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's attorney told the Journal the kickbacks ``never
happened.'' Rotondo's lawyer told the paper that the payments were
for services _ not improper commissions _ and that Cisco encouraged
his outside investments.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to disregard the news. Cisco's stock jumped
$2.25, to $69, yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco insists the arrangement was an isolated incident and
tightened its conflict-of-interest policies a month ago to prevent
similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Cisco had only required workers to disclose
investments in outside companies. Now it specifically bars workers
from investing in Cisco customers, partners or suppliers they deal
with on behalf of Cisco, unless they receive special permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the incident very seriously,'' said spokeswoman
Lorene Arey. But Arey said she doubted the incident would tarnish
the company's image.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cisco salesmen are widely considered aggressive,
awarding steep discounts to win business or making a plane trip to
close a sale, they don't have a reputation as sleazy or unethical,
said Esmeralda Silva, an analyst with International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   She said she cannot recall hearing about any similar allegations
against Cisco workers. ``This is very extreme,'' she said. But
generally, she added that workers often invest in the industries
and companies they know best, which can sometimes lead to conflicts
of interest.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
