<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9320 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-JOBFAIR-SELECTIVE-SFC     04-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBFAIR-SELECTIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB SEEKERS GETTING PICKY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; A warier, tougher type of job seeker waded
out into the WorkWorld career fair in San Francisco on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a roller-coaster month on Wall Street, plus reports of
some e-tailers running out of money, the job hunters were
determined to pick correctly in Silicon Valley's version of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Take Fernando Custodio. The San Francisco resident has already
been through one IPO meltdown. He wouldn't identify his current
employer but said its stock went public at $40 and now trades at
$11.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's not deterred from seeking dot-com riches; it's the
only way he can fulfill his goal of retiring by age 40 _ just 16
years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta roll that dice,'' said Custodio, who came to
WorkWorld seeking a systems administrator position.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of about 2,500 job hunters cruising the booths of 132
companies at the Bill Graham Civic Auditorium. The companies _
largely tech-related firms looking for everything from software
architects to XML experts _ had paid $4,500 to $10,000 for a chance
to recruit at the fair, sponsored by online job site HotJobs.com.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment in the Bay Area at record lows, the job
hunters had the upper hand. According to the California Employment
Development Department, the unemployment rate is 2.1 percent in
Santa Clara County, 2.8 percent in Alameda and Contra Costa
counties, and just 1.9 percent in San Francisco, San Mateo and
Marin counties. That compares with 5 percent statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Berkett, recruiting manager at Driveway, a San Francisco
company that provides file-storage space on the Web, said filling
open slots can be a tough sell. Like many firms at WorkWorld, the
company is bulking up dramatically: It needs to add 60 workers to
its 70-person staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting multiple offers; they can write their own
tickets,'' she said. ``Everyone wants to see what your business
model is, and that you're going to turn a profit at some point. We
have to sell them on the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides standard trade-show gimmicks like free Frisbees, mouse
pads and candy, plenty of companies were handing out fact sheets
packed with statistics on their customers, funding and long-term
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job candidates will be much more discerning,'' said Gail
Broson, a senior analyst at IPO Monitor in Palo Alto, Calif.,
speaking before the show. ``People who have some good notches on
their gun belt won't take the kind of risks they might have taken a
year ago because the market is so volatile now.''
</P>
<P>
   Anja Plowright of Berkeley, Calif., who brought her 3-week-old,
Andrew, in a stroller, was looking for a marketing position. She
was interviewing companies _ rather than the other way around _
``to make sure they have solid (financial) backing and who it's
from, how serious they are about sticking to their business plan,
when is the IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismal performance of recent IPOs was on many job seekers'
minds. A third of the 159 Bay Area companies that have gone public
since January 1999 are now trading below their offering price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leery of someone offering a lot of stock that could turn
into mush,'' said Oban Lambie, a systems administrator in Taos,
N.M., who wants to move to San Francisco by June. ``I can't eat
stock. I need money so I can afford to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambie stands a good chance of getting money thrown at him. At
10 p.m. Monday night, he posted his resume on Craig's List
( &LR; www.craigslist.org &LR; ), a San Francisco online bulletin board that
Forrester Research this month ranked as the most efficient
job-recruitment site. By Wednesday morning, Lambie had 70
responses. ``It's overwhelming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kristina Raines, who was seeking a systems administrator
position, scoffed at companies' attempts to lure new employees with
promises of work environments more fun than Disneyland. Internet
search firm Flyswat had employees garbed as giant flies handing out
full-color brochures touting the amenities of its South of Market
office _ a '50s diner-themed kitchen with all-you-can-eat gummy
bears and soda, a Moroccan tea room, a beach-themed meeting room
with real sand, Ping-Pong and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A foosball table isn't going to make me take a job,'' Raines
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent rash of bad news, experts commenting before
the show said they think new companies still will be able to staff
up. ``Historically throughout the Bay Area, people will always go
to new, exciting startups,'' said venture capitalist Philip
Halperin, general partner in Weston Presidio Capital. ``That's the
gene pool that has proliferated within the Bay Area since 1849.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Haley, managing director of Redpoint Ventures in Menlo Park,
Calif., said recruiting good people has always been a challenge but
can be overcome with aggressive networking.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in the throes of stock-market woes may be having a
harder time keeping the employees they already have. Last week,
headhunter Ellen Hathaway of San Francisco's Exceptional People
Inc. hired a free-lancer to cold-call executives at dot-com firms.
Usually, she gets at most a 2 percent response rate from such
calls. This time, 15 percent of the 100 or so people called said
they were interested in looking for another job.
</P>
<P>
   One senior executive at a dot-com applauded Hathaway for her
timing: The company will soon announce that it is three months away
from bankruptcy. ``This person had enjoyed the ride but wanted to
go to safer shores _ an organization with revenue-generation
opportunities,'' Hathaway said. The executive is about to sign on
with a ``more staid company,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   How can you figure out which companies will go belly-up? Faina
Brun of San Francisco, who was at WorkWorld looking for a job as a
quality assurance tester, had a fatalistic attitude. ``Nobody
knows; only God.''
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to Carolyn Said at &LR;  csaid(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
