<SLUG> BC-ARREST-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO MAN, 31, ARRESTED IN DEATH OF TEXAS A&AMP;M STUDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ A 31-year-old San Antonio man was jailed on
a murder charge Thursday for the mysterious slaying of Texas A&AMP;M
University student Kerry J. Kujawa of Richmond during a meeting the
two arranged in an Internet chat room.
</P>
<P>
   A motive for the killing _ and crucial details about it _
remained unclear. Investigators said the crime was not part of a
robbery scheme, but they wouldn't say whether the male suspect was
posing as a female named Kelly who the victim told his family he
was planning to meet in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Wayne Lockwood confessed to the crime and was caught at 2
a.m. Thursday while in a San Antonio hospital, where he was being
treated for undisclosed medical problems not related to the murder,
said Hays County Sheriff Don Montague.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood, who is unemployed, has no previous criminal record or
history of Internet-related incidents, officials said. ``There was
no indication he tried to lure others'' using a bogus cyberspace
persona, said Detective Samuel D. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood was released from the hospital a few hours after his
arrest and was taken before a Bexar County magistrate to have bond
set before being transferred to the county jail in San Marcos,
Montague said. He was being held in lieu of $500,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Kujawa, 20, was slain with a single gunshot to the back of the
head, but where and when the shooting occurred weren't immediately
disclosed by officials who said they didn't want to jeopardize
their ongoing probe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, investigators had speculated that the murder occurred
soon after Kujawa left College Station on April 7 to meet the
Internet acquaintance. The victim's car was found parked at the
Easterwood Airport in College Station on April 10, before he was
reported missing, but how and when it got there weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Kujawa's body was hidden on a ranch in Hays County,
the victim's family received several reassuring messages,
purportedly from the victim, that were sent from the e-mail account
of ``Kelly.'' The messages said Kujawa was in San Antonio taking
care of his new friend. Texas A&AMP;M police said ``Kelly'' claimed to
be a female with boyfriend problems.
</P>
<P>
   A pending analysis of Lockwood's confiscated computer should
help establish whether Lockwood and ``Kelly'' were one and the
same, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the arresting officer, said Lockwood was ``somewhat
cooperative'' during a six-hour interrogation that resulted in a
``full confession ... He confirmed most of our suspicions.''
Williams would not disclose whether Lockwood provided a written or
recorded statement, calling it only an ``interview.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're unwilling to comment on the motive ... There are a lot
of questions we can't answer. We owe it to the victim and the
families,'' Williams said. But he ruled out robbery or attempted
robbery as possible motives.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrest, law enforcement officials said they believed
Kujawa, a mechanical engineering junior at A&AMP;M and National Merit
Scholar from Austin High School in Richmond, disappeared after
leaving for San Antonio to meet ``Kelly.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the suspect and victim apparently made contact
through an Internet Relay Chat network, possibly in a chat room
whose theme ``was not sexual in nature,'' Williams said. However,
Williams declined to characterize the types of chat rooms or ``chat
channels'' visited by the victim or suspect.
</P>
<P>
   On April 19, the day before he was reported missing at Texas
A&AMP;M, Kujawa's badly decomposed body was found hidden on a ranch
near Dripping Springs in northwest Hays County. Because the body
was found in his jurisdiction, the Hays County sheriff took the
lead role in the ongoing investigation that also involves Texas
Rangers in five cities and police in San Antonio, College Station
and at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hays County prosecutors have agreed to handle the case,
they have the option of turning it over to another jurisdiction if
it's determined that the killing occurred in another county or if
the body was taken through another county, Montague said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to arresting Lockwood, the sheriff said his officers
searched Lockwood's residence Wednesday night in an upscale part of
northwest San Antonio and confiscated a computer and other
evidence. Williams, calling the case ``extremely complex,'' said
there was a ``mountain of stuff that has to be sorted through.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Texas A&AMP;M and its Association of Former
Students offered a reward of up to $10,000 for information leading
to the apprehension of the murderer, but investigators indicated
that the arrest did not result from the reward's posting.
</P>
<P>
   Kujawa was a President's Endowed Scholarship recipient at A&AMP;M.
He is survived by his parents, John and Lucille Kujawa, and his
brother, Kraig.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
