<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHTINEN PROGRESSING, BUT STILL NOT READY TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL, JENNIFER FLOYD AND CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ While Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said
yesterday he's optimistic about injured winger Jere Lehtinen's
progress, Lehtinen will not play in Game 1 tonight against San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said that Lehtinen has skated the past two days with
other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked really good,'' said Brad Lukowich, who skated with
Lehtinen. ``Whether or not he's hurting, I couldn't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the next step is for Lehtinen, who missed 65
games this season because of a fractured right ankle, is to join
practice. That could happen in the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than Lehtinen, who is really close, we are healthy,''
Hitchcock said. ``This will be a series key injuries are going to
be a factor. Hopefully we can stay healthy and get healthy right
along.'' \Nsubheds:Marshall ready and waiting After playing in two
of the five games in the first-round series against Edmonton, Stars
winger Grant Marshall is still not sure if he'll be in the lineup
against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the wrong guy to ask,'' Marshall said. ``I am going like I
am playing. You never know until \Rtoday\S.''  &QL; 
Bryan who?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars aren't about to let Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment
get under their skin before the series has begun. So they spent
much of yesterday's media session deflecting questions about
Marchment, who has become Public Enemy No. 1 in Dallas since he
knocked out three Stars players with knee injuries in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things I don't like about what he does, but
I'm not going to get in a words thing about him,'' Stars forward
Grant Marshall said. ``He's a guy who's playing really, really well
for their team right now. ... There's no question he likes to step
up and hit. But you can't just make it Stars vs. Marchment. It's
the Stars vs. San Jose. They have a very good hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars say that they haven't spent much time thinking about
Marchment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were that worried about Marchment, then that's what San
Jose wants. We're not,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said.  &QL; 
There are other issues
</P>
<P>
   While much of talk is focusing on Bryan Marchment and the rest
of the Sharks bruisers, not as much has been said about
high-scoring forwards Owen Nolan, Vincent Damphousse and Mike
Ricci.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about their defense to be honest,'' Derian
Hatcher said. ``I'm worried about their forwards.''  &QL; 
Isn't this fun?
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock appeared to be a little loose after yesterday's
practice, almost as if he can't wait for this series to begin. Is
he excited to get this thing going?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am, yeah,'' said Hitchcock, who knows Sharks coach Darryl
Sutter and Sharks assistant coach Paul Baxter. ``I've known them
for years. ... They know me. These are WHL \RWestern Hockey
League\S boys going at it. We know how to play them, and they know
how to play us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
