<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-535&AMP;ADD-NY     04-27 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD HASN'T ALWAYS BEEN KIND, BUT KNICKS ARE UPBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Johnson was asked whether the Knicks doubted
themselves after two narrow victories against the Toronto Raptors
at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you from, Toronto?'' Johnson asked. ``We won two
games. Doubt these two games? Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were unconcerned that they won Game 1 by 4 points and
Game 2 by a point. The only number they care about is 15, the total
number of victories it takes to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win is a win,'' the Knicks' Allan Houston said. ``That's
what our expectations are. And if we're going to get to that point
it's not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy before the series spoke of a need to start
quickly in Game 1. The Knicks dominated the first quarter,
outscoring the Raptors by 27-12and then hung on for a 92-88 victory
that wasn't secured until the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 2, Van Gundy thought his players seemed
overconfident and, sure enough, the Raptors raced out to a 15-point
lead in the second quarter and held a 14-point margin early in the
fourth quarter. But the Knicks rallied, outscoring the Raptors by
29-16 to win, 84-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then in a playoff series you have a real close
game like this,'' Marcus Camby said. ``Some team just beats on you
the whole game, but the other team finds a way to get out. I think
we kind of snuck one out. We didn't play particularly good
basketball, but we found a way to get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The series moves to Toronto, where the Knicks have had their
troubles, dropping both regular-season meetings by lopsided scores,
91-70 on Feb. 14 and by 86-71 on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the Knicks have had trouble winning on the road this
season. They lost their last four regular-season games away from
the Garden to finish 17-24 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd have won this game, homecourt advantage would have
had nothing to do with it,'' Johnson said. ``It'd be 1-1 going to
their place and they'd have home-court advantage. Now we're up two
and we can put a little pressure on those guys. We haven't won up
their in Toronto in a while, but we're up two games. We need to go
up there and play the way we played the first quarter of the first
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the postseason is a different time, as evidenced by the
Knicks' improbable path to the finals last season, when they were
6-2 on the road in the playoffs before dropping both games in San
Antonio. After Game 2 on Wednesday, they seemed determined to
squeeze the life out of the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough, but we're not going to make it easy on
them,'' said Latrell Sprewell, who hit the game-winning shot over
Vince Carter with 7.9 seconds remaining. ``To be honest, I'd like
to get it done in the next game. These guys are tough and we don't
want to give them any life.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby said after Game 2: ``It would be great for me to sweep
these guys, but that would be tough. They have a lot of veterans,
key players with pride who don't want to be swept. It will tough,
tougher than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors' Tracy McGrady, who shut down Houston in Game 2,
said: ``We're coming back. We've been so close in two games. We
could easily be up, 2-0, instead of down, 2-0.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Houston, if fact, has been a highly paid observer in the fourth
quarter of each game. In Game 1, he was 0 for 3 from the field
after scoring 21 points in the first three quarters. In Game 2, he
was on the bench until Johnson fouled out with 5 minutes 9 seconds
to play, and he did not hit a field goal. Houston's only points
came when he was fouled with 38.5 seconds left and converted two
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't get in a rhythm,'' Houston said after the game.
``The bottom line is I didn't let the game come to me as much as I
did in the past. Sometimes you can be a little too aggressive.
That's what I was tonight. You learn from it. In the last minutes I
said I was going to let it come to me and take what comes and at
the same time try to be aggressive. That's what happened the last
few minutes. I think I burden myself too much with scoring and
taking shots and it kind of backfired on me because I just wanted
to be aggressive, but at the same time, relaxed a little, and let
the game come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston still contributed in the end, driving and dishing off to
Patrick Ewing for a dunk with 1:06 left, and then hitting the free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I've learned,'' Houston said. ``It doesn't matter
what happens. If you're in the game that's when you can help your
team. I just wanted to put myself in a position where I could.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
