<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     04-27 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYSHAWN LIKES WHAT HE SEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson, who's never had a problem getting the word
out, shrugs when it's suggested he could become sports' version of
the king of all media.
</P>
<P>
   But, yes, he's already having a license plate frame made for his
car that says ``Keyshawn.com'' for his soon-to-revved-up Web site.
Likewise, he's already prepared to do battle with whomever to claim
what should be his in a media world that's constantly grabbing for
his opinions and images to entertain their own readers, viewers and
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, at the Interactive Sports 2000 West conference
in Santa Monica, Calif., for sports online media companies, the
newest Tampa Bay Bucs receiver, one-time New York media maven and
former USC All- American entertained hundreds of techies with his
visions of self-contained media supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   During a seminar entitled ``Web Rights and Sports Properties:
What Does the Future Hold?'' Johnson tried to build a beachhead in
defense of his right to promote himself as a property. It shows how
he could be ahead of the curve when it comes to individual athletes
rocking sports' continuing new voyage into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My site has only been up for a week, but mine will be more
advanced than probably a lot of sites with athletes because I want
to be involved and be more in depth,'' said Johnson, who signed
with Santa Monica-based Broadband.com to start a Web home first on
AthletesDirect.com and then his own Web venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably have some flack with the NFL over some things I
want to tap into. It'll come down to a fine line sometimes. Things
like logos and colors. The NFL may own them, but ultimately we wear
them _ and in fact if we didn't wear them, it wouldn't be much use
to them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   At immediate stake is control of video and audio clips, which TV
and radio pay rights fees for but don't always have exclusive
control over. Most Internet rights are owned by the leagues and
those images and sounds are, for the time being, funneled through
their official league sites. Ad revenue is being also being shared
and redistributed by the leagues to help teams they feel are most
in need.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Web's virile nature, the rapid advances in
technology and the constant redefining of boundaries, the league
rules and bylaws don't keep up with the latest in media rights and
wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   As athletes like Johnson continue to be inundated with media
requests _ including much more from the Internet for chats and the
like _ it behooves them to take control of their own message and
direct it toward their own sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some have taken that to an extreme, blocking out TV, radio and
print reporters while ``talking'' only on their site. In the 'Net
biz, it's known as ``commodity content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their prerogative,'' said Johnson. ``I have fan sites
who ask me to come on and do chats, and as long as I have the time,
I'll do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always deal with the media. I don't want to (use the Web
site to hide behind). That's not my nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I have something exclusive _ if I was about to sign
with Tampa Bay in about five hours _ then I'll have it first on my
site. My site will be for my fans instead of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   That will include links to newspaper sites that have
!ital!anything to write about Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A recurring theme from the two-day conference was that the
Internet is allowing teams and athletes to become media themselves
_ owning their own media channel rather than need to rely heavily
on a partner.
</P>
<P>
   With that, someone like Johnson can have his own cameraman come
out this season at Bucs games and shoot video of him so that he can
present his own highlight package within minutes. Even before ESPN
or Fox have a chance to put it out on their TV, radio and Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envision my site as a highlight show, like ESPN, with live,
not just taped highlights,'' said Johnson. ``Eventually we're going
to go in that direction. We just haven't figured it out yet.''
</P>
<P>
   More reshaping empires: Shaquille O'Neal's media makeover,
without the help of Reebok commercials or monotone movie roles, has
also being shaped through Internet endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Armato, O'Neal agent and Lakers courtside seat holder,
told the New York Times this week that the soon-to-be-MVP center
will soon appear in commercials for FreeInternet.com and he has
also finished a deal with Web-hosting company Digex. This, as his
apparel-selling site, dunk.net, has been netting plenty of local
exposure through T-shirt giveaways and promotions outside the
Staple Center during Laker games.
</P>
<P>
   Armato added that Shaq won't be making any more movies ``unless
he wins'' an NBA title. Call that a conflict of emotions for Laker
fans.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stern criticism: Monday's symposium with all four of the
major pro sports commissioners hosted by the Museum of Radio and TV
allowed NBA chief David Stern to get a blast off on how TV
sportscasters too often sink to struggling lounge act when they try
to inject snappy humor into their story intros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they need a director or a producer to tell them to get
on with their report,'' said Stern. ``I guess that if that's what
people watching ESPN want, that's what they want. But I don't know
if it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience is that it's all about the game. You start from
a fan base that wants to know about the game. If you want to have
in-depth reporting on athletes, that's fine. But when it becomes
about the next wisecrack, it cheapens the game. I think someone
should bring some order to the asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Added baseball commissioner Bud Selig: ``Levity is fine once and
a while, but sports fans do tune in to see what the score is and
how their team did. They're supposed to be journalists. I think the
line has been crossed, quite candidly.''
</P>
<P>
   In answer to Stern, Fox's Keith Olbermann replied on Wednesday's
``National Sports Report'': ``If you want fewer TV jokes about the
NBA, get rid of the Clippers.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for Bud: Here's a new flash _ that line was crossed long
ago. Quite loudly, if you'd been listening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
__ Back for its sixth year, Jim Rome's annual ``Smack Off'' runs
today (9-to-noon) on AM-1150. Smack on, you wayward clones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Who else but Vin Scully can ``remind'' viewers that ``you can
still buy four season tickets at Dodger Stadium for just sixteen
hundred and twenty dollars'' and make it sound like all you have to
do is search the cushions of your sofa and collect a few empty coke
bottles to come up with that kind of cash? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Adding to ABC's coverage of the NASCAR event from Fontana
live Sunday at 11 a.m. (with Bob Jenkins, Benny Parsons, Jerry
Punch and Bill Weber), KMPC-AM (1540) initiates radio coverage of
the event. Today's qualifying goes live on ESPN2 at 2:30 p.m., with
the Busch Series race Saturday at noon on ESPN. Sunday morning,
ESPN2 has RPM 2Day (10 a.m.) and NASCAR 2Day (10:30 a.m.) leading
into the event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Ed Goren, the executive producer of Fox Sports since its
inception in Jan. '94, has been named president of the company by
its former president, David Hill, currently the CEO and Chairman of
Fox Sports Television. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
__ In honor of the late commissioner of the league, they give out
the Walter Kennedy Trophy to the annual champion of the NBA. How
will they remember David Stern? How about with the Stern Urn _ a
big ash tray to the team that gets the biggest ratings during the
playoffs, thanks to his new, expanded format that allows the first
round to stretch longer than the final season of ``Chico and the
Man,'' post-Freddie Prinz. What a fine help it's been for everyone
else, too. While Tim Duncan gets every opportunity to get himself
healthy, the media has time to create new storylines to sustain
interest. Can't tell if it's worked or not yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ And then there's TNT's marketing slogan for the playoffs:
``Win Or Go Home.'' Sacramento lost Game 1 to the Lakers, then went
home. But they came back for Game 2. Is that how it's supposed to
work?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
