<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-BENSON-LADN-(SLAN     04-27 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BENSON-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENSON FINDS SUCCESS WITH NEW CREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Some called it a gamble, but Johnny Benson saw
it as an opportunity. So far, no one can argue with the results.
</P>
<P>
   The former NASCAR Winston Cup Rookie of the Year, who struggled
with consistency the past two seasons driving for Jack Roush,
appears to have gotten his second wind driving for Tyler Jet
Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who nearly won the season-opening Daytona 500 in
February, has six top-10 finishes in nine races and comes into this
weekend's NAPA Auto Parts 500 at California Speedway 18th in
points.
</P>
<P>
   This all with a second-year team that didn't acquire major
sponsorship until the Saturday of the first race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going pretty good,'' said Benson, who is also competing
in the Winston West 200 on Saturday. ``A lot of people from the
outside may have looked at it and thought it was a bad choice (to
leave Roush for Tyler Jet). But they didn't see the potential I
saw, the quality work this team did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an opportunity to walk through their shop and to meet
the guys on the team. I think what really impressed me was late
(last year), they had some successful qualifying runs and had some
good runs on race day. This is a good race team.''
</P>
<P>
   That was proven in February when Benson, who has yet to capture
his first Winston Cup victory, nearly won the Daytona 500. After
taking advantage of a two-tire pit stop, Benson led 38 laps and
looked primed to win NASCAR's version of the Super Bowl when a
crash brought out the caution with less then 10 laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to Daytona, we thought we brought a top-10 car,
with or without a sponsor,'' Benson said. ``Everybody thinks when
we got (Lycos to sponsor) the car (the Saturday before the race),
what a great story. But it didn't effect how the car ran. That's
what we had anyways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good feeling to have the opportunity to win the race.
But once the yellow came out, we pretty much knew we were in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson's fears came to fruition when the track went green with
three laps remaining. Dale Jarrett, the 1999 series champion, led a
train of Ford Taurus's past his Pontiac Grand Prix, giving Jarrett
the win and dropping Benson to 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost hard to believe,'' Benson said. ``We came to
Daytona with an unsponsored car and we left we everyone talking
about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had stayed green, would we have won? I don't know that.
But we finished 12th and that was a pretty good run for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That success has continued for Benson, who would like to finish
in the top-10 in points by season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure what a realistic goal for this team is,'' Benson
said. ``We want to finish in the top 10. We still want to win a
race, but that's a goal we have every year. After (failing to
qualify at) Atlanta, it's going to be extremely hard to finish in
the top 10. It's reachable and we're going to try to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, we've made some good runs. We were second at
Bristol and were running good before I crashed the car at Texas.
I'm hoping that with us starting off so good, much better then we
expected, that our growth continues to be on an uphill swing and we
can get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson has no harsh feelings toward his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is an easy answer why things didn't work
over there,'' Benson said. ``But I don't care. This team is a good
team and that's my focus right now. I don't worry about what
happened (at Roush). I can't change what happened and I can't do
anything about it. I think the situation just didn't work out the
way everybody wanted and there needed to be a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm on a different team now and I'm glad we're
running good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
