<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ROUGH ROAD AHEAD, METS' OFFENSE HITS A BUMP  
 BY JUDY BATTISTA  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets entered the game against the Reds Thursday
with an opportunity to equal their most successful homestand in
history. On the cusp of a schedule-by-sadists road trip _ 13 games
in 14 days in four cities, with no travel day between games in San
Francisco and South Florida _ the Mets had won eight of nine games
at home. They had even managed to keep Ken Griffey Jr. in check
during his first appearance at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday afternoon, the clubhouse was quiet and the quotes
were clipped. The Mets had lost, 2-1, in 12 innings to the Reds,
sending them to their chartered plane with overflowing luggage, two
difficult losses in a row and a sudden inability to score runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were demolished, 12-1, by the Reds on Wednesday, but
this loss seemed more annoying for the missed opportunities and
unexpected turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We misfired a little on offense is all,'' Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitcher, Glendon Rusch, using a revived changeup,
held the Reds at bay for seven and two-third innings, giving up
only a solo home run to Griffey in the fourth inning. That was
matched in the Mets' half of the fourth by a solo shot by Robin
Ventura off the Reds' starter, Steve Parris, who held the Mets to
four hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12-1 loss Wednesday, the Mets let the runs pile up
against pitcher Dennis Springer, so that the bullpen could have a
rest. But Thursday, the bullpen was nearly intact and kept holding
off the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good thing, since the Mets blew a chance to end the
game in the bottom of the ninth with a series of questionable
decisions and misfires: Why didn't Matt Franco bunt with no outs
and a runner on first? Why didn't Mike Piazza, who had the day off,
pinch-hit? What was the pinch-runner Rickey Henderson doing when he
was caught stealing after Franco struck out?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had two hits in the inning but left the bases loaded.
When the closer Armando Benitez, who had five saves and a victory
in his last six appearances, made his way to the mound for the 12th
inning, the Mets seemed prepared to extend the game.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez had struck out Griffey in the first game of the series
to close out a victory. But Griffey batted in the 11th inning
Thursday, grounding out harmlessly, so Benitez would be spared that
particular matchup again. Benitez made a rare mistake, however,
walking Sean Casey to lead off the inning. Casey advanced when
Aaron Boone sacrificed. Benitez walked the pinch-hitter Hal Morris
intentionally to get to Gookie Dawkins, the shortstop who had been
called up from Class AA last Saturday to replace the injured Barry
Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins entered the game batting .125 and he was behind in the
count, 0-1. Benitez threw Dawkins a fastball, his best pitch.
Dawkins connected, hitting a bloop single to left field. Jon
Nunnally charged the ball, but Casey was able to score from second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know this kid,'' Benitez said. ``I didn't know how to
pitch to this kid. He got me. The young guy has a good eye, can
make contact. He put the glove on and he showed he can play.
Sometimes you have to win, sometimes you have to lose. Now it's my
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez said he had felt a bit stiff when he came into the game,
as if he needed a little more rest. Even so, Benitez said, he had
to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, he needs me,'' Benitez said,
referring to Valentine. ``I'll be there. I can't say no.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had another chance in the bottom of the 12th, when the
Reds' pitcher, Scott Sullivan walked Nunnally with one out and then
threw a wild pitch to Derek Bell that put Nunnally on second. Bell
walked to bring up Edgardo Alfonzo. Sullivan went to a full count,
but Alfonzo popped up. So did Ventura to end the game and end what
had been a superb homestand on a disquieting note.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good chance,'' Alfonzo said. ``I thought we
could tie the game. I guessed wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
