<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-XEROX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX AND MICROSOFT CREATE DIGITAL SAFEGUARD COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Xerox Corp. and the Microsoft Corp. said
Thursday that they would create a company to produce and market
software that protects copyrighted materials like books, music and
video distributed over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, ContentGuard Inc., is being spun out of Xerox
and is based on technology developed at the Xerox Palo Alto
Research Center. A public offering is anticipated. Microsoft will
own a minority stake in ContentGuard, which will have headquarters
in McLean, Va., and operations in Palo Alto, Calif., and El
Segundo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox and Microsoft will collaborate with ContentGuard to
develop digital rights management technologies, which provide for
the distribution of digital content while protecting against
unauthorized copying. The lack of secure, reliable content
protection has hindered efforts to build an electronic market in
copyrighted materials. The challenge for the industry has been to
find a way to encode its intellectual property so that, once they
are paid for and downloaded by a buyer, music, videos or documents
can be stored and used only by the buyer without the threat of
piracy.
</P>
<P>
   G. Richard Thoman, president and chief executive at Xerox, and
Steven A. Ballmer, president and chief executive at Microsoft,
announced the formation of the company Thursday at the Xerox
research center. Though Xerox has been known to fail to capitalize
on breakthroughs developed at the research center, Thoman is taking
steps to capitalize on the center's discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the explosive growth on the Web, we had a hidden nugget
here, an asset we could monetize,'' Thoman said in a telephone
interview. ``Our intent is to IPO this company as soon as
feasible.'' Microsoft did not disclose the size of its stake in
ContentGuard, but Ballmer said the cost was in the tens of millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has 17 patents on the technology underlying ContentGuard
and has already announced partnerships with a number of companies,
including Adobe Systems and Hewlett-Packard. About 40 Xerox
employees in the United States and 20 to 30 abroad have been
working in the unit, formerly the Xerox Rights Management group,
Thoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Miron, who has managed the group at Xerox, will become
co-chairman and chief executive of ContentGuard. Richard Brass,
Microsoft's vice president of technology development, will also be
co-chairman of ContentGuard.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ties to Microsoft, ContentGuard will also work with
producers of competing software, Thoman and Ballmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ContentGuard will compete with a range of companies, including
small concerns like Sunhawk, InterTrust and Preview Systems and
large companies like IBM and AT&AMP;T. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
