<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE HULLABALOO AND LOOK AT REAL FACTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Everybody in hockey has heard about what has
gone on between the Dallas Stars and San Jose Sharks. There is too
much juicy stuff not to have.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk's knee. Bryan Marchment's style. Ed Belfour's
departure. But take a break from your regularly scheduled rivalry
talk for a word from the players, who swear that the Stars-Sharks
second-round playoff series, which begins at 6 p.m. Friday at
Reunion Arena, will be decided by things that nobody really talks
about.
</P>
<P>
   These are the types of things that will determine whether San
Jose or Dallas is left standing on the road to the Stanley Cup: 1.
ROOMIES
</P>
<P>
   Forget Marchment and Nieuwendyk. The story is going to be
Nieuwendyk and Jamie Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   Only instead of hating each other, Nieuwendyk and Langenbrunner
are best friends. Off and on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   They room together on the road. They double date with their
wives. But they weren't playing on the same line. Not since
midseason anyway. Not until Stars coach Ken Hitchcock reunited them
in Game 4 against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk has been playing like playoff Joe since.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as you want to downplay it, I think getting back with
my buddy there helps,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``You know, as soon as we
got back together, we were in their end. We were flying around,
buzzing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk had two assists in Game 5, including assisting on a
goal by Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line looks like it's hopefully ready to bust /Rout/S,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Either that line busts out or the Stars' playoff hopes go bust.
2. SMOOTH SAILING
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' power play wasn't great in the first round. OK, it
wasn't even average. It was 2-for-26 bad.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov has been missed.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't played since March 29 because of a partially torn
ligament in his right knee. He's set to play Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that he does do is drastically improve their
power play,'' Oilers assistant coach Craig MacTavish said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov is like a wishbone quarterback. He doesn't simply pass the
puck up ice; he carries it. He likes taking the puck from behind
the net and weaving through defenders like Picabo Street on a
slalom course. Trying to pry it away is futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must like the puck a lot,'' Oilers defenseman Janne
Niinimaa quipped, ``because he doesn't give it away too often.''
</P>
<P>
   Just wait, The Stars' power play is going to look a lot better
when they're able to set up. 3. THE OTHER CHEEK
</P>
<P>
   This series is going to be nasty. OK, so what's new? The key is
who will be able to keep their cool because referees often see the
retaliation, not the instigation.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the vacationing Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest reason we beat St. Louis?'' Sharks coach Darryl
Sutter said. ``We played with more composure.''
</P>
<P>
   No, turning the other cheek doesn't feel as good as putting your
fist in Marchment's. But if the Stars want to advance, they better
save their nasty stuff for carefully chosen moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real good penalty kill,'' Stars forward Brenden
Morrow said. ``So if it happens every once in a while, we can get
away with it.'' 4. SHIELDS' PSYCHE
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was watching Sharks goalie Steve Shields after he
allowed six goals on 13 shots before getting pulled in Game 6
against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was waiting to see what he was going to do in Game
7,'' Sharks forward Vincent Damphousse said. ``I think he showed a
lot of character by coming back and being able to forget what
happened in Game 6.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks have seen the best of Shields and the worst of
Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Which one the Stars will see only Shields can say. And who knows
what goes on in the heads of those goalies? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
