<SLUG> BC-FORD-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITEY FORD ADMITS THAT HE HAS CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Whitey Ford, the Yankees Hall of Fame pitcher, who
missed spring training this year for the first time in 49 years,
acknowledged on Thursday that he has cancer, although he declined
to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been treated for it,'' Ford, 71, said by telephone from
his part-time home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. ``We just hope that it
works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford declined to identify the type of cancer for which he has
been treated. ``We're the type of family that tries to keep these
things to ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, he noted that Nolan Ryan had undergone heart
bypass surgery in the past week and that Ryan's illness had been
covered extensively on television and in local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not like that,'' Ford said. ``I just like to keep things
within the family. I mean, a few of my friends know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said his prescribed treatment had been completed. His next
step? ``Just to make sure it hasn't spread,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Missing spring training was a telltale sign that something was
wrong with Ford, a left-handed pitcher who became known as the
Chairman of the Board in fashioning a 236-106 record for the
Yankees in the 1950s and 1960s. Since spending the 1951 season in
the military, Ford had attended every Yankees spring training until
this year, first as a player, then as a coach, then as a uniformed
guest of the team's owners, in part to display the franchise's
great history. ``It's been great,'' he said. ``I enjoyed it very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford's career winning percentage of .690 is the best of any
major league pitcher in the 20th century. He led the American
League in victories three times and in earned run average and
shutouts twice each. He won the Cy Young award in 1961 and holds
World Series records for victories (10), consecutive shutout
innings (33) and strikeouts (94).
</P>
<P>
   When first asked on Thursday why he had missed spring training,
Ford attributed it to ``a little medical problem.'' Only after
further conversation did he acknowledge that the medical problem
was cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a particularly difficult time for Ford and his wife,
Joan. Last August, their son, Tommy, died; Ford declined to talk
about his son's death, again citing his family's preference for
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Ford named one of the trotters that he owns Model T. Ford, after
the band in which his son once played.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being with the Yankees this spring in Tampa, Fla., he
spent some time at Pompano Park as a diversion, getting the horse
ready to race. Ford said he hoped to be there when the horse tries
to race at the Meadowlands later this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
