<HEADLINE>
MIAMI KIN REBUFFED IN BID TO VISIT ELIAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Thursday rejected efforts
by Elian Gonzalez's U.S. relatives to visit the Cuban boy, who was
whisked from their Miami home by armed federal agents Saturday
morning and reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also denied the family's
request to have the 6-year-old placed in an outside guardian's
care. The court, instead, accepted the Justice Department's offer
to submit to the judges biweekly reports from a psychiatrist and a
social worker on Elian's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miami relatives are extremely disappointed that they were
denied access to the child,'' said attorney Richard Sharpstein, who
is assisting Elian's U.S. family in its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a move welcomed by the relatives, the 11th Circuit
rebuffed a request by Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to have
them removed from the case. Gonzalez had argued that only he, as
the boy's father and sole surviving parent, could speak for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpstein said he was glad that the Atlanta-based court also
preserved its previously stated view that federal law might allow
Elian to request political asylum in the United States against his
father's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is recognizing the independence of the child,'' the
Miami lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit is scheduled to hear arguments May 11 on
whether Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez of Miami can pursue in
federal court his effort to gain asylum for Elian. Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, backed by the Justice Department, argues that he should
be allowed to return to Cuba with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attorney General Janet Reno on Thursday defended as a
necessary ``show of force'' her decision to order the pre-dawn
raid. In her first detailed statement on Saturday's strike, Reno
said Elian's intransigent U.S. relatives and sympathizers outside
their house tried to lasso officers and block the front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tried to throw &UR;  &LR; (television cables) around the agents
as they went into the house and obstruct their entry into the
house,'' Reno said. ``A couch was pushed up against the door to
limit entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents used a battering ram to force open the door. The
three-minute strike included a heavily armed officer taking a
frightened Elian from the arms of Donato Dalrymple, a fisherman who
had plucked the boy from an inner tube off the Florida coast
Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   A free-lance photographer captured the image of an agent
pointing his assault weapon in the general direction of Dalrymple.
Reno called the resulting picture, reprinted on newspaper and
magazine covers nationwide, the cost of effective law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had to be a show of force, not a use of force, to show
that we were in control,'' Reno said. ``I think that was done
carefully and thoughtfully based on the information that has been
provided to me to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and other federal officials have said the photographed
agent presented no real danger as his finger was not on the
trigger, the gun's safety lock was on and he was not pointing the
weapon at either Dalrymple or Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The raid involved federal agents storming the home of Lazaro
Gonzalez, who had steadfastly refused to surrender the boy to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service. Fellow agents stood
outside, keeping at bay Cuban-American protesters, who had kept a
months-long vigil outside the home since shortly after Elian was
rescued from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Agents then placed Elian on a government plane and flew him to
Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland, about 40 miles outside of
Washington, where he was reunited with Juan Miguel Gonzalez. The
father had flown from Cuba to the United States on April 6 in hope
of the reunion and bringing his son back to the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who faced intense criticism from House Republicans this
week over her decision, defended the timing of the raid as
necessary to protect the safety of Elian, the relatives, the
protesters and the federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a situation where if we did not go, people were sure to
find out that we were prepared to go and the crowd would gather and
keep a vigil and make it more difficult for the future,'' Reno
said. ``This seemed to be the safest time possible to effect the
transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   About 300 Cuban-Americans descended on the White House on
Thursday to protest the raid. Demonstrators chanted ``freedom for
Elian'' and one protester raised a sign with the widely shown
photograph and the caption ``Reno's justice _ child abuse at the
point of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian, his father, stepmother, Nersy, and infant half-brother,
Hianny, were staying at a secluded Maryland retreat about 70 miles
east of Washington while they await a final court ruling on the
U.S. family's asylum request. Elian was expected soon to be
reunited at the retreat with a 10-year-old cousin and a former
kindergarten teacher, who flew to the Washington area late
Wednesday, and four Cuban classmates and their parents, who landed
near Washington on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion between father and son ended a five-month separation
that began when Elian's mother, Elisabeth Bretons, attempted to
reach the United States by boat with him. The boat sank, drowning
Bretons and 10 other Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government had spent $578,000 on the Elian case
between Thanksgiving and Monday, the Justice Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   Of the federal government's expenditure on the Elian matter, the
INS had spent the most, $374,000, the Justice Department reported.
These costs went to training and housing 131 agents who
participated in the raid and paying for the government plane that
flew Elian from Florida to the base, among other expenses. The U.S.
Marshals Service, which provided 20 agents for the raid and
security for Elian's Cuban family, spent $161,000. The remaining
costs went to legal work, mediators, conciliators and psychiatric
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
