<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD PARK HOPES TO BE FAST OUT OF GATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Like a drowsy racehorse, Hollywood Park's
long, spring-summer meeting has suffered from slow starts in recent
years, the Kentucky Derby simulcast having been its only
early-season drawing card.
</P>
<P>
   But the track should be faster out of the gate for the 65-day
season that opens at 7 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes at the 62-year-old landmark next door to the
Forum is the debut on Sunday of an event called the California Gold
Rush. It's a 10-race program exclusively for California-bred
horses, and it provides an early attraction to serve as a bookend
with the Hollywood Gold Cup on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``A momentum-builder,'' in the words of Hollywood Park president
Rick Baedeker.
</P>
<P>
   Up for grabs will be $1.26 million in purses for the horses
competing in the 10 stakes, and a guaranteed $1 million pick-six
pool for bettors.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park executives are careful not to compare the Gold
Rush with the California Cup, the state-breds festival presented
each fall at Santa Anita by the Oak Tree Racing Association and the
California Thoroughbred Breeders Association. ``The Cal Cup is
probably still the championship event for Cal-breds,'' said racing
secretary Martin Panza.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gold Rush is a clever idea that should work. The card is
made up of existing races that never drew much fan interest when
they were scattered throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   The main event, the $250,000 Show Chief Stakes, a 1 1/8-mile
race for 3-year-olds, could send a horse on to the Preakness Stakes
in a good year.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-horse field for Sunday's running includes Hugh Hefner and
Grey Memo, co-high weights at 119 pounds; Queenie Belle, a filly
challenging males; Wolf With Integrity, ridden by 1999 Eclipse
Award winner Jorge Chavez, and Cozy Man, with Mike Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The East Coast-based Chavez, Smith and Jerry Bailey accepted
appearance fees to take part in the Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Hollywood Park's first spring-summer meet under the
management of Churchill Downs Inc., which purchased it from the
R.D. Hubbard-led group for $140 million in September.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter, fall meet was a success thanks to the drama
surrounding Laffit Pincay, who broke Bill Shoemaker's career-
victories record when he rode Irish Nip to win No. 8,834 on Dec.
10, 1999, and went on to capture his first track title since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   To try to maintain its momentum, the new management has put a
reported $6 million into facility improvements, including a more
attractive entrance from Prairie Avenue, establishment of well-lit
``mini sports book'' seating areas on the main floor, and the
``Handicapping Zone,'' a talk-show-style forum in which experts and
fans can exchange analysis throughout the day on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes:
</P>
<P>
   __ Chris Kotulak is the new announcer, replacing the outstanding
Michael Wrona, who took a better deal at Lone Star Park near
Dallas. Kotulak, 37, recently of Louisiana Downs, signed a
three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we've had a bit of a revolving door in the
announcer's booth,'' Baedeker said. ``We want to have a true `voice
of Hollywood Park.' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ Julie Krone, the leading female jockey of all time, will
analyze weekend races on the intertrack and Fox Sports Net shows.
</P>
<P>
   __ The nightly replays show on KDOC television moves to 9 p.m.
from its customary 8 p.m. slot. KDOC was asking Hollywood Park to
match the price it can get for infomercials and ``Perry Mason''
reruns at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Purses are going up at the claiming and allowance levels as
Panza tries to attract bigger fields.
</P>
<P>
   __ Concession prices are going down, with Hollywood Park
advertising the cheapest food in Los Angeles sports, including
$1.50 hot dogs and $2 beer.
</P>
<P>
   Clubhouse reserved-seat prices have been cut in half to $2.
Admission prices, which include parking and programs, remain $6 for
the grandstand and $9 for the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The first race is scheduled for 1 p.m. on weekends and holidays,
and 1:10 p.m. on Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Friday, May 5, the day
before the Kentucky Derby. All other Fridays will start at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ What, Neil worry? Neil Drysdale, one of the more fastidious
trainers, claimed not to be concerned after Kentucky Derby favorite
Fusaichi Pegasus' latest antics.
</P>
<P>
   The colt reared twice, flipped and dumped his exercise rider as
he returned from a jog Thursday morning at Churchill Downs.
Drysdale was close enough to catch Fusaichi Pegasus and lead him
back to the barn. Nobody was reported injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing superbly, and then he felt so good he reared up
and then sat down,'' Drysdale said, casting the incident in the
best possible light. ``So far he hasn't put on a real show (in
Louisville). When he's in California, he can really do some tricks.
We may be coming up with them this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some mornings he's a real gentleman. Some mornings he's
feeling so good he doesn't know what to do with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   As hard as he can be to handle, the Wood Memorial winner has
been notably well-behaved during races. But could that change in
front of the big crowd on Derby day?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 130,000 people may get his attention,'' Drysdale said,
again turning it into a positive. ``He's fascinated by people.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The competition: As many as 24 horses are listed as Derby
hopefuls, with the maximum field of 20 to be determined by earnings
in graded stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Recently declared out was Chief Seattle, the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile runnerup. He had a fever and didn't ship to Churchill
Downs from Lexington with fellow Dubai-based 3-year-olds China
Visit and Curule.
</P>
<P>
   Iffy are two D. Wayne Lukas-trained horses, Exchange Rate and
True Confidence. Lukas said True Confidence would have to run first
or second in the Derby Trial on Saturday to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the ``maybe'' category are Globalize, Snuck In, Ronton
and Unshaded, the Lexington Stakes winner who would have to be a
supplemental nominee at a cost of $150,000 to owner Jim Tafel.
</P>
<P>
   Other Derby probables listed as of Thursday morning included
Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy and other recent prep winners
Fusaichi Pegasus, Graeme Hall, High Yield and Trippi; Santa Anita
Derby grads War Chant, Captain Steve and Anees; and Aptitude,
Commendable, Deputy Warlock, Hal's Hope, Harlan Traveler,
Impeachment, More Than Ready and Wheelaway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
