<HEADLINE>
GORE HELPS PARTY, TOO; BOREDOM SETS IN; BUSH AHEAD IN OHIO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ohio, Wash.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after criticizing Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas for headlining a Washington fund-raiser that brought in a
record $21.3 million for the Republican Party, Vice President Al
Gore held bookend fund-raising events Thursday in Pennsylvania,
helping the Democratic National Committee raise more than $1.2
million. Over lunch in Pittsburgh and then dinner in Philadelphia,
Gore boasted about the Clinton administration's economic record and
accused Bush of advocating a ``don't worry about tomorrow'' plan of
``risky'' tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   BOREDOM SETS IN
</P>
<P>
   The drawn out, sometimes hectic system for nominating and
electing a president neither broadens the public's understanding of
campaigns nor encourages involvement in them and in the end leaves
many voters bored. That is the initial conclusion of the Vanishing
Voter Project, a study being conducted by the Joan Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy at Harvard
University. In weekly polls of voter perceptions last fall and this
spring, the center queried voters about what political issues they
were following each day, if any, and how much, if any, they were
discussing politics daily
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AHEAD IN OHIO
</P>
<P>
   A new presidential preference poll of Ohio voters by the
University of Cincinnati _ Ohio is considered a state that could go
to Bush or Gore _ has Bush leading Gore by 8 points, about the same
margin found by an Ohio State University poll taken a month ago.
The Cincinnati poll, conducted April 5 through 22 and covering 531
likely voters, found Bush ahead of Gore 47 percent to 39 percent.
Ralph Nader of the Green Party had 4 percent, Pat Buchanan of the
Reform Party had 3 percent, and 7 percent of the respondents said
they were undecided. The margin of sampling error for the poll was
plus or minus 4 percentage points. In Washington state, a newly
released preference poll has Bush ahead by a single point, 39
percent to 38 percent, with 18 percent of the respondents
undecided. The poll, by Elway Research, a nonpartisan firm,
surveyed 400 registered voters on April 11 and 12 and has a margin
of sampling error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   GROUPS ALLOWED TO PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   The city of Philadelphia reached an amicable settlement Thursday
with a coalition of more than 50 groups that had said their right
to public assembly would be violated during the Republican National
Convention. The groups initially were denied demonstration permits
by the city, but Thursday it backed off. ``I applaud the city for
reaffirming the notion that dissent is critical for a healthy
democracy,'' said Stefan Presser, legal director of the American
Civil Liberties Union, in withdrawing a federal lawsuit. The
agreement, worked out through the office of the city solicitor,
Kenneth Trujillo, allows a protest march along Benjamin Franklin
Parkway on July 30, the eve of the convention, by Unity 2000, a
coalition that includes the NAACP and the National Organization for
Women. The city also approved a march on July 29 through Washington
Square by the Ad-Hoc Committee to Defend Health Care, a group of
medical professionals demanding government action on the issue.
FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Philadelphia, Dallas, Albuquerque
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
