<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VETERANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL VS. CARTER: LOSE AND LEARN, LEARN AND WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When you break everything down, Latrell Sprewell knew
what to do. He knew Vince Carter had five fouls and could not
afford another. He knew he was going to drive to the basket and
take a short, step-back jump shot for the victory, not shoot some
wild baseline fall-away.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's defining moment soon came, with the ball in his hands
and Game 2 in the balance. He could have taken a deep 3-pointer or,
having already gone to the free-throw line 16 times, penetrated the
middle. He passed up his chance.
</P>
<P>
   He'll learn.
</P>
<P>
   When you break everything down, Vinsanity got a dose of
Spreeality.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won because a veteran pushing 30 showed more poise
than a 23-year-old participating in his first postseason. As the
fourth-quarter theater riveted Madison Square Garden, a recurring
playoff theme remained as contemporary as Old Man Malone: age
before aesthetics, old-school guile before young skywalkers.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sprewell, using all his savvy, desire and experience to
counter the most scintillating young player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my first year, I remember this older, slow guard taking it
to me,'' said Doc Rivers, the former guard and now the Orlando
Magic coach. ``I was faster, quicker and stronger than the guy, but
he just kept killing me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he have over me? Knowledge. Just more knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers was asked if he recalled the player's name. ``I can't
remember,'' he said. ``I want to say Kyle Macy, but my ego won't
allow me to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, Carter's performance at the end of Game 2
against the Knicks will most likely be a footnote, a small growing
pain toward his championship maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about regrets some day, he might think back to his forced
and rushed 3-pointer with more than 10 seconds on the shot clock
and 25 seconds on the game clock. His team was up by a point, still
in control. Or he will wish he was more assertive, taking the ball
to the basket with less than seven seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Lose and learn. It is a rough lesson in the younger and more
restless National Basketball Association, where age is being served
again in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   A quick perusal of first-round box scores unearths the truth:
curmudgeons rule.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone, 36, scored 14 more points than his age last weekend
in a 50-point explosion against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In two tight Western Conference thrillers, Scottie Pippen, 34,
outplayed Kevin Garnett, 23, the way the veteran Portland Trail
Blazers outplayed the young Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie made all the big plays, defensively, offensively,
ball-handling, making shots,'' Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy said.
``He has been incredible these past two games.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stockton, 38, had 21 points and 11 assists on Monday, and
they did not come in a rec-league semifinal in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Utah and Miami represent two of the oldest rosters in the
league, and both are in good first-round shape. Tim Hardaway and
Reggie Miller stagger around in the East. Jeff Hornacek and Steve
Smith ice their knees in the West. The only teams with
predominantly under-30 starters headed toward the conference
semifinals are the Lakers and the 76ers, and many of their role
players have extensive playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks may have the tricks of the trade down better than any
of their aging peers. Outplayed for much of the last six quarters,
they're up by 2-0 against Toronto. Only two of their top eight
players _ Sprewell and Larry Johnson _ have played to their
potential. But they know how to win.
</P>
<P>
   Every two decades or so, an aberration rises _ Magic Johnson
jumping center in Game 6 of the finals, Larry Bird and Tim Duncan
capturing championships in their second seasons. But mostly in the
NBA, you pay your playoff dues, one possession at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you are probably wondering how, in a span of two years,
Sprewell transformed himself from a freestyle Gen-X player with
much to learn into a postseason veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been in the league that long, there's a reason,''
Rivers said. ``And it's usually because you've figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, whose Lakers are favored to win it all, is
another example of a player who seems to have gotten it.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five minutes of Game 2, the Knicks went almost
exclusively to Sprewell on the left side as he was guarded by
Carter. He took one ill-advised jump shot, after which the Knicks
called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you in that timeout, Jeff Van Gundy told him there
is no need to take jumpers,'' Rivers said. ``I got to think Jeff
said something like, `This guy is not a good defender and he has
five fouls.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``After Sprewell went to his right four straight times, I was
surprised Vince kept letting him. When the game is on the line, I
always knew a guy would go to his staple move or his strong hand.
At that time of the game, that's who you are. He might beat me, but
I always thought I had to take that side away. I was not going to
give him that.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Carter time. He'll learn. After all his teachers retire and
become TNT analysts or coaches, he'll open his own classroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
