<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COL-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      04-27 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REFLECTIVE MAYOR FACES HIS ILLNESS WITHOUT SELF-PITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For columnists, reporters and assorted other pests,
there was one bright spot in the otherwise sad news from Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani on Thursday that he has prostate cancer. This bad
break, the mayor insisted, will not make him a nicer fellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way, no way,'' he said with a smile when asked about it at
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Whew!
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, Rudy Giuliani as Nice Guy would put an awful lot
of paid pundits out of work. They have been dining out for years on
his excesses of temperament. So it was particularly charitable of
the mayor to reassure them on Thursday, even in his moment of
trial, that he will continue to provide ample grist for their
mills.
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, one of the more striking features about the
way Giuliani announced his illness was his grace under pressure.
Not for a second during his news conference did he whine or indulge
in self-pity. He spoke in a clear voice and a straightforward
manner. When a little joke was called for, he joked. He was, in a
word, winning.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there reason for skepticism when he said that he had no
idea what the next step would be, in either his cancer treatment or
his Senate race. He wouldn't even be talking about it now, he
acknowledged, if a reporter had not spotted him at Mount Sinai
Medical Center on Wednesday and put two and two together.
</P>
<P>
   What his performance offered was a glimpse of how differently
his mayoralty might have gone had there been more performances like
Thursday's over the last six and a half years. A Mayor Giuliani
capable of admitting to a measure of vulnerability and uncertainty
could arguably have won broader support for his policies than the
man whose tendency has been to trumpet himself as the rare honest
man battling the armies of incompetence, corruption and
intellectual bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   It matters that opinion polls consistently show that most New
Yorkers do not like him, including many who consider him a great
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Likability may not seem terribly important in politics when
everything is going your way. But when you stumble _ as many
believe Giuliani did, badly, in episodes like the police killing of
Patrick M. Dorismond _ you need to have people willing to give you
the benefit of the doubt and to help you regain your footing.
Recent polls suggest that, because of his demeanor, the mayor is
running short of friends in his own city. Thursday's man of grace
might have fared a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Giuliani stood alone on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That is often how he likes to be seen: a Shane-like figure ready
to take on malevolent forces single-handedly. Still, there was
something sad and lonely about him as he spoke at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders in similar circumstances would have had spouses,
children and good friends at their side. That is not this mayor's
style. He has worked hard to keep his family life private, and for
the most part the press has respected his wishes. Gracie Mansion,
the mayor's home, has generally been off limits to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   There have been breaches, though, the most recent coming with
the eyebrow-raising announcement that Giuliani's wife, Donna
Hanover, had taken a part in ``The Vagina Monologues.'' And it was
impossible not to notice that Hanover was nowhere around the mayor
on Thursday, other than on a piece of paper announcing that she
would be ``very supportive of him in dealing with the choices he
has to make.'' Her statement also noted that she and Giuliani had
discussed his cancer. That she even felt obliged to make that point
may have said something.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he is broadly liked or not, whatever his home
situation may be, a serious illness that befalls a major public
figure reminds us all how slender the threads connecting us to this
life are.
</P>
<P>
   In Giuliani's case, there will be the added component of nonstop
political speculation. Will this help him bow out of a Senate race
that does not seem to have captured his heart and soul? If he
insists on running, will his cancer bring him sympathy votes? Or
will New Yorkers instead abandon him the way they did an ailing
Sen. Jacob K. Javits 20 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   But none of that seemed very important on Thursday, a point made
by Giuliani himself as he talked briefly about how a bad turn makes
you reflect on the things that really count. That's why even his
most bitter opponents laid down their swords for the moment, heeded
the admonition of Ecclesiastes that ``all is vanity'' and wished
the mayor godspeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
