<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      04-27 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
For those who got stuck in downtown traffic or in the concession
line and missed the first 10 minutes of Thursday's game, a quick
recap:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Young smack!
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez smack!
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rodriguez smack!
</P>
<P>
   Damon Buford smack!
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs roughed up Jose Lima for five home runs, a
record-tying four in the first inning, en route to a 12-3 pounding
of the Astros before a sellout crowd of 42,271 at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost over before it began,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost?
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs tied a 70-year-old club record with four homers in an
inning. Young and Gutierrez began the game with back-to-back
homers, Rodriguez hit a two-run shot, and when Buford connected,
Chicago had a 5-0 lead just seven batters and 30 pitches into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez sent a grand slam into the right-field upper deck off
Lima (1-4) in the fourth to make it 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   Lima tied a major-league record by allowing four homers in an
inning and set a club record by giving up five in the game.
Overall, he was tagged for 12 runs and 13 hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of mistakes. I don't know what's wrong,'' said
Lima, who has allowed 10 home runs this season, most in the majors.
``I can't wait for April to end. This month hasn't been kind to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who was 21-10 last season, has lost four times since
winning his first start April 5 at Pittsburgh. He has allowed 27
runs during that span.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 runs he allowed Thursday broke the club record of 10 set
by pitching coach Vern Ruhle (1980) and tied by Bob Forsch (1989).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the ballpark. It's up here,'' Lima said pointing to
his head.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 46 home runs in 12 games at Enron Field, where
the Astros are 3-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had few complaints about the quaint playing conditions
after outscoring the Astros 32-22 in taking two of three games.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez looked right at home with three home runs in the
series. He went 2-for-3 with a career-high six RBIs Thursday.
Former Astro Ricky Gutierrez went 7-for-12 with eight RBIs in three
games at Enron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him (Lima) like that,'' Rodriguez said. ``He
wasn't hitting his spots. He was just throwing the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lieber (2-2) pitched a five-hitter, becoming the first
pitcher to throw a complete game at Enron Field. He struck out
seven and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon showed you can get guys out if you make good pitches, no
matter where you're playing,'' Chicago manager Don Baylor said.
``Our guys really love this ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs didn't waste any time. Young opened the game by sending
a 2-0 fastball into the Crawford Boxes in left field. Gutierrez,
who had only one homer last season, drove the next pitch onto the
train tracks in left for his second homer in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Following a one-out single by Sammy Sosa, Rodriguez crushed 2-1
offering from Lima. Two batters later, Buford connected on a solo
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to shoot myself. Five runs in the first inning? I
asked myself, `What else can go wrong?''' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   Well in the fourth inning, Rodriguez hit his fifth career grand
slam, giving the Cubs a 10-run lead and prompting one fan in the
lower level to yell, ``Stop the bleeding!'' Mark Grace added a
two-run double in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Lieber retired the first 12 batters he faced. Ken Caminiti
reached on Grace's error to begin the fifth inning, and Daryle Ward
broke up the no-hit/shutout bid with a two-run homer to right
field.
</P>
<P>
   The game almost turned ugly in the eighth when Astros reliever
Doug Henry hit Rodriguez in the back. Lieber hit Matt Mieske in the
bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After an awful week at home, the Astros begin a 10-game road
trip today in Milwaukee. With the change of scenery, Dierker is
hoping for a change of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we go on the road and we get a chance to see if the
ballpark's got us psyched out or if we're just playing this
badly,'' Dierker said. ``I don't think it's the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
