u f BC-DEAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-27 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CAN YOUNG &AMP; RUBICAM MAINTAIN INDEPENDENCE WHEN WPP
COMES CALLING?
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a deal that would combine two of the world's largest
advertising companies, WPP Group, the British conglomerate that
owns Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J. Walter Thompson, acknowledged
Thursday that it was in talks to buy Young &AMP; Rubicam in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations have taken place in fits and starts over the
last four months, and executives close to the talks said the
outcome was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R, meanwhile, is also talking to other possible suitors,
perhaps as a way to force WPP to make a higher bid. Over the last
several days, Y&AMP;R has intensified merger talks with Publicis SA of
France, executives close to the company said, though it is unclear
whether those talks will produce a deal either. Y&AMP;R also made
overtures to Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, but those talks never took off, the
executives said. On the back burner, Y&AMP;R is talking with the direct
marketer Harte-Hanks Inc. about buying the company, but executives
close to the talks said a deal between the two would not proceed
until Y&AMP;R sorts out its discussions with WPP and Publicis.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to bulk up an already bulging WPP, Martin Sorell, the
company's chief executive, resumed negotiations with Y&AMP;R this week
after the talks broke down in late March. The main stumbling block
is now price, executives close to the talks said. Under the current
offer, Y&AMP;R would receive about a third of the enlarged group, or $5
billion, in an all-stock deal, the executives said. Based on WPP's
closing price Thursday, that would mean Y&AMP;R shareholders would be
paid about $69.15 for each share, a 31 percent premium over Y&AMP;R's
current stock price of $52.875. Shares of WPP fell 48 pence, to
9.73 pounds, while the company's U.S. depository receipts slumped
$1.625, to $78. Executives close to the talks said that a
Y&AMP;R-Publicis deal would be ``competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that seems to have a voracious appetite for
consolidation, Y&AMP;R, which has a blue-chip client roster that
includes Ford, AT&AMP;T and DuPont, has remained one of the last major
independent agencies. Thomas Bell, Y&AMP;R's chairman, has been
somewhat rankled by Sorrell's overtures, according to several
executives, but they say he thinks that strategically, Y&AMP;R will
have to do a deal with another player to remain competitive.
Indeed, as clients continue to demand a wider global advertising
presence, almost all industry analysts think it is inevitable that
Y&AMP;R will have to merge or risk losing business to bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more logic for Y&AMP;R to do a deal than WPP because they
have less global reach,'' said Gareth Thomas, an analyst at
Commerzbank in London. ``I don't think it's a necessity for WPP to
do a deal.'' Nonetheless, Sorrell has publicly stated his desire to
grow, yet he is faced with having few independent agencies to
pursue. And WPP has been burned after it went hostile in past
takeovers. After WPP's hostile bid for Ogilvy, a stream of
executives left the company.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, under an interim agreement between WPP and Y&AMP;R, it
would be almost impossible for Sorrell to undertake a surprise
hostile bid. According to executives who have seen the agreement
document, WPP is allowed to make an unlimited number of
``friendly'' offers to Y&AMP;R's board, but WPP is restrained from
making a hostile bid for a certain period of time. The document
also includes a confidentiality agreement that prohibits either
side from discussing the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said hostile bids rarely succeeded in the advertising
industry because the principal assets of an advertising agency are
the people who work there. Without an extremely lucrative ``golden
handcuff'' to induce employees to stay, the value of an agency can
literally walk out the door.
</P>
<P>
   A stumbling block for any deal is the issue of client conflicts,
Thomas said. Both companies have clients that could pose conflicts
of interest, but it is possible the companies could find a way
around it.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, it seems Y&AMP;R's days as an independent shop
are numbered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
