<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WIND DOWN SPRING FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA concludes spring practice Saturday with its
shrinking scrimmage at remodeled Drake Stadium. A slew of minor
injuries have forced the Bruins to shorten what was a 90-play event
in recent years. They simply don't have enough healthy bodies to
survive more than 40 or 50 plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're banged up, it's the end of spring, and the guys have had
enough,'' said coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's festivities begin at 1 p.m. with player introductions
and a condensed practice. Next comes a ``thud'' scrimmage (no
tackling) specifically designed for quarterback Cory Paus, who had
offseason shoulder surgery and cannot scrimmage. The main event
begins at approximately 1:45 and will dissolve into an autograph
session an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Several top players are either out or questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ryan McCann, who's battling Paus for the starting
job, injured his throwing elbow earlier this week and might not
play. In that case, third-stringer Scott McEwan will take all the
snaps in the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's wrong,'' McCann said Thursday. ``I can't throw.
I'm going to the doctor tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, tailback DeShaun Foster (sprained knee), receiver
Freddie Mitchell (baseball), center Troy Danoff (offseason knee
surgery) and guard Brian Polak (knee surgery) are out. Receiver
Brian Poli-Dixon (hamstring) is doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, end Kenyon Coleman (mononucleosis), linebackers
Robert Thomas (broken thumb) and Ryan Nece (shoulder), cornerbacks
Jason Bell (hand laceration) and Joe Hunter (shoulder), and
safeties Audie Attar (hamstring) and Lovell Houston (shoulder) are
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have something like 18 or 19 guys on the team who can't
play,'' said defensive coordinator Bob Field.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: The scrimmage is free. Drake Stadium is 200 yards north
of Spaulding Field.)
</P>
<P>
   __ Barnes update: It's official. Basketball player Matt Barnes
will join the football team for training camp. According to NCAA
rules, he'll remain on a basketball scholarship until he appears in
a football game. At that point, he will count against the football
team's 85-scholarship limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talked to (basketball coach) Steve Lavin and he wants to
give it a try,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, a 6-8 junior-to-be, played receiver in high school and
certainly has the requisite physical skills. He's long, lean and
fast. But there are several questions that won't be answered until
August: Can he catch the ball in traffic? Can he take a hit? Will
he be academically eligible? (He wasn't last fall and missed five
basketball games.) And what effect will football have on his
basketball career? With forwards JaRon Rush and Jerome Moiso
seemingly headed for the NBA, Barnes is the projected starter at
power forward.
</P>
<P>
   __ Look away: Thomas, the middle linebacker, suffered the most
gruesome injury of spring practice: a compound fracture of his left
thumb that required immediate surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was making a routine tackle on tailback Akil Harris when
his thumb jammed into Harris' thigh. Thomas looked down and saw the
top half of his thumb (above the joint) was perpendicular and had
broken through his glove. Bone was exposed. The medical staff
quickly popped the thumb into place, then Thomas headed for the
operating table. A pin was inserted to stabilize the joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst pain I've ever been through,'' Thomas said.
``It's disappointing, because I was having a real good spring. I
was excited for the scrimmage. My parents were coming (from San
Diego).''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his cast will be removed in about three weeks and
he'll promptly begin his summer conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   __ One loss, three gains: Coleman missed the entire spring
because of mononucleosis, but his absence created playing time for
three young ends (sophomore Sean Phillips and freshmen Mat and Dave
Ball) who have impressed the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The mono took Coleman by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' he said. ``At first I thought it was
tonsilitis, then strep throat. Then the day I started feeling
better, they told me it was mono. My spleen was swollen. I haven't
been tired and I don't know anybody who has it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
