<HEADER>
A9479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      04-27 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MAYOR GIULIANI'S PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, April 28:
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's battle with
prostate cancer is successful and mercifully brief. New York's
mayor, who has generally appeared in good health, surprised the
political world on Thursday by announcing that screening tests
during his annual physical had shown signs of cancer and that a
follow-up biopsy had confirmed that finding. Fortunately, the
cancer seems to have been detected at an early stage, so the odds
for successful treatment and cure may be good. But what impact the
cancer will have on the mayor's health or his campaign for the U.S.
Senate will not be known until he and his doctors settle on a
course of treatment, which could range from surgery to radiation to
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's diagnosis is a testament to the sensitivity of early
screening tests that have revolutionized the management of prostate
cancer in this decade. Years ago patients relied on physicians to
detect prostate tumors by a gloved digital examination through the
rectum. Now the Prostate Specific Antigen, or PSA, test measures
substances that are elevated in the blood when there is a prostate
cancer, making it possible to detect tumors much earlier. The tests
have a downside, often triggering needless and risky treatment for
tiny, languid tumors that might never have grown into medical
threats. But the upside can be a timely warning of potentially
aggressive cancer in men who felt no sign of it.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT &LR;      04-27 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEAFS GIVE THE DEVILS A TASTE OF DEFEAT IN ROUND 2
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The New Jersey Devils learned again what it is like to
lose in the playoffs. Although they did not play poorly and had
more scoring chances, they fell 2-1 Thursday night to the Toronto
Maple Leafs in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference semifinals at Air
Canada Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who made first-round exits in 1998 and 1999, had won
all four games in the first round this spring against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitri Yushkevich scored the first goal for Toronto, and Darcy
Tucker scored the winner. Petr Sykora scored for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs went up by 2-1 at 1 minute 18 seconds of the third
period on a goal by Tucker, who took a pass from Wendel Clark,
battled to control the puck, cut right to left and beat a sprawling
Martin Brodeur with a forehand shot.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and Clark were placed on the roster late in the season by
Pat Quinn, Toronto's coach and general manager, to add tenacity and
a mean streak to a roster dominated by skilled artistes.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third period, Clark created a scoring chance
by breaking through two Devils, Scott Niedermayer and Steve Kelly,
at the blue line. Bearing in on Brodeur, he clanged a shot off one
of the goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   When play stopped soon afterward for a long television
commercial timeout, the Toronto fans jumped to their feet for a
long standing ovation while the big screen on the scoreboard
focused only on Clark, who drank water and bent over the catch his
breath at the Leafs' bench.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 33, in his third tour with the Leafs, Clark is
extremely popular here. A native of Saskatchewan, Clark is a
Canadian archetype, the sort of player who reminds fans of the way
the NHL used to be.
</P>
<P>
   During the ovation, the people responsible for the arena
presentation did something rare and welcome: they played no
recorded music, allowing natural sound and natural emotion to fill
Air Canada Center at a special moment.
</P>
<P>
   With about three minutes left in the period, Clark again set up
Tucker, this time on a two-on-one break. But Brodeur turned aside
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 will be played here Saturday night. The winner of this
best-of-7 series will play either Philadelphia or Pittsburgh for
the Eastern Conference championship and the right to meet the
Western Conference winner in the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was scoreless, although the Devils dictated the
pace of play and held an 11-6 edge in shots on goal. Sergei
Nemchinov was credited with only one shot on goal, but he had two
good chances on the same shift, with one of his shots passing
through the crease without making contact with Toronto goalie
Curtis Joseph. Sykora rang a hard shot off one of Joseph's goal
posts.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had two power plays in the period, but one of them
was negated with 1:11 remaining when they were penalized for having
too many men on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   As anticipated, the Devils' captain, Scott Stevens, a veteran
defenseman, was matched against the top Toronto line of Mats
Sundin, Steve Thomas and Jonas Hoglund. When Stevens and Thomas,
close friends from Thomas' days as a Devil, came together behind
the Devils' net, Stevens greeted him with a shove of the glove that
players call a ``face wash.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto took a 1-0 lead at 1:07 of the second period on a long,
low slap shot by Yushkevich, who fired from above the right-wing
circle at the conclusion of a power play just as Niedermayer was
coming out of the penalty box. Brodeur may have been screened on
the shot. Moments later, Patrik Elias rang another of Joseph's goal
posts.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils tied the score at 1-1 at 5:54 on a long slap shot by
Sykora, who took a pass from Elias on the rush after Toronto turned
over the puck at its blue line. Along with Jason Arnott, their
center, these two wings from the Czech Republic were creating
chances frequently, usually off transitions. In the first series, a
sweep of Florida, Sykora had one goal and one assist, while Elias
had one goal and three assists. Arnott, playing with a sore right
wrist, had one assist against the Panthers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
