u k BC-OBIT-MERRICK-NYT &LR;      04-27 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MERRICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEATH OF A SHOWMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, April 28:
</P>
<P>
   Theatricality went to the core of David Merrick, who died
Tuesday at 88 in London. As a producer, he dominated Broadway from
1954 until 1980 with a string of hits that included ``Gypsy,''
``Hello, Dolly!'' and ``42nd Street.'' He possessed a keen
commercial and artistic sensibility and an almost hostile business
acumen, as well as a flair for publicity that will link his name
forever with the likes of P.T. Barnum. He belonged in the glare of
the footlights as much as any producer ever has.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of self-dramatization in Merrick, but very
little of it was autobiographical. It was his talent and his
temperament that made him famous, even infamous, not his life
story. Few people have enjoyed their prosperity less than he seems
to have done, except perhaps as self-vindication. He lived, in a
way, obscurely. He was a litigant in his own life.
</P>
<P>
   There is no formula for becoming a great theatrical producer,
and certainly no one will wish to follow Merrick's method in all
its misanthropic detail. He seems to have been determined to please
only the audience, and that he did. Tales of Merrick's acerbity are
rife, yet they are offset not only by the popularity of the shows
he produced but also by the high artistic merit of many of them. It
would be hard to make musical theater out of Merrick's life, for
the necessary vein of sentimentality is missing. If there were
indeed a play in his remarkable story, it would take Moliere to
write it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
