A9485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-STOP&AMP;FRISK-NYT &LR;      04-27 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STOP&AMP;FRISK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEW BOARD STAFF FAULTS POLICE ON STOP-AND-FRISK REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators for the Civilian Complaint Review Board
have determined that police officers routinely fail to file the
required paperwork after frisking or searching people on New York
City's streets. The board's staff has prepared a preliminary report
that raises questions about whether the widespread violation of
department policy has hampered supervisors overseeing the judgment
of officers on patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators for the board, which is charged with reviewing
civilian complaints of police misconduct, based their findings on a
study of hundreds of instances in which people had been stopped and
frisked or searched. In about half the cases investigated, the
staff found, the officers involved had failed to file a written
record of the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The written reports, known as UF250s, are in part meant to
establish a formal record of potentially dangerous or disputed
interactions with civilians, and thus to provide a measure of
accountability for police action. An officer, for instance, is
required to record the time, location and reason for frisking or
searching any civilian, as well as the result.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are included in a draft report, a copy of which was
obtained by The New York Times. Frank H. Wohl, the board's
chairman, called the report ``extremely preliminary,'' and added
that it had been prepared by the agency's staff, and had yet to
receive input from any of the panel's 12 sitting board members.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department's aggressive stop-and-frisk tactics long
have been the subject of scrutiny and angry debate.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether the police had been aggressive to the
point of recklessness with such tactics came up during the trial of
four police officers for their role in the shooting death of Amadou
Diallo. The officers were acquitted of all charges. And late last
year, the state attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, issued a report
saying that the city's black and Hispanic residents had been
unfairly singled out in the stop-and-frisk effort, a finding the
department dismissed as flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the review board staff's report suggests that even the
official Police Department statistics may have been inaccurate, and
that far more stop-and-frisk encounters may have taken place in
recent years and simply not been recorded.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department was unable to provide recent statistics on
stop-and-frisk reports, but said that 138,872 had been filed in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's report, based on department data, found that police
officers filed 175,000 reports between January 1998 and March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department defines a frisk as patting down the
outside of a suspect's clothing, feeling for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   A search is described as reaching inside a suspect's pockets or
other interior parts of clothing to determine if an object felt is
a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This failure to document stop-and-frisk encounters is
disturbing for several reasons,'' the review board staff's report
said. ``First, the under-reporting of the mandated stops shows that
NYPD policy is not strictly adhered to by its own police officers.
Officers are not filling out UF250 forms according to the Patrol
Guide's instructions, and this failure to appropriately document
stop encounters undermines the NYPD's policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, several senior police officials acknowledged that
officers commonly failed to file the paperwork, which is also meant
to protect officers from accusations of misconduct stemming from
the street encounters and to gather potentially valuable criminal
intelligence on suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials defended the department, noting that no other
large police force in the state uses the forms, and that
excessive-force complaints against New York City police officers
have been dropping despite thousands of arrests and hundreds of
thousands of encounters with the public each year.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir refused to discuss the draft
report Thursday, saying through a spokesman, ``It's inappropriate
to respond to a report that we have not received.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2324EDT &QL; 
