<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. MARTIN H. STEIN, PSYCHOANALYST, IS DEAD AT 87 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Martin H. Stein, a psychoanalyst who was
president of the New York Psychoanalytic Society in the 1960s, died
on April 19 at New York Presbyterian Hospital in Manhattan. He was
87 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Stein retired about a year ago from his private psychoanalytic
practice. He had practiced psychoanalysis for five decades.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught at the New York Psychoanalytic Institute in
Manhattan and was chairman of its faculty in the 1970s. He headed
the American Psychoanalytic Association's board on professional
standards in the 1960s. And he was on the editorial boards of
Psychoanalytic Quarterly and The Journal of the American
Psychoanalytic Association.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joan B. Erle, one of his colleagues, said in remarks before
a professional gathering in 1986 that Stein wrote ``lucidly on
complex and difficult analytic issues: acting out, masochism,
states of consciousness, character theory, moral issues in
psychoanalysis, mental health, the psychology of dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein was born in Newark, N.Y., and grew up in Brooklyn. He
received a bachelor's degree in 1932 from the College of the City
of New York, earned his medical degree from Cornell in 1936 and was
a New York University-Bellevue Hospital research fellow in
neuropsychiatry in 1939 and 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Stein was an Army Medical Corps psychiatrist during World War II
and after three years of training at the New York Psychoanalytic
Institute, he graduated in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to Jane Knoob, ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife Lucille Kuttner; two daughters,
Maurine Stein of Chicago and Nora Stein of London, and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000427.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-27 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-ALASKA-MECHANIC-SPI &LR;      04-27 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-MECHANIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA MECHANIC SEEKS EXPANDED WRONGFUL-TERMINATION LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 and PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A former Alaska Airlines mechanic says in a lawsuit
that the airline falsified maintenance records, pressured him to
``speed up repairs'' and ridiculed him when he asked for
maintenance manuals to fix planes in the Oakland hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Reza Zendehnam has asked the court for permission to
add the allegations to his year-old wrongful-termination lawsuit.
If the change is allowed by a federal judge, his lawsuit will
invoke the federal Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organization
Act, which means greater damages if he proves Alaska engaged in a
pattern of criminal behavior. His lawsuit was filed in U.S.
District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Vice President Lou Cancelmi called Zendehnam's lawsuit
``offensive'' in light of the Jan. 31 crash of Alaska Flight 261.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real moral and ethical issue here deals with opportunism
and a desperate hope to cash in on tragedy,'' Cancelmi said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to respond to Zendehnam's allegations, saying: ``We
won't do it in the newspaper. We will very vigorously pursue our
interests in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Zendehnam, 47, contends he was told to hurry repairs even when
he believed a plane needed more work to be fit for passenger
service. He claims Alaska threatened to fire him if he was unable
to do routine repair work faster.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations echo those raised last month by 64 mechanics who
work in Alaska's hangar at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.
They wrote company executives, saying they had been ``pressured,
threatened and intimidated'' by their manager to cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   But Alaska officials noted that Zendehnam, who is
Iranian-American, alleged only ethnic discrimination in his
original lawsuit, filed 18 months after he was fired in October
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he waited three years to file these serious
charges and only did so after his lawyer was contacted by a
reporter is most curious. Most curious indeed,'' Cancelmi said.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic's lawyer, Jonathan Preston, said his client would
not comment but provided court papers showing the allegations were
raised in early March, before he was contacted by the
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Amending the lawsuit to include the RICO claim reflects the fact
that new information has been shaken loose by the crash, making it
easier to prove his case, Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are other witnesses (who have) come forward,'' he
said. ``There are mechanics talking; I've got a case with mechanics
who can back my client up.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Flight 261 plummeted into the Pacific Ocean off Southern
California, killing all 88 people on board, federal investigators
have been trying to determine if any crime contributed to the
disaster. Federal agents are also probing whether Alaska encouraged
illegal maintenance practices that were either condoned or ignored
by Federal Aviation Administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Zendehnam alleges, without offering specifics, that Alaska
falsified maintenance records that let unairworthy planes to be
returned to service _ allegations that have been the subject of a
grand jury investigation in San Francisco for at least 16 months.
The grand jury has not returned any indictments, but the FAA has
recommended that three Alaska maintenance supervisors in Oakland
lose their mechanic's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska hired Zendehnam, who had 17 years' experience as an
aircraft mechanic, in June 1997. A U.S. Air Force veteran, he had
worked for 10 years as a United Airlines mechanic and inspector,
Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   Zendehnam had experience checking and repairing Boeing 727, 737
and 757 planes, and contends Alaska assigned him to work on MD-80s
without training him.
</P>
<P>
   His amended suit claims Alaska engaged in ``a pattern of
unlawful conduct by allowing non-qualified MD-80 mechanics to work
on MD-80 planes without the proper systems or cross-over training
required by the (FAA).''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's FAA-approved training program would require a new
mechanic with such experience to take a training class, according
to FAA spokeswoman Kirsti Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Zendehnam also contends that he was ridiculed more than once
when he asked for manuals to guide him through routine MD-80
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was never given a reason for his firing; Alaska says
none was needed because he was still in a standard, new-employee
probation period.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1998, his discrimination claim against Alaska was
dismissed in an administrative proceeding by the California
Department of Fair Employment &AMP; Housing.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Zendehnam's claim, a state official noted that a
co-worker had said that ``despite (the co-worker's) willingness to
answer your constant questions about how to perform each function,
you were exceedingly slow.''
</P>
<P>
   If Alaska is found to have violated RICO, Zendehnam could
collect triple damages, attorneys fees and costs. The 1970 law,
often used to combat organized crime, created a new class of civil
tort in which the plaintiff must show the defendant engaged in a
pattern of racketeering _ defined as being at least two criminal
acts connected by some common thread.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-83 that crashed in January had undergone a heavy
maintenance check in the Oakland hangar on Sept. 29, 1997. The
National Transportation Safety Board is looking closely at
maintenance of the plane in its efforts to to find the cause of the
crash. The FBI is conducting its own investigation to determine if
a crime contributed to the crash.
</P>
<P>
   As the airline was still reeling from the crash in March, the 64
SeaTac mechanics fired off their letter. Company officials
interviewed those who signed it and have said no planes were
returned to flight in an unsafe or unairworthy manner.
</P>
<P>
   They also transferred the maintenance manager to a
non-supervisory job, created a team to focus on safety and started
a safety hotline for employees.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the airline was subjected to a ``white
glove'' inspection by the FAA. The agency found irregularities in
maintenance records for two planes, prompting the company to
inspect the paperwork detailing heavy maintenance inspections on
most of its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chronicle, citing FAA records, reported
Thursday that an Alaska Airlines plane that was found this month to
have incomplete maintenance records had hydraulic problems on four
separate flights, that in some cases forced passengers to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's records came under review during the white glove
inspection. The Chronicle reported that the aircraft was
prematurely cleared for a test flight in Oakland despite
unspecified irregularities with its paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Alaska nor the FAA will say whether the review turned up
anything unusual, but the FAA said it plans to reach some
conclusions in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Zendehnam still contends two mechanics at the Oakland hangar
made repeated ethnic slurs in the four and a half months he worked
there.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's Cancelmi points out that 53 percent of the mechanics in
Alaska's Oakland hangar are people of color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let the facts of our employment statistics speak for
themselves,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
