<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY CAN'T CATCH LEADOFF MAN GREEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Race car drivers have a superstition: They
want to be neither the first nor last car out during qualifying.
That didn't seem to bother NASCAR Busch driver Jeff Green after he
led off and grabbed the pole Thursday for Saturday's Auto Club 300
at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The series points leader covered the 2-mile, D-shaped oval in a
track-record 40.391 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get paid to sit on poles and win races,'' said Green, one
of 30 cars to run quicker than the previous track record of 41.106,
set by Steve Park in 1997. ``So every once in a while, you have to
go out on the limb and scare yourself to death. It was pretty tough
going out first, but I knew that lap . . . if someone was going to
beat it, they would have to run a great lap. And if they did, it's
all theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup regulars Jeff Burton (177.550 mph) and Joe Nemechek
(177.519 mph) qualified second and fourth, respectively. Palmdale
native Ron Hornaday Jr., who is in his first season in the series,
qualified 16th at 176.121 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think that lap would hold up to be No. 2,''
Burton said. ``I had a great (line in turns 1 and 2), but I did a
terrible job in 3 and 4. We made improvements on the car after
practice, and the car drove great. I just didn't drive like I
needed to in 3 and 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's problem was with the line he took going into the
tri-oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a Busch car, you drive to arch your way into the corner,
then come down the race track,'' Burton said. ''I just didn't do a
good job of driving. I came off the corner too soon and that caused
me to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notables to qualify were former CART series driver P.J.
Jones (40.865), who is 13th, and Jason Leffler (40.980), who is
24th. Leffler, who won last season's USAC Turkey Night Grand Prix
at Irwindale Speedway, also announced he will drive in the
Indianapolis 500 for Treadway Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the Winston West Pontiac WideTrack Grand Prix 200
was dominated by Winston Cup regulars Ken Schrader and Johnny
Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, who has won two of the past four Winston West races at
this track since its opening in 1997, took the pole with a 39.906,
or 180.424 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who is competing in his first Winston West event, is
second at 40.001. Winston West regulars Austin Cameron (40.541) and
Brendan Gaughan (40.666) qualified fifth and seventh, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bean is 10th at 40.930. Former NFL coach Jerry Glanville,
who runs selected events, is 20th at 41.757.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
