<SLUG> BC-TEN-OJAI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD ON SCHEDULE AT OJAI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Underdogs beware.
</P>
<P>
   Everything went as expected for top-seeded Stanford in the
opening rounds of the Pac-10 divsion of the 100th Ojai Tennis
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Kim advanced to today's quarterfinals with a 6-3, 6-1
victory over Marius Lunde of Washington and a 6-3, 4-6, 6-2 win
over Andrew Park of USC.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Granville, the Cardinal's No. 1-ranked women's player,
also is headed to the quarters with wins over Melissa Pine of
Washington State (6-1, 6-2) and Christina Fusano of California
(6-1, 6-4).
</P>
<P>
   Park, who was fighting back spasms, wasn't discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been starting to play better over the past couple of
weeks, and it was a tough matchup because this is a guy that
doesn't give you any free points,'' said Park. ``I don't really
have a game that overpowers anybody. I've never been the big guy on
the court, so I don't get intimidated too easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the best matchup for me, but I think I put up a
fight, especially in the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford continued its dominance on the court with an upset
victory. UCLA's Jong-Min Lee, the No. 2 seed of the tournament,
lost to K.J. Hippensteel 4-6, 6-7(2) in a match that took just
under two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hong trailed in the second set 5-3 and broke Hippensteel's serve
to tie it eventually at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also had tough loss when Nick Rainey fell to
Oregon's Guillermo Carter in three sets 6-4, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The second-ranked Bruins had better luck in other matches.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Kramer of UCLA beat Alex Brown of Arizona 6-3, 6-3 and
Matt Klinger 6-3, 7-6 (7-4). Julian Rojer also swept his matches
(6-2, 6-3 and 6-4, 6-0) to advance to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Noel Grinda had six hard-fought sets and won both matches.
Grinda won 3-6, 6-0, 6-3 over Robert Kowalczyk of California and
6-3, 4-6, 6-4 over Matt Hanlin of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's Pac-10, the Bruins and Trojans each had one
player advance to the quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Walker of UCLA gave up only two games in her 6-1, 6-1 win
over USC's Jacqui Boyd in the second round. USC's Kara Warkentin
advanced with a 6-3, 6-3 win over Arizona State's Faye DeVera.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals begin at 8 this morning at Libbey Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
