<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ABC-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER WEEKS WITHOUT LEADER, ABC NETWORK GETS PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Walt Disney Co. has placed the president of its radio and
television stations division in charge of the ABC Television
Network, which has been without a direct leader for weeks even as
it has stood at No. 1 in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The executive, Robert F. Callahan, who has been ABC's president
of broadcasting since February 1999, assumed his new position as
president of the newly named ABC Broadcast Group Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan is now overseeing the ABC network's news,
entertainment, daytime and late-night divisions as well as its
affiliate relations and sales and marketing units. He will retain
his position as the executive in charge of Disney's radio and
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan is inheriting a network that is in very good shape.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled in large part by ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' the
popular game show that has Regis Philbin as its host, ABC has
become the most watched network in terms of households and viewers
after three years in third place behind CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The show's success in the ratings is estimated to have added
hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue this television season.
</P>
<P>
   As it prepares to announce a new fall television schedule next
month, the task at hand for ABC is to build on its success by
adding popular new shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got one show that is really healthy,'' said Tom
Wolzien, media analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``The real
test here is to see how they're doing when you get into next
December, when you've seen how their new shows have fared and how
the shows they bring back have fared.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Callahan does not have network programming experience,
Robert A. Iger, the Walt Disney president who was chairman of ABC
until midwinter, said he did not expect Callahan to have too much
trouble learning that end of the business. Also, Iger said,
Callahan has adept programmers beneath him in ABC Entertainment's
co-chairmen, Stu Bloomberg and Lloyd Braun.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan began his association with ABC in 1981, when he was
hired as sales manager of Multichannel News, a title owned by
Fairchild Publications, a unit of ABC's former parent company,
Capital Cities. After moving up the ranks at Fairchild, Callahan
was promoted to president of ABC Radio Networks in 1990 _ doubling
its number of radio stations to 44. In February 1999, he was also
given responsibility for ABC's 10 television stations. Under his
watch, the number of owned stations that were No. 1 in their
markets rose from six to eight.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan's television station division has been in heated
negotiations over retransmission rights with Time Warner Cable. The
two sides are at an impasse that could result in the removal of
local ABC stations from Time Warner Cable systems across the
country, including in New York and Los Angeles. The current
transmission agreement is set to expire at midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has proposed that the current agreement be extended through
May 24, the end of the crucial May sweeps ratings period, which
began Thursday night. Executives say they believe that Federal
Communications Commission regulations will require Time Warner to
honor that proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Time Warner said its lawyers were reviewing the
regulations and had no other immediate response.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said he would still closely monitor the situation. ABC
executives said Callahan's new job title essentially made him a
replacement for Iger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
