<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DENOUNCES PANEL'S REPORT ON POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir questioned the credibility of the United States Commission on
Civil Rights on Thursday and attacked the findings of its draft
report on the New York Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-page draft report said that evidence suggested the
Police Department engaged in racial profiling. It also recommended
that a monitor oversee how civilian complaints were investigated
and that a mechanism be created to pursue accusations of police
brutality independent of local prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Giuliani and of the police generally praised the
report on Thursday. Some said they hoped the final report would
call for an independent monitor to oversee the entire department.
</P>
<P>
   The report has not been released to the public, but The New York
Times obtained a copy. On Thursday, Giuliani accused the commission
of leaking the report and repeated his earlier accusation that the
agency had a partisan political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended a monitor for the Civilian Complaint
Review Board. Giuliani said that while the review board could be
improved, it functioned better than the report implied.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should take a look at their own process before they
recommend a different process for the CCRB,'' Giuliani said. ``The
CCRB does not leak information before it turns it over to the
commissioner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
