<HEADER>
A9507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ANTHROPOLOGISTS-NY     04-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ANTHROPOLOGISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DROPS EMBEZZLEMENT CASE AGAINST PROFESSOR
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After charging a trailblazing anthropology professor
at John Jay College of Criminal Justice last year with embezzling
money from a $2.6 million federal grant, federal prosecutors have
abruptly moved to dismiss the charges, although they say they are
still investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Ansley Hamid, who is credited with discovering
and documenting trends in urban drug use, was accused of using the
money to pay for travel and other personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At the prosecutor's request, a federal magistrate dismissed the
case against Hamid late Wednesday afternoon. A spokesman for the
U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan declined to say why the charges
were dismissed. The charges were dismissed by the judge without
prejudice, a legal term meaning prosecutors can reinstate the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it is the end of an unjustifiable ordeal,'' Hamid, 55,
said Thursday. He declined to speak further without consulting his
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid's lawyer, Paul Shectman, said: ``The United States
attorney has told us they have not made a final decision, but we
are very pleased they are taking a hard look at this case. They
have given us a chance to present professor Hamid's side of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   In October, prosecutors charged that Hamid embezzled more than
$5,000 from the grant for a study titled ``Heroin in the 21st
Century.'' The charges did not specify an amount, but prosecutors
said he used the money to pay for trips to Florida, Hawaii and
Trinidad, to buy compact disks and electronic equipment, and to pay
two research assistants who worked mainly on his private book
projects.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for John Jay College said Thursday that the school
had not been informed that the charges were dropped and still
intended to pursue administrative disciplinary charges against the
professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had deferred our case and charges against him to let the
federal prosecution go forward,'' said Jerry Capeci, the college
spokesman. ``If they have dropped their case, ours will proceed and
there is a hearing date scheduled in June.''
</P>
<P>
   Capeci said the college was seeking to dismiss Hamid, who is
tenured. ``The federal government charged him with crimes and we
are charging him with administrative violations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The professor was suspended from the heroin project in December
1997 and removed from teaching in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Hamid has been a pioneering researcher
in the study of America's drug underworld. A native of Trinidad, he
received degrees from the London School of Economics and Columbia
University. He has become known for his ability to win the
confidence of addicts he interviewed, and has documented trends and
shifts in drug use, such as the crack epidemic in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his work has been closely watched by the nation's drug
experts, and in 1996, John Jay College's research foundation was
awarded a $2.6 million grant to allow Hamid to conduct a five-year
study of heroin use in some of the city's bleakest neighborhoods.
The study proposed to establish a ``monitoring network to track the
development cycle of heroin use in New York City from 1995 to
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint filed last year by federal agents,
Hamid used some of the grant money for personal expenses. In one
count, the agents charged that Hamid purchased more than $2,000 in
electronic equipment and music compact disks. In the complaint,
federal agents said that an investigator from John Jay College told
them that Hamid said he felt he was entitled to listen to music
while working on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   The agents also said another witness, whom they did not
identify, told them that Hamid gave him $100 to buy 10 bags of
heroin so that the professor could compensate addicts for
participating in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal complaint also said the college investigator told
federal agents that Hamid ``admitted that he experimented with
heroin for approximately one month'' while working on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid has been free on bond while the charges were pending. He
has adamantly maintained his innocence and has publicly denied the
accusations, which he has described as ``trumped-up charges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
